<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AHEAD AT A LOOK BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles, Oct. 20, 2024
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe 25 years have gone by since the Staples
Center opened, and it's harder to believe we thought it was so
high-tech back then.
</P>
<P>
   Seems like only yesterday the arena debuted with a Bruce
Springsteen concert (the Boss in the flesh, not a life-size
hologram, like the concerts these days) and a Kings ice hockey game
against the Boston Bruins (before the water conservationists forced
the development of ``virtual ice.'').
</P>
<P>
   I guess it was only a matter of time before luxury-box patrons
demanded a more up-to-date building in which they wouldn't be
forced to actually sit up to watch the games.
</P>
<P>
   So, now we look forward to the opening of a new building on the
former site of Los Angeles City Hall, which never did produce the
revenue a major sports arena can.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good time to look back at the high and low points in
the history of the dear old Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 21, 1999: Arena officials announce they're closing the
arena for renovations after discovering it was accidentally built
with a sloping roof.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 10, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2004, 2007, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012,
2015, 2016, 2018, 2020, 2021 and 2023: The Clippers hold press
conferences to announce they've signed the NBA's No. 1 draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   April 2, 2004: The Dodgers move to the Staples Center for one
season while Dodger Stadium is being fitted with a dome. Although
the left-field fence is only 194 feet away, the team again fails to
produce a 50-home run hitter.
</P>
<P>
   May 6, 2006: George Foreman announces his retirement from boxing
after an eighth-round knockout loss to Laila Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 29, 2007: A maintenance crew sweeping a rarely used
stairwell discovers the frozen remains of a sportswriter who'd been
presumed lost in the arena catacombs since he wandered away from a
pre-opening tour in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   April 10, 2008: The Kings come back from a five-goal,
third-period deficit against the expansion Mexico City Iceberg to
win a playoff thriller to be remembered as the ``Miracle on
Figueroa'' until somebody thinks up a cooler name.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 14, 2009: After a member of the working class breaches
security by getting off the elevator on the exclusive Suite Level
A, scores of luxury-box holders suffer scrapes and bruises in a
panicked stampede to the exits.
</P>
<P>
   July 8, 2012: The arena plays host to the Reform Party national
convention at which Danny Bonaduce is nominated for his successful
presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 2, 2014: The Staples Center hosts the historic first game
of the new Coed NBA after a court bans separate men's and women's
pro leagues as unconstitutional. (Women's advocates continue to
challenge the ruling.)
</P>
<P>
   March 29, 2017: Arena workers go on strike midway through the
two-hour process of switching from a hockey rink to a basketball
floor. That night's basketball game is played anyway, and the
Lakers' defense improves with the adoption of the neutral-zone
trap.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 1, 2020: Shaquille O'Neal Jr. makes his NBA debut. The
7-footer is soon hailed as a pretty good point guard for a little
guy.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 20, 2022: The USC basketball team moves to the Staples
Center, having just moved out of the Sports Arena, which will be
leveled to make room for a parking structure if Los Angeles gets a
pro football team.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 18, 2023: Bruce Springsteen, 74, brings his fans to their
feet _ the younger ones, anyway _ in the famous ``Old Blue Jeans is
Back'' concert. The Rolling Stones open.
</P>
<P>
   June 6, 2024: Kobe Bryant, introduced as the Lakers' new head
coach, promises fans will see more teamwork, ``like we had when
Shaq and I played.'' Preseason magazines pick Lakers to end their
NBA title drought at 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 10, 2024: With banners, balloons and a blare of trumpets,
the Staples Center welcomes its 50 millionth fan. The man asks
directions to a restroom, explaining that he'd been idling in
Harbor Freeway traffic since opening night in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
