<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-NLCS-     10-20 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-NLCS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Braves top Mets, win NLCS 10-9 in 11-inning nail-biter
</P>
<P>
   By Carroll Rogers
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two can play this game. This
rip-your-heart-out-extra-inning kind. But only one can move along
to the World Series to face the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   And for that, the Braves fans are forever thankful. That and
completely wrung out after watching the Braves survive Game 6 and
the Mets with a 10-9 11th inning win that puts them back in their
fifth World Series of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves game plan for Wednesday night had called for patience
and it couldn't have been a better one. After waiting for six games
against the Mets and 11 innings on Tuesday night, Andruw Jones went
to the plate with the bases loaded and the game tied 10-10.
Historically one of the most impatient hitters in the Braves lineup
Jones watched a Kenny Rogers 3-2 pitch sail up and away to walk in
Gerald Williams from third base to send the Braves back to the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had doubled to lead off the inning and moved to third
on back-to-back intentional walks to Chipper Jones and Brian
Jordan. Then came the walk that sends the Braves jumping for joy.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch of the 1996 Yankees comes at the expense of the
Mets, who proved to be the most resilient of any team in recent
memory that followed up their 4-3 15th inning win in New York by
pushing the Braves to the limit themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Well enough alone? If the Braves didn't have a trip to the World
Series all but locked up with a 3-0 lead Friday night in New York,
then they surely had it early in the evening on Tuesday night when
they were up by five runs in the first inning of Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets made that Braves lead another in a long list of
disappearing deficits Tuesday night, clawing back to take a 9-8
lead after trailing 5-0, 7-3 and 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   But by the 10th the Braves had had enough. The Braves had been 1
for 30 against Armando Benitez this season, with nary a baserunner
on him until Eddie Perez singled in the 10th inning of Game 5. But
in the 10th inning of Game 6, they tied the game on him. Andruw
Jones led off the inning with a single to right and Ozzie Guillen
scored him an out and three batters later when he drove his 1-1
pitch past Edgardo Alfonzo and into right field to score Andruw
Jones and tie the game 9-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets took a place where they'd lost 13 of their previous 14
games and packed with an all-time high 52,335 fans and made it feel
like home, and invited themselves back for a Game 7 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves 3-0 lead has vanished in three losses to the Mets,
who have made a killing on winning against the most improbable
odds. They are a win away from making the Braves the first team in
major league baseball history to blow a 3-0 lead in a seven-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine is the last man standing for the Braves, as he faces
Rick Reed tonight for the right to take on the Yankees in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani burned John Rocker with a leadoff walk in the top
of the 10th inning, should have been picked off attempting to steal
second base but took a Brian Hunter throw between the shoulder
blades instead. He then advanced to third on a Melvin Mora single
and slid home head first to score the winning run past a twisting
Greg Myers, who'd gone up the third base line to field a throw from
Andruw Jones on a Todd Pratt sacrifice fly to shallow center.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of sliding, if the Braves are to make it back to a
fifth World Series this decade, they're going to do it the hard way
after being beaten in extra innings for a second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves left the winning run at second base in both the
eighth and ninth innings with strikeouts by Howard Battle and then
Brian Jordan to face extra innings for the second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves 4-3 15-inning loss in New York on Sunday seem simple
to take.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had erased Braves leads of 5-0 and 7-3 on two of their
toughest power-throwing pitchers Kevin Millwood and Smoltz, leaving
the Braves fresh out of ideas and the Mets leaning on their one
clear advantage over the Braves, their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But trailing 8-7, the Braves found an answer from the hottest
and coldest hitters on their team. Eddie Perez started it with a
single to left off John Franco for his 10th hit of the series,
highest for any hitter on either team. Then with Otis Nixon pinch
running for him, stealing second on a 3-2 pitch and taking third on
Mike Piazza's second throwing error of the game, Brian Hunter
singled to right center to tie the game 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken the Mets six innings to start cashing in
offensively, but once they started they wouldn't stop, first on
Millwood then on Smoltz. They got another chopper for a single by
John Olerud, another Edgardo Alfonzo double and more heroics from
Melvin Mora, who gave the Mets their first lead of the game 8-7
with a run-scoring single in the eighth inning off Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   After the Braves made a big inning pitcher out of the Mets big
game pitcher Al Leiter with five runs in the first inning, they
swallowed hard as Millwood gave three runs back in the sixth
inning. It would only get worse, as the Mets had an answer for
another Braves offensive surge in the sixth and a call to John
Smoltz out of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who'd done little but taken a physically beating this
series, finally took a big swing back. With only the fourth hit of
his series, Piazza drove a bullet into the Braves and their right
center field bleachers with his line drive two-run home run off
Smoltz to complete a seven-run comeback tying the game 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves offense, which had scored only five earned runs in
its previous 33 innings of the series, matched that in the first
inning, chasing Leiter after he faced six batters without recording
an out.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, pitching on three days' rest, hit Gerald Williams in the
foot, walked Bret Boone and gave up a run before he'd even thrown a
second pitch to Chipper Jones. Jones watched from the batter's box
as Williams and Boone took off on a double steal and Williams
scored on a drawing a wild throw to third from Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to put a little wood into their efforts, the
Braves did that too with a two-strike run-scoring single from Brian
Jordan and a bases loaded two-run single from Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   That ended Leiter's shortest outing since his rookie season in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
