single to left off John Franco for his 10th hit of the series,
highest for any hitter on either team. Then with Otis Nixon pinch
running for him, stealing second on a 3-2 pitch and taking third on
Mike Piazza's second throwing error of the game, Brian Hunter
singled to right center to tie the game 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken the Mets six innings to start cashing in
offensively, but once they started they wouldn't stop, first on
Millwood then on Smoltz. They got another chopper for a single by
John Olerud, another Edgardo Alfonzo double and more heroics from
Melvin Mora, who gave the Mets their first lead of the game 8-7
with a run-scoring single in the eighth inning off Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   After the Braves made a big inning pitcher out of the Mets big
game pitcher Al Leiter with five runs in the first inning, they
swallowed hard as Millwood gave three runs back in the sixth
inning. It would only get worse, as the Mets had an answer for
another Braves offensive surge in the sixth and a call to John
Smoltz out of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who'd done little but taken a physically beating this
series, finally took a big swing back. With only the fourth hit of
his series, Piazza drove a bullet into the Braves and their right
center field bleachers with his line drive two-run home run off
Smoltz to complete a seven-run comeback tying the game 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves offense, which had scored only five earned runs in
its previous 33 innings of the series, matched that in the first
inning, chasing Leiter after he faced six batters without recording
an out.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, pitching on three days' rest, hit Gerald Williams in the
foot, walked Bret Boone and gave up a run before he'd even thrown a
second pitch to Chipper Jones. Jones watched from the batter's box
as Williams and Boone took off on a double steal and Williams
scored on a drawing a wild throw to third from Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to put a little wood into their efforts, the
Braves did that too with a two-strike run-scoring single from Brian
Jordan and a bases loaded two-run single from Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   That ended Leiter's shortest outing since his rookie season in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
