<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR METS, A MONTH IS AN ETERNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Mets' season, in survival mode for four weeks,
tumbled back to Atlanta on Tuesday night for Game 6 of a series _
and a rivalry _ that has taken on a life of its own. For the Mets,
this city has become a lament: Atlanta, Atlanta, the road leads
back to you.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks ago to the day, the Mets barreled into town full of
heady pretensions and the fragile confidence of a team that was
having its first dreams of the top after a decade of mediocrity.
They had put distance between themselves and Cincinnati in the
National League wild-card race and had pulled within a game of the
Braves _ the foe they have chased so long in the East Division.
With three games at Turner Field, the Mets were certain of coming
out even with Atlanta at the very least.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mets were humbled. They suffered three
confidence-draining losses that set the stage for one of the
wildest rides in franchise history. Disaster in Atlanta; three more
demoralizing losses to lowly Philadelphia, then two more defeats to
Atlanta at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Mets had tumbled from the lofty quest of a
division championship to the desperation of a team trying to back
into a wild-card playoff. With their division dreams crushed to
pieces, the Mets put themselves back together with what was left.
The young players snapped out of a dream, the veterans faced up to
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young guys had been living a dream,'' recalled Darryl
Hamilton, the Mets' center fielder, who joined the team in a
midseason trade. ``First couple years in the big leagues with the
chance to go to the playoffs _ something they hadn't done here in
11 years. The older guys were thinking, `Hey, I'm running out of
time. It's time to turn it up.' The whole team realized we were in
a special position and needed to take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team grew, the team jelled, the team matured.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets swept a three-game series against Pittsburgh, then won
a wild-card playoff game against Cincinnati. They disposed of
favored Arizona, suffered three straight losses to Atlanta in the
Championship Series, then scored back-to-back victories, the second
in a 15-inning classic on Sunday. Hamilton reflected on the
mind-set of the team four weeks ago _ four weeks that seem like a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came here before, we were thinking, `Okay, we can
maybe get two out of three, maybe sweep these guys, then we're tied
up or ahead in the division. Then we can go on and take care of
business at home,''' Hamilton recalled. ``But when that snowballed
into a losing streak, guys realized that the only thing that was
important is the game you go out and play. One game at a time. Our
psyche has changed totally.''
</P>
<P>
   So the changed Mets came back to Atlanta. All those miles
traveled, the ups, the downs, the upheavals. All the steep inclines
and plummets.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Mets were right back where they started four
weeks ago when they came here a game behind Atlanta. But in a much
larger sense, the Mets barely resemble the team that left Atlanta
humbled and off center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude's a little different right now,'' Hamilton said.
``That losing streak was a very humbling experience. We realized
that, no matter how good your ball club is, usually the best team
doesn't win. We think we have a very good ball club but we lost a
lot of critical games at the end and it almost cost us a playoff
berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys really appreciate where we are right now. We understand
that it can go away at any instant.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps for those reasons, there is a pronounced sense of time
and fragility among the Mets. Before Tuesday night's game, someone
asked Bobby Valentine about a Subway Series against the Yankees.
Valentine sighed, gave the patent quizzical expression, then mulled
a complex response to a simple question. He framed his answer in
the context of a team that has nearly come full circle in four
weeks, but still, possibly not far enough. ``We're close,'' he said
``but we're really far away from that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said he looked at the
Mets' harrowing four-week journey _ from Georgia to Pennsylvania to
New York to Ohio to Arizona back to New York and now Georgia again
_ and believes it has built a resolve the Mets may not have had
four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things had gone differently, we could have won the division
and gotten here the same way,'' Phillips said. ``But the way we've
gotten to this point is going to be so much more fulfilling when
it's all said and done because we overcame something and a label
can never be attached to us again. We didn't choke. We didn't fold.
We won.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips paused and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had destiny in our own hands, we lost destiny, we got it
back in our own hands,'' he said. ``We won to get ourselves where
we are today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
