<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2349 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-N     10-20 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBWAY SERIES DERAILED AS BRAVES BEAT METS, 10-9 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story has been added to the New York Times front page ) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A team's momentum, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
believes, is only as strong as its starting pitcher. Valentine may
have underestimated his team's resiliency, but Wednesday morning,
in Game 6 of the National League Championship Series, the momentum,
the magic and the moxie that carried the Mets on their exhilarating
rampage through the post-season finally ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' magical month ended when the Atlanta Braves pushed
across a run in the 11th inning at Turner Field to win, 10-9, to
capture the National League pennant in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which will be host to the Yankees in Game 1 of the
World Series on Saturday night in a rematch of 1996 Series, blew
5-0 and 7-3 leads, fell behind by a run, tied the game, fell behind
in overtime, tied it again, and then finally ended matters, as well
as the Mets' seesaw season.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams carried across the winning run for Atlanta,
after opening the Braves' 11th with a double to left off Kenny
Rogers. A sacrifice and two walks set up a bases-loaded, one-out
situation for Andruw Jones, who walked on a 3-2 pitch to win the
pennant for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Down by three games to none to the Braves last Saturday and by
5-0 after one inning on Tuesday night, the Mets rallied in their
distinctively improbable fashion and the teams went into extra
innings for the second straight game. No team has ever come back
from 3-0 hole in the post-season to even earn a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets came close.
</P>
<P>
   In their 10th, a walk to Benny Agabayani, a botched pickoff by
John Rocker, a single by Melvin Mora and a sacrifice fly by Todd
Pratt fetched the run that broke an 8-8 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves, who won a major league-leading 103 games this
season, came back in the bottom of the 10th off Mets' closer
Armando Benitez. A single, a walk and a one-out single to right by
Ozzie Guillen got home the tying run for Atlanta. A nifty throw
from Mora in right that cut down Ryan Klesko at third base
prevented a bigger rally, but, as things turned out, only prolonged
the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The extra-inning drama came long after Al Leiter had one of the
worst outings of his career. The Mets' starter was charged with
five first-inning runs in a 25-pitch outing.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's shabby outing on three days of rest put the Mets into
an early hole. Whether he was overly charged up or simply so out of
gas that no amount of mental fuel could make up the difference,
Leiter had no command of his pitches, sending them swerving in all
directions. Piazza looked like an aerobics instructor, stretching
up and down and side to side to retrieve Leiter's offerings. The
left-hander bounced his second pitch of the game in the dirt and on
his third pitch he hit the Braves' leadoff hitter, Gerald Williams,
in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter walked the next batter, Bret Boone. Six of Leiter's first
eight pitches were balls. On his first pitch to the dangerous
Chipper Jones _ another ball _ the Braves executed a double steal,
sending Williams scurrying to third. When Piazza gunned the ball to
third, it bounced off Robin Ventura and skittered toward the Mets
dugout, scoring Williams for the first run of the game as Boone
advanced to third.
</P>
<P>
   On the next pitch _ Leiter's 10th _ he hit Jones near the knee,
putting runners on first and third. Brian Jordan, the fourth batter
in the lineup, sent a grounder into the gap between third and
shortstop to score Boone and to give the Braves a 2-0 lead with,
still, none out.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones, on a 1-1 pitch, hit a comebacker to the mound.
Leiter fielded the ball, but, after a moment's hesitation, he threw
sidearm to second base. The throw pulled Edgardo Alfonzo off the
bag and the bases were loaded for Eddie Perez, whose home runs in
Games 1 and 2 had helped put the Mets into their hole.
</P>
<P>
   Perez fouled off four pitches with the count 1-2 and finally
smacked a single into left field to score Jones and Jordan, giving
the Braves a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After 25 pitches, Leiter was gone and his slow walk to the
dugout, head hanging, was a study in distress. As he reached for
his jacket, he rubbed his head with his hands but he would watch as
reliever Pat Mahomes gave up a sacrifice fly to Brian Hunter to
lengthen the lead to 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets essentially shrugged and said, ``Got your back.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mahomes and Turk Wendell holding the Braves scoreless, and
the Braves' starter, Kevin Millwood, who was pitching on extra
rest, tiring, the Mets scored three runs in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo led off with a double and moved to third on John
Olerud's single. Piazza's sacrifice fly scored Alfonzo for the
Mets' first run. Ventura, whose grand slam single won the marathon
Sunday night, doubled to put two runners in scoring position and
both scored on Darryl Hamilton's single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   With his lead down to 5-3, Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox replaced
Millwood with Terry Mulholland, who promptly walked pinch-hitter
Benny Agbayani to extend the rally. But Rey Ordonez, who has failed
to bunt successfully in several key situations during this series,
lined out to shortstop Walt Weiss, who stepped on second base for
the inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves added two runs in the bottom of the sixth on
pinch-hitter Jose Hernandez's bases-loaded single and that should
have finished the Mets off. Good luck with that.
</P>
<P>
   With John Smoltz, who had saved Game 2 for Millwood, entering
for the seventh, the Mets did the unthinkable. Pinch-hitter Matt
Franco doubled to center field to lead off and he scored on Rickey
Henderson's double down the left-field line. Then, Alfonzo backed
Jordan against the right-field wall with his flyout that moved
Henderson to third.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud followed with a single that scored Henderson and then
Piazza, who joked before the game that his left arm was so banged
up he should seek a donor, used that arm to slug a 2-1 pitch over
the right-center-field wall to tie the score, 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser, who also pitched Sunday, came on to shut the
Braves down in the seventh, and the Mets faced Mike Remlinger in
the eighth. Agbayani rapped a leadoff single to right and Ordonez
finally sacrificed successfully, moving Agbayani to second.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Melvin Mora, the Wunderkind who has been
involved in some of the Mets' most important plays of the last four
weeks. He singled to score Agbayani and to give the Mets their
first lead of the game, 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   But the scrambling Mets could not push another run across in the
eighth, and when the Braves scored off John Franco in the bottom of
the eighth, the score was tied, 8-8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
