<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCOL-COMMENTARY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFLICTING INTERESTS FOR MLS DEPUTY GULATI?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Major League Soccer deputy commissioner Sunil Gulati is
back, but not everyone is happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Gulati, who left MLS last year to pursue other soccer-related
endeavors, had been hired as the managing director for Kraft
Soccer. Robert Kraft, whose MLS financial stake includes the New
England Revolution and San Jose Clash, pursued Gulati because of
his experience and strong ties to MLS and world-wide soccer.
</P>
<P>
   But Gulati's hiring has been criticized, especially by Galaxy
coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   Gulati, 39, helped launch the league in 1996. He was responsible
for negotiating player contracts, as well as acquiring and
assigning foreign talent.
</P>
<P>
   He left MLS last year to become the managing director of Project
2010. He also served on the committees for FIFA and CONCACAF and
the board of director of U.S. Soccer. He is still active in those
posts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gulati is basically the general manager for New England and
San Jose _ which, in itself, is a conflict of interest. But his
close ties to the league, especially to Ivan Gazidis, vice
president in charge of player-related issues, leaves coaches such
as Schmid wondering how they can play on a level field.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United president and general manager Kevin Payne also
serves on the board of directors for U.S. Soccer and is a member on
the MLS board of governors. His influence has helped strengthen
United, which has the most talent in the league and owns two MLS
cup titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sunil is a tremendous soccer person and he's very
passionate about the game,'' Schmid said. ``He also gives the teams
in New England and San Jose a tremendous advantage because he's
privy to information that everybody eventually gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like Kevin Payne at D.C. United. Sunil and Kevin
get the information a week ahead of everybody else. They're privy
to both sides of the equation. They're privy to the MLS equation
because they sit on the board of directors and they sit on the
board of directors for U.S. Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you have three teams in the league that will know a week
earlier than everyone else what's going on. That puts the rest of
us at a disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulati doesn't think he has any advantage. He's taking over two
teams that failed to make the MLS playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is playing by the same rules,'' Gulati said. ``No one
is going to get a Ronaldo, and the teams have a lot to say in the
sort of players they want to get. It has been increasingly true
since year one that we will stand and fall on the decisions we
make.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schmid would like to see both Gulati and Payne abandon
some of their influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying Kevin or Sunil is out to get anyone,'' Schmid
said. ``But are there other people out there in U.S. Soccer's inner
circle? Is there another person in U.S. Soccer who can do what they
do? That's something we have to look at in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Strike one: Galaxy striker Carlos Hermosillo is in the final
year of a two-year contract with MLS.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Mexican standout has a big decision. Does he
return to Mexico, where he is 34 goals shy of becoming the
country's career-scoring leader, and leave the MLS behind? Or does
he re-sign with MLS because his wife and children enjoy their
privacy in La Canada Flintridge and are happy with its school
system?
</P>
<P>
   He has another choice _ to continue playing year-round. But then
his body is subject to a beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot to consider,'' Hermosillo said recently. ``The 34
goals needed in Mexico is something to think about. But I like
playing here as well.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Hermosillo expect him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   __ Matthaeus dilemma: Schmid addressed the fact that German
standout Lothar Matthaeus joined New York/New Jersey, the worst
team in the MLS despite the coaching of Bora Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic, the only coach to lead four nations into the second
round of the World Cup (including the U.S. in 1994), couldn't turn
around the MetroStars' fortunes. Schmid doesn't think Matthaeus,
who signed for next season, can keep quiet if New York's struggles
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans are not very good losers,'' said Schmid, who was
born in Germany. ``They tend to open their mouth and they,
sometimes, say things without thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Lohar is probably the closest thing Germany had since
Beckenbauer in terms of being able to speak his mind. He can say
things and it doesn't matter what the coach says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Germany in 1974, when Germany lost to East Germany.
Beckenbauer went on TV and said this guy should go on the bench and
this guy should be starting. The next game that was the lineup and
Germany went on to win the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid is hoping Matthaeus arrives with some patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would he consciously work to undermine Bora? I don't think
so,'' Schmid said. ``But he'll say things. If they don't win, there
will definitely be some friction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
