<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EISENHOWER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EISENHOWER'S NAME PINNED FOR NATIONAL RECOGNITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dwight D. Eisenhower was a 39-year-old major in the
U.S. Army in 1929 when his upward mobility catapulted him into an
office in the old State, War and Navy Building next to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   He was assistant to the assistant secretary of war, proving that
Washington's penchant for bureaucracy started long ago. A few years
later, he moved down the hall with another title, assistant to the
War Department's chief of staff, then Gen. Douglas MacArthur.
</P>
<P>
   But now, 30 years after his death, Eisenhower, might go about as
high as you can go in that old edifice, and with the biggest title
of all: The building might be named for him.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the 34th president and hero of World War II who was
raised in Abilene, Kan., might soon be emblazoned on the building
itself. The Senate on Tuesday agreed to rename what is now called
the Old Executive Office Building for Eisenhower. Republican Sen.
John Chafee of Rhode Island sponsored the measure, which had
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is long overdue,'' said Douglas Brinkley, a
presidential scholar and director of the Eisenhower Center at the
University of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington D.C., the city of memorials to presidents, there
virtually is nothing to honor the supreme commander of the Allied
forces and former two-term president considered by most people to
be one of the great figures of the 20th century. It's really a
wonderful tribute.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is some poetry in the politics, too. While it struck
some as strange to rename Washington's airport for President
Reagan, the scourge of the air traffic controller's union,
Eisenhower, as president, saved his future namesake from demolition
in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The building, a mammoth structure of granite, marble and cast
iron, was the world's largest office building when it was completed
in 1888 after 17 years of construction. Now on the National
Register of Historic Places, it is one of the most flamboyant
buildings in the capital and a window onto another era, with
pillars, skylight domes, gaslight chandeliers, spiral staircases
and two stained glass rotundas.
</P>
<P>
   An ``architectural infant asylum,'' wryly observed Henry Adams,
one of Washington's earliest commentators.
</P>
<P>
   Seven presidents have had their offices there before becoming
president, along with numerous secretaries of war, state and the
navy. But each of those Cabinet offices eventually sought quarters
elsewhere, and by the late 1940s, the building had become an
extension of its neighbor to the east, the White House, and was
renamed the Executive Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Holt, director of the Dwight D. Eisenhower Library &AMP; Museum
in Abilene, Kan., said he didn't think titles and honorifics ever
impressed the late president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a little reserved about those kind of things,
but I would think that he'd be proud to know about this,
particularly given the history of the building. He'd be pleased
about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2353 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-AGRICULTURALSANCTIONS     10-20 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGRICULTURAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATORS DECRY AGRICULTURAL SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 SANCTIONS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan group of legislators vowed Tuesday to
push harder on the contentious issue of lifting agricultural
sanctions, calling them a ``thoughtless'' and ``absurd'' weapon in
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Republican Sens. John Ashcroft of Missouri and Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska, the group told a press conference that the trade
embargo on food and medicine currently in place against six nations
is only hurting American farmers, consumers and poor people across
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tear down this wall which keeps our farmers from being able to
sell food to hungry individuals around the world,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions are against Cuba, Libya, North Korea, Iran, Iraq
and Sudan. Democratic Sen. Byron Dorgan of North Dakota said that
neither Cuban leader Fidel Castro nor Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi
``ever missed a meal because of a U.S. trade embargo. The only
people hurt by food and medicine embargoes are poor people in those
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of their humanitarian concerns, the legislators said the
sanctions have cost the United States millions of dollars in sales
and opened up those markets to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Those six countries collectively imported $7.2 billion worth of
agricultural products from other countries in 1997, according to
Congressional Research Service. The National Association of Wheat
Growers reported that they imported almost 3.4 million metric tons
of wheat in 1997-98 from outside the United States, a loss to the
domestic economy that the group estimated at $560 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, a top wheat producer, would stand to gain from the
lifting of sanctions, as would Missouri, a major corn and soybean
supplier. Missouri could be losing $7.8 million in soybean sales
alone, some estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the embargo crystallized last month when
Congress passed an emergency aid bill for farmers without the
Ashcroft-Hagel ban on food and medicine sanctions. The Senate
passed the ban in July by a 70-28 vote, and a majority of Senate
and House members fashioning the final agricultural bill favored
its inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But it never made it because of concerns from the Republican
leadership that dropping the embargo against Cuba might offend
Cuban-American voters. At the time, Hagel called his party
leadership actions ``complete nonsense'' and ``buffoonery.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said Tuesday that the White House's chief trade
negotiator, Charlene Barshefsky, has urged him and his colleagues
to push the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
