<HEADER>
A2355 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GOODY-TV-AZR &LR;      10-20 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODY-TV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLY ... COW! ANOTHER TV TABOO FALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Standards erode, customs change, and the next thing you know,
you're watching ``Chicago Hope'' and Mark Harmon is saying . . .
well, I can't tell you exactly what he said because the newspaper's
standards and customs haven't changed enough to allow it.
</P>
<P>
   Shh. Add that sound before the first word of the first sentence
of this story, read the sentence aloud, and you'll re-create the
line of dialogue Harmon uttered near the end of a particularly
frustrating day.
</P>
<P>
   Realistic? Doubtless. Offensive? One might assume so, but only a
handful of people contacted Channel 5, the local CBS affiliate, to
complain. Of course, the low number doubtless has to do with the
show's lack of popularity; so few people watch ``Chicago Hope''
anymore that CBS could offer free flights to anywhere during
commercial breaks and never have to worry about getting anyone to
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, if you read lips even poorly, you can make out that
word and worse coming from athletes' mouths during just about any
major sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you didn't see it coming, hearing the word on a
network television show was a shock.
</P>
<P>
   But not to Nan Anders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Anders sent me an e-mail complaining about
the word ``ass'' popping up all over television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all thought it was pretty funny that they would stoop to
fifth-grade-level words to try to get to the adult market,'' she
wrote. ``We actually started keeping score for a while.'' When Ray
Romano uttered the word ``ass'' on ``Everybody Loves Raymond,''
Anders figured it was open season, that any show could and would
use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any input on what the new `adult' word will be and
when it will be introduced?'' she continued. ``We're betting on
(see above).''
</P>
<P>
   Never, I assured her. Won't happen. Networks simply won't allow
that word on TV.
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't. Until last Thursday. So how did she pick that
word? How did Anders know?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everything else had been used up,'' she said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Anders wanted to engage in a little I-told-you-so
gloating, but she kept things friendly. She's 65 and lives in Sun
City. But if you think she's a cranky prude who sits around
watching television and gathering fodder for things to complain
about, you're way off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my pet word,'' she said of Harmon's utterance. ``But I
don't want to hear it on television.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the use of the word offended her exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really, honestly didn't bother me,'' Anders said. ``I
thought it was a little gratuitous. But it just kind of blew by. If
you really weren't listening, you wouldn't have heard it.''
</P>
<P>
   That, she explained, is the real problem _ that use of
questionable language has become so commonplace that it is
``desensitizing people to where it becomes just everyday
language.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``that'' offends her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody talks like that, but that doesn't mean they
should,'' Anders said. ``You should have standards. . . .
(Television) shouldn't be a reflection of life. I think it should
lead the way. I think it should teach you what can be.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a mighty lofty goal for TV, which feeds off the lowest
common denominator to attract viewers. ``Popular'' is half the
equation of popular culture, after all. Network people said all the
right things about how this wasn't going to become a regular
occurrence, how it is an isolated incident and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   But come on. No one believes that, does he? Once the damn dam is
broken, other words follow. It's becoming increasingly clear that
if you're easily offended by off-color language, your best bet is
not to watch shows that are likely to use it. And that is an
option, something people tend to forget when they're complaining
about television's standards. You can always (gasp) read a book.
This isn't to say that's how things should be, simply that that's
how things are.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, will language on network television get worse? Can
it? Let's go to the expert for her analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're only a year or two away from the f-word,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm skeptical. But when it comes to disagreeing with
Anders on points like this, I've been wrong before. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
