<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KCSCHOOLS-KAN &LR;      10-20 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS PONDER POSSIBLE REMOVAL OF ACCREDITATION FROM KC, ST.
LOUIS SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
 SCHOOLS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mixture of sadness, chagrin and contempt emerged this week
after Missouri lawmakers learned that Kansas City and St. Louis
schools might be stripped of their state accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   But no one who has grappled with the districts' problems in the
last decade seemed surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mood is one of resignation,'' said Democratic Rep.
Steve McLuckie of Kansas City. ``But everyone asks the question:
Isn't there something we can do?''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment, lawmakers said, is likely to spark proposals for
dramatic change, including policies that until recently have been
dismissed as examples of right-wing extremism. They expect new
support for state-paid vouchers that students could use to pay for
private schools, tax deductions for private-school tuition, and
laws that would allow students to attend any public school they
chose.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also will consider ways to encourage private
organizations to operate troubled schools and to force urban
districts to delegate more decision-making to individual schools.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials are even talking about breaking the Kansas
City and St. Louis school districts into smaller districts to
reduce bureaucracy and encourage parent involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas are being tossed around in the wake of state
Education Commissioner Robert Bartman's recommendation to withdraw
accreditation from the state's two largest school districts.
</P>
<P>
   A recent state review found that the Kansas City district failed
to meet any of the 11 standards regarding student performance,
including scores on standardized tests and college entrance exams,
reading ability and dropout rates. The St. Louis district met only
three of the standards.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers across the political spectrum agree that those results
are unacceptable, particularly after more than $3.5 billion in
court-ordered spending to upgrade and desegregate the districts.
</P>
<P>
   That experience has convinced lawmakers that greater funding
will not solve the problems. It also has chafed outstate
legislators who believe that their schools have suffered so that
money could be poured into big-city schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will absolutely not spend more money on those districts,''
said Rep. Delbert Scott of Lowry City, the Republican House leader.
``It's been a total waste. The social experiment has failed. Rural
districts have been robbed for so many years, and look what we have
to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers are looking for alternatives that will give
students a way out of poorly performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   But solutions for individual students often create bigger
problems for those who remain, lawmakers said. And some proposals
invite fights with teachers unions, suburban schools or
public-school advocates, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marsha Campbell, a Kansas City Democrat who championed the
creation of charter schools in 1998, predicted a renewed effort to
allow students to use state vouchers to pay for private school. The
idea has been popular in suburban areas for years but opposed by
urban lawmakers, who argue that it would weaken public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If urban legislators begin to say, `Maybe this is a way out
for our children to get a decent education,''' then prospects for
such legislation brighten considerably, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   The success of charter schools _ which are publicly funded but
operate independently of the district _ shows the strong demand for
public education, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell and others argue that vouchers undercut public
schools by draining off the most active families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to educate the masses,'' said Democratic Rep. Bill
Skaggs of Kansas City. ``What about kids whose parents' only
involvement is to say, `Go to school'? And some parents don't even
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Bill Kenney of Lee's Summit said vouchers were a
difficult battle because teachers' unions saw them as a threat.
</P>
<P>
   He said he preferred a system of state scholarships that would
provide $2,500 to $3,000 a year that low-income students could use
to attend private schools. The remainder of the tuition could be
paid through a foundation funded with corporate and other
donations.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarships amount to about half of the amount of per-pupil
funding for public schools. Their advocates might go along if the
public schools were allowed to keep the other half, thereby
increasing their average per-pupil funding.
</P>
<P>
   McLuckie said he expected proposals to allow students to go to
any public school. But that would not help students who lacked
transportation to outlying schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And suburban lawmakers said they would oppose any plan that
would involve busing students to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, several lawmakers urged that the
legislature move cautiously. House Speaker Steve Gaw said he was
considering appointing a committee to gather information on the
ramifications of urban districts' loss of accreditation and the
potential impact on nearby suburban districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't put our heads in the sand, but we also shouldn't
rush in without knowing the implications,'' Gaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carson Ross, a Blue Springs Republican, said new
legislation was premature when lawmakers did not even know the
effect of laws enacted last year. He said he was encouraged by the
early performance of Kansas City's new superintendent, Benjamin
Demps Jr., and the competition for students that charter schools
had created.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make changes every time someone coughs, you never get
anything done,'' Ross said. ``We don't need to tamper with what we
have in place right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
