<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO TOPPER FOR THIS EPIC SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turn off the television Wednesday night. There will be
nothing worth watching. There may never be anything quite as
compelling as what transpired in recent evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Those two battered teams, the Braves and the Mets, will not
conduct a historic seventh game. They have given enough. They
played three of the most physically grueling and emotionally
draining post-season games that baseball has ever seen,
particularly in sequence. Ten innings. Fifteen innings. Eleven
innings. But now it is over.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will not come all the way back from the edge of three
straight losses. They scared the Braves, but ultimately lost, 10-9,
in the 11th inning at 12:38 Wednesday morning. There will be no
shot at four straight, but the Mets and Braves will always be
remembered for these three games, the late innings, the scrambled
scorecards, the pitchers working out of turn, in autumnal
desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Like cars parked on a New York street, the Mets and Braves have
their nicks and dings from a grueling post-season now two weeks
long. But the two gallant teams chugged out into heavy traffic
Wednesday night, producing yet another classic game of chicken in
the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   It finally ended after Gerald Williams, a former Yankee, doubled
to lead off the 11th against Kenny Rogers, normally a starting
pitcher, but nothing has been normal for many, many days. A
sacrifice moved Williams to third. Two intentional walks loaded the
bases. And Jones, from Curacao, took a 3-2 pitch for the walk that
ended this series for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   It will be noted in New York that John Rocker, who took on the
yowling mob in Shea Stadium over the last hectic weekend, and who
walked away from an automobile wreck Monday afternoon in Atlanta,
now gets to pitch in a World Series against the Yankees. If he
doesn't like the vile maledictions in Flushing, Rocker should bring
his ear plugs to Yankee Stadium, where the Bleacher Creatures lurk.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mets head for a well-earned winter tuneup. Nobody
needs it more than Mike Piazza, the most serially injured player of
all, who hit a game-tying homer Wednesday night but had to come out
in the ninth, just too beaten up to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza took one more tumble Wednesday night when he was upended
by Brian Jordan, whose wide slide would have earned him 15 yards
for unnecessary roughness in his National Football League days.
Jordan, unhappy with being hit on the hand by Turk Wendell, who was
surely pitching him inside, exacted his revenge on the ankles of
Piazza, who was six inches up the baseline from home plate after
stepping on home plate for a force with no chance to throw the
runner out at first. There was a bit of bristling by both teams,
but no repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza has taken so much incoming fire in recent weeks that he
finally had to come out after 13 innings in Sunday night's epic
game, two innings before the Mets stunned the Braves for a second
straight game in rather dramatic fashion. Twenty-four hours of
lounging around the hotel bought Piazza some time, but he could
still feel his strained left forearm, plus every collision, every
whack, every foul tip, every tumble he has endured in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a hit out on me,'' Piazza said, without
total confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves showed compassion when they clobbered him at home
plate, but they still stole five bases on him Wednesday night,
trying to insure that the Mets did not do anything truly historic
to them.
</P>
<P>
   The big catcher is dragging after two rounds of _ remember,
Major League Baseball hates this word _ playoffs. It sounds so much
like one of those tacky winter sports. Baseball is infatuated with
this cash cow, the three-tiered post-season, and if it happens to
chew up the most vulnerable talent, pitchers like Randy Johnson and
David Cone and catchers like Piazza, well, the ledger book tells
the owners it was all worth it _ for them, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Yet baseball keeps coming up with these classic games, late in
these post-season series. The Mariners' comeback over the Yankees
in the division series in 1995. The Yankees' comeback over the
Braves in the 1996 World Series. The very fact of the Florida
Marlins in 1997. And even El Duque, Orlando Hernandez, saving the
Yankees in the championship series last year.
</P>
<P>
   For all these heroics, no team has ever come from three games
down to tie a post-season series. The Mets and their bruised
catcher came close to history. They had a magnificent run, but they
now go up on the blocks, resting their weary frames. Their season
is over.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
