<SLUG> BC-JANUS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANUS FUND MANAGER IS APPOINTED JANUS CAPITAL'S RESEARCH DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Craig, portfolio manager of Janus Capital Corp.'s flagship
mutual fund, will relinquish his daily duties to become the fund
company's director of research.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, 43, will remain Janus' chief investment officer, but he
no longer will manage the $31 billion Janus Fund. Craig became
manager of the fund in 1987, when its assets totaled $377 million.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Bailey, Janus' chief executive officer, said Craig's
focus would be to strengthen the investment management team by
recruiting, training and mentoring analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Blaine Rollins will replace Craig as the Janus Fund's manager in
January. Rollins, 32, has been Craig's assistant on the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins also has been portfolio manager of the Janus Balanced
and Janus Equity Income funds. Succeeding Rollins as manager of
those funds will be Karen Reidy, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Ingalls, a Janus spokeswoman, said the change in Craig's
role had been planned for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim's single-minded dedication to developing our investment
management team will ensure that we continue our tradition of great
stock-picking,'' Bailey said. ``With Jim in this role, every Janus
shareholder will benefit directly from his influence, not just
shareholders of the portfolios he manages.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern Industries Inc. is the parent company of
Janus. Its top officer applauded Janus' move.
</P>
<P>
   Landon H. Rowland, Kansas City Southern's chairman and chief
executive officer, said Janus' continued growth had led to the need
for an overseer of all its mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Craig has the capacity and the record to carry on the
progress that Janus has made,'' Rowland said. ``We're extremely
pleased with this announcement. It's a sign of Janus' continued
growth in its organizational management structure as its assets
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern plans to spin off Janus and several other
financial service companies into a separate, publicly traded
entity. Included in the new company, Stilwell Financial Inc., will
be Berger Associates Inc. and Nelson Money Managers PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Some Janus principals in recent months have proposed that Janus
be spun off individually, without being attached to Kansas City
Southern's other financial service firms. Kansas City Southern has
rejected that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said Tuesday that his move was unrelated to the tussle
between Janus and Kansas City Southern, calling it ``a sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig said his appointment was driven by organizational changes
at Janus, which now has 21 research analysts. His goal, he said,
``is to increase the flow of ideas of portfolio managers.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver-based Janus is the country's fastest-growing mutual fund
company, managing about $170 billion in assets for more than 2.5
million investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-20 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER MANY RALLIES AND 11 INNINGS, METS RUN OUT OF MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Subway Series will not take the IRT to Queens. It
will ride Marta in Atlanta instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, as remarkable a team as has ever played a post-season
baseball game, ran out of incredulous comebacks early Wednesday
morning, dropping an 11-inning, 10-9 decision to the Braves in Game
6 of the National League Championship Series. Playing perhaps even
more magically than their 1969 ancestors in the past three weeks,
the Mets overcame deficits of 5-0 and 7-3, snatched 8-7 and 9-8
leads of their own and finally succumbed when Kenny Rogers threw a
bases-loaded 3-2 pitch high and outside to Andruw Jones, forcing
home Gerald Williams, who had started the inning with a double.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of four playoff games this month, Bobby Cox, the
Braves' manager, used two of his four starting pitchers in relief.
Kevin Millwood, who had pitched a one-hitter in the second game of
the division series against Houston, secured a 5-3 victory in Game
3 by pitching the 12th inning. In the second game of the NLCS
against the Mets, Smoltz made the first relief appearance of his
career and preserved a 4-3 victory with his ninth-inning effort.
</P>
<P>
   Cox resisted the temptation to use Millwood in relief in the
15th inning of Sunday's Game 5 in New York, and the Mets rallied
for two runs and a 4-3 victory. But Cox called on Smoltz in the
seventh inning Tuesday night, and he did not fare as well in the
second relief appearance of his career as he did in the first. The
Mets, continuing to display the most remarkable resiliency in their
history, battered Smoltz for four runs in the space of five batters
and overcame their second large deficit of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The day before this game, Millwood had expressed a view that so
many players on teams with a 3-2 series lead have uttered. ``We
definitely don't want it to go to a seventh game,'' the pitcher
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who had the look of a loser after Game 5, wasted no
time trying to make sure a seventh game would be out of the
question. They scored five runs and knocked Al Leiter out after he
had pitched to only six batters and thrown 25 pitches. Pitching on
three days' rest, an unnatural act for him, Leiter hit two of the
batters, walked another and gave up run-scoring singles to two
others.
</P>
<P>
   Cox had not used Millwood in relief Sunday because, he explained
yet again before Game 6, ``our club was not in desperation,''
``there's no guarantee he's going to lock it up on a rain-slickened
mound'' and ``he still had a game to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   This was that game, and Millwood made Cox look brilliant _ for
five innings. He maintained his 5-0 advantage easily, holding the
Mets to four harmless hits. But these Mets could be contained for
only so long. They came out scorching in the sixth inning, erupting
for three runs, the last two scoring on Darryl Hamilton's third
single, which also knocked Millwood out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets had wanted to make this comeback easy, they would
have held the Braves scoreless in their half of the sixth. But Turk
Wendell allowed the Braves to load the bases, and Dennis Cook gave
up a two-run pinch-hit single to Jose Hernandez. The hit gave the
Braves a four-run lead, but the Mets had already overcome a
five-run deficit, so obliterating that four-run Atlanta advantage
should not have been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. Smoltz came in to start the seventh. Cox used him
there because he didn't have another game to pitch, not in this
series; the mound wasn't wet and the Braves, well, maybe a trace of
desperation was creeping in.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz had started Game 4, allowing only two runs in seven and a
third innings. But that was the game the Mets used to begin their
comeback, scoring two runs in the eighth inning for a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franco, the Mets' pinch-hitter deluxe, was the first batter
Smoltz would face. Twice before in the series, Bobby Valentine, the
Mets' manager, had sent the left-hand-hitting Franco to the plate
to pinch-hit, but Cox had countered with a left-handed pitcher and
Franco was replaced by another pinch-hitter. This time, though, he
faced the right-handed Smoltz and drilled a line drive to
right-center field for a double.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson, slumbering much of this series, also rapped a
double, this one along the left-field line, and the Braves led,
7-4. Edgardo Alfonzo scared the Braves and their suddenly lively
fans by hitting a fly ball to the fence in right field, but Brian
Jordan was there to catch it for the first out.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud followed with another ball hit to right, but this
one went on a line and dropped in for a single as Henderson
scampered home. Now the Braves' lead was 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter was Mike Piazza, whose own play had epitomized
the admirable style of play the Mets had exhibited. The catcher
kept getting knocked down with injuries, but he kept getting up.
His next at-bat would be his crowning moment in the playoffs. He
swung at the last pitch Smoltz would deliver and drove it high over
the fence in right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Braves 7, Mets 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, the incredulity of their play rising batter by batter,
took the lead, 8-7, in the eighth when Melvin Mora singled home a
run against Mike Remlinger. But they let down their guard and
allowed the Braves to tie them in their eighth turn at bat. Brian
Hunter singled home their run against John Franco.
</P>
<P>
   The teams reprised that inning in the 10th. The Mets scored a
run on Todd Pratt's sacrifice fly against John Rocker, the Braves'
closer; the Braves scored on Ozzie Guillen's single against Armando
Benitez, the Mets' closer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, however, did not score in the 11th. The Braves did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
