<HEADER>
A2362 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-NOBELPRIZE-KAN &LR;      10-20 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY JERRY HEASTER 
</HEADLINE>
 PRIZE-KAN  
 Honoring supply-side economics  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the Nobel committee didn't get into supply-side
economics when honoring Robert A. Mundell, his prize signified
indisputable recognition of how this once obscure economist changed
the world's political economy.
</P>
<P>
   This year's economics award focused on Mundell's theories about
how exchange-rate policies affect global capital flows and monetary
and fiscal policy. He is credited with providing the intellectual
framework for the euro's creation, which may prove this
generation's most critical experiment in economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   As admirers point out, though, the common thread of his work has
been built on the notion that the wealth of nations is a result of
commitments to free trade, strong and stable currencies,
anti-inflationary policies and relatively low tax burdens.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Mundell became the key architect of supply-side
economics. In a 1990 article, he noted the importance of tax reform
embracing a ``drastic slashing of marginal tax rates.'' This theory
is rooted in the assumption that government should encourage
productive behavior by workers and investors by reducing tax
burdens while minimizing government's regulation of the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Mundell began his work in a postwar world of fixed exchange
rates and a widely accepted presumption that economies were closed
systems. Mundell argued, however, that the only closed economy was
the global economy. Some ridiculed the claim, which since has
evolved from disputed theory to recognized economic reality.
Countries that have in recent times attempted to pursue economic
policies independent of what their economic partners were doing
have suffered hard times in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of supply-side theory took form in the '70s as
Mundell, joined by his student Arthur Laffer, pondered how the
combination of stagnant growth and hyperinflation defied the
Keynesian model of demand-side economics.
</P>
<P>
   Supply side as theory was tested in practice during the 1980s by
the Reagan administration. While supply side isn't much discussed
anymore, it remains part of the U.S. economic policy mix. It
survives because it worked, although both its friends and foes are
reluctant to give credit where it's due because of the theory's
controversial nature.
</P>
<P>
   The proof of its success, however, has been the durability of
the economic expansion that began 17 years ago next month. Except
for a nine-month recession in 1990-91, the U.S. growth trend has
been steadily up since the practical test of supply-side theory was
initiated. Not even huge tax increases pushed by Presidents Bush
and Clinton have been enough to stop the momentum established in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the stock market as measured by the Dow Jones
industrial average soared from just under 800 to over 11,000, and
overall employment surged from just under 100 million to over 133
million. Despite the remarkable run of growth during this period,
the annual inflation rate has plunged from double digits to last
year's 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although supply-side economics was dismissed by mainstream
economists as lacking intellectual credibility, Mundell's honor
goes a long way toward giving it the respect it has always
deserved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
