A2363 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBN-NLCS-LEDE-TEX     10-20 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
 
ATLANTA HEADING TO FIFTH WORLD SERIES IN 1990s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There will be no Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   It took 4 hours and 25 minutes Tuesday night, but the Atlanta
Braves finally rid themselves of the New York Mets in this National
League Championship Series to earn their fifth World Series
appearance in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers, the Mets' eighth pitcher of the game, issued a
one-out, bases-loaded walk to center fielder Andruw Jones on a full
count to score Gerald Williams in the bottom of the 11th inning.
``I was trying to make sure I didn't take wings,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' 10-9 victory allowed them to eliminate the Mets at
12:38 a.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who replaced closer Armando Benitez, surrendered a
leadoff double to Williams, who advanced to third on the sacrifice
bunt of second baseman Bret Boone. Rogers walked third baseman
Chipper Jones and right fielder Brian Jordan intentionally, and the
left-hander could not throw a strike when he and the Mets needed it
most.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets took a 9-8 lead in the 10th inning. Benny Agbayani drew
a leadoff walk from Braves closer John Rocker, and Mets manager
Bobby Valentine instructed Rey Ordonez to attempt a sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez failed, though, and popped the bunt into the glove of
first baseman Brian Hunter. Agbayani attempted to move into scoring
position with a stolen base, but Rocker caught him breaking toward
second and threw to first. Hunter's throw to shortstop Walt Weiss,
though, hit Agbayani in the back, and he later scored on Todd
Pratt's one-out sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves answered against Benitez and forced the evening to
continue on the one-out, run-scoring single by pinch hitter Ozzie
Guillen. ``They were as tough of games as you'll ever want to be
involved in,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said of Game 6 and Game 5,
which the Mets won in 15 innings.
</P>
<P>
   For five innings, it appeared the Mets would never utilize their
closer. Left-hander Al Leiter, the Mets' best big-game pitcher,
invited the buzzards to form and circle early with his
six-batters-and-out performance. Leiter hit two batters, issued a
walk, surrendered two singles and allowed another to reach base on
a fielder's choice on a grounder hit to the mound in the Braves'
five-run inning. ``I thought we had a pretty good crack at them in
the first inning, but it got a little bit harry there later,'' Cox
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter joined Pittsburgh's Bob Moose as the only starting
pitchers in NLCS history not to record an out, and the Mets'
miraculous run during this best-of-seven series appeared done
before right-hander Pat Mahomes threw his first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes, though, provided four scoreless innings, and the Mets
struck their first blows in the sixth inning. Consecutive singles
by Edgardo Alfonzo and John Olerud off Kevin Millwood began the
evening's unlikely chain of events, and the Mets scored their first
run on Mike Piazza's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton delivered the clutch hit, a one-out, two-run
single that pulled the Mets within two runs and prompted Millwood's
exit. Atlanta responded to the Mets' challenge during the bottom
half of the inning against right-hander Turk Wendell, and the
Braves breathed a collective sigh of relief after a two-out,
two-run single by pinch hitter Jose Hernandez off left-hander
Dennis Cook.
</P>
<P>
   That 7-3 lead, though, didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied in the seventh inning against right-hander John
Smoltz. Matt Franco and Rickey Henderson hit consecutive doubles,
and the latter scored on Olerud's one-out single.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the evening's most dramatic at-bat to
that point.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, the Mets' banged-up catcher, strode to the plate hitting
.136 (3-for-22) for the series before pummeling Smoltz's 2-1
offering for a game-tying, two-run homer that shocked most _ if not
all _ of the 52,335 spectators at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Concern took over after Melvin Mora's pinch-hit, run-scoring
single off left-hander Mike Remlinger gave New York an 8-7 lead,
but Mets left-hander John Franco could not preserve it in the
bottom half of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Braves catcher Eddie Perez reached on a one-out single, and
manager Bobby Cox inserted Otis Nixon as a pinch runner. Nixon
stole second _ one of Atlanta's six stolen bases Tuesday night _
and advanced to third on Piazza's throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter's game-tying single ensured that this
thrill-a-minute contest carried into the early-morning hours. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
