<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG)--CORRECTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER MAKES IT ALL LOOK EASIER
</HEADLINE>
 TO LAKERS WINNING  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SAN DIEGO _ So who plays in Kobe Bryant's absence? Phil Jackson
made the decision sound easy, almost automatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait 'till you see him play this offense with the rest of the
guys,'' Jackson said of Ron Harper. ``Then you'll say, `Gee, he
really makes everything run a lot smoother for this team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After the Lakers' 97-90 win over the Golden State Warriors in
Tuesday's exhibition game at the San Diego Sports Arena, there was
only one thing to say about Harper's performance: !ital!Gee, he
really makes everything run a lot smoother for this team.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Harper's sore right knee and his lack of practice time
with the Lakers. Jackson, who coached Harper for five seasons in
Chicago, said before tipoff that the 35-year-old guard, in any
condition, would make the Lakers a better team when it came to
running the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   Results were quick. Harper, running with the first team, helped
the Lakers take a modest lead in the first quarter. But it was
after the Lakers' second team fell to a double-digit deficit in the
second quarter that Harper really made an impact.
</P>
<P>
   He re-entered the game with 4:49 left in the first half, the
Lakers down by 16 points. By halftime, the Lakers had pulled within
two points, 49-47. Harper scored four points in the run, including
a 3-point play, though that didn't account for his non-statistical
contributions. Harper also started the third quarter, and the
Lakers had a 10-point lead by the time he went back to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the offense,'' Harper said. ``I know where I'm supposed
to go and what I'm going to do. It's not new to me. . . . It will
help guys out, because you have to have someone who knows something
about what they're trying to do out there.''
</P>
<P>
   So what the Lakers will miss in Bryant's athleticism and scoring
as he heals from a broken hand, they will make up for with Harper's
knowledge. Jackson's only other real option was Rick Fox or rookie
Devean George.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher, Harper's backcourt mate, said there's a clear
difference with Harper on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he does allow things to flow a little better because a
lot of times, whether he cuts or makes a pass, he'll define what
option of the triangle we take advantage of, and I think it helps a
lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he would only play Harper about 15 minutes, out of
deference to his surgically repaired right knee and his lack of
conditioning. Harper ended up playing 22 minutes and finished with
nine points, six rebounds, two steals and two assists in his Lakers
debut.
</P>
<P>
   The game also featured Jackson's first technical foul as Lakers
coach. He earned it in the first quarter with a few verbal jousts
at official Leroy Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   __ True test: After the Laker Shootout at the Forum on Thursday
and Friday, the Lakers will have played three games in four days.
All that full-speed work should provide a clearer picture of the
team's progress, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens in a game is the intensity picks up naturally, so
their reaction has to pick up,'' he said. ``We've been on them
about their execution, about their passing right now. That's one of
our focuses, how good a passing team can we be . . . and under the
duress of the opponents stepping it up and playing tough defense.
It really makes sense for us to have more games because that
doesn't come in the practice setting as much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2380 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-2N     10-20 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUNG BY DEBATE, INDONESIAN PRESIDENT ENDS ELECTION BID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs grafs 1-4 for updating, rewriting) (bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Humiliated by a midnight ballot in the
national assembly that condemned his record, President B.J. Habibie
withdrew as a candidate for president on Wednesday and the assembly
prepared to vote hours later for Indonesia's next leader.
</P>
<P>
   An official of Habibie's party said he had ``conceded gracefully
not to run'' after the newly independent assembly, in a largely
symbolic vote, rejected his recent state of the nation address by a
margin of just 33 ballots of 690 cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was satisfied by my term in office,'' Habibie told reporters
at his home on Wednesday morning. ``I was given the opportunity to
devote myself to this nation. I'm happy that democracy has started
in Indonesia and I hope this will continue whoever the new
President is.''
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates were left to compete for the presidency: Megawati
Sukarnoputri, the opposition leader who won the most votes in a
parliamentary election in June, and Abdurrahman Wahid, an
influential Muslim leader who was once her closest political ally.
</P>
<P>
   The election of a new president will complete a tumultuous
transition from Indonesia's autocratic former president, Suharto,
who was forced to resign in May 1998. The vote against Habibie, a
close associate of Suharto who took his place as president, was a
sign of the momentum of democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the members of the assembly that will choose the
president were elected last June in Indonesia's first free
nationwide ballot in a generation. There are fears of unrest in
Indonesia if Ms. Megawati fails to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the vote on Habibie, the chairman of the assembly,
Amien Rais, announced that the group had decided by consensus to
end a quarter century of Indonesian rule in East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
   That decision formally accepted the results of an Aug. 30
referendum in which 87.5 percent of the people of East Timor voted
for independence. The referendum was followed by a wave of violence
that caused the deployment of an international peacekeeping force
that is still struggling to pacify the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said Indonesia would hand over
formal control of East Timor to the United Nations before year's
end. The United Nations plans to administer the territory for two
to three years as a transition to independent rule.
</P>
<P>
   In a session that took several significant steps toward remaking
Indonesia's political structure, the assembly also agreed by
consensus to limit the president to two five-year terms and to
shift lawmaking power from the president to the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Those steps toward establishing a more democratic and
accountable government were mirrored by the free-wheeling demeanor
of the assembly, flexing and admiring its new muscles after three
decades of subservience to Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Not once but twice in recent days, representatives of each of 11
parliamentary factions presented lengthy _ and mostly damning _
critiques of Habibie's state of the nation address, which he
presented last Thursday. The speeches were interrupted repeatedly
from the floor by legislators who, under Suharto, would have been
ejected for their effrontery.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Habibie sat to one side of the speaker's podium,
like a reprimanded schoolboy, grimacing and scribbling notes.
</P>
<P>
   No Indonesian president had ever been subjected to such
humiliation _ or such democracy. There was a certain dignity and
even bravery in this. Habibie is the first Indonesian president to
maintain a measure of humility about his role.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie was suffering not only for his own perceived sins but
also for those of his mentor and friend, Suharto, who was the real
foil for the changes taking place here.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations leveled at Habibie during the last few days in
the assembly had their roots in the abuses of Suharto's 32 years in
power: corruption, violations of human rights, the debacle of
Indonesian rule in East Timor and Habibie's refusal to pursue his
predecessor in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Indonesia's Supreme Court _ apparently no longer
feeling the need to support Habibie _ ruled that an auditor's
report must be released to the Parliament in a high-profile bank
scandal that has badly damaged his political standing.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy over the allegations that $80 million intended to help
banks restructure their debts had been channeled to Habibie's
supporters had led to a suspension of $4.7 billion in international
loans.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the vote Monday night, his candidacy had been
further wounded when the armed forces chief, Wiranto, went on
television to announce that he would not accept Habibie's
invitation to stand as his Vice Presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement suggested to some analysts that the military
had made a political judgment that Habibie was not likely to win
the election and that it would be politically damaging to be allied
with him. The general's withdrawal also freed military officers in
the legislature to vote against Habibie. The military controls a
bloc of more than 40 votes in the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many poignant moments for Habibie, a marginal
figure under Suharto who tried in vain to fill his shoes as
president. Wiranto had played a key role in May 1998 in telling
Suharto that the time had come for him to step down. He had then
become Habibie's first and most crucial ally.
</P>
<P>
   With his damning announcement Sunday, Wiranto earned the
distinction of having signaled to two successive presidents that
they had lost power.
</P>
<P>
   In the theater of Indonesian public life, where all Suharto had
to do was smile enigmatically to demonstrate his power, the last
few days of unabashed criticism appeared to have drained Habibie of
his public standing.
</P>
<P>
   The reading of the vote that sealed his future late Monday
night, with each tally marked on a large white board at the front
of the chamber, was accompanied by hoots and cheers and catcalls
that one local reporter compared to the irreverence of schoolboys.
</P>
<P>
   When the final count was announced, many of the parliamentarians
raised their palms in Muslim prayer and shouted, ``God is great!''
Some hugged each other.
</P>
<P>
   In the press gallery above, Indonesian reporters began to dance
and clap and wave their arms, and led the hall in the singing of
the national anthem: ``Free, Free Indonesia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 0142EDT &QL; 
