<SLUG> BC-STRIP20-LSTROMENGER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATION AREA NEAR CAN YON URGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new bill by Rep. Bob Stump challenges Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt's plans to preserve the vast lands northwest of the Grand
Canyon, calling instead for continued mining, road construction,
air tours and land giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   Stump, R-Ariz., told a U.S. House Resources subcommittee Tuesday
that his plan for a Shivwits Plateau National Conservation Area
would protect the environment and allow traditional and historic
uses of more than 500,000 acres across the southern tip of the
Arizona Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``H.R. 2795 protects the remoteness, native biodiversity and
ecological richness of the Shivwits Plateau, but at the same time
increases public awareness, outdoor recreation use enjoyment,''
Stump said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt joined environmentalists in denouncing the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation actually weaken(s) protections in existing
law,'' Babbitt testified, ``and would make it difficult if not
impossible to protect sensitive, valuable resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Stump, whose sprawling District 3 covers western Arizona and the
West Valley's Sun Cities, wants to create a ``national conservation
area'' in the sparsely populated lands settled over the past
century by Mormon pioneer ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   Stump said he developed his legislation in response to Babbitt's
plans announced last year for a Shivwits Plateau National Monument.
The measure was drafted, he said, after months of consultation with
those who live and work on the Arizona Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than stopping mining and development, as proposed under
Babbitt's plan, critics said, Stump's bill would specifically
prevent the Interior secretary from halting uranium mining near the
Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Stump's bill, they said, would also allow the spraying of toxic
herbicides and bulldozing of trees and bushes to open up grasslands
for local ranchers. And it would disclose the locations of
archaeological sites and delete proposed wilderness protections
from Glen Canyon National Recreation Area, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill would strip the Arizona Strip,'' said Dave Simon of
the National Parks and Conservation Association, one of several
environmental groups opposing Stump.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Eaton of the Wilderness Society said, ``I am stumped by Mr.
Stump's bill. He says that he wants to protect the lands
surrounding Grand Canyon National Park, then he goes on to ensure
they are pillaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Smith of the Sierra Club said Stump's bill ``should be
called the Grand Canyon National Destruction Act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal declares war on the wilderness and antiquities
of the Grand Canyon's wildest region,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Barnard, president of the Grand Canyon Trust, said Stump's
bill is about conservation ``in name only.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill must be put to a merciful death, and after that is
done, we have to go back to the drawing board and design a proposal
for real Shivwits protection,'' Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   Stump denounced the environmentalists' assessments as lacking
``any substance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in this bill that increases or encourages the
commercialization of the Shivwits Plateau,'' Stump said in a
statement released after Tuesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   A rancher, local county supervisors from Arizona and Utah and a
representative of Arizona Gov. Jane Hull testified in favor of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the existing use of the Shivwits Plateau is
balanced, appropriate and sensitive to the natural and historic
wonder of this beautiful part of the state of Arizona,'' Hull said
in a letter Tuesday to Rep. Jim Hansen, R-Utah, chairman of the
subcommittee on national parks and public lands.
</P>
<P>
   Hays Gilstrap, an Arizona Game and Fish Commissioner who
testified in behalf of Hull, said Stump's bill takes into account
the needs of the people who live on the Arizona Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Stump) also knows the commitments made by the federal
government to the people of Arizona regarding the use of this area,
and his bill incorporates those past promises,'' Gilstrap said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Babbitt spent two days traveling the region with
some of the nation's top environmentalists and some of the
Southwest's top brass of the National Park Service and U.S. Bureau
of Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   After scanning the area's canyons and climbing to the top of
7,000-foot Mount Dellenbaugh, Babbitt declared his intent to see
the establishment of a new national monument. He said it would be
preferable for Congress to establish the monument. But if that
fails, Babbitt said, he will recommend that President Clinton use
his powers under the 1906 Antiquities Act to establish a monument
through an executive action.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said his plans would ensure that ranching and hunting
across the Arizona Strip could continue. But at public hearings
earlier this year, ranchers and others voiced their suspicion of
any new federal controls. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at (602) 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
