<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES LOOKING FORWARD TO THEIR NEXT TRIP TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The rowdy John Rocker and his Atlanta Braves teammates
are returning to New York, the site of Rocker's war of words with
the city's baseball fans. But Rocker, who exchanged expletives and
obscene gestures with Mets fans throughout the National League
Championship Series, said he did not expect to have such a nasty
relationship with those who cheer for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no problem with the Yankees fans,'' said Rocker, who
pitched two innings in Game 6 as the Braves clinched their fifth
World Series appearance of the decade early Wednesday morning with
a 10-9, 11th-inning victory over the Mets at Turner Field.
``They're some of the best fans around, and I'm going to enjoy
playing at Yankee Stadium. Of course, it's a historic stadium and I
can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones, who told the fans at Shea Stadium to begin
rooting for the Yankees after his work as a one-man wrecking crew
left the Mets all but dead near the end of the regular season, said
he didn't plan to ignite as much of a furor in his next trip to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't giving nothing,'' Jones said when asked if he would
engage in trash talk with Yankees fans. ``I'm sure I'll have to
take a little bit. It's New York.''
</P>
<P>
   As the champagne squirted from bottles and the cheers and hugs
filled the clubhouse, the Braves refused to talk about strategy or
matchups for the World Series against the defending champion
Yankees. Manager Bobby Cox said he had not thought about who would
be his starting pitcher Saturday in Game 1 at Turner Field, though
Tom Glavine, who would have been the Game 7 starter against the
Mets, was the most likely candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having the league's best regular-season record at
103-59, the Braves consider themselves to be the underdogs. That
may be a ploy to get in the Yankees' heads or to take the pressure
off themselves, but Jones said no one expected the Braves to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the world champs you have to beat the world champs,'' he
said. ``They've been the best team in the league over the past
three or four years, at the top of the heap, so it's going to be a
tough job for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're obviously the favorites and we're the underdogs, so
we've just got to play our hearts out and let the chips fall where
they may.''
</P>
<P>
   In this new era of interleague play, the Braves met the Yankees
three times during the regular season, winning two of three games
at Yankee Stadium. Glavine defeated Roger Clemens, 6-2; Russ
Springer was the winner in a 10-7 victory, and Andy Pettitte led
the Yankees to an 11-4 victory in the third game of that mid-July
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did O.K. against them in the regular season, so we feel
good about our chances,'' said Kevin Millwood, who started Game 6
against the Mets but was relieved after allowing three runs and
eight hits in five and a third innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go out and pitch the way that we can and hit the ball,
we can win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The clubs also met in the World Series in 1996 in what became a
nightmarish experience for Atlanta. After outscoring the Yankees by
16-1 in taking a two-games-to-none lead, they lost four straight
games. Strangely, the Braves won the first two games at Yankee
Stadium before losing all three times at home.
</P>
<P>
   This Series also holds implications of which team will be called
the team of the decade. The Braves, winners of eight straight
division titles but only one World Series in the 1990s, would
probably get the nod if they defeat the Yankees. The Yankees would
almost certainly take the title if they win their third
championship in four years.
</P>
<P>
   After winning such a exhausting series with the Mets, the Braves
don't want to end the millennium empty-handed, as they have so
often this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this has been a great run and we want to finish it
off,'' pitcher John Smoltz said. ``All we want to do is win the
1999 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do some of the things we got away with in this
series. We can't do that against the Yankees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
