<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS &LR;      10-20 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ If you're going to gamble, you might as well do it with
someone named Kenny Rogers on the mound.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a manager loads the bases with a pair of intentional walks,
he's betting his pitcher will be able to throw strikes to the
hitter of choice. Rogers' inability to do so Tuesday night ended
the New York Mets' improbable rise from the grave in a 10-9,
11-inning loss to the Atlanta Braves in Game 6 of the National
League Championship Series at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers walked Braves center fielder Andruw Jones with the bases
loaded, forcing home the winning run and sending the Braves into
the World Series against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kenny felt he could throw a pitch and get him (Jones)
to swing on something on his own _ possibly early _ and he didn't
do it,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves appeared set to make short work of the Mets when they
jumped out to a 3-0 lead in the best-of-seven NLCS. But the Mets
won the next two games, making a strong bid to become the first
team in the history of postseason baseball to overcome a three-game
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Never was their resilience greater than Tuesday, when fell
behind by five runs after an inning but then chased red-hot Braves
starter Kevin Millwood from the game in the sixth. By the time the
seventh rolled around, John Smoltz came trotting from the bullpen
to protect a 7-3 Atlanta lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tied the game with four seventh-inning runs off Smoltz,
and the teams exchanged runs in the eighth and 10th innings before
the Braves had the last laugh in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what baseball is all about,'' said Braves left fielder
Gerald Williams, whose double started the 11th-inning rally. ``You
never know when you're going to be down, and you never know when
you're going to be up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep doing things that are going to allow you
to compete from inning to inning. Even when we lost the lead, we
knew that didn't mean we lost the game. Our guys never gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine spoke proudly when he said his team left it all on the
field in Sunday's Game 5 marathon, won 4-3 by the Mets in 15
innings.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong. There was plenty left in the Mets' tanks, almost
enough to deny the Braves a chance to defend their Team of the '90s
title in the World Series. Those holding out hope for a Subway
Series will have to settle for a rematch of the 1996 World Series,
which the Yankees won in six games over the Braves. Game 1 comes
Saturday night at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's clincher gave the Braves their ninth NL pennant and
their fifth of the decade, but this one almost slipped through
their grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to play better (against the Yankees) than we played
in the last four games, that's for sure,'' said Braves catcher
Eddie Perez, named Most Valuable Player of the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets wore the face of defeat early in the evening when
starter Al Leiter, working on three days' rest for only the second
time in his career, lasted just six batters and didn't record an
out. It tied for the shortest outing in LCS history.
</P>
<P>
   The first six Braves reached base before righthanded reliever
Pat Mahomes finally recorded an out on Brian Hunter's sacrifice
fly. Prior to that, Perez stroked a two-run single, Brian Jordan
had an RBI base hit, and Williams scored from third on an error by
Mets catcher Mike Piazza, who made a bad throw trying to thwart a
double steal.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets pulled within two runs with a three-run sixth inning
highlighted by Darryl Hamilton's two-run single. The Braves loaded
the bases against Mets reliever Turk Wendell in the bottom of the
inning, and pinch hitter Jose Hernandez alleviated the traffic jam
with a two-out, two-run single off Dennis Cook to push the Braves'
lead to 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, the Mets treated Smoltz no better than they did
rookie Kevin McGlinchy in his Game 5 pounding. Smoltz gave up one
rocket after another, culminating with Piazza's game-tying two-run
homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held their hitters in check for most of the series and most
of the year, and then all of a sudden everything was a line
drive,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``Smoltz was throwing
harder than I've seen him throw all year, and he got hit hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets outfielder Melvin Mora broke the tie with a single in the
eighth, but Hunter's line drive up the middle knotted the score
again in the bottom of the inning. The Mets scored again in the
10th on Todd Pratt's sacrifice fly, but the Braves answered that,
too, pulling even on Ozzie Guillen's pinch-hit single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take some time during the winter to watch these
games and try to enjoy them like I think millions of people got to
enjoy them,'' Valentine said. ``I think they were fabulous games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
