<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-20 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ Destiny? Bobby Valentine got a kick out of that one.
Sure, his Mets were still kicking, against some pretty unfavorable
odds, but he didn't see where they had quite saved the National
League Championship Series just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing in a place where we've won one game and lost 14,
and we have Kevin Millwood pitching against us,'' the feisty Mets
manager said Tuesday during his pre-game news conference in the
Turner Field basement. ``And people say, `Bobby, everything is
going your way.'''
</P>
<P>
   We laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Mets cried, losing as painfully as a team can lose,
10-9 on a bases-loaded walk in the bottom of the 11th inning. But
it wasn't before they made the Braves sweat BBs, bullets and blood.
For much of this interminable _ as usual _ evening, Atlanta's
Tomahawk Chop wore the look of another Tomahawk choke.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazins hadn't left everything at Shea. They had fought the
good fight there, saving two match points across the Flushing Line
tracks from the National Tennis Center, but enough was enough,
right? No, sir. Just as they were seemingly about to get aced in
Atlanta by the Braves' new ace Millwood, they staged another
gut-check uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Because a 5-0 first-inning lead wouldn't hold up, a 3-0 lead in
games nearly didn't hold up for the Braves, either. In this
30th-anniversary autumn of perhaps the most astounding championship
run of baseball's modern era, the Mets attempted, with everything
they had, to stage a worthy repeat.
</P>
<P>
   The 1969 team had no business going the distance, and neither
did this one. But it might have, if the Braves hadn't sucked up to
twice erase one-run deficits, the second of which victimized their
most feared nemesis, Armando Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   Once they broke through against Benitez, eking out a tying run
in the bottom of the 10th on Ozzie Guillen's pinch-hit RBI single
scoring Andruw Jones, Kenny Rogers figured to be an easy mark. And
he was, although Valentine put Mr. Rogers in a tough, tough
neighborhood by ordering consecutive intentional walks to Chipper
Jones and Brian Jordan, after Gerald Williams' leadoff double and a
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   With a full count and no place to put Andruw, he couldn't throw
one last strike.
</P>
<P>
   And so ends a stunningly memorable _ good and bad _ NLCS. There
will be no Subway Series. Atlantans probably will be disinclined to
take the Amtrak to Penn Station, then change trains to get them
uptown to the Bronx, where the Yankees wait.
</P>
<P>
   The Fall Classic begins here Saturday night. Maybe by then the
Braves' hearts will be out of their throats and they won't be
calling this place stomach-Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   It never should have come to an 11th-inning walk. You know it, I
know it, and they know it. How does a team of Atlanta's stature, a
team that has come to define pitching excellence in our time, give
up nine runs on its home turf under such crucial circumstances?
When spotted a five-run advantage before the other team manages to
get a second out?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Braves were lucky to take it to extra innings. The
three-run New York sixth might have been bigger if Rey Ordonez's
screaming liner hadn't had eyes for Walt Weiss' glove. Weiss, the
Astros-killer in the Division Series, easily doubled Darryl
Hamilton off second, slamming the door on that rally.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing apparently daunts these Mets. Not even the visage of
the great John Smoltz jogging in from the bullpen to work the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox had stupidly _ we thought _ let the rookie Kevin
McGlinchy self-destruct in the 15th inning Sunday while his stable
of stud starters stood around with their hands in their pockets in
the bullpen. Cox felt no sense of urgency, and some of us fried him
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Wrongly, I suppose, based on the train wreck Smoltz left in his
wake Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   His surprisingly stellar relief work in Game 2, when he earned
his first-ever save, had prompted conversation about him perhaps
finishing his career as another Dennis Eckersley. No chance now, is
there?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets humiliated Smoltz, who was greeted with a hero's
welcome only to slink off to a stunned silence after the Mets
pulverized him. He came in leading 7-3 and left to a tie score, if
you can imagine. The only out he got, a towering fly to
right-center by Edgardo Alfonzo, carried to near the top of the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz will start in the Fall Classic. He will not relieve. Bet
on it.
</P>
<P>
   Before Millwood took a header in the sixth after 5 strong
innings, each Atlanta starter had gone a minimum of seven, with
none yielding more than two earned runs or walking more than one
batter. And stopper John Rocker, although he tends to be goofiness
personified, never did officially surrender an earned run despite
appearing in every one of the games.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a chance to avenge their 1996 Series loss to the
Yankees, when a two-game lead was squandered, because of their
pitching, Smoltz's debacle notwithstanding. The Mets, in turn,
won't be there for a battle of the boroughs because theirs didn't
hold up, starting with Al Leiter, heretofore their Mr. Clutch.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's plunking Williams and Chipper Jones in the first inning
was unprecedented in LCS play. Add a walk plus Mike Piazza's errant
throw to third on a double steal, and the Mets quickly had a
serious mess on their hands. Atlanta was ahead 2-0 and still had
the the bases loaded with no outs in the first _ on one single.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' second single, by Senor October, Eddie Perez, the
series' deserving Most Valuable Player for going 10-for-20 with two
homers and five RBIs, gave them a 4-0 lead. Brian Hunter's
sacrifice fly _ the Mets' first recorded out _ made it 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Which, while ultimately far from enough, was one more run than
the Braves had tallied in any of the preceeding five NLCS games.
Atlanta had generated only five earned runs over the last 33
innings and was threatening another October crash. The Jones boys _
Chipper, Andruw and Dow _ have had much in common, you know.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves finally got mad. Now they've got a chance to get
even with the Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
