<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2398 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-1     10-20 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBWAY SERIES DERAILED AS BRAVES TOP METS, 10-9 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A team's momentum, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
believes, is only as strong as its starting pitcher. Valentine may
have underestimated his team's resilience, but early Wednesday
morning, in Game 6 of the National League Championship Series, the
momentum and magic that had carried the Mets on their exhilarating
rampage through the post-season finally ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming a 5-0 first-inning deficit, but drained of the
ability to hold on to their latest improbable comeback, the Mets
lost by 10-9 when Kenny Rogers, the eighth Mets pitcher, walked in
the winning run in the bottom of the 11th inning, to send the
Atlanta Braves to their fifth World Series in the 1990's. They will
face the Yankees, who beat the Braves in the 1996 World Series,
beginning Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' loss, coming after another ferocious game in which
they took their first lead in the eighth inning and had another
lead in the top of the 10th inning, ended a stunning monthlong run
that included more drama and spectacle than many full seasons:
</P>
<P>
   The despair of nearly missing the playoffs, the manager
suggesting he could be fired and later saying that some of his
players weren't terribly smart, and finally the exultation of
staving off elimination again and again, until _ after an epic
15-inning victory at Shea Stadium last weekend _ it seemed as if
the Mets had captured destiny and clutched it close to them.
</P>
<P>
   But after this draining game, Valentine looked crestfallen and,
when asked on television whether he expected to be back next
season, the manager, who has had speculation about his job security
and his desire to return swirling around him for weeks, responded,
``This is my life, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Valentine added: ``I think that stuff is silly. I love
the game of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had written an enthralling story line for much of the
second half of the season, but this, like Game 5, became a battle
of attrition and weariness. And it finally caught up with an
otherwise extraordinarily resilient team. As they did in Game 5,
the Mets used almost every pitcher available as the game dragged on
and the lead went back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had come all the way back from their first-inning hole,
to tie the game, 7-7, in the seventh and then took a one-run lead
in the eighth. But reliever John Franco yielded a single to Brian
Hunter in the bottom of the eighth that scored Otis Nixon to tie
the game again.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets again took the lead, 9-8, in the top of the 10th when
Todd Pratt, the backup catcher, hit a sacrifice fly that scored
Benny Agbayani; the Mets were two outs from forcing a decisive
seventh game in the series. But in the bottom of the 10th, the
Mets' closer, Armando Benitez, gave up a pinch-hit single to Ozzie
Guillen that scored Andruw Jones to tie the score yet again, 9-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could not score in the top of the 11th, but with Rogers
pitching in the bottom half of the inning, the game unraveled.
Gerald Williams led off with a double and he moved to third on a
sacrifice bunt by Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets intentionally walked Chipper Jones and then, after
throwing two balls to Brian Jordan on pitchouts to try to catch
Jones running, they intentionally walked Jordan, too, to load the
bases. Andruw Jones worked the count to three and two and finally,
4 hours 25 minutes after the game began, Rogers threw the fourth
ball to end the season.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Darryl Hamilton crouched for several minutes in
the field and several members of the Mets remained leaning on the
dugout railing, watching the Braves engulf Williams at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take some time in the winter to watch these
games, and try to enjoy them,'' Valentine said. ``I told my guys
after the game that it might be a shorter winter or a longer winter
for them but I think they played like champions. They should feel
like champions. It's very difficult to come back from five runs and
have a couple of leads. It's difficult to give it up, but we gave
everything we had.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Braves Manager Bobby Cox said he thought the
Braves had a chance to blow open the game in the first inning, when
Al Leiter, the ace whose complete-game, two-hit shutout against
Cincinnati in a one-game playoff launched the Mets into the
playoffs, simply had had enough. Pitching on just three days of
rest for only the second time in his career, Leiter seemed as
tattered as a worn coat as soon as he took the mound in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   He had hoped that the adrenaline would carry him, but the last
time he'd tried this was five years ago and near the start of the
season, and Valentine had hesitated to bring Leiter back on short
rest for the last game of the regular season against Pittsburgh,
explaining then that Leiter preferred extra rest if possible. With
the season on the line Tuesday night, though, and all but one other
starter employed in the desperate parade from the bullpen that
ultimately won Game 5, Valentine went with his ace, unsure of what
to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he was, in fact, overly charged up or simply so out of
gas that no amount of mental fuel could make up the difference,
Leiter had no command of his pitches, sending them swerving in all
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Piazza looked like an aerobics instructor,
stretching up and down and side to side to retrieve Leiter's
offerings. He bounced his second pitch of the game in the dirt and
on his third pitch smacked the Braves' leadoff hitter, Gerald
Williams, in the foot. He walked the next batter, Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Six of Leiter's first eight pitches were balls. On his first
pitch to the dangerous Chipper Jones _ another ball _the Braves
executed a double steal, sending Williams scurrying to third.
</P>
<P>
   When Piazza gunned the ball to third, it skittered instead
toward the Mets' dugout and Williams scored the first run of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   On the next pitch _ Leiter's tenth _ he hit Jones near the knee.
Brian Jordan, the fourth batter in th lineup, sent a grounder into
the gap between third and shortstop to score Boone and give the
Braves a 2-0 lead with, still, none out. And single to left field
by Eddie Perez scored two more and after 25 pitches, Leiter was
gone and his slow walk to the dugout, with head hung, was a study
in distress. As he reached for his jacket, he rubbed his head with
his hands but he would watch as reliever Pat Mahomes gave up a
sacrifice fly to Brian Hunter to lengthen the lead to 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few weeks, the Mets have resembled a creature
from a horror movie that, with the doomsday music swelling, rises
from the muck again and again. They nearly became the Braves' own
personal nightmare in a sixth inning that conjured thoughts that
perhaps the Mets had at least one more astonishing comeback
remaining in them. Braves starter Kevin Millwood was going on extra
rest, five days, since he allowed the Mets three runs in seven and
a third innings in Game 2. But by the sixth inning tonight, he,
too, began to look weary.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo led off with a double and moved to third on a
John Olerud single. A sacrifice fly by Piazza scored Alfonzo and
Robin Ventura doubled to right field to move Olerud to third.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them scored when Darryl Hamilton hit a single up the
middle to close the Braves lead to 5-3 and send Millwood to the
shower.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Terry Mulholland walked pinch-hitter Benny Agbayani to
extend the rally. But Rey Ordonez lined into a double play to end
that threat. The Braves would add two runs, but the Mets tied the
game with a four-run seventh inning, capped by Mike Piazza's
two-run home run. They took the lead in the eighth inning when
Melvin Mora, the rookie Wunderkind pinch-hitting for reliever Orel
Hershiser, singled to score Benny Agbayani.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves tied the score in the bottom of the inning, when
Brian Hunter stroked a single to center off John Franco that scored
Otis Nixon to send the game into extra innings.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
