<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-INACTIVE(ANALYSIS)-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEWS ANALYSIS: MUCH TALK, LITTLE ACTION FROM 106TH CONGRESS  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's defeat of campaign finance reform
Tuesday adds to Washington's impressive record of taking on the
tough issues _ and then relegating them to a legislative trash
heap.
</P>
<P>
   On matters ranging from gun control and tax cuts to health care
and campaign finances, the 106th Congress has established a clear
pattern of gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   After hours of quarrelsome debate, backroom deal-making and
roll-call votes, Congress either sends proposals into a legislative
limbo or forwards them to the president for his veto.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the product of Democratic stubbornness, right-wing
extremism or the GOP's narrow margin in the House, Washington has
become a far better showcase for grandstanding and polemics than a
forum for enacting laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Congress has a rendezvous with obscurity,'' said Jack
Pitney, a professor of government at Claremont McKenna College in
Los Angeles and the author of several books on Congress. ``Each
side is just strong enough to score points on the other, but not
strong enough to get its agenda into the law books.''
</P>
<P>
   The past few days provide a perfect illustration of how
Washington operates under an ideologically divided government.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, the long-anticipated debate over reforming
campaign finance laws generated scores of floor speeches, news
conferences and editorials. But after four days of debate, the bill
offered by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold,
D-Wis., failed to muster enough votes to overcome a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Democrats brought in 350 kids from around the
country to participate in a conference on violence aimed at
embarrassing Republicans into taking action on dormant gun control
measures. As Democratic press secretaries tried to generate
publicity, Republicans largely ignored the event.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, congressional leaders and President Clinton met at
the White House late yesterday in a struggle to fulfill even their
most basic duty _ enacting a budget for the fiscal year that began
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk a lot about different issues _ but none of it is
focused solving any problems,'' said Rep. Mike Thompson, D-Calif.,
who came to Congress this year. ``When someone takes to the floor
to talk about an amendment or a bill, they often cast it in a way
that is designed to win over a group of people, not to pass
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitney said the 106th Congress, which is less than halfway
through its two-year session, ``may not be the least (productive)
in history, (but) it certainly is going to be toward the bottom of
the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that inaction is necessarily bad. The stalemate over how to
spend the projected $1 billion surplus prevented Republicans from
providing tax cuts and Democrats from spending money on social
programs and Medicare. As a result, the money will stay in the
treasury, which many economists believe is the soundest policy.
</P>
<P>
   On guns, while many pockets of the country are outraged by the
lack of new restrictions, gun supporters like Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas, have insisted that killing gun control measures is
exactly the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday night, after his filibuster successfully thwarted
campaign finance reform, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., boasted that
his parliamentary maneuvers had done ``the country a favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans protest that they have done their share. A major
reorganization of the Department of Energy was recently signed into
law, as were laws sending education dollars back to the states and
limiting liability for Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there is a widespread feeling that much of
Washington is on hold until next year's elections for control of
the White House and Congress have been settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members feel this has been a wasted year,'' said veteran
Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative gridlock is in part the result of the
Republicans' precarious 10-seat majority in the House, the
narrowest majority since the first two years of the Eisenhower
administration nearly half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, with the help of a few moderate Republicans, have
been able to put forward measures such as HMO reform, campaign
finance and the minimum wage, which most Republicans would just
assume  &LR; as soon not place on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who took
over from Newt Gingrich less than a year ago, has been unwilling or
unable to rein in the more conservative members of his own  &LR; party
who have sought to block such legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had he been speaker for five years, I think he'd be in a
better position to walk away from the far right of his party,''
Matsui said. ``He isn't solidified yet as the speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans point their finger at the White House, where Clinton
last month vetoed the most sweeping tax cut bill to pass Congress
in nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps there's evidence of a do-nothing White House,'' said
Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who is at fault, most observers agree the inaction
is likely to most hurt Republicans next year at the polls _ a
belief that some believe may pressure them into acting on
now-dormant legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a dramatic switch in control of Congress and the
White House in next year's election holds the possibility of
producing more gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats win control of the House, they will also govern
with a tiny margin. If GOP front-runner George W. Bush wins the
White House, it could be a very similar situation to today, just in
reverse. ``We have a period of instability now, and it probably
will go on for some time,'' Matsui said. ``And when you have
instability, it's hard to get things done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
