<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVIATION-FUTURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NASA CHIEF ENVISIONS BOLD NEW AGE FOR CIVILIAN AVIATION  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGAME, Calif. _ NASA director Daniel S. Goldin, whose
agency most often aims at distant planets, focused Tuesday on the
more down-to-earth problems of airplanes that must carry growing
multitudes through ever-more congested skies and airports.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin, who spoke to a meeting of the World Aviation Congress in
this San Francisco suburb, envisions a new era when civilian planes
will be equipped with ``virtual cockpits'' and will fly at
altitudes of 80,000 feet and at speeds far above supersonic.
</P>
<P>
   Some day, he said, airline passengers will disembark at
``rent-a-jet'' facilities at major airports. There, they will board
_ and fly themselves _ small, sleek, personal craft to unmanned
``smart'' local airports, where instruments equipped with ``neural
networks'' that mimic the circuitry of the human brain will control
safe landings regardless of weather.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin's motto of ``faster, better, cheaper'' space exploration
has cut the cost of unmanned missions to the moon and the planets
tenfold, and he told his audience of aircraft engineers that they
can do the same as they build new generations of planes and
airports.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that airlines in America have already carried 680
million passengers this year _ a number that will increase to 1
billion early in the coming decade and reach 11/2 billion by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are crowding our airways, our airports and our world,'' he
said. ``We want to travel _ to any place, at any time, from
anywhere. But we demand it be done safely, conveniently and
economically _ without adversely affecting the environment in our
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   At NASA's research centers, Goldin said, his engineers are
already seeking a ``revolution'' in technology that will enable
both large and small aircraft to fly at many times the speed of
sound.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, he said, is now developing ``artificial vision'' for
pilots, with advanced sensors capable of detecting turbulence,
storm cells and wind shear conditions far in the distance.
Satellite networks will provide pilots with constant and accurate
information on the aircraft's position, and digital processing will
provide ``perfectly clear 3-D picture of terrain, obstacles, runway
and traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   As for aircraft today, Goldin said, ``The reality is that we are
pushing against the limits of existing technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldin described work at NASA's Dryden Flight Research Center in
the Mojave desert, where a new prototype aircraft called Helios is
now undergoing flight tests. It is remotely controlled from the
ground and can fly at 80,000 feet, ``making it independent of
weather and other potential threats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And aircraft like Helios, Goldin said, could be deployed above
disaster areas as a cellular telephone relay center for rescue
workers. In longer high-altitude flights, planes like Helios could
serve as monitors of environmental conditions and be used to patrol
borders and to conduct surveillance of drug trafficking, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a few decades _ with aggressive, visionary and bold
investments _ we could put together all the technical achievements
in safety, noise, emissions, capacity, cost and revolutionary
designs, Goldin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
