r k BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-OPED-I     10-20 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-OPED-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN'S TROUBLES SEND A MESSAGE TO INDIA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 550-word ``separate buy'' op-ed is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By SUNANDA K. DATTA-RAY  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALCUTTA _ It was coincidence that as India anointed another
democratically elected prime minister, Pakistan succumbed once more
to military adventurism.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the conditions behind the contrasting events are
similar enough to restrain any tendency to gloat in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   The Westminster system of parliamentary democracy works in
India, albeit creakily, and not only for a ruling elite. People
have faith in it, and that matters almost as much as what it
actually delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy, Indian-style, allows the pressing and often
conflicting urges of a highly complex society to be expressed
through the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
   But poverty _ the one issue that should be central to all public
activity _ did not feature anywhere in the recent election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Such mundane concerns last impinged on Indian leaders in the
1998 election when furor over the soaring price of onions confirmed
the high tolerance level of people who feared that the only
flavoring for their poor diet would become unaffordable.
</P>
<P>
   India's constitution lists several lofty fundamental rights and
a high-sounding set of directive principles that outline the
rudimentary needs of civilized society.
</P>
<P>
   Jawaharlal Nehru, the first prime minister, used to claim
inspiringly that there were no orphans because Mother India was the
universal parent.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfashionable now even to dwell on things like jobs,
potable water, elementary health care, housing, schools or birth
control. Personality looms above parties and programs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it would still be inconceivable for an Indian equivalent of
Pakistan's opposition Grand Democratic Alliance to clamor for the
army to overthrow an elected leader.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would any self-respecting Indian politician emulate Benazir
Bhutto, the former prime minister who lost no time in courting the
coup leader, General Pervez Musharraf _ ``a courageous and bold
professional, committed to civilian order,'' of whom she claims
always to have had ``a good opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 12 is not the day that democracy died, Ms. Bhutto says,
``but rather the day it began to be reborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she hopes that the general will do to Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif what General Mohammed Zia ul-Haq did to her father _
execute him _ so that she and her family fortune (much of which was
amassed in power, according to critics) can go home safely.
</P>
<P>
   Karachi greeted the coup with jubilation partly because the city
is dominated by people who, like General Musharraf's family,
migrated from India, but mainly because Pakistanis accept a
military solution to civilian problems.
</P>
<P>
   Security is New Delhi's primary concern. Pakistan's troop
pullback from India's borders is being treated warily by the Indian
government and armed forces, who have a history of rivalry and
tension with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But joy in India over last year's nuclear explosions was
short-lived because Indians felt that daily necessities mattered
more than the deterrent of mutually assured destruction.
</P>
<P>
   However gratifying Pakistan's plight might seem to Indians,
their own massive electoral upheaval might prove to be another
exercise in futility unless Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
fulfills grassroots expectations. Sharif fell for failing to do so,
as did the late Indian leader Indira Gandhi in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Retribution strikes differently in each case, but strike it
does. Democracy, like patriotism, is not enough. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Sunanda K. Datta-Ray is a former editor of The
Statesman, in India. He contributed this commentary to the
International Herald Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 550-word commentary from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
