r a BC-`TOUGH-LOVE'-RUSSIA-O     10-20 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`TOUGH-LOVE'-RUSSIA-OPED-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP TURNING A BLIND EYE TO RUSSIAN MONEY MISCHIEF  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 950-word excellent ``separate buy'' op-ed is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARSHALL I. GOLDMAN  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Every day there are new revelations and now
even indictments stemming from the avalanche of hot Russian money
passing through the Bank of New York on its way to a myriad of
other U.S., European and offshore banks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost no responsible officials in the U.S. and Russian
governments, nor those in international lending organizations, will
admit publicly that their funds or foreign aid have been misused.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, there may have been a failure to report the sudden
influx of a few billion dollars now and then, but otherwise, as
Strobe Talbott, the deputy secretary of state, put it in a slightly
different context, ``Calm down world.''
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt a substantial portion of the $7.5 billion that was
filtered through Benex, a Potemkin-like office set up in 1996 by a
Russian emigre in Queens, N.Y., was not criminally derived money.
Much of it was from Russian and foreign businessmen seeking to
evade Russian taxes. That is unethical but not criminal.
</P>
<P>
   But some of this money did come from corporate theft, organized
crime and government kickbacks as well as from misuse of U.S.
foreign aid, World Bank support and IMF loans.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a sophisticated Western investor like BP Amoco, which may
never again see the $571 million it invested in Sidanco, a once
well regarded Russian oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Or ask the Dart Group, which is struggling to retain its
investment in Yukos, another oil company. Or Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &AMP; Company and the United States-Russia Investment Fund,
which has just discovered that their investment in the Lomonosov
porcelain factory has been nationalized to keep them from taking
control.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, ask Boris Yeltsin's son-in-law how he happened to
end up with $2.7 million in that same Bank of New York, not to
mention the other son-in-law's accounts in various Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   To be even more specific, Russian economists have complained
that in 1993, U.S. food aid was diverted and then re-exported,
which was contrary to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Roskhleboproduct, the Russian agency chosen to distribute the
grain in Russia, profited at the expense of the intended
recipients. Yet the same firm was selected to process the U.S. food
aid provided last year.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one example of misappropriated foreign aid. Even
former Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin has complained that ``30
percent of &QL; 
our humanitarian aid is invariably stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   What about loans from the World Bank? A few weeks ago the
president of the World Bank asserted that there was no evidence
that its loans to Russia had been misused.
</P>
<P>
   This came as a surprise to several economists in and outside the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed specifically to money lent by the World Bank to
restructure and close many of Russia's obsolete coal mines.
According to the audit committee of the Russian Duma, the $600
million loan provided in 1996 for the coal mines seems to have
disappeared with little evident restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the loans from the International Monetary Fund.
It has acknowledged that there have been some problems.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it has complained that the Russian central bank
diverted some of the country's reserves to an offshore account that
the bank had set up to avoid scrutiny and seizure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the IMF has charged that the Russian central bank
deliberately lied to the IMF by reporting that those funds were
still in Moscow, whereas they were actually in a controlled account
in the Channel Islands.
</P>
<P>
   But what IMF officials have not addressed is the claim that
senior central bank personnel took those funds and invested them in
high-yielding government securities back in Russia and kept the
proceeds for their personal use.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank also has a long history of taking dollars
borrowed from the IMF. Instead of selling them all at auction to
prop up the ruble, as it is supposed to do, it sets aside a
substantial portion at a lower rate for a few selected banks owned
by a few favored oligarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, these transfers have a habit of taking place
immediately before a sharp devaluation of the ruble. Many of those
dollars then quickly find their way back to the West, if not
through the Bank of New York then through other Western banks.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way money flows and deals are made and unmade, it
is difficult to document most forms of corporate and government
theft in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   True, government officials in Russia are not the only ones in
the world who enter government service poor and exit as
multimillionaires or CEOs of their country's wealthiest utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet failure to penalize those Russian officials, institutions
and businessmen who have taken advantage of loose procedures,
including those who have stolen from the West, only perpetuates
such practices.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder so many Russians laugh at the naivete or seeming
obtuseness of Western officials, both private and governmental, who
seem to blind themselves to obvious examples of malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
   To say ``no'' to Russia now and then does not mean that we want
to cut Russia off from the world and force it to resume a hostile
arms buildup. After all, there are responsible voices in Russia,
including the former minister of finance, Boris Fyodorov, who have
urged the IMF to stop lending money to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Russia unable to repay such loans, Fyodorov warns,
but continued borrowing only nourishes destructive habits.
</P>
<P>
   Call it tough love. The time has come for policymakers to ask
themselves whether saying ``no'' occasionally might not facilitate
the reforms they seek more effectively than always saying ``yes.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Marshall I. Goldman is the Davis professor of
Russian economics at Wellesley College and associate director of
the Davis Center for Russian Studies at Harvard University. He
contributed this commentary to the International Herald Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 950-word op-ed from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
