<HEADER>
A2435 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CENSUS-YANKS-ABROAD-I     10-20 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-YANKS-ABROAD-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOUGH TASK OF COUNTING AMERICANS OVERSEAS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 650-word ``separate buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By KENNETH PREWITT  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How many Americans live overseas? The U.S. State
Department estimates 3 million. Other estimates double and triple
this number. There is no reliable estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, does not the Census Bureau count overseas Americans?
After all, many of them pay taxes and vote in U.S. elections.
Surely they can be counted?
</P>
<P>
   They cannot be easily counted for the simple reason that there
is no ``comprehensive control file'' of Americans living abroad.
This technical term refers to what the Census Bureau uses to
identify persons who do not cooperate with the census and thus must
be tracked down if the census, as it must, is to approach a
complete count.
</P>
<P>
   In the stateside census, the control file is a listing of about
120 million household addresses that has been painstakingly
constructed by labor-intensive, expensive operations.
</P>
<P>
   Next March, the Census 2000 effort will mail or deliver a census
questionnaire to each of these addresses.
</P>
<P>
   We expect that 60 to 65 percent of the households will mail the
form in. The others are then sought out in a vast effort known as
nonresponse follow-up, an effort to raise the response rate to as
near 100 percent as feasible.
</P>
<P>
   No analogous control file exists for Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned citizens living abroad have suggested that the Census
Bureau might make forms available through embassies or employers.
But this is to suggest a voluntary census. There would be no
practical way to locate the unknown number who never heard about or
ignored the census appeal. That is, there is no way to mount a
nonresponse follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   But is not a partial count better than no count at all? Not
necessarily. In the absence of the follow-up designed to reach
every possible respondent, the count would be biased and would not
withstand the inevitable legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional purpose of the decennial census is to provide
state-by-state population totals that are used to reapportion 435
seats in the House of Representatives among the 50 states. Any
counting procedure that might disadvantage a given state would be
biased.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to imagine scenarios that could advantage or
disadvantage particular states.
</P>
<P>
   Assume that it is comparatively difficult to count Americans
living in Canada, who are not required to have passports, seldom
register with the embassy and are often retired.
</P>
<P>
   Then assume that it is comparatively easier to count Americans
in Saudi Arabia, who must carry passports and who often work for
U.S. firms and pay U.S. taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Assume further that many of the Americans retired to Canada
moved from northern border states such as Maine or Washington,
while many who work in Saudi Arabia are from oil-producing states
such as Texas or Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau does not know a priority if it would be harder
to count Americans living in Canada than in Saudi Arabia. Nor can
we be certain that there is a correlation between (1) living in an
easier-to-count world region and (2) home state in the United
States. But these are plausible assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious that a census of Americans abroad that counted a
lower proportion in Canada than in Saudi Arabia would not be
neutral with respect to congressional reapportionment. It would
harm the northern border states but benefit the oil-producing
states.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau could not stand behind a count with a known
bias; and it is a near certainty that such a count would be
challenged in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   To devise procedures designed to find every American living
abroad poses substantial operational and statistical challenges.
These are challenges that the Census Bureau would willingly meet,
but it can do so only with congressional authorization and funding.
Moreover, it needs time to plan and test alternative procedures.
This is not a task for the next few months. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Kenneth Prewitt, director of the U.S. Census
Bureau, contributed this commentary to the International Herald
Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
