<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 04:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2436 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-WHO'LL-RUN-UNESCO?-IH     10-20 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHO'LL-RUN-UNESCO?-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNESCO VACANCY OPENS WAY FOR UNDERDOG CANDIDATES  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``a'' general news files.)  
  
 By JOSEPH FITCHETT  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The race to run UNESCO could be opening to underdog
candidates, diplomats said Tuesday, as Japan failed to muster
enough backing to push through its candidate in a second round of
voting.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite is still the Japanese candidate, Koichiro Matsuura.
On Tuesday, he fell only three votes short of the 30 needed for a
majority in the 58-nation executive board, which chooses a
director-general for the 187-nation organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the early stalemate could open the way to more reform-minded
contenders, including former Foreign Minister Gareth Evans of
Australia and Ismail Serageldin, an Egyptian architect and World
Bank vice president _ partly because UNESCO has a tradition of
consensus and would be uncomfortable with a split vote as an
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the deadlock lasts, there's a real chance that the job can
go to an outsider determined to shake up the organization and find
a new place for it internationally,'' a European ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
   The election of a reform-minded director-general could signal a
fresh start in the next six years for UNESCO, the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an improved image in recent years, the organization has
been plagued with continuing accusations of mismanagement and lack
of focus that peaked in the mid-1980s when the United States left
UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
   A holdover from that period _ the system of choosing a new
director-general that resembled a papal enclave in its secrecy,
with officials declining even to make public the candidates' names
_ has been jettisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the candidates met last week with UNESCO's executive
board. The quasi-interviews at UNESCO headquarters were monitored
from an adjoining room by diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp calls for change _ to find contemporary relevance for an
organization that seems to be drifting _ emerged from the
reform-minded candidates.
</P>
<P>
   These candidates, diplomats said, argued that UNESCO needed to
reorganize its work to meet new technological challenges in
communications and shift its priorities to help tackle educational
crises in trouble spots such as the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the diplomats said, the status quo sounded
acceptable to the two front-running candidates: Matsuura, Japan's
ambassador to France, and Ghazi Gosaibi, a poet and Saudi Arabia's
ambassador to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on strong backing from their governments, the two men
lead in the UNESCO polling, with Gosaibi winning 10 votes.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between the two front-runners could hand early victory to
Japan, but both Evans and Serageldin vowed to stay in the contest _
which could last until a final round between the two leading
contenders on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Serageldin, who was knocked back to only four votes Tuesday,
complained that governments were letting their political ties
outweigh candidates' individual merit.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo continued lobbying in world capitals, telling governments
that the job should go to Matsuura because of the amount of
Japanese aid to UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
   Even blunter messages _ about the future of Japan's bilateral
aid _ have been reported by diplomats in some countries, especially
in French-speaking Africa and in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government, which is a major donor to the U.N.
system, has worked consistently in recent years to promote Japanese
to prominent U.N. jobs. A U.S. ambassador in Europe said Tokyo saw
such jobs as a way of increasing Japanese influence in the world
body at a time when there was still no early prospect of Japan's
getting a permanent seat on the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' a UNESCO official said, ``they've built up a
bad reputation because so many Japanese officials had trouble
making the move to an international job and proved unable to work
with foreign colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Evans, the Australian candidate, and Serageldin have
generated support among people who have worked with them in many
countries. Both have endorsements from cultural figures suggesting
that they could attract intellectual talent to a refocused UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, 55, came to international prominence as a foreign
minister in Australia, but never let diplomacy (or his Oxford
education as a barrister) stifle his personality.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging his lack of fluent French, Evans urged French
officials to get him the UNESCO job anyway so he would be sure to
learn the language in Paris, where UNESCO is headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Evans contends that his main qualification is his ``enthusiasm
for multi-ethnicity, which should be the galvanizing value for
UNESCO.''
</P>
<P>
   Serageldin stresses that UNESCO needs a higher profile on global
scientific issues and technological challenges. A tenet of his
campaign is restored ties with the United States because, he says,
it is ``the most revolutionary country in technology,
communications and science.''
</P>
<P>
   Serageldin has gambled on opposing Saudi Arabia, notably on
human rights, and the Saudi government has lined up most Arab
nations _ including Egypt, Seraladgin's own country _ behind
Gosaibi.
</P>
<P>
   A major issue for UNESCO _ especially in Washington _ is press
freedom. Evans told UNESCO that peace and democracy required ``an
independent, pluralistic and free press -_ free of government
control, free of monopoly and committed to the free flow of ideas
and information.'' But Matsuura has been noncommittal. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 850-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
