<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYERERE-LEGACY-OPED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYERERE: AFRICAN LEADER MADE A DIFFERENCE FOR THE BETTER  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 400-word ``separate buy'' commentary is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julius Nyerere, former president of Tanzania, died after he had
voluntarily left office, still respected by his people. To this
extent alone, he set himself apart from many of his fellows in that
small club of African men who guided their countries to
independence.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast Kwame Nkrumah, the first to break from Britain's
colonial grip when the Gold Coast became Ghana in 1957, was
transformed during his reign from a charming and popular natural
leader to a diabolic force who built statues to himself, undermined
the judiciary, and left his opponents to rot in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the Nkrumah path has been more frequently travelled by
African leaders than Nyerere's.
</P>
<P>
   Mobutu, Bokassa, Banda, Amin, and many others, all used their
office to fatten their foreign bank accounts and further their
megalomaniac ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Their ideology _ usually an ill-defined and sentimental
nationalism _ was the thinnest of disguises for crude kleptocracy.
Much wickedness progressed under the guise of the ``African way''
of running things.
</P>
<P>
   Nyerere, too, tried to find an African way forward for Tanzania.
He thought the continent was a natural home of socialism, that
sharing and cooperation were the norm for pre-colonial African
society, and that post-colonial leaders would be able to resurrect
this heritage with ease.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to organize Tanzania into a system of collective
villages. But the peasants, as they had done before, worked for
themselves, and only pretended to work on communal plots. The
economy stagnated, and corruption was endemic.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the villages was a hard lesson. But there was one
legacy of Nyerere's ``ujamaa'' socialism that blesses Tanzania to
this day: it defused the country's ethnic rivalries _ divisions
that blight every country on the continent, providing so often a
pretext for ambitious men to grab power.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations _ Nigeria, Angola _ have only themselves to blame
for their poverty. They have the resources, but abuse them.
</P>
<P>
   Tanzania has precious few resources. But at least the only war
it has fought in recent times was to enter Uganda and remove the
appalling Idi Amin from power.
</P>
<P>
   A leader can make a difference. There are very few in Africa who
have made a difference for the better _ Nelson Mandela is the
outstanding example. Perhaps Nyerere should also belong to this
too-small club. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 400-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
