<HEADLINE>
PLANNED PARENTHOOD HEAD CRITICIZES BOTH PARTIES ON REPRODUCTIVE 
 CHOICE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ The head of Planned Parenthood lambasted
presidential candidates Tuesday _ Republican and Democratic alike _
for failing to address issues of reproductive choice critical to
millions of American women, and called for a nationwide
mobilization to counter ``noisy ideological groups (who've) set the
agenda for too long.''
<P>
   Gloria Feldt, president of both the Planned Parenthood
Federation of America and its powerful political action committee,
was in San Francisco to announce a 2000 pro-choice initiative she
said is designed to force presidential hopefuls to outline
positions on issues such as sex education, access to family
planning services and funding for contraceptives to poor women.
</P>
<P>
   ``If presidential candidates can be war heroes, they can be
heroes for responsible choices,'' said Feldt, who heads the
nation's oldest and largest family planning organization, in a
speech before the Commonwealth Club of California. ``If they can be
blessed by family fortune and privilege, they can feel for those
who are not. If they can be a role model for women, they can listen
to women who have brought them this far.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of reproductive health care _ including the volatile
issue of abortion _ has proved a dramatic factor in California
politics as recently as the 1998 governor's race. State polls have
shown that two-thirds of all California voters are satisfied with
current abortion laws or favor even less restrictive laws, and that
an equal number would be less likely to support a candidate who
opposed abortion rights for women. Such views, political insiders
said, were a deciding factor in the landslide victory in
California's governor's race of pro-choice Democratic candidate
Gray Davis over GOP challenger Dan Lungren, who was vociferously
anti-abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt said Tuesday that next year's election will be a watershed
for the 90 percent of American voters who favor family planning
services.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she said, both Republican and Democratic candidates have
been largely silent on issues that go far beyond abortion. Those
include whether emergency contraception should be made available to
millions of American women, or whether they support the so-called
``conscience clause,'' which allows private hospitals to decide if
they will make available family planning or fertility treatments _
even if they are the only health care provider in a community, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush, recant your arrogant statement that Americans'
hearts are in the wrong place,'' Feldt said, in her critique of the
crop of presidential candidates. ``Steve Forbes, stand up for
responsible choices like you did in your first campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain, you say your incarceration made you value America
and its freedoms even more. What about the freedom to choose family
planning?
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth Dole, show the compassion in this debate that you
did at the Red Cross,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt also had sharp words for Democrats, saying that pro-choice
Al Gore needs to be more specific and ``articulate the connection
between the environment and family planning.'' And Bill Bradley,
another pro-choice Democrat, ``may have voted right'' in the U.S.
Senate but now needs to ``make these issues a visible and important
plank'' in his platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all must zero in on every candidate and make them tell us
where they stand on responsible choices,'' Feldt said. ``If a
candidate won't stand up for responsible choices on reproductive
health during the campaign, he or she won't do so in office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
