<HEADER>
A2509 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-GULFWAR-SYNDROME-SFCH     10-20 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULFWAR-SYNDROME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERVE GAS PILL WAS CALLED SUSPICIOUS 2 YEARS AGO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SABIN RUSSELL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ A new Pentagon study suggesting a link between
Gulf War syndrome and a precautionary nerve gas pill taken by
American troops has a familiar ring to it, according to Dr. Joyce
Lashof, former dean of the Berkeley School of Public Health.
<P>
   Nearly three years ago, a White House commission headed by
Lashof made the same observation in a detailed study of the
mysterious maladies affecting tens of thousands of Gulf War
veterans. Tuesday's report made bigger waves, however, because the
Pentagon has long denied any possible link between the nerve gas
pill _ pyridostigmine bromide _ and the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a recommendation for further research on the possible
synergistic action between pyridostigmine bromide and pesticides,''
said Lashof. ``We left the same door open.''
</P>
<P>
   While only a few hundred U.S. service members died as a result
of the conflict, wildly varying estimates of between 20,000 and
100,000 veterans have unexplained symptoms of chronic pain, skin
rashes, nausea, memory loss and concentration problems.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Rand think tank report released by the Department of
Defense Tuesday, Lashof's Presidential Advisory Committee on Gulf
War Veterans Illnesses study, released in January 1997, found that
there was reason to suspect that the prophylactic doses of the drug
might be involved in the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   GIs took up to three pyridostigmine bromide pills a day in
combat zones where Iraqis were believed to have stocks of soman, a
fast-acting nerve gas. In fact, Saddam Hussein's troops did not
have that weapon at their disposal.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier study noted, however, that the nerve gas pill _ long
approved for the treatment of the neurological disorder myasthenia
gravis _ was not known to cause chronic illness except in cases
where there were acute symptoms of poisoning by overdose.
</P>
<P>
   Lashof's study made headlines at the time for debunking the
popular notion that Gulf War syndrome was linked to nerve gas
exposure, and it leaned heavily toward the theory that Gulf War
syndrome is a range of real illnesses triggered by stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real illness,`' said Lashof. ``People are sick. I
personally think it is very similar to chronic fatigue syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Berkeley dean, who is also a past president of the
American Public Health Association, said stress can have a
significant impact on the immune system and the endocrine system.
``Similar symptoms have been described after other wars, dating
back to the Civil War,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon report is based on a survey of dozens of studies on
pyridostigmine bromide, among them findings by University of Texas
and Duke researchers that the drug can cause nerve damage when
mixed with other chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the Pentagon has spent $133 million researching Gulf
War syndrome, and has devoted $20 million of that amount
specifically to studies of pyridostigmine bromide. In her Rand
report Tuesday, Dr. Beatrice Golomb of the San Diego Veterans
Affairs Medical Center said further study is needed to explore the
potential interactions of the drug with pesticides and other
chemicals _ including nerve gas agents _ that may have been
encountered by troops.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that these interactions might permanently disrupt
the body's regulation of acetylcholine, a molecule that plays a
pivotal role in the process of nerve signaling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
