<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNHAPPY-VOTERS-INDONESIA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAF, BLIND, MUTE: THREE WISE MONKEYS VIE FOR INDONESIA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors _ TIMELY for Indonesian election!)   (This heads-up 925-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA _ Sometime Wednesday evening in Jakarta _ or perhaps it
will be early Thursday morning _ after one, two or maybe three
separate votes, Indonesia's highest legislative body will elect the
country's fourth president.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will a female nationalist, although it could also be
a Muslim cleric, or a former aeronautical engineer _ or possibly
none of the three.
</P>
<P>
   His, or her, vice-president will definitely be a civilian,
provided, of course, that he is not a general.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the result will bring true democracy to
Indonesia for the first time in its history _ unless, that is, it
plunges the country into renewed political chaos and violent
disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian politics has never been easy to follow, but rarely
has Jakarta seen the confusion which has gripped the capital this
week. For the last three days, crowds of demonstrators have filled
the streets _ but whether they are jubilantly celebrating the
advent of democracy or angrily protesting its passing, is
completely unclear.
</P>
<P>
   With less than 24 hours to go Tuesday night until one of the
most important votes in recent Southeast Asian history, and despite
a blizzard of analysis in magazines, newspapers and on television,
no one had a blind idea of who is going to win.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything about today's presidential election is
uncertain, from the list of candidates to procedures for the vote
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Since May last year, when President Suharto was bounced from
power after 32 years as Indonesia's undisputed dictator, a wave of
democratic fervor has swept the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 17 months, Indonesia has acquired countless new political
parties and a raucously free and unruly press. But the basic
political machinery, the institutions through which leaders are
elected and dismissed, is still essentially those of the old
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the strain is beginning to show and the euphoria of
the post-Suharto era is slowly turning to cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the problems is the People's Consultative Assembly
or MPR, the 700-strong body which nominally wields supreme power in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In the past its business was simple. During the rule of Suharto,
all of its members were personally approved by him _ in any case,
he was the only candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, no one knows how many there will be _ so vague are the
rules governing the nomination of candidates that the final list
will not be drawn up until just before the election itself.
</P>
<P>
   The main contenders have already staked their claims, but as
politicians they are as confused and compromised as the MPR itself.
</P>
<P>
   The insiders' joke is that the leading candidates are a version
of the three wise monkeys: one who is deaf, one who is blind, and
one who is mute.
</P>
<P>
   The deaf ``monkey'' is B.J. Habibie, the former vice-president
of Suharto, who succeeded to the post by default after the forced
resignation of his old friend and patron.
</P>
<P>
   During his brief tenure, he has liberalized press laws, released
political prisoners, and brought about the long-awaited referendum
on independence in East Timor. But his achievements have been
swamped by his omissions _ his failure to check corruption or to
bring successful prosecutions against Suharto and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Far from winning credit, he has secured a reputation as a
bumbling incompetent, deaf to the wishes of his people.
</P>
<P>
   The unspeaking ``monkey'' is Megawati Sukarnoputri, leader of
the Indonesian Democratic Party-Struggle (PDI-P), and still a
heroine to many Indonesians for her stubborn, dignified and
peaceful resistance to President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   As the daughter of the country's nostalgically revered founder,
Sukarno, she is held in almost mystical regard by many of the
country's poor.
</P>
<P>
   As a secular-minded nationalist, she has positioned herself
above the often bickering internal disputes of Indonesian Muslims.
But even her closest advisers have become exasperated by her
failure to articulate clear policies, or to engage seriously in the
construction of a credible coalition.
</P>
<P>
   July's parliamentary election, she won one third of the votes _
enough to give her a moral mandate as the country's most popular
leader, but not enough to control the MPR. Since then her aloofness
has alienated potential allies, although she still remains the most
likely winner today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call her an aristocratic democrat,'' says Mochtar Buchori, a
close adviser and member of her inner circle. ``She was born and
brought up the daughter of a president. She always lives in
isolation and she never mixes with ordinary people.''
</P>
<P>
   The third, Abdurrahman Wahid, is an exception in that his
disability is literal. A brilliant and unpredictable Muslim cleric
and scholar, he is almost blind and has recently suffered two
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation last night that he might withdraw his
candidacy in favor of Nurcholis Madjid, another respected Muslim
scholar with no party affiliation and no direct experience of the
political hurly-burly. There was speculation last night that
Habibie's party, Golkar, might replace him with his chief enforcer,
Akbar Tanjung. Last night, there was speculation in abundance, but
no firm information at all.
</P>
<P>
   By a small margin, Madam Megawati is the favorite but her
success will depend on last-minute deal-making with adversaries
which will dilute her government.
</P>
<P>
   Her defeat is still a distinct possibility leading to a highly
unpredictable government under Wahid, or success for Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   The last possibility would provoke angry protests which could
easily degenerate into rioting and violence. Or, they might not.
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty about the election is that it will leave
many, many Indonesians unhappy. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this insightful 925-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please
call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
