<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2639 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1021-     10-20 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1021-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTOPHER TOMLINSON
 &HT;    ``I NEED MORE ROOM,'' says Joanne Taylor, owner of The Treasure
House in Mesa. Taylor opened the store seven years ago, after
working at a variety of jobs.
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: Grand Mesa lover sees (and sells) everything
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND MESA, Colo. _ The house is too small for the treasures.
</P>
<P>
   One corner is crowded with ``I fish therefore I lie'' baseball
caps, Old Dutch cleanser and Powderhorn sweat shirts, another
corner overflows with handmade dream catchers, postcards and books
about Grand Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need more room,'' said Treasure House owner Joanne Taylor,
scanning the 800-plus-square-foot building from her vantage point
behind the counter, which also is stacked with things like
newspapers and candy, treasures to the right person.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent treasure, though, the one beyond pop rocks and
pewter jewelry, is outside the window. Right now it's a palette of
autumn, oak brush leaves rusted auburn like barn door hinges and
the pine and spruce forest up Grand Mesa slopes marbled with gold
stands of aspen.
</P>
<P>
   Colors and textures change with the seasons, but always are
treasured by Mesa residents who give themselves a gift just by
looking out the window each morning. Having been spared, so far,
many of the more pernicious effects of rampant development familiar
to the rest of western Colorado, Mesa remains a town where people
wave to strangers they pass on the street and keep canoes on their
front porches.
</P>
<P>
   And there's that view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why I moved here,'' Taylor said, interrupting her
explanation to talk with a customer who needed party balloons. ``I
came up here the first time when I was 7 _ I lived in Fruita _ and
fell in love with the mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the wide-open valleys that caught her, the variegated
landscape of desert cliffs to oak brush to high country aspen and
pine, with Mesa on the cusp of it all and a view to everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   She came up again after graduating from high school, and briefly
flirted with moving to Mesa, but was hindered by the question of
how she'd support herself, ``and that's always been the problem up
here,'' she said. ``There's not a lot of full-time work. When I
finally did move up here I worked three jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and her family moved to Grand Mesa 18 years ago _ she was
37 and her sons were 10 and 7. For several years she worked part
time at the general store, was relief postmaster, refinished
furniture, mowed lawns and house-sat. For the past 15 years she's
been a single parent, and money's always been tight, but for years
she dreamed of opening a store like The Treasure House. Seven years
ago she took a deep breath and did it, after her youngest son
graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the first couple of years were a struggle,'' she said,
``but I wanted it to be more than a gift store, so it would be for
the people in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   So when townspeople asked her to stock necessities like cleaning
and office supplies, she complied. And when area artists asked if
they could put their creations in her store on consignment, she
agreed, so now more than 135 people consign wares with her. And
when kids wanted toys, she added toys, and candy, and Powderhorn
memorabilia, until now every conceivable inch of shelf and wall and
floor space is home to something for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next week, she'll be the busiest she is all year with
hunters coming in to buy ``guilt gifts,'' she calls them, to take
home to their families. In fact, Taylor's store has become a
constant for a steady stream of out-of-state hunters who stop by
every year on their way through Mesa. The town itself is a constant
for all sorts of people.
</P>
<P>
   There's some dispute over how the town started, whether it was
an offshoot of the Mormon pioneers who came up the Grand Mesa to
start a settlement or whether it was started by ranchers who
appreciated the proximity of summer and winter pasture in the
manageable area of Grand Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   But Mesa was and largely remains a ranching town. At the end of
last century and into this one, enormous ranches dominated the
landscape around Mesa. Bertha Lloyd, a lifelong Mesa resident, at
one time owned, with her husband, Dick, 26,000 acres of land on
which they raised cattle.
</P>
<P>
   And with ranching came not just issues of land use, water rights
and grazing regulations, but the more interesting characters
ranching can attract. Lloyd remembers stories of the Brinks family,
who owned the ranch E.D. Stewart eventually bought, and were
notorious for stealing cattle, drinking and riding their horses in
the house. When the Lloyds were first married and Dick worked for
the Stewarts, he brought Bertha into the house and showed her the
grooves in the sandstone staircase created by horseshoes.
</P>
<P>
   Families like the Stewarts and Stoddards, Saunders, Lloyds and
Pruitts shaped Mesa as a town, back from the time when the only way
to town was over the Hogback down the front of the mesa and
everybody gathered at the post office at 5 p.m. every day for the
mail, to now when the old ranchers are retiring and the big ranches
are being sold off in parcels.
</P>
<P>
   But the feel of the town hasn't changed much. People still know
each other and stop to talk on the sidewalk and know the old
stories. Though there has been an influx of newcomers in the last
few years, most of those people are looking to escape the rush of
cities and don't want to disrupt the ebb and flow of life in Mesa.
Kids go to school at Plateau Valley, people support 4-H and think
twice about going to town.
</P>
<P>
   The town is unincorporated and a population estimate based on
the 360 boxes rented at the post office is less than 1,000, so it's
one of those small Colorado mountain towns that frazzled city
people dwell on and teenagers who grow up there can't wait to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   But they're replaced by people like Taylor who can't wait to
move there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here,'' she said. ``It's the kind of place where you
can watch wildlife walk through your front yard.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, she said, is the best treasure of all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
