 Wednesday, Oct. 20, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-BIRTHCONTROL (Oakland, Calif.) _ A small billboard aimed
at drug-addicted women offered $200 cash if the women got birth
control. But to the two dozen community activists and recovering
mothers who protested, the billboard was an affront to poor black
women. It was quickly torn down. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Albany, N.Y.) _ More New Yorkers would vote
against Hillary Rodham Clinton as a U.S. Senate candidate than vote
for her, a now poll indicates. The survey by Zogby International
shows the probable Democratic nominee carrying an ``unfavorable
rating'' of 48.4 percent among likely voters, as opposed to her
``favorable rating'' of 46.3 percent. It marks the first time her
statistical negatives have eclipsed her positives. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-LAWSUIT (Oakland, Calif.) _ Ford Motor Co. spent $10
million on expert witnesses who, according to a lawyer representing
clients suing the car company, used faulty data or irrelevant
figures to argue that the rate of accidents or injuries from its
cars and trucks that had a defective ignition part were not that
different from other vehicles'. By MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-SHELTERS (San Francisco) _ The county of San Francisco
sends sick, disabled and homeless people to residential hotels that
routinely flunk city inspections, official records show. By
KATHLEEN SULLIVAN and EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ENCYCLOPEDIAS (San Francisco) _ Howard Halfon has 20 years of
his life bound up in the business of selling encyclopedias. But
after Encyclopaedia Britannica made its volumes of knowledge
available on the Internet, in full, for free, Halfon sees an end to
his career. ``Business is getting very difficult. The printed form
is becoming a thing of the past,'' he said. By JENNY STRASBURG.
</P>
<P>
   ATHLETE-ASTHMA (Albany, N.Y.) _ Even diligent care can't remove
the threat of an attack that hovers over every asthmatic. It's a
risk Jill Meconi, a 19-year-old reserve forward for the College of
Saint Rose soccer team, is willing to take so she can play the game
she loves. By MARK SINGELAIS.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL/BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOU-DOBBS (San Francisco) _ Space _ as William Shatner intones
at the start of countless Star Trek reruns _ may be the final
frontier. But Space.com, says ex-CNN financial journalist Lou
Dobbs, is the beginning of a Internet business model that has been
as barren as the dark side of the moon. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OKTOBERFEST (Undated) _ The harvest is a season for celebrations
and toasts. For raising a glass to bless the bounty. No one does
this better than the French, who have turned the annual release of
Beaujolais nouveau into an international gala event. But the
Germans are not crying in their beer. They have captured the
world's fancy with Oktoberfest, a nearly 200-year-old celebration.
By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Watching the 49ers in these
dismal dying days of their dynasty, one thing is painfully obvious:
They don't have enough talent. Where they once had talent by the
bushelful, the basket is nearly empty now. A few of the greats
remain, but they're a tad superannuated and there aren't enough of
them to keep the club forceful. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Can Willie Brown outperform
Martha Stewart? I don't mean at setting party tables or
field-stripping a jammed glue gun. And I'm sure Brown is ahead of
Stewart in most matters of taste, as long as it doesn't involve
anything trickier than opening a bottle of Dom. What I'm talking
about is money, a field in which Brown is no slouch either. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
