<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START YOUR DAY THE MUNI WAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating for all needing)   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A little pat on the back, by someone other than
a pickpocket _ that's all we really need in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Farnsworth, a newcomer to San Francisco, got hers on Muni.
She was riding the J line when her Muni driver called out the stop:
``Van Ness! Give all the glory to God and praise his name, and have
a wonderful and stress-free day!''
</P>
<P>
   That's a violation of the separation of church and state, maybe,
but Muni has inspired more praying than any church in town.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: ``Civic Center! Don't judge your importance by how
many people serve you, but by how many people you serve!''
</P>
<P>
   One passenger wondered aloud, ``What is this? Chicken soup for
Muni?''
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth figures it beats the bags of M&AMP;Ms Muni recently
handed out as an apology for blowing a day's commute.
</P>
<P>
   HOW ABOUT some chicken soup for the 49ers' soul?
</P>
<P>
   At his Monday press conference, 49ers' coach Steve Mariucci said
part of the problem is injuries. Gee, in  &UR; football? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``We're looking for a way to healthy-up ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Mariucci channeling Mammy Yokum?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Steve oughtta fuss 'round the kitchen and rustle up a mess
o' vittles, put some meat on the bones of them football hombres o'
his'n.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe help can be found in the photo-op backdrop used at
Mariucci's press conferences. The 49er logo is interspersed with
the logo of a team sponsor. ``This sponsor is what the team needs
to hold it all together this season,'' Lou Bristol points out:
``Staples.''
</P>
<P>
   IN NEON, VERITAS: The United repair hangar on the Bay side of
101 has a huge neon sign, and the second ``n'' is burned out.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Hyams noticed it, and having suffered many delays and
cancellations on United Shuttle, assumed it was a simple
confession: UNITED AIR LI ES.
</P>
<P>
   PLEASE, MARLA, don't tarnish our image of the Don:
</P>
<P>
   Marla Maples, ex-wife of Donald Trump, vows that if he runs for
president, she'll tell the world what he ``is really like.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that like Hillary threatening to tell the truth about
Bill?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a story going around: Trump finds himself alone in an
elevator with a beautiful woman. She tells him how much she admires
him, offers to do a Lewinsky right there in the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Trump says, ``OK, but what's in it for me?''
</P>
<P>
   IT WAS SAD when a delivery van driver knocked over the ancient
sidewalk clock in North Beach. Although, realistically, the clock
has Roman numerals and hands, so within 10 years there won't be
anyone around who could read it.
</P>
<P>
   Based on early reports, the driver won't be cited. Shouldn't he
at least be ordered into a diversion program for dangerously lousy
drivers, or for clock abusers? That was a big clock, a million
people have parked there without clonking it. And it could have
been a baby stroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is no one being held responsible for this?'' asks Daniel
DeTori, who phoned to protest.
</P>
<P>
   I guess DeTori thinks the driver should do some time.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCALES of justice can be messier than the scales of a dead
halibut, but it wouldn't seem fair to punish a careless driver in
the same week when John and Patsy Ramsey get cleared by a Boulder
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Says Jim Greene, ``The Ramseys should think about pooling their
resources with O.J. and looking for all the real killers.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU WANT a policewoman in San Francisco, buddy, you have to
travel back in time.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeant Leanna Dawydiak, SFPD, notes my recent mention of a
``policewoman,'' and points out that years ago, before women were
allowed to be full-fledged S.F. cops, they could hire on for a desk
job classified as Q-20, or ``policewoman.'' No street work, no
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, S.F. police officers _ men, women and misc. _ are police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just about being politically correct,'' Dawydiak
notes, correctly, ``it's also about giving us the respect of the
title we had to go to court to attain.''
</P>
<P>
   One thick skull, penetrated.
</P>
<P>
   NO PENCILS, no books, and now:
</P>
<P>
   A school board meeting at Everett Middle School was called to
order and the board president asked everyone to stand for the
Pledge of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people stood, and glanced about, looking for the
flag. Didn't find it. Sat down. No pledge.
</P>
<P>
   SOOO MARIN: A want ad in the Marin Independent Journal, for a
'90 Volvo: ``Silver, 5-spd., A/C, phone, sunroof ... Great au pair
car.''
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE THIS will help the 49ers healthy-up, in lieu of chicken
soup:
</P>
<P>
   Dippy Foods, Inc. (Motto: ``Respect us, dammit!'') will soon be
supplying Candlestick Park beer carts with ``fresh, prepackaged
nacho, cheese and salsa meals called `Dippers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the answer to the age-old question: ``If we can put a
man on the moon, why can't we can't find a way to make ballpark
nachos look and taste even more pre-fab?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how the Dippy nacho cheese will get melted, 49er
fans, so just in case, BYO magnifying glass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-20-99 0439EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
