 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
MiniDisc players cheaper with new Sharp product 
By James Cummings  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's getting cheaper to carry around a miniature
digital recording studio. New Jersey-based Sharp Electronics Corp.
has introduced a personal MiniDisc player/recorder that the company
says is the first of its kind to retail for less than $200.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp's MD-MT15 has many of the features of more expensive
machines, but while most other MiniDisc player/recorders start in
the $300 range, the MD-MT15's suggested price is $199.95.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-MT15 is just under four inches square and records music
and other sound on small discs similar to CDs. Each disc holds 74
minutes of sound, and blank discs are sold for about $4.50.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp's new MiniDisc player/recorder is powered by a
rechargeable nickel metal hydride battery that allows 12 hours of
playback or seven hours of recording. It has a 10-second memory so
it can continue playing without interruption if it is shaken or
shocked.
</P>
<P>
   The player has a view screen, and the user can mark songs on the
disc with a titling function. The device also marks selections with
the date and time they were recorded. Sharp claims discs can be
rerecorded up to 1 million times without losing sound quality.
</P>
<P>
   For additional information on the MD-MT15 and the nine other
MiniDisc players in the Sharp line, call (800) 237-4277 (BE-SHARP).
The MD-MT15 was not included on the Sharp Web site as of last week,
but you can access information on or order other products at
www.sharp-usa.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
