<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-MEDIA19-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Colorful iMac line a trendsetter 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple Computer's zoomy iMac line has kicked off a trend that few
thought would happen. Manufacturers are racing to provide colorful
new computers and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The November issue of Yahoo Internet Life looks at this trend
and tries to determine whether it will last. Among companies that
have jumped on the color bandwagon are Epson, Iomega and
HandSpring, the new maker of hand-held computers.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the big computer media companies are selling out to
bigger rivals. Boston-based IDG, publisher of InfoWeek and
ComputerWorld, is staying proudly independent. Read about the
company's leaders and strategy in the October issue of MC. For IDG,
independence hasn't meant standing still. The magazine says the
company is undergoing a major cultural change to keep itself a
strong competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Sega Dreamcast, the latest video console, has been on the market
less than a month, but developers are releasing a steady stream of
new games for the platform. The latest is ``The House of the Dead
2.'' This arcade-style game, available in stores now, features a
horror story depicted in 3-D color. The retail price is about $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tetris,'' one of the first digital games, lives on. Hasbro
Interactive has released the latest version of this classic, a
title in which players must fit together falling geometric blocks.
Called ``The Next Tetris,'' the game features breakaway and sticky
blocks, as well as the opportunity to play against others.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest trends in software now is open-source code.
Anyone can take and improve on this software code, which is
unprotected by corporations or copyright laws. The Linux operating
system is the biggest example, but there are plenty of other
open-source projects under way.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can find out all about them in one place. Xnot is a site
that lists links to all the open-source projects across the
Internet. New projects are added weekly. You'll find this site at
www.xnot.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-18-99 1111EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
