</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-ETAILING19-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
This year could be key to making 'e-tailing' mainstream 
By Marilyn Geewax  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For retailers, the holiday shopping season is the
crucial period of the year when their decisions about inventory,
staffing, pricing and advertising will result in drinking champagne
in January _ or bathing in red ink.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the stakes are even higher for merchants who plan
to use the Internet to capture customers. The electronic retailers,
or e-tailers, who can attract eyeballs and open wallets during the
last 10 weeks of 1999 may well become the masters of merchandising
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be an absolutely huge season for online companies,''
said David Baltaxe, who studies Internet commerce for Current
Analysis, a research firm in Sterling, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Having enough merchandise in stock, employees on hand and
sophisticated technology in place will be the keys to handling
explosive growth, he said. ``This is the first year that we'll have
real mainstream shopping done through the Internet. Sales are
expected to be three times what they were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of how much Christmas shopping will be done on the Web
vary from roughly $5 billion to $8 billion. Whatever the final
tally, it is sure to be a leap from last year's $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But even more important to e-tailers will be the ``buzz'' the
season generates. Companies that perform well from mid-October
through December could see their stock prices rocket up in January
as more investors become believers in electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Christmas '99 is so important because it will be
the first time that millions of Americans will try shopping with a
mouse rather than at a mall. Their experiences could shape a
lifetime of buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly scenarios haunt e-tail boosters who fear those experiences
won't measure up to expectations. They worry that shoppers will
show up online, only to find they can't get accurate inventory
information or understand how to complete orders. Or perhaps
consumers will find what they want and buy it, only to discover the
delivery system is a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's my nightmare: It's December 23rd and I'm at the mall
shopping because the things I ordered didn't show up,'' said Mary
Helen Gillespie, president of e-BuyersGuide.com, a Burlington,
Mass., firm that gives consumers advice.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers are turning to the Web because ``they want to make
things easier for themselves,'' Gillespie said. Online merchants
``have to fulfill those expectations, not make life more difficult.
If they don't perform, people are going to say: 'I'm never going
back there.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if consumers find Web shopping a breeze, the
retail world may be turned upside down. Traditional merchandisers
who expect customers to drive to a store during business hours may
find they can't compete with the 24-hour-a-day e-tailers.
</P>
<P>
   The Web's round-the-clock convenience will be the main lure
during the hectic holiday season for Damali Noel, a 27-year-old
Atlanta resident who recently made an online purchase through
FlowersAGoGo.com, a Decatur, Ga.,- based florist. She said that
smooth transaction has encouraged her to try surfing the Web for
bigger purchases during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It beats leaving the house,'' she said. ``You can sit in your
robe ... and shop in the middle of the night. It's very
convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that convenience is what draws people to the Web, Wall
Street analysts are trying to figure out which kinds of companies
have the best chance of getting everything right. The Internet
offers essentially three formats for buying goods. One is the pure
Internet company, such as Amazon.com, which operates only in
cyberspace. Some observers believe these Web-only businesses will
be the winners in the e-tail world because of their laser-like
focus on online consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But others predict this holiday season will reveal the strengths
of the second type of Web merchant: the traditional retailers who
have stretched over into the Internet. Their advantage is having
real storefronts where shoppers can return merchandise without
having to ship goods back. For example, if a consumer goes on line
to buy a Christmas present through gap.com, he knows the recipient
will be able to return the gift at any Gap store and pick out
something that fits better.
</P>
<P>
   The third type of online merchant is the catalog company, which
sits somewhere between the Internet-only e-tailers and the
traditional stores with Web sites. The companies with vast
experience in direct merchandising are trying to use their brand
names and well-developed delivery systems to leap ahead of others
online.
</P>
<P>
   Lands' End, the 35-year-old clothes company based in Wisconsin,
is perhaps the most aggressive in trying to make the transition
from the printed catalog to the Web. Last year, the company sold
about $61 million worth of goods through its Web site, or about 4.5
percent of total sales. That was up from $18 million in 1997. So
far this year, Web-based sales are running at 2.5 times last year's
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bass, vice president of electronic commerce at Lands' End,
said that to boost holiday sales, the company has started offering
a ``live chat'' box to allow customers to ``talk'' to sales clerks
while looking at merchandise on line. By clicking on the chat box,
the shopper will synchronize her screen with the clerk's so that
together, they can exchange messages about clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The shopper also can use the ``shop-with-a-friend'' option,
which brings a companion into the chat. That will allow, for
example, two sisters who live hundreds of miles apart to go on line
together and chat while picking out a present for their parents,
Bass said. In addition, they can put the clothes on a model, a
cyberfigure who can be configured to resemble the recipient of the
gift.
</P>
<P>
   By using these new technologies, Lands' End hopes to greatly
reduce shoppers' concerns about making exchanges of gifts. ``We are
trying very hard to make sure you get the right product right from
the beginning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Baltaxe, the e-commerce analyst, said Lands' End's
spending spree to boost technology and staffing is typical this
year. ``A lot of money has been spent to make sure people are
ready,'' he said. ``Last year, some Web sites crashed because they
weren't prepared for the crush of business. ... They won't let that
happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is so intense because the scrutiny from Wall Street
will be so close, he said. ``Now is the time to prove you can grab
(online customers) and make sure they enjoy using you,'' he said.
``If you can do that, you'll find the Holy Grail _ the ability to
carry over customers'' into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Big holiday sales and satisfied customers will prompt venture
capitalists and stock investors to pour much more money into
e-commerce, making instant millionaires, even billionaires, out of
many e-tailers.
</P>
<P>
   Those entrepreneurs are hoping they'll please first-time holiday
shoppers like Jennifer Reichenbach, a 32-year-old Atlanta resident
who recently has begun making purchases online, primarily because
of the 24-hour-a-day convenience. ``I really, really like it,'' she
said. ``In fact, I almost fear getting addicted to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-18-99 1111EDT &QL;
</P>
