 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Quicken upgrade a bit buggy 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to personal finance software, Mac users
don't have much choice. It's either Intuit's Quicken or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Intuit has done a pretty good job with Quicken. The
company just released the latest version, called Quicken 2000, and
it's a nice upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been two years since the latest version, you
won't find any major breakthroughs in terms of features in Quicken
2000. This version largely represents a fine-tuning of old features
and a touch-up of the program's look and feel.
</P>
<P>
   As always with a Quicken update, there's a host of bugs.
Internet bulletin boards have been plastered with user complaints.
The biggest seems to be the inability of Quicken 2000 in some cases
to read and update old files.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled launches are nothing new for the latest versions of
Quicken, which are often buggy. The good news is that Intuit is
pretty good about fixing problems through patches that can be
downloaded from the Internet or your local Mac users bulletin
board.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I've had no problem with either installing or
updating my Quicken files to the latest version. I suspect problems
are isolated and probably created by conflicts with certain system
extensions.
</P>
<P>
   The best new addition to Quicken 2000 is something called the
Insight window. It's a customized screen that gives you a snapshot
of your financial status.
</P>
<P>
   Insight can list and total all your accounts, including credit
card debt, and display in multicolored charts your cash flow or
lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   The other big change is the new, cleaned-up interface. Gone are
the big buttons that lined the top and left side of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   They have been replaced with a tabbed toolbar along the top of
the screen. You can customize both the tabs and the toolbars under
each of them. This is a less cluttered, easier-to-use layout.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements include a tighter integration with the
Internet. Quicken 2000 comes with direct links to Intuit's vast Web
presence. With a click of a button you can download through Quicken
2000 historical share prices of mutual funds or individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   You can also jump to services that provide comparative shopping
for insurance, mortgages and credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite among the new features is a small but
highly useful change. Quicken can now accurately recognize
electronic payments. In the past, many merchants were identified
only as addresses if you banked electronically through Quicken.
</P>
<P>
   Should you run out and buy Quicken 2000? It depends on the
strength of your stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Go out and upgrade if you don't mind the potential risk of some
buggy installation and conversion problems. Otherwise, wait a few
more weeks until Intuit inevitably posts the fixes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
