<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-CYBERWARFARE-REVI     10-20 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERWARFARE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWN TO BITS: CYBERWARFARE BREAKS THE RULES OF MILITARY 
ENGAGEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixteen Years ago, in the movie ``WarGames,'' Matthew Broderick
played a computer hacker who electronically ferrets his way into
the Pentagon's Norad early warning system inside Cheyenne Mountain,
Colo., and almost starts World War III by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the military finally struck back. The Pentagon
created a new military center to harness the nation's disparate
cyberwarfare forces under the Air Force Space Command at Peterson
Air Force Base in Colorado Springs. That followed the public
acknowledgment by Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, that the United States played hacker itself earlier this
year _ waging a keyboard war against Serbian computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond challenging America's own military culture and requiring
sophisticated technology, cyberwarfare raises a fundamental
philosophical question. The biggest challenge that such warfare may
pose for democratic societies is that it further blurs the line
between military and nonmilitary targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cyberwarfare involves deliberately targeting noncombatants,''
said Mark Rasch, a former federal prosecutor and an expert on legal
issues in computer security. ``Frequently, you're not going after a
government or military or some strategic target.'' The target might
instead be a public utility.
</P>
<P>
   The new command's first mission will be to coordinate the
defense of the military's computer networks against foreign threats
and cyberterrorists. Soon after the mission will expand to include
offense: Joint Task Force Computer Network Attack, in Pentagon
jargon, designed to conduct wartime military operations against
computer networks in enemy countries.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of an information-war fighting capability to the
Pentagon's quiver takes activities that have largely been confined
to covert military and intelligence operations and makes them part
of the nation's military chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the new center is a public acknowledgment that
as the world's most technically advanced nation, the United States
is also potentially the most vulnerable to foreign cyberthreats.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of simultaneous computer network attacks against
banking, transportation, commerce and utility targets _ as well as
against the military _ conjures up the fear of an electronic Pearl
Harbor in which the nation is paralyzed without a single bullet
ever being fired.
</P>
<P>
   But the real-world challenge faced by the military is likely to
be more subtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat is going to be death by a thousand cuts, rather
than a giant attack,'' said a former top military scientist.
``There will be a little bit of this and a little bit of that.''
</P>
<P>
   This ghost-in-the-machine threat is perhaps the military's worst
nightmare and also the one that a closed and secretive military
organization may have the most difficulty combating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can throw technology at this but it's not a
technology problem at all,'' said Ronald Knecht, a former Pentagon
official who helped develop information warfare policy for three
decades and who is now senior vice president for corporate
development at Science Applications International Corp., a large
military contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, he said, is to change a military culture that has
fought wars with bombs and tanks into one that fights with bits and
bytes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preparing for cyberwar will force the nation to rethink the
way it fights wars,'' said Steven Lukasik, a military analyst at
the Center for International Security and Cooperation at Stanford
University and a former director of the Pentagon's Advanced
Research Projects Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trained to fight nuclear wars where static defenses
are fatal,'' he said. ``But in information warfare we have to
rethink everything. It may be that Maginot Lines have basically
gotten a bad name.'' In other words, building impenetrable
electronic walls may be a more effective tactic in cyberwarfare.
</P>
<P>
   A deeper challenge for the Pentagon may be keeping pace with
Silicon Valley's fast-paced consumer technology companies. Until
the end of the Cold War, the most powerful computer technology
would trickle down from a handful of defense contractors and
supercomputer companies financed by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, however, the most powerful computer
technologies are increasingly made by companies that make products
that go under Christmas trees. To cope with the consumer technology
challenge, the CIA announced plans this month to set up a venture
capital fund to gain quicker access to state-of-art technologies
being incubated in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon's problem may be compounded because the
technology is the same as in consumer products but the rules of
cyberwarfare are different, said Knecht of Stanford. He said a
military commander should expect an attack that blocks access to
his computer networks ``and he should assume that somebody who has
approved access to his networks is working for the other side _ and
still be ready to fight a war.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-18-99 0924EDT &QL;
</P>
