<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-TIME-HNS     10-20 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-TIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH TIME ZONE ARE YOU IN: INTERNET OR ROADKILL? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVE MURPHY   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When our home phone line went dead recently, it
reminded me of something that workers had better know. There are
two time zones in America these days: Internet time and roadkill.
</P>
<P>
   When I called the phone company that Wednesday afternoon, the
recorded voice told me that a technician would arrive on Saturday
between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m. When I called back the next day to ask a
real person if she could narrow that 10-hour window, she said the
technician would show up between 2 and 6.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday came, and so did the technician _ at 11:30 a.m. He
fixed the line outside, but didn't bother to call afterward just to
make sure everything was OK. The next day, an automated voice from
the phone company called to say the line was fixed; it didn't
mention anything about crediting my account for the three days my
line didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a phone company horror story. The line did get fixed,
and I'm sure I could get a credit on my bill if I called to
complain. But you could also say that waiting three days and having
that original 10-hour window is ridiculous in this day and age,
that it's pretty bad when a technician misses a four-hour window by
2 1/2 hours, and that I shouldn't have to complain to get my
account credited.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company is operating in the roadkill time zone, acting
like a monopoly at a time when few monopolies are safe. Too many
companies and industries are still in that zone, not realizing that
the Internet not only has increased competition, but has made
people more impatient with the old ways of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a booming economy like this one, lots of companies fail.
</P>
<P>
   And even with unemployment at 30-year lows, many workers get
left behind. In both cases, the problem is usually the same:
They're operating on roadkill time.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have more skills today than you did five years ago,
the world is passing you by. The status quo just won't cut it
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses get comfortable. They have happy customers, and
all seems to be well. Then the landlord raises the rent or a
competitor moves in, and their business suddenly isn't so
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Workers get comfortable, too. Then their company pushes for more
profits or increased productivity, and their jobs suddenly aren't
so comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to blame greedy landlords or office politics or evil
bosses, but the main cause is that people are reacting _ slowly _
to things as they happen. You need to be thinking a couple of years
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Look at your career. Do you see your company doing business as
usual five years from now? If you do, somebody is a fool; now all
you have to do is decide whether it's you or your chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still operating on roadkill time, five years isn't
much.
</P>
<P>
   But on Internet time, it's a couple of generations. Think back
to how relatively meaningless the Web was in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Roadkill thinking is dangerous even for people who believe they
have it made, like government workers. Local governments have been
known to outsource entire departments to get the work done less
expensively. If people see more efficiency in business and less
efficiency in government, expect the political pressure to
increase.
</P>
<P>
   How do you see your company changing in five years? Are
competitors likely to surface? Will your industry have more or
fewer jobs? What will you need to know then that you don't know
now? When you're applying for a job, are you just responding to the
employer's questions, or are you offering ideas of your own?
</P>
<P>
   Take the ``Where do you see yourself in 10 years?'' job
interview question and turn it around. Where do you see that
company in 10 years? Where does your prospective boss see it?
Before you even write a cover letter, show some initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the company's store or Web sites. Find out what
competitors are doing. Go into the interview prepared to talk for
10 minutes about why you want to work for that company and what you
could offer. (Don't actually give the 10-minute talk; just think
about the elements that would go into it.) And, of course, don't
show up for an appointment 2 1/2 hours early. Only phone companies
can get away with that.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-19-99 1442EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
