r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-20 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW GOOFY CAN WE GET ON CANDIDATES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald Trump for president. Is that the goofiest idea to drop
out of nowhere onto the 2000 campaign trail?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really. The goofiest idea would be Warren Beatty for
president.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, Beatty for president isn't the goofiest idea.
The goofiest idea is Cybill Shepherd for president.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there's Jesse Ventura for president. There's Pat
Buchanan for president. And, of course, there's the truly goofy
idea that never seems to go away: Ross Perot for president.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that's weirder than such would-be commanders in
chief running for president is the mind-boggling decision of the
media and the public to treat them as serious candidates. If we
took the whole bunch of them and cooked them into some sort of
star-studded candidate stew, we wouldn't have the ingredients for
one legitimate contender.
</P>
<P>
   And yet here we are, talking about them as if they have
something going for them as potential presidents _ something beyond
unrestrained ego and unbridled audacity, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a reflection of the voters' lack of enthusiasm for the
real candidates? Or an indication that voters and the media have
become hopelessly undiscriminating in their view of politics as we
enter the waning days of a presidency that has demonstrated
conclusively that the elected leader of the greatest nation on the
planet need not be someone who commands widespread respect, much
less admiration?
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Clinton can be elected twice and survive both terms in
the face of irrefutable evidence that he is a self-serving,
duplicitous worm, why shouldn't we look favorably upon the
candidacies of tabloid celebrities, professional wrestlers,
has-been speech writers and blowhard billionaires?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe our yearning to curb the business-as-usual escapades of
professional politicians is so desperate that we're willing to
consider drastic measures. Or maybe the populace is simply inclined
to wager that a ``character'' might exhibit more character than
some of the pols we've endured in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' as the great Bob Dole used to say.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, individuals whose presidential aspirations would
have been ignored or laughed off not so long ago are suddenly being
taken seriously _ or semi-seriously, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Take Donald Trump. The real estate/casino kingpin has formed an
exploratory committee to ponder a possible run for the White House.
He's so serious about it, in fact, that he said the other day that
he'd be filing papers to put his name on the ballot in California.
</P>
<P>
   And others are taking him seriously, too. One of Trump's
ex-wives, Marla Maples, is so horrified by The Donald's interest in
the White House that she has vowed to campaign against him if he
runs.
</P>
<P>
   According to news reports, Maples intends to ``tell the people
what he is really like'' if Trump dares to seek the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And what was Trump's reaction to the former Mrs. Trump's
critique of his fitness for the Oval Office? According to the New
York Daily News, Trump refused to hand over a $1.5 million payment
that he owed Maples on their divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
   This guy knows how to play hardball. You think Saddam Hussein
won't be shaking in his boots if Trump is elected president of the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   Look, folks, the 2000 election is still a long way off, and it's
undeniably fun to imagine what a Donald Trump administration would
do about nuclear proliferation or what a President Ventura would do
with the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   It's even fun to imagine Warren Beatty conducting a
no-holds-barred campaign just like the one his fictional candidate
staged in that ``Bulworth'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   But imagining is all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   Even if one of these National Enquirer headline-grabbers winds
up on the presidential ballot, he or she will be lucky to collect
more than a handful of votes. In the end, voters will realize _ as
they always do _ that choosing a president is serious business.
</P>
<P>
   The real candidates may not be exciting, but they are the real
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
