<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING STOCK IN HIZZONER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Can San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown outperform
Martha Stewart? I don't mean at setting party tables or field-
stripping a jammed glue gun.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm sure Brown is ahead of Stewart in most matters of taste,
as long as it doesn't involve anything trickier than opening a
bottle of champagne. What I'm talking about is money, a field in
which Brown is no slouch either.
</P>
<P>
   If Willie Brown went public, would his stock outperform that of
Martha Stewart Omnimedia Inc., which raised $129 million in a day?
I'm sure it would. This is a man who can lift an eyebrow and raise
millions from developers and big corporations for host committees,
which throw the dough away on conferences, summits and junkets.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, unlike the kind of hostess gifts Martha might
suggest, there are some real returns for those corporations in
terms of doing business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's initial public stock offering probably would even
outperform the World Wrestling Federation, whose IPO raised $170
million in a day. After all, the WWF's performers aren't as
colorful or as good at in-fighting and braggadocio as Brown is.
</P>
<P>
   Why should the chief executive of San Francisco have an IPO?
Well, this public servant has to have something to offer the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been at the helm of a great enterprise of a city, one
which has allowed developers to build up San Francisco block by
block and parking lot by parking lot. So we might as well have a
chance to buy stock in a company _ which like Stewart's, is just
him.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stewart, he's selling style. Like a lot of dot-com
companies, his promises are his most important product.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown had an IPO, he should stay away from cute Internet
names like DaMayor.com. He should just stick to Willie Brown Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown is a powerful brand name, almost as powerful as
Martha Stewart. He exerts complete control over his empire the way
she does over hers. And he doesn't waste time constructing cute
centerpieces. Well, not counting that tacky stadium and mall which
was supposed to be a centerpiece of his administration, but is on
hold for a festive football season to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, if Brown went public, the public could lose big time.
</P>
<P>
   Like most IPOs, ``qualified investors,'' better known as
insiders, would snap up ``pre-market'' shares.
</P>
<P>
   You know who the qualified investors would be. Name some hotel
chains, banks and corporations with interests in San Francisco, as
well as the lobbyists who represent them.
</P>
<P>
   What would the Securities and Exchange Commission think of an
IPO by Willie Brown Inc.? You know this is a guy who'd have a hard
time with the quiet period that's supposed to surround a stock
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Executives aren't supposed to hype their stock, something Brown
has been doing with himself for years. The phrase ``quiet period''
doesn't fit with a man who is all exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   He'd have to continually say, ``You'll have to check with my
staff, and they're not allowed to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, where does Brown go? For a quiet period, he
could be locked in Sony's Metreon. This greatest of San Francisco
movie fans could shuttle among 11 screens, watching ``Blue Streak''
instead of talking one, and enjoying ``Fight Club'' instead of
blood-lust campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   It would give all of us a break, too.
</P>
<P>
   If Willie Brown went public, the biggest problem he'd face is
the same one Martha Stewart faced. His face and voice are his
company, just as her face and voice are her company.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to invest in a company of one person, even if that
person comes with a massive cult of personality.
</P>
<P>
   If Martha Stewart died in an unfortunate chutney-bottling
accident, her stock would go through the highly polished hardwood
floor. No one can replace Martha.
</P>
<P>
   No one can replace Willie, either. His Stepford Supervisors are
great at following his orders, but they can't follow his act.
</P>
<P>
   If Willie Brown leaves office, an event most polls say will
happen in four years, shares of his stock wouldn't be worth the
cocktail napkins they were written on.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
