<SLUG> BC-OKTOBERFEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAWING ON GERMAN TRADITION, OCTOBER'S A TIME FOR BEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The harvest is a season for celebrations and
toasts. For raising a glass to bless the bounty.
</P>
<P>
   No one does this better than the French, who have turned the
annual release of Beaujolais nouveau on the third Thursday in
November into an international gala event.
</P>
<P>
   But the Germans are not, dare we say, crying in their beer. They
have also captured the world's fancy with Oktoberfest, a nearly
200-year-old celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It began as a party honoring a prince and princess but it has
evolved into a festival that salutes that country's premier
beverage: beer.
</P>
<P>
   The craft-beer renaissance that has swept across America in the
past decade has inspired breweries big and small to fall in step,
producing their own versions of Oktoberfest.
</P>
<P>
   But what is Oktoberfest beer, which some U.S. breweries spell
with the Germanized ``K'' while others, like Boston-based Sam
Adams, with a ``C'' _ as in October Fest lager?
</P>
<P>
   ``A traditional Oktoberfest is an orange-gold beer that's malty
and stronger than a normal lager, and not very hoppy. The malt is
in the forefront of the flavor,'' explains Paul McErlean, head
brewer at the Van Dyck brew pub in Schenectady. McErlean has made a
beer in this style, though he spells it with a ``C,'' and he
reports it is selling fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far and away the best-selling seasonal beer that we brew.
It just flies out of here the moment we make it. I don't know if
it's the name, but there's no comparison to Oktoberfest,'' McErlean
notes, explaining how this nation has embraced the harvest
celebration with gusto. ``You could basically call anything
Oktoberfest and it will sell out.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because Oktoberfests can be whatever the brewer wants
them to be. Charles Noll, at Malt River in Latham, has a
traditional Oktoberfest lager on tap, but Drew Schmidt, at the Big
House in Albany, is serving a non-fruity ale he calls ``Fest''
beer. He had produced a Vienna-style beer similar to the
traditional Oktoberfest, but it disappeared quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Peter Martin at the Troy Pub and Brewery made a
German alt (an Old World-style ale) for the annual Oktoberfest
celebration, which took place the first weekend of the month. It
also went in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Says Martin, ``Oktoberfests can be anything. It's tough to
define Oktoberfest. It's anything you want it to be, though it's
usually a heavier-body-type lager or ale. The way I understand it,
an Oktoberfest is any beer brewed for a festival.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, no ``event beer'' has more flexibility than
Oktoberfests. The German festival, the mother of all Oktoberfests,
is held in Munich. It actually begins in mid-September and runs
through early October. An estimated 6 million visitors attended
this year's event, putting away some 5 million liters of beer and
200,000 pairs of pork sausages.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their variety, Oktoberfest beers also have something in
common. Explains Noll, at Malt River: ``If it's done right, you
don't want just one pint of Oktoberfest. It's the type of beer you
want a couple of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      10-20 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLS GIVES GIULIANI THE EDGE IN SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ More New Yorkers would vote against Hillary
Rodham Clinton as a U.S. Senate candidate than vote for her, a new
poll indicates.
</P>
<P>
   The survey by the Zogby International polling organization shows
the probable Democratic nominee carrying an ``unfavorable rating''
of 48.4 percent among likely voters, as opposed to her ``favorable
rating'' of 46.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time the potential candidate's statistical
negatives have eclipsed her positives in her still-undeclared
campaign, pollster John Zogby of Utica said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Catholics, independents and political moderates
strongly favor Clinton's likely Republican opponent, New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, in the potential Senate contest, according to the
poll. That is bad news for Clinton, who will need to curry support
among those groups _ particularly in the suburbs and in upstate New
York _ in order to win.
</P>
<P>
   If they become the nominees, Clinton and Giuliani will be vying
to succeed Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat who is
retiring at the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's favorable rating stands at 54.5 percent, compared to
his unfavorables, which tally 35.4 percent, according to the Zogby
poll.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed Clinton trouncing Giuliani in New York City
and among liberals, blacks and Hispanics. Overall, however,
Giuliani is leading Clinton by a 51 percent to 40 percent margin,
according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson declined to comment.
Democratic officials, however, privately complained about the poll,
charging that Zogby is partial to Giuliani since he worked on the
mayor's 1997 re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I'm proudest of is that Republicans think
I'm a Democrat and Democrats think I'm a Republican,'' said Zogby,
shrugging off the criticisms. Zogby is an enrolled Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was taken Oct. 15-18 and included interviews with 700
likely New York voters. It has a margin of error of 3.8 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby also tested voters' inclinations on a possible Democratic
presidential primary between Vice President Al Gore and former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The two contenders remain in a statistical dead heat, with Gore
edging Bradley in New York by a 41 percent to 37.5 percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side of the political aisle, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush would sweep Arizona Sen. John McCain by 48 percent to 12
percent, the poll indicates. McCain's campaign, however, won an
important endorsement this week from former Rep. Guy Molinari, the
current Staten Island borough president, signaling a split within
the state GOP. Gov. George Pataki and state Republican Party
Chairman Bill Powers support Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      10-20 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
