<HEADLINE>
EX-CNN ANCHOR SAYS THE SKY'S THE LIMIT FOR NEW WEB VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Former CNN financial journalist Lou Dobbs is on
a mission to change the perception that Web sites stressing stories
over selling stuff are doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I hear these generalizations, I know I'm listening to
someone who doesn't understand the Web at all,'' said Dobbs, in his
trademark sonorous voice between puffs of a cigarette. ``The Web,''
he said, ``is an ever-changing world that sweeps aside anyone's set
conceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, Dobbs created a sort of journalistic sun flare
when he clocked out as anchor of CNN's ``Moneyline,'' the cable
news network's daily business report that was its most lucrative
program.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs blamed his departure on CNN upper management, which he
said sent him mixed messages on his involvement with his business,
Space.com, a project he decided to pursue in June.
</P>
<P>
   Space.com (www.space.com) features an array of space-related
subjects: breaking aerospace industry news, gossip, the shooting of
horror film director John Carpenter's coming science fiction epic,
``Ghosts on Mars.'' The site sports an impressive array of talent,
including the Internet site's president, Sally Ride, the first
woman in space. It has opened bureaus at Cape Canaveral and
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   When CNN brass finally said Dobbs could not be even a passive
investor in Space.com, he quit the network.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines of a CNN front office feud followed, which Dobbs now
waved away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just fishing last month with Ted, and he said to me `I
hope you make a million dollars,''' Dobbs said, referring to CNN
founder Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs said he continues to hold a grudge against some senior CNN
executives. ``I wouldn't return some phone calls,'' Dobbs said with
a sniff.
</P>
<P>
   CNN spokesman Christa Robinson said the network had no comment
on Dobbs' departure, except to say, ``Lou Dobbs? Oh, we've heard of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dobbs-CNN spat is far from over. The financial anchor
appeared Oct. 4 on NBC's ``Today'' show to announce he would be
providing occasional business news commentary, which could brush up
against a non-compete clause in Dobbs' previous CNN contract.
</P>
<P>
   The move prompted CNN to issue a terse statement: ``We have a
contractual agreement with Lou Dobbs, and we expect that he will
live up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs prefers to talk about his new venture.
</P>
<P>
   Space.com is funded with Dobbs' own money and $25 million from
Venrock Associates, the venture capital company of the Rockefeller
family. Its basic business model is selling advertising, which has
also been a less-than-roaring success in stemming the red ink
spilling from many Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked for 19 years at CNN under the advertising model,''
Dobbs said. ``It works in cable. It can work for the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs added that the site also will announce some electronic
commerce plans within the next 60 days, though he did not offer any
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want it all to be a big surprise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe Space.com's success could be more than a
science fiction story.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the popularity of science fiction of Web sites for Babylon
5, Star Trek and Star Wars are any indication, then he has a pretty
good chance,'' said Tom Huskerson, a research associate with the
Redwood City-based Zona Research, an Internet market data company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer in sites that are organized around
existing interest groups,'' said David Card, a senior analyst with
Jupiter Communications Inc., a New York Internet research company.
``So on that basis, I think Space.com has a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
