A2815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MITCH-REBUILD-$ADV23-     10-20 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-REBUILD-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A NEW TOWN, HOPE RISE OUTSIDE FLOODED HONDURAN VILLAGE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For locator map purposes, Marcovia is a village a few miles
from the Gulf of Fonseca on the Pacific coast.
 &HT;    With CENTAM-MITCH-$ADV23.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARCOVIA, Honduras _ The walls are unadorned cement blocks, the
floor is poured concrete, the roof made from plain sheets of metal.
The kitchen is a lean-to out back with a small, smoky cooking fire.
</P>
<P>
   But Rita Galvez proudly sits inside the tiny structure, holding
her breath. To her, this diminutive house _ the size of a typical
two-car American garage _ may as well be a millionaire's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed I would have a house like this,'' she says,
gazing with wide eyes at her 400-square-foot, four-room bungalow.
``Sometimes I talk with friends from my old village and I still
can't believe I am living here.''
</P>
<P>
   One year after Hurricane Mitch devastated Central America, life
is getting better for thousands of the killer storm's victims.
Although new flooding this fall has brought more misery to many of
those left homeless by Mitch, a massive rebuilding program
spearheaded by aid groups from around the world has made
significant progress.
</P>
<P>
   A dramatic example is here in Marcovia, a low-lying village in
south Honduras, a few miles from the Gulf of Fonseca on the Pacific
coast. Mitch's torrential rains turned the normally placid
Choluteca River into a raging force that inundated miles of the
flat coastal plain.
</P>
<P>
   Small villages were swept away or covered with mud to the
rooftops, and dozens of people drowned. Prized farm animals were
lost, along with the sugar cane, cantaloupe and pond-raised shrimp
that provided most of the work in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based CARE, Ox-Fam, the Red Cross and other
international aid agencies joined forces to build a whole new town
on high ground a few miles outside flood-prone Marcovia. The new
village is called ``Renacer Marcovia,'' or ``Reborn Marcovia.''
</P>
<P>
   It spreads across 70 acres of pasture, row upon row of small,
square houses. The streets are still muddy in places, and children
bath in a stream that winds through the property. Sewer and water
lines have yet to be installed, but temporary latrines and
trucked-in water are an improvement over what many of the poor
residents lived with previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``My old house had a dirt floor,'' said Galvez, who now sweeps
her new home's cement floor several times a day, stepping carefully
over a threshold poured in the doorway that is inscribed with the
family's name. ``It only had two rooms and no windows. We had nine
people living there.''
</P>
<P>
   The new town was designed by Carolina Gamero, a Honduran
architect. In an exhausting year of work, she has seen the town
rise before her eyes, an accomplishment that many residents never
believed would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them didn't want to leave the places where they lived
before,'' she said. ``At first, they didn't like this place because
it was hot and had few trees. But as the houses have come up, they
are starting to see what we envisioned.''
</P>
<P>
   The residents were required to build the houses themselves, with
aid workers teaching them how to lay block, square up walls and mix
cement. Some 600 homes are now finished, with another 600 to go.
The town will eventually house about 8,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Gamero, 35, now walks around town, overseeing construction
crews, pushing for faster work, resolving small conflicts. She is
constantly praised and hugged, often by proud new homeowners with
tears in their eyes. She is also begged by doubters who didn't
commit to work on the new town but now want in.
</P>
<P>
   ``For months we came here and it was some new problem every
day,'' she said. ``It was 120 degrees at times and people didn't
want to work. They didn't believe we could do it. Now we walk
around and see children playing and it's becoming a real town.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
