<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COLLEGES-SECURITY-2ND     10-20 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGES-SECURITY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... they have  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If they don't, they are in violation of the law and they will
lose any federal funding,'' says Howard Clery, who wrote most of
the law. To get the law passed, the Clerys rallied a dozen parents
of murdered students from all over the country to lobby Congress.
</P>
<P>
   One might think that campus security is a no-brainer: Who would
be against it? But colleges have thrown up numerous roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're afraid to lose money, they're afraid to lose
enrollment and alumni giving,'' says Connie. The Clerys feel the
laws they have pushed for have closed many loopholes, but they
remain vigilant _ ``pit bulls,'' as she puts it. Schools that used
to hide behind the confidentiality of student records must now
disclose the names of those charged with violent crimes so that
other students can be protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``A reporter once asked Harvard about the punishment for a
campus rape,'' Howard says, ``and the dean said it was none of
their business. It had been handled through the campus judicial
system. That's what we call a coverup.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Clerys set out to change the law. Under the old system at
many colleges, victims could bring neither character witnesses nor
lawyers to the campus hearings, while the accused could. The Campus
Sexual Assault Victims Bill of Rights assures the same rights for
both parties _ and makes a rapist's punishment, and whether he
remains on campus, public information.
</P>
<P>
   Campus police logs, many of them formerly closed even to student
reporters, are now required to be open to the public. (The Clerys
were assisted by an editor of the Harvard Crimson, who wrote the
law.) Another Security on Campus law mandates that crime statistics
be reported to the US Department of Education, or campuses will be
fined $25,000 per infraction. (The Clerys have recently
investigated six schools and all were found guilty of failing to
report crime.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Most colleges do not want to have rape exposed, and religious
schools are the worst,'' says Howard, 69. ``They say, `We teach
morals,' and all that, and rape blows the whole thing out of the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clerys and their son, Howard III, 40, who is treasurer of
Security on Campus, can rattle off case after case of violent
campus crimes, enough to make parents want to send their child to a
deserted island instead of college. They're currently bothered by
the swiftness with which campus security cleans up a crime scene,
often leaving little evidence behind.
</P>
<P>
   And they are horrified by binge drinking: 80 percent of violent
campus crime is alcohol-related. The most recent law they worked on
requires that a student arrested for selling or using drugs must
forfeit any federal scholarship money and can only reapply to
school a year later _ with drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Change for the better
</P>
<P>
   Still, they see some positive changes, with the presidents of
113 colleges banding together for a major advertising campaign
against student drinking. More administrators, they say, are
cracking down on underage drinking, calling the police themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the Clerys are turning their attention to the college
admissions process. If applications can include such questions as
those about your parents' income and what they do for a living, why
can't they ask if you have ever been arrested and convicted of a
felony or of drunken driving? And, while students are submitting
their physical forms, why not send along a drug test, too?
</P>
<P>
   The Clerys don't just criticize; each year, they recognize
progress. They recently gave Michigan State University the Jeanne
Clery Award for Campus Safety: The campus has 50 armed police
officers, 50 security officers, a SWAT team, and an undercover
narcotics force, more than a decent-sized town.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, they honored Boston University for its openness in
reporting campus crime. Today, they are disappointed to hear about
a recent campus rape at BU, along with allegations by an earlier
victim that the school did little to protect her.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Connie and Jeanne Clery won the Eastern US
regionals in a mother-daughter tennis tournment. Connie is 67 years
old now, a former soccer-and-tennis mom who would never have
dreamed about speaking to the PTO, much less Congress. But since
her daughter's death, she has traveled the country, appearing on
talk shows and before congressional committees to plead for campus
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lehigh University erected a pavilion in memory of Jeanne
Clery, her parents' activism remains a living monument. ``You
couldn't have paid me a million dollars to get up and speak
before,'' Connie Clery says. ``But Jeannie's death has freed me.
I'm not afraid of anything or anybody anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
