<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MERCY FOR POOR TENANTS IN MASS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts has appointed himself
chief landlord and leech, leading the call to bleed apartment
dwellers dry. Speaking before the Rental Housing Association of the
Greater Boston Real Estate Board, Cellucci said he would veto any
new legislation for state housing subsidies despite runaway rents
in Boston. He also said he would block any attempt to bring back
rent control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not waive the rules of the competitive free market,''
Cellucci said. He added, ``The free market got us into this
situation, and it will be the free market that gets us out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience of about 100 fellow leeches cheered the governor.
Housing advocates and Boston politicians groaned. Two months ago
Mayor Menino said, ``We just don't have the partnership with the
federal government anymore, or much of one with state government.''
Upon hearing Cellucci's latest speech, Menino said, ``The market
hasn't handled the problem because there's not enough support out
there to help build affordable housing.''
</P>
<P>
   The free market forces, or rather, the forces that freed the
market from conscience by persuading the state's voters to kill
rent control five years ago, act as if they owe nothing to the
collective good of the city. In their mind rent control was just
the beginning of a bonanza _ the average studio in Boston's Jamaica
Plain section has gone from $549 a month in 1995 to $959 today.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, as Cellucci and the 100 leeches celebrated the free
market at the glitzy Seaport Hotel, that they do not want to hear
how the market has closed in on families who cram into small
apartments with other families. The number of families who are
huddling up together, perhaps 5,000, has grown to a level where
housing advocates call them the ``invisible homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going into a house and there were 20 people living
there,'' said Jamaica Plain housing activist Norma Rosario in an
interview last May in the Globe. ``When the landlord walked in, the
children rushed in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the landlords do not recoil at the sight and outright
evict them, Boston-area tenants are increasingly being forced to
undergo slow torture. In Cambridge at least 40 percent of renters
are forking over more than 30 percent of their income toward rent,
the maximum level that is considered affordable. In Boston, over
37,000 tenants, enough to burst out of Fenway Park, pay 50 percent
or more of their income in rent.
</P>
<P>
   The response of government has been appalling. Last winter the
federal government slashed funding for the homeless in Boston by 40
percent. Between 1994 to 1997, Massachusetts's share of federal
funds for housing was cut by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rent control surely had its anecdotal abuses that locked the
truly deserving out of apartments, but rents without control are
far more abusive to the multitude. City Hall housing adviser Pat
Canavan has said: ``If we don't do something collectively, as a
region, it will have implications none of us want to see. It will
become more difficult for young people to come in and find work.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Gornstein, executive director of the Citizens Housing and
Planning Association, has said, ``I think in terms of what it will
take to change this is that housing will have to be put on the
radar screen like education and health care, and if it is not
elevated, then we won't make a dent in the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step is for Cellucci and the leeches to admit that
there is a problem. Right now they reflexively pooh-pooh anything
that smacks of controls. Last year, Edwin Shanahan, executive
director of the state Rental Housing Association, said that without
rent control, ``the city is very, very much alive again.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment it is _ for those with money. But recent major
studies strongly suggest that one of the major threats to continued
economic development in Boston and its near suburbs is the cost of
housing. The threat is so obvious that religious leaders such as
Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston have called it a ``critical growth
issue,'' a problem ``we can either take on rationally or wait until
it has done this area serious economic damage.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is time for Cellucci to stop saying things like ``a hot
economy comes at a price,'' as if it is perfectly acceptable that
the price is being paid by families who pay so much in rent that
they could never afford the down payment for a house. It is time
for the leeches to stop talking about the infusion of wealthy
high-tekkies and think about the housing choices those tekkies are
going to make when they start pushing around innocent tykes.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci says he will not ``waive the rules of the competitive
free market.'' If he is not careful, many people whom we need to
maintain the vitality of this city and state will wave goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
