<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TINA'S WAKE, A DEVASTATED NEW YORKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a man in New York City named Robert Gottlieb, who works
for the publishing house Alfred A. Knopf. He is in his 60s, about 6
feet tall, not very gray. He works a lot at home, and occasionally
lopes over to Knopf headquarters on East 49th Street, where he
mooches around the office, chatting amiably with acquaintances in
the corridors.
</P>
<P>
   He is not vainglorious and, in keeping with company tradition,
there is no corporate biography or curriculum vitae of Gottlieb
available to outsiders. ``They should be talking about the books,
not about us,'' was how Knopf himself put it. But to an
ever-growing number of magazine readers, Gottlieb will always be
remembered as the last editor of the New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The clouds are finally parting around the country's most
prestigious literary magazine. And the vista is not very pretty.
The incalculable damage of the Tina Brown editorship is clearly
visible now. The magazine has been reduced in stature, and her
handpicked successor is floundering, imprisoned by her legacy of
``buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brown game has been laid bare in her new, already failed
magazine Talk. Her goal, as in her early years at the New Yorker,
was to generate talk, or ``buzz'' about the publication. And just
as people talk about a New Yorker cover depicting a Hassidic Jew
kissing a black woman, people buzz about Gwyneth Paltrow in a
leather bikini, or about George W. Bush using the ``f'' word _ a
much-remarked-upon Brown innovation at the New Yorker. But people
talk about the toilet backing up, too. Talk is cheap. The magazine
is putrid, the staff is bolting, and Brown's Miramax backers must
be wondering what they got themselves into.
</P>
<P>
   Second verse, same as the first. It is astonishing to leaf back
through the ``old'' New Yorker under Gottlieb's five-year
editorship (1987-1992), and then remark upon what Tina wrought.
Gottlieb continued the magazine's tradition of serendipity (``A
Reporter at Large: Elephants'') and seriousness, publishing an Alec
Wilkinson series on sugar cane workers, William Finnegan's
multiparter on the drug trade in New Haven, and the astonishing
serial excerpts from Neil Sheehan's ``A Bright Shining Lie'' and
Robert Caro's Lyndon Johnson biography. Put another way: When is
the last time you couldn't wait until the next issue of a magazine
arrived?
</P>
<P>
   Brown took over the magazine in the summer of 1992, and her
first trademark issue appeared on Oct. 5. The cover depicted a
purple-haired punk slouched in a Central Park hansom. The expanded
table of contents launched several new departments, and facing the
contents one found the signature Calvin Klein ad, a photograph of a
man nuzzling a bare-breasted women who is having trouble keeping
her CK jeans around her waist. That sensibility would soon migrate
to the editorial pages, where Brown's shock-the-bourgeois style
would show us O.J. Simpson's undraped girlfriends, and much, much
more.
</P>
<P>
   What changed between Gottlieb and Brown was the social compact
between the magazine and its readers. Under Gottlieb and his
predecessor, Wallace Shawn, the readers trusted the editors'
judgment that a report on, say, the traditional Siennese horse race
(``Annals of Intrigue: The Palio'') would be worth reading. But
Brown had no judgment, no editorial compass. The magazine delegated
the responsibility of choosing its subject matter to Hollywood
flacks and Capitol Hill spinmeisters. Now it's just part of the
hype.
</P>
<P>
   The real question, is where can the magazine go now? Brown has a
superb eye for talent, and many of her hires, including editor
David Remnick, are still at the magazine. Whether through fealty to
his preceptor or lack of oomph, Remnick has yet to steer a new
course. The latest of the Brown-inspired double issues _ not the
unreadable fashion twofer, this is the unreadable ``Next'' twin
issue _ has just landed with a thud in mailboxes across the
country. And you really don't feel like opening it, because you
don't really care.
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
