<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOATED E-HEROES; HAVEL TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're not already weary of Internet hype, you might well be
after reading the current issue of Civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The usually terrific magazine surrenders more than a dozen pages
this month to cyber-bloviation, including interviews with a bunch
of corporate bigwigs Civilization insists on dubbing ``e-Heroes.''
And certainly they see themselves and their industry in a heroic
light.
</P>
<P>
   Who will gainsay them? No one, it seems. Under our swiftly
congealing conventional wisdom, it's not enough to say that
Internet entrepreneurs have come up with some useful products and
latched onto a dandy get-rich-quick scheme. No, they must be
portrayed as visionaries whose vast networks and brilliant
inventions will not just transform our planet _ Goodbye, world
hunger! Outta here, global warming! _ but may actually change human
nature itself.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most irksome is the self-celebration masquerading as
selflessness, given voice in Civilization by Sun Microsystems CEO
Scott McNealy. He boasts that he tells his employees that because
``they have all the tools and all the capabilities,'' they are
``cursed to go work hard, harder than the rest of mankind.'' (So
count your blessings, all you ditch-diggers and hotel maids toiling
for minimum wage; the stock-optioned propeller-heads of Silicon
Valley are working harder than you.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That is their donation; that is their charity; that is their
calling,'' McNealy goes on. ``And they should just deal with it,
get over it, feel good about it, and enjoy the psychic income of
making a difference.'' Oh, brother. What's the remedy for a psychic
headache?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sorry Dan, Tom, and Peter: None of the anchors of the three main
network newscasts made it onto the list of the 25 most influential
people in the media compiled by Brill's Content.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself speaks volumes about the way the media universe
has changed. It is no longer a straightforward thing to decide Who
Matters in an era when the media marketplace has exploded in a
thousand different directions, and when Oprah Winfrey, as the
magazine notes, has more clout governing best-sellers than the New
York Times Book Review does.
</P>
<P>
   So who made the influence list? Winfrey, of course, but the
magazine also delivers useful, if brief, profiles of a host of
relative unknowns who wield day-to-day decision-making power in new
spheres of influence. They include Dave Sirulnick, the 35-year-old
in charge of MTV's news operation; Lisa Prisco, who oversees the
Gap's catchy ad campaign; John A. Walsh, the snowy-bearded
innovator who has made ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' more than a
scores-and-highlights compendium; and Adrian Lurssen, the head of
the ``surfing department'' at Yahoo! Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A cursory nod to the more established media is given _ with Tim
Russert of NBC's ``Meet the Press'' andNew York Times executive
editor Joseph Lelyveld among the 25 _ but the edge goes to
new-media types. (Ironically, or tellingly, one of the ``old
media'' leaders who did make the list, Wall Street Journal managing
editor Paul E. Steiger, is reportedly weighing an offer to become
president of CNNfn, a financial-news cable network).
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the shifting balance of power, network heavyweights
such as ``60 Minutes'' honcho Don Hewitt, ``Today'' host Katie
Couric, and ``20/20'' host Barbara Walters _ along with Rather,
Brokaw and Jennings _ didn't make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not every head of state whose metaphysical ruminations
you'd care to hear, but then not every head of state is Vaclav
Havel. He holds forth to George Stephanopoulos in this month's Talk
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A dissident playwright when Czechoslovakia was one of the
captive nations in the Soviet bloc, Havel's name became familiar to
the West. Now, as the president of the Czech Republic, Havel is
grappling with both the fruits of democracy _ a ``cultural,
spiritual, social life (that) is immeasurably richer than it ever
was before'' _ and some of what he sees as drawbacks. Namely, a
newly unleashed media that raised questions about whether Havel and
the TV actress he married after his first wife died had been having
an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does bother me a little bit that of all the things
(imported) from the West, we have to go and choose one of the
worst,'' he sighs.
</P>
<P>
   But Havel speaks also of higher things, such as the question of
how God can allow suffering like that in Kosovo. He draws from his
own experience in prison, citing the time he had to make an
excruciating decision involving the freedom of his wife and
brother. ``When I decided, the decision was probably made in
relationship with that `eye' who never speaks,'' he says. ``It
speaks only very indirectly to us, the owner of that `eye'; it
speaks through our conscience. . . . He won't get rid of (Slobodan)
Milosevic for us. We have to get rid of him ourselves, but we have
to understand that we have to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
