<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-KITCHEN-BOS &LR;      10-20 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-KITCHEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KITCHEN WARS': THE REDUCTION OF A MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MY KITCHEN WARS: A MEMOIR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Betty Fussell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Point Press, $23
</P>
<P>
   Betty Harper was a smart, fun-loving Pomona College coed with a
soft pastel angora sweater and a Phi Beta Kappa key. The Second
World War was almost over. When the vets began returning home, she,
like the other girls, went looking for handsome GIs. They necked
and petted freely until each settled down with someone.
</P>
<P>
   Betty, raised by fundamentalists in a household where swearing
and drink were prohibited, found Paul Fussell. ``I fell in love the
way girls did in movies,'' she writes in ``My Kitchen Wars,''
``from the way he looked, tall and lean with jutty brows, slanted
pixie eyes and tilted smile, his shoulders slightly hunched in a
gray-blue crewneck sweater over a button-down shirt, white buck
shoes beneath gray flannels.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul hung out with an interesting literary crowd, he was headed
for Harvard for a doctorate, his father was an important corporate
lawyer, and he had a sharp wit.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps too sharp _ but that came later. The young, eager Betty,
who went on to become an important food writer and author (``The
Story of Corn,'' ``I Hear America Cooking''), saw Paul as her guide
to a higher, more cultured life she wouldn't have found otherwise.
Her mother had died tragically when she was young (``unresolved,''
wrote the insurance company after she was found dead beside an open
tin of rat poison), she had a horrid stepmother, and this guy
looked swell.
</P>
<P>
   Their life became a big academic party that went on for years
and years, first at Harvard (she went to Radcliffe for a master's
degree), then at Connecticut College for Women, and finally at
Rutgers University, in New Jersey, where they hung out mostly with
a heady group of intellectuals from Princeton. Their world was
male-dominated, and the women were there to see the men through to
their tenure posts and publications.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Fussell wanted to be taken seriously. ``I discovered that
all I had to do was ask intelligent questions,'' she writes, ``and
men of all ages would find me intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   This food-driven memoir begins in a run-down apartment with clam
dip and Ritz crackers, Betty spilling sherry down the front of a
pretty but cheap blue satin cocktail dress. It weaves through many
elaborate dinners, where the high-minded partygoers drank a lot. By
the '60s, when they fell on Julia Child's first ``Mastering the Art
of French Cooking'' volume, they began outdoing one another in the
kitchen and trading spouses after dinner. They didn't even go off
into the bedrooms, but preferred their own living rooms. Most, says
Fussell, did nothing more than neck.
</P>
<P>
   Then the cool, self-controlled Betty took the plunge and began
an affair. She and Dave shared picnics of rich chicken liver pate
with ``buckets of heavy cream,'' good Bordeaux wines,
buttermilk-battered deep-fried chicken with avocado and pear salad
in a lime vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Dave, like Paul, had a wit that often translated into withering
remarks. Paul was much too interested in himself and his own work
to take a real interest in Betty, she writes. He was becoming known
in his field. When they were having adventures abroad or people
were coming for one of Betty's famous parties, it was still fun _
too much fun to decide that the marriage really wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   Betty wonders if the downturn didn't begin when Paul wrote ``The
Great War and Modern Memory,'' which won him acclaim. Or whether it
was when she decided to return to graduate school for a doctorate
when their children were grown. She wanted him to thank for all her
years of devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul reaped the merit badges for his prize-winning book, and I
faded like an old Polaroid. I grew resentful, but not, as Paul
assumed, because I was jealous of his fame. I wanted something
simpler and subtler, some sign of recognition from him that his
achievement, which was real and admirable, was the result of labor
shared.'' But she acted jealous and seemed angry all the time.
</P>
<P>
   She became curious when Paul seemed too devoted to some of his
young male students. He would parade nude around a houseful of
friends. One day, she found him after a party in the study with a
male student, both naked, locked in an embrace. Later, when she was
no longer stung, they revealed their transgressions to each other.
</P>
<P>
   They lived a fascinating life, and between the food, the
parties, and travels, she has lots of stories to tell. But
Fussell's writing lacks real emotion. We never know the terrible
pain she must have suffered later on learning that she as a
2-year-old crawled around the kitchen floor beside her dead mother
while her 6-year-old brother ran for help. Or the sadness of a
stillbirth. Or the deep humiliation that her husband took no
pleasure in her. ``This would never have happened if I hadn't been
so lonely,'' he told her after she found him in the study. ``But
you admitted you're incapable of loving anyone but yourself,'' she
reminded him.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Fussell fought her war like a brave, detached soldier. Now
all the withering remarks are aimed at Paul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0163 </DOCNO>
