   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Thursday, Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ANIMATION (Hollywood) _ Admirers of Japanese animation,
including many of the pivotal figures in the American animation
community, get a certain catch in their voices when they mention
the name Hayao Miyazaki, as though describing someone not quite
human, like one of the ghostly forest spirits who populate his
work. Barry Cook and Tony Bancroft, co-directors of the Disney
animated feature ``Mulan,'' said simply in a recent tribute:
``Miyazaki is like a god to us.'' Now the great man himself is here
for the American release of ``Princess Mononoke,'' his latest work.
By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   MISHIMA-MEMOIR (Tokyo) _ Arts Abroad: A memoir about the famous
novelist Yukio Mishima stirs a copyright dispute. By Howard W.
French.
</P>
