<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2859 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LAWYER-PROFILE-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     10-20 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-PROFILE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... simple, simple, simple.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a young lawyer, Lee tried 29 cases with St. Clair, who became
his mentor and guide through the snakepit politics of big-firm
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I will always remember about him is that if
something bad happened on a case, he said it was his fault. If
something good happened, he gave the credit to those of us working
for him. I think that may have been the most important thing he
taught me. It made you want to do anything at all for him and it
made you want to take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee began trying cases on his own, amassing an impressive record
that put him on a fast track at Hale and Dorr, a notoriously
cutthroat firm. In the courtroom, he is even-keeled, quick-witted,
and meticulously prepared, his colleagues say. He preferred
simplicity and elegance to grandstanding, they say.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, after 11 years with the firm, Lee had earned enough of
a reputation to catch the attention of Lawrence Walsh, the special
prosecutor investigating the Reagan administration's role in the
Iran-Contra arms scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Hired to trace the flow of money and weapons to Nicaraguan
rebels, Lee took a leave from Hale and Dorr to spend time in
Washington and Central America, often in clandestine meetings to
determine how much contact the Contra leaders had with Reagan
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all very cloak-and-dagger,'' Lee says. ``We would get
an anonymous phone call, and someone would say, `Go to the Budget
rental car, go around back and look for a yellow car and a guy with
a green shirt.' And there we'd be, interviewing these people who
hated us and were ostensibly dangerous people. It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   He left the investigation abruptly in 1989, after getting a call
from Hale and Dorr asking him to return to take on a highly
publicized patent dispute between two biotech heavyweights,
Genetics Institute and Amgen.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen had sued Genetics Institute over the Cambridge company's
plans to market a genetically-engineered drug to treat anemia, a
drug that Amgen claimed it already owned the exclusive rights to.
Lee buried himself in the case, and as he was preparing to go to
trial, a New York Times editorial said Lee was sure to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we won, and we shocked everybody,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The case was overturned by the US Court of Appeals in
Washington, but Lee's underdog victory at trial resulted in an
explosion of so-called intellectual-property litigation at Hale and
Dorr, Lee says. Intellectual-property litigation _ the vast and
growing practice of settling disputes over the ownership of ideas,
be they software, drugs, or technological developments _ is now
among the hottest legal trends. Of the country's 10 largest
biotechnology cases, Lee has handled six. Huge clients such as
Intel and General Electric came to the firm in part because of
Lee's reputation, and it helped catapult him to prominence within
the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of that, Lee says he rarely experienced overt
racism. But the shadows of some lurking bias occasionally crossed
his path _ things he says he tried to turn to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how many times people have assumed I'm a
scientist,'' he says of the stereotype of Asians belonging in
mathematical and technical fields. That presumption, he said, is
not always a bad thing when one is in court with a highly technical
case.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, he recalls going to trial in Dallas in a lawsuit
over the ownership of video conferencing technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was this Massachusetts company trucking a Chinese lawyer
down to Texas,'' he says. ``You had to wonder what they would think
of me. But we put on a simple, elegant trial in two days. We got
experts on and off the stand quickly after they made their points
succinctly. There is a lot of merit in putting on a good case.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said that in a profession that often consumes the lives of
those who practice it, he tries most nights to leave the office
around 7 p.m. to spend time with his family. Even when he was
working on the Iran-Contra investigation, he says he made sure he
was home to coach his daughter's soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   He still plays on a team himself in a weekend league where,
according to a teammate, he plays like he lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's aggressive, fair, and extremely devoted,'' says the
teammate, Michael Eby of the Boston firm Gilman, McLaughlin &AMP;
Hanrahan. ``We've been friends and neighbors for years. I think you
could safely say he applies those things to all aspects of his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite criticism from some circles in the Asian community
that he doesn't speak out enough on behalf of racial causes, others
say Lee is doing all he ought to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is a very Darwinian profession, and for a racial
minority, it can be a very lonely place to be,'' said Rebecca Lee,
president of the Asian American Lawyer's Association of
Massachusetts and a partner at Goodwin, Proctor &AMP; Hoar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the first in this town, and he's been a beacon
for a lot of others. Every time we've needed his support, he's been
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he will spend most of his time on administrative tasks
after his promotion takes effect Feb. 1, Lee plans to try at least
three cases a year to keep his hand in litigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Lee said he hopes his work and a balanced life will
be his legacy to Asian Americans. ``What I want to be, what I hope
I am, is an example,'' he says. ``My family is most important to
me. I want to raise children who are good people. I think of my
wife and my three children. Of all the things I've done in 25
years, that's what I'm most proud of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1456EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2860 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-INTERNET-INCUBATE-ART     10-20 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-INCUBATE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREEDING TOMORROW'S NET FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Next month, Drs. Robert Adelman and Elizabeth
Quattrocki Knight will start an Internet company without maxing out
their credit cards or begging their families and friends for money.
</P>
<P>
   The two physicians will not have to go looking for office space
or arrange for phones, computers, and office furniture. They won't
need to find lawyers, accountants, or a technical team to develop
their Web site, or job search firms to fill out their management
team.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they will focus exclusively on their business concept,
knowing that they have $250,000 to $1 million available to them,
with venture capitalists nearby to finance their growth stage and
provide connections to potential business partners.
</P>
<P>
   They won't be alone. Working next to them will be another set of
Internet entrepreneurs using some of the same resources. Why?
Adelman and Knight recently moved into The Cambridge Incubator in
Kendall Square.
</P>
<P>
   This community concept of hatching Internet companies in a
single space is part of a trend in business incubators that began
with idealab of Pasadena, Calif., which has helped launch two-dozen
on-line companies in barely two years. Now that trend, having moved
through Santa Monica and Silicon Valley and into Atlanta and New
York, is catching on in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge Incubator is one of five existing or proposed
incubators in the Bay State. Each promises to provide office space,
$250,000 to $1 million or more in seed financing, shared businesss
services _ from receptionist to chief financial officer and legal
counsel _ and computers, software, networking gear, and access to
venture capitalists for future financing and advice. Entrepreneurs
will be able to share ideas as they develop their companies.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for money and nurturing, the incubator owners
receive up to 30 percent ownership stake in each start-up, which
could be worth 10 to 30 times their investment if businesses grow
quickly and are acquired or go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not want to spend a lot of time looking for office
space, setting up phone systems, interviewing venture capitalists,
buying computer equipment,'' said Adelman, who with Knight is
developing a Web site for patients with life-threatening diseases
that would offer the latest information about treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're buying time,'' added Knight, who will keep her staff
position as a psychiatrist at McLean Hospital in Belmont, Mass.,
where she is doing research on schizophrenia. ``We are probably
saving about six months by using the incubator.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Rowe, a former e-commerce consultant at Boston
Consulting Group, began the incubator, which now has three infant
companies, in June. In February it will expand into an
18,000-square-foot facility on the 14th floor of 1 Broadway, where
it will be able to hold as many as 20 start-ups plus a 100-seat
auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, getting the best and brightest ideas and turning them
into young companies that we can nurture and grow quickly to gain a
competitive edge is what we are about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe, whose father, Richard, recently began RoweCom, a Cambridge
e-commerce firm, is working with PricewaterhouseCoopers and Testa
Hurwitz &AMP; Thibeault for financial and legal expertise. Timothy
Rowe's wife, Amy, is developing a Web-based service for frequent
business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Incubator space developers say a start-up will go through nearly
$1 million over three to six months with a staff of two to five
people. Some may grow more quickly, leaving the incubator and
becoming self-sufficient with their own facilities within four
months, and in another four to eight months will have a staff of 20
and raise nearly $30 million in venture capital before being
acquired or going public.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from the late 1970s and early '80s, when local
business development agencies and nonprofit corporations set up
incubators in old factories to showcase economic development. Often
the do-good spirit did not lead to self-sustaining companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the first biotechnology incubator opened in
Worcester, Mass., with venture capital backing. Several companies
have emerged from it, and a biotech incubator opened recently in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The new Internet incubators aim to take advantage of Wall
Street's love affair with dot-com businesses, which seem to raise
money one day and go public within eight months.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone welcomes the growing numbers of Internet
incubators. Critics say the abundance of venture capital will spawn
scores of new companies in the coming years that are not likely to
survive because their ideas were poorly conceived, they were slow
to get started, or they missed the market window or failed to
differentiate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young guys with ideas are essentially looking for
adult supervision and some facilities to work out of,'' said Todd
A. Dagres, general partner at Battery Ventures in Wellesley, Mass..
``Some of them think they can outdo eBay and the auction companies
or run the next eToys, so the bar is very low to get funded. That
means weaker companies that survive in incubators may crash and
burn when they go out on their own and struggle against established
players. So I think we're going to see the `amateur hour' of
Internet start-ups next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, are betting on Internet incubators to spawn the
next big successes. ``The next generation of Internet companies
will need more advanced technology, and that's the space we want to
play in,'' said Howard Anderson, who is leaving active management
of the Yankee Group, the technology market research firm he formed
30 years ago, to create Yankee Tek, a 5,000-square-foot incubator
to open next month at 1 Memorial Drive in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike The Cambridge Incubator, Yankee Tek plans to focus on
companies developing Internet infrastructure rather than dot-com
electronic commerce businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a 2-square-mile radius of MIT are some of the nation's
first-rate minds, many of whom we in New England have lost to
California, but who now might stay and work in an incubator to
launch the next great company,'' said Anderson, whose eldest son
works for an Internet start-up on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who recently began teaching a course on Internet
entrepreneurship at the Sloan School of the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology, plans to house no more than three companies in
Yankee Tek, plus investments in three other companies.
</P>
<P>
   While he admits he earns more money from Silicon Valley
start-ups than in New England deals, he said he expects to invest
as much as $3 million per company for start-ups developing the next
generation of Internet infrastructure software. However, most deals
will be in the $500,000 to $1.5 million range.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he has lined up about $40 million in financing
from Battery Ventures, which he cofounded, and from several other
venture capital sources including Thomas H. Lee Internet Partners,
a Boston-based innvestment firm where he is an adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the chief evangelist, the guy with the fat Rolodex,'' he
said, noting Yankee Tek's goal is to cultivate ties with
professors, campus research labs, and recent graduates. ``When an
entrepreneur needs an introduction to, say, someone at General
Electric or they need a vice president of sales and we know of four
sales guys who are looking for their next hot company, we can
arrange a meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other executives of incubator companies say they, too,
can reach out to bring in needed talent, find corporate partners,
and arrange venture capital financing. Pasadena-based idealab,
which launched eToys and GoTo.com Inc., an Internet search engine,
could have a Boston version next year, said Bruce Johnston, who
last month left venture capital firm TA Associates to spearhead
idealab East's development.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Softbank Venture Capital, which has a combination of
Japanese and American funds, plans to open an Internet incubator
space in a former mansion in Boston's Back Bay. It will be called
HotBank, a brand name Softbank will use as part of an affiliated
network of Internet incubators in California, New York, and three
other areas _ six facilities all slated to open by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Said Charles R. Lax, managing director of Softbank Technology
Ventures' East Coast operations in Newton, Mass., and an adviser to
the Boston HotBank incubator: ``For me, I'm seeing 80 deals a week
come into my office, and with this incubator some of them will get
a home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
