</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-PROFILE-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING THE BAR   FOR ASIAN-AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ William Lee embarked on his law career in 1976 planning
to employ a trial tactic used by his Cornell law professor and role
model, famed litigator Irving Young. Wear a bow tie, the professor
had told his student; it makes you stand out in the minds of jurors
and tricks them into remembering what you say.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee, who took a job at the prestigious law firm of Hale and
Dorr in Boston to further his dream of becoming an acclaimed trial
lawyer, scrapped the bow-tie idea after a few weeks on the job. An
Asian-American in Boston's then white-dominated Yankee legal
community, ``it took me about two trials to figure out I didn't
need a bow tie or anything else,'' he says now from his 32d-floor
office at Hale and Dorr's downtown headquarters. ``Being Chinese, I
was enough of an oddity.''
</P>
<P>
   In that way, he says, his race may have curiously helped him
become one of the nation's most successful intellectual property
litigators _ if only by setting him apart from the pack. But 23
years later, Lee nonetheless remains a rarity in the legal
profession. Named earlier this month as his firm's new managing
partner, he is the first Asian-American in Boston to achieve that
status and one of only a handful of Asian managing partners across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Minority groups have hailed him as a groundbreaker and said he
has helped inspire a new generation of young Asian-Americans who
long avoided careers in law, preferring technical fields and
viewing the bar as a foreign domain that held little promise for
them. Considered a pioneer in the still-young but exploding field
of intellectual property, his technical prowess in intensely
complex patent disputes has won him national acclaim. The National
Law Journal three years ago said his winning record made him one of
the country's 10 best litigators. He is highly regarded by his
peers, including those who play with him on a weekend soccer
league. (He is an admirable halfback, they say.) ``He's a very
smart, careful, shrewd litigator,'' says Regina Pisa, managing
partner of Goodwin Proctor &AMP; Hoar in Boston who served with him on
a governor's panel to review applicants for the state Supreme
Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at the top of his game, and he represents a certain
vitality that's valuable and hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Lee, 49, also has been criticized by some in Boston's
Asian community _ though no one would speak out on the record _ for
not using his success to more aggressively confront racial issues
in the practice of law. Lee himself confesses that, while race has
in some ways defined his career, he has preferred to sink himself
into other roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to give back to the community, and I make an effort
to do that,'' he says, admitting that from his office with its
panoramic view of Boston Harbor, it's easy to become isolated from
issues outside the firm. ``I am intensely proud of being Chinese.
And for people who are Asian, this (promotion to managing partner)
is a significant event. But for me, it has always been about the
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lee says that success has come to him through personal
effort, a value he says came from his immigrant father, who left
China for the United States in 1948. His father, an engineer, put
himself through school, earning master's and doctorate degrees. He
went to work for General Electric and eventually became a professor
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   While his two brothers followed their father into technical
careers, Lee took a path not often followed by Asians, especially
at the time. ``Asians didn't tend to go into the law,'' he says.
``The language barrier makes it difficult, and there are cultural
barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Lee, it was alluring, partly because he was drawn to the
action of the courtroom and partly because among his brothers, ``I
was the least likely to win a Nobel Prize.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating magna cum laude from Harvard, Lee went to
Cornell, where in addition to his law degree, he got a master's in
business administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be the least intelligent of my brothers, but I have the
most business sense,'' he says. ``They all come to me for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee joined Hale and Dorr's litigation department after
graduating in 1976 to learn at the feet of legends like James St.
Clair, who helped bring down Wisconsin Senator Joseph McCarthy and
later represented President Richard M. Nixon during the Watergate
investigation. Another was Jerome Facher, a crusty trial lawyer
known for his slavish devotion to the law and excoriations of
opponents. Facher is now best known for his successful defense of
corporate giant Beatrice Foods in the 1986 industrial dumping
lawsuit detailed in the book ``A Civil Action.'' The suit, which
culminated in a grueling five-month trial in Boston, alleged
children in Woburn had contracted leukemia after toxic waste had
leaked into drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Facher is a brilliant, gifted thinker,'' Lee says. ``He knew
how to distill a case to its essentials. He'd give you a
three-by-five index card and say, `Write your case on this. If you
need more room than that, you don't understand it.' That's what I
always say now. Keep it simple, simple, simple.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
