<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN GRADE THEIR WORKING PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children whose parents spend at least six hours a day with them
on work days give their mothers and fathers top grades for making
them feel loved and important.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one conclusion of researcher Ellen Galinsky's
interviews with 1,023 US children about their parents' work lives.
Two issues loomed large in the study: whether parents were giving
their children ``focused'' time, and whether dad was gainfully
employed.
</P>
<P>
   Galinsky's findings, compiled in the book ``Ask the Children:
What America's Children Really Think About Working Parents''
(William Morrow and Co., 1999), have struck a nerve. Newsweek
serialized the book. The Washington Post last month put the
findings on the front page. And anxious readers are calling talk
shows to discuss the results and communicating with Galinsky on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   After randomly interviewing with children in grades 3 to 12, as
well as telephone interviews with 170 parents in 15 states,
Galinsky found that both the amount of time and the quality of the
interaction were important to children. Not surprising, older
children were more likely to focus on how time was spent. Were
parents listening to them? Did parents understand their
adolescents' day-to-day lives? Were parents too overwhelmed, too
stressed by work and financial matters to spend a few hours a day
tuning in?
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that the quantity of time with mothers and fathers
does matter a great deal,'' said Galinsky. ``Children who spend
more time with their parents on workdays and nonworkdays grade
their parents higher. They feel their parents are more successful
in managing work and family, and they also feel that their parents
are putting them first.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics were striking. Eighty-three percent of children
whose parents spent a minimum of six hours per day with them on
working days gave their mothers top grades for making them feel
loved and important. Additionally, 84 percent of the children gave
fathers high marks for spending a minimum of six hours per day with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm upset, (my parents) talk to me,'' the book quotes a
9-year-old saying. ``They want to know why I am upset, which is
comforting because I can't talk to myself. They help me deal with
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Who spends more time with their children? According to Galinsky,
mothers spend more time with children from birth to age 18 than
fathers. She found that more than twice as many mothers (33
percent) spent 4.5 hours or more on workdays with their children
than fathers (15 percent).
</P>
<P>
   A family's annual income makes a difference, too. Parents whose
household incomes were $25,000 or less spent more time with their
children than parents whose household incomes were $75,000 or more.
Parents with lower household income may work less or be employed in
jobs with more regular or part-time hours.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, working-class parents were more likely to rely on each
other or relatives to care for their children than were middle and
upper middle-class parents.
</P>
<P>
   Galinsky's book, described by one critic as a ``guilt buster,''
contains a surprise: Most kids don't care whether mothers work or
not, though younger children were more likely to say they liked
having their mothers home. Still, few children regarded working and
stay-at-home moms differently. Rather, they were more concerned
about the working status of their fathers, possibly because of the
emphasis society places on the male's role as economic provider.
</P>
<P>
   The study, one of the first to assess the views of children and
parents, also revealed that children are detecting signs of stress
and work-related fatigue among working adults a lot more  &UR; today &LR; 
and are concerned about what they see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't work too hard,'' one child wrote in the study. ``Know
when to quit because, if you don't, you'll get all stressed out and
take it out on us!''
</P>
<P>
   With work hours increasing, it is hardly surprising Galinsky
found that guilt is still prevalent among parents, especially among
working mothers.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter was seven months old when I returned to work
following maternity leave 14 years ago. Though eager to re-enter
the tug and pull of the newsroom, I felt guilty for wanting to
return at all.
</P>
<P>
   My feelings were eased by my daycare provider, who was
recommended by my daughter's pediatrician. Lillian O'Keefe had four
children ages 9 to 16 when she began caring for my child. Then 38,
she not only loved children, she thrived on the activity and
constant give-and-take that made her household a real source of
inspiration for me. In doting on my child as much she doted on her
own, Lillian gave me the freedom to work.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when at 13 months my daughter called her caregiver Mommy, I
cringed. Had my child confused this wonderful woman with her real
mother? Was I spending too little time with my infant and too much
time at work? Were deadlines and bylines more important to me than
mothering?
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years have passed since those questions kept me up at
night, and the report from the homefront is more positive than I
ever dreamed. These days, my child is healthy and happy, though
there are times when she feels her mother's job should be on the
periphery of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Like most parents of adolescents, the amount of time I spend
with my daughter has lessened because of her social activities,
homework demands, and the well-documented teenage insistence on
autonomy. As one parent told Galinsky: ``I would like to be with my
teenage daughter more, but she is so involved with schoolwork,
activities, and her friends. Inevitably, I will hang around the
house weekend after weekend, and the one day that I make plans, she
will come up to me and say, `Let's do something together today.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But even with teens there are ways to carve out time. The sheer
regularity of certain activities such as eating meals together,
watching television together, taking walks, or simply discussing
homework appears to inextricably be linked to the way younger and
older children view their parents and how they develop as a result,
reports Galinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The kids in ``Ask the Children'' seem to agree. When Galinsky
asked children what they would like to tell the working parents of
America, many wanted their parents to know they were proud of them.
``If you are trying as a parent,'' said one child, ``if you are
leading by example, if you are following what you preach, then your
kids will turn out pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1500EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
