<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2867 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE21-COX     10-20 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For a better taste, try concentrating
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most cooks have puzzled over the ingredients of a particularly
delicious restaurant dish and tried emulating it in their own
kitchen. Sometimes the results are satisfactory, but more often
they fall short. It's frustrating to a home cook when a particular
quality, flavor or texture of a restaurant dish simply can't be
duplicated, no matter how hard you try.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the reason is a truly secret ingredient that's used by
professional chefs but is not readily available to the rest of us.
That secret: concentrates and bases.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you're at a restaurant and marvel over a savory
bisque, a glorious gravy, a satiny sauce or a gorgeous glaze,
there's a good chance the chef used a prepared base or concentrate
for those spectacular results. Of course, the chef might spend
hours and sometimes days reducing the meat, fish, poultry or
vegetables, but why should he when there's at least one company
that will do it for him?
</P>
<P>
   Minor's, the original and leading manufacturer of concentrates
and bases for professional cooks, does not produce the sodium- and
additive-packed bouillon or powdery flavor enhancers that are
common on supermarket shelves. Theirs are fresh food products that
contain meat, poultry, seafood or vegetables, reduced to a paste
that must be refrigerated. The products are 100 percent natural,
with no artificial ingredients, chemical preservatives or coloring,
and they contain less than 1 gram of fat per serving.
</P>
<P>
   When food scientist Lewis J. Minor founded his concentrate
company in the 1950s, he started with chicken and beef bases. But
as methods have improved and restaurant demand has increased, the
product line has multiplied. Now there are also concentrates of
pork, turkey and ham, and seafood bases including clam, crab, fish,
lobster, seafood and shrimp. Vegetable bases include garlic,
sauteed garlic, roasted onion, mushroom, sauteed vegetables,
roasted red pepper and herbes de Provence. The uses of bases and
concentrates expand every day. Along with sauces, gravies, dips,
soups and stews, they can be used to enhance just about any dish
you can think of.
</P>
<P>
   So why can't you buy them in a grocery store?
</P>
<P>
   Concentrates aren't usually found there because you don't just
pick one up and use it to see what happens. The average person who
is unfamiliar with concentrates and doesn't have specific recipes
for their use wouldn't know what to do with a small $10 jar that
contains the essence of half a bushel of lobsters or clams. In
other words, you have to know at least a little about how
concentrates work.
</P>
<P>
   That's where David Sievers comes in. A few years ago, Sievers,
an enthusiastic amateur chef, was installing security systems for a
living when a friend introduced him to cooking with concentrates.
Finding out that such a small amount of an ingredient could provide
such an explosion of taste spurred his culinary creativity, and
he's been on a journey of discovery ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's the exclusive national home-cook distributor of Minor's
concentrates. Sievers and his wife, Heidi, run a sort of
concentrate correspondence school on the Internet. They have about
7,000 devotees, who have found out about concentrates by word of
mouth, from a professional chef or online. They regularly visit the
Web site (www.allserv.com/) to find out about new products, updated
recipes and new uses. The couple also have a toll-free number
(1-800-827-8328) and are available seven days a week to answer
questions and offer suggestions. With every purchase of a
concentrate, they include booklets and loads of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Seafood and
</P>
<P>
   Artichoke Chowder
</P>
<P>
   Makes 9 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 (14-ounce) can artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   8 medium mushrooms, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Dash cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 cups hot water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Minor's Lobster Base
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound small shrimp, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound bay scallops
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound lump crab meat
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pale dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   Drain artichoke hearts and reserve liquid. Cut artichokes into
thin strips and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a 4-quart pot, melt butter over medium-high heat. Add
mushrooms, onion, garlic and cayenne. Saute until vegetables
soften, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in flour. Continue to cook, stirring constantly, over
medium-high heat for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add hot water, artichokes and their liquid, Lobster Base,
shrimp, scallops and crab meat. Mix until well-blended. Heat to
boiling, then reduce heat to low and simmer for 3 minutes, stirring
occasionally to prevent sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Add half-and-half and sherry and stir well. Increase heat to
medium-high and return to a boil, stirring constantly. Reduce heat
and simmer for 2 minutes, stirring constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 238 calories, 11 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 60), 14 grams carbohydrates, 74
milligrams cholesterol, 1,108 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
