<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2870 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-ITALIAN-RECIPES2     10-20 2877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ITALIAN-RECIPES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dinner evokes spirit of Italian countryside
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether it's a quick weeknight dinner or a special celebration,
there are three descriptions that often roll off the tongues of
rural Italians to describe their food _ nostrano, campanilismo and
si sposa.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Italian Country Table'' (Scribner, $35), author Lynn
Rossetto Kasper explains nostrano literally translates as
``local,'' but it's a term that's more about an embrace than
geography.
</P>
<P>
   Campanilismo is similar, meaning within the sound of the local
bell tower. Both convey the food is as much a part of an Italian's
personal identity as family name and individual personality.
</P>
<P>
   Si sposa means ``it marries'' and is always used in talking
about food. Essentially, it's used to explain why someone in Milan,
where risotto is practically religion, would never sprinkle
Sicilian sheep cheese over a plate of Risotto alla Milanese. The
flavors simply don't marry; they are from different regions,
climates and mentalities.
</P>
<P>
   Kasper captures these expressions and their meanings in the 200
recipes and dozens of stories she gathered in five years of
research in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The key to country Italian cooking, Kasper said, is keeping a
few key ingredients in the pantry, like olive oil, tomatoes,
vinegars and pastas. And remember to keep thinking locally and
seasonally. Use the fresh herbs at hand; find the best domestic
cheeses you can. ``I had to give domestic options for many of the
recipes,'' explains Kasper. ``But I came up with recommendations
that won't violate the spirit of the dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   She gives suggestions on how to find the dried pastas, canned
tomatoes and balsamic vinegar, from the mainstream supermarket to a
list of mail order sources that she includes in the back of the
book.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond ingredients, Kasper offers instructions on techniques.
She gives primers on building flavors in a tomato sauce (depending
on the ingredients and time you have). There also are clear
instructions for glazing chicken, storing dried beans and selecting
olive oils.
</P>
<P>
   But best yet, she gives the stories behind many of the recipes
and food ways of rural Italians. So many in fact that an audiobook
companion will be available this month. The tape is of Kasper
relating the stories she heard and her adventures in researching
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you can listen to it while you are preparing this rustic
fall dinner for your family or a few close friends. Go casual. Get
a head start by roasting the tomatoes and making the soup the day
before. Invite guests into the kitchen for the bruschetta, so they
can savor the aromas of the pancetta-stuffed chicken roasting in
the oven. Pour round, robust red wines and soon a rosy glow will be
upon the cheeks of those around the table. And divine smiles as
guests savor the pear pizza. It is fall.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Oven-Roasted Canned Tomatoes (Pelati al Forno)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 2
hours, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 6 hours
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Rossetto Kasper describes these as ``scarlet medallions of
tomato flecked with herbs, tasting almost brazenly meaty and
sweet.'' It's hard to improve on that description, so I add only an
endorsement. I love opening the refrigerator door and finding a few
of these waiting. I could toss them in pasta or salads or add them
to pizzas. But often, I just pop one in my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   2 (28-ounce) cans peeled whole tomatoes, drained, halved and
seeded
</P>
<P>
   (preferably Muir Glen, Hunt's Contadina or Red Pack)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 2/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   14 large fresh basil leaves, torn
</P>
<P>
   2 (4-inch) branches fresh
</P>
<P>
   rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium red onion, cut in
</P>
<P>
   1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   5 large cloves garlic, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Spread tomatoes in a large shallow
pan (a half-sheet pan is ideal) and sprinkle with olive oil, basil
leaves, rosemary, onion, garlic, salt and pepper. Turn to coat well
with oil. Bake 2 1/4 to 2 1/2 hours, basting and turning tomatoes
several times. They're done when their color deepens to dark
scarlet and they taste mellow and very rich. Don't let them brown
or allow the garlic to brown because it will turn bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer tomatoes and their oil to a glass or china bowl. Let
them mellow at room temperature up to 6 hours. The flavors will
ripen in this time. Refrigerate up to 4 days, or freeze up to 3
months. Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 160 calories, 2 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 79), 8 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 291 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Sicilian Farmer's Bruschetta
</P>
<P>
   (Bruschetta del Contadino Siciliano)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get any simpler or more delicious than toasted slices
of rough country bread rubbed with garlic and moistened with olive
oil. What you put on top is quite up to you. But here is a classic
Italian combination that's hard to beat. I used the finest goat
cheese I could find (at Whole Foods). If you wish, prepare the
toast and make a buffet of the ingredients and let guests build
their own. Kasper recommends pairing with a red Corvo Rosso wine
from Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   8 1/2-inch-thick slices chewy, crusty country bread
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, split
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup robust extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Several generous pinches dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Italian cheese: sheep's or cow's milk ricotta,
mozzarella, fresh goat cheese or medium-aged sheep cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium red onion, sliced in thin rings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mixed torn leaves fresh basil and Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   (optional)
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 Oven-Roasted Canned Tomatoes (see recipe), sun-dried
tomatoes or fresh tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Toast bread over a wood fire or under a broiler or grill it on
top of the stove. Rub toast with garlic (for milder garlic flavor,
rub it on the bread before toasting) and moisten lightly with olive
oil. Sprinkle each slice with a little oregano, salt and red pepper
flakes. Cut each slice into 3 or 4 pieces. Top each slice with a
generous layer of cheese. Put several onion rings on the cheese.
Sprinkle with a few torn herb leaves and pieces of tomato. Serve at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with goat cheese): 326 calories, 10 grams protein,
21 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 58), 25 grams
carbohydrates, 22 milligrams cholesterol, 385 milligrams sodium, 2
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Hot-and-Spicy Eggplant Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Marinating time: 20 minutes Cooking
time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The garnishes are as important as the soup here. Shredded
ricotta salata cheese adds depth. The mint and chiles provide the
tingling finish. We give both the summer and autumn versions.
Either way, this soup is hearty and for this menu should be served
in small portions. It can be made a day in advance. Kasper
recommends serving a round rustic red wine like Ceregio Sangiovese
di Romagna Superiore.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds long narrow Japanese eggplants, peeled and cut in
1/4- inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 (15-ounce) can chickpeas, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 to 3 1/2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, cut in 1/4- to 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 tightly packed tablespoons chopped fresh Italian parsley
leaves
</P>
<P>
   6 large fresh basil leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   4 canned whole tomatoes, chopped, with 1/4 cup of their liquid
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 to 5 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Garnishes:
</P>
<P>
   3 tightly packed tablespoons chopped fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-hot fresh chiles, seeded and cut in tiny dice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (4 ounces) shredded ricotta salata cheese
</P>
<P>
   In a colander, toss the eggplant with about 1 tablespoon salt
and let stand 20 to 30 minutes. Meanwhile, in a bowl, marinate
chickpeas in 1 tablespoon of the vinegar and a little salt and
pepper for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the eggplant onto a towel and squeeze away about half its
moisture. Film the bottom of a 12-inch saute pan or a medium-size
soup pan or Dutch oven with 1 to 2 tablespoons of the olive oil and
heat over medium heat. Add the eggplant and saute 5 minutes, or
until pale gold and tender, seasoning with black pepper. Turn out
of the pan, reserve, and wash the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Set the pan over high heat and heat the remaining 1 1/2
tablespoons oil. Add the onions and parsley and quickly brown the
onions. Reduce heat to medium, stir in the chickpeas with their
marinade and cook about 3 minutes. Add the basil and garlic and
cook another 5 minutes, stirring frequently. Stir in the wine,
tomatoes and tomato liquid, reducing the heat to medium-low. Cook 2
to 3 minutes, uncovered, or until the liquid is rich-tasting and
thick.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the eggplant and 3 1/2 cups of water, or enough to make
a thick broth. Simmer 15 minutes to blend the flavors. Stir in the
remaining 1 tablespoon vinegar and cook another few minutes. Taste
for seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, serve the soup at room temperature, garnishing each
portion with mint, chiles and cheese. In the fall, prepare the
variation below.
</P>
<P>
   Autumn Eggplant Soup: Follow the directions through sauteing
chickpeas and reducing tomatoes. Add 3 cups water to the chickpea
saute. Cook 15 minutes. Puree 1/3 of the soup in a blender or food
processor, and stir it back into the pan. Then add the eggplant and
remaining 1 tablespoon vinegar. Simmer another 10 minutes. Taste
for seasoning. Serve warm with the garnishes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 240 calories, 10 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 24 grams carbohydrates, 21
milligrams cholesterol, 79 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Balsamico Roast Chicken
</P>
<P>
   and Potatoes (Pollo Arrosto)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Seasoning time: several hours to overnight
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 90 minutes Standing
time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a one-pan roasted dinner. Herbs and pancetta under the
skin of the chicken help it to roast and bronze while adding
unbeatable flavor. The potatoes roast right in the pan juices. It's
the essence of rustic Italian cooking, especially if you use the
best balsamic vinegar you can find. I rarely have instant repeats,
but I made this dish two Sundays in a row. Kasper recommends
serving with a Piemontese red Paitin Sori Paitin Dolcetto d'Alba.
</P>
<P>
   1 (3 1/2- to 4-pound) chicken (hormone- and antibiotic-free, if
possible) whole or cut up
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 medium onion
</P>
<P>
   3 large cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup tightly packed fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried marjoram
</P>
<P>
   4 slices (1 1/2 to 2 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   pancetta, chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons high-quality commercial balsamic vinegar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 medium Yellow Finn, Yukon Gold or red skinned
</P>
<P>
   potatoes, scrubbed and cut in 2-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   Parsley or fresh thyme for garnish
</P>
<P>
   If time allows, season the chicken with salt and refrigerate it
several hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees when ready to cook the chicken.
Mince together by hand or in a food processor the onion, garlic,
fresh basil, dried basil, oregano, marjoram and pancetta. Then
blend in 1 tablespoon of the balsamic vinegar, the olive oil and
salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   If using a whole chicken, cut out the chicken's backbone and
open the chicken out flat, skin side up. With your palm, firmly
press down the breast area to flatten.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff most of the herb mixture under the skin of the thigh, leg
and breast areas or under the skin of each of the pieces if using a
pre-cut chicken. Rub the rest all over the chicken. Place the bird
or pieces skin side up on a large shallow pan (a broiler pan or
jelly-roll or half-sheet pan). Scatter the potatoes around it and
sprinkle everything with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Roast 20 minutes, then pour in 1/2 cup wine. Roast another 70
minutes, or until the thigh reaches about 175 degrees on an
instant-read thermometer. Baste the potatoes and chicken frequently
with the pan juices, turning the potatoes often to brown evenly and
prevent them from sticking. Add more wine if the pan is dry. Turn
over the chicken two-thirds of the way through cooking for even
browning. If after an hour of roasting the chicken isn't browning,
raise the heat to 500 degrees to finish cooking. (Or wait until it
is done and run it under the broiler 5 minutes to crisp the skin.)
</P>
<P>
   Let the chicken rest 5 to 10 minutes at room temperature, then
present on a warmed platter along with the potatoes, sprinkling
everything with the rest of the balsamic vinegar. Garnish with
bouquets of parsley or fresh thyme.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 545 calories, 34 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 35), 53 grams carbohydrates, 92
milligrams cholesterol, 214 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Simplest-of-All Green Beans
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 10
minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons salt, plus more to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pound green beans, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fruity olive oil (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Add the three tablespoons salt to boiling water. Drop in beans
and boil uncovered 5 to 10 minutes, until tender but with no hint
of mushiness. Timing varies greatly according to size, age and
freshness of the beans. Taste for doneness and trust your judgment,
not the clock. Drain immediately in a colander and turn into a
bowl. Most important is to season the hot beans right away with
salt and pepper. Then taste again, adding more seasoning if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot, warm or at room temperature. Toss the beans in the
olive oil, if using, just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without oil): 29 calories, 2 grams protein, no fat,
7 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 45 milligrams sodium, 3
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Rosemary-Pear Pizza
</P>
<P>
   (Pizza alle Pere e Rosmarino)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 30 minutes to overnight Preparation time: 30
minutes Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The spicing of this pizza is an unusual mixture of sweet and
savory straight out of centuries-old recipes for sweet pizzas. In
central and southern Italy, sweet pizzas used to be commonplace;
the flavor of this pie is uncommonly good. If you have a dough
phobia, rather than rolling out to a large, thin round, roll the
dough out just a bit, then place on the prepared pizza pan and
press the dough to the edges and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   For the pastry:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups (7.5 ounces) unbleached all-purpose flour (preferably
organic)
</P>
<P>
   Generous 1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 stick (4 ounces) cold unsalted butter, cut in chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons cold water
</P>
<P>
   For the topping:
</P>
<P>
   4 (1 1/2 to 2 pounds) firm-ripe Bosc pears (preferably
</P>
<P>
   organic)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1 large orange, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh rosemary leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   For the pastry: Combine the flour, salt and sugar in a food
processor or large bowl. Cut in the butter with rapid pulses in the
processor, or rub between your fingertips until the butter is the
size of peas. Add the egg and 2 tablespoons water. Pulse just until
the dough gathers in clumps, or toss with a fork until evenly
moistened. If the dough seems dry, blend in another 1/2 to 1
tablespoon water.
</P>
<P>
   Oil a 14- to 16-inch pizza pan. Roll out the dough on a floured
board to an extremely thin 17-inch round. Place on the pan. Don't
trim the excess pastry _ fold it over toward the center of the pie.
Refrigerate 30 minutes to overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Set an oven rack in the lowest position and preheat the oven to
500 degrees. Take the dough out of the refrigerator. Peel, core,
halve and stem pears. Slice vertically in 1/2-inch-wide wedges,
about 10-14 slices per pear. Moisten with a little lemon juice.
Fold back the dough's rim so it hangs over the edge of the pan.
Arrange the pear slices into an overlapping spiral on the dough,
starting right at the rim of the pan. Sprinkle with orange zest,
basil, rosemary, cinnamon, pepper, sugar and oil. Flip the
overhanging crust onto the pears.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 20 to 25 minutes, or until the pears are speckled golden
brown and the crust is crisp. Check the crust after the first 15
minutes and cover the crust's rim with foil if it's browning too
quickly. Remove the pizza from the oven and serve hot, warm or at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 264 calories, 3 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 35 grams carbohydrates, 57
milligrams cholesterol, 71 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
