<HEADER>
A2872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-20 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGING BRONCOS COMING TO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about a reversal of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the Patriots couldn't wait for Denver to get to
Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were 4-0 and headed to Kansas City, with control of
their season clearly in their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, the two-time defending Super Bowl champions, were
on the brink of disaster. They were 0-4 and heading to Oakland to
play a much-improved Raiders team. Head coach Mike Shanahan had
just benched second-year quarterback Brian Griese in favor of Bubby
Brister. But on game day, Brister said he couldn't play because of
an injury, and Griese was forced back into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Patriots have lost twice, to Kansas City and
Miami, in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Denver has rebounded to stun the Raiders and the
Packers, reviving hopes of making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Foxboro Stadium could become the real Spooky World for the home
team this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have not beaten Denver since 1980. They have lost
11 in a row to the Broncos. They have lost to Denver each of the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Broncos are not what the Patriots want to face.
They can run the ball. They can stop the pass. Just ask Brett
Favre.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver defense gave Favre the worst day of his career. He
and the highly regarded Green Bay offense were humbled. Green Bay
ran just 35 offensive plays; around 70 is normal. Of the 35 plays,
only 12 made yardage. On the other 23 offensive attempts, the
Packers either made no gain or lost yardage. On the day, they had
just 133 yards total offense, one of the worst performances in the
team's storied history.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, the Patriots' offense has been stuck in
the teens. It scored 16 points against the Giants, 14 in Kansas
City, and 16 against Miami. The Patriots' defense has not been able
to stop the run. Kansas City hammered them on the ground, and
Miami, playing without its top two linemen, rushed for more than
100 yards. Now comes Denver, with the best offensive line in the
league. A rookie named Olandis Gary rushed for 137 yards against
Green Bay, and most people would say that Green Bay has a better
defensive front than the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, John Elway and Terrell Davis were the Denver
dynamic duo who spanked the Patriots. Elway has retired. Davis is
out for the year with a knee injury. Pro Bowl tight end Shannon
Sharpe is out injured. Left tackle Harry Swayne went to Baltimore
in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   But after staggering out of the box with four straight losses,
Mike Shanahan has righted the ship. Shanahan says he won't announce
his starting quarterback yet, but how can it not be Griese after he
posted back-to-back wins?
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four games, the Denver defense has given up an
average of 11 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Broncos match up well with New England. Denver's
defense is third in the league against the pass, and the Patriots
have to live by the pass. They have proven for five years that they
cannot run the ball effectively.
</P>
<P>
   What has to be scary for Patriots fans is the way Denver can
rush the passer. The Broncos have 19 sacks. Trevor Pryce, a
first-round choice three years ago, is coming on strong as one of
the best pass rushers in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Gregg Robinson has had a way of getting a
lot of hits on Drew Bledsoe. When Bledsoe was a rookie in 1993,
playing in New York against a Jets team coached by someone named
Pete Carroll, Robinson was the Jets' defensive coordinator. Bledsoe
got hammered. In recent years, Robinson defenses in Denver have
knocked around Bledsoe with regularity.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were awful on third downs against Miami: 2 for 11.
Denver is ranked third in the league defensively on third downs,
limiting the opposition to a 27.5 percent conversion rate. That is
a high rate of efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Denver needs this win to stay in the playoff picture, and it has
a difficult schedule upcoming: vs. Minnesota, at San Diego, and at
Seattle. Both San Diego and Seattle are ahead of the Broncos in the
AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   With a loss to Denver, the Patriots can forget about home-field
advantage in the playoffs and start worrying about making the
playoffs. That seemed laughable two weeks ago when they were
undefeated and sitting in the catbird seat.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
