<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ITALIAN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Italian cooking fresh from the farm
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fusion is in. South American food is sizzling, and
tapas are still tempting, but food trends come and go.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of Italian food, however, transcends trends, and
our love for it has grown beyond bowls of noodles in red sauce.
Witness the way Atlantans flock to such restaurants as La Grotta,
Veni Vidi Vici and newcomer Sotto Sotto, where the specialties are
creamy risottos, grilled fish, white beans and lamb shanks.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of food that beckons from the Italian countryside,
at once creative and comforting. Food like the portobello
``steaks'' with ``holy oil'' that Adelina Norcia, a farmwoman in
Sicily, makes. She brushes the large mushroom caps with olive oil
infused with a trinity of garlic, oregano and crushed chiles and
then grills until crispy.
</P>
<P>
   Or imagine digging into a bowl of tagliatelle with chicken ragu
and asparagus, like Ida Lancellotti and her son, Angelo, prepare in
a small restaurant in the Emilia-Romagna region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italian food tastes to us like home cooking even if we don't
have a drop of Italian blood in us,'' said Lynne Rossetto Kasper,
who shares the stories and recipes of Norcia, the Lancellottis and
many other Italian farm families in her new book, ``The Italian
Country Table: Home Cooking From Italy's Farmhouse Kitchens''
(Scribner, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Kasper does have a drop or two of Italian blood. Both sets of
grandparents were Italian immigrants. She grew up and began her
culinary career in New York, teaching and writing in the late
1960s. Then she moved to Denver, where she created a cooking
school. In the early '80s she lived in Europe, which eventually led
her to research in her ancestral land of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Her first major work was ``The Splendid Table'' (Morrow, 1992),
an enormous volume on 500 years of cooking in the Emilia-Romagna
region. The book was the first to win both the Julia Child/IACP and
the James Beard ``best cookbook of the year'' award, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Now she hosts a nationally syndicated radio show on food by the
same name. Though it doesn't air locally, you can access recipes
and quick audio segments via the Web site, www.splendidtable.org.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first book was published, she has returned to Italy
each year to research the ``Country Table,'' staying with friends
and on guest farms all over rural Italy, witnessing both daily
rituals and special occasions, compiling the stories and collecting
the recipes. In addition to the cookbook, which arrived in
bookstores this month, there's an audio book with Kasper reading
the stories she collected.
</P>
<P>
   Her research began at a cousin's farm in Tuscany, where she
helped prepare a feast to celebrate the grape harvest. More than 70
friends, family and neighbors helped gather the grapes, and then
sat down at long tables in a hayloft to enjoy antipasti, beef
cutlets, roast chickens, pizzas, tarts, cookies and cakes.
</P>
<P>
   In Umbria in central Italy, she watched as a farmwoman prepared
a quick weeknight dinner for a crew of men who trained horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She walked out her back door, picked some chives, put them on
a board with crushed garlic, salt and red onion. She used a
mezzaluna to chop it all together and drizzled the olive oil right
in. Then she tossed it with pasta, added a little cheese and she
had dinner,'' said Kasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything begins with the land, with what's seasonal and
local,'' said Kasper. ``Country cooking is much more about what's
in the larder, the refrigerator. You can't run down to the corner
store.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Naples countryside, Kasper found that farmwomen often
make a casserole of mashed potatoes mixed with salami and peas.
Thick slices of mozzarella are buried in the center. Neapolitans
love mozzarella and it is plentiful there.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Italian Alps, Kasper befriended Margherita, the cook
at a cowherd's hut where hikers often stop to eat. Margherita used
buttermilk left over from her daily butter churning to cook
potatoes, then crushes them with browned butter. She has no
connection to mozzarella and wouldn't use it in her potatoes,
Kasper explains, but she had quarts of leftover buttermilk every
day.
</P>
<P>
   For the book, Kasper took great care in finding acceptable
substitutes for ingredients that may be hard to find here, and she
gives recommendations for brands and varieties of such items as
canned tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The cooler days upon us beckon comforting food. And for cooks,
it's an ideal time to bask in the warmth of the kitchen. Kasper
offers several menus in the book for casual fall dinners that are
hard to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Start with simple bruschetta, or toasted rounds of Italian
bread, and top with the best goat cheese you can find at the
grocery, some oven-roasted tomatoes that taste like candy and fresh
basil leaves.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a table in the kitchen, simply set up the fixings
for bruschetta and let guests build their own while you warm up
hot-and-spicy eggplant soup (which can be made a day ahead of time)
and prepare simple green beans.
</P>
<P>
   While folks are gathered around the table enjoying the soup,
with its garnishes of hot peppers and mint, the chicken and
potatoes will be browning in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   When the bird is roasted, transfer it with the potatoes a
platter and splash it with the best balsamic vinegar you can find.
With a paste of herbs and pancetta stuffed under the crisp skin,
this chicken is worthy of your finest friends.
</P>
<P>
   Finish with a pizza of pears sprinkled with rosemary, basil,
cinnamon, sugar, orange zest and olive oil _ a centuries-old
technique farmwomen used to do once a week as a special treat for
the family.
</P>
<P>
   With a few glasses of full Italian red wines, it's a meal that
will transport you to the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
