<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aromatic bread nearly foolproof
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Silly me.
</P>
<P>
   I forgot about the Dilly Bread sought by C.A. Johnston Folds of
Decatur (Ga.). The 1960 Pillsbury Bake-Off winner should have rung
a bell, because it has become one of the company's all-time
favorites. The original recipe from Leona Schnuelle of Crab
Orchard, Neb., became so popular, in fact, it caused a run on dill
seed at grocery stores, according to Ralph V. Campbell of Doraville
(Ga.), one of dozens who sent copies of the Pillsbury recipe or one
of many that included slight changes and were published in
community cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amateurs _ even beginners _ with yeast doughs,'' Campbell
said, ``can have outstanding success with this unusual recipe but
should be forewarned that, while baking, it fills the house with
the most appetizing aroma known to mankind. Don't be surprised if
you cannot wait to cut into it. Fine! After a few minutes of
cooling, slice with an electric carving knife. The bread will still
be hot enough to melt butter.''
</P>
<P>
   As I write this, responses are still landing on my desk with
other comments from bakers who really love this recipe: ``great
with potato soup,'' ``large-curd cottage cheese makes a more
attractive product,'' ``this is the first bread I ever baked,'' and
``we prefer dill weed to dill seed.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the day the request was published, Jean Kay Holmes of
Bogart (Ga.) said she was getting ready to bake a loaf for a family
reunion that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   We wonder if it made it all the way to the get-together.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Dilly Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 round loaf, about 20 slices
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rising time: 1 hour, 20 minutes to 1 hour, 40 minutes, divided
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 package dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creamed cottage cheese, lukewarm
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon instant minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dill seed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 unbeaten egg
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Melted butter, optional
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt, optional
</P>
<P>
   Soften yeast in water. In mixing bowl, combine cottage cheese,
sugar, onion, butter, dill seed, salt, baking soda, egg and
softened yeast. Add flour and mix well to form a stiff dough. Cover
and let rise in a warm place until light and doubled in size, about
50 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Punch down dough. Turn into well-greased round 1 1/2- to 2-quart
casserole dish. Let rise in warm place 30 to 40 minutes. Bake at
350 degrees for 40 to 50 minutes until golden brown. Brush with
soft butter and sprinkle with kosher salt, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per slice: 74 calories, 3 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 18), 12 grams carbohydrates, 14 milligrams
cholesterol, 181 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   Judy Harris of McRae (Ga.) is looking for a lost Corned Beef
Casserole recipe she got more than 20 years ago. She said it called
for two cans of corned beef, spaghetti, cheese and maybe a can of
mushroom soup, in addition to other ingredients she cannot
remember. Instead of croutons, it was topped with small squares cut
from buttered bread slices.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Lambert of Fayetteville (Ga.) seeks a Sauerkraut Pie
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
