<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ELECTION21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Election' a fun take on slippery truth
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Election'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   A high school satire infused with precise anthropological
observation _ a combination that can make you both giggle and
wince. It's painfully funny.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Broderick plays Jim McAllister, a Nebraska schoolteacher
who really, really loves his job. Reese Witherspoon is his nemesis,
Tracy Flick, an overachieving student whose perky persona masks a
ruthless lust for power. Her latest target: presidency of the
student government. Letting us into the heads of both characters,
the movie takes a skeptical look at the idea of ``truth'' by
showing us the same situation from different perspectives,
``Rashomon''-style.
</P>
<P>
   Additional viewpoints come from two other students running for
SGA: a jock (Chris Klein) and his lesbian kid sister (Jessica
Campbell). Justifying their actions, they constitute a round-robin
chorus of self-deluded rationalizations. The film's unspoken idea
is that nobody really enters politics for the good of their
constituents. In ``Election'' we watch the characters (well, except
for jock Paul, who's too dim to scheme) break rules and lie to get
what they want. It's one of the movie's balder jokes that Jim
teaches his students the difference between ethics and morals, even
as his vendetta against Tracy blurs his own integrity, at school
and at home.
</P>
<P>
   As a decent guy who gets in over his head, Broderick is ideal,
lending both his boyish charisma and memories of his 1986 screen
role as class cutter Ferris Bueller. Witherspoon is a perfect foil,
a lethal kewpie doll with a glass-cutting chipmunk voice.
</P>
<P>
   Like one of last year's best movies, ``Rushmore,'' ``Election''
barely made a ripple at the box office. Rediscover it on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
