<HEADER>
A2876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS21-COX     10-20 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Shane Harrison and Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  URBAN
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' Soundtrack
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Columbia. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the better-known R&AMP;B and rap artists on ``The Best
Man'' soundtrack don't necessarily turn in the best work here.
Hip-hop band the Roots' just-OK ``What You Want'' is not what you'd
expect from one of the few acts in this genre not afraid to change
chords and direction away from the usual material-minded
storytelling. Singer Maxwell's ``Let's Not Play the Game'' is an OK
exercise in how the cooer can also clip his vocals for effect. (He
sounds much more comfortable on ``As My Girl.'') And Beyonce from
Destiny's Child's soaring Disney-like duet with Marc Nelson,
``After All Is Said And Done,'' doesn't affect as much as Xscape's
Latocha Scott's piercing solo bow, ``Liar, Liar.'' For a much
better compilation with many of these same artists, try the ``Love
Jones'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Introducing Michael Fredo''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fredo. Qwest/Warner Bros. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Enjoyable fluff is nothing to be scoffed at. Sure, a steady
stream of cheesy pop will rot your brain as surely as a diet of
sugar will rot your teeth and seriously endanger your health. It's
a real treat in small doses, though. Tommy Hilfiger model Fredo
dispenses some tasty, nutrition-free pop candy. He has nothing new
to add to the musical lexicon, but the tunes are as beautifully put
together as Fredo's mug. Consummate radio pop such as ``This Time
Around'' and ``Love All Over Again'' should tickle the fancy of
Backstreet Boys fans everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Matters of the Heart''
</P>
<P>
   Patti LuPone. Varese Sarabande. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Any Patti LuPone recording is an event. She defines the nature
of that event _ celebration, meditation, discovery _ by the
unpredictable mix of music she chooses. Here LuPone (Broadway's
``Evita'' and a whole lot more) swings her muscular mezzo from
Sondheim (``I Never Do Anything Twice'') to Lennon and McCartney
(``It's for You''), from Rodgers and Hammerstein (``A Cock-Eyed
Optimist'') to Beth Nielsen Chapman (``Sand and Water''). She sings
of love lost, found, kinky and unrequited. Of family. Of wistful
regret. Of passing the torch. It's as if LuPone, as talented as
anyone singing today, holds out her hand and invites you to join
her wild ride. What'll you find may surprise or sadden or enlighten
you. And it will most certainly leave you better for making the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   _Kathy Janich
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Shane Harrison and Kathy Janich write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
