<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2878 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS21-COX     10-20 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Bob Longino, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Life'' (R) _ Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence bicker for
more than 60 years in this sometimes hilarious and racially
poignant prison comedy. How they landed in a Mississippi
correctional facility with life sentences isn't nearly as important
as the knack these talented performers have for taking turns at
generating laughs out of a throwaway script. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``eXistenZ'' (R) _ In the near future, virtual-realty games
have become so mind-blowing that a counter movement called realists
has arisen. One of their targets is celebrity game inventor
Jennifer Jason Leigh, a.k.a., the ``game-pod goddess.'' Fans of
director David Cronenberg's creepy genius know to expect
mutilations, mutations, squishy-icky stuff and pitch-black humor.
But whether he's cracking you up or grossing you out, his is a
unique cinematic vision. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Walk on the Moon'' (R) _ It's as fake as the tie-dyed
extras in its Woodstock re-creation. The movie starts as a fondly
observed look at upstate New York's Jewish family resorts. But when
housewife Pearl (Diane Lane) gets an itch once her husband goes
back to the city, her actions seem both dumb and selfish. By the
time she's making picturesque whoopee under a waterfall with her
lover, the movie has veered from well-observed 1960s character
study into silly soap opera. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Metroland'' (R) _ This sometimes compelling film wonders if
settling down is the same as selling out. In 1977, a 30-ish ad man
(Christian Bale) with a wife (Emily Watson), baby, mortgage, etc.,
is taunted by his free-wheeling '60s youth when an old
counterculture buddy (Lee Scott) shows up. The movie starts well
but seems to lose energy _ conviction? _ as it goes along. Still,
the theme is worthy and the performances good, especially Watson
who does hard-headed sensible as well as high-strung flaky. Grade:
B-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Xiu Xiu: The Sent-Down Girl'' (R) _ Joan Chen demonstrates a
real director's touch in eliciting rich performances in this tale
of a Chinese girl relocated to the Tibetan outback. Chen gets
maximum effect from the gorgeous but indifferent landscape of her
locations. The story's emotional bleakness will limit its appeal,
and an over-explicit score underlines and weakens the movie's
punch. But it's a rigorous piece of work. Beautifully shot and
acted but brutal in its view of human nature, it's an art-house,
feel-bad film. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   NOTABLE DVDs
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hard Eight'' (R) _ The goodies in this special edition of
Paul Thomas Anderson's (``Boogie Nights'') first movie include a
deleted scene and audio commentary by Anderson and star Philip
Baker Hall. While it's fun to hear the writer-director admit his
influences (``The Hustler,'' ``The Silence of the Lambs'' and
Jean-Pierre Melville's ``Bob le Flambeur''), Hall rambles on much
too long talking about the differences between acting for the
theater and acting onscreen. $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Steve Murray write for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
