<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2879 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-STING21-COX     10-20 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-STING21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Every little thing Sting does is no longer magic
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nope, it's just the same old stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Sting's latest album further establishes the singer as a pop
demigod emeritus, a once-major figure who has happily hit midcareer
autopilot. At this stage, with nothing left to prove and the
royalties continually rolling in, Sting can pretty much show up at
the Grammy Awards every year, collect his trophy, knock
</P>
<P>
   off a movie soundtrack or campaign for charity and then go
musing amid the lush landscape of his English country estate.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of mature, musically sophisticated male vocalists
whose solo careers peaked in the 1980s (think of fellow artsy
Anglos such as Steve Winwood, David Bowie and Peter Gabriel), Sting
seems a bit besides the point these days. He makes good albums, but
they lack the impact of the old days _ when the man born Gordon
Sumner dared to be the most pretentious man in rock (looks like
Smashing Pumpkins' Billy Corgan swiped the title). ``Brand New
Day'' offers a lovely, shifting tapestry in which easy, melodic pop
ballads get jazzy, percussive upgrades or detour into nouveau
country music and film noir soundscapes. (Helps to have buddies
like Branford Marsalis, Stevie Wonder and James Taylor dropping
by). Somehow, though, nearly all the songs _ midlife reflections on
love and eternity _ disappear into that fancy fabric. One
exception: ``Tomorrow We'll See,'' in which Sting sings from the
fatalistic point of view of a streetwalker (of vague gender), is
too weirdly contrived to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   Sting performs Nov. 7 at the Fox Theatre in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brand
</P>
<P>
   New Day''
</P>
<P>
   Sting. A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
