<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     10-20 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV24-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST BAN TREATY REJECTION SIGNALS MORE POLITICAL WARFARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 24)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To rephrase Bette Davis' most memorable movie line,
``Fasten your seat belts, voters, it's going to be a bumpy year.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of acrimonious skirmishing, a war that will haunt
Bill Clinton's remaining days in the White House has begun with a
bang.
</P>
<P>
   It is not, to borrow Woodrow Wilson's description of World War
I, a war to end all wars. As long the presidency and the Congress
are dominated by ambitious individuals from opposing political
parties, the two institutions will be in conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a parallel between the Wilson tragedy of 80 years
ago and Bill Clinton's problems today. In both instances, the
president was a victim of his own stubbornness as well as the
obstructionist tactics of his Republican opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The opening shots in the current showdown were fired on Oct. 13
when Senate Republicans defeated the nuclear test ban treaty and on
Oct. 14 when Clinton accused his foes of indulging in ``reckless
partisanship'' and retreating into isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the GOP titans of Capitol Hill are engaged in a
battle that essentially is about power, politics and the coming
election.
</P>
<P>
   The president, although technically a lame duck, is obsessed
with the need to establish a legacy that will help counter memories
of the Monica Lewinsky affair. He is equally determined that Al
Gore will succeed him and that Hillary Clinton will succeed New
York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans have their own political agenda. They seek to
expand their power, pick up additional House and Senate seats in
next year's election, reduce Clinton's authority now and place a
Republican in the Oval Office in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The president is rightly concerned that his prestige and that of
the United States may have been diminished by Senate rejection of
the nuclear treaty. The leaders of Britain, France and Germany all
urged the Senate to ratify the pact that they had signed.
</P>
<P>
   Some GOP members and most Democrats would have preferred to
delay the vote on the treaty until the next president has had a
chance to decide whether he wants it ratified. That strategy was
far preferable to outright rejection of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But others, especially those on the far right who detest
Clinton, were determined to defeat the treaty now, although they
may have won a Pyrrhic victory. Only four moderate Republicans _
Rhode Island's John Chafee, Vermont's James Jeffords, Oregon's
Gordon Smith and Pennsylvania's Arlen Specter _ joined the
Democrats in support of the pact.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to claim that the GOP stance was wholly partisan
when it was backed by such Senate Republican internationalists as
Indiana's Richard Lugar, Arizona's John McCain, Virginia's John
Warner and Maine's Olympia Snowe.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, if the treaty were as dangerous as its critics
claim, it would not have been supported by such highly respected
Democrats as Moynihan, South Dakota's Thomas Daschle, Nebraska's
Bob Kerrey, California's Dianne Feinstein and Louisiana's John
Breaux.
</P>
<P>
   As the ailing Wilson might have saved the League of Nations in
1919 by agreeing to reservations demanded by the Republicans,
Clinton might have prevented rejection of the test ban treaty by
agreeing not to seek its ratification during the remainder of this
presidential term.
</P>
<P>
   But both presidents drew the line on how far they would go to
satisfy the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's refusal to ratify the test ban pact marked the
first time it had voted down a treaty since it rejected the 1919
Treaty of Versailles officially ending World War I and creating the
League of Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Every Republican president since Herbert Hoover has had to deal
with a Democratic Congress during all or part of his tenure, while
only two Democrats, Harry Truman and Clinton, have been confronted
with Republican-dominated Congresses.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Virginia, former President George Bush,
whose son could be the next president, described what it was like
for a Republican chief executive to confront a Democratic Congress
for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hell of a time fighting with an entrenched
congressional leadership that seemed determined to fight me at
every turn,'' said Bush. ``We were playing hardball politics and it
was kind of uphill and we weren't able to take the offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   If Wilson were alive he could recount an even more agonizing
tale.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the fighting in World War I stopped in
November 1918, he journeyed to Paris as the head of the American
delegation to the Versailles Peace Conference where he conferred
with the leaders of England, France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But he had made two mistakes. He first asked the people to
reelect a Democratic Congress in 1918, and instead they chose
Republicans. Then he did not include any Republican senator or any
other representative of the Republican Party in the peace
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   After months of often-heated negotiations, Wilson and the other
leaders signed the Treaty of Versailles in 1919. Wilson then
returned home and launched a cross-country tour to sell the League
of Nations to the American people. That journey ended when he was
felled by a debilitating stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But from his sick bed he fought on, refusing to accept
concessions demanded by Senate Republicans because he claimed they
would destroy the League. Thus, the treaty and U.S. membership in
the League failed to win Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Wilson predicted, another world war began two decades
later.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, it is possible that rejection of the test ban
treaty could spur India, Pakistan and other countries to move more
swiftly down a perilous path toward nuclear conflagration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
