<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-WOMEN-GUTHRIE-BOS &LR;      10-20 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-GUTHRIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RACING PIONEER WHO WAS DRIVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Janet Guthrie said that she harbors no malice. That
times have changed. That even back 22 years ago, while a target of
endless ``woman driver'' jokes as the first female to drive in the
Indianapolis 500, she was able to shrug off the sexist ridicule,
the gratuitous barbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly I could laugh at it,'' Guthrie recalled. ``I really did
think it was funny.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean she's forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   When Guthrie was approached for an interview Monday afternoon
after a rehearsal for the Women's Sports Foundation's 20th annual
Salute to Women in Sports, she quickly agreed. She just as quickly
recited the gist of a 1976 column in the Globe that painted a
picture of her futilely fishing through her handbag for the keys to
her car at the start of the race, sifting through bobby pins and
makeup and hairbrushes, then using the rear-view mirror to judge
her mascara as the other 32 drivers angrily blew their horns.
</P>
<P>
   I'll meet you after lunch if you don't mind chatting while I get
a manicure, she concluded breezily.
</P>
<P>
   Whew.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old Guthrie, who in 1980 was among the first class
of inductees into the foundation's International Women's Sports
Hall of Fame, wears her history as matter-of-factly as she wears
her tailored gray pantsuit but relays it with a quick and flawless
smile. As far as she's concerned, she should have been respected in
the first place, as a driver who had competed for 13 years on
sports car road-racing circuits before she ever showed up at the
fabled speedway in Indianapolis. (``I knew the fact that I was a
woman was completely irrelevant,'' she said. ``It was just that
nobody else seemed to know that.'')
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear she was going to have to prove herself
beyond what would have been expected of a man, she figured she'd
just have to drive fast and well to shut everyone up. For the most
part, she did just that, finishing ninth at Indy in 1978, beating
25 of the 32 male drivers while competing with a broken wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's done a good job,'' Bobby Unser told the Philadelphia
Inquirer magazine in 1979. ``I gotta admit that I had my doubts
about her. But she's proven her point.''
</P>
<P>
   If Guthrie carries any sadness, it's that she didn't get a
chance to prove it year after year. Despite a solid early career in
both Indy cars and on the NASCAR stock-car circuit, she was able to
find top-level sponsorship for only three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had been able to go on, but no money, no race,'' she
said. ``That remains a problem for many women athletes. I was
shocked and dismayed. You can compare my record in my 11 Indy-car
races with the first 11 Indy-car races of any of the superstars,
and I think you would find the comparison quite decent. I had a
hard time reconciling myself to that. It was a sport I loved very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   So Guthrie, who had trained as a physicist and once hoped to
become an astronaut, left for Colorado to write a book that reached
1,200 pages by the time she said everything she had to say. It
awaits publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm cutting,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the most popular honorees at Monday's gala were members of
the 1999 US women's soccer team that won the Women's World Cup,
including Michelle Akers, Briana Scurry, Saskia Webber, Tracy
Ducar, Julie Foudy, Kristine Lilly, Carla Overbeck, Cristie Pearce,
and Sara Whalen. Led by Mia Hamm, who was named Team Sportswoman of
the Year for the second time in three years, even those who
couldn't make it, including Brandi Chastain, received their share
of attention. ``Hopefully the next time we can host the World Cup,
we're going to ask Brandi to take off her shirt in the first game
because then we know we're going to get more than 650,000 people to
come out to the games,'' joked Hamm . . . The World Cup hardly went
unnoticed by the children of several other award winners, either.
Juli Inkster, who was named Individual Sportswoman of the Year,
reported that her two daughters, ages 5 and 9, ``loved following
the World Cup. They were all over it.'' Afterward at a champagne
reception, Joan Samuelson's husband, Scott, clutched a folded Mia
Hamm jersey for autographing on behalf of daughter Abby, who will
be 12 Saturday. Samuelson was one of four women inducted into the
Hall of Fame . . . Foudy, a World Cup co-captain, will succeed
Basketball Hall of Famer Nancy Lieberman-Cline as president of the
Women's Sports Foundation in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The oddest pairing of the night had to be the outrageously perky
Goldie Hawn giggling her way through presenting the reserved
Samuelson with her induction award . . . Also among the presenters
was Buffalo Bills quarterback Doug Flutie, who confessed, ``We did
a celebrity ski race six or seven years ago, and Joan Benoit kicked
my butt.'' Before she broke her leg on the slopes of Pleasant
Mountain in Maine as a 15-year-old, Samuelson had dreams of
becoming a world-class skier . . . Flutie, joined on stage by his
10-year-old daughter, Alexa, gave an example of how times are
changing: After watching the Gatorade ad featuring Hamm and Michael
Jordan that began airing during the World Cup, Alexa turned to her
father and asked, ``Who's the guy in the commercial with Mia?'' . .
. Although this was the 20th year for the awards dinner, the
foundation itself has reached the quarter-century mark. To note the
achievement, the celebration was subtitled ``25 Years of Making a
Difference'' . . . Six of the eight surviving co-founders of the
LPGA _ Alice Bauer, Patty Berg, Marilynn Smith, Betty Jameson,
Bettye Danoff, and Shirley Spork _ attended. ``When Babe
(Didricksen Zaharias) died, it strengthened the bond among all of
us. It made us determined that the organization didn't die.'' said
Smith. Zaharias, one of the co-founders, died of cancer in 1956 at
age 43 . . . Cammi Granato, captain of the 1998 Olympic ice hockey
team who missed last year's dinner ``because I had a real job,''
was there this time around. Granato is taking a year's leave of
absence from her job as radio color commentator for the NHL's Los
Angeles Kings to train full time. Joining her were teammates Karyn
Bye and A.J. Mleczko. Mleczko, who led Harvard to the national
title last spring, was a nominee for Team Sportswoman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also getting a night in the spotlight were athletes in the top
echelons of less-publicized sports. Among the 100-plus women who
paraded across the stage of the Waldorf-Astoria's Grand Ballroom in
the traditional march of athletes were:
</P>
<P>
   --Jill Bakken, bobsled. Ranked among the top 10 in the world
since 1995, Bakken will be a favorite to compete in the 2002
Olympics, in which women's bobsled will make its debut.
</P>
<P>
   --Rhoni Barton, waterskiing. A professional competitor in
slalom, tricks, and jumps, Barton was among the finalists for
Individual Sportswoman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   --Janet Dykman, archery. At 47,Dykman has qualified to compete
in Sydney. In 1996, she posted the best Olympic finish ever for the
US by reaching the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   --Cheryl Haworth, weightlifting. Owner of 35 American records,
the 17-year-old is also headed for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   --Jan Schmidt, bowling. Marketing director for the professional
women's bowling association, Schmidt won the Women's International
Bowling Association national singles title in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
