<HEADLINE>
N.Y. DEVELOPER BUYS BOSTON'S RITZ-CARLTON HOTEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ritz-Carlton, the reputed grande dame of the city's luxury
hotels, has been sold for $122 million to Millennium Partners, a
New York developer that unveiled plans Tuesday to open a second
Ritz-Carlton in Boston in the spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The new 155-room Ritz will face Boston Common as part of the
$500 million Millennium Place project, which will include 270
premium condominiums, a movie theater, fitness club and 85
apartments, all within two city blocks bounded by Washington,
Tremont and Boylston streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news for the city,'' said Mayor Thomas M.
Menino, who was present for the announcement on the Ritz's Roof
Restaurant. ``It blows your mind that they're putting a
Ritz-Carlton on Washington Street.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Millennium is considering closing the current
Ritz for one year to give the hotel a sorely needed $30 million
face lift. The alternative, to keep portions of the 72-year-old
hotel open while it is renovated piecemeal, would take several
years and might disturb guests, said Christopher Jeffries,
principal and founding partner of Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am nervous that such extensive renovation would make for a
miserable guest experience,'' said Jeffries, who said a final
decision is dependent on a feasibility study now underway.
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz-Carlton, a 17-story beaux-arts style hotel that has
hosted Winston Churchill, John F. Kennedy and Tennessee Williams,
is widely seen as being somewhat dated. Cracks in its facade and
small room size are among the problems that the renovation would
address, Jeffries said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Ritz is relatively full, with 88 percent of its
rooms occupied Wednesday, according to Henri A. Boubee, general
manager of the hotel. The high occupancy suggests that Millennium
may wait for the new Ritz hotel on Washington Street to open before
proceeding in earnest with renovations of the current Ritz on
Arlington Street to take advantage of the red hot hotel market,
industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boston hotel rooms commanded the second-highest
prices in the country, averaging $177.65 a night, according to John
A. Fox, senior vice president of PKF Consulting Inc. in New York.
Boston's hotel occupancy rate _ 78.8 percent _ was the
third-highest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the market shows no signs of cooling. In August, 85.7
percent of the Boston's hotel rooms were full, compared to 83.4
percent in August 1998, according to PKF figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is one of the hottest hotel markets in the country,''
said Fox, who attributed the strength to a combination of a limited
supply of rooms and surging demand in a booming local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Boston could support two Ritz-Carlton hotels only
a few blocks apart, Jeffries said the city could use 10
Ritz-Carltons. ``The demand for luxury hotel rooms is enormous
here,'' said Jeffries, who noted there were fewer than 1,000 luxury
hotel rooms in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The market is so good that officials at the Four Seasons Hotel,
the luxury hotel that has emerged as the Ritz's main rival just a
block away on Boylston Street, went so far as to welcome the
addition of a new hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about as positive as it could be,'' said Robin A.
Brown, general manager of the Four Seasons, which had just two
vacant rooms out of 288. ``Having two Ritz-Carltons in the city
will attract more sophisticated travelers to Boston, which will
benefit us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Millennium is seeking to differentiate the two Ritz-Carlton
hotels by giving the new hotel a more contemporary look of glass
and steel, while preserving the old world mahogany-trimmed elegance
of the current hotel, where rooms start at $250 a night and top out
at $2,500 for a suite that comes with a jacuzzi and private butler.
</P>
<P>
   While Millennium is developing four Ritz-Carlton hotels
elsewhere in the country, including two in Washington, D.C., one in
Atlanta and another in New York city, the Boston hotel is the
company's first acquisition of an already established hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made an exception because we wanted to control the
Ritz-Carlton name in Boston,'' said Jeffries.
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz, which was mostly recently owned by the Host Marriott
Corp., has changed hands several times in recent years as it fell
upon hard financial times. The hotel's $135 million mortgage was in
default when it was auctioned for $75 million in 1998 to the
Blackstone Group, a privately held New York investment firm. Two
months later, Blackstone sold the hotel to Host Marriott for a
reported $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Ritz insisted that the hotel was profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel is doing extremely well,'' said Leonardo Inghilleri,
vice president of the Ritz-Carlton Hotel Co., which runs the hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
