<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANCUISINE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: fine slivers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heat 3 tablespoons of butter in a heavy 12-inch skillet over
high heat for 1 1/2 to 2 minutes, until it melts, foams up, then
subsides. Add half the pork and stir-fry 3 minutes, until no longer
pink. With slotted spoon, lift to a large heat-proof bowl and
reserve. Brown remaining pork the same way. Return first batch to
skillet, pour in Calvados, heat for about 1 minute, then blaze with
a match. As soon as flames subside, transfer skillet mixture to
bowl, sprinkle with 1/2 teaspoon of salt and pepper and set aside.
Keep skillet handy.
</P>
<P>
   In small, heavy saucepan, melt 2 tablespoons of remaining butter
over moderate heat. Blend in flour to make a smooth paste. Add
broth and remaining 1/2 teaspoon salt; cook 3 to 5 minutes,
stirring constantly, until thickened and smooth. Remove sauce from
heat and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Add final 3 tablespoons butter to skillet and set over moderate
heat. When it melts, add onion and saute about 5 minutes, stirring
often, until limp and golden. Add mushrooms, reduce heat to low and
saute 5 minutes, stirring often, until mushrooms have released
their juices and these evaporate. Add riesling and red wine, raise
heat to moderately high, and boil uncovered for 3 to 4 minutes,
until skillet liquid is reduced by two-thirds. Add tomatoes, olives
and pimentos, and bring to simmer over moderate heat. Mix in
reserved sauce, mustard, Worcestershire, red pepper sauce, port and
cream. Bring to a boil over moderate heat. Adjust heat so mixture
bubbles gently and simmer, uncovered, for 25 to 30 minutes,
stirring often, until skillet liquid is reduced by about half and
is the consistency of gravy. Mix in corn, reserved pork, and all
pork liquid and simmer, uncovered, for 3 to 5 minutes, just until
serving temperature. Serve over rice.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 427 calories, 30 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 20 grams protein, 74 milligrams cholesterol,
787 milligrams sodium, 64 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New German Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED RED CABBAGE WITH ONIONS AND APPLES IN RED WINE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 large red cabbage (about 2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large tart green apples, peeled, cored and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rich beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 large whole bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry red wine (preferably German)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red currant jelly
</P>
<P>
   Trim coarse outer leaves from cabbage and discard; quarter
cabbage, slice off hard white core at the point of each quarter and
discard. Slice each quarter very thin. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a very large, heavy skillet over moderately high
heat, sprinkle in sugar, heat 2 to 3 minutes _ just until
dissolved. Add onion and apples and stir-fry about 5 minutes, until
limp and golden. Add cabbage and stir-fry about 5 minutes, until
nicely glazed. Pour in red wine vinegar and 1/2 cup beef broth.
When mixture simmers, adjust heat so liquid bubbles very gently.
Sprinkle in salt and add bay leaves, pushing them down into
cabbage. Cover skillet and simmer 20 to 25 minutes, until cabbage
is crisp-tender.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle flour over cabbage and toss well to mix. Add wine and
remaining 1/2 cup beef broth. Heat, stirring gently, for 3 to 5
minutes, until liquids are thickened and no raw starch taste
remains. Remove and discard bay leaves, add jelly, toss lightly to
mix. Warm, uncovered, for 5 minutes and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 114 calories, 4 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 258 milligrams
sodium, 27 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New German Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PLUM CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8-10
</P>
<P>
   Pastry:
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons cold unsalted butter, cut into small cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cold milk
</P>
<P>
   1 extra-large egg yolk blended with 1 tablespoon milk (this is
the glaze)
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Italian black plums, pitted (but not peeled), then
quartered, but not cut all the way through so quarters can be
spread like flower petals, or 2 (16 ounces) cans purple plums,
drained well, pitted and halved.
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soft white bread crumbs, optional
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar mixed with 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Generously butter bottom and sides
of 11-inch slip-bottom tart tin and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter in small mixer bowl with electric mixer at high
speed for 2 to 3 minutes, until light and fluffy. With motor still
running, add sugar, 1 tablespoon at a time. Continue beating 2 to 3
minutes longer. By hand, mix in flour, baking powder and salt, then
the milk, stirring after each addition only enough to combine.
Press pastry smoothly over bottom and up sides of prepared tart
tin, brush with egg glaze and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   If plums seem very juicy, scatter bread crumbs evenly over the
pastry. Arrange plums skin-side down in pastry shell in rows,
fanning quarters out and overlapping plums slightly. (If using
canned plums, arrange halves hollow side down in concentric
circles.) Sprinkle with cinnamon sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Set tart on baking sheet and bake in lower third of oven for
40-45 minutes until pastry is nicely browned and filling is bubbly.
Before cutting, cool tart to room temperature on wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, carefully loosen and remove tart tin sides, then
transfer tart (still on pan bottom) to round platter or cake stand.
Cut into wedges at table.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with bread crmbs: 270 calories,
9 grams fat, 44 grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 62 milligrams
cholesterol, 272 milligrams sodium, 30 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Cuisines of Germany''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
