<HEADLINE>
SAY AUF WIEDERSEHEN TO SUMMER FARE, WITH HEARTY BUT FLAVORFUL
DISHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Face it. German food isn't sexy.
</P>
<P>
   But the short shrift that German fare gets in this country isn't
fair.
</P>
<P>
   Too often labeled heavy and mundane, German food is perhaps too
close to our own home cooking for us to appreciate its nuances. And
there are nuances. We too often tend to associate German food with
huge portions of underspiced cabbage, warm potato salad and fat
wursts, all accompanied by loud music.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's a lot of meat and potatoes, but there are also the
glories of white asparagus in the spring and earthy mushrooms in
the autumn and delicate cookies at Christmastime. There's always
bread with gumption and wondrous cheese and snappy mustard and
luscious wine and beer with body.
</P>
<P>
   When Francophile Patricia Wells reviewed the restaurants of the
world for an International Herald Tribune series, she ``went
kicking and screaming to Germany.'' But to her surprise, ``I found
several lovely restaurants there.''
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, despite a history of wars and famines (agriculture
yields weren't stable until the potato migrated from here to there
in the 18th century), the Germans managed to create a cuisine of
rich stews and brined vegetables and formidable noodles and
dumplings. The cooks aren't the alchemists of Italy or France, but
this food, along with that of the British, helped fashion the way
we cook in America today. Chicken-fried steak is more akin to
schnitzel than it is to steak au poivre.
</P>
<P>
   German leaf salads are lovely _ usually a combination of butter
lettuce with some pickled or marinated vegetables, such as baby
corn or salsify or green beans. Soups run the gamut from light,
cold berry combinations to sturdy liver-dumpling numbers. Meats
include everything from the barnyard _ not just the pork we so
often expect _ and quite a haul from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   As summer melts into winter, all of this not-so-sexy food
becomes a lot more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plain low-fat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh dill, chopped medium-fine
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds pickling cucumbers, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Whisk first 6 ingredients together until creamy. Taste for
mustard and add a bit more, if needed; there should be a distinct
mustard flavor, but take care not to add so much that you overpower
the flavor of the cucumbers. Add cucumbers to bowl and toss well to
mix. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate at least 4 hours
before serving, or better yet, chill overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 57 calories, 4 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 11 milligrams cholesterol,
295 milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New German Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson and Hedy Wuerz
(HarperCollins, $25)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRIED POTATOES WITH MARJORAM
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds potatoes, peeled and sliced or diced
</P>
<P>
   2-3 tablespoons lard
</P>
<P>
   8 strips medium-lean bacon, cut into matchsticks
</P>
<P>
   Crushed marjoram
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Heat lard in large skillet or in heavy-bottomed saucepan. Add
bacon to lard, along with potatoes. Fry bacon and potatoes for a
good five minutes, turning frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle a generous amount of crushed marjoram, as well as salt
and pepper, over the contents of the skillet. Add water, stir once
more, then cover and cook over medium-low heat for just about 30
minutes, stirring every 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 204 calories, 9 grams fat, 27
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 11 milligrams cholesterol,
142 milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Cuisines of Germany'' by Horst Scharfenberg (Poseidon
Press, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED BEEF ROLLS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 6-ounce slices top or bottom round
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons strong mustard
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 slices medium-lean bacon
</P>
<P>
   2 large gherkins or dill pickles, halved lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1-2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lard or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 cups beef stock
</P>
<P>
   1 large carrot, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   Lay beef slices out flat and thinly coat with mustard. Sprinkle
with pepper. Place 2 strips bacon on each slice, then a pickle or
gherkin. Roll up tight. Keep from unrolling with cooking twine or
poultry skewers. Sprinkle lightly with salt and pepper and coat
beef rolls in flour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat fat in large stew pot. Saute onions until translucent. Add
beef rolls, browning them well on all sides. Pour in 1 cup beef
stock, add carrot, cover and braise over moderate heat for 2 hours.
You may want to add a little more stock occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Remove beef rolls from broth. Stir cornstarch in a little cold
water; add this to cooking liquid and bring to a boil. Gravy can be
strained, but it is not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 431 calories, 22 grams fat,
grams carbohydrates, 43 grams protein, 109 milligrams cholesterol,
965 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New German Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   RAT TAILS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) unsalted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless pork loin, trimmed of excess fat and cut into
31/2-by-1/8-by-1/8-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Calvados or applejack
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rich beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion, peeled and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound medium-size mushrooms, wiped clean and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup riesling or other dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry red wine (preferably German)
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-size vine-ripe tomatoes, peeled, cored, seeded and
coarsely chopped, or 1 cup canned crushed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons coarsely chopped pimento-stuffed olives
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup thinly slivered pimentos
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon hot red pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ruby port
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   4 ears pickled baby corn, cut lengthwise into fine slivers
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
