<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-CO     10-20 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Searching for Willie Morris
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAZOO CITY, Miss. _ I was standing beside the highway that leads
into the center of town, reading a historical marker that turned
out to be all about the C.S.S. Arkansas, an ironclad ram
commissioned by the Confederate Navy on July 14, 1862.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mississippi's version of Civil War history, the
Arkansas was the scourge of the Yazoo and Mississippi rivers,
engaging the combined Union fleet at the naval siege of Vicksburg.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Confederacy itself, the glory of the Arkansas was
brief, ``scuttled north of Baton Rouge Aug. 5, 1862 to prevent
capture by Union forces.''
</P>
<P>
   But not one word about Willie Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Such was my quest so early in the morning, to discover what
memorials Yazoo City has bestowed on its recently departed, most
famous man of letters. I would have thought a plaque at the very
least.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Morris died this year at a too-young age, hardly in his
60s. Jackson, where he made his home in recent times, treated him
properly in death, seeing to it that his body lay in state in the
rotunda of Mississippi's Old Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has its own claim to Willie Morris, renowned in his youth
as a muckraker in the finest traditions of journalism, first as
editor of the University of Texas campus newspaper and later as
editor of the Austin-based Texas Observer.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to edit Harper's magazine in New York for a brief,
glorious career _ best remembered for printing in one issue the
entire text of Norman Mailer's ``Armies of the Night,'' which would
win a Pulitzer in book form.
</P>
<P>
   Though Willie Morris made publishing history, he did not make
enough money for the magazine's publishers. Eventually, sadly, he
was forced out.
</P>
<P>
   I never met him, despite our having mutual friends. One time I
had hoped we could get together in Oxford, Miss., where he was
writer in residence at Ole Miss. As it turned out, he was traveling
on the day I was visiting.
</P>
<P>
   His first book has long been considered his best book, ``North
Toward Home,'' a young man's memoir, from Yazoo City to New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   But Willie Morris did it right, dying at the right time. His
last book, ``My Dog Skip,'' a story from his boyhood, has become
his greatest success, including a Hollywood deal with all the
trimmings.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to compare, of course, with the C.S.S. Arkansas, when it
comes to markers. Or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Early as it was that morning in Yazoo City, there was no one
that I could find to ask: What have they done for Willie Morris
lately?
</P>
<P>
   Only later, on down the road, was I able to telephone the
Chamber of Commerce. A nice Southern lady was happy to fill me in.
</P>
<P>
   Yazoo City has ``My Dog Skip'' tours that visit the sites that
Willie Morris wrote about. His cemetery plot is an attraction
itself, buried as he is just 13 steps from the Witch's Grave, the
occupant of which, local legend says, used her black magic to burn
down the town. Willie, in turn, used her for one of his stories.
</P>
<P>
   More is planned. An exhibit is in the works. No reason not to
think that eventually he'll be right up there with Jerry Clower,
the country comedian, Yazoo City's other famous son who died this
past year.
</P>
<P>
   So, stop by if you're in the neighborhood of Yazoo City. They
seem like nice folks, who remember their own in the nicest way.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Remember the Arkansas!
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75904; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net. Children
can write to Free Books for Kids at the above address, and a book
will be sent to them.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
