<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PANDAS-1021-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA STATE TV SAYS ATLANTA ZOO TO GET TWO PANDAS SOON, BUT IS
IT FINAL?
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    EDs: Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   KORLA, China _ Pandemonium!
</P>
<P>
   Two of China's national treasures, a pair of panda bears, will
be going to Zoo Atlanta by the end of this month, the dominant
state television network here CCTV-1 reported late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But whether 2-year-old female Lun Lun and her 2-year-old male
pal Yang Yang were really about to split from the Chengdu Research
Base of Giant Panda Breeding appeared to be still slightly up in
the air Thursday(CQ), despite this unqualified report to millions
of viewers on Chinese government-run television.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday night, Sarah Bexell, Zoo Atlanta's researcher on
the ground in China, said she had no official confirmation that
China's ruling State Council had finally approved the long-delayed
export permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be great news,'' said Bexell after hearing about
the TV report.
</P>
<P>
   Xinhua, China's official news agency, carried nothing about the
prospect that the two pre-adolescent fuzz balls had been given
formal permission to grow up half-way around the world in
air-conditioned cages in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Without signed export licenses, the pandas aren't going
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Zoo Atlanta and its winged partner United Parcel
Service were already deep into contingency planning to fly the two
pandas out of Beijing International Airport at 5 a.m. (local time)
on Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo Atlanta's ranking veterinarian, Dr. Rita McManamon, has
reservations to arrive in Beijing and go on to Chengdu on Sunday to
accompany Lun Lun and Yang Yang on their flight to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no pandemic problem, they should cross the
international dateline and arive at Atlanta's Hartsfield
International Airport at around 9 a.m. (EDT) on Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The television news segment was built on an interview taped
earlier in the day with Bexell, who was asked by a CCTV reporter
about her research and how it will help protect the giant panda, an
endangered species in China.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the report, the Chinese journalist said simply
that the two pandas will head to Atlanta by the end of the month.
The television news did not mention the need for export permits or
the delay already keeping Zoo Atlanta guessing about when or
whether it will receive the pandas.
</P>
<P>
   An expected Oct. 7 departure was missed for lack of the
requisite Chinese export approvals. Now the paperwork has been
bumped all the way to the top of the bureaucracy, awaiting approval
only from the State Council and Prime Minister Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   After setting another shipment date of Oct. 28, Zoo Atlanta, the
Chinese panda keepers and UPS have set in motion the plan to
transport Lun Lun and Yang Yang from their home amid bamboo
thickets to their new home in the southeastern U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The two animals, who are at a rolly-polly rambunctious stage of
panda life, have been spending time just about every day in the
cages provided by UPS to get used to their temporary habitat for
the 10,000-mile air trip.
</P>
<P>
   A UPS spokeswoman said its special ``Panda Express'' plane,
painted with a panda motif and donated for this flight, is planned
to arrive in Beijing on the morning of Wed., Oct. 27. This assumes
that UPS is granted the necessary landing rights to fly into
Beijing airport.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, the pandas will fly to Beijing on a Chinese
commercial flight from the Chengdu base where they were born, then
hitch up with the UPS plane.
</P>
<P>
   The UPS plane, the vet and the pandas are scheduled to depart
around 5 a.m. on Oct. 28 Beijing time, arriving in time for
Atlantans' morning coffee break.
</P>
<P>
   That is, it will happen if China's bureaucrats come through with
the export permit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
