<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
Oct. 21. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   ACCRED: The state Board of Education _ on Tuesday anyway _
appeared steadfast in its desire to revoke accreditation for the KC
School District despite the school board's pledge to fight the move
in court. Meanwhile, the school board continues efforts to press
its case. Lance Loewenstein meets with The Star's editorial board
Wednesday. We recheck the state board's position Wednesday, check
the stance in St. Louis and add more detail to the potential
outcome of losing accreditation. Phil O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   BART (with ACCRED): Other educational leaders say the
recommendation to strip KC and St. Louis of accreditation is a
gutsy move by state Education Commissioner Bob Bartman. But Bartman
says it's the right thing to do for the kids. A profile of the
former Vietnam platoon leader, marathon runner and speaker of
Italian. Photo. Will Sentell.
</P>
<P>
   NELSON: Federal indictment likely today against Keith Nelson.
Those charges could include counts for murder, kidnapping and
sexual abuse of Pamela Butler. All of those counts could carry the
death penalty. Mark Morris. 20. File mug.
</P>
<P>
   GRIEF (with NELSON): The Pamela Butler visitation, and the
funeral today, are drawing strangers as well as friends of the
family, repeating a phenomenon seen worldwide with JFK Jr. and
Princess Di, and on a lesser scale when teen-agers leave flowers
and memorials where dead friends died: mass public grieving. This
is a contrast from the time when strangers just didn't intrude on
people's grief. So what is it about society that has caused all
this change? We talk to experts and people who participate. Don
Bradley and John Martellaro. 25.
</P>
<P>
   EVICT: An elderly woman with two adult disabled children is
being foreclosed on Thursday. Neighborhood people are rallying
behind her because she appears to be a victim of a home improvement
loan program that preys on inner city residents. Ruth Igoe. 18.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   TWA _ TWA reports a larger third quarter loss as fuel costs rose
and business travelers fled to rivals after a threatened machinists
strike. By Randolph Heaster
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT _ Sprint Corp. releases its third quarter earnings
Wednesday. By Ted Sickinger
</P>
<P>
   STAFF _ Educators wish teen-agers worked fewer hours during the
school year. Paycheck pursuits are producing sleepy, sub-par
students. Are employers listening? At Work column By Diane
Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   CERNER _ Cerner announces financial results after the market
closes Wednesday. Julius Karash
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   WRS. Wide receivers Joe Horn and Kevin Lockett are really
cooking these days. Really. Horn and Lockett, part owner in a
Kansas City restaurant, have roasted secondaries in the last two
weeks and are finally emerging as go-to threats. Randy Covitz.
25-30. Graphic, photos
</P>
<P>
   FALLFISH. Fishing in the Big River, Meramec or Bourbeuse for
smallmouth bass is a passion for Al Agnew of Desloge, Mo. His
passion is also painting the fishing on the stream. He tries to
transfer the beauty his sees and experiences on the rivers to his
canvas. Brent Frazee. 25. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   MUFT. Jimmie Dougherty is quarter back 1A through 1Z now. Just
like Dylen Smith at KU. He's brittle, he's banged up, and he knows
he may not finish the season after the example of what happened to
Kirk Farmer. But he's game. And he has the confidence of his
teammates. 15-18. Mike DeArmond. File photos
</P>
<P>
   KUFT. Dylen Smith gets his fourth start Saturday against
Missouri. How's he doing? Bob Dutton. 18-20. File photos
</P>
<P>
   MASK. The evolution of the hockey mask, which has gotten pretty
funky. They never wore masks years ago. Now they're painted and
cool, like Blades goalie Bruce Racine's mask, which features the
Kansas City skyline. Howard Richman. 18. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   POZ. Joe Posnanski column on the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   DERRICK. The subject came up a month ago in a casual
conversation with Derrick Alexander about the impending return of
Denver cornerback Dale Carter to Kansas City and Arrowhead Stadium.
Alexander, the Chiefs wide receiver, said he had a pretty good
guess about how Carter felt playing against his former team because
Alexander himself was just a few weeks from playing in a similar
game. ``When we go back to Baltimore this year,'' Alexander said,
``I feel like I'm going to have to play the best game I've ever
played in my life.'' Adam Teicher. 20.
</P>
<P>
   KUHOOP. KU's depth may causes potential problems for Roy
Williams in establishing a player rotation. He says he's only
comfortable playing nine. Bob Dutton. 18-20. Photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
