<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Oct. 21:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ In a big surprise, the national
assembly elected an ailing Muslim leader, Abdurrahaman Wahid, as
Indonesia's new president today. Followers of the opposition leader
who was expected to win, Megawati Sukarnoputri, are out on the
streets, clashing with police. At least 2 people die as a car bomb
explodes. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-WAHID (Jakarta) _ A man-in-the-news profile of
Indonesia's new president: Who is Abdurrahaman Wahid and what does
he stand for? The question seems to be asked most often by people
who know him best. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMS (Moscow) _ Russia strongly rejects the American
proposal to revamp the ABM treaty. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Russian Prime Minister Putin,
President Yeltsin's latest choice to be his successor, visits the
restive province of Chechnya as his popularity rises. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PAPON (Paris) _ Former Vichy official Maurice Papon,
sentenced in 1998 to 10 years imprisonment for helping deport Jews
to Nazi death camps, said Wednesday that he was fleeing into exile
rather than spend his last years in jail. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-LOBBY (Washington) _ Richard Holbrooke, the U.N.
envoy, lobbies on Capitol Hill for the U.S. to pay U.N. dues. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-AFRICA (Abuja, Nigeria) _ Secretary of State Albright
urges Nigeria to continue reforms, saying it could be a ``signpost
for others in search of freedom.'' By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKES (Tokyo) _ Japan's vice defense minister resigns on
Wednesday after proposing that Japan drop its renunciation of
nuclear weapons. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Top Justice Department
officials try to explain their studiously neutral analysis of the
clemency request from the Puerto Rican terrorists. Eric Holder and
the top pardon attorney testify before Senate Judiciary Committee.
By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the spending
bills. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate votes to ban
partial-birth abortion, but falls short of votes necessary to
override an expected Clinton veto. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House is expected to pass an
education bill. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-AWARDS (Washington) _ Kennedy Center honors are to be
announced. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-WITHDRAWS (Washington) _ Citing her inability to raise
money, Elizabeth Dole, the first woman to make a credible race for
the White House, drops out. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-ASSESS (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ How the Republican race may be
affected: Good news for McCain; bad news for Bush. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTER-TRIAL (Undated) _ Federal prosecutors make opening
statements in the trial of William Hamilton, the Teamsters Union's
former political director, who is charged with helping divert union
money toward the campaign of Ron Carey, formely the union
president. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-SUIT (New York) _ For weeks, in the wake of the
controversial ``Sensation'' exhibit, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has
been talking about seizing control of the Brooklyn Museum of Art by
ousting its Board of Trustees. But the city's legal strategy has
evolved and now embraces a much more drastic solution, which is to
evict the museum and its vast holdings of artwork. City officials
acknowledge that this strategy could result in Brooklyn losing
possession of the nation's second largest art collection _ 1.5
million paintings, sculptures and decorative objects that took a
century to assemble. By David Barstow. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional and White House
negotiators continue work on toward a compromise on a bill
overhauling the nation's financial system. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-EARNINGS (Undated) _ IBM reports third-quarter earnings
after the market closes. The consensus forecast is 90 cents a
share. The ``whisper'' _ 91 cents. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-ONLINE (Undated) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter is expected
to announce today its plans to offer on-line trading. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-ONLINE-TEEN (Undated) _ Morgan Stanley's planned Web site
faces one obstacle: a California teenager.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDICARE (Undated) _ Looking at the Clinton Medicare
proposal, which uses PPO providers as a model, and what it may mean
to private health plans. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Undated) _ The United States trade deficit
narrowed slightly to $24.1 billion in August, as exports rose
sharply for the third consecutive month. Exports rose 3.7 percent
to $82.03 billion, a sign that demand from overseas markets is on
the upswing after the global financial turmoil of last year.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Chase Manhattan reports a 61 percent
rise in third-quarter earnings, exceeding analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Looking at the third-quarter
performance of the airlines: UAL, parent of United Airlines,
reports a 12 percent drop in profits, at the low end of estimates,
and US Airways reports a wider-than-expected loss. AMR, parent of
American, is also scheduled to report. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ America Online reports after the market
close. Consensus is 13 cents a share. The ``whisper number'' is 12
cents. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-CHARITY (Undated) _ The IRS plans to crack down on
accelerated charitable remainder trusts, sometimes known as
``chutzpah trusts.'' By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-INVEST (Hong Kong) _ With Asia's stock markets shaking off
two years of near-paralysis, it is no surprise that Asian companies
are rushing to raise billions of dollars. The surprise is how hard
they are finding the job. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-MISSILES (London) _ Boeing will team with Matra BAe
Dynamics, which is jointly owned by Aerospatiale Matra and British
Aerospace, to bid against Raytheon for a $1.5 billion contract to
supply Britain with air-to-air missiles for the Eurofighter
warplane. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ Looking at the weakening real despite
recent data, including today's employment report, that show the
economy strengthening. The real has fallen to 2 reals to the dollar
for the first time since March. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
