<HEADER>
A2942 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-AIRCRASH-ADVISORY-COX     10-20 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTN: News editors, national editors
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service is preparing to distribute another compelling
investigative series on the U.S. military by The Dayton Daily News.
``Falling From the Sky,'' a six-day series that starts Sunday, Oct.
24, concerns the recent rise in military air crashes and its
causes. The Daily News found that the U.S. military routinely sends
planes and helicopters in the air that it knows are plagued with
deadly safety problems. The series is based in part on
never-before-seen information from three databases from the Army,
Navy and Air Force safety centers.
</P>
<P>
   Publication of the stories is likely to have a national impact.
The Daily News won a Pulitzer Prize in 1998 for a series uncovering
problems with the military's health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Falling From the Sky,'' CoxNet will produce a Focus page
for Sunday, Oct. 24, based on the comprehensive first day of the
series. That page will be available Friday afternoon for a download
charge at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   Those stories, and subsequent days' offerings, will also be
available on the New York Times wire. The Sunday and Monday
installments will move on Friday, Oct. 22. Subsequent stories will
move daily next week. Photos and graphics accompany each
installment.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a budget of the page and stories that Cox will offer
from Dayton. If you have questions, please contact CoxNet at
404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Falling From the Sky
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Oct. 24: Day 1 (This installment will be available as a
CoxNet Focus page Friday, Oct. 22. Stories and photos will also
move separately.)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-MAIN _ The U.S. military routinely sends planes and
helicopters in the air that it knows are plagued with deadly safety
problems. An 18-month Dayton Daily News examination found that
planes keep falling from the sky for the same reasons, that
hundreds of crashes can be linked to maintenance errors, and that
the military keeps hundreds of crashes off its yearly accident
totals. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-CASE _ After an F-16 crashed into a South Carolina
neighborhood and killed a man, the Air Force assured the
congressman representing the district that the plane had been
``trouble free.'' But a Dayton Daily News investigation into the
crash found that in the months preceding the Sept. 13, 1988, crash,
the engine had been on two other F-16s and removed after pilots
reported smoke and fumes in their cockpits. (Carollo, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-HOW _ The series wouldn't have been possible without the
release of three databases from the Army, Navy and Air Force safety
centers.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-WEB _ Where to find the complete series on the web.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Oct. 25: Day 2
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-METAL _ A type of metal is in the middle of an
investigation involving a series of crashes of the Army's CH47
Chinook helicopter. The story came to light when a whistleblower,
working at a former factory in Springfield, Ohio, found flaws in a
metal used to construct gears that power the helicopter's huge
rotor blades. Investigators now suspect that seven crashes may be
linked to the metal. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Oct. 26: Day 3
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-MAINTENANCE _ The system used to maintain military
aircraft is itself broken. Hundreds of crashes can be linked to
work performed by unqualified mechanics, parts installed
improperly, engines overhauled incorrectly and inspection records
that were falsified. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-TIMMER _ A Hamilton, Ohio, man died in a helicopter that
should have been grounded. The test result that would have grounded
the craft arrived in the field three weeks after the crash.
(Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Oct. 27: Day 4
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-COUNT _ Since 1980, the military has omitted hundreds of
aviation incidents from its official accident rates, the statistics
used by Congress and the public to assess military safety.
(Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-BUTTON _ Among those not counted: the 1997 crash involving
Capt. Craig D. Button, who took off from an Air Force base in
Arizona and crashed an A-10 jet filled with bombs into a Colorado
mountain. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Oct. 28: Day 5
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-CONTRACTORS _ Private companies that do business with the
government, including large aircraft manufacturers, are protected
against many lawsuits by the government-contractor defense. The
defense means companies have limited liability even when they
produce defective products. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Oct. 29: Day 6
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-KNIGHTS _ The military's handling of the hydraulic
problems on the CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters is typical of the way
it handled numerous other mechanical failures in many types of
aircraft. Costs are weighed against risk. Some 70 incidents,
spanning more than 11 years, can be traced to hydraulic problems on
the Sea Knights. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-MCNALLY _ Anatomy of a crash. A detailed analysis of a
1994 crash in California involving a pilot named Randall McNally.
No cause was ever determined, but a Daily News examination found
that mechanics had detected problems with the plane's stabilizer
augmentor eight days before the crash. The augmentor was never
found. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
