A2949 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-ENCYCLOPEDIAS-HNS &LR;      10-20 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCYCLOPEDIAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENERABLE BOOK OF KNOWLEDGE SEES ITS FUTURE ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNY STRASBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Howard Halfon has 20 years of his life bound up
in the business of selling encyclopedias. But he's mostly just
watching as the latest volume in encyclopedia history is written.
</P>
<P>
   The text is about technology. Halfon isn't.
</P>
<P>
   With Encyclopaedia Britannica available on the Internet, the
231-year-old company is taking a new direction as it seeks to
reflect culture but also respect its dramatic shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Halfon, 58, of Daly City, loves encyclopedias as much as ever,
but he doesn't own a computer and really doesn't want to. The
habits of a salesman die hard: ``I might have to call it quits.
Business is getting very difficult. The printed form is becoming a
thing of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Halfon make $50,000 per year as he relished his job
of making phone calls and personal visits to sell new sets of
Encyclopaedia Britannica, long considered the leader in its class
for authoritative accuracy. For years, house calls were a trademark
of the company, which sold books by direct mail and at
shopping-mall kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   Halfon even met his wife, Nora Casal, 51, on a sales call to her
San Francisco home in 1979. She wanted to buy a set of
encyclopedias; he sold her that and more, a set of Great Books of
the Western World.
</P>
<P>
   He also persuaded her to go dancing with him. It was the sale of
a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   But the boom days of selling encyclopedias that way _ knocking
on the doors of America's blue-collar families, inviting a customer
to flip through pages and fill out order forms on a coffee table _
have faded.
</P>
<P>
   And over the past decade, Halfon has felt his relevance slipping
away. He still sells encyclopedias as an independent distributor,
but he doesn't sell Britannica. He had no choice but to discontinue
the brand in 1996 when the company axed its door-to-door sales in
favor of telephone and Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   Encyclopaedia Britannica has Halfon one more reason to feel like
a dinosaur in a high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Tuesday that its 32 volumes of the latest
Britannica wisdom and research are accessible on the Internet at
www.britannica.com. However, the company still sells $5 monthly
subscriptions for an Internet site (www.eb.com) that offers more
features and options.
</P>
<P>
   Britannica said it hopes to make money from the advertisements
on its free site after luring people there with the publisher's
reputation for quality. The company said it will spend about $35
million over the next year to advertise its site.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Britannica's belated but aggressive move into
electronic distribution _ including its CD-ROM sales _ just might
work toward reviving the company's profits. And Britannica admits
it needs an infusion of revenue. Don Yannias, chief executive of
Britannica.com, acknowledged that sales of print volumes have
declined steadily, leaving the company looking for newer, more
``now'' outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for other encyclopedia publishers, but
Britannica, once a leader, lost ground as competitors more deftly
navigated a Web-crazy world.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, for instance, encyclopedia publisher Funk &AMP; Wagnalls
teamed up with Microsoft _ which Britannica had spurned _ to
produce a colorful, multimedia CD-ROM encyclopedia. Britannica
stutter-stepped with a weaker, graphics-challenged version a year
later.
</P>
<P>
   Then Switzerland-based investor Jacob Safra bought Britannica in
1996, and the company pushed hard toward the electronic market.
Soon CD-ROM sales were accounting for the bulk of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as momentous a change as when we moved from England to
Chicago 75 years ago,'' Kent Devereaux, senior vice president of
product development and editorial on the digital side of
Britannica, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things come out of what we are doing: We are embracing the
future. We intend to be able to deliver trusted, aggregated,
intelligent information and content to users by any means
necessary, not only on the Internet, but down the road into
wireless Palm Pilot applications and WebTV.''
</P>
<P>
   This is no longer a business in which an asphalt-walking
salesman is likely to land a life-changing date.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably my best experience with Britannica: I met my
wonderful wife,'' Halfon said. Then he added, ``No more getting
married through (sales) leads with Britannica.''
</P>
<P>
   Britannica's newly renovated Web site, www.britannica.com, was
quickly overloaded with millions of users, a problem the company
said it planned to fix soon.
</P>
<P>
   The news is especially promising for computer users who want to
tap up-to-date, reliable research sources without leaving home,
said Dennis Maness, manager of General Collections at the San
Francisco Public Library and a self-described encyclopedia fanatic.
</P>
<P>
   Since childhood, he has enjoyed sitting down with a thick
encyclopedia volume and reading it, page after page, like a regular
book.
</P>
<P>
   He insists that the same opportunity for accidentally
discovering new and fascinating information _ what Maness calls
``the serendipity'' effect _ exists in the on-line encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he believes actual books will maintain their relevance
in a universe of CD-ROMS and Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with on-line (books) is they're not very
portable,'' Maness said. ``You can't take it to your table and read
it. You can't prop it up in bed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its best years, Britannica collected about $650 million in
revenues and employed about 3,500 people, including salespeople
like Halfon. The work force now is at about 350.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it intends to continue selling its bound
volumes, which cost about $1,250 a set. But the future of the books
depends on the company's Internet-related success, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Halfon's former peers in encyclopedia sales during the
'70s and '80s, some pulled in a quarter-million dollars in profits
during their best years as district managers. But they have moved
on, Halfon said. ``Most of the people are out of the business now.
They're doing other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``But life is change. Now I have to march on to a different
avenue of earning a living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
