<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TRADE-SUGAR-$ADV24-CO     10-20 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-SUGAR-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUGAR GROWERS WATCH WARILY AS NEW TRADE TALKS OPEN
 &HT;    760&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, Oct. 24.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the world prepares for a new round of trade
talks next month in Seattle, the producers of sugar and the users
of sugar are hoping for radically different outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   American sugar growers want to make sure the so-called
Millennium Round, which begins Nov. 30 and is expected to last
three years, doesn't open the door to greater imports of
foreign-grown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   American sugar users would love to see the door thrown open,
because the price of surplus sugar on the world market is about 6.7
cents per pound, while the price of American sugar is about 19.4
cents, a drop of about 3 cents in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to the opening session, the American position has
been to preserve existing sugar protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told sugar growers and producers ...that we would not
sacrifice the sugar growers or any other parts of agriculture at
this round, and certainly, they would not be treated in any kind of
disproportionately negative way,'' Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman said at a recent White House briefing on the upcoming
trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   But sugar growers worry that the Clinton administration, which
has made the export of U.S. agricultural products a top priority,
may ultimately use sugar as a bargaining chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get sacrificed on the altar of free trade in
the trade round,'' said Dalton Yancey, Washington representative of
the Florida Sugar Cane League and other sugar consortiums. ``We
don't want to be split off. We're an integral part of American
agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is one of ``fair trade'' versus ``free trade.'' While
the two terms seem similar, there is a world of difference in the
eyes of growers.
</P>
<P>
   For them, ``free trade'' means goods can flow across borders
unimpeded by tariffs. They say such a situation would be unfair to
American sugar because much of the foreign sugar is subsidized by
foreign governments, protected by government purchasing boards, or
produced under conditions that don't meet the stringent pollution
and labor standards met by U.S. growers.
</P>
<P>
   Growers prefer the term ``fair trade,'' which means tariffs are
imposed on foreign sugar to offset the advantages under which the
crop is grown or marketed.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. growers say the world market price is illusory. They note
that pound for pound, sugar is cheaper in the United States than in
most countries which produce the excess sugar sold on the world
market. For example, the price of a pound of sugar is about 71
cents in France, compared to about 41 cents in America.
</P>
<P>
   Judy C. Sanchez, director of corporate communications for U.S.
Sugar Corp., said Europe has distorted the world sugar market by
dumping about 6 million tons a year on the market at a time when
their own citizens pay far more than Americans for sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar users prefer the concept of free trade, which would give
them access to sugar at far lower prices than they pay
domestically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes no economic sense to have U.S. sugar prices that are
five times the world price,'' said Sarah Fogarty, senior manager
for international trade with the Grocery Manufacturers' of America.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baskin, a spokesman for Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co., said
that for his firm this issue is not just the cost of sugar _ he
noted that most American-made soft drinks use corn fructose as a
sweetener _ but also the implications of trade protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in free trade with a reduction of market barriers
to entry across the world,'' Baskin said. ``Coca-Cola does business
in about 200 countries worldwide, so obviously you can see the
reason why free trade and open markets are important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ardis Hammock, who runs 650-acre Frierson Farm in Glades
County, Fla., with her husband, Alan, and his elderly relatives,
the trade talks may mean the difference between a future of farming
or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``These negotiators don't have a clue that with a stroke of a
pen they can affect a whole industry,'' said Hammock, who serves on
the presidential Agricultural Trade Advisory Council.
</P>
<P>
   Hammock and her 15-year-old daughter, Sarah, attended a hearing
this year in Winter Haven to discuss the U.S. position on sugar in
the upcoming trade round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them: 'You're not trading away our crop, you're trading
away her future,' `` Hammock said. ``You shouldn't sell out the
America farmer to bankroll the foreign farmer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But while American farmers see danger in the trade talks,
American food manufacturers _ particularly cake, candy and soft
drink companies _ see a golden opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nedelman, a spokesman for the Coalition for Sugar Reform,
an umbrella group of consumer groups, government watchdog groups
and food industries, said he hopes U.S. trade negotiators play the
sugar card wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. is not going to give the U.S. sugar program away, we
hope they will negotiate it away for freer agricultural trade,''
Nedelman said. ``It's impossible for the United States to realize
its agricultural trade goals with the U.S. sugar policy intact.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes sugar so different from other agricultural products
is that the United States is a net importer of sugar. Most other
crops are produced in higher quantities than can be sold
domestically. For those crops to thrive, American farmers need
greater access to foreign markets. That's a top priority of the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, opening the American market to increased sugar
exports is a big priority for other countries and regions, such as
Australia, Brazil and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar is an important issue for us,'' said Paul Morris,
minister counselor for agriculture in the Australian Embassy.
``We'd like to see a total removal or significant (reduction) in
the quota tariff rate.''
</P>
<P>
   While the agriculture community is united going into the talks,
sugar users hope the negotiations will drive a wedge between sugar
growers and other farmers. A recent letter from the sugar users and
sugar refiners addressed to the agriculture community tried to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar users hope a split in the agriculture community will play
out in Congress, which has repeatedly rejected efforts to kill the
sugar program. The program sets limits on imports in order to
preserve a threshold price for domestic sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope they (U.S. trade negotiators) will come back from
Seattle and tell the agriculture community and Congress, 'we're
getting killed,' `` Nedelman said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
