<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2954 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     10-20 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR DWINDLING SUPPLY OF DUMPLINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As closely as I can figure _ using less-than-precise
calculations _ we have about 20 or 10 years left before we will be
completely out of chicken and dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   I have made this evaluation by stopping women, most of whom were
completely unknown to me _ and asking them if they knew how to make
the thick, rich dish.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, which often came after a frightened look, was almost
always the same. They didn't know how to make the dish, but their
mothers did. But, they would quickly add, their mothers didn't make
as good a chicken and dumplings as their grandmothers did.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother makes chicken and dumplings,'' one woman said. ``But
when she wants chicken and dumplings, she goes to my grandmother's
house.''
</P>
<P>
   I have since found that the number of chicken-and-dumpling
recipes is directly proportionate to the number of grandmothers.
When all of today's grandmothers are gone, there will be no more
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken and dumplings will then come only in a can, and our
children will never know that the dish was concocted as a way to
serve a really tough bird, stewed for hours in a roiling broth.
</P>
<P>
   To extend it so it could feed the whole family a couple of
times, the cook then added a dough mixture and called it dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   I have found that some people put vegetables in their chicken
and dumplings, but for the most part, that has always been done the
day after the dish was first served.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any left, the next step would be to add peas and
carrots and a few potatoes and maybe some celery, then cover the
whole thing with biscuits and bake in the oven. Voila, chicken
potpie _ a completely different meal.
</P>
<P>
   There are several variations on chicken and dumplings, and there
is really nothing that is strictly taboo. It is perfectly fine to
use cans of cream of mushroom and cream of chicken soups in the
recipes. Some folks use straight sour cream to add flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes call for chicken bouillon cubes to enrich the
broth. I admit I cheat. Instead of boiling the chicken, I prefer to
cook it in a pressure cooker. It takes less liquid, but the liquid
that's left is rich in flavor and makes a superior broth. Just
refrigerate overnight and remove the separated fat.
</P>
<P>
   Thickening is also a matter of choice. A little of the broth
mixed with flour into a slurry works fine. For just a bit more
taste and to add a little sheen to the dish, a couple of
tablespoons of flour creamed with an equal amount of butter is
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   I can't account for the loss in popularity of chicken and
dumplings. Perhaps the dish will re-emerge someday with a fancier
name _ sort of the way cornmeal mush made a comeback as polenta.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps people just got tired of haggling over whether to use
the puffy, ball-like dumplings or the thin, denser strips. Maybe
there just aren't that many tough old birds that need boiling
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, I'd like to see the dish make a comeback.
Chicken and dumplings is certainly a comfort food. And it is an
easy dish to make. Just ask your grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a couple of simple recipes, offered in the hope of
keeping the dish alive. They were taken from soiled index cards and
anonymous scraps of paper. If you like them, claim them as your
own.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you are scared away by the thought of making dumplings
from scratch, just buy a can of refrigerated biscuits, cut the
biscuits into smaller pieces and drop into boiling broth.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN AND DUMPLINGS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   Filling
</P>
<P>
   1 whole chicken (cut in pieces)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water, or enough to cover chicken in large pot
</P>
<P>
   Dumplings
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons shortening
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Put chicken in large pot and bring to gentle boil. Add salt and
pepper and cook until meat begins to pull away from bones. Remove
meat from broth and set aside to cool. Now is a good time to
prepare dumplings. When chicken cools, shred meat from bone with
fork.
</P>
<P>
   Dumplings:
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, add baking powder, salt and pepper to flour.
Using a pastry blender or large fork, cut in shortening until
mixture resembles cornmeal. Add milk and stir just enough to mix
well. Drop mixture a tablespoon at a time into boiling broth.
</P>
<P>
   Cook dumplings for 10 minutes, then add shredded chicken back to
broth and cook for additional 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 334 calories, 15 grams fat, 23
grams carbohydrates, 24 grams protein, 65 milligrams cholesterol,
973 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN AND DUMPLINGS NO. 2
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 fryer, boiled and boned
</P>
<P>
   1 can cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1 can cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   1 can evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water (or enough to cover chicken)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Boil chicken in water until meat pulls away from bone. Remove
chicken and allow to cool before boning. To broth add soups,
evaporated milk, salt and pepper. Put flour in a bowl and make a
hole in the center. Add enough water to flour to make a stiff
dough. Roll dough out as thin as possible and cut into strips. Drop
strips into boiling broth and cook for 3 to 5 minutes. Add boned
chicken to mixture and cook at slow simmer for another 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 577 calories, 16 grams fat, 71
grams carbohydrates, 34 grams protein, 79 milligrams cholesterol,
919 milligrams sodium, 25 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
