<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     10-20 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECIDING ON A PLACE FOR A HOME OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home offices usually start as a makeshift workstation in a
little-used corner of the house. As the workload increases, so does
the demand for a larger and more efficient office.
</P>
<P>
   Creating an efficient home office requires planning. Before
adding an office to your home, check the local zoning laws to see
if there are any restrictions for a home-based business. Then
evaluate your business operation so you can determine the amount of
work space you need. Depending upon your business, you may need as
many as five separate areas _ computer, production, administrative,
meeting and storage _ to create an efficient office.
</P>
<P>
   If the computer is an important part of your operation, make it
the focal point of your plan and be sure to allow enough space for
this area so you can work comfortably without feeling cramped.
There should be ample space for the computer, keyboard, monitor and
printer and any additional hardware (like a scanner or color
printer) you may add in the future. Also plan for worktables to
hold reference materials that you might use when working at the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   The production area is the place you actually make your product.
For home offices where the entire product _ reports, articles,
spreadsheets _ is generated on the computer, there would be no need
for a separate area. But some businesses require working space for
product drafting, manufacture or assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative area is the space set aside for running the
business -- opening mail, making out invoices, bookkeeping and
making bank deposits. It is the best area to situate office
machines like the copier, fax and answering machines.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, plan for a storage area to hold reference materials,
records and supplies. You may want to divide this area into two
spaces. One area for long- term storage of items that you use
occasionally (this may be away from the immediate work area in the
garage or attic), and another close by the production area for
records and materials that you have to retrieve on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have an idea of the amount of space you need, you can
start looking in your house for possible locations. The most likely
sites for a home office are a spare bedroom, garage, family room,
attic or basement. Each has advantages and disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   A spare bedroom is a good choice because it is a finished room
with electrical outlets and heating fixtures already in place. In
addition, spare bedrooms have windows for light and ventilation.
The spare bedroom may not be a good choice if you have clients
visiting because you will have to bring them through the living
area in the house to get to your office. One solution may be to
install a separate door from the outside directly to the room.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage to using the garage as an office is that it is
away from the rest of the house. The work area will be relatively
isolated with no distractions from the living section. However,
most garages are unfinished. The floor and walls will have to be
insulated, and electrical power and air-conditioning and heating
units will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The family room is often a good choice for an office. It is
already finished and supplied with electrical power, heating and
air-conditioning. In addition, most family rooms are situated away
from the living quarters with a separate entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Although the attic is relatively isolated from the rest of the
household, it is usually accessible only by going through the
living quarters. The major problem with attics is that they are
often very hot in the summer and cold in the winter. Installing
insulation will help, but utility bills are apt to be high. In
addition, attics do not have a lot of working space. Much of the
floor space is under the eaves, so it can only be used as storage
area.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways an unfinished basement is like the garage; it is
away from the living quarters and it needs a finished ceiling,
walls and a floor. It is relatively easy to add additional power
outlets and heating to a basement office because it is near the
main service panel and furnace. The main disadvantage to a basement
location is that it is apt to be cold in the winter and humid in
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have chosen the area, the next step is to design a
functional workstation arrangement on paper. This will be featured
next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
