   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FALN-JUSTICE (Washington) _ In late 1996 the Justice Department
recommended against releasing the 16 Puerto Rican militants who
were offered clemency by President Clinton in August. Then last
month a report from Attorney General Janet Reno said the
nationalist groups they had been aligned with pose an ``ongoing
threat'' to national security. Documents revealing these
assessments are made public by a Senate panel today. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPENDING (Washington) _ President Clinton signs a $99
billion spending bill for housing, veterans and NASA, hailing it as
a sign of cooperation with Congress. Meanwhile, work continues on
remaining spending items as a continuing budget resolution is about
to expire. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Olympic runner Frank Shorter is
among those testifying before a Senate panel hearing evidence about
the potential risks of using performance-enhancing drugs. By ANDREW
BROMAN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-2000 (Washington) _ Elizabeth Dole quits her quest for the
Republican presidential nomination, blaming her departure on her
inability to raise money in the face of the George W. Bush
financial juggernaut. Her departure leaves Steve Forbes and Sen.
John McCain of Arizona as the strongest challengers to Texas Gov.
George W. Bush. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENVIRONMENT (Dallas) _ Following criticism about the
state's environmental record in recent years, Gov. George W. Bush
helps clean up a dirty industrial site with the assistance of the
Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SERIES (Undated) _ The Atlanta Braves have been to the World
Series five times this decade but have won only one world
championship, while the New York Yankees will be going for their
third world championship in four years. Which franchise can claim
to be the ``Team of the `90s?'' They will have a chance to settle
it on the field starting Saturday when the two teams meet in the
final World Series of the 20th century. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBO-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ There is a parallel between the
defeat of the League of Nations favored by President Woodrow Wilson
80 years ago and Bill Clinton's recent loss on the nuclear test ban
treaty. In both instances, the president was a victim of his own
stubbornness as well as the obstructionist tactics of his
Republican opponents. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
