<P>
   A host of other often hotly debated issues, such as Internet
gambling, cyberterrorism, and potential cyberattacks by hostile
foreign powers were scarcely mentioned. The terrorism concerns have
led the Clinton administration to develop a $1.4 billion plan to
monitor the nation's data networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not yet blips on the public's radar screen,'' Doble
said.
</P>
<P>
   The theme that did strike home was the need to better protect
children from exposure to online pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``More generally, many felt that the abundance of pornography on
the Net is an indication of our ethical decline, a sign of what we,
as a nation and as a global community, have come to value,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, most participants opposed imposing an outright ban
on sexually explicit online material. They cited four reasons:
</P>
<P>
   Such materials are protected by constitutional freedom of
speech.
</P>
<P>
   No consensus exists about what constitutes pornography.
</P>
<P>
   The government cannot be trusted to censor wisely or well.
</P>
<P>
   As a worldwide phenomenon, the Web is virtually impossible to
control.
</P>
<P>
   As they deliberated, the forum participants favored the adoption
of improved software filters _ the online equivalent of the
so-called V-chips now being implanted in TV sets that would enable
parents to limit what comes into the home _ without limiting what
is actually online.
</P>
<P>
   Some participants noted that pornographic sites have been known
to use deception to lure people. Thus, a high school student from
Long Island described how classmates seeking information about the
Mars Pathfinder had navigated to a porn site designed to snare
surfers intending to reach NASA's Web page.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that the most computer-literate participants,
including high school students, were among those least shocked that
personal information is available on the Internet, reflecting that
people have to get used to the fact that ``times have changed and
the old rules no longer apply.''
</P>
<P>
   The full 34-page report, entitled, ``Protecting Our Rights: What
Goes on the Internet?,'' may be found online at www.nifi.org.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
