<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW iMACS COME IN DIFFERENT FLAVORS AND COLORS  
 (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bubble-like, blue-and-white iMac was a classic from the day
it was born. Apple has now come up with a born-again iMac that is
so good it even has a glowing halo built into its new design. There
are three new models, ranging in price from $999 to $1,499.
</P>
<P>
   All still suffer from some of the original sins of the first
iMac _ lack of a removable storage drive, a relatively small
15-inch screen, and a clumsy mouse _ but they are redeemed by an
impressive array of advanced features not found on any other home
computer.
</P>
<P>
   While the first iMacs were notable mainly for their all-in-one
packaging and daring color schemes, the underlying technology was
rather mundane. The new models appeal to both sides of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, the new iMacs appear to have had a fanny tuck and
dermabrasion. The backside rides a little higher, and the system is
about an inch shorter front to back. Its skin is now clear instead
of cloudy, so the inner components are all visible through the
plastic.
</P>
<P>
   The base model iMac ($999) will not be widely available for a
few weeks, Apple said. It is based on a 350-megahertz G3 Motorola
processor, which has all the power needed for routine household
computing tasks. Apple asserts that the iMac's processor `toasts'
any Pentium chips made by the Intel Corp. Any such `cross-platform'
chip comparisons are difficult to measure. Nick Stam, technical
director of PC Magazine, said his benchmark tests show the iMac's
G3 being toasted by an Intel Pentium III. Stam said he believes the
400-megahertz G3 chip is comparable to Intel's 500-MHz Celeron
chip.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has boosted the standard system memory to 64 megabytes,
and for the first time there is a convenient expansion hole on the
bottom of the machine that enables owners to easily add, up to 256
megabytes of memory. Each 64 megabyte upgrade costs $140 and the
more you have the better the computer handles things like 3-D games
and video.
</P>
<P>
   It stores 6 gigabytes on its hard drive. A 56K modem and a
high-speed Ethernet port are built in for Internet connections, and
peripherals are attached through a pair of USB ports. An ATI Rage
128 graphics chip makes the iMac a good game machine.
</P>
<P>
   But the most intriguing networking option is in the belly of the
iMac, where Apple has included a slot for an optional $99 Airport
radio network card. Not yet available in stores, the Airport card
will enable the iMac to share files and resources at high speed
with other Airport-equipped Macintoshes without cables or wires, up
to a maximum distance of 150 feet. To share Internet access, one of
the Macintoshes on the wireless network has to be equipped with a
$299 Airport base station.
</P>
<P>
   The radio frequency used by the Airport system apparently
conflicts with a communications system used by the French military,
but Apple says that is not the cause of delays in Airport
availability. An Apple executive said the wireless networking
products would be available in several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This assumes France does not declare war, of course. It would be
an interesting fight. Apple boasts in its advertisements that the
iMac's big brother, the new G4 desktop Macintosh, is so powerful it
is officially classified as a weapon by the State Department.
France, meanwhile, bases some of its military communications on the
same frequency used by millions of cordless phones worldwide. I'm
betting on Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's other innovations with this model include a slot-loading
CD-ROM and a CD audio drive similar to the audio CD players found
on some car dashboards. The CD slot eliminates the rickety
slide-out tray that is familiar to most PC users, and sometimes
confused as a cup-holder.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has also added a pair of hi-fi stereo speakers from Harman
Kardon. They are no match for a set of good external speakers, but
they definitely run sonic rings around the characteristically weak
speakers built into other home PC systems. Harman Kardon plans to
offer a $99 external subwoofer for the iMac next month, which will
enhance the sound quality even more.
</P>
<P>
   The new iMac is also notable for the sounds it does not make.
Apple engineers have eliminated the internal fan used by other PC
makers to keep the computer's circuitry from overheating. Heat
escapes from the iMac instead through a large halo of holes atop
the computer. If the top of the iMac did not slope quite so much it
would be a favorite snoozing spot for cats.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a fan means the iMac is exceptionally quiet when it
is working. In its sleep mode, when the screen goes dark and the
drives spin down, the only indication that it is still drawing
power is the slow, hypnotic pulsing of the green power light.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one model of the original iMac, but Apple has
expanded the line to include two higher-end models. The iMac DV
($1,299) is available in five different fruit colors that are even
fruitier than before because of the clear plastic case. The DV has
all of the features of the base model, plus some extras related to
digital video.
</P>
<P>
   The DV models have a slot-loaded DVD-ROM drive instead of a
CD-ROM drive. DVD discs may some day replace CDs as a way to
distribute music and software, but for now the most novel use of
DVD is digital video, mainly playing prerecorded movies. The DVD
drive also loads software and plays audio discs.
</P>
<P>
   The microprocessor in the DV models is a bit faster, (400 MHz),
and the hard disk is much bigger, (10GB), which is useful for
storing music and video files. There are two Firewire connection
ports, not found on the base model, for digital cameras and other
high-speed peripherals. And the DV models come with iMovie, a
digital video editing program that Apple insists will some day be
as significant as desktop publishing software was to the original
Macintosh almost 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the line, and the model Apple provided for review, is
the iMac DV Special Edition, ($1,499), which comes only in a
gorgeous new silver color scheme that Apple calls ``graphite.'' The
DV Special Edition model has an even bigger hard disk, (13GB), and
even more memory, (128MB).
</P>
<P>
   I watched several movies on the iMac DV SE, and all were plagued
by a tendency for the video and audio to drift out of
synchronization as the movies progressed. The effect was like
watching a poorly dubbed foreign movie. Apple says it has
identified the problem and will issue a software patch on line in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Also, performance of the iMac DVD player suffers significantly
if the user tries to use any other applications. Apple uses
software decoding for playing DVD movies, which saps even the
robust 400-MHz G3 chip and makes basic navigation commands, like
pause and skip chapter, extremely sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   The front-mounted speakers put out a brilliant sound, but at
weak volume for DVD soundtracks even with the controls set to
maximum. Audio CDs, in contrast, belted out the sound loud and
clear.
</P>
<P>
   Those gripes aside, the born-again iMacs are, dollar for dollar,
the best computers Apple has produced in many years. Other PC
makers will be racing to match the iMac's blend of high-tech
features and simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope that they do not try to match Apple's arrogance,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with continuing product shortages of its new Power Mac G4
desktop computers, Apple last week scored another industry first by
announcing a hardware downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Apple had taken tens of thousands of advance orders for three
new G4 models that it had rushed to announce this fall before
making sure it had a reliable supply of microprocessors. When the
chip supply fell short, Apple informed its customers that it was
``reconfiguring'' their orders with slower microprocessors, but
without any price reduction. People who ordered a 500-MHz G4 would
get a 450-MHz model instead, for example, but they would be charged
the original 500-MHz price, Apple said.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with angry protests, Apple simply canceled everyone's
order.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with even angrier protests and threats of boycott,
Apple finally did the right thing this week and agreed to reinstate
the earlier orders and original prices, but only for people who
ordered systems through the Apple Store before Oct. 13. The 500-MHz
G4 systems will not be available until ``early next year,'' Apple
said, so people who ordered them are being offered the 450-MHz
version instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
