<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crowning Glory
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a two-year-old crown of thorns, nearly 18 inches tall,
with lots of leaves and flowers. The catch is they are all on the
top three inches. How do I make it branch out?
</P>
<P>
   A. Crown of thorns (Euphorbia milii) is a spiny succulent that
blooms almost constantly. There are many different selections, with
flowers ranging from brilliant red or pinkish to salmon, yellow or
white. It is perfect for the person who always wants a bit of cheer
around the house. Since yours is flowering and healthy, it is
getting enough bright light and warmth, but when the leaves are
concentrated in a tuft at the top, it is telling you that you are
keeping the soil too dry. Change your watering routine to keep it
evenly moist and you will stimulate it to produce leaves lower down
the stem, lessening that feather-duster appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Let it know you want it to branch by cutting a quarter inch off
the top. Once it knows you don't want a telephone pole, it will
branch just below the pinch and also along the lower part of the
stem. And later on, pinch those new branches a quarter inch, too,
to form a nice, well-grown plant. The scars from pinching will be
minimal because the tissue at the growing ends is soft, and the
thick white sap (which can irritate skin) will coagulate quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Sources crown of thorns selections include Grigsby Cactus
Gardens, 2326-2354 Bella Vista Drive, Vista, Calif., 92084; (760)
727-1323 (catalog is $2) and Louisiana Nursery, 5853 Highway 182,
Opelousas, La. 70570; (318) 948-3696 (catalog is $6).
</P>
<P>
   Dodder Invasion
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our sidewalk tree wells are planted with impatiens. Every
year, one well develops spiderlike thin branches that coil around
the impatiens stems and kind of ``choke'' the plants. They only
come out when the well is planted with flowers. We weed them out
but they grow right back. Do you have a solution to get rid of
these spider plants permanently?
</P>
<P>
   A. Dodder is a nasty annual vine that doesn't even bother to
produce its own chlorophyll. Instead, it parasitizes and robs other
plants of their nutrients. The seeds, probably brought in with the
soil in the tree well, lie dormant for years until an appropriate
host is present. Vinca, chrysanthemums, ivy and impatiens are among
its many victims. At first, dodder grows roots, but these stop
functioning after the plant forms a large, sprawling, tangled
network of thin yellowish or reddish stalks that drapes itself over
and physically joins itself to the impatiens, and begins stealing
food.
</P>
<P>
   Dodder germinates in July, producing small white flowers and
seeds within weeks, so vigilance is crucial. Prevent it from
seeding by removing the dodder, and the impatiens it is wed to, as
soon as you can. By autumn, it has already set and dropped seed,
but you can get the jump on next year's battle. Throw out the
impatiens and then carefully remove the top inch or so of soil and
replace it. That should eliminate most, but maybe not all, of the
dodder seeds. There are no effective control products, so you need
to be ruthless and constantly on the lookout for its first
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   No Magic Potions
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will be moving into a new house in December, and I have a
problem with the landscaping. I'm 76, and I don't want to pay for
large plants or have to wait 20 years for small plants to mature.
Gibberellic acid, the plant growth hormone, is available from a
mail-order nursery that also sells small, inexpensive trees and
shrubs. Would that hormone be the answer to my problem?
</P>
<P>
   A. Sounds logical, and you probably wouldn't be the first person
to be disappointed, but it isn't a magic potion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Davies, an expert in plant hormones at Cornell
University in Ithaca, N.Y., said that gibberelins are plant
hormones that occur naturally and help control growth. Gibberellic
(pronounced jib-er-EL-ic) acid makes some plants grow taller, but
it does so by an unnatural elongation of the cells, not the
production of healthy new tissue. While there has been no research
into its effect on trees, he expects that it would not work at all.
</P>
<P>
   Gibberellins do have uses in horticulture, including in the
testing of dormant seeds to see if they are still viable, but
instant landscaping isn't one of them. Buy medium-size, well-grown
plants you can enjoy watching grow, and let the future take care of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
