<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOW TO MAKE A CLEAN START
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you delete a program from the Start menu in Windows
95? We have America Online 3.0 and 4.0 on the menu but do not use
them anymore since we got AOL 5.0. We tried to right-click on the
names, but the Delete option did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   A. Deleting outdated shortcuts from the Start or Programs menu
is not hard. Click on your Start button, then go to Settings and
click on Taskbar and Start Menu. Once there, click on the Start
Menu Programs tab on the box. Pick Remove and find the name of the
program that you wish to discard on the list. Select the program
name and then click the Remove button.
</P>
<P>
   These actions just remove the program's listing from the Start
Menu. If you think you will not need the older versions of AOL, you
may want to remove them to free up space on your hard drive. A safe
way to do this is with the Add/Remove utility in your computer's
Control Panel.
</P>
<P>
   Macintosh users have been using the Apple Menu for years to do
similar tasks, like opening popular programs with one easy motion.
Some program installers will leave alias files (shortcuts) in the
computer's Apple Menu. Mac users wishing to do a little pruning
just need to open the Apple Menu Items folder in the computer's
System Folder and drag the unwanted program aliases to the Trash.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
