<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-EARTHQUAKES-ART-N     10-20 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EARTHQUAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE PLACES TO SURVEY QUAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER DIZIKES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major earthquakes aren't occurring more frequently now than they
have in the past. It just seems that way, given the recent
earthquakes in Turkey, Greece, Taiwan and Mexico, which have
produced a succession of all-too-familiar images: collapsed
buildings, rescue crews hunting through rubble and victims being
pulled from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the United States have their own reasons for
reflecting upon the subject: Sunday, Oct. 17, for example, was the
10th anniversary of the devastating Loma Prieta earthquake in
Northern California, and it came just one day after a quake shook
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Although earthquakes make compelling television, the Web is a
better place to learn about them. Some earthquake Web sites are a
natural fit for the medium, neatly combining the original purpose
of the Internet (linking scientists together) with the advantages
of the Web (presenting information in a broadly accessible way).
Through them, the public now has easy access to almost
instantaneous updates about earthquakes occurring anywhere in the
world, descriptions of seismic activity in particular regions,
explanations of how faults and plate tectonics work and
retrospective looks at individual earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   A good starting point is the site run by the National Earthquake
Information Center (earthquake.usgs.gov), a division of the U.S.
Geological Survey. The Current Earthquake Information link leads to
the most notable feature of the site: the center's Near Real-Time
Earthquake Bulletin ``Finger'' List, a continually updated list of
the 21 most recent substantial earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   The list gives the epicenter of each earthquake, the time it
occurred and its magnitude. Clicking on any quake produces a set of
relevant maps that highlight the epicenter and indicate the area's
major faults.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, a written description supplements the raw data.
Hours after the tremor that shook Mexico on Sept. 30, for instance,
a posted summary noted that the effects of that powerful jolt, as
big as the Taiwan quake, were diffused partly because the epicenter
was far beneath the earth's surface _ an atypical occurrence for
earthquakes caused by the Cocos plate off Mexico, which have
produced some major disasters in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Certain portions of the earthquake center's site are technical
and intended for seismologists, but the General Earthquake
Information section is meant for the lay reader. Several links
describe how earthquakes are measured. (A 7.0 quake, like the one
that struck Southern California on Saturday, releases 30 times as
much energy as one measuring 6.0, for example.) Others provide a
history of seismology, list major historical earthquakes and
discuss earthquake preparedness. There is also an earthquake
database, searchable by region.
</P>
<P>
   Major earthquakes ``have remained fairly constant throughout
this century,'' the site says, ``and have actually seemed to
decrease in recent years.'' Scientists detect more minor
earthquakes than ever before, it says, but only because more
seismograph stations have been placed around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites also provide a mixture of quake updates and
background information, although they all rely upon the earthquake
center's data to do so. A rare privately run site doing that is
called Seismo-Watch (www.seismo-watch.com).
</P>
<P>
   One attraction of Seismo-Watch is that its Special Earthquake
Reports contain more complete descriptions of major earthquakes
than the earthquake center's site does, even detailing how
residents perceived them. It also produces weekly regional surveys
of seismic activity, with better maps than the center's.
Seismo-Watch is, however, a commercial site, so only some of these
are free.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a university consortium, the Inc. Research
Institutions for Seismology, has developed its own update system
(www.iris.edu), using the NEIC as a source. The Seismic Monitor
link on the home page displays an interactive, real-time global
earthquake map; clicking on it produces lists of earthquakes by
date in the past 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   This format seems cumbersome, but buried beneath the surface is
a surprise: graphic animations illustrating the different types of
faults. (The direct address for this is
www.iris.washington.edu/seismic/events/faults.html.)
</P>
<P>
   The companion site to the public television series ``The Savage
Earth,'' produced by WNET in 1998, also shows how faults move
(www.wnet.org/savageearth/earthquakes/index.html). Through a series
of animated clips, it depicts various types of faults, the
propagation of earthquake waves and even the way the earth's
surface shakes during a quake.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Geological Survey has posted a 10th-anniversary
retrospective (quake.wr.usgs.gov/study/LomaPrietaAnniversary) about
the Loma Prieta quake. It gives a dire warning: ``The next big
earthquake in the San Francisco Bay Area may come sooner than you
think.'' That is hardly reassuring for people with close ties to
the region. But when it happens, at least they will know where to
find a quick and accurate report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
