<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3008 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-HELMS-ENVOYS-$ADV24-C     10-20 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELMS-ENVOYS-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HELMS NO STRANGER TO CONFIRMATION BATTLES
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 24.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., whose opposition to the appointment of Carol
Moseley-Braun as ambassador to New Zealand reportedly stems from a
dispute over the Confederate flag, is no stranger to confirmation
fights.
</P>
<P>
   Helms says he is holding up Senate consideration of
Moseley-Braun, who last year was defeated for re-election as
senator from Illinois, because of character concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nomination comes to the Senate with an ethical cloud
hanging over Ms. Moseley-Braun. (Indeed, I wonder if the president
and his associates even examined her record before submitting it to
the Senate.) Charges of ethical lapses led the voters of Illinois
to determine she was not fit to represent them in the U.S.
Senate,'' Helms said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   However, a dispute between the two of them over the ``stars and
bars'' has been mentioned as a possible reason for Helms's
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   As a senator, Moseley-Braun, who is black, led a successful
effort to reject a Helms amendment that would renew a United
Daughters of the Confederacy patent on an insignia that included
the Confederate flag. According to newspaper accounts, the two
combatants once found themselves in a Senate elevator and Helms
started singing ``Dixie,'' telling a bystander, Sen. Orrin G.
Hatch, R-Utah, ``I'm going to sing 'Dixie' to her until she
cries.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms's action in the nomination has been denounced by the White
House and Moseley-Braun supporters, including Julian Bond, chairman
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is beyond disgraceful _ that this racist reprobate would
dare to block this appointment,'' Bond said. ``In the past,
nominees have been turned down by the Senate because they belonged
to all-white clubs; now this all-white club has turned on the only
black female to have ever gained membership. Is there no shame?''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, told
reporters Wednesday that ``Carol Moseley- Braun is just the latest
victim of increasing sentiment expressed by an increasing number of
Republican senators that I
</P>
<P>
   think is very dangerous for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms has stopped the hoped-for diplomatic careers of previous
ambassador nominees in their tracks and delayed others.
</P>
<P>
   In reverse chronological order, the disappointees include:
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Brian Atwood, President Clinton's choice for ambassador to
Brazil, who on May 18 withdrew his name from consideration, citing
lingering differences with Helms. Atwood, who had been Clinton's
administrator for the U.S. Agency for International Development for
the previous six years, said he suspected Helms was blocking his
nomination because he defied the chairman in keeping AID a separate
agency during last year's reorganization of the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   _ William F. Weld, a former Republican governor of
Massachusetts, who on Sept. 15, 1997, abandoned his bid to become
ambassador to Mexico, ending a five-month-long showdown. Helms, who
refused to hold a confirmation hearings, had accused Weld of being
soft on drugs. He gaveled moderate Senate Republicans into silence
when they attempted to bring up the nomination before his
committee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nineteen ambassadorial nominees whom Helms blocked in 1995 as
leverage to force agreement on legislation to reorganize foreign
policy agencies _ the same reorganization Atwood and others
successfully opposed. Helms released the nominations after
Democrats agreed to procedural moves he had demanded on the
reorganization legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to play hardball, we can play hardball,'' Helms told
reporters several months before he released the nominations. ``They
get no more ambassadors, they don't get any treaties, they don't
get anything. And when they're ready to do business, they can get
in touch with me and we'll work together.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Pastor, whose nomination as ambassador to Panama was
withdrawn by the Clinton administration in 1995 after Helms blocked
it. The North Carolina senator said he was still angry with Pastor,
who served on the National Security Council staff during the Carter
administration, for the role he played in negotiating the treaty to
return sovereignty over the Panama Canal to Panama. He said Pastor
had presided ``over one of the most disastrous and humiliating
periods in the history of U.S. involvement in Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Melissa Wells, whose 1987 appointment by President Reagan as
ambassador to Mozambique, was held up for 15 months because of
Helms's displeasure over Reagan administration's policy toward the
Southeast African nation, at the time governed by a Marxist regime.
She was confirmed after the Senate voted to override Helms's
objections.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
