retirement, developers around the nation are planning gay-only
retirement communities and assisted-care facilities that would
allow aging gays to grow old surrounded by others like them, where
they do not have to hide books, magazines or artwork _ let alone
their partners _ and do not have to live, and ultimately die, amid
lingering condemnation. By Rick Bragg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-SUIT (New York) _ For weeks, in the wake of the
controversial ``Sensation'' exhibit, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has
been talking about seizing control of the Brooklyn Museum of Art by
ousting its board of trustees. But the city's strategy now embraces
a much more drastic solution, which is to evict the museum and its
vast holdings of artwork. City officials acknowledge that this
could result in Brooklyn losing possession of the nation's second
largest art collection _ 1.5 million paintings, sculptures and
decorative objects that took a century to assemble. By David
Barstow.
