<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUIT PRESERVES THAT GO INTO THE BREAD, NOT ON IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loretta Goodfellow of Mansfield, Texas, saw our request for a
strawberry bread made with strawberry preserves instead of the
more-usual frozen strawberries and sent in her version.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I had contacted the people at Smuckers,
thinking they might have such a recipe in their files. They didn't,
but they did send two alternatives recipes.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 loaves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice OR 1/4 teaspoon lemon extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup strawberry preserves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red food coloring
</P>
<P>
   3 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda dissolved in 1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Blend butter, sugar, vanilla, salt and lemon. Beat in eggs, stir
in soda mixture. Fold in rest of ingredients. Put in two greased
loaf pans. Bake at 350 for 35-45 minutes (or until a toothpick
inserted in center comes out cleanly).
</P>
<P>
   This bread freezes nicely. I slice frozen bread into thin slices
and make sandwiches by combining 8 ounces of room-temperature cream
cheese with a little red food coloring (if desired) and strawberry
preserves (enough to make a nice spreading consistency). Spread
between slices and cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per slice for 36 slices without filling:
163 calories, 7 grams fat, 23 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein,
39 milligrams cholesterol, 89 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY BISCUITS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 18
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour, stirred before measuring
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 2/3 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup strawberry preserves
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together flour, baking powder and salt. With pastry blender
or two knives, cut butter into mixture to the consistency of coarse
crumbs. Stir in just enough milk to make a soft dough. Turn dough
out onto a lightly floured board and knead lightly for a few
seconds. Roll dough out to a 1/2-inch thickness. Cut with floured
2-inch cutter. Place biscuits on ungreased baking sheet. Make a
depression in center of each biscuit and fill with about 1/2
teaspoon preserves. Bake 10-12 minutes or until golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per biscuit: 87 calories, 3 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 1 milligram cholesterol, 245
milligrams sodium, 30 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PICTURE-PRETTY BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 loaf
</P>
<P>
   1 cup warm water (105-115 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   1 package active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sweet orange marmalade OR apricot, peach, pear or
strawberry preserves
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour, stirred before measuring
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup nonfat dry milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons wheat germ
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons whole bran
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Measure water into large, warm bowl. Sprinkle in yeast; stir to
dissolve. Stir in marmalade or preserves; let stand 5 minutes.
Combine 1 cup flour with dry milk, wheat germ, bran and salt. Add
to yeast mixture; stir until well-mixed. Stir in oil and remaining
flour to make soft dough. Turn out onto floured board and knead
until smooth and elastic. Place in greased bowl, turn dough over to
grease top. Cover and let rise in warm place, free from drafts,
until doubled in bulk, about 1 hour. Turn out from bowl onto a
board, knead slightly and shape into a ball. Let stand 20 minutes.
Grease a 9-by-5-by-3-inch loaf pan. Shape dough into loaf and place
in prepared pan. Cover and let rise in warm place, free from
drafts, until doubled in bulk, about 45 minutes. Preheat oven to
350 degrees. Bake 50-60 minutes or until bread sounds hollow when
tapped. Turn out onto rack and cool thoroughly before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per slice for 18 slices: 108 calories, 2
grams fat, 20 grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, trace
cholesterol, 139 milligrams sodium, 14 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   REQUEST: Essie Mallard of Fort Worth, Texas, would like a recipe
for fresh apple cake. She misplaced one she had for 20 years that
included chopped apples, dates and oranges.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
