<SLUG> BC-FORTWORTH-FILMFEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH FILM FESTIVAL OPENS AMID SURPRISING FILM FEST BOOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Fort Worth Film Festival begins Thursday, it will fall
within a period of film-festival mania in the Metroplex. The Vistas
Film Festival, a Hispanic-themed fest, concluded Sunday in Dallas.
OutTakes, a gay and lesbian fest, will run Nov. 4-7 at Dallas'
Lakewood Theater. The Deep Ellum Film Festival, which puts the
spotlight on alternative cinema, will run Nov. 11-14 in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Four film festivals in four weeks, and the oldest _ Fort Worth's
_ is celebrating only its second birthday. Even if you're a movie
buff, you might not have been aware that any of these fests
existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of this is just informing folks,'' says Dwight Greene,
vice president and co-founder of the Fort Worth fest. ``When I
mention the Fort Worth Film Festival, they say, `What's that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth film festival is four days of movies ranging from
low-budget independent films looking for a distributor to the movie
classic ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' which is part of a tribute to
Gregory Peck, whose stage show ``A Conversation With Gregory Peck''
will run at the Bass Performance Hall during the festival.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only part of the story. If casual filmgoers have a
mental picture of a festival, it probably comes from media
reporting on the glamour festivals _ Cannes, Sundance, Toronto, New
York and a handful of others. Cannes and Sundance, in particular,
are such celebrity draws that they've been criticized as becoming
as much about glitz as they are about film.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's inaugural Fort Worth fest was probably more
representative of what happens at most of the 1,000 or so film
festivals in the United States. The quality of the films varied
widely, as did the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depended on which show you went to,'' says Greene, who also
works in the Star-Telegram's obituary department. ``We had the star
and director in for a family film called `Lunker Lake,' and not a
single child showed up, even though we showed it on a Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we brought in Tippi Hedren, and it was packed for `The
Birds,' '' Greene says, referring to the Alfred Hitchcock movie and
its lead actress.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is bringing in the right talent. Peck is certainly a
drawing card, although he's not expected to attend any of the
half-dozen Peck movies that the festival is screening. But the
festival is bringing in Mary Badham and Phillip Alford, who played
Peck's children in ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' as well as Brock
Peters, who played the rape defendant in the film.
</P>
<P>
   And on opening night _ a three-picture tribute to James Cagney
that will also feature the unveiling of a Cagney postage stamp _
the fest is bringing in Anne Francis, the fiery actor's former
co-star. Francis' sci-fi classic ``Forbidden Planet'' will also
screen during the fest.
</P>
<P>
   Some fests have come under fire for programming movies that are
available on video or that have aired often on TV. Many of the Peck
titles are airing this week on Turner Classic Movies as part of the
cable channel's own Peck tribute. But Greene finds such criticism
misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people have seen `Roman Holiday' on the big screen,
without the top and bottom cut off?'' Greene asks, referring to
another Peck film on the festival program. ``What we're doing is
showing the classic movies the way they were meant to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Fort Worth fest is just as much about getting new stuff
seen, and last year's program took some heat for that as well.
Greene, a filmmaker who has carted his low-budget speed-freak
thriller ``Ramming Speed'' on the festival circuit, is generous
when it comes to giving raw talent exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say to me, `You're supposed to show the very
best,' '' Greene says. ``But that's not necessarily what our
mission is. There's a lot of raw talent out there that needs to
have its work seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of this year's shorts _ the Martin Scorsese-goes-to-Oz
twistfest ``New Kansas,'' the Shakespeare-on-acid ``Midsummer,''
and Danny DeLoach's rubes-find-a-bomb satire ``New Clear Farm'' _
show a lot of promise.
</P>
<P>
   What this year's festival lacks is a strong premiere. Last
year's kicked off with ``Rushmore,'' a critical favorite that wound
up on some year-end Top 10 lists. Although some people hated the
movie, it was still a major-studio release, months ahead of its
opening date, and it got the festival off to an auspicious start.
</P>
<P>
   This year brings two new studio movies, Fine Line's
``Tumbleweeds'' and ``Man of the Century,'' each of which will be
in theaters in coming weeks. But neither is being billed as an
``event,'' and neither will have appearances by filmmakers or
stars.
</P>
<P>
   The festival has made changes that should help. It has cut back
on weekday-matinee programming, which was poorly attended last
year. A couple of last year's interesting but underappreciated
experiments _ screenings of old two-reel westerns and projecting
movies on the Chisholm Trail Mural wall in Sundance Square _ have
been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Greene worries that with the sudden wealth of festivals, the
North Texas film audience will feel a little overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know that there were this many fests,'' Greene
says. ``But then again, I've had my head buried in the sand,
working on my fest. Maybe other people have got their heads buried,
too, and when they hear the words `film fest,' they just lump them
all together.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
