<HEADLINE>
TEST YOUR LITERARY KNOWLEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you believe that these tests have been overly difficult of
late, here's an author trivia quiz that gives you at least a 50
percent chance of scoring correctly on each question, even if you
only guess. It's true or false. You pass with 12 correct answers
and earn an A with 15 right.
</P>
<P>
   1. Nobel Prize laureate Saul Bellow was born in Chicago. True?
False?
</P>
<P>
   2. Another Nobel awardee, Toni Morrison, was originally named
Chloe Wofford. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   3. James Thurber was also awarded the Nobel Prize in literature.
True? False?
</P>
<P>
   4. Sinclair Lewis was the first American author in the Nobel
rolls. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   5. Sinclair Lewis and William Saroyan both refused to accept
Pulitzer Prizes. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   6. Before he was a published author, Theodore Dreiser composed
the lyrics for a popular song. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   7. William Dean Howells wrote a campaign biography of Abraham
Lincoln. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   8. Nathaniel Hawthorne wrote a campaign biography of Franklin
Pierce. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   9. Upton Sinclair wrote a campaign biography of Woodrow Wilson.
True? False?
</P>
<P>
   10. Before he was president, Woodrow Wilson was a published
author while president of Yale University. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   11. T.S. Eliot and F. Scott Fitzgerald were classmates at
Princeton. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   12. Willa Cather was born in Nebraska. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   13. Joan Didion is married to author John Calvin Batchelor.
True? False?
</P>
<P>
   14. Robert Penn Warren was married to author Eleanor Clark.
True? False?
</P>
<P>
   15. Stephen Crane and Hart Crane were brothers. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   16. Langston Hughes and Dorothy Hughes were brother and sister.
True? False?
</P>
<P>
   17. Helen Hunt Jackson was grandmother to Shirley Jackson. True?
False?
</P>
<P>
   18. Ernest Hemingway was married three times, twice to the same
woman. True? False?
</P>
<P>
   19. William James and Henry James were first cousins. True?
False?
</P>
<P>
   20. Cooperstown, N.Y., is named for James Fenimore Cooper. True?
False?
</P>
<P>
   Quiz answers: 1. False (Canada); 2. True; 3. False; 4. True; 5.
True; 6. True ``(On the Banks of the Wabash):'' 7. True; 8. True;
9. False; 10. False (author, yes, but president of Princeton); 11.
False; 12. False (Virginia); 13. False (John Gregory Dunne); 14.
True; 15. False; 16. False; 17. False; 18. False (four marriages to
four different women); 19. False (brothers); 20. False (named in
honor of the author's father).
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
