<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GIANT-SQUID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEA MONSTER SURFACES ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This month was a historic one for scientists and armchair
daredevils who like their calamari 25 feet long and marinated in
ethanol. The American Museum of Natural History has unveiled in its
Hall of Biodiversity, the first giant squid available for public
viewing in New York City. You can read about it at www.amnh.org, by
clicking on the squid icon.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's squid, believed to be the world's best-preserved
specimen, was caught accidentally in late 1997, by a fishing boat
off New Zealand, where deep-net trawlers have been catching unusual
numbers of the extremely rare animals. It was flash-frozen on the
boat (thank goodness) and flown to New York in June 1998, where it
spent 16 months in a coffin-like container in the museum's research
wing while a special fiberglass viewing tank was being prepared.
</P>
<P>
   When it arrived last year _ all arms, two tentacles, parrotlike
beak and eyes the size of saucers _ Neil Landman, a museum curator
and specialist in invertebrate paleontology, called it
``gorgeous.'' Richard Ellis, author of ``The Search for the Giant
Squid,'' exclaimed, ``This is the greatest event in New York City
squid history.''
</P>
<P>
   The giant squid (genus Architeuthis) was made for overwrought
superlatives. It is the world's largest invertebrate _ it can grow
to more than 50 feet long from tail to tentacle tip _ and one of
biology's biggest mysteries. It was described scientifically only
in the 19th century, and, even today, the truth is obscured by sea
legend and accounts from awestruck sailors. All specimens have been
found either dead or dying, and scientists have little idea what
they do in their deep water habitat, other than get eaten by sperm
whales, their only known predators.
</P>
<P>
   How long do they live and how big do they grow? Just what do
they eat? Do they swim slow or fast, alone or in schools? How far
do they migrate? Can they use their ability to change color to
``talk''? How do they make little squids? No one knows for sure. In
fact, a well-preserved specimen is so important that this one will
be on view for only two years or so; it will then go back upstairs
to the research department. The American Museum's Web site gives an
expert summary of what we do know.
</P>
<P>
   For a longer but entertaining account, complete with travelogue,
the Smithsonian Institution has an online exhibition, ``In Search
of Giant Squid'' (http://seawifs.gsfc.nasa.gov/squid.html). It
reproduces 16th-century drawings of mermen (Norwegians' first guess
at the identity of the creatures that occasionally washed ashore),
as well as dramatic, and sometimes fanciful, 19th-century
engravings of sea battles between squid and ship and squid and
whale.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian has also provided an excerpt from Chapter 18 in
Jules Verne's ``Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea,'' a link to
information about the Disney movie and another link to the entire
book on line. Clicking on the Smithsonian site's reference to Dr.
Clyde F.E. Roper, the curator of the exhibition, produces more
squid information and an additional reward: an excerpt from Chapter
59 of ``Moby-Dick,'' part of which follows:
</P>
<P>
   ``As with a low sucking sound it slowly disappeared again,
Starbuck still gazing at the agitated waters where it had sunk,
with a wild voice exclaimed _ `Almost rather had I seen Moby Dick
and fought him, than to have seen thee, thou white ghost!'
</P>
<P>
   `` `What was it, Sir?' said Flask.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The great live squid, which, they say, few whale-ships ever
beheld, and returned to their ports to tell of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and again this year, Roper made a myth-dispelling
expedition to the underwater Kaikoura Canyon off New Zealand, and
obtained new data about a number of species, including diving
patterns of sperm whales, which the scientists hoped to use as
hound dogs to track their quarry.
</P>
<P>
   The journeys did not accomplish their most ambitious goal, to
photograph a giant squid in its natural habitat. (Scientists do not
know why they can't find them and sperm whales can.)
</P>
<P>
   But the 1999 expedition's journals are available, with
digressions about submersibles and dragon-boat racing, at
http://seawifs.gsfc.nasa.gov/squid99.html. An account of the 1997
expedition is available on the National Geographic's Web site:
www.nationalgeographic.com/features/97/kaikoura/index.html.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
