<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-STONE-GAME-NYT &LR;      10-20 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STONE-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A STONE-MATE, THE PUZZLES BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stone is a brilliant concept, badly executed. The idea is to
sell physical objects that unlock a virtual world. The Web space is
a series of puzzles, and the stone functions as an entry key.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: You buy a small plastic pyramid containing
a stone pendant on a string. The pendant is black and smooth and
heavy and readily absorbs the warmth of your skin. Small silver
symbols are laser-etched onto its surface.
</P>
<P>
   You put on the necklace, find a computer and type in the Web
address on the plastic box. You see a registration screen with six
question marks. Replace the question marks with the symbol sequence
that matches your stone. Once you select the symbols that match
your stone, you're given a password to enter the game's matrix of
interlocking puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   There are 25 symbols to choose from, allowing for hundreds of
billions of sequence combinations, so the odds of randomly typing
in a valid sequence are slim. And even if you did, the system would
probably sniff you out because each symbol sequence is printed only
twice.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one stone in the world that matches yours, and the
site links you to the person who owns it, whether he or she lives
around the block or across the world. It's in your interest to help
each other _ when one person solves a puzzle, both get points.
</P>
<P>
   The other stone owner can help you, and vice versa. And
ultimately, that partner is the only person whose view of The
Stone's virtual space matches your own _ everyone else's view of
the puzzle world is slightly and subtly different.
</P>
<P>
   It's appealing, the idea that someone out there matches you. It
introduces all kinds of romantic ideas about chance and fate. If
you'd taken the box on the right instead of the one on the left,
you'd be linked to someone else. If that other person had been born
a week later, they would have got a different stone for their
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But the events in your life have led you to a certain point in
time and space, and to a certain person. You cannot choose that
person. The universe chooses.
</P>
<P>
   That lends a sense of mystery to the game world. Cyberspace is
full of serendipity _ you randomly bump into people all the time.
But you don't have any formal link to them, and you don't have to
stay with them. And you have no connection to those people in the
real, physical world. But the key to this game is tangible. It is a
bridge between the universe of objects and a universe of hidden
information. That is a very powerful idea.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's a more powerful idea than this game probably
deserves because, unlike the retail mechanism and the social
dynamic, the puzzles are not well designed. They are supposed to be
interrelated, but the references are so esoteric they're almost
useless. The common logic that binds them is extraordinarily
tenuous, and there is no strong defining sensibility or coherent
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   These are the elements that make a collection of puzzles into a
game. In Riven, for instance, the whole world was infused with
Christian gnosticism, and the puzzles formed a recognizable
constellation if you adopted that particular mind-set. The Stone's
constellation doesn't resolve that well. Its overarching structure
is rickety.
</P>
<P>
   On a micro level, it also leaves a lot to be desired. The
puzzles are too hard for the average person to solve. There is
nothing wrong with difficult puzzles, per se, if the challenge is
purely intellectual. But a lot of these puzzles are difficult not
because the logic is complex but because you need to know obscure
factual tidbits before you can even begin to solve them.
</P>
<P>
   The Stone's designers want you to do research on the Internet.
That's a reasonable idea for an online game. But the factual
information is so gratuitously obtuse that the puzzles are
annoying, even after you solve them.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, they're supposed to be tedious so you will be driven
onto the Commons, a threaded discussion board where players cast
about in hopes that someone has found the arcane splinter of
information they need and will nudge them in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   The players are invariably smart people. One gets the sense that
they could devise better puzzles than they are given to solve. The
Stone's publisher, Abject Modernity, should give them the source
code. Instead of presenting 200 tedious problems that don't hang
together, let the players design their own. Let them form puzzle
clusters informed by their own philosophy. Let them collaborate.
Let them build. They will improve the system _ it would be
impossible not to.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of 10,000 people scratching their heads, there would be
1 million people pouring their brain power into the system. And
each of them would have paid $19.99 for a rock on a string.
</P>
<P>
   Just a suggestion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stone, published by Abject Modernity (www.abject.com);
requires version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator or Microsoft Explorer;
$19.99 plus shipping and handling. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
