<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AWARDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL BOOK AWARDS PLAY `WHO'S THAT?'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditionally, there have been a number of literary ``Who's
Who'' award dinners. But the National Book Awards' 50th anniversary
program, scheduled for Nov. 17 to honor 1999's nominees and
winners, might be better described as a ``who's that?'' of
literature.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when Frank McCourt published `` 'Tis,'' Edmund Morris
offered his controversial ``Dutch'' and Susan Faludi followed her
monumental ``Backlash'' with ``Stiffed,'' the nominating committee
of the National Book Foundation has come up with a slate of
nominees that includes just one previous winning author _
biographer Judith Thurman _ and one other previous finalist _ poet
Louise Gluck.
</P>
<P>
   Book critics, let alone casual readers, would be hard-pressed to
have read half the books up for awards. The best-known honoree
during ceremonies at New York's Marriott Marquis Hotel undoubtedly
will be TV talk-show queen Oprah Winfrey, honored for ``influential
contribution to reading and books,'' although none of the nominees
this year copped honors in Oprah's Book Club.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whoever wins in the categories of fiction, nonfiction and
poetry will collect $10,000 and a crystal sculpture. Runners-up win
$1,000 and a bronze medallion.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbnail descriptions of nominees in each category include:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiction:''
</P>
<P>
   ``House of Sand and Fog'' by Andres Dubus III (Norton, $25.95) _
A former colonel in the shah of Iran's army has trouble finding
work in the United States. He ends up in a house whose former
owner, an alcoholic woman, wants it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting'' by Ha Jin (Pantheon, $24) _ The author, a Chinese
exile, spins a tale of a married army doctor and a nurse who fall
in love during the Cultural Revolution. Kirkus Reviews descibes
``Waiting'' as ``a kind of Chinese `Dr. Zhivago.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong,'' by Kent Haruf (Knopf, $24) _ This is an unadorned
story about the people living in a small town on the Colorado
plains. It is distinguished by fabulous dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hummingbird House,'' by Patricia Henley (MacMurray &AMP; Beck,
$22) _ An American midwife staggers through adventures in Nicaragua
and Guatemala, and _ surprise _ discovers love along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Do You Love?'' by Jean Thompson (Harcourt Brace, $23) _
Thompson's collection of short stories focuses on the romantic
traumas of seemingly unlovable men and women who already bear their
share of life's scars.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Haruf should win. ``Plainsong'' is the only book
resonant enough to connect with a variety of readers. But the NBF
likes to confound (last year, they dissed Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in
Full'') and, if they're in the same mood this time around, they may
go for Ha Jin's ``Waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonfiction:''
</P>
<P>
   ``Secrets of the Flesh: A Life of Colette'' by Judith Thurman
(Random House, $30) _ The author won in 1983 for ``The Life of a
Storyteller,'' which was about Isak Dinesen. ``Secrets of the
Flesh'' is anything but dry reading. Still, how many people these
days even know who Colette was, or why they should care? Anyone
who's read ``The Vagabond'' wouldn't have to ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman: An Intimate Geography'' by Natalie Angier (Houghton
Mifflin, $25) _ Angier won a Pulitzer for previous books on
biology. She has been described as someone who ``writes like Walt
Whitman crossed with Erma Bombeck,'' and this time around, Angier
wants everyone to understand exactly how a woman's body works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Hawk Down: A Story of Modern War'' by Mark Bowden
(Atlantic Monthly Press, $24) _ This is an unjustly overlooked
study of the 1993 U.S. military operation in Mogadishu that
resulted in 18 dead American soldiers and subsequent horrifying
film footage of their bodies being dragged through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of World War II'' by John
W. Dower (W.W. Norton, $29.95) _ After the Japanese surrender,
there were no magic buttons to push to restore economic health and
moral starch to the devastated island nation. Dower makes history
read like a gripping novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Places Left Unfinished at the Time of Creation'' by John
Phillip Santos (Viking, $24.95) _ The Mexican-American journalist
traces his family history, providing lots of insights into modern
Hispanic culture along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prediction:'' Dower will probably win, and probably should.
His track record is more impressive than Bowden's. But ``Black Hawk
Down'' is an awfully good book.
</P>
<P>
   Nominated poets include Louise Gluck ``(Vita Nova),'' Ai
``(Vice: New and Selected Poems),'' Clarence Major
``(Configurations),'' Sherod Santos ``(The Pilot Star Elegies)''
and C.K. Williams ``(Repair).''
</P>
<P>
   Children's authors up for awards are Louise Erdrich ``(The
Birchbark House),'' Laurie Halse Anderson ``(Speak),'' Kimberly
Willis Holt ``(When Zachary Beaver Came to Town),'' Polly Horvath
``(The Trolls),'' and Walter Dean Myers ``(Monster).''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3028 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS     10-20 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A capital place to relive Georgia history
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To amuse himself when he was a kid, Jake Goldstein used to jump
from one bale of cotton to another on Wayne Street, the heart of
downtown Milledgeville. The bales were lined up to be taken to five
cotton gins surrounding this Middle Georgia town.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 70-something businessman and property owner admits
the street is different and ``one has to adjust to the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what business owners and restaurateurs are
doing _ changing the old buildings into a healthy mix of shops,
eating establishments and services for visitors and the town's
18,000 citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Epps turned a 1900 Victorian house into Daphne's Gifts on
Greene Street, which features all types of home accessories, china
and artwork. Calvin and Anne Brooks, along with daughters Mystie
Dennard and Merrie Collins, converted a 1921 gas station on East
Hancock into a charming florist shop, Anna Claire's.
</P>
<P>
   But some stores have a long history with the town. The J.C.
Grant Company Jewelers has been selling diamonds, crystal and gifts
in Milledgeville since 1909, while Harrold's Apparel store has
occupied its location for 50 years, and Bayne's Army Store, housed
in a restored 1908 building, has been in business since the early
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with most downtowns, the exodus of stores to malls and
strip centers took its toll on business in the late '60s and early
'70s,'' says Paula Bryan, executive director of the
MainStreet/Downtown Development Authority. ``Now we are trying to
restore the vitality. But Milledgeville is unique. It's anchored by
Georgia College &AMP; State University (1889) and Georgia Military
College (1879) on the old statehouse square. The students, over
4,500, give us a good customer base. Since most of our stores are
locally owned, the owner is always at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Milledgeville _ in Baldwin County _ was founded in 1803 and
included four public squares and 19 streets laid out in
checkerboard fashion. A local wag said one of the reasons people
settled in Milledgeville was that the branch water running off the
Oconee River went well with bourbon _ and politicans.
</P>
<P>
   It was Georgia's capital from 1804 until the designation was
moved to Atlanta in 1868. Named for John Milledge, a Revolutionary
War hero who also was a Georgia governor and U.S. senator, the town
boasts a nationally acclaimed historic district with a variety of
architecture including Federal, Greek Revival and Victorian. The
core shopping district is compact and easily walkable. Plenty of
free parking is available, and while you stroll, you can appreciate
the flowers and planters maintained by ``adopting'' parents in the
community, who give money or volunteer their labor.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday afternoon, Al and Helen Carroll of Chicago
were enjoying the beautiful fall weather and doing a bit of window
shopping. On the advice of friends, the two were checking out
retirement possibilities on nearby Lake Sinclair. ``We are already
drawn to this area after one visit,'' said Helen. ``Everyone is so
friendly, and Milledgeville has so many historical attractions and
shops to see and explore.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the gift shop that best sums up Milledgeville's
hospitality is Strictly Southern. Items range from locally bottled
honey to artwork and books by Southern artists and authors,
including ``Birthflowers of the Landscape'' by Linton Wright
McKnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a down-home kind of shop,'' said co-owner Jean
Babcock. ``We have a good time here. It's not like coming to work.
It's like coming to visit a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From downtown, take I-20 east. Take Exit 51 and
go right on U.S. 441 south. Stay on this road, which changes to
North Columbia Street as you approach Milledgeville. Go into town
and turn left on Hancock Street. Georgia College &AMP; State University
will be on your left. The downtown area is straight ahead. It's
about a two-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most stores are open 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free parking on street; also, parking in lots on
Hancock Street beside the post office and on South Jefferson Street
behind City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: All stores
</P>
<P>
   are accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Located in the Milledgeville-Baldwin County
Convention and Visitors Bureau, 200 W. Hancock St. Also,
restaurants have restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Milledgeville-Baldwin County Convention and
Visitors Bureau, 1-800-653-1804.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amici Italian Cafe. Visitors and locals alike flock to this
brick-walled restaurant, which was once a bookstore, to eat such
Italian specialities as spinach and cheese calzones ($6.50),
eggplant Parmesan ($8) and spaghetti with marinara sauce ($7).
Pizzas are crusty (a 9-inch pie, $6) and toppings (each $1) include
``whatever is in the kitchen.'' 11 a.m.-2 a.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
101 W. Hancock St. 912-452-5003.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buffington's Bar and Grill. Traditional bar food includes
stuffed baked potatoes ($3.75), Buffalo wings ($3.50) and chicken
fingers ($4.75). Also on the menu: salads of all kinds ($5-$6) and
a Fred Flinstone Plate: turkey leg with mashed potatoes and fried
okra ($6.25). 11 a.m.-2 a.m. Mondays-Saturdays.120 W. Hancock St.
912-414-1975.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Puebla's Mexican Restaurant. Hungry shoppers will dive into
chef-recommended specialities of steak ranchero ($8.95), pollo a la
Maxicana (chicken breast with rice and beans, $7.95) or chuleta de
puerco (pork chop with rice and sauteed veggies, $7.25). 11 a.m.-10
p.m. Mondays-Fridays; noon-10 p.m. Saturdays. 112 W. Hancock St.
912-452-1173.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other recommended spots: The Brick for pasta, pizza, salads
and sandwiches ($2.25-$7.25). 11 a.m.-11 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
136 W. Hancock St. 912-452-0089. Brewers Downtown Cafe for
sandwiches, pastas, wraps, fabulous desserts and specialty coffees.
($1.25-$10). 11 a.m.-10 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays. 138 W. Hancock St.
912-452-5966.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Antebellum Inn. This gracious 1890s white Greek Revival
home in the heart of Milledgeville's historic district boasts two
parlors and five bedrooms with all the modern amenities. Rocking
chairs on wraparound porches provide the perfect place to relax
after a day of shopping. For breakfast, innkeepers Debbie Thompson
and Dianne Johnson might fix pecan pancakes, baked apple French
toast or grits made with cream and Gruyere cheese. Rates are
$65-$99. 200 N. Columbia St. 912-453-3993.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mara's Tara Bed &AMP; Breakfast. Scarlett could easily have slept
here. Conveniently located in the historic district, the
white-columned Sanford-Binion-Mara House, circa 1825, has four
air-conditioned/heated rooms with TV and private bath. They are
filled with antiques collected by owner Rowena Mara. Before you
start on a shopping trip, you'll be fortified with Mara's
specialty, Southern spoon bread, as well as fresh fruit, eggs and
bacon or ham. Rates are $65-$75. 330 W. Greene St. 912-453-2732.
</P>
<P>
   Shop Talk
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of shops in downtown Milledgeville:
</P>
<P>
   Antiques/Gifts/Collectibles
</P>
<P>
   Daphne's Gifts on Greene, 236 E. Greene St.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine Antiques, 117 W. Hancock St.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson Street Interiors, 140 N. Jefferson St.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly Southern, 101 S. Wayne St.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel/gifts
</P>
<P>
   Bayne's Army Store, 118 S. Wayne St.
</P>
<P>
   Bridals by Harrold's, 148 W. Hancock St.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill Emporium, 201 S. Wayne St.
</P>
<P>
   Harrold's Fine Women's Apparel, 144 W. Hancock St.
</P>
<P>
   Kids Exchange, 122 S. Wayne St.
</P>
