<TEXT>
<P>
   Can't find it? We did
</P>
<P>
   By Marylin Johnson
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to
help you locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track
down every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the
column will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag.
Write us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at
buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please include your name, the city you live
in and daytime phone number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Lestoil household cleaner. I have found it
occasionally at Drug Emporium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Syresa Pilcher, Covington (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   Another Lestoil request: I am looking for Lestoil, a liquid
cleaner that I could always find in Massachusettes but not here in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laurie Smith, Marietta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Lestoil plea: Harris Teeter in Alpharetta used to
carry Lestoil, the concentrated cleaner. When I went to replace my
supply, it was gone from the shelf. It's the best spot remover, and
now I can't do my laundry without it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Claxton, Alpharetta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a product beloved by many but not widely distributed
by the Clorox Co., since it is not considered a big seller. We
found Lestoil at Publix, 5885 Cumming Highway, Buford
(770-614-8860). It's $2.89 for a 28-ounce bottle. Ask for it at the
special order desk in customer service. If this location is not
convenient, ask your Publix store to order it. The stock number is
89443. Harris Teeter also will order it for you.
</P>
<P>
   According to its fans, Lestoil will clean everything from
floors, walls and kitchen appliances to oil, food and ink stains on
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife is looking for a draft stopper, a weighted item to go
at the base of a door.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wes Anderson, Stockbridge (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: You can be a draft dodger and keep your home toasty warm when
the wind blows. We found two different types of door draft
stoppers. The Vermont Country Store catalog has a 42-inch long
sausage-shaped stopper ($15.95, pictured) covered in a navy or tan
leaf pattern. It's filled with aromatic balsam needles, which makes
you think of a stroll through the woods. The catalog also carries a
30-inch long window draft stopper for $13.95. To order:
1-802-362-8440.
</P>
<P>
   Or, visit the Welcome Home store in the Tanger Outlet Mall in
Locust Grove (770-957-1490).
</P>
<P>
   Their 31-inch-long door draft stoppers ($12.99) are stuffed with
polyester and covered in Christmas-themed tapestry prints.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some years ago, the Faygo soft drink company made a drink
called Rock 'n' Rye. I have looked everywhere and cannot find it.
Do they still make it and where can I buy it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bet Leamon, Marietta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: For 92 years, this Michigan-based company has been producing
a line of soda pops. Although not big sellers outside the state,
these flavored drinks have their fans. Original flavors were fruit
punch, strawberry and grape. Rock 'n' Rye has been around since the
early '20s, when, according to the company ``the vanilla and
seltzer drink became a must with a corned beef sandwich.'' This
pop, so called because of the sound made when opening the bottle,
is available in and around the Michigan area. But you can get a fix
via the Internet. Call up www.faygo.com and order your favorite.
Eight 2-liter bottlers are $10.99 plus shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you help me find a great perfume called Molinard de
Molinard? For over 10 years I've asked department stores and
boutiques but to no avail. Last year I saw it in a street shop in
San Francisco but could not go back to get it. Hopefully I can find
it it in this area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharon Behre, Duluth (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   A: We sniffed out your request and came up with several options.
Neiman Marcus in Lenox Square carries the fragrance (3.3 ounce eau
de toilette, $77.50) and the Sephora stores, in Lenox Square and
Gwinnett Place mall, also stock it (1.68 ouce eau de toilette $50;
the 3.3-ounce, $77.50). Debuting in 1929 from the House of Patou,
Molinard de Molinard is a classic floral fragrance, a soft blend of
jasmine and rose.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You would help us lactose-intolerant people if you could tell
us where Rice Dream Supreme ice cream can be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   _ A. C. Kelley, Decatur (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: You can soon enjoy double dips of Rice Dream Supreme nondairy
desserts in such yummy flavors as cappuccino almond fudge, cherry
chocolate chunk, double expresso bean, peanut butter cup and
pralines 'n' dream. A pint is $2.49 at Return to Eden, 2335
Cheshire Bridge Road N.E. (404-320-Eden). Whole Foods Market, 2111
Briarcliff Road N.E. (404-634-7800) also carries the line in a
variety of flavors. A pint is $2.59; a quart is $3.89. Also, you
can order Rice Dream Supreme through Sevananda Community-Owned
Natural Foods Market, 467 Moreland Ave. N.E. (404-681-2831).
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is this stuff? According to company spokeswoman
Ellen Weiser, it's made from brown rice. A patented process enables
the starches in the rice to convert to natural sugars. No other
sweetner is used in the basic receipe. Some flavors contain grain
malts. But no white sugar, fructose, corn syrups or honey are used.
A half-cup serving of this non-cholesterol cool treat contains
about 150 calories and 6 grams of fat. For more information, visit
the company Web site: www.imaginefoods.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
