<HEADER>
A3030 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-LEE-COMICS-NYT &LR;      10-20 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LEE-COMICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATOR OF MARVEL SUPERHEROES IS READY TO SPIN MORE TALES ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANK HOUSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next to his superheroes, Stan Lee has the most recognizable name
in comic books. The longtime writer and editor for Marvel Comics
helped create, among others, the Fantastic Four, Spider-Man, the
Silver Surfer and the X-Men. In his 60-year career, he has become
perhaps one of the best-read authors in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Lee about his effect on popular culture, not to mention
his influence on the literacy of a couple of generations' worth of
comic-book readers, and his voice takes on a hushed, disbelieving
tone. ``I'm constantly amazed to meet people who grew up reading
these things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at age 76, Lee wants to spin his own Web. In December, his
site (www.stanlee.net) will introduce a new comic-style story
called ``The Seventh Portal,'' Lee's first new series since
assuming the publisher's seat at Marvel in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who is writing all the plot lines for ``The Seventh
Portal,'' said that the five-minute episodes will offer ``the
equivalent of a 10-page comic, but with a lot more detail and a lot
more going on.'' The series is about an international team of beta
testers who are transported through the Internet into another
dimension, where they gain superhero powers and battle the evil
Mongorr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that there are seven portals that lead to other
dimensions,'' Lee explained. ``Mongorr has conquered the other six;
the seventh leads to earth. It's up to these heroes to keep him
from finding it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee made his career in pen and ink, and he hopes his online
comics stimulate renewed interest in the paper kind, too. Comics
publishers could use the boost. Marvel's bankruptcy, in 1996, was
only one symptom of an industrywide slump, which occurred after a
brief speculative boom in the early '90s. Sales are back to where
they were 10 years ago, but most observers agree that comic books
have been hurt _ even supplanted _ by home video games and the
arrival of the Internet, technologies that are aimed squarely at
comics' core audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other media, like video games and the Internet, have become
more compelling than comic books in recent years,'' said Gareb
Shamus, chairman of the comic-book fan magazine Wizard.
</P>
<P>
   Like Slate and Salon, original magazines that first appeared on
the Web, comic books have been quietly developing online since
1996, with artists and writers experimenting with the form in a
variety of ways. Ranging from reproductions to blends of comics and
animation, few have thus far attracted much notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about it is that it's a wide open field,'' said
Buddy Scalera, the online editor of Wizard. ``Nobody has come out
on line with the definitively must-read comic book that everybody
is talking about. If anybody could do it, it probably would be Stan
Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvel's characters landed on America Online in 1996 in a series
of weekly ``Cybercomics,'' and the stories have evolved on the Web
with tales of Spider-Man, Wolverine and several others.
(Cybercomics are also available, after free registration, at
www.marvelzone.com.) New episodes were recently scaled back to a
monthly basis, according to Marvel president and chief executive
Peter Cuneo, and will be tied in more directly with Marvel's
newsstand offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difficulty facing writers and artists of online
comics is recreating the comic book's particular blend of words and
pictures. Utilizing Macromedia's Shockwave software, Marvel's
Cybercomics have the polish of comic books. Readers guide the
action by clicking through word balloons and following panels.
</P>
<P>
   Although complete with animation, sound effects and background
music, the Cybercomics ``are still very much in the comic book or
strip genre,'' Cuneo said. The result is a cross between comics and
animation with effects that are sometimes superfluous but
occasionally interesting.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a panel from ``Doom Control,'' a Marvel series
currently running on Macromedia's Shockwave site
(www.shockwave.com), Dr. Doom's ``mechanism for seizing mental
control'' takes over the roof of the Chrysler Building. The
building juts into the frame at an off-angle, and weird electrical
impulses are seen and heard crackling from the device.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seventh Portal'' promises to move further in the direction
of sophisticated animation, combining aspects of layout with camera
angles and dissolves to simulate motion pictures, Lee said, ``but
with their own superhero comic-book flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Mann, director of the documentary film ``Comic Book
Confidential,'' said he was very interested to see the development
of online art and storytelling. ``The page is completely different
on a computer screen,'' he said. ``You can endlessly scroll down.
The screen itself is a frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann has experimented with rendering comic book panels on line.
The CD-ROM version of ``Comic Book Confidential'' includes
reproductions of seminal comic books, on big pages that can be
moved for different views, as well as background information on
major artists, including Lee and his long-time collaborator, the
late Jack Kirby.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mann said, ``because there are too many bad comics on
line, it is harder to find the good comics.'' One Web-only comic
that has sparked interest within the comics industry is a companion
site to the film ``The Matrix''
(www.whatisthematrix.com/cmp/comicindex.html). Comic-book-style
stories are evolving in the gap between the hit movie and its
planned sequels. Current tales, in prose and comic-book form, are
by writers and artists from Dark Horse, DC and Marvel.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McCloud, a comics creator, theorist and author of
``Understanding Comics,'' a comic book about comic books, has
created several strips on line (www.scottmccloud.com) that explore
the outer reaches of single Web pages, including Choose Your Own
Carl, a reader-guided comic strip that is long on nonlinear
narrative and short on flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comics are a kind of temporal map,'' McCloud said. ``As you
move from one inch to the next, you're actually moving from one
moment to the next. That's a really powerful idea, and a really
simple one.'' It's also one that may not be preserved in online
comics, he said. ``The moment you have broadband, you can have full
animation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Can online comics ever match the vitality that sprang from Lee's
dialogue and Kirby's panels? No matter how close they come, of
course, the industry feels secure with its books. ``A computerized
piece of art is going to appeal to different senses,'' said John
Jackson Miller, editor of Comics Retailer. ``It almost takes you
out of the realm of literature. Getting comics to work on the
screen takes a transformation of what the thing is into something
different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
