<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-CONSERVANCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GARDEN CONSERVANCY AIMS TO SAVE SOMEONE ELSE'S VISION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.H., Mass., Italy)   By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURY, N.H. _ Colette wanted to be buried in her garden with a
sign that said something like, `Here I am, surrounded by le debris
des reves,''' Frank Cabot said, using the French for ``ruin of
dreams.'' Cabot, the founder of the Garden Conservancy, a group
devoted to preserving distinctive American gardens, was musing
about the near impossibility of its mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't easy, trying to sustain the Creator's vision,'' he
said. ``But usually these people are wonderful characters, who have
a coterie of friends. And if those friends can form an ad hoc
charitable company, and hire an inspired horticulturist, they have
a chance of saving the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   The Garden Conservancy has taken on 18 preservation projects
around the country since it began in 1989. It was a 1930s rock
garden at the Fells, a 935-acre estate now known as the John Hay
National Wildlife Refuge, that set off an unusual collaboration
between the conservancy, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the
Forest Society of New Hampshire to not only restore the house and
gardens on the property, but also to use the 700-acre woods as an
education center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, the setting was wonderful,'' Cabot said, recalling
the first time he stood at the top of the rock garden, which
cascades down the slope south of the house and meanders into the
woods as if it had always been there. Lake Sunapee shimmered
through tantalizing breaks in the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed to open up those vistas,'' Cabot said. ``It would
take people who really knew what they were doing to resuscitate
that rock garden. Then Bill Noble came on the scene with 40
volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   William Noble, now the director of preservation projects for the
conservancy, is an inspired horticulturist sensitive to the spirit
of a place. The first ``garden'' he weeded on the Hay estate six
years ago, with a group of hardy volunteers, was the woods that
serve as a meditative entrance to the house and gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The gardeners took out hundreds of sugar maple, red oak and
hemlock seedlings to reveal the reindeer moss under white birches,
the hay-scented ferns beneath the beeches. They left things too,
like dead trees the woodpeckers need for shelter.
</P>
<P>
   When visitors come out of the woods, and into the sunny pasture
that overlooks Lake Sunapee, they have experienced one of the deep
pleasures of a country place. The house, with great-paned windows
open to the views and a wide porch, was built in 1891 by John Hay,
who had been an adviser to Abraham Lincoln and ended up as
secretary of state for Presidents William McKinley and Theodore
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   John Hay, wanting to escape from the Washington summers, bought
this abandoned farmland. He hoped to set up a summer colony for his
friends, similar to the one in Cornish, N.H., where the sculptor
Augustus Saint-Gaudens, the architect Charles Platt and others were
drawn to what reminded them of the Italian lake country. Hay called
his place the Fells, an English word meaning an upland, remote
pasture or moor.
</P>
<P>
   His friends never followed _ though Roosevelt planted a sugar
maple that still stands in the pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Hay was content to plant a few hydrangeas and look at the
lake, and maybe there's a lesson in that,'' Noble said. It was
Hay's son, Clarence, who became the plantsman. As a teen-ager,
Clarence started building his romantic ruins of rock walls,
rhododendrons, climbing roses, a few pergolas and brick walks. He
roamed the woods, observing the native plants and animals. At
Harvard University, he took a course in landscape design with
Frederick Law Olmsted Jr. When he inherited the house at 21, he
hired Italian stone masons to build the walled gardens that his
wife, Alice, wanted for roses, cut flowers and perennials.
</P>
<P>
   But Clarence's triumph was the rock garden, which he started in
1929, using the weathered granite his wife insisted he drag off the
lawn, as well as the flat, lichen-covered stones he found in the
countryside. This was the height of the rock garden fever that
swept through New England from 1910 to 1930, as amateur collectors
competed to grow the rarest, most fragile Alpine plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clarence Hay had been a legendary figure in the rock garden
world,'' Cabot, a rock gardener himself, said. ``And this was a
real amateur rock garden, done by someone who had moved the rocks
himself, who had tried everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Garden historians estimate that two-thirds of America's great
gardens have succumbed to weeds or bulldozers, and Cabot could not
stand to see more disappear. The Garden Conservancy began with four
acres of giant cactuses, succulents and native species that Ruth
Bancroft, now 91, had spent her life creating in Walnut Creek,
Calif. ``I found it a hostile mixture of plants, but it was a great
artistic success,'' said Cabot, who visited with his wife, Ann, in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that as they left the garden, he said to Mrs.
Bancroft, ``I hope your family can carry this on.'' She replied
that her children had neither the interest nor the money. So Mrs.
Cabot, who was on the board of the Nature Conservancy, said,
``Well, Frank, why don't you start a Garden Conservancy?''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Cabot set up a board and scrounged enough money to hire
Antonia Adezio, previously at Wave Hill in the Bronx, as the
executive director. Ten years later, the Garden Conservancy, based
in Cold Spring, N.Y., has 6,000 members and a $1.8 million a year
budget. Its annual Open Days Directory, inspired by the famous
British yellow book of gardens, lists 400 private American gardens
open to the public on certain days. From Oct. 21 through Oct. 24,
the conservancy celebrates its 10th anniversary with a symposium in
Charleston, S.C., examining the American garden.
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy doesn't buy gardens, though it may subsidize
them. It offers technical assistance with a horticulturist who is
sensitive to the garden's original spirit. The conservancy also
helps to develop a board of friends, which can raise money for the
garden and use it as a community resource.
</P>
<P>
   So the question becomes, which gardens are worth saving? Ms.
Adezio sends a committee, led by Marco Polo Stufano, the garden
genius from Wave Hill, around the country to evaluate the gardens.
``Gardens are very personal works of art,'' she continued. ``We
feel you know when you see it.'' Private gardens, unlike botanical
gardens or public parks, are idiosyncratic expressions.
</P>
<P>
   It was their love of the land that prompted Clarence and Alice
Hay to donate 675 acres of woodland to the Society for the
Protection of New Hampshire in 1962. When Clarence died seven years
later, Alice gave the house and gardens to the Fish and Wildlife
Service.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no endangered species in these gardens, and the
federal government had no interest in weeding Alpine plants. ``When
we first started in 1993, the rock garden was overrun with heather
and wild geranium,'' Noble said. As his crew weeded, garden classes
and nature study programs began to grow at the Fells, with the
house increasingly used for education.
</P>
<P>
   The Friends of the John Hay National Wildlife Refuge now runs
the property, with a full-time director, Maggie Stier, and a
full-time gardener, Jeff Good.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Noble like a hen without his chicks. These days he
stands by as others bring to life the ``Hay mix'' _ a lovely
interweaving of mountain cranberry and ferns that Clarence Hay
first encouraged in his rock garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
