<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3035 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VIRTUAL-DASHBOARD     10-20 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIRTUAL-DASHBOARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE WHEEL, AND AT THE MONITOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Iowa)   (af) 
By SAM HOOPER SAMUELS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Information overload is never good. At the wheel of a car, it
can be downright hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   As car and truck makers load up on high-tech features, the
dashboard can sometimes become a bewildering array of buttons,
dials and displays. Sprinkle in emerging technologies like
computers for e-mail and Web access, and suddenly there's a lot of
reading matter for a driver to absorb.
</P>
<P>
   One company wants to solve the problem by adding even more
technology. Diversified Software Industries of Iowa City has
developed a system designed to juggle on-board information so
drivers don't have to.
</P>
<P>
   It's called IVIS, for In-Vehicle Information System. Right now
it exists only in the form of prototypes on desktops and in one
demonstration vehicle. As early as 2001 or 2002, 20,000 to 50,000
luxury cars will be offered for sale with the system, in what will
amount to a large-scale test run.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the system, said Jim Griffin, founder and
president of the company, ``is to consolidate all the different
technology that's coming available in the vehicle now onto a
central display that graphically presents the information.''
</P>
<P>
   A car equipped with the system will have no mechanical dials or
gauges. Instead, the car will have one or two liquid-crystal
displays on the dashboard, ranging in size from 6{ to 11 inches,
measured diagonally, depending on the car manufacturer's
preference. Most of the time, the system will display virtual
reality images of a traditional instrument cluster.
</P>
<P>
   But when the driver needs to consult a map, for example, the
dials and gauges will shrink to the side to make room for a
navigational program. All the information in the car, from the gas
gauge to the driver's address book, will be available on screen.
</P>
<P>
   The control buttons will be mounted on the steering wheel under
the thumbs, making it easy to operate systems like the radio, the
cell phone and air conditioning from one set of controls with
minimal hunting and pecking. Eventually, Griffin said, the buttons
will be all but replaced by a voice activation system.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the system is designed to assign priorities to
information. If a driver is retrieving e-mail and the engine
temperature suddenly rises to a critical level, the system will
interrupt the e-mail and display a vehicle status warning.
</P>
<P>
   All of that opens the door to more complex way to get
information in cars. The system could be loaded with a database of
travel information on CD-ROMs or have a wireless Internet
connection providing real-time updates on traffic, weather and road
conditions (but no Web-surfing capability, for obvious safety
reasons).
</P>
<P>
   The system is also designed to offer motorists a dose of visual
splash by letting them customize their dashboard displays. If one
driver in the family car likes the wood-grain look of a Jaguar but
another prefers futuristic Star Wars graphics, they will be able to
switch configurations at will.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola has put its money on IVIS in two ways. Last month the
company released a product called Mobile GT, a combined hardware
and operating system that will form the platform to run the system.
And Motorola has also bought an interest in Diversified Software
Industries.
</P>
<P>
   The makes and models of the first IVIS-equipped cars remain
undisclosed, but they will be luxury cars. Like the first airbags
and antilock brakes, this system will be tested on affluent car
buyers. The system's makers hope that the technology will become
more widely available as costs come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``In about five years,'' Griffin predicted, ``it's going to be a
pretty standard option on a vehicle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
