r s BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS &LR;      10-20 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS NEED IMPROVEMENT IN THE TALENT DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Watching the San Francisco 49ers in these
dismal dying days of their dynasty, one thing is painfully obvious:
They don't have enough talent.
</P>
<P>
   Where they once had talent by the bushelful, the basket is
nearly empty now. A few of the greats remain, but they're a tad
superannuated and there aren't enough of them to keep the club
forceful. In 1999, the 49ers are like any other team in the league
struggling against the rising tide of mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   It's shocking, actually, how far the 49ers have fallen in such a
short time. It seems like only yesterday they had an offense lousy
with Pro Bowl players like tackles Harris Barton and Steve Wallace,
center Jesse Sapolu, tight end Brent Jones, quarterback Steve Young
and wide receivers Jerry Rice and John Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   On defense they used to have Dana Stubblefield teaming with
Bryant Young for a terrific tandem at defensive tackle, linebacker
Gary Plummer controlling the middle and cornerback Eric Davis
defending the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have an older Steve Young near the end of his career
and Rice trying to regain his form after knee surgery. Oh, could
they use a cornerback like Davis today. Or Ronnie Lott or Eric
Wright or even Tim (the Blanket) McKyer, for heaven's sake.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are needy at so many positions it's tough to decide
where to start. Cornerback might be it, though. It's one of the
four most difficult positions to fill with star quality players,
along with quarterback, left offensive tackle and a pass rushing
defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   During the glut of football games last Sunday, a few television
highlights were shown of Washington Redskins rookie Champ Bailey.
Reaction: So this is what a cornerback looks like.
</P>
<P>
   It's been too long since the 49ers had a quality cornerback, as
evidenced by the club's ranking 29th in pass defense in the league.
Every year it seems there are two or three top cornerbacks
available in the draft. This might be the year to go get one.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the mythical Quarterback of the Future? If Young
never plays again because of repeated concussions, the future is
now. Jeff Garcia might be the finger that shores up the dike but is
he someone to rebuild a once-storied franchise around? Who knows?
What is known is that Garcia is 29 years old and, as of Monday,
weighed 188 pounds. De La Salle has bigger quarterbacks than Jeff
Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got thrown to the wolves with very little practice in our
system,'' coach Steve Mariucci said. ``He's going to get better
every week. His teammates will be more comfortable with him. The
timing and accuracy with the West Coast system takes time. Maybe he
can be a good player in this system. I'm not going to put any undue
pressure on him. There's a chance we could develop him into a
pretty darn good quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Garcia can be the guy who becomes The Man for the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   He's certainly not lacking in confidence or self esteem.
However, the 49ers are long overdue in drafting a quarterback who
has a reasonable chance of developing into a starter in their
system. No matter how hard he worked when he was here, a Belgian
draft horse like Jim Druckenmiller was never going run like a
thoroughbred.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what good is a quarterback if he keeps getting
pounded like a tough steak in a cheap diner? It's too late to
benefit Young, but perhaps the 49ers should target an offensive
tackle with the dimensions of a polar bear and make him their top
pick of Draft 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that teams with studly tackles generally do
well on Sunday. Consider Tony Boselli at Jacksonville, Orlando Pace
at St. Louis, Larry Allen at Dallas, and Ross Verba at Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   There's another, less obvious, reason why the 49ers are humping
along at .500 these days: They don't have much team speed. Lawrence
Phillips might be the fastest player on the roster, but he's not
being given much of a chance to show it. Charlie Garner is quicker
than he is fast.
</P>
<P>
   Midget cornerbacks Darnell Walker and Mark McMillian (who was
cut Tuesday) have good speed but they can't cover receivers taller
than Danny Devito! When none of the fastest four or five players on
an NFL team is a wide receiver, that team is officially classified
as slow. You want speed, quickness and rapid response, not the Pony
Express coming in from Sioux Falls during a snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's too early to concede the season, the 49ers should
be planning for a future that does not include Steve Young or Jerry
Rice. As Mariucci is wont to say, the time is now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
