<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HULSE-SENIORS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PENSION PLANS FACE SCRUTINY FROM CONGRESS, WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group Washington Bureau   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Corporate America thought the uproar over the
newest trend in pension conversions would subside as employees and
lawmakers took a closer look, it miscalculated.
</P>
<P>
   A recent hearing in Congress and events at IBM demonstrated that
companies have a long way to go in selling what they say are the
obvious advantages of cash balance pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and employee groups say the retirement plans amount
to age discrimination because they penalize long-time workers by
reducing benefits they would have received under the traditional
approach.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the plans _ designed to appeal to today's mobile
work force _ pay workers a defined amount based on their average
salary rather than the historic method of tying pension benefits to
higher salaries earned in the final years of service. The
difference in retirement income can be substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., a critic of the new retirement
wrinkle, said the impact on older workers represents the ``dark
side'' of a corporate push to reconfigure pension offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about workers in the prime of their productive
lives,'' said Leahy. ``Workers who have played by the rules, saved
for their kids' college educations, put away money for their
retirement, who wake up one day and read that the rules by which
they have lived their lives have been changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Worker advocates say the conversion push, which could save the
corporations involved millions of dollars, is all the more
aggravating to workers whose benefits would be reduced because it
is coming during an economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that most of their companies are enjoying a period
of unprecedented prosperity and their pension funds are overflowing
with billions of dollars of `surplus' assets,'' said Karen
Ferguson, director of the Pension Rights Center.
</P>
<P>
   Her group contends the conversions are illegal _ a claim
disputed both by the companies and the federal agencies that
regulate pensions. Nonetheless, the hue and cry raised by the
critics is causing members of Congress from both parties and the
Clinton administration to give cash benefit plans a close look.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislation governing them is likely, with several
proposals circulating that would at minimum require companies to
better disclose to workers what they would receive under the old
system compared with the new.
</P>
<P>
   The pension community and the companies believe they are being
unfairly labeled as callous and greedy in the current focus on cash
benefit plans when their goal was mainly to create a pension
package more relevant in today's job climate. They say employees
now stay at a job less than four years, on average, and are not
interested in long-term pensions but want easily understood, easily
transferred benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chambers, a lawyer for the Association of Private Pension
and Welfare Plans, told Congress companies are not making the
switch to save money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather, companies are moving to hybrid designs because these
plans provide the individual accounts, portability and even accrual
pattern that workers are telling companies that they want,'' said
Chambers. He said an actuarial study found that most workers did
better under the cash balance approach.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that pension plans are for the most part voluntary
and that companies could rethink their offerings altogether if
Congress places undue restrictions on them. And he said companies
are making the transition easier on employees though a variety of
initiatives, including allowing workers near retirement to stay in
the existing plan if they choose.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was among those companies. Initially, the computer giant
allowed workers within five years of retirement to retain their old
pensions. But after a revolt by its workers, it extended that
option to thousands more. Critics say the opportunity should be
further expanded to anyone eligible for a pension.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Krueger, a former IBM worker now working with the IBM
Employee Benefits Action Coalition, said she was unable to
determine exactly how much her pension was cut through the
conversion, but that it was hefty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are huge sums of money at stake here as well as the
futures of hundreds of thousand of loyal employees nationwide,''
she told a Senate panel. ``As a society, we need to do what is
fair, what is right and what is just.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
