<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3043 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-RANCH-ECONOMICS20-COX     10-20 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANCH-ECONOMICS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sheep ranchers say they're being fleeced by market
 &HT;    By Marija B. Vader
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEEKER, Colo. _ In 1951, a steer brought $100 a head at a sale
here, and a rancher could buy a new pickup for $1,700.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, though, that steer brings in $500, but the pickup,
integral to ranch operations, costs $38,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices haven't quite kept up,'' said Ginny Love, who ranches
here with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   High land prices, low livestock prices and a flood of imports
make it difficult, if not impossible, for newcomers to break into
the ranching business.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the writing on the wall, some second-generation ranchers
are getting out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just barely made expenses this year,'' said Tom Theos, 80,
who's ranched in the White River Valley of northwest Colorado since
1926 and whose family owns one of the largest tracts of land in Rio
Blanco County.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad and I and my son have been in this business for 80
years and I haven't seen it this bad in my whole life,'' Theos
said. ``My grandson is interested, but what do you tell him? You
just can't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the good old days of sheep ranching here, as many as
60,000 to 70,000 head of sheep grazed on the sweet summer grass in
the White River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that number has dwindled to around 18,000 head.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 8 saw the last of sheep rancher Gus Halandras' 2,200
animals shipped.
</P>
<P>
   Halandras sold his grazing allotment and his sheep to pay off
the bank and get him out of debt.
</P>
<P>
   After 35 years running sheep in Meeker, he's now officially out
of business.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, ``I couldn't maintain the bottom line,'' said the
Meeker native whose father immigrated here from Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up, the day was bright and beautiful, and I said,
`Damn. I rather enjoyed this for the last 60 years,' '' said
Halandras. In Meeker, it costs between $50 and $60 to raise one
sheep. In New Zealand, whose sheep imports are flooding the U.S.
market, ``I understand they can do it for $12 to $15,'' Halandras
said. ``Even with freight, they can undersell us by dollars, not by
pennies.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearing a sheep costs $2.60 a head, but Halandras said he
received about $2.24 a fleece.
</P>
<P>
   It upset Halandras recently when he picked up a magazine that
featured Italian wool suits advertised at $3,800.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that suit are 3 pounds of raw wool. ... I sold my wool this
year for 28 cents a pound,'' Halandras said. ``I had less than a
dollar in that $3,800 suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Halandras' wife, Christine, worked for years, substitute
teaching and, more recently, working as a caterer and
bed-and-breakfast owner.
</P>
<P>
   One night as she prepared a deposit for two weeks' work with her
catering business, Gus did the same after he sold two years' worth
of wool.
</P>
<P>
   ``His deposit was less than mine,'' Christine said. ``How can
you work this hard unless it's a hobby?''
</P>
<P>
   Many ranchers begin their year with a zero balance at the bank,
and as the bills mount over the year _ for items like gasoline,
wages for their help, car payments, predator control, inoculations,
groceries, feed, taxes, grazing fees, sheep shearers, insurance and
household expenses _ ranchers will draw from their line of credit,
like a revolving loan.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during one or two days a year, when ranchers sell their
lambs and their wool, they'll return to the bank and pay off the
line of credit.
</P>
<P>
   If the weather and the market have been kind, they leave the
bank with a little in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they leave with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made about $250,000 off the sale of 3,400 sheep,'' Theos
said. ``We owed the bank $191,000 this fall and just barely paid
them off. Now we have to start borrowing again.''
</P>
<P>
   The balance, he said, went to living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   And, if someone wants to break into the business, high land
prices, skyrocketed by out-of-state owners seeking the wide-open
spaces of the American West, make it impossible, Theos and
Halandras agree.
</P>
<P>
   Like Theos, the Halandrases are now looking to the future
generations to either carry on the ranching tradition or get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something don't change in the next year, we'll be out of
business,'' Theos said. ``We're one of the oldest people around
here running sheep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad. We did everything we could to discourage our kids
from coming back to the ranch, but lo and behold, they're here,''
Christine Halandras said of sons Regas and John, who have some cows
and sheep. ``It's not going to be ranching as Gus and I knew
ranching.''
</P>
<P>
   Marija B. Vader writes for The Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction,
Colo. E-mail: mvader(AT)gjds.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
