r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN20-COX     10-20 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids giggle _ what's the big deal?
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a rainy morning in Georgia and I'm killing some
time in Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport waiting for the
monsoon to slacken so my flight to Toledo, Ohio can take off.
</P>
<P>
   I've already browsed a cosmetic shop in search of a miracle, and
picked up a copy of Martha Grimes's latest Richard Jury mystery.
Now there's nothing left to do but eat.
</P>
<P>
   A little restaurant named the Coach's Corner is right next to my
gate. I suspect it's really a sports bar but since it's too early
for booze or baseball, breakfast is being served. I choose a table
next to the window so I can watch the airplanes not going anywhere
during my meal. With a sigh of relief, I unload two carry-on bags
onto the unused second chair and have a seat. The local morning
news is on the television. The weather guy tells me it's raining.
</P>
<P>
   I tune out and focus on the menu. Order something sensible, I
remind myself. Bran flakes and a sliced banana would be good. Root
out some of that bad cholesterol Doc is always on my case about.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. When pigs fly. I'm south of the hash browns border and I
want grits. Lots of it! Bacon, and a tall baking powder biscuit
loaded with strawberry jam, and don't forget the sweet coffee with
extra cream.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, as I'm working my way into a food coma, the
waitress stops by to ask if I need anything else. All I can do is
shake my head, since my mouth is full of grits. She smiles and
turns to leave, but something on the news has caught her attention.
She jabs a finger toward the screen and, in a drawl sweeter than
the preserves I'm smearing on my biscuit, asks, ``Y'all hear about
that where you live?'' I stop chewing long enough to listen with
her.
</P>
<P>
   It seems a couple of elementary schools in the Atlanta area have
yanked 2,300 textbooks from the classroom because some folks (two
of them, I think) are objecting to a full-page reproduction of a
portrait of George Washington crossing the Delaware. I lean in for
a better look. What's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong river? Is George's hat on crooked? Zippers hadn't been
invented back
</P>
<P>
   then so his couldn't be undone. Well then, what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   About this time the waitress nudges me with the hand that's not
carrying the
</P>
<P>
   decaf, as she unloads on the television screen. ``Dern fools!
Some folks just don't have enough to do,'' she mutters as she
wanders off. Apparently she'd heard the whole story on the
early-early news. I listen.
</P>
<P>
   The issue seems to be a couple of decorative orbs from George's
watch fob that are resting on his right thigh that just might be
misconstrued by a bunch of goofy fifth-graders as his privates.
Yeah, well, what's new? That's what kids do. We did it when I was
in school. It breaks the monotony.
</P>
<P>
   No textbook ever has been written that doesn't have at least one
whispered
</P>
<P>
   must-see page in it. It's kind of like the Land 'O Lakes butter
carton that if you fold it just the right way the Indian
maiden...never mind. Let the kids find their own like we had to.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, a flock of educators have spent weeks painting out
George's orbs so
</P>
<P>
   that no valuable instruction time will be wasted in bringing a
class of giggling kids back to order. Baloney! It'd take about
thirty seconds to point out the absurdity of their
misinterpretation, and if properly applied, could also be a window
to one of those ``learning moments'' teacher-types love to rave
about. Like, Hey guys, get over it. That may be what it looks like
to you, but here's what it really is.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, orbs or no, the Father of our country deserves a little
more
</P>
<P>
   respect than to have his portrait picked apart by a bunch of
grown-ups because they're worried about some ten-year-olds getting
the giggles.
</P>
<P>
   That's what kids do. Too bad the big people have forgotten how.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431; E-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
