<HEADER>
A3047 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VOICE-CHAT-ART(2T     10-20 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VOICE-CHAT-ART(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY'S TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, it seemed like a typical chat room. A list of people
with names like Lizardog and Lisarae appeared on the computer
screen. Curious visitors came and went. Someone had typed a few
words of hello.
</P>
<P>
   Then Lizardog spoke up _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real quiet in here,'' he said, his low gravelly voice
coming through the computer speakers.
</P>
<P>
   His words broke the ice. Soon a man with a British accent chimed
in, followed by the hesitant questions of a middle-aged woman with
a voice that cracked slightly, and the Texas twang of what sounded
like a woman in her 20s.
</P>
<P>
   These were the sounds of the latest in online communication:
voice chat. Instead of typing messages back and forth, people are
talking into their computers and hearing the spoken responses of
others from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, hundreds of thousands of people have
downloaded some version of voice chat software. Some users are
gathering in public chat rooms for free-form conferences, while
others are locking the doors on their chat rooms and having private
conversations. Many people have gravitated toward the technology
for one-to-one talks, using computer speakers and microphones in
much the same way as they would use the telephone, often to avoid
long-distance charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're seeing instant messaging married to voice, to become
close to a real-time conversation,'' said Mark Plakias, a senior
analyst for the Kelsey Group, a research firm that has been
following trends in online communication.
</P>
<P>
   Voice chat blends the sense of personality that comes through a
phone conversation with the anonymity of online chat. Although
people can still hide behind screen names, their voices speak
volumes about their ages and sexes and where they grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Typed communication is still a large part of voice chats, which
gives them a leg up over traditional phone calls, some analysts
say. In most voice chat systems, people who talk to each other
still have the option of typing messages to those in the chat room.
As one person talks to a group, another might type a few words of
encouragement or jot a thought to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have simultaneous public and private conversations,''
said Paul Matteucci, president and chief executive of Hear Me, a
company based in Mountain View, Calif., that develops voice-chat
software. Business executives might open an online conference call
to negotiate a deal, Matteucci said, and someone might want to send
a private instant message to a lawyer. Or a family might be
gathered on line, he said, and two siblings might prod each other
to tell Grandma a story.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce and online education are two other areas in which
voice chatting may have an impact, software developers say. A
person with a question about an online purchase will be able to
talk with a customer-service representative without having to get
on the phone. And a professor can hold a group discussion on line
that sounds like a traditional seminar.
</P>
<P>
   The Saddle Brook, N.J., Police Department is even starting to
use voice-chat software to provide another communication channel
between residents and the police. ``Residents can be anonymous,''
said Len Azzarone, an officer who works in the community service
bureau, ``so they might be a little more comfortable and tell us
how they feel.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, voice chat appears to be catching on fastest in chat
rooms that are just like text-based chat rooms except that they are
designed to handle voices, too. To enter one of these rooms, a
person must download software that places a voice-chat window on
the computer screen. Excite and Hear Me offer their own versions of
voice-chat systems. Another is Firetalk, a program designed by a
company called Multitude, based in South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Like text-based chat rooms, voice rooms can be X-rated. But many
people simply gather on line to tell jokes, try out bird calls,
practice a foreign language, play the guitar or talk sports.
Lizardog and Lisarae say they regularly meet in a Firetalk chat
room to tease each other about the Dallas Cowboys (Lisarae's
favorite football team).
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those who just like to sing. Some of the most
popular online voice chat rooms, in fact, offer online karaoke. On
one recent night, the Karaoke Club at Excite became so crowded that
someone created an overflow room, Karaoke Club 2.
</P>
<P>
   Dizzy-138 was one of the 20 guests in Karaoke Club that night.
She had come to sing ``Faith,'' a song by the alternative-rock band
Limp Bizkit. Her voice had the high pitch and slight shyness of a
teen-ager. Later, she said she was 19, from Montana, and had been
to the Karaoke Club before. ``I like hearing the voices,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others singing that night included a woman who sounded like
Oprah Winfrey and a man with a thick Italian accent. Sometimes a
man named Knowmaad, who has a penchant for John Denver songs, took
the microphone. He spoke with a slow Southern drawl and had a way
of making everyone in the room more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone want to sing?'' he asked, a few minutes after launching
into a version of ``Rocky Mountain High.''
</P>
<P>
   Sending voices over the Internet is a relatively old concept, in
Internet years.
</P>
<P>
   Internet telephony companies have been converting sound into
data packets since the mid 1990s, when people saw the potential for
transmitting voice telephone calls over Internet wires instead of
traditional phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Today, people can make one-to-one calls from a personal computer
to a phone and from a phone to a PC, as long as they have the right
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Internet telephony also occurs from phone to phone: people who
make long-distance calls today may even be using Internet telephony
without knowing it. Many long-distance companies are routing
traffic over the Internet to cut costs, especially for overseas
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Voice-chat systems use the same basic technology as Internet
telephony, but without the telephones. As people found ways to
communicate on their PC's using instant messages, e-mail and chat
rooms, software companies realized that people might be willing to
have spoken conversations using their computers.
</P>
<P>
   On-line game fanatics started the trend. Several of the
companies that provide voice-chat software for general use _ like
Hear Me and Multitude _ once focused entirely on making voice chat
possible for networked games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Several executives of Hear Me, for example, were college friends
who kept in touch by playing networked computer games like
Warbirds, a World War II flight simulation. They often scheduled
telephone conferences before and after their games to tease one
another about their game-playing prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we had an epiphany,'' said Adam Frankl, who founded a
voice-chat company that was recently purchased by Hear Maine ``The
hour we spent planning strategy, and the hour we spent gloating
about it, were as much fun as the half-hour we spent playing. So we
said, Let's do this over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Voice chats do not match the quality of telephone conversations.
Sometimes there are gaps of silence. Voices can be garbled and fade
in and out, making the experience as annoying as talking to someone
on a cell phone with a bad connection.
</P>
<P>
   One recent voice-chat session between two friends in New York
City turned into a stuttering mess, as some words seemed to get
stuck while coming through the speakers. The karaoke session
sounded like an online version of an AM radio station that is not
quite within listening range and riddled with static.
</P>
<P>
   When people first describe a visit to a voice-chat room, they
often compare the experience to a radio call-in show. But there are
subtle differences.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rusanowsky, the play-by-play radio announcer for the San
Jose Sharks professional hockey team, experimented with voice chat
last spring. He moderated a voice-chat session in which people
could log on anywhere in the world and talk to some of the team's
top players.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered, he said, that people were ``a little less
inhibited'' on line. Instead of asking a question that was being
broadcast indiscriminately across the airwaves, guests knew that
their questions were going to be heard only by the 50 to 75 people
in the chat room.
</P>
<P>
   Rusanowsky also liked the combination of voice and text. During
the chats, he requested that people type their questions, which he
said forced them to think about what they were asking. Then he
edited the questions and repeated them to the whole chat room.
</P>
<P>
   Few people are predicting the demise of typed chats as voice
technology becomes more ubiquitous. Sherry Turkle, a professor at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who conducts research on
computers and communications, said she expected that text-based
chats would continue to thrive among people who use text to
organize their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have rediscovered writing on the Internet,
rediscovered the power of the written word,'' Dr. Turkle said.
``There is still going to be a place for the kind of
self-reflective practice that writing has allowed for.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Dr. Turkle said, some people feel the need to
present personas that are different from the images they project in
person, or even through their voices. She said she had once talked
to a woman who said she enjoyed typed chats because she felt
liberated from her voice, which was too high pitched for her own
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our voices reveal us,'' Dr. Turkle said, ``but they don't
always reveal the truth of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the advent of voice on the Internet also has its dark side,
which Rusanowsky encountered when he was moderating the hockey
sessions. Sometimes, he said, ``wise guys'' would come in and yell
obscenities. Fortunately, technical assistants from Hear Me, the
company that set up the voice chat, helped him by kicking out
people who were acting up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets really, really fun at its best,'' said Knowmaad, one
of the karaoke singers, in a text chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``At its worst, it's 15-year-olds singing Britney Spears and
Backstreet Boys over and over again. And at its very worst, it's
kids cursing on line because they can.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be a bit unsettling to parents who do not want their
children innocently logging into a chat room and suddenly hearing
obscenities through the computer speakers, or even being lured into
a conversation with a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have very mixed emotions,'' said Arrazone, of the Saddle
Brook police, who is also a father. ``Hearing is a lot different
than seeing typing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, hearing voices may be safer than reading text,
said Richard H. Dym, vice president of marketing for Tribal Voice,
a software company that creates voice-chat and text-to-voice
software. ``The advantage of voice chat is that you have a much
better idea of who you are talking to,'' Dym said.
</P>
<P>
   In voice chats, for example, it is much easier to determine who
is a child, a man or a woman _ that is, until someone comes up with
voice-masking software.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the cacophony of voices seems entirely genuine. When a
person who called himself Good Guy appeared in the karaoke club, it
became clear right away that he was, in fact, a guy. ``OK, here I
go,'' he said in a low voice.
</P>
<P>
   In the background, visitors could hear strains of the music to
``Straight From the Heart'' by Bryan Adams. Someone yelled, ``Hit
it,'' and Good Guy started to sing.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a sound-enabled computer, a microphone and a speaker
can engage in online voice messages and conversations. There are
many versions of voice-chat software available, ranging from
systems that store and relay one-to-one voice messages to those
that make full chat rooms possible. Some systems are available only
as stand-alone applications that can be downloaded from the
Internet. Others are integrated into traditional text-based chat
systems, like Yahoo Messenger, although they still require
downloading some sort of plug-in. And a small number of systems are
being integrated into Web pages so that visitors to the page can
engage in conversation with others there after they download the
software. In most cases, the systems are free (although the vast
majority work only on Windows machines.) Here are several options.
</P>
<P>
   BEECALL: www.beecall.com _ Lets users send and get voice
messages over the Web. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXCITE: &UR;  &LR; www.excite.com/communities/chat/vo _ Offers
public and private voice chat rooms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIRETALK: &UR;  &LR; www.firetalk.com _ Provides access to public chat
rooms and the ability to conduct a voice conference through a
particular Web site. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEAR ME: www.hearme.com _ Provides voice chat rooms and
voice-chat technology that can be embedded in Web pages. Used in
Yahoo Messenger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET PARTY LINE: www.internetpartyline.com _ Free voice
conferencing for use over both the Web and the telephone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PALTALK: www.paltalk.com _ Enables instant voice-messaging
between two people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POWWOW: www.tribalvoice.com _ Enables instant voice messages to
be sent between two people and also offers text-to-speech
conversions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VISITALK: www.visitalk.com _ Offers voice chat rooms and instant
voice messages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
