<HEADLINE>
BULK BUYING MEETS THE AUCTION BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (af) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For me, the concept of bulk buying has always conjured up images
of cold warehouses filled with shoppers wrestling with mammoth
containers of mayonnaise or struggling toward their cars under the
weight of a pallet of canned green beans.
</P>
<P>
   A new breed of online shopping sites offers a novel twist on
bulk buying, a version that doesn't involve lugging around
six-gallon drums of peanut butter. Sites like Mercata, Accompany
and (scheduled to start next month) Act Big are bringing shoppers
together to form groups to make large-volume purchases on hundreds
of items, like computer equipment and baby supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Although each site operates differently, the principle is the
same: the more shoppers who agree to buy a certain item, the lower
the price goes. For instance, last week at Accompany
(www.accompany.com), the first five shoppers who wanted to buy
Nintendo Gameboy Color could pledge to purchase it for $56.95
apiece. If 10 buyers pledged, the price would drop further.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Accompany's rock-bottom price, $49.95, a minimum of 21
buyers would have had to pledge. Then everyone, even the shoppers
who had signed up back when the price was higher, would have paid
only $49.95.
</P>
<P>
   The caveat? The price may never drop; in fact, on the half-dozen
items I monitored at both sites last week, only one dropped (by
less than $2). And, I had assumed, once I pledged to buy an item, I
was committed to buy.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the risk didn't seem great. The opening prices
(before any bulk discounts) at the Accompany and Mercata sites seem
competitive with other available prices, both off and online. But
there are hidden costs.
</P>
<P>
   Accompany's Gameboy cost an extra $4.99 for shipping and 35
cents for insurance. (Accompany plans to offer free shipping until
the end of the year.) Since Accompany's items are shipped directly
from suppliers, a shopper who lives in a state where a supplier is
located would have to pay sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to try out Mercata (www.mercata.com), which offers
free shipping and ships items from warehouses in Pennsylvania and
Washington, so I could avoid the sales tax, as well. Mercata was
also enticing new shoppers with $50 of credit that could be used to
pay up to half the price of any item. (Mercata also offers some
products at discounted, non-negotiable prices.)
</P>
<P>
   Mercata advertised a 32-inch JVC set (model number 32050, with
all the features my gadget-addicted husband craved) for $744.80,
well below the manufacturer's suggested price of $849.99. And the
price could conceivably go even lower if enough buyers signed on.
Plus, with my new-shopper credits, I could drop the price to
$696.50.
</P>
<P>
   I wavered for three days, returning to the site to check to see
if the price dropped; it never did. I then began to wonder how many
other shoppers like me were out there, unwilling to be the first
ones to take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   I suspected there were quite a few, which was confirmed by
Jonathan Ehrlich, Accompany,'s vice president of marketing, who
said that two kinds of buyers frequent bulk sites: people who
really, really want a specific product and people who want it only
if it's a great deal. The first kind of buyer helps drive down the
price.
</P>
<P>
   If too many of the people who visit the site are like me _
customers who hover but do not commit _ the price will never drop.
The lesson here would seem to be this: unless you're comfortable
with the first, undiscounted price quoted on a bulk site, you
shouldn't pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Restless, I began some comparison shopping. One online merchant,
Intec, advertised a price of $630 and was coincidentally
headquartered in Hicksville, N.Y., near where I live. I phoned
Intech's toll-free number and reached Ken Yokel, the company's
president, who told me that I could avoid shipping costs by picking
up the television at the company's nearby warehouse. Yokel also
offered me an additional 5 percent off the purchase price if I paid
in cash. Total, with sales tax: $647.88.
</P>
<P>
   Smug about finding a good deal, I invited my friend Nancy Bendit
(widely considered the best bargain shopper of her generation)
along to witness my triumph. Instead, she was present as I was
humiliated twice: first when the television would not fit into my
Honda Civic without first being unpacked from the box and later
when I panicked that the hulking monster was bigger than my
cabinet. (``You didn't measure?'' she asked. Nancy carries a tape
measure on her key ring.)
</P>
<P>
   At that point, I realize that I had come full circle, standing
behind a chain link fence in a warehouse, waiting to take delivery
of an unseen item.
</P>
<P>
   It was not, however, a complete defeat for bulk-buying sites.
Unknown to me when I first used Accompany, the site offers Buyer
Flash, which will notify you if the price drops to a certain level.
Mercata will allow hoverers to make conditional bids _ you pledge
to buy an item at a certain price, and if it drops to your price,
you must buy. Otherwise, you don't have to buy.
</P>
<P>
   The larger point about bulk sites, about all online shopping, is
that whether you are shopping online or off, if you start your
search on the Internet, you will be much better informed and can
potentially arm yourself with a target price to use as leverage.
</P>
<P>
   The same JVC model was marked $749 at a P.C. Richards store a
mile from the warehouse; when I told a salesman I could get it
cheaper on the Internet, he dropped the price to $680.89 including
sales tax. Forget the days when shoppers lived in a great
information vacuum, at the mercy of local retailers with limited
selection and confusing pricing policies.
</P>
<P>
   If I sound cocky, it may be because the 32-inch television fit
in my cabinet. With a quarter-inch to spare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
