r e BC-WALKINTHEDOG-REVIEW-T     10-20 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKINTHEDOG-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO MYSTERY THAT MOSLEY IS A SUPERB STORYTELLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walkin' the Dog
</P>
<P>
   by Walter Mosley
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   While walking his two-legged dog, Killer, Socrates Fortlow meets
Lavant Hall, a purple-clad, perfumed thief, rebel and philosopher.
That climactic encounter proves to be a defining moment in the life
of the protagonist of Walter Mosley's latest and best novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walkin' the Dog'' is an elaboration on the themes and
characters Mosely introduced in the tantalizing web of vignettes
``Always Outnumbered, Always Outgunned.'' The shorter work set the
table for the rich repast of the fully developed novel in the same
way that ``Gone Fishin' '' would have whetted the appetite for the
mystery thriller ``Devil in a Blue Dress,'' had the novella been
published first.
</P>
<P>
   Fortlow is angry at the beginning of ``Dog,'' having been kept
awake much of the night by the haunting music of an unseen trumpet
player, whose strains evoked poignant childhood memories and the
dark reflections of an inscrutable aunt on the existential
predicament of black men.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he gets to the supermarket where he works, the
ex-convict and murderer is primed to commit homicide again. Only
the intervention of store manager Marty Ganzalez saves his
immediate supervisor, who chided Fortlow for being late, from
feeling the brunt of the ex-con's pent-up rage.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has been a way of life for Fortlow. He has spent most
of his adult life in prison for a double murder and rape. While a
guest of the Indiana penal system, Fortlow killed repeatedly to
survive. During the nine years he has been out of prison and living
in Watts, Fortlow has constantly had to struggle to keep his rage
on a leash _ like his misnamed dog, Killer, who is really a gentle
beast.
</P>
<P>
   The very fact that Fortlow has saved and taken care of Killer
after the animal had its hind legs destroyed by an automobile
indicates clearly that there is more to him than being a murderer.
So does his surrogate parenting of a street kid named Darryl; his
love for the deceased, philosophical friend Right Burke; his
affection for Iula, his part-time lover; and his rescue of Hoagland
Mars, the destitute wino trumpet player whose bittersweet
intonations have mesmerized him.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a gigantic young mugger assaults him in an alley, an
enormous moral transformation has occurred in Fortlow. Forced to
kill the mugger in self-defense, the man who has killed several
times before and felt no remorse is consumed by guilt.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate evidence of the change in him occurs when,
having decided to kill a cruel and corrupt police officer, he finds
another way to get justice _ a way influenced by his fateful
meeting with Lavant Hall while walking Killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walkin' the Dog'' invites favorable comparison to Ralph
Ellison's ``Invisible Man.'' In fact, Mosely invites that
comparison by having Hall mention Ellison's acclaimed novel.
Socrates Fortlow, like Ellison's protagonist, lives in a makeshift
sleeping and eating space between two buildings.
</P>
<P>
   His is a shadowy existence. And the novel is about his coming
out of those shadows, like Plato's man in the cave, and coping with
reality.
</P>
<P>
   This is Mosely's finest achievement in prose. It has all the
lyricism, lush imagery and humor of his splendid mysteries. But it
transcends them in that it does not depend upon the devices of a
suspense thriller to keep the reader enraptured.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley has crossed the threshold from excellent storytelling
into literature with this work. If the reading public is fortunate,
it has not heard the last of Socrates Fortlow.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a ``Star-Telegram'' columnist and editorial
writer. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
