<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAPAN-ANIMATION-2TAKE     10-20 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ANIMATION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DARKLY MYTHIC WORLD FROM JAPAN ARRIVES IN HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Admirers of Japanese animation, including many of
the leading figures in the American animation community, get a
certain catch in their voices when they mention the name Hayao
Miyazaki, as though describing someone not quite human, like one of
the ghostly forest spirits who populate his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a pure filmmaking standpoint, his staging, his cutting,
his action scenes are some of the best ever put on film, whether
animated or not,'' said John Lasseter, director of ``Toy Story,''
``A Bug's Life'' and the upcoming ``Toy Story 2.'' ``Watching one
of his films is the best medicine when you have writer's block.
When we at Pixar feel that we're beating our heads against the
wall, we go in the screening room and put on a laser disc and watch
one of his films and it's like, whoa, look what he did. It's
inspiration to power through that brick wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Cook and Tony Bancroft, co-directors of the Disney
animated feature ``Mulan,'' said simply in a recent tribute:
``Miyazaki is like a god to us.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's a little disconcerting to find the great man himself,
seated quietly on an outdoor patio at the Four Seasons Hotel, a
pack of cigarettes nearby, his plain dress shirt open at the
collar, a cascade of salt-and-pepper hair hanging across his
forehead and an oblique grin on his face. A translator is nearby,
as are three or four aides (their faces and numbers shift as they
blend in and out of the surrounding tropical foliage) and a handful
of publicists and representatives from Miramax, the company that
will distribute ``Princess Mononoke,'' the legendary animator's
latest work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we must betray the expectations of the audience
in order to keep them,'' Miyazaki said as those around him hung on
every word. ``The best thing is to try to make a movie that you
don't have a clue how to make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Princess Mononoke,'' which opened in Japan in 1997, earned
more than $150 million and became the most popular Japanese film
ever to be released in that country and second only to ``Titanic''
on Japan's all-time box-office list. It was only the latest in a
string of critical and popular successes for Miyazaki, 58.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Miyazaki is largely unknown in the United States, outside of
a small, cultlike following, most likely because until recently his
films could be obtained only with difficulty and only in the
original Japanese. Recent efforts to introduce the films of Studio
Ghibli, the animation company that Miyazaki founded with his
longtime associate, Isao Takahata, in 1985, in English-dubbed
versions have begun to lift the veil.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many admirers are hoping that the release of ``Princess
Mononoke'' with a new English script and a major American
distributor will finally get Miyazaki the wider recognition he
deserves when the film opens Oct. 29 in New York and three other
cities. Wider distribution is to follow Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax certainly has high hopes for the release of this dubbed
``Mononoke'' _ especially with its English-language script by Neil
Gaiman, a novelist and author of adult-oriented comic books and
himself a highly respected figure in the animation world, and the
participation of such actors as Billy Crudup, Claire Danes, Minnie
Driver, Billy Bob Thornton and Gillian Anderson. But no one expects
it to turn into the smash phenomenon that it was in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of Miyazaki's work, it is too long, too sprawling, too
darkly nuanced and, ultimately, too unresolved for that. ``It does
not have the cathartic ending where the hero conquers the villain
and justice wins the day,'' Miyazaki said. ``And it is too long,
more than two hours, which is difficult, no matter how brilliant
you make it. I tried, but the film would not allow me to make it
shorter.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are hopes that the film, even if it is not a
commercial blockbuster, will expand the audience for sophisticated
Japanese animation in the United States and maybe even lure people
into sampling the rest of Miyazaki's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's going to be a commercial success, I don't know
and I don't care,'' Gaiman said. ``I'm just proud of being a part
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaiman said his goal for the ``Mononoke'' script was dialogue
``that didn't sound like Saturday morning cartoons'' and that gave
American audiences as close as possible the richly textured
experience that Japanese audiences had. The challenge was to match
his dialogue to a finished film: he tried to be scrupulous about
writing lines that required no more mouth movements than were in
the movie. Normally, dialogue is recorded before a film is animated
so that the drawings can match the sound, but with a dubbed version
this is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I would come up with a really beautiful line that
would take four or five mouth movements and I would only have
three,'' he sighed. ``So it had to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaiman said he did all of this without meeting the animator.
Indeed, the two did not meet until last month, in New York. ``I
nervously went over and asked him for his autograph,'' Gaiman said.
``He gave me a hug and told me how pleased he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Nervous? Why was he nervous?
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I was terrified,'' Gaiman said. ``Why? Because he is
Miyazaki.''
</P>
<P>
   Miyazaki's work is praised not merely for its scope and
ambitious themes, but also for its filmmaking virtuosity, the way
it subtly expands upon the conventions of live-action filmmaking,
especially in his action scenes (he is particularly famous for his
flying sequences), which rush across the screen with a vertiginous,
roller-coaster intensity.
</P>
<P>
   And there is also the simple issue of artistry. ``People ask me
what my favorite moment is in `Princess Mononoke,' and I tell them
it's when you see a rock and a raindrop hits it, and then another
raindrop and then another and then it's slick with water and it's a
moment of simply unutterable beauty,'' Gaiman said. ``Sometimes the
point of what you are seeing is simply that what you are seeing is
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Miyazaki was born in 1941 to a well-to-do family. His father was
the director of Miyazaki Airplane, which made rudders and wing tips
for Japanese Zero fighters. He remembers making drawing after
drawing of airplanes and battleships as a youth, but when he began
to seriously entertain the idea of becoming an animator he found
that he was clumsy at drawing people.
</P>
<P>
   So he became a political science and economics major at
Gakushuin University, where he also became a Marxist, remaining
there until the late 1980s. In 1957 he saw his first Japanese
animated feature and decided that this was what he wanted to do.
After graduating in 1963, he joined the staff at Toei Doga, the
largest animation studio in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
