<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADDY'S-GIRLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DADDY'S LITTLE GIRL WILL MAKE HER OWN DECISIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you heard about this professional tart, Melissa Joan Hart?
She plays the lead character in the rather wholesome TV show
``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch.'' She was beloved as the sainted,
taintless lead on the Nickelodeon program ``Clarissa Explains It
All.'' Now, however, she has upset her employers and some of her
fans by baring too much of her 23-year-old figure in a suggestive,
underwear-clad manner. Pick up the recent covers of national
magazines ``Maxim'' and ``Bikini,'' and you'll see what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   In response to her employer's outrage, Ms. M.J.H. explained her
actions thusly. ``I'm a pretty open person,'' she told ``USA
Today.'' ``I don't have much to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   One more perusal of said magazines proves her point.
</P>
<P>
   However, let us not let her seemingly airtight explanations
distract us parents from the point at hand. As the responsible
father of a young, impressionable girl, I think it's my duty to
weigh in on the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   My official statement to Ms. M.J.H.: ``You go, girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Space allowing, I would like to add the following: ``You lookin'
`fine,' girl-fren.''
</P>
<P>
   When I issued those sentiments to several female colleagues,
they immediately struck up a fascinating discourse. ``You
contemptible man-pig!'' was the phrase most often bandied. Several
of these lay-philosophers went on to ask that I consider the
following hypothetical: ``What if that were YOUR daughter? Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the fact that this would never happen _ what swimsuit
magazine wants to put on its cover a picture of a 5-year-old
wearing her pink, daisy-covered one-piece, complete with the
headline ``Hart Attack!''? _ I decided I should address the issue
in this column. That way, if you want to yell at me, too, you're
well-informed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   I admit that every father is uncomfortable with the inevitable
transformation of his daughter from innocent, pony-tailed little
girl to full-blown woman. For example, I don't like it that she
will, most likely, one day date boys, because I was a boy, and I
knew many boys; trust me, boys are no good. Even the sweet ones,
the ones who get good grades and floss and pray before bedtime, are
trouble. OK, they're not bad per se, but they become bad when
paired with girls. They lure girls with promises of prom dates and
Backstreet Boys concerts, they belch, they break hearts _ they
flat-out do not add to the collective emotional maturity of our
species. They're like killer bees; you can't stop them, so you must
regretfully learn to live with them.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, it drives me and every father I know crazy that,
someday, sooner than we think, our precious little daughters will
become ... you know ... grown-up type people who ... may have ...
desires that are ... not exactly childlike.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the record, if she wants to be a nun, I'm down with
that. We're Baptists, but I'm sure there are loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I am fully able to separate my paranoia over my
daughter's entrance into womanhood and her right to make big-time
coin showing off the results of the perfect genetic coding her
parents passed on to her. If she were 23 and wanted to flaunt her
Celeste-ness on national magazine covers, I could only hope that
she would be doing it for the right reasons. To financially support
her old man, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Would it make me nuts? Of course. If my creepy friends made
suggestive comments to me, would I knock the holy snot out of them?
You betcha. But does my reaction mean she shouldn't do what she
wants at 23? I hope not. Because if she is forever forbidden from
doing things that will turn me into a
freakazoid-come-on-and-wind-me-up, then she better never bring her
high-school sweetheart over. For when I meet Brad or Jake or Cody,
the captain of the swimming team with perfect teeth who just bought
his own Chrysler with money he made building orphanages who wants
to take my little girl to the movies, I will not see him; I will
see only a ``man-pig.'' And something tells me that might make it
hard for her to get a date. .MDUL/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
