<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Dismissing God''
</P>
<P>
   By D. Bruce Lockerbie
</P>
<P>
   Baker, $15.99
</P>
<P>
   If it seems that the attitude of many authors during the past
100 years has gone from ``Is there a God?'' to ``God? How quaint''
to ``God? You idiot!,'' then D. Bruce Lockerbie has news for you: A
lot of writers do think that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do artists ... seem to need to adopt the stance of a
bantam bully picking a fight with an oversized and reluctant deity
...?'' the Long Island author asks. And further, ``What, if any,
value can the believer find in the art of the unbeliever, the
nonbeliever, the disbeliever?''
</P>
<P>
   Lockerbie surveys the work of more than a dozen prominent
writers, including Emily Dickinson, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Mark
Twain, James Joyce and Ernest Hemingway. The critique is far from
flatly condemnatory, but Lockerbie's comments can bite nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dismissing God'' provides a much-needed viewpoint from an
author who gives evidence of knowing his material. Although one
need not be on campus to benefit from this book, Lockerbie's work
would be a highly appropriate text for a college literature course.
Any takers, faculty?
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``True North''
</P>
<P>
   Twila Paris
</P>
<P>
   Sparrow Records
</P>
<P>
   Twila Paris is without peer in Christian music circles as a
lyricist and vocalist, as her 19-year career, 15 albums, 27 No. 1
songs and numerous awards will attest.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Peacock is one of the best producers in the business,
having worked with the likes of Avalon, Audio Adrenaline and
Margaret Becker.
</P>
<P>
   It follows that a collaboration between the two should yield
something special, and indeed it does.
</P>
<P>
   The Peacock-produced ``True North'' is Paris' first adult
contemporary album in almost three years, and a departure from her
previous pop fare.
</P>
<P>
   Not a radical departure. She hasn't done a Pat Boone and covered
heavy-metal tunes. But from the opening jazzy guitar riffs on ``Run
to You,'' the first song, it's obvious that something's a little
different.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Paris might have been perceived as a pre-eminent
inspirational artist who also did a pretty good job in her forays
into the adult contemporary field. ``True North,'' though, is on a
par with anything done by pop stars such as Amy Grant, Cheri Keaggy
or Cindy Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   That is, the sound is on a par with anyone else's. Paris never
has taken a back seat to anyone when it comes to her lyrics, and
this album is no exception. The title cut refers to a Christian's
moral compass, and how the pull of our culture competes with God's
true north.
</P>
<P>
   Combine Paris' usual outstanding lyrics with a Peacock-produced
pop sound, and the result is an outstanding album.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAPAN-ANIMATION-2NDTA     10-20 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ANIMATION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: in Asia. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually Miyazaki left Toei, first to join another company,
then to try to start his own, all the while building his reputation
as an animator until, in 1984, with ``Nausicaa of the Valley of the
Wind,'' he drew serious international recognition. The story, set
in a future where the world has been poisoned by industrial waste
and other ecological horrors, is about a young girl in the
wilderness fighting giant insects and clashing tribes. (As a
tribute, the makers of the television series ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation'' named one of their alien races Nausicaans.)
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of the film's success, Miyazaki helped found
Studio Ghibli, where except for one brief and unsuccessful attempt
to retire, he has worked ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nausicaa'' was followed in 1986 by ``Laputa: The Castle in the
Sky,'' a science-fiction adventure with some stunning action
sequences. Then, in 1986, he released ``My Neighbor Totoro,'' about
a pair of Japanese children who move to the countryside when their
mother falls ill ( Miyazaki's own mother was bedridden for nine
years) and who discover a world of forest spirits. His 1989
action-adventure, ``Kiki's Delivery Service,'' was the biggest box
office hit of the year in Japan, but an even bigger success was
1992's ``Porco Rosso,'' a strange adventure about a biplane pilot
with the face of a pig ( Miyazaki often draws himself with a pig's
face) who battles smugglers in the skies over the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   And then ``Princess Mononoke'' in 1997. A sprawling adventure
that runs for more than two hours, it is Miyazaki's first Japanese
period piece, set during the Muromachi period (1392-1573) and
drawing on the era's folk tales, though its central characters are
outcasts and working people rather than the samurai and village
elders that normally populate such stories. The film's hero is a
young prince forced into exile who comes to the edge of a
wilderness where a fortresslike community of iron forgers is in
conflict with the aging animal spirits in the surrounding forest.
There, he meets Mononoke, a wild-child who lives with the animal
spirits and is a kind of echo of the young girl in ``Nausicaa.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, the animator said, it was he who resisted the idea of
allowing someone to write an English script for a dubbed version.
He was not convinced that the film's strong Japanese elements would
translate for American audiences. ``All I have is a vague sense of
the lives and dreams that American children have,'' he said. he was
also uncertain that young American audiences, accustomed to lighter
fare, would be willing to embrace a film that is, at its deepest
level, somewhat despairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you are very genuine in doing films for young
children, you must aim for their heads, not deciding for them what
will be too much for them to handle,'' Miyazaki said. ``What we
found was that the children actually understood the movie and what
we were trying to say more than the adults.''
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, he said, ``Mononoke'' was never sold as a children's
film, though he envisioned his ideal audience as anyone over the
age of 10. The downbeat tone is a mirror of the world children
actually face, he said. ``I wanted to be honest with the young
audience, to tell them that human society is not fundamentally
blessed,'' he said. ``I do this not out of a desire to reassure
children, just to say that this is the world that we all live in,
children and adult, that we share this despair.''
</P>
<P>
   That oblique smile again.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes American audiences will embrace ``Mononoke'' and,
perhaps, develop an appetite for more sophisticated animation.
``But you know, I hope the same thing for Japanese audiences,'' he
said. Bad animation is a problem the world over, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why is that? He shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many animators making junk,'' he said. ``And too
many people who want to see junk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
