A3073 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-VIDEO-GAMES-TEX     10-20 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO SKATER IS A WHEEL DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skateboarding without all the scrapes, bruises, bloodied elbows
and police tickets _ music to Mom's ears.
</P>
<P>
   That's what ya get with Tony Hawk's Pro Skater (Activision for
Sony PlayStation, $40, age 13 and up), not the first but definitely
one of the best skateboarding video games.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the top skateboarders from around the country _ I didn't
know there was such a thing as a national ``top skateboarder,''
either _ are featured, complete with their signature moves, such as
Tony Hawk and Rune Glifberg's vertical-skateboarding flip-flop
jumps, which'll make your knees hurt just watching.
</P>
<P>
   Gamers can compete or skate around different environments. Every
skateboarder's dream comes true on one level that allows the player
to burn rubber all over the hood of a police car.
</P>
<P>
   The game is rated age 13 and up, not for violence or close-ups
of skinned shins but for coarse language _ we dock it a star for
stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   Education and tearing stuff up have never mingled so well as
they do on Construction Zone (Mattel Media, $40, age 5 and up), a
really cool game for kids that lets 'em drive around in those big
yellow Caterpillars.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a great idea: Players climb aboard one of six
Caterpillars to take on a series of missions, ranging from
demolishing an unsafe building to repairing a busted pipe below the
city streets (cars are honking at ya and stuff, too) to clearing
rocks from farmland.
</P>
<P>
   Construction's main goal is to teach young gamers how to follow
directions _ but that doesn't mean it's just a kid's game. The
graphics are realistic enough and the game play challenging enough
to interest gamers of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   They've rereleased and repackaged Donkey Kong, Pac Man and
Asteroids. Wonder what took 'em so long to get around to Space
Invaders. More like it: Wonder why they even bothered.
</P>
<P>
   Activision's version of a game that really wasn't all that great
to begin with is, naturally, a stinker. Space Invaders (Activision
for PlayStation, $30, all ages) is basically the same game with a
new face: better graphics (well, how could you do worse than the
original?), a few added features (new ``worlds'' and power-ups or
some such) and multiplayer options. Oh, yippie _ I can play with a
friend!
</P>
<P>
   And guess what the ``hidden'' level is? Yep, the original
version, which, depressingly enough, is a lot better than the new
one. And that's not saying a whole lot.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
