<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Oct. 21, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the wind ceased on the island of Antigua shortly
after reaching a speed of 102 mph as the eye of hurricane Jose
passed overhead. Thursday, Jose will grind toward the northwest,
tracking just to the north of Puerto Rico. This will bring squalls
of heavy rain and high surf to the island during a portion of
Thursday. A vigorous southwest to northeast flow in the jet stream
will cause the storm to eventually veer toward the north and
northeast, sparing the U.S. East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather will cover much of the nation Thursday, though
scattered showers and spotty thunderstorms will surround a
stationary front stretching from the Gulf of Mexico to near the
southern Middle Atlantic Coast. A few of the showers will be heavy,
which may lead to local flooding across the Florida peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Sinking air currents associated with high pressure will bring
abundant sunshine to the Northeast. After a cool start, afternoon
readings will rebound toward seasonal levels. Farther west, dry,
gusty winds from the southwest will direct very mild air into the
western Great Lakes and central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Potent low pressure will track near Lake Superior Thursday,
causing gusty winds from the northwest to buffet the northeast
Plains and upper Mississippi Valley. Local gusts near 50 mph are
possible over northern Minnesota and in the eastern Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   A stationary high-pressure system at the surface and aloft will
continue to promote mainly sunny and very warm weather across the
West. Gentle onshore breezes will bring patchy clouds to the
northern California and Oregon coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Kona Low
</P>
<P>
   High surf battered the northern shores of Hawaii the past few
days with crashing waves as high as 12 feet. Large swells were
generated by ocean-churning winds associated with a low-pressure
system about 600 miles northwest of Kauai. This low-pressure
system, called a Kona low by local meteorologists, also helped to
erase the faithful trade winds which typically blow from the
northeast. Instead, winds from the south spread over the islands,
bringing increasingly humid air which fueled a spate of showers and
thunderstorms. The temperature at Honolulu only reached 77 degrees
on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
