<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3079 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SMALL-CHURCHES-TEX     10-20 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-CHURCHES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGER IS NOT NECESSARILY BETTER, CHURCH MEMBERS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the pulpit, the Rev. Ronnie Reese can see the people
throughout the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Reese leads the Beacon Baptist Church in Haltom City, Texas, a
flock that averages a little more than 100 for Sunday services. He
knows the members of his congregation by name and he notices when
they are not sitting in the pews.
</P>
<P>
   When they're sick, he visits them. When they are troubled, he
consoles them. When they need inspiration, he preaches to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main characteristic about this church is that it's like a
family,'' he said. ``It's very caring. It's very loving.''
</P>
<P>
   In the age of the megachurch, the corporate merger and
international communications, small has not lost its charm for some
churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the small-church faithful arrive weekly in clumps of 30
to 100, seeking close personal relationships with the Lord and with
the people next to them. For most, the church congregation _ all of
it _ is family.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a small church, you have a feeling of so much support
around you,'' said Ray Springer, a deacon at Beacon Baptist. ``You
are never alone when the Lord is with you, but when you have
friends right next to you, it is a big lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Brick for brick, most churches in the United States look more
like Beacon Baptist than like Fellowship Church in Grapevine,
Texas, which attracts thousands to its services. But sheer size
often makes the megachurch the most noticeable to the passing
motorist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big churches are the big churches on the block,'' said Bryan
Feille, professor of pastoral ministry at Texas Christian
University's Brite Divinity School in Fort Worth. ``But well into
this century, most of the churches have been small churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at the end of this century, the median-size religious
congregation has about 75 regularly participating adults, according
to data collected in 1998 for the ongoing National Congregations
Study, funded by the Lilly Endowment. Only about 10 percent of
congregations have more than 350 regularly participating adults,
said Mark Chaves, a sociologist at the University of Arizona in
Tucson, Ariz., and the study's principal investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Although most congregations are small, the majority of people
attend congregations of 400 or more, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic thing is that small congregations do a lot less than
big congregations do,'' said Chaves, who will publish results of
the study this year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, congregations of 350 or more perform 85 percent of
the social services that religious organizations provide, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Internally, large churches have activities that vary from drama
groups to youth mission trips _ programs that appeal to young
families in particular, Feille said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger people are accustomed to being in large institutions
that prize quality,'' he said. ``People today tend to be more
consumers when they shop for the needs for their families.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are still plenty who prize the characteristics of
small churches. And there are some notable characteristics, Feille
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the pastor of a small congregation is accessible to
all members and is often considered more of a ``family chaplain
than a leader,'' Feille said.
</P>
<P>
   In many instances, the church has a bi-vocational pastor, such
as Mount Horuhm Missionary Baptist Church in Grapevine, near Fort
Worth. The minister there, Richard Montgomery, is also a
transportation supervisor with the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, church members value their friendships more than
they prize the number of Bible study groups or youth programs
offered, Feille said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a key to the church,'' said Chris Hughes, pastor
of Covenant United Methodist Church in Arlington, a Fort Worth
suburb. ``That's part of the family feel. It's like this is their
house. You just walk in.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the manpower,'' said Ralph Evans, chairman of
the administrative board of White's Chapel United Methodist Church
in Southlake, a Fort Worth suburb. ``You don't have the facilities.
You don't have the infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans is acquainted with both the big and small church.
</P>
<P>
   Since it began holding services in the 1870s, White's Chapel had
traditionally been small, Evans said. When he joined the church in
1970, between 35 and 65 people attended services, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very intimate, very nice,'' Evans said. ``It filled the
needs of a lot of people. But basically, your worship service was
all that you had.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, when Southlake began to grow, so did White's
Chapel. Now the church counts about 2,800 members and draws about
1,900 for weekly services, senior Pastor John McKellar said.
</P>
<P>
   The church also holds numerous Bible studies, supports youth
mission programs and donates time and money to feed the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things we are able to offer to people
because of more members and more pastors,'' said McKellar, who
oversees five pastors.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting young families often requires small churches to
provide some of these services, pastors say.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to attract the families that travel to the large,
predominantly African-American congregations in Fort Worth or
Dallas, Montgomery and the congregation at Mount Horuhm are
planning to add classrooms and nurseries onto their building,
Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the membership of Beacon Baptist Church in Haltom
City recently added classrooms in an effort to reach out to young
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that if we don't, we will lose everything,''
Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are trying to attract young members, Reese and
other pastors of small churches say they do not count success by
the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives a false indication of success if you are going to
look at size,'' Reese said. ``... If you build a church on the word
of God and preach it, it's never going to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
