<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FALUDI-MEN-2TAKES(TRI     10-20 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALUDI-MEN-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME WITH SUSAN FALUDI  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla.)   By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's almost midnight in the Hollywood Hills. At a
neighborhood bar with a disco ball and gaudy red drapes, one of the
regulars is sitting with her boyfriend nursing her thrice-weekly
chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   She is on first-name terms with the bartender, Bob, who knows
what she drinks. ``I would come back after two hours of prayer with
the Promise Keepers, and I was ready for a bar,'' says the patron,
Susan Faludi, referring to the soul-searching Christian men's
movement profiled in her new book, ``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the
American Man'' (William Morrow &AMP; Co.).
</P>
<P>
   It was here, near the cottage they share, that Ms. Faludi, 40,
and Russ Rymer, her 47-year-old boyfriend, hashed out ideas on bar
napkins that would eventually become ``Stiffed,'' her 608-page
listening tour through the postwar American male psyche. In the
book, a sprawling look at men in crisis, Ms. Faludi examines a web
of social expectations and shifting values _ millennial fault lines
_ that she feels have trapped men.
</P>
<P>
   She dedicates the book to Rymer, a critically acclaimed writer
whose own book ``American Beach,'' a chronicle of four generations
of a wealthy black family, came out nine months before hers. (``It
was shorter,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   If it is strange being Susan Faludi _ whose willingness to take
on the big ones, from antifeminism to her current focus on men
adrift, has made her a human lightning rod _ it may be stranger to
be Rymer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interviewing someone the other day who said, `My God,
you're living with that feminist!' '' he said, clearly amused.
``Then he said, `Do the words John Wayne Bobbitt mean anything to
you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Faludi is aware of the cartoon caricature of herself _
a sort of Faludi De Vil _ she considers Rymer to be a model
``evolved'' male, one who combines old-fashioned know-how with
new-fashioned values, a type largely missing from her book. The two
share many things: two cats, a 1947 house and a passion for social
justice.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that Rymer does not consider himself ``stiffed'' by
society or women or his father. Perhaps that is why he feels
comfortable cooking, building shelves and being, as he puts it, in
charge of the ``physical plant.''
</P>
<P>
   They moved to Los Angeles in 1993, he from Fernandina Beach,
Fla., and she from Palo Alto, Calif., where she had a journalism
fellowship at Stanford University after winning a Pulitzer Prize
for her reporting in The Wall Street Journal and writing
``Backlash: The Undeclared War Against American Women,'' her
best-selling 1991 manifesto about the deliberate undermining of
women's advances in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   They met in San Francisco in 1992 after being introduced by a
mutual editor. At the time Ms. Faludi happened to be on the cover
of Time. ``It occurred to me to turn around and go home,'' Rymer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Faludi added, ``It wasn't a very flattering picture,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   As serious as they are, they have a comfortable comic repartee;
he is outgoing, she is soft-spoken, even demure.
</P>
<P>
   Their house is uphill from the bar, on the street where aliens
tried to change humans into pod people in ``Invasion of the Body
Snatchers,'' a lush and twisting Eden where coyotes can be spotted
skulking past the bougainvillea.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Stiffed,'' Ms. Faludi describes an ``ornamental culture''
in which men have been duped into obsessing about consumerist
trappings and cover-boy appearances the way women once did. There
is little ornamental culture in her home, a spare, clean space with
conservative sofas and paintings of industrial and street scenes
rented from the Los Angeles County Art Museum. The spareness is
intentional, because, she said, ``I live more in my head.'' He
added: ``Our work is so cluttered that we're cluttered internally.
It would drive us crazy to be in a Victorian drawing room with
fringes.''
</P>
<P>
   Her office is larger than his, no-nonsense, with a
nouveau-Mission desk and pine bookshelves he made for her. It is
decorated with rousing artifacts from her ``Stiffed'' odyssey,
among them a press pass from the Million Man March and an
anti-Shannon Faulkner ``Save the Males'' bumper sticker from the
Citadel.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, which she calls a journey, Ms. Faludi tries to come
to grips with postwar social upheavals, from downsizing to the
Vietnam War, that she feels have short-circuited men. ``Stiffed''
is at once sweeping and intimate and largely sympathetic, using
individual tales as well as group portraits _ Citadel cadets,
members of the Spur Posse gang, even pornography stars _ as a way
of examining social disjunction. Above all, perhaps, it is pervaded
by a sense of loss _ of family, community and ties that bound men
to each other and to the traditional institutions they trusted,
from sports teams to the Army.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many of the voices eerily echo women, pre-Betty Friedan. In the
book, Jack Schat, a member of Alternatives to Violence, a Long
Beach, Calif., counseling group for batterers, explains: ``What
really excited me about getting married was not her, but just being
married, doing what I was supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have accused Ms. Faludi of focusing on a bunch of
losers. ``I find it shocking, this throwing out of the word
`losers' to describe people who got the short end of the stick,''
she said over lox and bagels in their dining room. Her
publicity-shot blue eyes looked as if she had been in a pool with
too much chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean for these men to be representative, but to
illuminate themes that run through our society and how men are
caught in the gears,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The happy, well-adjusted guys who some say are missing from her
book do exist. She lives with one. Her chivalrous boyfriend, whose
voice and easy manner bear traces of his Southern roots, grows
agitated when his firecracker-lobbing damsel is attacked. ``It
makes me crazy,'' he said. ``Susan's not angry. But what she does
have in spades is conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Both have impeccable antennae for the subtext of the cultural
conversation; she takes the broad strokes, he burrows into a sense
of place. Both grew up as ``the other,'' Rymer said, which gave
them the desire to enter worlds ``that by pedigree wouldn't accept
us.'' She was a middle-class Jew living in a tract house in a
predominantly Roman Catholic neighborhood in Yorktown Heights,
N.Y.; he was a Southerner whose mother rallied for school
desegregation and drew the ire of the local Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Faludi describes her own mother, Marilyn, now studying for
her master's in Victorian literature at New York University at age
69, as ``a Village person, a bohemian,'' who gave up her career as
an editor to be a 1950s housewife, albeit an unconventional one.
While other mothers went grocery shopping, she would take Susan and
her younger brother, Robert, on field trips to the meatpacking
district, the Fulton Fish Market, even the dry cleaner. They would
stroll under the West Side Highway, because, Ms. Faludi said, ``my
mother loves rubble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a desire to show her children behind the scenes,'' she
continued, ``not just the cleaned-up, sanitized version of life.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
