<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. A photo and a sig/locator map are
available.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA 1021 _ Grand Mesa lover sees (and sells)
everything _ GRAND MESA, Colo. _ The house is too small for the
treasures. One corner is crowded with ``I fish therefore I lie''
baseball caps, Old Dutch cleanser and Powderhorn sweat shirts,
another corner overflows with handmade dream catchers, postcards
and books about Grand Mesa. ``I need more room,'' said Treasure
House owner Joanne Taylor, scanning the 800-plus-square-foot
building from her vantage point behind the counter, which also is
stacked with things like newspapers and candy, treasures to the
right person. The permanent treasure, though, the one beyond pop
rocks and pewter jewelry, is outside the window. Right now it's a
palette of autumn, oak brush leaves rusted auburn like barn door
hinges and the pine and spruce forest up Grand Mesa slopes marbled
with gold stands of aspen. Colors and textures change with the
seasons, but always are treasured by Mesa residents who give
themselves a gift just by looking out the window each morning.
Having been spared, so far, many of the more pernicious effects of
rampant development familiar to the rest of western Colorado, Mesa
remains a town where people wave to strangers they pass on the
street and keep canoes on their front porches. And there's that
view. (Sauer, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CARTER _ Jimmy Carter was talking about vision. No, not grand
sweep, big picture kind of vision. The former president of the
United States was talking about the failing eyesight of a child.
Carter, 75, was haunted by the image of a cute 2-year-old boy he
had seen last weekend in the poor West African nation of Mali. The
boy suffered from the early stages of a disease called trachoma, an
ailment that has blinded 6 million people and that infects millions
more. The boy's grandmother has already been blinded by the
disease. But the boy, the former president said, still has a chance
of keeping his eyesight. The youngster from Mali, and others like
him, will have more a chance thanks to new programs the Carter
Center is announcing today. (Thursday) (Graham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PANDAS _ KORLA, China _ Pandemonium! Two of China's
national treasures, a pair of pandas, will be going to Zoo Atlanta
by the end of this month, the dominant state television network
CCTV-1 reported late Wednesday. Whether two-year-old female Lun Lun
and her two-year-old male pal Yang Yang were really about to split
from the Chengdu Research Base of Giant Panda Breeding was still
slightly up in the air despite this unqualified report to millions
of viewers on Chinese government-run television. Late Wednesday
night, Sarah Bexell, Zoo Atlanta's researcher on the ground in
China, said she had no official confirmation that China's ruling
State Council had finally approved the long-delayed export permit.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-HONDURAS _ MARCOVIA, Honduras - It seems relatively
simple: a nation torn apart by Hurricane Mitch's raging floods
needs to be rebuilt. Donor countries and international charities
step in, providing millions in aid to rebuild infrastructure and
hundreds of volunteers to help provide housing. Slowly, roads are
cleared, washouts filled in, temporary bridges installed and
hundreds of new cement block houses are constructed. But a year
after Mitch's floods, it's clear that rebuilding a poor country
devastated by a natural disaster isn't so easy - at least not if
you want to address the underlying problems that made the disaster
so much worse than it might have been. (Williams/, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
