<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FALUDI-MEN-2NDTAKE-NY     10-20 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALUDI-MEN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: of life.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She credits her mother with kindling her concern about social
issues. Her father, Steven, who now lives in Budapest (her parents
divorced when she was 17), was an only child whose family was
largely eradicated in the Holocaust. He spent his early adolescence
hiding from the Nazis in a safe house in Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although the men in her book open their souls to her, her
descriptions of her own father, who has returned to Hungary to
attend to unfinished emotional business, are surprisingly muted.
``Like many Holocaust survivors, he has so much not to talk
about,'' she said. ``He lost his inheritance, his country, his
patrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With feminism, the narrative of women like Ms. Faludi's mother
became a national anthem. ``The women's movement hit my
neighborhood like a freight train,'' she said. ``Everybody got
divorced. You wonder what would have happened to women if the
suburbs hadn't been built.''
</P>
<P>
   But what she initially overlooked, she said, was the effects of
middle-class suburban expectations on men like her father. ``Part
of me has certainly been motivated by wanting to take a stand
against the restrictions that made Mother give up so much,'' she
said. ``But men's lives were diminished by the same deal. When my
father got married, he gave up the dream of moving to L.A. to
become part of the Hungarian Jewish filmmaking mafia.'' Instead, he
worked in a commercial photography studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were all sorts of domestic things he loved, including
cooking, that he could have fostered, instead of playing the
commuter guy with the fedora taking the 4:59 home,'' she said. As
an immigrant, she noted, her father was under even more pressure to
assimilate and fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women rubbed the sand dust out of their eyes and said, `Wait a
second,' while the men just stumbled on,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Among the exceptions, apparently, is Rymer, who says his life
choices were deeply affected ``by not wanting to be an organization
man like my father.'' The career his father, Richard, pursued as a
electrical engineer was eventually derailed in much the same way as
the careers of the men in the aerospace industry in Ms. Faludi's
book: their glittery titles and fancy nameplates couldn't save them
from pink slips. ``A lot of men who loved the art of engineering
got run out by business types,'' Rymer said. ``And it really
crushed my father.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Rymer's story deeply influenced Ms. Faludi. ``Russ'
father had a real sense of how that betrayal worked, because he'd
experienced it up close,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rymer went a different route, opting not to attend college.
Before embracing the literary life (his first book, ``Genie: A
Scientific Tragedy,'' 1991, was excerpted in The New Yorker and
received a Whiting Writers' Award), he worked as a printing press
mechanic, a carpenter and a seaman.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of old-fashioned, manly training is somewhat
romanticized in ``Stiffed.'' It also may be a key to their
relationship. ``He gives her a lot of ballast,'' said Steve Oney, a
friend and writer in Los Angeles. ``Russ is the opposite of the Ivy
League cerebrates Susan went to college with, for whom irony and
bored affectation is a personal style.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Faludi went to Harvard and is now a famous writer,
Rymer says, ``I never felt outgunned.''
</P>
<P>
   Their idea of a good time is talking. And talking, and talking.
They talk while strolling in Huntington Gardens in Pasadena, around
the Hollywood Reservoir, over wine or gin at the bar. ``People ask,
What are our hobbies?'' she said with amusement. ``Our hobby is
when we sit down at the end of the day and hash out our ideas and
struggle with our thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   During the day, they sometimes hang around the doors to each
other's offices waiting to be noticed. They remain at this point
wedded to their work and skittish about marriage. ``We like to do
what's not expected,'' she said. ``A lot of people seem to want to
make the institution of marriage substitute for a real
relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
