<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-ATHLETE-ASTHMA-HNS &LR;      10-20 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHLETE-ASTHMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE ATHLETE'S BIGGEST RIVAL IS ASTHMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK SINGELAIS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Even when Jill Meconi is struggling for her next
breath, she is fighting to live life on her terms.
</P>
<P>
   That is evident at all times, in all places, especially on the
soccer field. Meconi plays for the College of Saint Rose even
though she has severe asthma, a condition that has sent her to the
hospital several times and requires daily doses of medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a different breed,'' Saint Rose trainer Jay Geiger said.
``She definitely pushes herself to the limit. Sometimes we have to
make the call to take her out (of games), but she's learning and
getting better (at pacing herself).''
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Meconi even had heart surgery as a result of a
complication of her treatment for asthma, a chronic inflammation of
the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   When Meconi kneels to adjust her socks or falls a step behind
other players, those are signs that she is struggling to breathe
and needs to rest and use her inhaler.
</P>
<P>
   To ignore the warning signs, Meconi said, would mean risking her
life. She said she has suffered frightening episodes of
disorientation from a lack of oxygen, and she remembers receiving
this warning from one of her doctors: ``He said if I didn't take
care of myself and stop when I needed to stop, I'm a time bomb
waiting to go off.''
</P>
<P>
   Meconi and the Saint Rose trainers, adhering to a treatment plan
prescribed by Meconi's doctor _ who has given her clearance to play
_ battle every day to prevent those ominous words from coming true.
</P>
<P>
   But even diligent care can't remove the threat of an attack that
hovers over every asthmatic. It's a risk Meconi and her parents are
willing to take so she can play the game she loves.
</P>
<P>
   Meconi, a 19-year-old reserve forward, said she has come to
grips with the fact that she may never recapture the form she had
in winning the Section VII Most Valuable Player award at Seton
Catholic High School in Plattsburgh two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That was before her asthma worsened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be untouchable,'' Meconi said. ``I got to taste the
goals, the winning and the glory. Now it's hard for me to realize
what I have to do. For Saint Rose, I may not be the star athlete,
but I can say I have a big heart and a big drive for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   While Geiger said he is nervous about Meconi's condition, he is
in awe of her determination, especially in a sport that demands
constant movement and stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's playing a lot by her heart and not with her lungs,''
Geiger said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Meconi is the most watched player on her team, not
only by Geiger but by coach Laurie Darling Gutheil and Meconi's
teammates, who worry about her well-being.
</P>
<P>
   And, frankly, Meconi said she doesn't like the extra attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want everyone to know I have limitations,'' she said.
``I want to be considered a normal person, even though I'm not. And
everyone knows I have these problems. That's fine, but I want to
try to do everything like anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   During Meconi's senior year in high school, the mild asthma she
had had since childhood developed into the severe kind, for unknown
reasons. There was no history of asthma in her family.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Stoloff, a Plattsburgh doctor who specializes in allergies
and asthma and who treats Meconi, said that fewer than 5 percent of
his patients are afflicted as badly as Meconi is.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes things with Jill a little more complex is we're
trying to get her to be able to function at a very high competitive
level in a very aerobic sport,'' Stoloff said. ``If she was playing
left field in softball, it would be less of an issue because she'd
be doing a lot of standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoloff said he never has discouraged Meconi from playing.
Stoloff said he'd rather see patients lead active lives, as long as
they monitor their condition and seek appropriate treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Jill, she has severe asthma and she's playing
competitive college sports,'' he said. ``Some people with asthma
think that if they wheeze, they should be excused from gym for the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meconi is feeling and playing better than she did during her
trying freshman year. The 5-foot-4 Meconi gained 40 pounds last
year to increase to 155, a side effect of steroids she was taking
to reduce the inflammation in her lungs.
</P>
<P>
   At times last season, Meconi said she would come out of a match
in a confused state, unable to remember what she'd done in the game
because of a lack of oxygen to her brain. Meconi also said that on
one 80-degree afternoon, the team cloaked her in several coats
because she complained she was freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Meconi tries to explain to a non-asthmatic person
what it's like to have an attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give them one of those little bar straws and tell them to
breathe through it,'' she said. ``It's like that. You can't get
enough air in and it's a very restrictive, tight feeling. I get
really light-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides too much exercise, there are other factors that trigger
Meconi's asthma attacks: common colds, animals and some allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Meconi's situation became more serious last winter. Doctors had
implanted a portocath in her chest so that she could receive
frequent injections of an experimental asthma drug. But a piece of
the portocath broke off and lodged into the right atrium of her
heart. It took more than five hours for doctors at Champlain Valley
Physicians Hospital in Plattsburgh to remove the piece, pulling it
out with a wire through her groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know what, she was a really good sport about it,''
said her mother, Barb. ``She doesn't really remember, but they said
when she was under anesthesia, she was telling Bill Clinton
jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Meconi has had another portocath implanted, and the
device _ about the size of a quarter _ stays permanently in her
chest above her heart.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, again having difficulty breathing, Meconi was flown
to the National Jewish Hospital in Denver, one of the nation's
foremost centers for asthma and other lung diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Barb Meconi, who is a nurse, said her daughter's condition
improved when doctors changed some of her medications, eliminating
some drugs that had the side effect of weakening her immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Jill Meconi returned home to Plattsburgh in July,
she was feeble from a lack of exercise. While teammates were going
through an off-season conditioning program that included five-to
six-mile runs four times a week, Meconi couldn't climb a flight of
stairs or do a single push-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had no muscle to move,'' Meconi said. ``I started at
square one, below that. It was two hours in the gym (in
Plattsburgh). I'd stay in there and it got to a point where slowly
things were coming back. It was very hard and very frustrating, the
most frustrating time of my life, but the hard work paid off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
