<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3095 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BOTANICAL-INSTITUTE-T     10-20 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTANICAL-INSTITUTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTIVATING THE SEEDS OF KNOWLEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sy Sohmer, president and director of the
Botanical Research Institute of Texas, surveys the rows of metal
cases kept in a handsomely remodeled warehouse on the east edge of
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cure for cancer is somewhere in these cases,'' he says,
confidently.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Fort Worth aren't even aware that BRIT exists.
But in its short history, the research institute has become a
botanical equivalent of the Kimbell Art Museum, as a local cultural
and educational resource and in its potential significance in
international botanical research.
</P>
<P>
   BRIT was established in 1991 after Southern Methodist University
decided to divest its large but neglected collection of southern
coastal-area plant specimens, which were then crammed into a
basement on its Dallas campus. But the university wanted to find an
ethical owner.
</P>
<P>
   A few interested Fort Worth individuals became aware of the
specimens and agreed to take responsibility for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a good thing those folks didn't know what they were
getting into,'' Sohmer says.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Bass, one of Fort Worth's most influential citizens, whose
interest in botanical and environmental issues is well known, soon
became involved in moving the collection to the city. Bass also was
on the board of the New York Botanical Garden.
</P>
<P>
   He examined 40 potential sites to house the collection before
settling on the old Ellison Furniture Co. warehouse complex of
three buildings. The SMU collection was brought over and BRIT was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vanderbilt University in Nashville had also decided
to transfer a collection of specimens. BRIT stepped forward again
to claim it. Having since added to the SMU and Vanderbilt
collections, BRIT now owns more than 1 million plant specimens and
has a library of 60,000 volumes and journals. The oldest specimens,
still in excellent condition, date from the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the stuff you need to do botanical work anywhere in
the world,'' Sohmer says.
</P>
<P>
   New York-born Sohmer, who holds degrees from City University of
New York, the University of Tennessee at Knoxville and the
University of Hawaii, was the senior adviser for biodiversity at
the federal Agency for International Development in 1992. It was a
job he enjoyed, and wasn't planning to leave, until he heard from
BRIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew nothing about this place,'' he says. ``But I sensed
something unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawn by the possibility of building a major institution from
the ground up, Sohmer came to Fort Worth in 1993; his wife, Sara,
now teaches history at Texas Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   Storing the specimens is not as complicated as one might think.
Properly dried plants pasted on paper and kept in a cool, dry room
will last indefinitely, unless insects get to them.
</P>
<P>
   So far, cigarette beetles _ little bugs the size of pinheads
that live in tobacco products _ have been the main worry. Signs at
the entrance to BRIT ask that visitors leave all tobacco products
outside, but BRIT still must be fumigated for cigarette beetles
twice.
</P>
<P>
   The one piece of unusual modern technology required at BRIT is a
large chest freezer in which new specimens are chilled to minus 76
degrees for 2 1/2 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kills anything they may have on them,'' Sohmer says.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sohmer hopes eventually to have a ``black box'' setup
that will house the specimens in an even more secure, sanitized,
insect-free environment; the current environment is adequate but by
no means perfect, he says.
</P>
<P>
   BRIT operates with an efficient staff of 10 full-time and six
part-time employees. It has an annual operating budget of $900,000
that usually expands to about $1.4 million with specially funded
projects. An annual event features guest celebrities such as
prominent environmentalists Lady Bird Johnson, Jane Goodall and
President Jose Maria Figueres of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 26,000 students, from elementary school through
college, have visited BRIT since the education program began four
years ago. As those students become adults, BRIT's name recognition
in the community is expected to increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who haven't heard of BRIT are getting rarer,''
Sohmer says.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
