<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 GEEK NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Creative Labs Introduces Redesigned MP3 Player
</P>
<P>
   Hardly six months after Creative Labs entered the highly
competitive market for portable audio digital players, commonly
called MP3 players, the Singapore-based electronics company has
introduced a radically redesigned player called the Nomad II.
</P>
<P>
   Looking little like its shiny, metal-skinned predecessor, Nomad
II has a hardened plastic shell that covers a slightly larger and
heavier machine that stores and plays MP3 music and voice files.
But the new $400 player (almost twice the price of the old player)
can do much more, which, its designers say, makes it practically
``future proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides playing the MP3 audio format, the Nomad II is
programmable, meaning that it can download instructions that would
permit it to use a variety of formats like Windows Media Audio, and
even some formats not yet developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a product that will change as the industry continues to
evolve,'' said Hock Leow, chief technology officer for Creative.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the old Nomad, which will remain on the market, the new
player connects to the computer with a high-speed USB cable.
</P>
<P>
   Nomad II features a backlighted LCD screen, but no built-in
memory. All memory is removable. It comes with a 64-megabyte flash
memory card and an improved set of bass-enhanced headphones.
Similar to first-generation Nomad, Nomad II features an FM tuner,
but can store many more preset stations.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   Sony Has a Free (and Secret) Fix For Out-of-Sync DVD Players
</P>
<P>
   Consumers buy DVD players looking to get a razor-sharp picture
and high-fidelity surround sound, and they get it _ most of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   But a problem that puts sound out of sync with the picture has
popped up in some DVD players by several major manufacturers. The
problem appears to affect some Sony products in particular. DVD
owners in chat rooms on consumer Web sites like Deja.com say that
dialogue occasionally lags behind an actor's lip movements, which
leaves films looking like badly dubbed foreign movies.
</P>
<P>
   Sony said it was tough to determine the exact cause because
sometimes the trouble was with the disk (``The Matrix'' is reported
to be problematic) and because the error appears randomly. Bill
Cubellis, director of DVD marketing at Sony Electronics, said that
there was no design flaw and that the cause was commonly ``a chip
failure.'' He said the problem had been more apparent with Sony
products because ``we are selling more DVD players than anyone else
on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   A representative at Sony's service line, (800) 222-7669, said
the company could ``cure'' the problem, but the company will not
say what the cure is. Sony will fix a problem player free if the
owner will pay to ship it to a repair center. But owners have found
their own ways of solving the problem. Some say turning the machine
off, then on again, will fix it. Others advise using the ``jog
shuttle backward'' feature, then Play.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother? Some owners say that the combination of features and
value are a fair trade-off, even if ``The Unforgiven'' occasionally
looks like ``The Good, the Bad and the Ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ROY FURCHGOTT
</P>
<P>
   Encyclopedia Britannica Goes Online, But Its Site Is Quickly
Overrun
</P>
<P>
   The Encyclopedia Britannica, once sold door to door, is now
coming in through the Internet. This week, Encyclopedia Britannica
said all 32 volumes would be available at www.britannica.com, free
of charge. The site will also feature news feeds, magazine articles
and a list of Web sites chosen by Britannica's editors. Within days
of the opening of the site, however, the Britannica servers were
overrun, leaving millions of grade-school term papers in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   _ BRUCE HEADLAM
</P>
<P>
   From Interact, a New Game Pad That Shakes, Rattles and Rolls
</P>
<P>
   Videogame veterans have long known that those knobby ``analog'`
controllers offer better control than the older up-down-left-right
button controllers. Now PC gamers can have tighter control over
their virtual battles with Interact's Hammerhead FX game pad
(www.interact-acc.com), which sells for $39.99. The smoothly
sculpted device houses tiny vibrating motors that offer
force-feedback shakes, rattles and rolls in response to on-screen
blasts and bang-ups.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOE HUTSKO
</P>
<P>
   A Professor Lands in Hot Water When His Modem Calls Police
</P>
<P>
   Yigal Ehrlich, a 56-year-old professor in Staten Island, N.Y.,
has experienced something of an Internet emergency: When installing
MCI Worldcom Internet software recently, his computer mistakenly
dialed 911.
</P>
<P>
   Through his computer speakers, he could hear police asking for
his location. Within minutes, he said, they had arrived at his
door. While Ehrlich was wrangling with customer-support technicians
on the phone, his wife explained the problem to police. They were
not amused and gave Ehrlich a warning, which he said was now a
permanent part of his record.
</P>
<P>
   But the tale gets worse. Ehrlich's modem software was damaged so
badly that he could no longer make connections, and he wanted to
warn others about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   An MCI Worldcom technician told Ehrlich that the problem might
have occurred because he was using a Macintosh computer with an
operating system older than version 8.1. What appears to have
happened, Ehrlich said, is that when his computer dialed the
software's toll-free set-up number _ (888) 234-5911 _ the computer
dialed only the last three digits.
</P>
<P>
   The CD that Erhlich was using did not have a warning label about
the recommended operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Hassett, a spokeswoman for MCI Worldcom, said that the
company had never heard of anyone else having the problem and that
such a scenario had never come up in testing, even on a Macintosh
with an 8.0 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of an 800 number not completely dialing,''
Ms. Hassett said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the operating-system requirement was noted in the
software's terms and conditions and that the company would make the
requirement clear on the labels of future CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich is not satisfied. ``I have no reason in the world to
invent such a story,'' he said. ``I don't want any other person to
have to go through this.'' He has asked MCI Worldcom to write a
letter to his local police, clearing his name. So far, he said, MCI
Worldcom has refused. And his modem is still not working.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
</TEXT>
