<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In the first
democratic transfer of power in its history, Indonesia inaugurated
a new president Wednesday, Abdurrahman Wahid, a respected Moslem
leader whose message is tolerance, inclusion and self respect. The
vote for Wahid, 59, in an electoral assembly was a surprise. There
was violence on the streets as thugs joined disappointed supporters
of the opposition leader who had been expected to win the
presidency, Megawati Sukarnoputri. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REFUGEES (Cucuta, Colombia) _ As Colombia's
longstanding civil conflict intensifies, the fighting is inflicting
a major social crisis on a country that is already deeply
fractured. Hundreds of thousands of civilians are being forcibly
uprooted and turned into fearful, persecuted migrants. The vast
majority are peasants caught in the crossfire between Marxist
guerrillas and the right-wing paramilitary forces that seek to wipe
them out. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CLEMENCY (Washington) _ The Puerto Rican nationalists
offered clemency by President Clinton failed to make the standard
display of remorse by personally requesting clemency. The top
Justice Department lawyer who handles such requests personally
coached their advocates about how to word an application. And a
department attorney was ``baffled'' by the interest of the White
House in the case. These details showing the highly unusual
treatment the administration gave to the clemency offer were
released Wednesday at a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing into the
issue. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-WITHDRAWS (Washington) _ Elizabeth Dole, the first female
candidate of a major party to make a serious run for the
presidency, dropped out of the race Wednesday, saying she could not
raise enough money to compete with the personal fortune of one
rival and the political heritage of another. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-GAYS (Fort Lauderdale, Fla.) _ As the first openly gay
generation grows grayer and contemplates a potentially lonely
retirement, developers around the nation are planning gay-only
retirement communities and assisted-care facilities that would
allow aging gays to grow old surrounded by others like them, where
they do not have to hide books, magazines or artwork _ let alone
their partners _ and do not have to live, and ultimately die, amid
lingering condemnation. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOODLION-ABC (Undated) _ A jury verdict that found ABC had
committed fraud in a hidden-camera expose of unsanitary conditions
at Food Lion's supermarkets was reversed Wednesday by the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals. The court threw out a $315,000 judgment
against ABC over a 1992 ``PrimeTime Live'' story. (Summary from
wires.) By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
