<HEADLINE>
IN A BOOM YEAR, THERE'S ROOM FOR RETRO-MODERN AND A BIT OF
BAROQUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By LIZ SEYMOUR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ Once upon a time, everybody wanted to be in
pictures. Now, every able-bodied celebrity wants to be in the
furniture business.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Forbes, the vice chairman of Forbes, the magazine
publishing company, was here to introduce furniture, lamps, rugs
and bedding from a variety of makers inspired by the domestic
trappings of his late father, Malcolm Forbes, the Tangier-loving,
Elizabeth Taylor-squiring, Harley-Davidson-riding millionaire
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Kathy Ireland's white stretch limousine idled
outside Vanguard Furniture, where Ms. Ireland _ the Sports
Illustrated swimsuit model and ``a modern Renaissance woman'' in
the words of the company's news release _ conducted tours of a
3,000-square-foot display dedicated to a furniture collection
bearing her name. (She already lends her wholesome good looks to a
signature clothing line for Kmart, which Women's Wear Daily has
declared the seventh most popular brand of women's clothing in the
country.)
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Jack Palance, the great B-movie actor, was touting
the virtues of Action Lane's reclining leather chairs and sofas.
</P>
<P>
   Even the trend forecaster Faith Popcorn, who has long scolded
the male-dominated furniture industry for giving short shrift to
its largely female consumers, put her money where her mouth is: her
own home office collection for Hooker Furniture designed to appeal
to women.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of a strong economy and the steady march of baby
boomers toward midlife affluence was projected by the American
Furniture Manufacturers Association to bump consumer demand for
furniture to $61.105 billion in 1999, an increase of 5.5 percent
over 1998. With 2,400 exhibitors and 8 million square feet of
showroom space _ and another million square feet to be added in the
next six months _ the twice-a-year International Home Furnishing
Market is the biggest wholesale furniture market in the world. It
opened last Thursday and continues through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the opening days of market was as buoyant as the
Faberge-egg-shaped hot-air balloon that bobbed in the sky above a
weedy vacant lot where Forbes made his presentation (bejewelled
Faberge eggs were one of his father's passions). After years of
grumbling about sluggish sales and thin margins, manufacturers were
worrying about meeting demand. However, few of them were rocking
the boat with startling new products, preferring to concentrate
instead on what was selling. ``There's more merchandise being
deleted than being added,'' Epperson said. ``Why change?''
</P>
<P>
   Showroom building corridors were filled not just with furniture
buyers, but with buyers from office supply stores, home
improvements stores and home electronics stores as well. (In one
odd-couple matchup, Bose, the maker of high-end audio equipment,
will start carrying Mitchell Gold furniture in some of its mall
stores this fall.) Catalog companies like Pottery Barn and Crate &AMP;
Barrel were given credit for rehabbing furniture's dowdy image
among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden there started being all this good stuff
available through catalogs,'' said Thomas O'Brien, 38, a cofounder
of the hip SoHo design firm Aero Studios, who was in town to
introduce a resolutely modern-minded collection for Hickory Chair,
for 99 years a bastion of traditionalism: Mount Vernon
reproductions, Mark Hampton historicism.
</P>
<P>
   In general, two nearly antithetical style directions vied for
attention. On the one hand, sophisticated retro-modern design
continued to gain strength, and dark woods, especially mahogany,
had all but displaced the light birch and ash that had been
celebrated just a couple of markets ago.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's vision for the millennium is sleekly elegant
eclecticism with a gentle Mixmaster edge: a bit of 1940s Chinese
here, some embossed velvet there, a slipper chair with an
exaggerated towering back, a seriously scholastic scroll-arm chair
based on a Greek Revival original that O'Brien has owned since he
was in college. Even Stanley Furniture got into the modernist act.
Its Reflections of the 20th Century collection was similar in
feeling to O'Brien's serene chic _ but priced to reach the
midmarket consumer rather than Hickory Chair's typical posse of
well-heeled suburbanites.
</P>
<P>
   The prevalence of clean lines, tight upholstery, exposed legs,
sexy little ottomans and silvery hardware at almost every price
level proved that modern design had lost its shock value. Or, just
maybe, the typical diehard American consumer, though still in love
with tradition, has begun to accept the obvious _that it is 1999,
not 1799.
</P>
<P>
   The entire second floor of Mitchell Gold's cobalt-blue
headquarters, once the epicenter of the slouchy slipcover look, was
devoted to severe tailoring. ``I wouldn't make them if they didn't
sell,'' said Gold, the president of the company, whose stylish
upholstery is a staple at Crate and Barrel and other young-consumer
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Other introductions, however, took a distinctly baroque route.
Thomasville's Bellasera, Stanley's Coronation, Lexington's
California Legacy, and Bernhardt's Coronado were Euro inspired and
heavily ornamented, combining metal, stone and glass with light
woods and painted finishes. The pieces were also scaled to behemoth
proportions, targeted at consumers with bodacious suburban homes to
fill and a weakness for flashy effects. It could have been called
``Married to the Mob.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, European designers seemed to have recolonized America,
some more successfully than others. Despite Ms. Ireland's
pronouncement that she was ``making it safe for people to take
risks,'' she gamely trotted out furniture that was neither
controversial nor new: a bun-foot damask sofa, a whitewashed side
table with barley-twist legs and nonthreatening rattan dining
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Baker's Continental Collection was a quietly
elegant treat. Culled from surprisingly diverse sources _ Baltic
manor houses, anyone? _ the 16th-, 17th- and 18th-century designs
were oddly contemporary, proving that clean, crisp design knows no
era. The company's Biedermeier-style center table, for example,
could be pure Eames.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The most notable holdout was Lane Furniture, which introduced
American designs from Colonial Williamsburg. But the introduction
had more to do with marketing savvy than a devotion to America's
historic best. In making the move from Baker, which had been
licensed to produce high-priced reproductions for a small and
rarefied market, to Lane, whose new midpriced ``interpretative''
pieces are priced to appeal to a much larger audience, Colonial
Williamsburg joined a mainstream trend: aggressive licensing.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry notably short on household-word brands, an
increasing number of companies hoped that a borrowed name _ whether
of a museum, a designer or simply a celebrity, even a dead one,
like Thomasville's Ernest Hemingway range, released last spring to
consumer acclaim and critical drubbing _ would help to create
instant recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Branded furniture stores such as Ethan Allen are doing very
well,'' Epperson said. ``It's logical that brands would become more
important in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If so, the industry will have to grapple with another challenge:
how to sell brand names over the Internet. In an industry
traditionally fiercely protective of sales territories, the
Internet's borderless markets are both attractive and threatening.
Nonetheless, a growing number of furniture companies gingerly
crossed the line between E-information and E-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Directions, a Georgia-based manufacturer of contemporary
upholstered and occasional furniture, was typical of the smaller
companies seeking a larger impact on line. In addition to
maintaining its own Web site, the company is now selling selected
products through an E-retailer called Living.com. ``If we're going
to jump into it, this is the time to jump into it,'' said Al
Lewinger, president of Directions. ``We're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Although online retailing still accounts for less than 1 percent
of all furniture sales, representatives of Internet companies set
up tables and monitors in every available space, from lobbies to
corridors to hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The furniture industry is highly fragmented and a little
primitive,'' admitted Linda Lewi, vice president of marketing for
Home Portfolio a Web site (www.homeportfolio.com) that offers
access to a wide range of home products, from kitchen appliances to
paint. ``But there's a vortex of energy out there right now.
Something's happening in furniture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
