<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3112 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-BRADLEY-VIEQUES-HNS &LR;      10-20 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY CALLS FOR END TO NAVY BOMBING ON VIEQUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley
called Wednesday for the Navy and Marine Corps to permanently end
their target practice on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's public stand is the same as the one that Vice
President Al Gore has reportedly voiced in private to elected
political leaders with ties to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   After Bradley's public announcement, Gore spokeswoman Julie
Green Bataille said the vice president had no public comment to
make on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should end further use of Vieques for live-fire training,''
Bradley said in a statement issued by his campaign in West Orange,
N.J. ``It is wrong for us to continue imposing this burden on
citizens of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has visited Puerto Rico during his presidential
campaign, said the ``humanitarian and environmental destruction''
caused by the target practice on Vieques was ``unacceptable.'' As a
result, he said, it has been difficult to achieve economic
development on the island where more than 9,300 civilians live
adjacent to 22,000 acres of Navy-owned property.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the Navy should find an alternative site for aerial
bombardment and naval gunfire that the Pentagon says is needed to
maintain combat skills of sailors, aviators and Marines.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, Bradley's rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 2000, has voiced similar sentiments to
Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello (D), according to Rossello. The
two-term governor, Gore's fund-raising chief in Puerto Rico, has
promised to campaign for First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, a
prospective Senate candidate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton called on Monday for a permanent end to bombing on
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live ordnance training should not take place on a small,
inhabited island,'' she said. ``There should be an immediate and
permanent end to the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's likely rival for the Senate seat, New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, (R), called on Tuesday for the Navy to end target
practice on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the fate of the 58-year-old bombing range
has embroiled the Puerto Rican community, both on the island and in
New York. Puerto Ricans, who are U.S. citizens by birth, make up
about 60 percent of the 2.6 million Hispanics living in New York
State.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who will decide the issue, awaits
recommendations from Defense Secretary William Cohen on the future
of the bombing range. The site was closed in April following a
Marine Corps bombing mishap that claimed the life of a Puerto Rican
security guard and injured four other civilian workers there.
</P>
<P>
   A four-member Pentagon review panel appointed in June at the
president's request recommended resumption of Navy and Marine Corps
target practice on the island during a five-year withdrawal period
while the Navy searched for a new location for its target practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, testifying before the Senate Armed Services Committee
on Tuesday, rejected appeals for negotiations over future use of
the range and vowed that Navy and Marine Corps bombs will ``never
again'' fall on Puerto Rican territory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has sent mixed signals in the dispute. A handwritten
note to national security adviser Samuel Berger dated July 26
called Navy bombardment ``wrong,'' and said that the Navy ``can
find a way to work around it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also has written Senate Armed Services Committee
Chairman John Warner, R-Va., that he would do nothing that would
compromise the combat readiness of Navy and Marine Corps forces.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig, asked about Mrs. Clinton's
remarks Tuesday, said her comments reflect the depth of concerns
over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that is striking about a thing like this is
that everybody who has a set of concerns and interests expresses
themselves with regard to this,'' Danzig said. ``I'm hopeful though
that we can keep our eye on the ball _ the well-being of sailors
and Marines (and) the well-being of the people on Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
