<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-FALN-JUSTICE-HNS &LR;      10-20 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALN-JUSTICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT CALLS PUERTO RICAN GROUP AN `ONGOING THREAT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two months after President Clinton offered clemency
to 16 Puerto Rican separatists, Justice Department documents made
public Wednesday showed that the agency recommended against
releasing the militants in late 1996 and continues to view their
nationalist group as a threat.
</P>
<P>
   A July 25, 1997, letter from Margaret Colgate Love, then the
Justice Department's pardon attorney, to White House Counsel
Charles Ruff said that a department report ``recommending denial of
clemency'' for the Puerto Ricans was sent to Ruff on Dec. 16, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was released during a Senate Judiciary Committee
hearing on the Justice Department's role in the president's
decision to offer clemency to the militants, most of them
associated with the terrorist group FALN, which seeks Puerto Rico's
independence from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1974 and 1983, the FALN was linked to 130 bombings that
killed six people _ including four police officers _ and maimed
dozens of others. In addition, the group was involved in a number
of armed assaults against government buildings and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, the Justice Department's own people were against
letting these terrorists go,'' said Judiciary Committee Chairman
Orrin Hatch of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Justice spokesman Myron Marlin said his department could not
discuss the letter to Ruff or its anti-clemency stance because the
president has invoked executive privilege to bar administration
officials from publicly discussing the subject or releasing
government documents related to the decision.
</P>
<P>
   According to congressional and administration sources, the
letter to Ruff was mistakenly included in the more than 10,000
pages of documents sent from the department to the committee last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that many documents are involved, sometimes things slip
by that shouldn't,'' a congressional aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Justice Department document released at the hearing
Wednesday was a report last month from Attorney General Janet Reno
that said the FALN posed an ``ongoing threat'' to national
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Factors which increase the present threat from these groups
include ... the impending release from prisons of members of these
groups jailed for prior violence,'' said the report, called the
department's Five-Year Interagency Counterterrorism and Technology
Crime Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton decided in August to commute the militants'
sentences, clemency for them was strongly opposed by the federal
Bureau of Prisons and the United States Attorneys in Illinois and
Connecticut. The FBI also has opposed the clemency.
</P>
<P>
   The crimes committed by the 16 FALN members included possession
of unregistered firearms, interstate transportation of a stolen
vehicle, interference with interstate commerce by violence and
interstate transportation of firearms with intent to commit a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 16 were specifically linked to crimes that resulted
in deaths or injuries. Even so, they received sentences of 50 or
more years in prison, and most had already served more than 19
years. Their time served was greater than most sentences for such
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans and members of the law enforcement community
have accused Clinton of offering clemency to the Puerto Rican
nationalists to help his wife's all-but-announced Senate candidacy
from New York, where some 1.3 million Puerto Ricans are eligible to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president has insisted that politics played no role
in his clemency decision and has said it was based in large part by
the lengthy prison terms already served by the FALN members.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people had signed petitions and lobbied for the
prisoners' release. They included former President Jimmy Carter,
the Rev. Desmond M. Tutu, a Nobel laureate of South Africa, and
Coretta Scott King, widow of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the clemency offer Aug. 11. After protests from
some law enforcement groups and several Republican and Democratic
lawmakers, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on Sept. 4 criticized
the decision, saying her husband should withdraw it. The next day
the White House issued a statement noting that the president had
given the 16 FALN members until Sept. 10 to accept several
conditions, including one that they renounce terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16, 14 accepted the conditions and two declined.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   President Clinton has also said that the prisoners had shown
remorse for their crimes and that they deserved a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   But a transcript released at the hearing Wednesday demonstrated
that at least one FALN member, in an April 1999 phone conversation
monitored by prison officials while he was incarcerated, appeared
unremorseful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to ask for forgiveness from anybody,'' Adolfo
Matos said, according to the transcript. ``I have nothing to be
ashamed of or feel that I have to ask for forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Matos did not mention any specific plans, he said that
his prison sentence would not stop him from ``fighting'' for Puerto
Rican independence. ``My desire has gotten stronger, to the point
where I want to continue,'' he said. ``Continue to fight and get
involved with my people, because I love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators at the hearing also criticized the Justice
Department for failing to consult the victims of FALN terrorist
attacks and their families beforehand about the possible offer of
clemency or to even inform them that the prisoners were being
released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think that these people deserved to be heard?'' Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, asked Deputy Attorney General Eric
Holder.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said that the department made a ``mistake'' in not
contacting the victims about the possible clemency decision.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Justice is developing rules requiring that
comments from victims be obtained as part of the clemency process.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
