<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-OILGAS-NAT     10-20 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-OILGAS-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        Oil and Gas Industries Must Make Y2K Back-up Plans 
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct.20 - Y2K will be ``business as usual'' for the
oil and gas industries, but contingency plans need to be completed
before the roll-over to 2000, representatives from an industry task
force on Y2K readiness said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, the natural gas industry is in good shape for the
year 2000,'' said Oliver Richard, CEO and president of Columbia
Energy Group and representative of the President's Council on Year
2000 Conversion.
</P>
<P>
   But some gas stations, pipelines and natural gas facilities need
to make extra precautions in the next 72 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a singular accomplishment that we are reporting here
today, but I would stress, as the industry is aware, that there is
still work to be done,'' said John Koskinen, who chairs the
president's Y2K council.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of oil and gas companies met the goal of
being ready for the Year 2000 electronic glitch in a survey
released this week by the American Petroleum Institute and the
Natural Gas Council. Ninety-six percent of the industry (2,160
companies) took part in the survey, a three percent increase since
the group's last poll in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The survey indicates that all the activities to fix the
problem are essentially coming to a close,'' said Ron Quiggers,
director of the Y2K Program for Shell Services International and
chairman of the American Petroleum Institute's Year 2000 Task
Force.
</P>
<P>
   The survey covered 99 percent of pipelines, 94 percent of
natural gas distributors, and 77 percent of the country's 180,000
retail gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's contingency plans place responsibility on the Y2K
task force to urge the 4 percent of the industry that isn't ready
for the 2000 glitch to hurry its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Because most gas stations are privately owned, persuading all of
them to prepare for Y2K is ``no small task,'' Quiggens said.
</P>
<P>
   Shell Services International has coaxed the unprepared stations
to get ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the [Shell] stations that are not classified as making
proper progress, we have removed from our network to encourage them
to get Y2K prepared,'' Quiggens said.
</P>
<P>
   While there is not a gaurantee that the stations will report,
``there is increasing confidence that this industry will be 100
percent ready [for y2K],'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Second, natural gas utilities and local gas stations must have
back-up plans to make sure the natural gas flow is not interrupted
that an electricity outage or a natural disaster might cause.
</P>
<P>
   In the contingency plans, interstate pipelines should store an
extra day's worth of natural gas in the countries' 400 underground
storage chambers, allowing time to fix any problems that might
arise in the transmission of natural gas from suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Because most compressor machines that boost gas along interstate
pipelines run on some of the gas instead of electricity, a loss of
electricity would not interrupt gas flow in those cases. The
compressor machines that do use electricity will be backed up by
diesel generators.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas utilities must plan to have extra staff on duty for
the turn-over.
</P>
<P>
   If telephone service glitches, gas utilities should have
satellite-system telephones to stay in communication with each
other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SINGLES-HOUSING-ART-2     10-20 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGLES-HOUSING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A SINGLE WOMAN'S HOME IS HER CASTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The words ring with romantic promise: ``Evenings in front of the
fireplace, and a morning jog along secluded pathways with familiar
footsteps at my side. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not a personal ad. It's the come-on of a Colorado
builder making a sales pitch to single women buying houses.
</P>
<P>
   So what if those familiar footsteps belong to the dog cuddling
in the arms of a smiling, 20-something bachelorette. The message is
clear: Why wait for your prince to come? You can afford a home now
_ and ``Woof! woof!'' surely beats a husbandly whine.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Owens Corning Inc., a Chicago-based manufacturer
of building materials, introduced a television ad campaign called
``Siding Beauty'' in which a damsel awakens after 100 years to find
that the vinyl siding covering her palace has outlasted them all.
</P>
<P>
   Subliminal message: Men may come and go, but good siding is hard
to find.
</P>
<P>
   These scenarios were not scripted by writers of ``Sex and the
City,'' but by savvy marketers trying to reckon with the
fastest-growing buying force _ the single American woman.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics are head-turners. Thanks to delayed marriages,
profitable careers, higher divorce rates and longer lives, the
number of women living alone has increased by more than a third in
the last 15 years, to 30 million, according to the Census Bureau.
Nearly 57 percent of single women now own their own homes, throwing
cold dishwater on the accepted wisdom that homes are the exclusive
territory of couples with children.
</P>
<P>
   Most houses are still purchased by couples, but women living
alone, or who are single heads of household, increased as a share
of total home buyers, from 10 percent in 1985, to 15 percent in
1997. ``That's a huge number, very dramatic,'' said Kermit Baker,
an economist at Harvard University's Joint Center for Housing
Studies. For 1996 and 1997, single women outpaced single men in
making home ownership an investment goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the home-improvement arena, the weekend warrior is a she,
taking on small fix-its that once fell to the now-vanishing
handyman. At the Home Depot in Clifton, N.J., last week, Denise
Ramos, 36, was carrying a bundle of uncut trim she needed to finish
the porch of a new house she had bought three months ago for
$133,000. To pay for the house, Ms. Ramos, who is divorced and has
three children, holds down two jobs. ``I wanted more space and a
better life for my children and for myself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A half million people tune in weekly to PBS' ``Handy Ma'am,''
starring Beverly DeJulio, a divorced mom and former dressmaker in
Chicago. The magazine This Old House, a hammer-thumping bible for
the mustard-stained T-shirt set, is undergoing its own renovation;
a new editor, Donna Sapolin, wants to transform it into a guidebook
for do-it-yourself lovebirds.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when hardware stores sold tools packaged with pictures
of scantily clad lovelies? Now, women in hard hats adorn the
labels, women are likely to be buying the tools and women are often
even running the stores. At Ace Hardware, the international chain,
more and more women own or manage its stores.
</P>
<P>
   With their ``Siding Beauty'' ad campaign, Owens Corning was
acting on a company survey on the next generation's home ownership
priorities; 70 percent of female respondents between ages 23 and 35
claimed owning a home was their highest priority, above buying a
car and paying off debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a tremendous shift in women's roles in home
improvement over the last 20 years,'' said Jerry Oleshansky, the
company's vice president of marketing. ``Just like their baby
boomer mothers, these Gen X and Gen Y women are taking a hands-on
approach, doing everything from planning the project to buying the
products and doing the actual work.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's changing the industry down to its subflooring. Eight
years ago, Nancy Stoner, a divorced mother of two, tried to build a
home for herself and her sons in Lexington, Ky., but was forced to
give up her dream when financing fell through. ``Back then, it felt
like the way car dealers used to treat women by asking, `So where's
your husband?''' said Ms. Stoner, a 49-year old schoolteacher. ``I
couldn't go through with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, who built several houses when she was growing up,
inspired her to keep trying. Today, Ms. Stoner is customizing a
$120,000 carriage house with Ball Homes of Lexington. She's removed
walls between rooms, added bigger windows and requested a walk-out
basement that works as a separate entrance for her boys, who are
now in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time was a lot different,'' she said. ``Everyone accepted
me as I was, a single woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Ball, the co-founder of Ball Homes, said about 30 percent
of his business is selling to single women. ``They seem to like our
garden-type houses with the smaller backyards walled-in,'' he said.
``They like the security.''
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, Bernard Glieberman, the president of Crosswinds
Communities, called single women ``probably the fastest growing
segment of the buying public in the last five years.'' He said,
``The only thing we can figure is that young males think they're
invincible and don't bother much about living arrangements, while
young women think, `I need some security,' and buy a home.''
</P>
<P>
   While the company, which builds 700 houses a year, has sold
frequently to single women, it does not create plans specifically
for that market. ``We haven't changed anything,'' Glieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was the industry's impassive attitude _ acknowledging that
single women are buying homes in droves, while not doing much to
appease them _ that finally drove David Miles, a real estate
consultant, to create his ad featuring the young woman with her
trusty dog for McStain Enterprises of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is becoming obvious that single professional women have a
different time line for their lives than men,'' he said. ``As they
begin to make more money and become self-sufficient, they're less
willing to commit to relationships until they're very sure of
themselves. But they still want that home.'' Builders have been
slow to design specifically for single women, Miles contends,
because ``most builders are small local companies, and they don't
understand who their customers are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've only just figured out the market for empty-nesters,''
he continued. ``They're going to need at least three to five years
of media attention to get this trend.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad for McStain did the job, and then some. The company
received calls not only from single women interested in buying, but
also from men wanting to know if that girl really lived in that
house because they'd like to meet her.
</P>
<P>
   If builders are late to the party, home-store retailers are
eager to get women on their dance card now. Research has told them
that women make 50 percent of the purchases in the $30.2 billion
hardware and home renovation industry. Taking note, Ace Hardware
changed its motto from ``The helpful handy guys'' to ``The helpful
handy folks.'' Too subtle? They also added softer lighting, browser
displays and hunter-green decor to stores, in place of bare
concrete walls. Seminars for staff on how to relate to women
customers have put Ace in touch with its inner handy gal, said Ann
Marie Hickey, a spokeswoman at Ace headquarters in Oak Brook, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest home improvement chain, Home Depot, has set
out in earnest to woo women to the warehouse. In 1998, the company
settled a blistering lawsuit, in which 7,000 of its female
employees claimed discrimination in hiring, pay and promotions, and
paid out $65 million. The company recently began Home Depot
University, with seminars for renovation neophytes, from installing
vinyl flooring to reroofing. About 50 percent of the student body
are women, said John Simley, the chain's Northeast spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Though Simley said the store didn't carry gender-geared
products, ``we do carry Ralph Lauren paint,'' he admitted, adding,
``I, as an ordinary guy, don't give two hoots about it, but a woman
may respond to a name brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Marian Salzman, 40 and single, is a co-author, with Ira
Matathia, of ``Next: Trends for the Near-Future'' (Overlook Press,
1999), a study that identified single women as a retailing force to
reckon with on an international scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies have traditionally only sold to single women in the
woe-is-me category, with low-cal diets and single-portion meals,
based on the idea that if a woman is not in a relationship, she
must be doing everything possible to land one,'' said Ms. Salzman,
a trend spotter for Young &AMP; Rubicam. ``There's no celebration of
the single woman as a satisfied consumer, who is buying not in a
must-have mode but a would-like-to-have style,'' she added. ``It's
a very different situation, and we're going to see a lot of changes
in the market place.''
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs, where the handyman has disappeared from under
the sink, often heading for greener pastures as a contractor, women
are picking up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't get a small-job person anymore,'' Lois Slocum said, with
good-natured resignation. Mrs. Slocum, 62, and her family have
taken over the neighborhood family store, Handyman Hardware, in
Stamford, Conn., ever since her husband contracted severe Lyme
disease 14 years ago. It's a traditional outfit with a
nontraditional staff: her daughters, Nancy Ligi, 37, and Michelle
Arvan, 28.
</P>
<P>
   The women (Jessica, 11, Mrs. Slocum's niece, helps out on
weekends) cut keys, repair chain saws, rewire lamps and swap sports
scores with the male clientele. From Mrs. Slocum's vantage point,
``Men don't have an idea how to fix a toilet, so it's the wife
who's stuck at home who has to learn how.'' She added: ``Women seem
to learn the proper way. They read the directions. Men jury-rig.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Burkert, 35, is her own handyman. A record company
executive who shares an apartment with a roommate in Manhattan's
Greenwich Village, Ms. Burkert has a toolbox that her mother helped
her stock. ``Those gruff guys at the hardware store looked us up
and down as if we didn't know anything. And then my mother pulled
her list out with the size of the nails, the grade of the sandpaper
and all the right screwdrivers with their own screw heads, and she
had them running all over the store.''
</P>
<P>
   This Gen X bachelorette calls her apartment the Den of the
Goddesses, and has furnished it with tapestries and candles. She
likes it so much, she said, that when Mr. Right comes along, ``he
can move in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Burkert was recently featured in ``On the Loose'' (William
Morrow, 1999) by Melissa Roth, an account of a year in the life of
three women in their late 20s and early 30s. Ms. Roth, 32, has
spent considerable time studying women in what she calls ``the
panic years'' and has noticed that retailers market to her age
group ``as if all we do is buy clothes.'' She added: ``But that's
only true for the first 25 years. After that, you realize that
you're not seeing your clothes, you're looking at your crummy couch
most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Ms. Roth, a Manhattanite, went to Janovic Plaza
where she said she encountered ``nothing but single women shopping
for paint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we all are,'' she said, ``ready to commit, maybe not to a
man, but definitely to a place of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Woolf had it wrong. Why settle for a room, when you can
have the whole house?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
