<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      10-20 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: GAY BOOKS ARE FACING THE DOWNSIDE OF ACCEPTANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Norman Laurilla is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great vexation for lesbians and gay men in book publishing
has been that their assimilation into that world in particular and
into the cultural life in general has made it more difficult for
their books to get published and be sold, rather than easier. That
is because, in part, the first gay literature to come to public
attention was considered notorious no matter its quality, and its
celebrity appealed to a certain dark stealth when, for instance,
one purchased Radclyffe Hall's landmark novel ``The Well of
Loneliness.'' But to make it to the book racks now, gay writing
must compete with the mainstream work that, at least in some
instances, it has become. Acceptance, as every minority group has
found, has its difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a great adventure is now about marketing and
visibility, and this leads to the Publishing Triangle, an
association of about 225 gay and lesbian editors, publishers,
writers, agents, librarians and teachers. It was founded in 1989
not to fight discrimination, which was not viewed as a big problem
in book publishing, but to foster networking and mentoring. ``Today
it's about selling books, helping the gay bookstores and small gay
presses to survive; a different emphasis,'' said its president,
Charles Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   To publicize itself the organization holds seminars, publishes a
newsletter and gives annual awards for gay books. This summer it
compiled a list of the 100 greatest gay novels. (Thomas Mann's
``Death in Venice'' was No. 1.) Soon to come: the 100 greatest
nonfiction titles. Still, as is the case with other assimilations,
appealing to the professional progeny of the first two generations
of Triangle members is strenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Denneny, a senior editor at St. Martin's Press, and the
editor of Randy Shilts' seminal best-selling ``And the Band Played
On'' (St. Martin's Press, 1987), said that ``the last generation in
the organization has not replaced itself with the younger editorial
assistants, younger publicists.''
</P>
<P>
   If a gay book sells 20,000 or 25,000 copies _ a robust sale for
most literary novels _ it is considered a smashing commercial
success; 10,000 copies sold makes for a happy publisher. But the
definition of such a book is fuzzy. Does it mean the author is gay?
Does the book have to have gay characters? A gay subject? Was ``The
Band'' a gay book, or did its plummy sales and crossover readership
make it mainstream? And do sales determine category?
</P>
<P>
   Novels like ``The Well of Loneliness'' (1928), Gore Vidal's
``City and the Pillar'' (Dutton, 1948) and ``Rubyfruit Jungle''
(Daughters Inc., 1973) by Rita Mae Brown were considered dangerous,
to be tucked under their arms in brown wrapping paper. Carole
DeSanti, editor at large at Penguin Putnam, said: ``A gay book
could break out as a cult favorite. Gay books were a novelty for a
while, but now the gay-content books are subject to the rigors of
publishing's economic tracking system.'' But this year ``The
Hours'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux) by Michael Cunningham won the
Pulitzer Prize for fiction, a true coming out.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to gay books in this ``tracking system''?
Quality, more than shock, has taken its toll. Will Schwalbe, an
executive editor at Hyperion, said that after a flush of
high-quality gay books, ``there was a rush of modest-quality gay
books and readers turned away from that market.'' He added, ``I
don't think people realize how many talented writers we lost to
AIDS, but also how many dedicated readers we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than that. Nearly every gay editor and gay agent
and gay bookstore owner believes that young lesbians and gay men
don't read as much as their elders did, and when they do read they
don't necessarily make a dash for the gay-book racks. Moreover,
bookstores specializing in gay writing are suffering from the same
chain-store squeeze that hurts mainstream independent stores. Books
with gay subject matter are cheaper at Borders, for instance, than
at a gay shop that can't offer a high-volume discount.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Laurilla, owner of A Different Light bookstores in New
York, West Hollywood and San Francisco, said that he believed that
his customers ``more than the general public, have computers at
home, which take time away from reading, but when they want books
they buy with quick-stop shopping on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, gay book stores were part of a political movement
of sorts, he said. ``Then we had to become booksellers and business
people, and younger gays don't remember those days. They're
perfectly comfortable picking up books where they can get them at
best value. A gay bookstore is not as wondrous to them as it was to
us in the '70's when our customers were overwhelmed because they
never saw that stuff before.''
</P>
<P>
   So for nearly three decades gay people involved in the
publication and sales of lesbian and gay writing have struggled to
get more of their books published and have succeeded, only to find
that their victory has come back to haunt them and perhaps put many
of these stores out of business, a trend the Publishing Triangle is
trying to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Malaga Baldi, an agent, said advances for gay authors had shrunk
because publishers were less willing to gamble on the idea that gay
people, who as a group have a relatively high income, are going to
use it for books. ``I find fewer people to go to to sell gay
books,'' she said, ``so I'm doing more business with smaller houses
outside of New York, but it's scary.'' She said that some
publishers would not put the words ``gay'' or ``lesbian'' on their
jackets. ``Perhaps in the short run it hurts if they do, but in the
long run it's good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, acceptance and affirmation do have their happy surprises
as well as their melancholy. Andrew Holleran, a gay novelist, said
that last year he was teaching creative writing at American
University to a class that included three gay students. ``I was
flabbergasted that these kids submitted gay stories and were
discussing them in class and no one batted an eyelash,'' he said.
``It's very strange being assimilated and writing material no
longer considered different. The newness is gone, and there's the
other countermovement: You don't want to be considered a gay
writer, and you feel marginally diminished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
