<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-TOBACCO-REVIEW-NYT     10-20 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOBACCO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOBACCO WARS': JOE CAMEL, THE MARLBORO MAN AND THE CYNICAL ART OF
DENIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review)  
(bl) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now few viewers can be astonished to learn that cigarette
makers have not been models of candor when it comes to their
products' effects on the health of their customers. But a little
recapitulation can't hurt, and ``Tobacco Wars,'' which begins
Thursday night on The Learning Channel, is a forceful reminder of
an industry's half-century of efforts to obscure, obfuscate and
delude.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief reminder by a former researcher for Philip Morris
of the lure of nicotine and the efficiency of the cigarette as ``a
drug delivery device,'' the three-part documentary moves briskly
into the marketing and advertising techniques that helped propel
tobacco into a $200 billion business. The old advertisements add a
touch of nostalgia to the program's grim indictment.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the 1930s, a few surgeons, notably Michael
DeBakey, became convinced that there was a connection between
smoking and lung cancer, but their findings had little impact.
Instead, among the side effects of World War II was an explosion of
the smoking habit.
</P>
<P>
   With postwar studies confirming a statistical relationship
between smoking and cancer, the industry went into a denial phase
that would last decades. Company executives and advertising
professionals recall some of the industry's favored techniques,
like playing up the fact that many doctors smoked and that some
even recommended smoking for the relief of stress and throat
irritation.
</P>
<P>
   As the link between smoking and lung cancer became more widely
accepted, the tobacco companies undertook what is described as
``the longest and costliest public relations campaign in history.''
A marketing executive tells how filtered cigarettes were designed
to make smokers absorb even more smoke: ``Really it was naughty.''
Another advertising man says of the slogans and images (the
Marlboro Man) that lulled people's fears: ``Deceptive? Of course
it's deceptive. What are we going to say, `Buy our product, it'll
kill you'?''
</P>
<P>
   After the Office of the Surgeon General issued its famous report
in 1964 connecting smoking and cancer, the industry's lawyers
joined in promoting the idea of a warning label, their strategy
being to divert legal responsibility from producers to consumers.
Walter Cronkite, the program's narrator, reports on their success:
``All attempts at litigation against them failed throughout this
period. And most cigarette smokers just kept on smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, big tobacco found itself on the defensive.
When opponents began running effective anti-smoking commercials,
the industry agreed to discontinue cigarette advertising on
television and radio in hopes of defusing the attack. But
billboards appealing to the young (Joe Camel) kept luring new
customers for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco Wars'' brings the shabby story up to the present, when
cigarette makers have been embarrassed by the exposure of their
efforts to conceal the results of their own research. The famous
scene of the companies' chief executives' swearing to a
congressional committee that they did not believe nicotine was
addictive remains an embarrassing moment in their careers and a
tribute to the revelatory power of television.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the courts have not been kind to big tobacco:
suits by the states and by survivors of cigarette smokers have
forced the industry into costly settlements. (In the latest effort
to polish its image, Philip Morris issued a belated acknowledgment
last week that smoking was related to disease.)
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of this history of corporate deception and social
irresponsibility, Steven Goldstone, who was chairman of RJR Nabisco
when it split off its R.J. Reynolds Tobacco unit in March, says,
``I think we could have done a better job as an industry over the
past 40 years.'' That's putting it, as the advertisements used to
say, mildly.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TOBACCO WARS'
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Channel, tonight &UR;  &LR; at 9;
</P>
<P>
   Part 2, Friday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   A BBC/TLC co-production. Narrated by Walter Cronkite. Mary Ellen
Iwata, executive producer for TLC; Peter Horrocks, executive
producer for BBC News; Peter Molloy, series producer, BBC News;
Chris Hoelzel, producer, The Learning Channel; Scott Davis,
production assistant, The Learning Channel.  &QL; 
