<HEADLINE>
HOUSE CONSERVATIVE ISSUE BUDGETARY WARNING TO CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House conservatives warned President Clinton on
Wednesday they will defeat any attempt to raise taxes to pay for
his spending priorities, a shot across the bow as budget
negotiators opened their first session on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, signed a $99 billion spending bill for
housing, veterans and space programs, hailing the measure as
symbolic of the bipartisan cooperation that can be displayed
between the White House and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But while Clinton talked peace, he also prepared for budgetary
war, suggesting he would hold the $268 billion defense spending
bill, containing lucrative pork for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott's hometown in Mississippi, until negotiators reach agreement
on all outstanding funding issues.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Clinton met with congressional leaders and they
agreed on a framework to begin resolving a spending impasse, the
spirit of bipartisan cooperation seemed to wane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here today to send one very clear message: Mr.
President. No means no,'' said Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
``When the Republicans say we're not going to touch the Social
Security surplus, we mean it. When we say that we're not going to
raise taxes, we mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said Republican leaders left the White House session with
the understanding that Clinton would keep all the Social Security
surplus off limits and forgo tax increases. He termed ``very
unsettling'' comments made later by Democrats that taxes remained
on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters that he realized his proposal to raise
cigarette taxes by 55 cents a pack would not be acceptable to
Republicans. However, he said his spending priorities were ``quite
modest'' and that a way would be found to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So all I said was that I realized they weren't going to accept
my proposal, but that now we were talking about much more modest
amounts. ... I thought we could find a way to pay for them that
they (Republicans) could live with,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also kept Republicans bristling by saying he agreed to
avoid the Social Security surplus but that the GOP already had
dipped into the extra cash. Republicans, in turn, continued touting
a Congressional Budget Office letter that says they had not spent
the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The tax issue is just one of many that White House and Congress
must resolve by a Tuesday deadline set for themselves. Negotiators
held an opening session on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 fiscal year began Oct. 1, but Congress has not
completed work on all 13 spending bills. Clinton, with his action
Wednesday, has signed six into law, two remain on his desk and he
vetoed two. Three others are pending in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again I say, in spite of all the conflicts of the last few
weeks, we still have a great opportunity to make this a season of
progress and work together to pass a budget that lives within its
means and lives up to our values,'' Clinton said as he signed the
spending bill funding the Veterans Affairs, Housing and Urban
Development, and independent agencies such as NASA.
</P>
<P>
   The measure provides $13.7 billion for the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration, an additional $100 million over current
funding. The House wanted to cut NASA by $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives NASA the resources it needs to probe the mysteries of
space,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides money for an additional 60,000 home vouchers
for low-income families, provides $70 million for Rural/Urban
Empowerment Zones that provide tax breaks for businesses moving
into designated areas and provides $19.8 billion for medical care
for veterans. It includes $2.5 billion in emergency funding for
victims of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would not decide until next week whether to sign
a defense spending bill that Republicans are pressing him to
approve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   It contains a 4.8 percent pay increase for military personnel.
But, it also includes a $375 million downpayment on a $1.5 billion
``minicarrier'' being built in Pascagoula, Miss., the home town of
Lott. The Navy did not want the ship until 2011.
</P>
<P>
   The defense bill may become the White House's hold card as
Republicans push for an across-the-board spending cut. Republicans
want to exempt the defense bill from reductions, but the White
House contends the GOP would have to cut 17 percent from other
bills if they exclude the military.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he outlined the priorities to Republicans that he
intends to fight for. They include more funds to place 100,000
teachers in the classroom, to hire more police, to help finance the
Middle East peace process, to help reduce Russia's nuclear arsenal,
to pay for debt relief for poor nations and to pay the back dues
owed the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite negotiations, Republicans moved ahead to send remaining
spending measures to the president. The House narrowly passed, on a
215-213 vote, a $38 billion funding bill for the departments of
commerce, state and justice. Clinton has said he would veto the
measure as written.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the House also takes up its version of education
policy, eliminating Clinton's program for 100,000 classroom
teachers enacted last year and turning over the money to states in
the form of block grants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
