<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LOST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-20 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOST':   A LONG-MISSING BROTHER IS DISTURBINGLY PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the youthful narrator tells it in ``Lost,'' Hans-Ulrich
Treichel's bitterly comic first novel, his family has long been
haunted by his missing older brother, Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that just after World War II, during ``the long trek
from the East to the West'' in flight from the Russians, the family
was set upon by Russian soldiers. Thinking they would be shot, the
narrator's mother put Arnold in the arms of a passing woman without
even telling her his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she'd been too quick in fearing for her life and the life
of her child,'' the narrator reports, ``and if she were honest,
she'd been too quick to give the child away.'' Instead of shooting
the family, the soldiers ``had thrown themselves on my mother,''
although ``I wasn't really clear what exactly it meant when the
Russian threw themselves on someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since this incident, before the narrator was born, the
atmosphere in the family has been poisoned. ``From the day of my
birth, guilt and shame had ruled the family, without my knowing
why.'' His mother keeps herself from weeping by busying herself
around the house. His father immerses himself in his successful
food wholesaling business.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator, secretly rather pleased that he doesn't have to
share his parents with Arnold, feels guilty about any pleasure he
takes in life. He tries to comfort his mother about Arnold's fate.
```Maybe he was lucky,' I said, `and they named him Arnold again,'
at which my mother looked at me with such incomprehension and
sadness that the blood rushed to my head and I was ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as his mother recovers in a clinic from a breakdown, his
father tells him that the authorities may have found Arnold in a
Red Cross foundling home. Like their lost child, ``foundling 2307''
has ``a noticeable cowlick in his hair on the right side of his
head.'' Records show that he was on the same postwar trek from East
to West and that it was ``the same day, 20 January 1945, when the
boy was laid in an unknown woman's arms.'' Finally, a photograph
reveals that ``the boy had an absolutely astonishing resemblance to
me, his putative brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrator reports: ``The supposedly amazing likeness made me
feel less and less like myself. Every look in the mirror grated on
my nerves. I didn't see me, I saw Arnold, and he was getting less
appealing all the time. If only he had starved to death during the
escape. Instead he was interfering in my life. And in my
appearance. I longed for a Third World War so that he would starve
to death after all. But the Third World War never came.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities, however, will not let his parents visit the
possibly Arnold. Psychological damage might be done if the
identification is in error. Tests must be administered,
fingerprints and blood samples analyzed by the Institute of
Forensic Medicine at the University of Muenster. Expert opinion
states that while ``I, the legitimate child, was `possibly and even
probably positively' the issue of both my mother and father,''
foundling 2307 ``was `possibly but not probably positively' the
issue of my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The family travels to Heidelberg for further testing: a Rohrer
Index, taken with wooden calipers that pinch the stomach; ``the
relative width of the angle of the jaw,'' which, says a professor
at the Institute of Forensic Anthropology, ``can be the decisive
factor.'' Doubt about the relationship increases. Mother grows more
depressed. Father flies into a rage and suffers a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   What does ``Lost'' signify, besides the pain of sibling rivalry
and the Kafkaesque nightmare of bureaucracy? Long after finishing
Treichel's mesmerizing tale, I was struck by how perfect an
allegory it is of the division and reunification of East and West
Germany, with the snarling of red tape interfering with the
recognition of human fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Lost'' doesn't have to mean. The narrator's voice _
beautifully translated by Carol Brown Janeway, who did ``The
Reader,'' by Bernhard Schlink, among other books _ won't let you go
as it draws you into its labyrinth of absurdity. Take the account
of the family's semiannual pig's-head feast, where the guests'
hearty tales of slaughtering animals ``acted as a tranquilizer on
my father, so that this man who was otherwise so choleric and prone
to rages had such a forgiving look in his eyes that I thought I
would never have to be afraid of him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Or take the grotesque conversation of the hearse driver the
family happens to lunch with in the canteen of the Forensic
Anthropology Laboratory. While the narrator searches for death in
the hearse driver _ ``Death had a ruddy face and brownish teeth
with a gap in the lower jaw. . . . The hair was shiny and obviously
had hair cream in it. Death used hair cream'' _ the hearse driver
speaks of the latest fashions in shrouds and the newly completed
Heidelberg South Crematorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``To show him how perfectly clean and hygienic his cremation
ovens were in operation,'' the director had recently removed a few
remaining little bones from the ash pan, put one of them in his
mouth and ``chewed around on it and asked him, the hearse driver,
whether he wanted to try it once too.'' The hearse driver declined
the offer, remarking that ``everything had its limits, although he
had absolutely no doubt that the ovens operated completely
hygienically.''
</P>
<P>
   After the tests the family leaves the Forensic Anthropology
Laboratory and walks on a bridge over the Neckar River that is
famous for its swaying. ``The bridge turned out to be a massive
stone bridge, built of huge, weathered, brown-stained blocks, and
it didn't seem to sway at all,'' the narrator reports. ``I banished
my sadness by jumping in the air several times and landing as hard
as I could, to make the bridge start swaying after all. I wouldn't
have minded at all right then if the bridge had collapsed. But it
didn't. It didn't even sway. Not the slightest movement to be felt.
My parents paid no attention to my antics and were walking on.''
</P>
<P>
   As happens throughout his brilliant tragicomic story, the world
simply won't move for him.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `LOST'
</P>
<P>
   By Hans-Ulrich Treichel
</P>
<P>
   136 pages. Pantheon. $19
</P>
</TEXT>
