<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 21 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
the Daily News at (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC_STUNT (Los Angeles) _ Here is the shocking situation: A
man covering his eyes with ski mask, aluminum foil and ski goggles
drove through the San Fernando Valley _ and the police did nothing
to stop him. It was all part of the Fox Family Channel's taping of
World Magic Awards. ``We were told it would be a magic trick and
that he would be wearing a blindfold that he could see through,''
said LAPD officer Jason Lee. ``We would not permit anything like
this if it wasn't safe.'' By Phillip Browne. (Will move in the
``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT-FATE (Los Angeles) _ Despite skyrocketing costs and
concerns about mitigation, a citizens commission is expected to
recommend completing the Belmont Learning Center, a $161-million,
scandal-plagued high school under construction downtownatop a
former oil field that seeps toxic and explosive gasses. School
board members, who previously vowed to stand by the commission's
recommendation, were set to vote on it Thursday. By Greg Gittrich
and Beth Barrett. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHIMP-LAZOO (Los Angeles) _ Abandoned by her mother at a Florida
zoo, the eight-week-old chimpanzee named Zoe arrived at LAX and was
resting Wednesday in quarantine at the Los Angeles Zoo. By Amy
Raisen. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-SOCAL (Los Angeles) _ The cumulative investment in Southern
California's major development projects has climbed to $13.6
billion, reflecting strong confidence in the region's economic
future, according to a study to be released Thurday. It's the
biggest collective total for ``major'' projects in a decade,
economists with the Los Angeles Economic Development Corp. said. By
Gregory J. Wilcox. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NEWHALL-EARNINGS _ Land sales are likely to fuel another strong
earnings report Thursday by The Newhall Land and Farming Company,
the Santa Clarita Valley's largest developer. By Jason Takenouchi.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
