<HEADER>
A3143 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FORTWORTH-DANCERS-TEX     10-20 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTWORTH-DANCERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOVELY PAS DE DEUX, ONSTAGE AND OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, TEXAS _ Tang Min and Zhao Min Hao are a Hollywood
casting director's dream of what a ballet duo should look like.
</P>
<P>
   Both are handsome, and they're perfectly matched physically at 5
foot 6 and 5 foot 8. More than that, as they proved in their area
debut at a recent outdoor dance festival in Dallas, they share a
rare expressive grace and apparently effortless ballet technique.
</P>
<P>
   Tang, 37, the female half of the couple, and Zhao, 36, have
known each other since the age of 11, and have been married for 12
years. They experienced the Chinese Cultural Revolution together
and have lived in three countries together.
</P>
<P>
   Born in different provincial cities in China, they met in 1973,
when they arrived at the country's principal ballet school in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Russian system,'' says Tang, the more outgoing
of the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, they look at your face,'' she explains. ``Then they
measure your body. Then they look at your parents to see what you
will look like later. They check everything. And if they choose
you, the government pays for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither found the experience of leaving home at an early age
damaging or painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of fun for a young kid,'' Tang says. ``You live, eat
and sleep there. The government pays for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And they quickly became accustomed to stringent training _
although, Tang admits, ``Sometimes we cried.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the young dance students rise at 5:30 a.m., run
outdoors and train for two hours before breakfast every day, study
ballet for three hours in the morning and three hours in the
afternoon, and learn gymnastics as well as dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes your body very strong,'' Zhao says. ``If you want to
be good, you have to work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The lingering effects of the Cultural Revolution, so devastating
to many artists and intellectuals in China, were relatively
painless for the young dancers. They had to spend only a few weeks
a year on a farm or in the army, and the physical work there was
hardly as stringent as their training at ballet school. Both recall
the short stints in the countryside to have been almost vacations
compared with their usual lives at a ballet academy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1970s brought increasing interchange between China and the
rest of the world, and a revolution in ballet repertoire within
China. Ballet training and style, introduced by the Russians after
the communist takeover in 1949, had been classical. But the
repertoire had been dominated by communist propaganda works. With
the 1970s, traditional classical works such as ``Swan Lake'' and
``Sleeping Beauty'' were introduced.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, when Zhao was 18, he was selected along with four other
young male dancers from Beijing to study for the summer with Ben
Stevenson at the Houston Ballet. That gave Zhao his first view of
life outside China.
</P>
<P>
   Although they had known each other since childhood, it wasn't
until several years later, while working together in the grand pas
de deux from ``Don Quixote,'' that Tang and Zhao fell in love. When
they married in 1984, both had several competition wins to their
credit, and they settled in for several years at the Beijing
Ballet, which provided living quarters as well as studio space.
</P>
<P>
   But they had also tasted the freedom, seen the new dance
developments and glimpsed the lifestyles of the West _ and had
decided that that was what they wanted. In 1988, they obtained
visas to come to the United States, where they joined the
Pittsburgh Ballet. Because of immigration laws, they had to move to
Canada after only eight months. Ten years later, protected from
deportation to China by their Canadian citizenship, and longing for
a warmer climate, they applied to the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet.
Although they're not media superstars, they have a strong
reputation within the dance community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend who couldn't believe that I made them
audition,'' Fort Worth Dallas Ballet artistic director Benjamin
Houk says.
</P>
<P>
   Their hearts are in China, which they visit annually, but their
home now is in Fort Worth. Besides sharing a profession, they share
a passion for fishing and the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   And they find that their constant togetherness is an advantage
as partners in dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We push each other,'' Zhao says, describing their professional
relationship in the dance studio. ``We're not polite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight, we argue, but that's normal,'' Tang says. ``The
result is always good.'' .MDBO/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
