<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MISHIMA-MEMOIR-NYT &LR;      10-20 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISHIMA-MEMOIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT IN JAPAN HALTS PUBLICATION OF DEAD AUTHOR'S LETTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Reviving the controversy that followed novelist Yukio
Mishima throughout his life, a Tokyo court has banned further
publication of a memoir by a writer who says he had a homosexual
relationship with him. The court ruled Monday that the use of
Mishima's letters represented copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, which could have far-reaching consequences for
Japanese publishing, the court held that Mishima's letters to Jiro
Fukushima were protected under the country's copyright laws and
could not be used without permission of Mishima's estate. Fukushima
and his publisher, Bungei Shunju Ltd., one of Japan's largest
producers of books and magazines, were ordered to pay $47,000 in
damages to the plaintiffs, Mishima's son and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Mishima, perhaps Japan's most widely known modern writer,
committed ritual suicide by sword, or seppuku, at age 45 in 1970.
His death was an act of protest after failing to persuade the
country's Self Defense Force to stage a coup d'etat and renounce
the U.S.-imposed postwar constitution that places a perpetual ban
on aggressive military action by Japan.
</P>
<P>
   During the latter part of his career, Mishima, a prolific author
whose works include ``The Sound of Waves'' and ``The Temple and the
Golden Pavilion,'' became one of Japan's most flamboyant public
figures as he earned a reputation as a crusader for
ultra-conservative and nationalistic causes. He led an open, if not
explicitly acknowledged, life as a homosexual, even as he
maintained the appearance of happily married family life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sword and Winter Red,'' Fukushima's memoir, contains 15 of
Mishima's letters and was originally published last year. It caused
a great stir among the public, particularly for its descriptions of
its author's sexual liaison with Mishima.
</P>
<P>
   Fukushima, a novelist and former high school teacher of
literature, recounts, among other episodes, how he first approached
Mishima in a letter asking him for details about a homosexual club
described in Mishima's writings.
</P>
<P>
   From the exchange of correspondence, it appears that Mishima
took Fukushima to the actual club in Tokyo upon which the fictional
account was based, and the two subsequently became lovers.
Throughout their relationship, however, Fukushima used the
respectful term sensei, translatable as teacher or master, to refer
to the famous author.
</P>
<P>
   Fukushima was a relatively obscure writer until the publication
of his Mishima book, but in the space of 10 days more than 90,000
copies were sold. The memoir's cover illustration, a painting of
the martyrdom of St. Sebastian, depicts of a young man in bondage
being pierced by arrows.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mishima dealt extensively with the theme of
homosexuality in writings like ``Confessions of a Mask,'' open
declarations of homosexuality were unusual in the Japan of his day.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually successful commercial run of Fukushima's book was
quickly halted by a lawsuit by Mishima's two adult children, Noriko
Tomita, 40, and Jichiro Hiraoka, 37. The legal action resulted in a
``provisional disposition'' in their favor in Tokyo District Court,
in which the judge ordered a ban on further publication and the
recall of copies already sold. In the end, however, only about
10,000 copies were successfully recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an epoch-making decision that the letters be recognized
as the author's works by the court,'' said Katsuhiko Konno, the
lawyer representing Mishima's children. ``You are free to sell a
painting that is given to you by a painter, but you are not allowed
to reprint it, make a collection and sell them. The same can be
said for letters.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's ruling, which upholds the initial ban, the presiding
judge, Toshiaki Iimura essentially agreed. Publication of Mishima's
personal letters ``infringed the right to take copies of them,
which is given exclusively to the bereaved family,'' he wrote. ``If
Mishima were alive, the publication would have also infringed the
right to publish them, which would be given exclusively to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Correspondence between Mishima and translator Donald Keene and
with other Japanese novelists like Yasunari Kawabata has also been
published recently but has not prompted legal action by the
author's family.
</P>
<P>
   The decision appears to be the first instance in Japan in which
a copyright has been granted for letters. If upheld, it stands to
reverse a venerable literary tradition, both in Japan and
internationally, of the free posthumous publication of
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Amemiya, an official from Fukushima's publisher, told the
Kyodo News Agency that an appeal would be filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
