<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDIT-CORETTA-AIDS21-C     10-20 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CORETTA-AIDS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blacks can't ignore AIDS epidemic
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Wednesday's Atlanta
Constitution.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More leaders in the African-American community are
speaking out about AIDS, and this week a powerful voice turned up
the volume. Addressing students at Atlanta University, Coretta
Scott King urged young people to recognize and defeat the deadly
killer in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   Rising AIDS rates among blacks will not reverse unless other
influential African-Americans join King in speaking openly and
urgently. AIDS death rates are almost 10 times higher among blacks
than whites, although blacks represent only 13 percent of the
American population.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, many churches and civil rights groups remain silent. Their
reticence has been devastating. Young African-Americans are now the
population at greatest risk for infection with HIV. AIDS is the No.
1 cause of death for black males between 25 and 44 and the second
leading cause of death for women in that age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone who cares about the future of black America had
better be speaking out about AIDS, calling for preventive measures,
increased funding for research and treatment,'' said King, widow of
Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Already battling against racism, some black leaders complain
there's not enough energy to add AIDS to their political agenda.
That excuse can no longer be accepted. Too many young men and women
are dying of a preventable disease because of homophobia, ignorance
and embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The stigma against homosexuality in the African-American
community has led to higher rates of bisexuality, researchers
believe. That, in turn, raises infections among women. The stigma
also stymies education efforts and stops people from being tested
for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Because many blacks living with HIV hide the truth, the
community has been able to deceive itself that AIDS wears a
different face, that it is somebody else's burden. Black families
sometimes disguise an AIDS death as cancer or pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlanta University forum, Atlanta activist Denise Stokes
rebuked that myth. Raped at age 13, Stokes has been HIV-positive
for 17 years. Stokes told the spellbound college students that,
``AIDS looks like me, 5'-9'', chocolate brown and healthy
looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Her willingness to give a human face to AIDS will help save
lives. But the message of Stokes and King must be echoed by
preachers in their pulpits, civil rights leaders at their news
conferences and parents in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
