<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-WOOTEN-COLUMN21-COX     10-20 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOOTEN-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Department of Education out of our misery
 &HT;    By Jim Wooten
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Without any essential role in education, the U.S.
Department of Education has developed a fitting use: as a dumping
ground for in-laws, outlaws and other Clinton administration
loyalists in need of steady work _ or at least a steady paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the hiring of political appointees and consultants
outside normal civil service channels is nothing new in
Washington,'' writes Judy Pasternak in a report for The Los Angeles
Times, ``the patronage system is more pervasive at Education than
at any other federal agency.'' One in every 29 workers is a
political appointee, a Democratic loyalist in need of a job, she
reports. For Cabinet departments, the average is one in 807.
</P>
<P>
   They include the president's goddaughter, the transportation
secretary's sister-in-law and a slew of Clinton-Gore campaign
workers. Defeated U.S. Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, now looking for a
better job as U.S. ambassador to New Zealand, became a
$453.84-per-day consultant after being ousted by Illinois voters.
</P>
<P>
   She was hired to provide political advice on school construction
issues, though state and local governments, and not the U.S.
Department of Education, build schools. Although Clinton has sought
to inject the federal government into local school construction,
the department has no money or authority to go there.
</P>
<P>
   But no money, no matter. Another political appointee, former
White House domestic policy Chief Carol H. Rasco, is paid $125,900
to run America Reads. But Congress has provided no funding for the
program, so she essentially makes speeches advising parents to read
to their children.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on. The U.S. Department of Education is a place to
stockpile politicos and to farm out friends without disrupting
anything truly important.
</P>
<P>
   Though bloated with patronage appointments and without any
essential role in education _ a state and local responsibility _
the Department of Education, like the season's mutating flu virus,
simply refuses to go away. Five years ago, conservatives were
promising to eliminate it and to bundle up its appropriations and
dispatch them to the states. Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Congress is even outdoing the Clinton administration
in swamping the department in new money. The Senate Appropriations
Committee would outspend the president by $500 million on
education. Discretionary funding would be increased from $23
billion to $33.5 billion, a 46 percent increase. Both Democrat Al
Gore and Republican George W. Bush promise to expand spending even
more.
</P>
<P>
   A major difference exists, however, in Clinton's approach and
the Republicans'. Clinton wants to expand the federal role in local
schools. To make the intervention palatable and even desirable to
local communities, it's being marketed as ``100,000 new teachers''
to ``shrink'' classroom size.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are willing to expand federal spending, same as
Clinton and more, but they want the money to go as block grants,
with local officials given spending discretion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is insisting he will veto the appropriations bill, and
even hinting of government shutdowns, unless he gets the new
federal spending programs. Clinton and congressional leaders are
negotiating now.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome will be revealing. Conservatives should, of course,
resist all efforts to expand the reach of the U.S. Department of
Education. Priority One is to eliminate it. Until that's possible,
it should be shrunk. If that's not possible, it should be
contained. If that's not possible, it should be expanded, but the
money should be given as block grants to be spent as local school
boards choose. If that's not possible, it should be expanded only
marginally. And next year revert to Priority One.
</P>
<P>
   Elimination of the U.S. Department of Education should be a
permanent priority. Every course conservatives choose every day
should be a step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
