<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ENVIRONMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PRAISES TEXAS CLEANUP PROGRAM, DEFENDS ENVIRONMENTAL RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Under fire from environmentalists in recent weeks over
the declining air quality in some parts of Texas, Gov. George W.
Bush stopped by a ceremonial completion of a contamination cleanup
program Wednesday to condemn pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our prosperity means nothing if we leave future
generations with land that is contaminated,'' he said, standing in
a cavernous former Army Corps of Engineers laboratory that is being
converted into a mission for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The new Union Gospel Mission occupies once-contaminated land
that was cleaned up under federal, state and local programs that
target tainted properties and rehabilitate them.
</P>
<P>
   A state law passed in 1995 _ the Texas Voluntary Cleanup Program
_ offers incentives for redevelopment of such land. Future owners,
lenders or lessors, are released from liability for the land's
previous contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, sites such as this were closed to development
because of wrong management and bad regulations,'' Bush said.
``This program is making them productive again.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the law was passed, Bush said, 400 sites in the state have
been cleaned up and another 500 are in development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very successful program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While a handful of demonstrators across the street held a banner
that said, ``Polluters For Bush _ Thanks Gov,'' Bush defended his
environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   That record has been sharply criticized in recent weeks, largely
because Houston surpassed Los Angeles as the city with America's
dirtiest air and the Dallas-Fort Worth area, under pressure from
the federal government, is considering harsh measures to reduce its
air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air pollution in Texas has declined 10 percent since '94,''
Bush said. ``Toxic pollution has declined 14 percent since '95. We
have high standards and those who don't meet them will be held
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Texas industries were fined $27 million last year for
noncompliance with pollution control measures.
</P>
<P>
   His comments in Dallas came one day after the head of the Texas
Air Crisis Campaign accused the governor of creating an ``air
quality crisis'' in the state by going easy on industrial
polluters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are both sins of omission and sins of emission,'' said
Meg Haenn, referring to the lack of inspection and enforcement by
the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush raised money in Seattle for Sen. Slade Gorton,
R-Wash., who intervened with the Environmental Protection Agency on
behalf of a Houston gold-mining company that wants to run an
open-pit gold mine that environmentalists say will allow cyanide to
leak into the groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic front-runner whom Bush
has dismissed as an ``environmental extremist,'' plans to lob his
second attack on Bush's environmental record Thursday in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
