<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     10-20 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A SERIES TO REMEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cancel the limo. Don't bother upgrading the funds in
your EZ-Pass account. Never mind laying in extra Metrocards.
</P>
<P>
   The Subway Series is not going to happen, and maybe it is just
as well. The grandiosity and braggadocio and civic incivility
emanating from New York would have been too, too much.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers would have whipped themselves into a xenophobic
frenzy over a Subway Series, which would have been yet another sign
that New York is the center of the universe. Since everybody
sensible already knows that, who needed rival hordes riding the
Triborough Bridge and the IRT subway to prove the redundancy?
</P>
<P>
   Better to have self-important Yankee fans spewing their verbal
abuse and conformist Atlanta fans Tomahawk-chopping on command,
regional stereotypes coming true. A World Series of cliches. North
vs. South. Big Boss vs. Big Ted. Bluster vs. Bombast. Fine.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how much can the fragile national ticker stand? The
dysfunctional Mets, a collection of disparate types who became
something akin to a team, thrilled the entire baseball diaspora
with their highs, their lows, their ups, their downs, as Lerner and
Loewe put it. We've grown accustomed to their inconsistencies.
</P>
<P>
   After all the local boosterism anticipating a Subway Series, the
Mets and the Yankees could only have been a hypester's letdown
compared to what transpired on recent nights.
</P>
<P>
   Zombie-like, people shuffled into work the next morning, still
replaying the machinations of the Braves-Mets series. People
bickered at the water cooler, disputing Bobby Valentine's logic on
the double switch in his lineup card or Bobby Cox's implacable
hesitancy to go for the jugular in the rain forest that was Shea
Stadium last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With Tout New York waiting for the Subway Series, the Braves and
the Mets merely played the most exciting series imaginable,
although it took awhile for the plot to become apparent.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games, the Braves, built with logic for the
past decade, pushed the Mets onto the tracks in front of an
oncoming Marta train.
</P>
<P>
   (Atlanta has its own little toy subway, by the way, two
bisecting lines with clean cars and quiet wheels and audible
announcements and readable graphics, rather than the Tunnel of
Babel system that is New York.)
</P>
<P>
   After losing the third game in front of their screeching home
folks, the Mets promptly clambered onto the platform. They won on
Saturday night in 10 innings, then Sunday night in 15 innings, with
both teams running out of players.
</P>
<P>
   Glorious personal things kept happening _ unexpected things, by
unexpected people, the way it happens with baseball, with its deep
25-player rosters and timeless games. Bearded John Smoltz, the
Braves' great pitcher, trudged out of the bullpen for the first
time in his career to save a game. A reserve catcher named Eddie
Perez clubbed vital home runs like a latter-day Yogi or Campy or
Bench.
</P>
<P>
   A bumpkin named John Rocker, with hair-trigger linebacker
emotions, dared to criticize the bards of the No. 7 line for their
foul language, if you can imagine. Now eyewitnesses are coming
forth with tales of the righteous Rocker making obscene gestures to
the fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets unveiled a player named Melvin Mora who had barely
spent time with the varsity during the season. The Mets were
clearly hiding him, for the value of a shock. By the extra-inning
games, Mora had gained the aura of a modern Mookie, that sweet and
mobile icon of the Mets' 1986 world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Mora ran. Mora caught. Mora threw. Mora hit. One can hardly wait
for spring training for Mora to resume his career. Or perhaps
nothing like this will ever happen to him again in his life, or our
lives. But for those late nights in October of 1999, there was
Melvin Mora.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 48 hours, the world persuaded itself that there could
never be another game like the 15-inning madness in Flushing. But
there was. On Tuesday night in Atlanta, the Braves went ahead by
scores of 5-0 and 7-3. Then it was the Braves who had to fight
back, not once but twice.
</P>
<P>
   'Round midnight, between Tuesday and Wednesday, the Braves
mounted a rally. It ended with the weakest of series-winning
efforts, a bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and other rabid towns, fans toss back balls hit by a
yokel like Chipper (Lar-ree! Lar-ree!) Jones. The Braves did not
decline the gift. They wanted to get their fans back to the 'burbs.
They had to catch the Marta to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Now the stage belongs to the Braves and the Yankees, but Mets
fans have their memories. In time, people will forget the angst of
the manager who called for his own scalp in the midst of a losing
streak. Fans will remember a pitching staff without an ace that
somehow terrorized the Braves up until 12:38 a.m. on the morning of
Oct. 20. The fans will remember the infield of Olerud and Alfonzo
and Ordonez and Ventura, who scooped up everything, and the big
gentle slugger, Mike Piazza, behind the plate, and mercurial Rickey
and promising Cedeno and Darryl Hamilton who came late with a
twinkle in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the third-best team in baseball,'' bragged Todd Pratt,
the useful reserve catcher, in the grieving clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   There is room for only two teams in the World Series. There will
be no transfer at Grand Central Terminal, no tollbooth on the
Triborough.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series between the Braves and the Yanks can never
possibly measure up to the league championship series. We've all
been wrong with those kind of predictions, haven't we? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
