<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-PAPON-NYT &LR;      10-20 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PAPON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED VICHY OFFICIAL CHOOSES EXILE OVER PRISON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ With only hours to go before he was to spend his first
night in jail, Maurice Papon, the 89-year-old career civil servant
convicted last year of complicity in Nazi war crimes, said
Wednesday that he would flee the country rather than surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Papon disappeared from his home near Paris a week ago, just
after a court ruled that he would have to start serving his 10-year
sentence before his appeal could be heard. He made no statement at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But in a four-paragraph statement issued to newspapers here
Wednesday, Papon made clear that he had no intention of giving
himself up, as the court had ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the latest court ruling only ``the crown'' on a long
list of illegal acts that had marked the investigation and trial
against him, Papon said he would ask the European Court of Human
Rights to condemn France for denying him a fair proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said, the only ``honorable course was exile,
as painful as this might be for a man in his 90th year.'' He added
that exile was ``a choice that had been made by some of the most
noted men of history.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials immediately said that they would use all
measures possible to find Papon, who has steadfastly refused to
take any blame for the hundreds of Jews deported from France to
Nazi death camps under his signature as the third-ranking official
of the Vichy government in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maurice Papon will, at the request of the prosecutor, be
pursued, apprehended wherever he is, and taken to the penitentiary
establishment where he will serve his sentence,'' said Daniel
Vaillant, the government's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin condemned the flight as a cowardly
act and said France would ask for Papon's extradition if it turns
out he is indeed in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Papon's actions shocked many of his victims and their families
and is likely to raise questions about whether Papon still has
friends in high places protecting him. After the war, Papon went on
to serve as Paris' prefect of police and then budget minister. He
regularly met with President Francois Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
   His statement Wednesday also set off an avalanche of speculation
about where he had gone; his chief lawyer, Jean-Marc Varaut, said
he would not discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those representing the victims and their families blamed
authorities for allowing Papon to remain free without restrictions
after he was convicted. They pointed out that Papon's passport was
never confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put people in jail for stealing chickens, but this man
who is responsible for the death of hundreds of people just walks
free to go back to living in his chateau,'' said Therese Stopnicki,
whose two sisters were taken away under Papon's orders.
</P>
<P>
   Serge Klarsfeld, who helped collect the evidence against Papon
and whose son Arno represented some of the victims' families during
the trial, also admonished the authorities. ``We always believed he
would do this,'' Klarsfeld said. ``We warned the government and
they did nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stand during his trial, Papon argued that he had
actually saved Jews and done favors for the French Resistance. To
hear him tell it, if his Office of Jewish Questions had not existed
the Nazi ravages would have been much worse than they actually
were, with far more than 74,000 of the 330,000 Jews living in
France deported to Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, after the longest trial in modern French history,
Papon was convicted of helping to transport Jews to Nazi death
camps and sentenced to 10 years in prison. The court also ordered
Papon to pay $750,000 in damages and legal fees to the victims and
their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Under French law, he was required to turn himself in for one
night in jail before his appeal hearing, scheduled for Thursday,
could begin. His lawyers said they would now seek a delay in
Papon's appeal proceeding, based on the notion that the case was
being appealed to the European Human Rights Court. No precedent
exists for such a request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
