<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-KENNEDY-AWARDS-ART-NY     10-20 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-AWARDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINTERS TAKES TWAIN PRIZE FOR HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif.)  (Duplication warning: also moving in `e' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jonathan Winters, who came to Washington to receive
the Mark Twain Prize for humor from the Kennedy Center for
Performing Arts on Wednesday night, warmed up for the event in the
afternoon with a discussion in which it was difficult to separate
the serious from his improvisational wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a true story,'' he began, an introduction that made
the listener wonder if it really was, and he went on to tell about
a recent trip around the world that found him one day at the Temple
of Athena in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman asked what I thought of it,'' he related, ``and I said
that I was terribly disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it goes back five centuries before Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been fixed by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters will be 74 years old next month, and he made most of his
movies before actors were able to demand multimillion-dollar fees.
Robin Williams, who came to Washington to participate in the
tribute to Williams, gets $20 million for a movie, Winters said.
</P>
<P>
   So he said he told a studio executive, ``If Robin says I'm his
idol, shouldn't you give me $1 million more than that?''
</P>
<P>
   It did not work, and Winters said that for his movie work, which
includes ``It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World'' and ``The Russians Are
Coming! The Russians Are Coming!'', his biggest pay was $130,000.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Williams, many other comedians came to Washington to pay
homage to Winters and make some people smile.
</P>
<P>
   At a panel discussion at the Kennedy Center on the golden age of
television on Tuesday night, Steve Allen said a lot of humor comes
from the art of exaggeration, and he gave this example from Fred
Allen:
</P>
<P>
   ``This scarecrow was so scary that not only did it scare away
the crows, but they also came back with corn they had stolen two
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Sid Caesar told two stories about television sponsors in the
1950s, one funny and the other serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinah Shore wanted to book Tennessee Ernie Ford,'' Caesar
said, ``but she was told she couldn't because she was sponsored by
Chevrolet. She solved it by having him on as Tennessee Ernie
Chevrolet.''
</P>
<P>
   Caesar told of his own booking problem: When he tried to
schedule the singer Billy Daniels, who was known for his rendition
of ``That Old Black Magic,'' it was vetoed by the sponsor, Camel
cigarettes, because Daniels was black.
</P>
<P>
   That happened so many years ago that Carole Crosslin, a
spokeswoman for R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., the makers of Camels,
said Wednesday, ``I have no idea whether this ever happened and no
way of finding out.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters is the second recipient of the Mark Twain Prize for
humor. The first prize was awarded last year to Richard Pryor.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute to Winters was taped for broadcast on Jan. 12 on the
Comedy Central network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; taf-z
