<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNESCO-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNESCO CHOOSES MATSUURA OF JAPAN AS   NEW DIRECTOR GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ALAN RIDING    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Unesco executive board Wednesday chose Japan's
ambassador to France, Koichiro Matsuura, as director general of the
organization. Matsuura's nomination for a six-year term is expected
to be confirmed by the 186-nation general conference of Unesco when
it meets here on Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese diplomat had long been considered a strong
contender, because Japan is the largest contributor to the $544
million biannual budget of the U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization. He also benefited from intense lobbying by
his government, which has in recent years been seeking a higher
profile in international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Matsuura, 62, the front-runner in the first two ballots
conducted by the 58-nation executive board this week, won a
majority, with 34 votes. Ghazi Algosaibi, Saudi Arabia's ambassador
to London, was second, with 13. This election was the most open to
date. But the outcome was no less conventional than in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Unesco headquarters here has been buzzing
with rumors that the Japanese and Saudi governments had promised
generous aid packages to several third world countries in exchange
for their votes. Japanese and Saudi diplomats strongly denied
engaging in so-called checkbook diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The election has nonetheless brought to the surface widespread
unhappiness with the way Unesco and its 2,326-member staff have
been run by its current director general, Federico Mayor Zaragoza
of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor promised sweeping change in 1987, when he succeeded Amadou
Mahtar M'Bow of Senegal, whose left-leaning scandal-ridden tenure
prompted a walkout in 1985 by the United States and Britain. But in
recent years, Mayor has come under increasing criticism. An
external audit requested by Canada last year said that Unesco was
wracked by inefficiency and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
   Although candidates to succeed Mayor did not directly attack his
administration, some made it clear that they believed that Unesco
needed a thorough shake-up. Matsuura, though, was decidedly more
cautious, noting in a campaign statement that ``I hope to make it a
more dynamic, efficient and harmonious organization'' and to win
recognition of Unesco's ``usefulness and dynamic potential.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent reference to the United States, where he studied
economics at Haverford College in Pennsylvania in the late 1950s,
Matsuura also said he would extend an invitation to nonmember
states to join. Although Britain returned after Prime Minister Tony
Blair's Labor government took office in 1997, congressional
hostility toward Unesco still appears to stand in the way of the
United States' rejoining in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-WAHID-1STLD     10-20 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-WAHID-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S NEW PRESIDENT CAN BE A MYSTERY, EVEN TO HIS FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds: SUBS 15th graf, There have ..., to CORRECT, assassinated
Israeli leader was Yitzhak Rabin, sted Shimon Peres.) (With INDONESIA-POLITICS) 
(nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The revealing title of a biography of
Indonesia's new president, published just last week, is ``Gus Dur:
Who Are You?''
</P>
<P>
   It is a question many people, using his common nickname, ask
about President Abdurrahman Wahid. Indeed, the better people know
him the more often they ask it.
</P>
<P>
   His shifting pronouncements, alliances and public stands have
led to a common joke in Indonesia that there are three things you
can never be certain about: life, death and Gus Dur.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, 59, a moderate Muslim leader who is one of the nation's
most prominent public figures, decided to become a presidential
candidate only this month, breaking a political partnership with
the woman he eventually defeated, Megawati Sukarnoputri.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone here dismissed his candidacy as unrealistic,
vain and even, literally, crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gus Dur is strange, strange,'' a former Cabinet minister who
knows him well, Sarwono Kusumaatmadja, said at the time. ``In no
way should he stand as a candidate. He is in ill health. He
suffered a major stroke one and a half years ago. It has impaired
his judgment and he is showing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has suffered two strokes in recent years. He is also
nearly blind, guided everywhere he goes, even around his own home,
by an aide and accustomed to delivering his speeches without notes.
He traveled this fall to Salt Lake City for laser surgery, which he
said restored some black-and-white vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has been examined,'' he assured a local magazine
after declaring his candidacy. ``Stomach, kidney, blood, mental and
memory assessment. Everything is good, excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   His health aside, Wahid is revered by millions of Indonesians as
a brilliant and cultured man and the apostle of a tolerant and
inclusive brand of Islam that many people say embodies the best in
Indonesian society.
</P>
<P>
   As the leader of the nation's largest social group, a Muslim
organization called Nahdlatul Ulama, he has championed the rights
of minorities, of non-Muslims and particularly of the often-abused
community of ethnic Chinese. His organization claims a membership
of more than 30 million people.
</P>
<P>
   In his nickname, Gus is a Muslim honorific and Dur is an
affectionate use of the second syllable of his name.
</P>
<P>
   Though Indonesia _ the world's most-populous Muslim nation with
more than 200 million people _ practices a more moderate style of
Islam than is characteristic in the Middle East, Wahid has been
criticized by some clerics here for his ecumenism.
</P>
<P>
   He responds: ``Those who say that I am not Islamic enough should
reread their Koran. Islam is about inclusion, tolerance,
community.''
</P>
<P>
   His first gesture after his election Wednesday was
characteristic. Still sitting among the delegates to the national
assembly, he took the hand of Mrs. Megawati and continued holding
it as he joined in the singing of the national anthem and she
struggled to hold back tears. Then he raised her hand in a shared
salute of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other gestures in the past. When other Muslim
leaders here joined in the condemnation of the British author
Salman Rushdie, Wahid stood alone in his defense. When others
condemned Israel, he visited Jerusalem to accept a prize in honor
of the assassinated leader Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid received his Islamic education in Egypt and Iraq and he is
noted as a religious scholar. But his interests also range from the
arts (he was a member of a Jakarta arts council) to soccer (he once
wrote about the sport for the magazine Tempo). He is a lover of
Beethoven and Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He is also known for his love of pranks. He recently placed his
traditional Indonesian cap atop a bust of Beethoven and posed for a
photographer side by side with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jokes a lot, almost continuously,'' said a leading editor,
Goenawan Mohamad. ``Gus Dur loves joking _ of course at the expense
of others.''
</P>
<P>
   In one joke recounted by a friend, Wahid said Christians are
closer to God than Muslims because they whisper when they pray,
whereas Muslims have to chant their prayers through loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   While he is admired for his culture, he is also revered among
Indonesia's uneducated masses for more exotic qualities: He is
believed to have supernatural powers.
</P>
<P>
   After his election Wednesday, a radio host joked about his
blindness, saying that since a sniper uses just one eye, Wahid
would probably make a fine sniper.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing the joke, a taxi driver was aghast. ``He'd better be
careful what he says,'' the driver said of the radio host. ``Gus
Dur has a sixth sense and can send you bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Trusting in his special powers, people sometimes come to him for
guidance, an Indonesian journalist said. Sometimes they drink from
his unfinished glasses of water hoping to imbibe his spirit.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new president's demeanor and his changeability lead to a
good deal of confusion about him. Is he smart or foolish?
</P>
<P>
   Wahid seems to relish the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that everyone is now confused, with three
presidential candidates,'' he said as he challenged Mrs. Megawati
and the incumbent president, B.J. Habibie. ``So we will build a new
democracy based on the confusion of the assembly members.''
</P>
<P>
   A leading political scientist, Arief Budiman, worried Wednesday
that Wahid had been seriously damaged by his strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new Gus Dur is different from the old Gus Dur,'' he said.
``We can hope for the old Gus Dur. But what we can expect now is a
combination of the two. Sometimes he may be confused in his
actions, and that will have to be compensated for by his
advisers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Goenawan, the editor, there is no question about Wahid's
sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he is very clever,'' Goenawan said. ``But whether you can
trust him is another matter. He is too clever to be consistent.
That will make it very difficult for people to be comfortable with
his political positions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
