<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3169 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ARUBA-$ADV24-2     10-20 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ARUBA-$ADV24-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAILING THE BLUE HIGHWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 24) 
(jt) 
 By JERI CLAUSING    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the first things I noticed when we arrived for our
much-anticipated week at Aruba's famous windsurfing village last
December was the so-called Blue Highway, a streak of light blue
water about a quarter-mile offshore where masters of the sport zip
back and forth at speeds as high as 40 mph.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sea was flat and clear. That, combined with steady trade
winds and sunny skies, made it immediately apparent why Aruba has
become one of the favorite destinations of windsurfers from all
over the world, and the location for the sport's premier high-speed
sailing contest, the Aruba Hi Winds Competition, in June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, as we prepared for our first windsurfing
venture, the young Dutchman who was helping out for the high season
at our guesthouse, Roger's Windsurf Place, showed us a map of the
beach and the shallow reefs to avoid. Out where the reef ends was
the Blue Highway, clearly marked, for experts only. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Experts only? I want to be sailing that before we leave,'' I
said with a cocky smile, half joking. Nonetheless, I was confident
that I had mastered the basics of the sport during my first
windsurfing vacation in the Outer Banks of North Carolina a few
months before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If only I had known how quickly that wish would come true. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blessed, or perhaps cursed, with the first strong winds of the
season, Roger (pronounced roh-ZHAY) Jurriens, the owner of Roger's
Windsurf Place, set my husband, Roberto, and me up on beginner
boards and sails, reminding us that we could swap equipment any
time if they weren't fast enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The offshore winds were gusting over 20 knots as we headed out.
Roger reminded us to sail close in, parallel to shore (and to the
Blue Highway) so as not to get blown out too far, where the winds
are even stronger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sailing any direction would have been just fine with me. Just
when I'd get my balance and start moving, a gust would catch me off
guard and I'd plunge back into the water. After an hour or so of
struggling, I was getting a little more comfortable with the wind
and caught a few decent runs. But I was still falling a lot, and
getting exhausted hoisting the heavy sail back up each time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Be patient, I told myself, unaware of how far out I was drifting
every time I had to pull myself and my sail out of the water and
get back into the proper beginner position. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I got up and caught a good, fast ride, but I kept getting pushed
out. For some reason, my basics in steering didn't seem to be
working. Then I caught a big gust and went flying forward. My knee
crashed into the board. Frustrated, in pain, and too far from
anyone else to worry about my composure, I clung to the board and
cried. After the initial pain and panic began to subside, I decided
to try swimming the board back closer to shore. I'm a strong
swimmer, but trying to swim a sailboard into the wind is like
trying to swim against a current. It didn't take long to realize
that wasn't going to work. And every time I kicked, my knee felt
odd, as if it were popping. I started looking around for the boats
that the windsurfing rental places keep on alert, ready to drag in
novices like me. Just my luck the boat was beached. I took a deep
breath and tried again. Another big gust toppled me. So I finally
gave up and sat down on the board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, as another sailor zipped by, I realized where I was.
Yes, out in the expert-only area, stranded on the Blue Highway.
Panic set in. But I tried to hide it. Finally, at the sailor's
urging, I swallowed my pride, put my arms over my head and began
waving for a rescue. Not exactly the way I'd planned to make my
debut on the Aruba windsurfing scene. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back at shore courtesy of the rescue boat, I sheepishly dragged
myself out of the water just as Roberto _ who, unaware of my
misadventure, had been off sailing on his own _ was coming in. He
had managed to make it back, but he was equally frustrated. Roger
promised a lesson the next day to get us on track. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite our frustration, we were pleased with Aruba and our
accommodations. Roberto likes to vacation in remote places, so I
had booked the seven-day trip at Roger's guesthouse _ all equipment
included _ as a holiday surprise. Then I kept hearing about how
developed the island had become. That made me nervous. It's true
that downtown Oranjestad and the hotel strip that extends north
almost to the island's main windsurfing area in Malmok are quite
built up, with shops and casinos catering not only to resort guests
but also to the heavy cruise ship traffic. But the development has
been tastefully done in the tradition of Aruba's Dutch Colonial
heritage, and the island is very clean. We saw no poverty anywhere
on the island. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aruba is flat and arid, its plant life an odd mix of tropical
growth and cactus. In the northwest and parts of the interior, it
almost looks as if a chunk of Arizona had been plopped into the
Caribbean. The beaches vary. Along the northern shore, there are
mostly rocky cliffs overlooking very rough surf. The windsurf area
and the hotels are on the western side, which boasts pristine
white, sandy beaches.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a small island, just 20 miles long and 6 miles across at
its widest point. Oranjestad is the capital and tourism center.
Sint Nicolaas, to the southeast, is the industrial area, with an
oil refinery. To the north are various attractions including a
natural bridge that was formed by the rough Atlantic surf. On the
southwestern side is Savaneta, the oldest town in Aruba, the former
capital and now a fishing village. It is here that the Dutch first
settled after re-establishing control of the island in 1816. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The windsurf strip was just far enough away from the bustle of
Oranjestad to satisfy my taste. Nestled in an oceanfront
neighborhood that is more like a suburb than a resort area, Roger's
guesthouse is actually a three-room extension of the house where he
grew up and where his parents still live. The rooms, simply
furnished, with private baths and cable television, are spotless
and share a courtyard and kitchen. Each room has a deck, where you
can watch the windsurfers, read, have a beer with other guests or
feed the resident geckos.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was quiet, relaxed and friendly. We made friends,
swapping windsurfing stories and sometimes exploring restaurants
together or trying our hand at blackjack in one of the island's 11
casinos. The casinos are simpler and for the most part smaller than
those in Las Vegas or Atlantic City, and never seemed crowded. Most
of the bettors are tourists, as the government restricts how often
residents can gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around the island is quite easy. If you're content to
stay around the hotel and downtown areas, there is no need to rent
a car. Buses run regularly from near the windsurf area, through the
hotel strips and into town. But we enjoyed having a car, which we
rented for about $20 a day, because we could look for more
traditional restaurants and explore the island. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment was the lack of unique restaurants.
There is no real Aruban food. The island is a Dutch territory with
a heavy Dutch influence. The food is a lot like the language,
Papiamento, a creolized Spanish with admixtures of Dutch and
Portuguese. With a little searching, we did find a few good
restaurants such as Gasparito, offering seafood and pork and
chicken dishes with an island flair. But the restaurants in town
were mostly mediocre, serving food much like that you could find in
chain restaurants in any United States city.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the real mission of the trip was to windsurf, not sightsee
or gamble. We soon discovered it was going to take a lot more than
a week to master anything beyond the very basics. And I was already
limping from what I later found out was torn knee cartilage from my
first-day fall.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We had already signed up for a lesson, so I hobbled across the
courtyard to the windsurf shop and listened to Roger review the
basics for us. My problem, and one of the big problems with the
sport, became immediately clear: different instructors teach very
different basics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So I went to the beach and watched Roberto windsurf. He seemed
to be doing better with Roger's techniques. Later we took the
afternoon off to explore the the natural bridge, a place where the
ocean has carved out an overpass in the rocks on the Western
shore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day, braced with Advil, I decided to get back onto the
board. But first we had another lesson. This time Roger was showing
us how to use a harness to hook ourselves to the sail. Although it
makes it easier to sail fast without so much strain on your arms,
there is a steep learning curve, he warned. You will take a lot of
spills into the sail before you learn how to unhook the harness
when falling. I decided to stick to the basics and not push
myself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be a wise choice. Roberto went out and almost
immediately fell into the mast, bruising his ribs. The next trip to
town was in search of a jumbo bottle of Advil.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We were certainly learning that this sport was much more painful
and difficult than we had anticipated. But Roger's is not overrun
with scheduled lessons from outside guests, so staying there was
really like having a private instructor. And one of the best things
about Aruba is that from December through June you are almost
guaranteed rain-free windy days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite our injuries, we pushed ourselves to sail better each
day. And Roger was a good and patient teacher. His credentials were
impressive: he represented Aruba at the Olympic windsurfing
competition in Barcelona in 1992. Still, every time we tried to go
up a notch, it felt like starting over. ``No pain, no gain,'' our
fellow, more experienced windsurfers didn't fail to remind us with
a smile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As our stay was ending, we were still frustrated. After a little
discussion, we signed on for three more days. On our last day we
were still in pain but felt we had managed to improve. We made
ambitious plans for more sailing in the United States. As we said
goodbye, I vowed, ``Next time you see me, I'll be sailing the Blue
Highway.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go:
</P>
<P>
   ROGER'S WINDSURF PLACE, 472 L.G. Smith Boulevard, Malmok, Aruba,
(297) 861-918, offers convenient packages that include unlimited
use of equipment that is stored right across the street from the
beach. Gear can be tied out in the water for easy breaks, or easily
swapped throughout the day if you want try different sizes of
boards or sails. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For $700 a week each, not including air fare, we had a room at
Roger's guesthouse. For about $100 more, you can rent an apartment
in a small building with a pool. The rates, which start at $600 a
week, go up slightly from late December through June, and drop from
July through December. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Private lessons with Roger cost $75 an hour. Or you can buy
three hours of private lessons for $200. When you're a guest, he is
quite flexible about breaking up the time over different days to
suit your needs. He also offers group lessons, as well as hourly
and daily equipment rentals for people not staying in one of his
rooms or apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GASPARITO, 3 Gasparito, (297) 867-044, is a nice, family-owned
restaurant set in a neighborhood away from the main hotel strip.
The menu offers a mix of authentic Aruban dishes, as well as
internationally inspired entrees, such as barracuda-stuffed
ravioli. I enjoyed the Aruban combo, which included samplings of
seafood and meat dishes cooked Aruban style. None of the dishes
were too hot, but they still had an interesting mix of spices.
Dinner with wine averages $30 a person.
</P>
<P>
   BOONOONOONOOS, 18A Wilhelmina-straat in downtown Oranjestad,
(297) 831-888, bills itself as an Aruba Caribbean Bistroquet. Its
more traditionally Caribbean menu includes Jamaican jerk ribs,
roast chicken Barbados and plantain dishes. Its pumpkin soup was
delicious, as were the Cuban-style garlic shrimp. Dinner with wine,
$30 a person.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
