<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-BUSH-HNS &LR;      10-20 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BLASTS BUSH ON ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday sharply
criticized the environmental record of Republican presidential
front-runner George W. Bush and suggested that turning the White
House over to the GOP next year could have a disastrous
repercussions for the Adirondacks and the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Washington with reporters
representing eight New York news organizations, Gore said Bush's
environmental policies have resulted in Texas having the most
polluted air, water and land in the nation. He also accused the
Texas governor of fostering an unhealthy relationship between his
state's environmental regulators and polluting industries, and said
Bush ``has carried water for the special interests; he has carried
dirty water for the special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign insisted that the Texas governor is committed
to the environment and has signed legislation to reduce toxic
wastes and other pollutants. Spokesman Scott McClellan said Bush
was ``mystified'' by the vice president's remarks Wednesday and
``like New Yorkers ... (is) interested to know what Mr. Gore has
done to clean up the Hudson River during the last seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is locked in a tight contest with former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic presidential nomination,
declined to say specifically what he would do to control Midwestern
factory emissions that cause acid rain to fall on the Adirondacks,
or how he would address the problem of PCB, or polychlorinated
biphenyl, contamination of the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   However, the vice president, who has a long history of
environmental activism, said his record on the environment stands
in stark contrast to Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you look at Governor Bush's record in Texas
you would have to conclude that if ... he had the opportunity to
take the same approach nationally, we would see the same kind of
results,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was ``committed to a cleanup of the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Also during the telephone interview, Gore:
</P>
<P>
   _ Promoted the ``next step in welfare reform,'' a plan aimed at
strengthening child support collections and increasing parental
responsibility. The proposal, released in Washington on Wednesday,
would require fathers who owe child support to pay up or go to
work, deny new credit cards to parents who owe support, eliminate
the ``marriage penalty'' in the tax code to encourage couples to
stay together and provide government grants for marriage counseling
and parenting classes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sidestepped questions on whether he supports dairy compacts,
which require milk processors to pay farmers a minimum price for
their milk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Renewed his challenge to Bradley to engage in a series of
debates before the end of the year and quipped that his opponent
would only agree to debate on the ``eve of Christmas'' at 11:30 on
a Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bradley has agreed to participate in six debates
before the end of January _ two of them before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Denied ever calling Bradley a ``quitter'' for retiring from
the Senate in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ignored comments suggesting that he had allowed or encouraged
surrogates, New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer and Comptroller
H. Carl McCall, to do name-calling for him.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent political event, Spitzer and McCall harshly
criticized Bradley for choosing to leave the Senate in 1996 rather
than continue battling with the Republican majority. Bradley, who
had served in Senate for 18 years, was among seven Democratic
senators who left office in 1996, and the Gore campaign repeatedly
suggested that Bradley abandoned his party and principles.
</P>
<P>
   However, with that issue clearly not resonating with voters,
Gore seemed to back off somewhat on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Gore and Bradley running neck-and-neck in New York, a
critical battleground for both the primary and general elections,
and both candidates are stepping up their activity in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been to New York state several times in recent weeks.
Bradley is scheduled to campaign in Schenectady and Albany on
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
