<HEADLINE>
A LONG LIFE WITH DOLPHINS AND ICE CREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (For release Thursday, Oct. 28) 
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TYBEE ISLAND, Ga. _ Frances introduced herself by saying she
first came to Tybee Island on her honeymoon in ``nineteen hundred
and thirty-three,'' drawing it out all slow and syrupy. It became a
favorite vacation spot of hers and her late husband's and she had
``no idea this is where I'd end up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ending up on an island off the coast of Georgia, bothered only
by the occasional hurricane threat, we told her, looks pretty good.
Don't even talk about that Floyd, she said, pulling a face and
calling it a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   She, along with everyone else on the island, was forced to
evacuate and that meant she spent 14 hours in traffic with her son
and daughter-in-law driving to Atlanta and then turning around and
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes don't worry her. At 89, she says ``someone's always
saying it's going to blow hard and then it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Two friends and I came to Georgia for a long weekend, choosing
the Savannah area because we thought it sounded exotic, we like
grits and we'd read ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   We often talk about how we'll still be together when we're very
old, sitting on a porch somewhere, finishing each other's sentences
and continuing to bicker over politics and the acting abilities of
Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   Even though an 89-year-old kindly called us ``y'all girls,'' the
idea of how and where people end up is something we relate to. We
notice a woman like Frances, walking barefoot with a cane, gold
earrings in, cutting a sharp figure in a cream-colored blouse
tucked into cream-colored shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Frances has a best friend, too, whose name is Mabel and who just
turned 90. They've known each other since they were 5 and 6 years
old. Mabel was there when Frances gave birth, telling her when to
push and forever claiming that Frances' son Charlie is part hers.
Frances keeps a photograph of Mabel on her coffee table and the two
talk on the phone every day.
</P>
<P>
   Since Frances moved to the island, seven of her friends have
died and five have moved into nursing homes. My friends and I know
about people dying and living in nursing homes. Frances has lived
longer and happier than two of our mothers. We prefer her way.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't plan ahead to age well. She claims she never even got
much exercise before she started walking up three flights of stairs
three times a day from the beach to her apartment. She says
``people have always spoiled me,'' including her son, who lives
down the beach and comes by every day.
</P>
<P>
   Her balcony looks out to where the wide Savannah River joins the
Atlantic. From a tall captain's chair she sees container ships go
by and shrimp boats, like the ones in ``Forrest Gump.'' She has a
sunset view of the Savannah skyline. On the beach, groups of people
catch shrimp in wide nets, and someone is always dropping off some
at her door.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all there are dolphins. If you've never been here before
you will stare at the water when the sun is coming up and think you
see a swimmer, but it's a fin. When that fin becomes a
better-than-Sea World leaping dolphin, you'll jump up and down in
your pajamas and force your friends awake for the miracle, which as
it turns out, happens every morning with many dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Frances streamlined her life when she moved to Tybee, giving
most of her furniture to relatives who still had big houses and
taking with her mostly photographs of friends and family. She may
have great stories to tell. She hinted at something involving Henry
Ford and a woman she once knew. But she wants to talk about our
lives as much as we do hers and invites us back for ice cream,
``any time before midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   So, that's what we'll strive for. To live long and be lucky
enough to wake up to dolphins and eat ice cream before bed.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
