<HEADLINE>
HAVE MILLENNIUM ANXIETY? BLAME THE MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, Oct. 22) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the American Dialect Society (how many ``Brand X''
humor-columns begin with those words?), Millennium Anxiety
Disorder, or MAD, was one of the top-three new words in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that you have never heard of the term Millennium
Anxiety Disorder before could be a sign that you are suffering from
the thing. Or it could simply mean that you do not keep up with the
comings and goings of the American Dialect Society, which is
another problem entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the American Dialect Society are much too busy
nominating words in categories like ``most useful,'' ``most
unnecessary'' and ``most outrageous'' to offer any clues to what
the causes and, more importantly, the cures, of Millennium Anxiety
Disorder might be. This is just another service that I perform,
along with weekly updates on my dog.
</P>
<P>
   If you look around, it is obvious that nearly everyone is
suffering from MAD, to a greater or lesser extent. If you're
nervous, excited and irritable, chances are you're suffering from
MAD. If you're not nervous, excited or irritable, then you are deep
in MAD-denial, which is even worse. Like everything else that's
wrong with America today, the blame rests squarely on the hairy,
sloping, apelike shoulders of the evolution-loving media.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the media drove us crazy by repeating the phrase
``millennium bug,'' ``millennium bug,'' ``millennium bug'' over and
over again until some of us went completely over the edge and began
collecting Pokemon cards, which apparently can be boiled down into
a nourishing broth in the event of the apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   (The American Dialect Society, which does not create the problem
but simply acknowledges it, voted ``millennium bug'' the 1997 Word
of the Year.)
</P>
<P>
   The media hammered other words into the American consciousness
with equally predictable results. One example is the phrase
``sexual relations'' (No. 2 Word of the Year for 1998; No. 5 in the
category Most Euphemistic), one of many anxiety-producing words
that emerged from Monicagate (there's another). Another is ``Big
She'' as a synonym for you-know-who, and the verb ``Lewinsky,''
which means to have what might or might not be sexual relations
with another person, depending on what your definition of the word
``person'' might be.
</P>
<P>
   (All Monica-related words, by the way, were voted, as a wad, the
Most Unnecessary Words of 1998. Can we give the American Dialect
Society some sort of medal?)
</P>
<P>
   Other media-promoted words that could lead directly or
indirectly to Millennium Anxiety Disorder include e-commerce,
Viagra, road rage, wrong-site surgery (euphemism for cutting off
the wrong leg, arm or whatever), angst bunny (young woman with
black clothes and lots of body piercings), symmetry failure
(another term for wrong-site surgery) and dot (to strike someone
with the light from a laser pointer).
</P>
<P>
   So if the media are responsible for Millennium Anxiety Disorder
(and I think we have established that beyond a shadow of a doubt),
then what is the cure? Less media? Good luck. That's like telling a
Florida resident that the cure for mildew is less humidity.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm afraid that the media, like professional wrestling, will
be with us for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium itself, however, is another story. In another 78
days, we'll be able to put this whole thing behind us. All the
world's computers will have crashed or they won't have crashed.
Either way, it will be over.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you happen to be one of those annoying
literalists who insist that the millennium will not end until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If you are, then I hope you come down with Millennium Anxiety
Disorder so bad that you require wrong-site surgery from a
road-raging angst-bunny.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3182 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-20 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BRADLEY'S POVERTY PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Bradley, eschewing small themes in favor of a
grander vision of America, will argue Thursday, at a speech in
Brooklyn, that the United States has a moral obligation to do what
it can to lift as many children as possible from the punishing
confines of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a time of unprecedented prosperity,'' he said in an
interview, ``and yet there are still nearly 14 million children who
live in poverty. I think there is a broad consensus that we need to
change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he planned to ``lay out a broad goal to reduce
child poverty by a specific amount at a specific time.'' And he
will detail what he described as the initial steps, or ``down
payment,'' needed to move toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   The speech is scheduled for Thursday morning at the Concord
Baptist Church in Bedford-Stuyvesant. And like his proposal to make
health care available to virtually all uninsured Americans, and his
insistence that a Bradley administration would work constantly to
break down racial barriers, his approach to child poverty appears
to be far more ambitious than the terminally incremental
initiatives that have plagued the country since the Clinton health
plan imploded.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his speech would address the following: ``How do we
increase income for people who are poor? How do we provide child
care for people who are poor? How do we generate hope in the lives
of people who have had very little hope in their lives?''
</P>
<P>
   This antipoverty initiative is linked both literally and
symbolically to Bradley's desire to forge a more tolerant and
unified society. He noted that 36 percent of the poor children in
the United States are white, about 30 percent are black, and 22
percent are Latino. ``What I see as a possibility,'' he said, ``is
a multiracial coalition that would rekindle the same kind of
purposefulness as the civil rights revolution in the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   Most politicians have run like rabbits from that kind of talk.
Grand visions, idealism, kind words about the '60s _ all have been
anathema in the '90s. But Bradley, quietly, almost serenely, has
been saying the nation is ready once again to assert its better
self.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we still have a lot of catching up to do in terms of
our commitments to each other and our commitments to children who
are poor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley acknowledged that inroads against poverty had been made
as the economy has improved over the past few years, but he said
that was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty dropped, I think, 1 percent last year,'' he said.
``I'd rather have that happen than not happen. But it is still
higher than it was in 1989 and far higher than it was in 1970.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley voted against the so-called welfare reform legislation
that Bill Clinton signed into law in 1996. ``I didn't think the
federal government should cut off its commitment to individual
children who are poor,'' he said, adding, ``I didn't think the
answer to the problem of children in poverty was to have a group of
federal politicians take a pot of money and send it to the state
politicians and say, `Handle this problem as best you can.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said some of the more objectionable aspects of the law
had been modified, but more changes were needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign has been on a roll lately. He has raised
more money than expected, is doing better in the polls than
expected, and is planning a Madison Square Garden fund-raiser for
mid-November that will feature many of his big-name pals from
professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Vice President Al Gore has been thrown on the
defensive, and Gore has been insisting he is now the underdog. I
asked Bradley for his view. He laughed and said, ``I'm running
against entrenched power. Anytime someone has the support of the
president of the United States, who is loyal to you because you've
been loyal to him; anytime someone has essentially the Democratic
National Committee and its leadership; anytime somebody has all the
big Democratic fund-raisers; anytime somebody arrives in Air Force
2 _ that's entrenched power.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have are the people. And what I have is going out and
telling them what I want to do, and what I believe _ and just
trying to be who I am. And I think up to now, that's why we're
making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
