<HEADLINE>
CRITICS CALL IOC CRACKDOWN A `PUBLIC RELATIONS PLOY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW BROMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House drug czar said Wednesday an
International Olympic Committee crackdown on the use of
performance-enhancing drugs by athletes amounted to a ``public
relations ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has proposed a new independent agency to oversee
existing anti-doping programs that critics say are too lax.
</P>
<P>
   But those same critics say the proposed agency only appears to
be independent and will lack the sort of power needed to ensure all
Olympic athletes play by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our view that the IOC is rushing forward to build an
institution that we cannot support,'' said Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey,
director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal should have strong guarantees that the agency
will be independent and operate based on basic principles of good
governance ... '' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and other lawmakers are advocating
the creation of an agency that would mandate year-round, random
drug tests for all Olympic athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the IOC controls drug-testing operations and is not
accountable to any other agency or government.
</P>
<P>
   One IOC official told the Senate committee they would welcome
more oversight by the international community.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of IOC policy should involve ``close cooperation
from all those countries involved,'' said Richard Pound, vice
president of the IOC. But the agency did not include the United
States or any other country in its planning process for an
anti-doping agency because he said it would have ``complicated
things.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey saw problems with excluding the United States. ``The
proposal asks national governments to pay half the bill for the
agency but fails to accord these governments a sufficient role in
the policy-making process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Schamasch, director of the IOC medical commission, said
the international community should give the IOC's proposal a chance
to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to set up something and people say we don't do it
ight. Let the people who want to work, work,'' Schamasch said.
</P>
<P>
   Scrutiny of IOC operations peaked in January when officials were
accused of taking bribes so that Salt Lake City could land the 2002
winter games.
</P>
<P>
   That event, along with the discovery of widespread substance
abuse at the Tour de France in 1998, has prompted more calls for
reforms within the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Former Olympian Frank Shorter said athletes can attain human
growth hormone, and even laboratory-produced artificial blood, to
enhance performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us close to international sport were not surprised''
by the use of drugs at the Tour de France, he said. ``The elite
athletes' grapevine is very extensive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said any new agency to conduct drug tests will have to
administer both blood and urine tests to detect different types of
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Wadler, associate professor of clinical medicine at New
York University, said more extensive research on performance
enhancements is needed because many of those substances banned are
found naturally in the body, making their presence difficult to
detect.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the IOC has not kept up with science, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because advances in biotechnology have outpaced advances in
laboratory science, the detection of certain drugs or biologicals
is today either impractical or impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
