<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE FORBES FACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth Dole's withdrawal was not good news for
the Republican front-runner, George W. Bush, who hoped she would
stay in, split his opposition and muddy up debates. Her supporters
will go mainly to John McCain, partly to Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Though the maverick McCain's steady rise in the polls has made
him the realistic alternative to Bush, Forbes is the Texan's
immediate worry. The well-heeled publisher knows where to spend and
how to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the Bush campaign lined up focus groups in Iowa,
New Hampshire and South Carolina. After absorbing 10 TV spots
extolling Bush's virtues, these 70 willing guinea pigs were
subjected to three attack ads _ the sort of mean-spirited stuff
that Forbes is expected to use against Bush. Finally, the focus
groups were treated to the Bush response, deploring such tactics
and looking nobly put-upon.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sources assured The AP's Ron Fournier that the results were
``encouraging'' to their man. The Bush strategist Karl Rove tells
me the same, but won't be specific. The Forbes people smile,
disbelieving, and smack their lips.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes will not make the same mistake he did four years ago,
when his spot onslaught savaged Bob Dole but lashed back against
himself. This time a friendly Steve Forbes will appear on camera,
make nice to his GOP rival George W., and then take issue on a high
level.
</P>
<P>
   He will lay bare to GOP viewers Bush's tax raises in Texas,
perhaps recalling the read-my-lips heritage. Forbes will
respectfully disagree with Bush's education proposal, arguing
against transferring power from local parents to Washington. He
will deplore Bush's refusal to debate health care in depth and
stress the need to be able to choose one's own doctor. He will
contrast his strong policy toward Russia and China with the
Clinton-like Bush's ``tepid'' (never say ``wimpish'') approach.
</P>
<P>
   This will be subtler than the ``harsh, ugly words'' Rove reports
were used in Bush's simulated attack ads on himself. (Gee, I'd like
to see those self-flagellating spots.) Will the Forbes substitution
of the stiletto for the bludgeon enable him to run ``better than
expected'' in Iowa's January caucuses? Bush cannot counterattack in
kind; he will have to defend his record and expound his positions.
</P>
<P>
   With McCain passing up Iowa (his opposition to ethanol subsidies
infuriates farmers), Forbes might give Bush a run for both of their
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the conservative alternative,'' Forbes told me after
Dole's withdrawal Wednesday, ``in what is now a three-man race.''
He sees himself alone on the right (the tenacious Gary Bauer
notwithstanding), opposing a moderate and a maverick.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Forbes is the only one of the three not running
against the conservative GOP congressional leadership, but I see
Forbes as a key factor in Bush vs. McCain rather than an
alternative to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   So does John Zogby, the only major pollster who was right on the
money in the last presidential campaign. ``When you ask people the
first thing that comes to mind about Forbes,'' Zogby says, ``the
answer is `multimillionaire.' His negatives are much too high for
him to be a nominee.'' Life is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes Factor, however, is a constructive one. With not one
primary vote cast, the Bush war chest has already forced out Dole,
Dan Quayle and Lamar Alexander, but it won't force out Forbes. His
role is the opposite of spoiler; this time, he could be The
Improver, whose intelligent right-wing challenge will test Bush's
mettle in both necessary debate and in a preliminary War of the
Spots.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush can take on Forbes head-to-head in Iowa debates, and
then McCain head-to-head in New Hampshire debates, he will be not
bloodied but what old pols call ``blooded'' _ in shape to take on
either Al Gore or Bill Bradley. But if he ducks early, he will lose
later.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby sees Bush support ``a mile wide and an inch deep.'' Here's
the polling trend to watch: Last month, Bush beat the Democrats
Gore and Bradley by an average of 16 points, while McCain lost to
them by 9 points. That's changing; let's see how much
``winnability'' changes in the months to come.
</P>
<P>
   Note to Steve Forbes: The last day for filing in the New Jersey
senatorial race is March 8. That is the day after the decisive New
York and California presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
