<SLUG> BC-UPS-IPO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS sets price for IPO
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service set a price range of $36 to $42
a share for its upcoming initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based UPS will sell 109.4 million shares, or about 10
percent of its stock. The expected price range and number of shares
to be sold reflect the effects of a planned 2-for-1 split prior to
the offering.
</P>
<P>
   A midrange price of $39 would value the offering at $4.2
billion, eclipsing the $4 billion Conoco Inc. offering of 1998,
considered the biggest to date.
</P>
<P>
   UPS shares are valued at $25.50 internally, including the effect
of the split, so the company hopes for a significant boost in the
public market. The offering is expected to occur in November,
pending employee-shareholder approval at a special meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, employee-owned shares still would exercise 99
percent voting control after the offering. UPS would use cash from
the offering to launch a tender offer to employee shareholders,
giving them a chance to sell up to 10 percent of their shares at
the market-established price. The company says the main purpose of
the offering is to create a public market for shares that can be
used as currency in future acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Wednesday, the Teamsters union said UPS is
creating the first 2,000 new full-time jobs under terms of a 1997
strike settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement had called for 2,000 new full-time jobs in each
year of the five-year deal, for a total of 10,000. But UPS refused
to add the jobs during the first two years of the pact, saying it
didn't have to because package volume remained below pre-strike
levels.
</P>
<P>
   UPS spokesman Norman Black said volume has now recovered, and
that the company expects to add 2,000 jobs in each of the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The union has filed grievances against UPS, contending it should
still add the total of 10,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 180,000 Teamsters waged a major national strike to
win these new jobs,'' Teamsters President James P. Hoffa said. ``My
administration is committed to getting all 10,000 jobs. We will not
tolerate company delays and numbers manipulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
