<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE SHOWED SPUNK ON DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pedro Cirino and Chris Hovan, Boston College's
defensive cocaptains, sat beside each other on the Alumni Stadium
bench last Saturday and fought feelings of frustration. The Eagles
trailed Pittsburgh, 16-13, with 4:01 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much eye black Hovan smeared on his face _ which
has been his custom before every game the last two seasons _ there
was no masking the emotions that stirred within the senior
defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I remember most about the game was sitting on the
sidelines with Chris Hovan and his eyes were watering,'' Cirino
said. ``He was like, `We can't lose this game, you know?' And I was
like, `We're not losing this one. Don't worry about that.' And he
went out there, man, and he put on a damn show. If there's a better
defensive lineman than he is, I'd like to see him in person,
because I doubt there is one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can't be anyone better than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   On BC's final two defensive series, Hovan dominated the line of
scrimmage and, for all intents and purposes, took control of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just unleashed Chris,'' Cirino said Wednesday, four days
after the Eagles' 20-16 victory. ``There's not that much to say
other than they just unleashed him. They put him at the end and,
like I said, they can't block that kid, man. They can't block him.
He's such a pleasure to watch out there. I'm sitting in the
secondary and I watch him sometimes, he's so much fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovan dropped Pitt running back Kevan Barlow for a 3-yard loss
on the Panthers' first play from scrimmage on their own 30. After
two incompletions, the Panthers punted and BC's offense capitalized
with Tim Hasselbeck's 36-yard strike to Dedrick Dewalt with 1:48
left. Then Hovan and Co. shut the door on the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   On Pitt's final possession, Sean Guthrie and Hovan rang up
back-to-back sacks of quarterback David Priestely to force the
Panthers back to their 10, where a fourth-and-28 completion fell 3
yards shy of a first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last four minutes of the game, I've been there so many
times in my life where you look back at the Notre Dame or maybe the
Navy game, and sitting there on that last series I'm like, `This is
up to us,' '' said Hovan, a 6-foot-3-inch, 290-pound senior from
Rocky River, Ohio. ``It's up to us on the defensive line to put
pressure on the quarterback so he can't make things happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean Guthrie came up big on first down and fueled the fire,
and I came back on second down, and then we forced him out of the
pocket on third down, and forced him to make a bad pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we had to do to win that game. The emotion that
was present at that stage of the game was (pretty) high.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovan's inspired effort against the Panthers, who were held to
45 yards rushing, earned him Big East Defensive Player of the Week
honors. He rang up seven tackles (including four for losses
totaling 27 yards), had two quarterback sacks, one quarterback
hurry, and one forced fumble. It prompted Pitt coach Walt Harris to
seek out and salute Hovan afterward _ as coaches often do to
players _ with a pat on the butt.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Miami's offensive line offered Hovan a
similar gesture after he waged a tremendous battle in the trenches
last Halloween in a 35-17 loss to the Hurricanes at the Orange
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was great respect, but the fact of the matter was
that they won that game,'' Hovan said. ``No matter how hard I
played, we still should have won that game. That's the thing I
remember. Some of those guys said, `You're the hardest guy I've
played against,' but they still beat us, so I have that hanging
over my head.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Eagles (5-1 overall, 2-1 Big East) play host to No. 23
Miami (2-3, 0-0), Hovan would like nothing more than to return the
compliment after a BC victory. However, BC's defense will first
have to figure a way to contend with the Hurricanes' myriad of
playmakers, _ from running back James Jackson to wideout Santana
Moss to quarterback Kenny Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to start with the defensive line,'' said Hovan, who has
made five sacks, forced three fumbles, and leads the conference in
tackles for a loss (11 for 59 yards). ``They have a good offensive
line, a great tailback, a good quarterback, and two great
receivers. So it's going to have to start with us, because we're
going to have to step up and stop the run, and we're going to have
to put more pressure on the quarterback.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
