<HEADLINE>
BROWN HOPES TO BREAK PENN'S HOME FIELD ADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brown is off to a successful start to the Ivy League season and
has won 10 of its last 11 games the past two years. But if the
Bears lose to Pennsylvania on Saturday, their league title hopes
could be finished. Brown has not won at Philadelphia's Franklin
Field since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put that kind of pressure on the team, but I
don't think you are going to win the Ivy League with a 5-2
record,'' Brown coach Phil Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (2-1 in the league, 4-1 overall) squandered a 21-point
lead against Cornell Oct. 2 and lost, 33-28. Last week, the Bears
had a 24-point advantage over Rhode Island, but prevailed, 27-25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been jumping out to the lead by 14 or 21 points and
squandering it in the second half,'' Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've set goals for the team each game _ to beat Yale at the
Yale Bowl, to beat Princeton at Brown, where we hadn't beaten them
since 1987, and now it's to win at Franklin Field.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Brown defeated the Quakers, 58-51, in Providence as
James Perry passed for 470 yards and five touchdowns. Perry passed
for 299 yards and four touchdowns against Rhode Island and is the
Ivy League career leader in completions (634) and touchdown passes
(60). Perry has 7,591 career passing yards, second to Columbia's
John Witkowski (7,849 yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Perry) directs our offense and he has a great sense of
being in the pocket,'' Estes said. ``And our receivers have really
stepped up.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be another high scoring game. Penn's Gavin Hoffman
had a school-record 399 yards passing in a 41-17 win over Columbia
last week. Hoffman threw four touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   In other Ivy League games, Cornell (3-0, 4-1) visits Dartmouth
(0-2, 0-5); Harvard (1-1, 3-2) hosts Princeton (0-2, 2-3); and Yale
(1-1, 4-1) visits Columbia (0-2, 2-3). In a Patriot League game,
Holy Cross (1-1, 2-4) visits Lehigh (1-0, 6-0).
</P>
<P>
   Harvard has struggled to maintain a lead the last three games,
but held off Fordham, 37-30, in a nonconference win last week.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross snapped a three-game losing streak with a 24-23 win
over Fairfield last week as Tavares Brewington made five tackles
for losses and James Jenkins blocked a 26-yard field goal attempt
on the final play of the game. Holy Cross displayed resourcefulness
against Fairfield, which had 27 first downs to 15 for the
Crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Crusaders will have a difficult test with Lehigh, which has
an 18-game winning streak. Last week, Lehigh defeated Delaware,
42-35, as Rick Moore caught nine passes for 224 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
