<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLER-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TEXAS CITY SEEKS TO PUT CAP ON ITS POPULATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KELLER, Texas _ Surrounded by Fort Worth and two airports and
faced with growth that many communities would envy, this city is
moving to cap its population at fewer than 45,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The plan may seem surprising to other communities, but not to
the 24,500 residents of Keller or any of its neighboring North
Texas towns, said Mayor Dave Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any opposition to it, it's only come from people
who don't think we're limiting it enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council this week voted to pursue a plan to increase
the minimum size of a single-family residential lot from 8,400
square feet to 12,000 square feet. The idea is that, that will
result in no more than 43,400 residents within Keller's 19 square
miles during the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting about 10 miles north of downtown Fort Worth, Keller was
a rural whistle-stop for almost 90 years. It was originally named
Athol, but when a railroad stop was placed there in the 1880s, the
town was renamed after Texas and Pacific Railroad foreman John C.
Keller. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Its growth was slow until the 1970s, when Fort Worth's
population began to edge northward. Even then, however, it remained
rural with a population at less than 5,000. Recently, though,
Alliance Airport and its attendant growth has been added to north
Tarrant County. On top of that is the North Texas Speedway
northwest of Keller and Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport on
the east.
</P>
<P>
   And Keller has been growing steadily. Between 1980 and 1990 the
town's population grew from 4,156 to 13,683. By 1999, estimates put
the number at 24,500. At that rate, Keller's projected population
could be at 50,000 within five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean we'll have absolutely no lots less than 12,000
square feet,'' said Phillips of the city's new plan. ``We have
subdivisions on the south side of town, what I'd call ``high end'
subdivisions, but with lots as small as 8,400 square feet, and
those lots are not all filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the north side it's almost all `ranchettes.' People from
Fort Worth with the money to buy acreage and build on it have moved
in up there. They've been there for several years with pasture land
and cows surrounding them and, all of a sudden, they fear a
subdivision with little lots coming in behind them, and they don't
want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they'll even oppose a subdivision with the same size
lots as the one they live in.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of limiting growth is not unique to Keller. The
nearby community of Flower Mound has opted for no population
expansion with an ongoing moratorium on new housing, and Southlake,
to the east, also is temporarily limiting building permits to no
more than one house per acre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody moved up here just so they could reach out and touch
their neighbor's house,'' said Susan Ford, president of the Keller
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I could have moved just about anywhere in north
Tarrant County, but we chose this place because it was rural and we
wanted the acreage. There might be some opposition from some
developer to this plan, but I doubt if you'd find any resident of
Keller who opposed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said the council considered the fact that limiting
residential growth would mean higher taxes but decided residents
would prefer higher taxes to closer neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on current costs, we projected taxes will rise between
$48 and $65 per capita over the next 20 years,'' he said. ``Based
on the average family of 3.08, that would mean an increase of about
$150 per household. We think they can afford it and are willing to
pay it.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal will have to go through a series of public hearings
by the City Council and Planning and Zoning Commission before it
can be adopted, but Phillips said he foresees little opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just surprised at the interest we generated with this,''
he said. ``I've even gotten calls from Austin about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
