u f BC-BIZMAGS21-COX     10-20 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine perfectly in tune with Fed chief
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Does Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan read
Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (November)?
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman warned in a speech last week that the biggest
Y2K risk isn't likely to be the breakdown of computers on Dec. 31
but the potential panic of investors. That's the same message from
Kiplinger's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear of the computer bug will harm stocks more than the bite
of the bug itself,'' the magazine says. ``Many people worry more
about fellow investors bailing out of the market than about the
computer code.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's editors offer this advice in reassuring readers that
Y2K won't be a disaster: ``Long-term investors should do nothing,
but people planning to spend some investments early next year might
want to protect themselves from an overreaction.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate, special publication _ Kiplinger's Stocks 2000
(available until February) _ offers some nuts-and-bolts advice on
stock picking, online trading, planning and data on 2,000 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE FOR LIST FREAKS
</P>
<P>
   Forbes (Nov. 1) is out with still another ``best list,'' this
time the 200 ``best small companies in America.'' They are ranked
according to a formula that includes return on equity, sales growth
and profit growth for one-year and five-year periods.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-ranked Georgia company _ sixth place _ is Innotrac,
a Duluth provider of Caller ID and other phone services.
</P>
<P>
   The others, all in Atlanta, are LHS Group, 16th place; Advanced
Technology Products, 26; Profit Recovery Group International, 54;
Theragenics, 117; and Cotton States Life Insurance, 198.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list is Cognizant Technology Solutions, a
Teaneck, N.J., software company.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET TAKES OVER
</P>
<P>
   No topic has dominated the covers of U.S. business publications
in the past year more than the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This continues with Business Week (Oct. 25), whose cover story
profiles David Wetherell, a veritable evangelist of the Internet as
chief executive officer of a company that owns 11 Internet
companies, has sizable shares of 38 others and has three deals
pending.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine says his company, CMGI, became a hit with investors
``as a kind of Internet mutual fund: a way for investors to buy
into a broad array of Internet companies through just one stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (Nov. 8) looks at the ``e-volution'' of big business
with a package of articles that concludes that ``the window of
opportunity may be closing on large corporations who haven't yet
adopted e-business strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Stewart Alsop says a slew of new companies rushing to
use e-business ``is quickly edging out opportunities for big old
companies who want in on the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
