<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NUKE-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE OFFICIAL FORCED TO QUIT OVER REMARKS ON NUCLEAR ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A political furor erupted Wednesday over a senior
Defense Ministry official's proposal that Japan abandon one of its
most hallowed principles: its longtime renunciation of nuclear
weapons. As a result, the official was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks published Tuesday, the deputy vice minister of
defense, Shingo Nishimura, said that since other countries
considered Japan a target, parliament should ``consider the
possibility that Japan would be better off if it armed itself with
nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuclear weapons equal deterrence,'' said Nishimura, who
emphasized that he was expressing a personal opinion. ``If there
were no punishments for rape, we would all be rapists. We do not
become rapists because there is the deterrent of punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks, published in Weekly Playboy, which specializes in
light political commentary, humor and semi-nude portraits of women,
quickly set off an unusually intense round of denunciations.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, Nishimura, a self-styled defense expert and
conservative politician who has called Japan's rearmament his
``life's work,'' was forced to resign his defense post under heavy
pressure from the prime minister's office, which seemed deeply
embarrassed by the comments.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is the only country to have been attacked with nuclear
weapons, and has made banning them a cornerstone of its foreign
policy. And under the constitution imposed by the United States
after World War II, Japan has forsworn ``war as a sovereign right
of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by the daily Asahi Shimbun late Tuesday, before his
resignation, Nishimura seemed to dismiss the idea that either
longstanding policy or the constitution would bar nuclear armament.
``I did not think that the government principles were written in
stone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's chief Cabinet secretary, Mikio Aoki,
commented, ``Although it is only natural for politicians to have
personal opinions, it is extremely inappropriate for a
parliamentary vice minister to voice them in public, or in an
interview like this.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Japan's Defense Agency, Tatsuhiko Fukui, said
that ``any discussion on nuclear armament is simply impossible,''
adding that officials of his ministry were not authorized to
discuss the topic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the the government's quick effort to dissociate itself
from the official, the strong reactions by Japan's political
parties made clear that Nishimura's comments had a resonance beyond
the simple matter of a gaffe by an official.
</P>
<P>
   The furor laid bare deep fault lines in the new and politically
shaky coalition government and seemed bound to prematurely trigger
a long-planned parliamentary debate on a revision of Japan's
national defense policies.
</P>
<P>
   Nishimura was appointed earlier this month in a government
shuffle when Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi formed the largest
governing coalition in postwar Japanese history.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has never been directly cited as a platform issue,
it has been said that a principal reason for enlarging the
coalition was to gain passage of legislation to amend the
constitution to allow more leeway in defense.
</P>
<P>
   Public and political support for a more assertive defense stance
has grown sharply in the last two years in response to a missile
test by North Korea that violated Japanese airspace.
</P>
<P>
   One of Obuchi's longstanding coalition partners, the
conservative Liberal Party, led by Ochiro Ozawa, has always made a
strengthening of Japan's defense posture a centerpiece of its
policies.
</P>
<P>
   But the governing Liberal Democratic Party's newest coalition
partner, the loosely Buddhist-affiliated New Komeito Party, has a
longstanding tradition of pacifism. Although the New Komeito has
indicated that it will support a greater Japanese role in
international peacekeeping efforts, it has said nothing in support
of broader military activity by Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
