<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MORNING AFTER , METS REMEMBER A REMARKABLE SEASON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES(TRIM)- NYT   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shawon Dunston stood in the middle of the clubhouse
early Wednesday morning, still in uniform after the Mets'
season-ending loss to the Braves, his head down. He could not look
everyone in the eye, Dunston said later, but he wanted to tell the
team he reluctantly joined at the trading deadline one thing before
he headed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I was proud to be a Met,'' said Dunston, who created one
of the signature moments of the this series when he ended a
12-pitch, 9-minute at-bat with a single that began the Mets' rally
in the 15th inning of the Game 5 victory. ``They're all
professionals. They had to know that. It was nice being here. I
hope I stay here. It's very first class. I met a lot of nice
people. hen I retire in three years or five years, I'll take that
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the valedictory of a man who had to be convinced by his
wife and parents to join his hometown team after he was traded in
late July against his wishes. If there was some scattered sadness
in the clubhouse after the bittersweet ending to the Mets'
captivating season _ the banged and bruised Mike Piazza seemed
mentally and physically spent and Bobby Valentine, befitting his
intense personality, looked inconsolable _ the rest of the Mets
seemed to appreciate just how magnificent their last few weeks had
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few of us on the way stopped in the video room to make sure
we get a copy of the last two games,'' Darryl Hamilton said. ``We
could get old and gray and still watch those games.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, about half the team came home to Shea
Stadium to pile personal belongings into garbage bags and boxes and
head off to a winter of wondering what if. It was as if Game 6 of
the National League Championship Series was scripted to embody, in
11 innings, all that the Mets had endured for the last month _ the
failings and recoveries and, ultimately, the heartache of a near
miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `We're going to play the Yankees,''' Dunston
said. ``The little kid came back to me. I was so excited. I was
like a kid in high school and like in high school, I always miss
the championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Mets were spent from fighting for almost every
victory in a harrowing and exuberant four weeks. When Kenny Rogers
walked in the game-winning run in the 11th inning, the Mets went
down quietly for perhaps the only time all season, which might
explain why, after the initial devastation of the loss, this was no
morose clubhouse, with no tears and with more than a few hugs and
pats on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should hold the heads up high,'' Valentine said.
``It may leave a void, but they should have a feeling of a job well
done. There's not even a question it's the best group I've ever
had. Let's not say it was always perfect, but the majority ruled
here and the majority was very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Mets reflected on the burnished finale to the
season, they, inevitably had to look forward, too. For all the
millions of dollars spent to improve this team _ for the enormous
contracts given to Al Leiter, Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura last
year _ the Mets challenged the Braves enough to make most games
close, but they are still not complete enough to beat them
consistently. So, with the obstacle not yet overcome, the Mets head
into the winter with a few large questions still looming.
</P>
<P>
   What is Valentine's fate? The frequently embattled, always
compelling manager has received several high-profile votes of
confidence from the Mets' co-owner, Fred Wilpon. But a recent
magazine article suggested that Valentine's wife was trying to
convince him not to return and that his friends would be shocked if
he came back. It is hard to imagine a man as competitive as
Valentine walking away from a team as good as this one. But his
reluctance to answer directly the question of whether he will
return will leave the story floating for weeks, which is probably
just what Valentine wants, in the hope that he will be offered a
contract extension before he begins the final year of his deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a contract for next year,'' Valentine said after the
game. ``I can't wait to come back.'' Wednesday, pressed for a
clarification, Valentine said of his chances to return: ``Why
wouldn't I? I don't want to talk about it. It gives credence to
ridiculous thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Will first baseman John Olerud, who is eligible for free agency,
re-sign with the Mets? The team certainly hopes so, and _ as they
did with Leiter and Piazza last season _ they'd like to wrap it up
quickly. ``We've made it clear we want to bring him back, and we'll
move aggressively to do that,'' General Manager Steve Phillips
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Olerud, who took a pay cut to sign his two-year, $8 million
deal, may not be in such a rush. He said after the game that he
wants to talk to his wife, Kelly, before deciding what to do and he
was noncommital about whether he wants to return to New York, or
possibly return to his home state and play for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've both had a great time in the city,'' Olerud said. ``It's
been a great experience for us. It's a big decision. It's something
I'm going to talk about. It's what's best for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens with Olerud, one thing is certain: Piazza,
banged up as he is, will be the catcher next season, even if an
eventual move to a less jarring position would protect his
offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   Wither Rickey Henderson? The phenomenal age-resistant leadoff
man put up great numbers for the Mets this season, batting .314 and
stealing 37 bases. But there were startling lapses in his hustle in
the field and around the bases. Although the team holds an option,
which vested when he made his 500th plate appearance in the waning
days of the regular season, that would pay him $2 million next
season, Henderson says he wants more money. ``If they want me to be
here, I want to be here,'' Henderson said. ``I want to be paid what
I mean to the club. I probably meant more to the club this season
that what I signed for.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Henderson come along quietly? ``I'm not worried about
that,'' Phillips said, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Mets have any interest in re-signing Rogers, in light
of the calamity of Game 6? Does Melvin Mora _ ``Who is this guy?''
NBC's Joe Morgan said in wonder during Game 6 _ get a shot at a
starting job next season based on his dazzling performance in the
playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   What about the loose ends?
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser, according to some reports, is considering a
career switch to coaching, and he has reportedly had contact with
the Cleveland Indians. But Hershiser was a valuable presence in the
clubhouse, particularly as an elder statesman among pitchers and
became, in effect, a part-time coach to Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla, and his $5.9 million salary, are almost certain
to be gone next year in some fashion, with the Mets probably having
to eat a large part of his contract. He and Valentine clearly can
not exist together. When Valentine left the clubhouse in Atlanta at
1:50 a.m. Wednesday after the game, he walked right past Bonilla
without saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-2NDTAKE-NYT     10-20 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: a word.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Valentine seemed to take the loss the hardest of anyone in the
organization, perhaps because he has been on the firing line with
regularity. It seems, in retrospect, as if the season could not
possibly have been long enough to contain all the events that
occurred within it, many of them involving the manager.
</P>
<P>
   An early eight-game losing streak, the firing of three coaches,
Valentine's near brawl with Bonilla, a surge in the second half, a
seven-game losing streak that nearly cost the Mets a trip to the
post-season, a four-game span where the Mets fought off elimination
every day, Valentine, in late September, musing that he might be
fired, a one-game playoff to clinch the wild-card berth, the
manager opining that his players weren't very smart, and then a
recovery from losing the first three playoff games to the Braves to
fashion one of the most compelling post-season series in memory.
</P>
<P>
   If Valentine looked heartbroken afterward _ until the rookie
Octavio Dotel walked into his office for a hug and a few words from
Valentine, reminding him that he was only at the beginning of what
promises to be a successful career _ then his players seemed to
have come around, at least a bit, to Piazza's way of thinking.
Before the series began, Piazza said that anything that happened
would be gravy, considering where the Mets had come from in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One large group of players, that included several relief
pitchers, pulled the folding chairs that sit in front of each
locker into a circle and sipped beer together. ``It was a great
season,'' one said, to nobody in particular. Who could argue?
</P>
