<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAD21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slump in paper prices at fault for slow sales, Mead says
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Mead Corp. blamed a dip in third-quarter sales on
a continued slump in paper prices, the struggling School and Office
Products Division and operational trouble in its Stevenson, Ala.,
mill.
</P>
<P>
   Mead reported Wednesday third-quarter sales of $982.2 million,
down from $1.01 billion for the same period last year. Earnings,
excluding special items, were $49.1 million, or 46 cents per share,
down slightly from $49.4 million, or 47 cents per share, for the
same period last year. The analysts' consensus estimate was 46
cents per share, based on 13 estimates, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial, an analysts monitoring service.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of the year, Mead's sales were $2.85
billion, down slightly over $2.9 billion for the same period in
1998. Earnings, excluding special items, for the first nine months
of 1999 were $126.8 million, or $1.20 per share, compared with
$146.1 million, or $1.39 per share, for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the third quarter, coated paper prices declined, impacting
our largest segment. However, as the fourth quarter begins, we
anticipate some price improvement,'' said Mead Chairman, President
and Chief Executive Jerry Tatar. ``When combined with ongoing
productivity efforts and continued market improvement in other
segments, we are becoming more optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Third-quarter earnings in the paper division dropped 24 percent
to $42.2 million while sales dipped only 1 percent. Excluding
special items, earnings in the packaging and paperboard segment
slipped 11 percent to $41.4 million while sales were $389 million,
up $1 million over the same period last year. Tatar said
technicians are still trying to solve problems with a new machine
at the Stevenson mill _ difficulties that have been hurting Mead
for about three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the high-profile School and Office Products Division,
third-quarter earnings dropped 30.5 percent to $9.1 million while
sales dipped 14 percent to $146 million. Mead officials are hoping
to turn sales and earnings around with new licensing agreements and
the purchase of AT-A-GLANCE Group, a calendar and planner maker
based in upstate New York. The division also signed new licensing
agreements with Nike Inc. and M&AMP;M/Mars to feature their brands on
Mead products.
</P>
<P>
   Mead stock (NYSE:MEA) closed Wednesday at 33 7/8, up 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
