<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-AFRICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUDING NIGERIA, ALBRIGHT VOWS INCREASE IN AID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright praised
the five-month-old democratic government of Nigeria Wednesday and
pledged more financial support for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who is on a weeklong visit to Africa, said Nigeria was
undergoing a historic transformation that could potentially rank
alongside ``the Czechoslovak Velvet Revolution and South Africa's
long walk to freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, she said, will try to ensure that democratic
change continues in Nigeria, which has emerged from 16 years of
military rule. She proposed raising aid to the country threefold or
fourfold from its current level of $27 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is Africa's most populous country and supplies 8 percent
of America's oil.
</P>
<P>
   Early this week, President Clinton vetoed a $12.6 billion
foreign aid bill passed by the Republican-led House. The amount was
$2 billion less than the president requested.
</P>
<P>
   In her tour so far of Africa, Albright has also pledged $55
million in aid to Sierra Leone, where an agreement has been signed
to end an eight-year-old civil war. The Clinton administration has
been accused of neglecting Africa while responding quickly to
Kosovo and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Albright arrived here late Tuesday and held a two-hour meeting
with President Olusegun Obasanjo, who is to visit the White House
next week.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official who attended the meeting said
Obasanjo pledged to pursue an aggressive campaign against
corruption no matter ``whose goat is gored.'' Cronies of the late
dictator Gen. Sani Abacha are already targets of the anticorruption
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo also said he expected a ``democracy dividend'' in the
form of debt relief, according to the State Department official.
Nigeria's shaky economy cannot get back on its feet and its leaders
will find it hard to sustain democracy if the country has to spend
more than 30 percent of its export revenues to service its $30
billion debt, the official reported him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Obasanjo government has ``already done much to restore
Nigeria's democratic institutions,'' Albright said in a speech here
to a West African economic organization. But she said the
government still needed to repeal repressive laws and to reform its
judiciary and military fully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
