<HEADLINE>
TALKING POINTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Alan Porter &LR;  heard  &UR; Barbara Walters &LR;  say on Friday's ``20/20''
that viewers at an auction preview ``gazed in hushed tones'' at
 &UR; Marilyn Monroe &LR; 's personal effects.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of ideas well expressed,  &UR; Jack Carter &LR;  suggests
that old-fashioned phone booths without telephones, or tall
cardboard boxes like those in which refrigerators are delivered, be
placed in areas where people congregate as ``venues for those who
wanted to talk via cellular phones.''
</P>
<P>
   As to face-to-face conversations,  &UR; P.J. Corkery &LR;  was sitting at
Caffe Centro, in San Francisco's South Park media gulch, when he
overheard one young tycoon tell another, ``One thing we do really
well is to take, like, a fuzzy idea and `issualize' it so it's
really buff and full of definition.'' At another table, another
tycoon: ``We're having a millennium conference in London, which is
like cool, since London is so old, so turn of the century. The
other century. It's Dickensonian.'' Elsewhere, an additional world
view was expressed at the corner of Fifth and Mission, where one
raconteur was heard telling another: ``If he hadn't been on
crutches, I woulda hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Bill Minutaglio &LR; 's definitely unauthorized biography of
 &UR; George W. Bush &LR; , ``First Son'' (Times; $25), reports that when
 &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR;  came to dinner at the White House in 1992,
 &UR; Barbara Bush &LR;  seated son  &UR; George W. &LR;  at the end of the table and
told him not to address the royals. The Q &LR; queen asked him whether
he was the black sheep in the family, says the book, and he
replied, ``I guess that might be true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GREAT BEATTY COVERUP? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Warren Beatty &LR;  is still reshooting some scenes of ``Town and
Country,'' his forthcoming movie about a middle-aged philanderer,
leading MSNBC to speculate that his presidential murmurs are
intended to deflect interest from a movie that may be a dog.
</P>
<P>
   The movie stars Beatty,  &UR; Diane Keaton &LR; ,  &UR; Garry Shandling &LR; ,
 &UR; Goldie Hawn &LR; ,  &UR; Jenna Elfman &LR;  and  &UR; Andie MacDowell &LR; . According to
Slate gossipist  &UR; Mickey Kaus &LR; , ``Hollywood has been amusing
itself'' for a year and a half ``with tales of the movie's
interminable production schedule and budget overruns.'' Although
the film's opening has been set for February, screenwriter  &UR; Gary &LR; 
 &UR; Ross &LR;  has been called in to write more scenes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Dean Goodman &LR; , who was briefly married to  &UR; Marlene &LR; 
 &UR; Dietrich &LR; 's daughter,  &UR; Maria &LR; , in the '40s, writes to say he was
interviewed by a German documentary crew last weekend. ``Do I have
pangs of conscience when I accept payment for these interviews?''
he asks. ``Not at all. I am very discreet in everything I say about
Marlene and my ex-wife, and I consider the payments as small
compensation for the pain I suffered during that foolish episode 50
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The British Press Association reports that at a state banquet
at Buckingham Palace this week for Chinese President
 &UR; Jiang Zemin &LR; , Queen Elizabeth (see above for previous dining
adventures) told him that Chinese food was very popular in England.
The Grenadier Guards played tunes from ``Hello, Dolly,'' and
bagpipers concluded the evening's entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ann Moller Caen &LR;  received a recent letter from San Francisco
photographer  &UR; Timothy Shonnard &LR; , a stranger who told her that he
was married on August 28 to  &UR; Cheryl Spease &LR; , a woman he met while
stopping for a martini at Pier 23 during the candlelight vigil
after  &UR; Herb Caen &LR; 's death. The wedding ceremony was followed by a
toast to Herb and a first dance to  &UR; Tony &LR; 
 &UR; Bennett &LR; 's ``I Left My Heart ...''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gordon Burns &LR;  forwards word, from the Wall Street Journal,
that consumer affairs officials in England have proposed a law
against a pub pouring a glass of beer with more than 5 percent
froth at the top.  &UR; Tim Hampson &LR;  of the Brewers and Licensed
Retailers Association opposes the bill, saying, ``Froth is a rich
part of British culture, and we would hate to see it go.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Earth Island Journal praises  &UR; Don Johnson &LR;  for investing
in Xebra Motors, which will manufacture electric cars; and TV actor
 &UR; Brandon Brooks &LR;  of the series ``Malibu, California,'' an animal
rights sympathizer who refused to take part in a promotional event
at Sea World. The event was moved to an ``animal-free amusement
park,'' says the Journal.
</P>
