<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      10-20 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE POP-UP BOOK OF PHOBIAS'' &QL; 
By Gary Greenberg (Morrow, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We heard about this one before we saw it, and that's always a
good sign. It has been New &AMP; Notable's policy to mock pop-up books
on the grounds that they are both silly and oxymoronic _ something
can't pop up and be a book at the same time. We prefer to think of
them as ````gadgets''.'' The last one we paid any attention to was
about golf courses, and it might have been the nadir of pop-up
books _ little greens rising at you like some dopey delusion, sand
traps floating through the air. So, when we got wind of this one,
we licked our chops, found ``moronic'' in the thesaurus and waited
for the kill. Now, we must eat crow. New &AMP; Notable has been
conquered by a pop-up book, wrestled into submission by a gadget.
Gary Greenberg, the stand-up comedian who created it, begins with
the mother of all phobias, the Dentist and the Drill. This
particular drill twists as it rises into view, and it is big enough
to roto-rooter your nostril. When it reaches dead center, it is
aimed straight at you, right at your very teeth, and behind it is a
dentist who bears more than a passing resemblance to Joseph
Mengele. You have to laugh _ what else can you do? Greenberg has
paired off the ludicrous and the macabre, and we couldn't wait to
turn the page and see what he'd do next. There are 10 phobias here,
including most of the big ones, but we won't say more. The
dentist's drill is funny whether you know it's coming or not, but
others profit from an element of surprise. Either way, phobias beat
golf courses, hands down. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``DOGS THAT KNOW WHEN THEIR OWNERS ARE COMING HOME'' &QL; 
By Rupert Sheldrake (Crown, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Sheldrake is preaching to the converted when he makes
the case for studying our own pets (and not just creatures in
research labs) to foster our awareness of ``the unexplained powers
of animals.'' After all, the people most likely to buy his book are
those who agree with him, who object to our longstanding taboo
against taking pets seriously. There's nevertheless something
heartwarming about his arguments, which embrace the animals we love
as both gifted creatures and sources of scientific knowledge.
Through interviews and surveys with pet owners, veterinarians, dog
trainers and zoo keepers in the United States and Britain,
Sheldrake explores the phenomenon of telepathic communication
between people and animals _ in other words, he asks why a dog
might know 20 minutes in advance that its owner is coming home,
even when the owner is unexpected. Or how a cat hearing a ringing
telephone would know that someone it loves is on the other end of
the line. What makes an animal show unmistakable signs of agitation
a full three hours before an earthquake, or enables a horse to find
its way home across unfamiliar terrain? And why, if there are some
dogs that know their owners are coming home, are there other dogs
that don't have a clue? Are some breeds more sensitive than others?
Sheldrake explores animal empathy, the therapeutic effect of pets,
animal-to-animal telepathy, the phenomenon of bird migration, and
animal premonitions. His book is an engaging look at domesticated
creatures and the mysterious things that connect us to them. &QL; 
``PLAINSONG'' &QL; 
By Kent Haruf (Knopf, $24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This lovely, evocative novel is set in Holt, Colo., a prairie
town so small that it takes only an hour for two boys to deliver
all of its newspapers. Those boys are Ike and Bobby Guthrie, whose
father, Tom, teaches history at the high school, and whose mother,
Ella, has taken silently to her bed and will soon move out of the
house and then out of town altogether. Other characters are
Victoria Roubideaux, a pregnant teenage girl whose mother has
locked her out of the house, and the senior McPheron brothers, two
self-described decrepit old bachelors who agree to let Victoria
come and live with them on their farm until her baby is born. Haruf
lets his characters reveal themselves slowly and compassionately,
and the story that takes shape as the ties between them grow is
oddly comforting even as they grapple with changes in their lives.
The feel of this book is not unlike that of Cormac McCarthy's later
novels, both in tone and in the atmospheric sense of place that
becomes almost a character in itself (missing is McCarthy's
trademark violence, although there is one menacing scene in which
Ike and Bobby are roughed up by a teenage bully). Haruf has written
a quietly moving book about ordinary people dealing with the
emotional twists of ordinary life. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``BROTHERS'' &QL; 
(Hyperion, $26.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing about my brothers is a dangerous occupation, dancing
through a minefield,'' Frank McCourt says. Maybe so, but there's
something to be said for having tissues on hand if you intend to
read this book _ you might get weepy. There are some fine writers
here _ McCourt, Tobias Wolff, Richard Ford, David Sedaris, James
Alan McPherson _ all talking about their brothers and the bonds and
conflicts between them. We were most taken, however, with the essay
by Charles P. Pierce, who is the son of a brother and the father of
brothers, but who himself is an only child. His is the clear-eyed
view from beyond: ``I have watched brothers all my life,'' he says.
``I watched them in my family growing up, and I watch my children
today, the blood speech of the code-talkers in the other bedrooms,
the swift bursts of anger and the reconciliations, all operating on
rules as foreign and distant to me as Hammurabi's Code.'' Mixed
with these essays are portraits of brothers, some well-known (the
Dalai Lama and his brother, Martin Scorsese and his), some not at
all. This was put together by the editors of ``Esquire.'' &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
