<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARTHLINK-MINDSPRING-     10-20 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK-MINDSPRING-EARN2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring, EarthLink earnings top
 &HT;    estimates
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises performed better than expected
in the third quarter, beating Wall Street expectations despite
posting its third straight losing quarter.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring reported a loss of $10.8 million, or 17 cents a
diluted share. The Atlanta-based Internet access provider reported
income of $4 million, or 7 cents a diluted share, for the same
three months in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink Network, the Pasadena, Calif., company expected to
merge with MindSpring early next year, also beat analysts'
expectations with its third-quarter performance. If the merger is
completed as expected, the two companies would be the nation's
second-largest ISP behind America Online. The combined company will
be called EarthLink, but will be based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MindSpring dropped 87 1/2 cents, closing Wednesday at
$25.81 1/4. EarthLink shares closed at $41.68 3/4, down $1.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring is amortizing ``goodwill'' costs for its recent
acquisitions of Sprynet ($32 million) and Netcom ($245 million).
The deals gave MindSpring 500,000 more customers. Excluding those
costs, MindSpring reported income of $3.4 million, or 5 cents a
share, beating the First Call consensus estimate by 2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   When a company buys another company, it is allowed to write off
``goodwill amortization,'' the difference between what one company
pays for another company and the acquired company's book value.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring also said it will spend between $7 million and $9
million less than planned on sales and marketing in the fourth
quarter. The company planned to spend more than $55 million on a
advertising campaign to make the MindSpring name better-known
nationwide. But if the EarthLink merger is approved, the name
MindSpring will exist only in the e-mail addresses of its existing
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company will use some of the national marketing
money to send disks, America Online-style, through the mail and
with Sunday newspapers closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of September, MindSpring had about 1.3 million
customers, an increase of 69,000, or 5.6 percent, from the previous
quarter. The advertising campaign did not start until September.
The company said it does not expect to see large numbers of new
subscribers until the fourth quarter and that even that growth will
be slower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink has 1.57 million subscribers. The company said it
added 231,000 customers, a 17 percent increase from the previous
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink is growing more quickly because it started an
aggressive marketing campaign nine months before MindSpring, said
Jeff Sadler, an analyst with F.A.C. Equities.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is EarthLink growing more quickly, it is keeping more
of its customers than MindSpring. EarthLink loses 3.6 percent of
its customers each month, compared with MindSpring's ``churn rate''
of 4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring has one full-time person and two half-timers working
on the churn issue, said Mike McQuary, MindSpring president and
chief operating officer. He said the company will focus on
customers who drop out in the first two months by calling new
customers who aren't using the service much and asking why.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to rely on them calling us,'' McQuary said.
</P>
<P>
   People calling MindSpring's technical support spent an average
of seven minutes on hold during the third quarter, an increase of
five minutes from the previous quarter. Callers to the customer
service center saw their average hold time increase from one minute
to four minutes over the same period. Call center hold time, or
lack therof, is something MindSpring has used to distinguish itself
from its competitors with billboards teasing, ``Their hold music is
better than ours. It has to be.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuary said MindSpring was deluged by the number of calls from
former customers of Netcom, who, prior to MindSpring's acquisition
of Netcom, had no toll-free customer support number.
</P>
<P>
   The company hired 185 customer service employees during the
third quarter. McQuary said callers to the technical support lines
are averaging four minutes this month.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Russ, an analyst with Robinson-Humphrey, attributed the
call center delays to normal issues that occur when a company tries
to absorb customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you double your subscriber base like they did with
Netcom, there's going to be a little bit of a lag time before you
can catch up with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink took in $89.6 million in the third quarter but spent
that, and $31.4 million more, for a per-share loss of $1.07. A year
ago, EarthLink reported a net loss of $18.8 million, or 78 cents
per share, on $49.8 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting goodwill amortization, EarthLink reported a net
loss of $13.7 million, or 42 cents per share. Analysts expected
EarthLink to lose 43 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
