<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3243 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-2T     10-20 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A SURPRISE, MODERATE MUSLIM LEADER CHOSEN TO LEAD INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (With INDONESIA-WAHID) 
 (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In the first democratic transfer of power
in its history, Indonesia chose a new president Wednesday,
Abdurrahman Wahid, a respected Muslim religious leader whose
message is tolerance, inclusion and self respect.
</P>
<P>
   The vote for Wahid, 59, in an electoral assembly Wednesday, was
a surprise, the result of fast-moving coalition building that
followed a general election in June in which the prominent
opposition figure, Megawati Sukarnoputri, won a plurality of
parliamentary seats.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, nearly blind and weakened by a stroke, defeated Megawati
373-313, with five abstentions, after President B.J. Habibie
withdrew his candidacy earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid raised Megawati's hand as he joined in the singing of the
national anthem at his inauguration. His opponent stood beside him
swallowing back tears and biting her lip.
</P>
<P>
   It was an extraordinary moment of anticlimax as, suddenly, with
a minimum of fuss, a new leader took power in the world's fourth
most-populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, who is a practicing cleric as well as a religious leader,
pushed ahead with his presidential bid despite almost unanimous
warnings here that he could not win. After his National Awakening
Party placed a distant third in June, he had become a key supporter
of Megawati, then broke with her early this month when she hung
back from forming a coalition, seeming to believe the presidency
was hers.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid put together his own winning numbers in the hours before
the balloting began when Habibie's withdrawal left hundreds of
anti-Megawati votes looking for a standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   His victory gives Indonesia the clean break with the past for
which Megawati had been the symbol, and in a moderate form that is
acceptable to most minorities. It also gives the world's most
populous Islamic nation its first cleric as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised,'' said a leading economist, Emil
Salim. ``Everybody is surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   And the only thing that is certain is the likelihood of more
surprises, according to those who know Wahid, who he is
unpredictable by nature.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral assembly was scheduled to choose a vice president
on Thursday. The choice, which is not governed by party tickets,
gained special importance because of Wahid's poor health and
because of the need to create an alliance that would mend political
rifts.
</P>
<P>
   Then the real, long-postponed work of government must resume as
the country attempts to settle down from a two-year period of
economic and political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The urgent agenda is daunting as Indonesia works to restart its
economy and rebuild its government institutions and its sense of
national pride and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, there was violence on the streets of Jakarta
Wednesday night as street thugs joined disappointed supporters of
Megawati in battling the police and soldiers in what has almost
become a ritual here.
</P>
<P>
   The violence included stone throwing, vandalism, arson, tear gas
and a car bomb that the police said injured 18 people. At least one
person was reported killed. At nightfall, the Jakarta Convention
Center was on fire and gangs continued to roam some streets,
pursued by the police.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening's rampage did not approach the kind of broad
social unrest that people had feared might occur if Megawati lost
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Schwarz, an expert on Indonesia at Johns Hopkins
University, said it would be up to Megawati now to draw on her
popularity to contain the anger and frustration of her followers,
who were convinced that she would win.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence, Wednesday was a day of national pride as
Indonesia embraced its experiment with democracy, breaking away
from 32 years of selfish and autocratic rule under President
Suharto, who was forced to resign in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His vice president, Habibie, who had taken over leadership and
then fought hard to win Wednesday's vote, accepted defeat with
smiling good grace.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces, which had served as the arm of Suharto's
repression, and which hold seats in the assembly, for the most part
were careful to stay out of the political fray both in the June
ballot and in the electoral assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military has played a fairly responsible role in terms of
what is apparent,'' Schwarz said. ``It was a secret ballot so we
don't know how they voted. But clearly they have decided to make a
concerted effort to at least give the impression that they are
playing a neutral, on-the-sidelines role.''
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces on Wednesday pledged its support to a new
president who may have benefited from the parliamentary votes of
its 38-member bloc but, for the first time in Indonesian history,
did not appear to owe his tenure to it.
</P>
<P>
   The chief military spokesman, Maj. Gen. Surdrajat, said the
country's armed forces, ``together with the Indonesian people, are
thankful in having Abdurrahman Wahid as our new president.'' He
added, ``I believe that people will accept the reality of
democracy. We ask people to return to their homes and not to create
unrest.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The day was marked by gestures of unity and conciliation from
the new president and his two defeated rivals, moments of
extraordinary emotion given Indonesia's history of ruthless
transfers of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here with Mrs. Megawati to celebrate our victory and our
democracy and our second independence since the founding president,
Sukarno, planted the flag upon our soil,'' Wahid said immediately
after the vote, as he held her hand. ``I have great respect for
Mrs. Megawati and she must be respected for her role in all of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference to Sukarno was a generous nod to Megawati, who is
the former president's daughter and who drew much of her popularity
from her association with him.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a seat beside Wahid, she addressed television cameras,
saying, ``For the unity of the nation, I call on the people of
Indonesia to accept the results of the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, as Wahid slowly climbed to the dais to take
his oath of office, Habibie _ humiliated just hours before in the
same chamber by a no-confidence vote _ rose to take the new
president's arm and guide him to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   The show of reconciliation was all the more remarkable because
the outcome of the vote differed so completely from that of the
June vote and from the months of horse trading that followed it.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nobody apart from Wahid himself had expected him to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could have predicted this eight months ago?'' said a
diplomat Wednesday as the voting was about to begin. ``The two
people who you thought were most solid with each other are now
vying for the presidency. It is a remarkable turn of events.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to most analysts, Wahid's victory resulted primarily
from Megawati's refusal to compromise or build coalitions after the
election in June in which her party won 34 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   As she and her advisers waited for other parties to come to
them, and then as often as not rejected their overtures, the
political landscape shifted rapidly. Wahid broke away from her
earlier this month, supported by a coalition of Muslim and other
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the assembly on Tuesday night voted to reject
Habibie, after 17 months in office, he withdrew from the race,
leaving scores of votes uncommited. Most of them apparently went to
Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Now the nation must turn from politics to policy as it faces an
economic crisis, separatist rebellions, and what many analysts say
are urgent needs for fundamental political and structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said that, particularly because Wahid was not
seen as a hands-on manager, his selection of a Cabinet would be the
most crucial step he would take in the early part of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural speech Wednesday evening, he stressed his
vision of national reconciliation and mutual respect and touched on
some of the themes that most concern Indonesians today: national
dignity and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a mood of wounded pride following months of
demands for reform by the International Monetary Fund and following
the introduction of foreign troops in East Timor, he spoke of
``insensitive'' criticisms from other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically he included a small joke, saying he would
keep his speech short because ``the longer I speak the more
responsibilities I'll have in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign he said that he supported Indonesia's
emerging democratic reforms and that he would support the economic
reforms that have been demanded by international lenders in return
for continued assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But most economists agree that given the strictures of the
demands of donors and investors, there is in any case little room
for maneuver in setting economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   If Wahid hopes to lead Indonesia to a clean new page in its
history, he brings a not-insignificant new virtue to the
presidency. He has not been tainted by accusations of corruption or
ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
