<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DOLE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      10-20 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WILL TOO MUCH SUCCESS SPOIL GEORGE W. BUSH? 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DOLE-WITHDRAWS) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, it may be too much
success _ and too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has chased the fifth candidate _ Elizabeth Dole _
out of the Republican presidential competition, Bush leaves
absolutely no question about his political might.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush's unprecedented success _ never have so many
big-name candidates exited a presidential race more than three
months before the first votes are cast _ could complicate what thus
far been his painless glide to the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bush has benefited immeasurably from divisions among
his opponents. But now, those left standing, particularly Sen. John
McCain of Arizona and Steve Forbes, have a much clearer, though
certainly uphill, shot at toppling the front-runner, particularly
as the campaign enters a phase of high-profile debates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bush's advisers said they would have preferred that Mrs.
Dole had stayed in the race, at the very least to distract McCain
and the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mixed blessing for us,'' said one Bush operative,
speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``It shows our continued
incredible strength. Anytime you begin to shrink the field, you
increase the potential of the vote for those who remain. So I would
have liked Elizabeth to stay in for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as former Sen. Bill Bradley is drawing enormous press
attention from his one-one-one competition with Vice President Al
Gore, the shrunken Republican field will give those still competing
a much larger public stage. Besides McCain and Forbes, Gary Bauer
has been organizing aggressively among grassroots conservatives.
Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and Alan Keyes, the radio talk show host,
are also campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But the timing of Mrs. Dole's announcement was most propitious
for McCain because he has been battling Mrs. Dole over the same
pool of moderate and independent voters and, in the past several
weeks, has been on something of a roll: He recently completed a
successful book tour. He is creeping up on Bush in polls in New
Hampshire, which holds the first primary. This week, he grabbed the
endorsement of the borough president of Staten Island, Guy
Molinari, who defected from the Bush campaign. And while his bill
to overhaul the campaign finance system suffered a stinging defeat
in the Senate on Tuesday, McCain attracted plenty of publicity for
pushing the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a nice little boomlet going here,'' said Rick Davis,
McCain's campaign manager. ``This brings it into focus as a two-man
race.'' The altered dynamics, he said, could lead his campaign to
reconsider elements of its strategy, such as the decision not to
compete heavily in Iowa, which holds the first important caucuses
in January.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's greatest vulnerability is Forbes' greatest
strength: money. Because he is dipping into his personal fortune,
Forbes has the resources to stay in the contest longer. The
narrowed field allows him to train his advertising blitz more
directly on Bush and to draw contrasts between his conservative
views and more moderate positions of Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This underscores that I am the conservative alternative
against two moderate establishment candidates,'' Forbes said in an
interview. He added that he believed the others dropped out because
of ``discouragement over what they see as the coronation process
for the front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   One Bush adviser, expressing concern that Forbes will begin to
attack the governor on television commercials, said, ``This shifts
the dynamic so Forbes gets rid of the clutter and he gets to really
rumble with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But another Bush adviser shrugged at the notion that the
campaign was unnerved by Mrs. Dole's withdrawal. ``You don't have
any control over any of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are now more big-name candidates out of the race
than in it, Mrs. Dole's departure is particularly notable because
as the only woman contender, she brought a star quality to the
campaign and was something of a wild card because she was popular
with many women and young voters who had not before participated.
In survey after survey, she had scored second to Bush _ albeit a
far distant second.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who benefits from the hasty exits, Bush deserves
credit for showing his opponents to the door, with the help of a
$60 million warchest and towering poll numbers. Mrs. Dole was
preceded by former Vice President Dan Quayle, Rep. John Kasich of
Ohio, Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire and former Gov. Lamar
Alexander of Tennessee. And though it is not official, Pat Buchanan
is out the door as well, positioning himself for the Reform Party
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``However this plays next January in terms of who it helps or
who it hurts, the plain fact is that Bush has enjoyed a level of
support never seen in presidential politics,'' said Ralph Reed, an
adviser to Bush. ``This speaks more to the strengths of Governor
Bush than it does the weakness of the Dole candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   While the shrunken field may offer new hopes and opportunities
for Bush's rivals, in practical terms there were no immediate signs
that he is diminished. Thus far, there is no change in the dynamic
of Bush dominance that has guided this race from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Even here in Arizona, where McCain is the favorite son, the
senator is still in a neck-in-neck competition with Bush in the
latest polls. ``I hope to do well here,'' Bush said in an interview
in Phoenix on Monday. ``I'm in the business of trying to earn a
broad base of support across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   And although McCain and Mrs. Dole were battling the same turf,
Bush could actually pick up more raw votes from her withdrawal than
McCain because of his broad appeal to Republicans across the
political spectrum and his aura of invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup Poll, said that in
a national survey taken by his organization early this month Bush
drew 60 percentage points. Mrs. Dole pulled in only 11 percent. But
when her supporters were asked for their second choice, Bush was
the overwhelming favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ''This doesn't alter the lineup _ it makes everybody a little
bit bigger,'' said Ed Gillespie, a Republican strategist. ``The
question is whether Forbes or McCain can capitalize enough right
now to thrust themselves into the principal challenger's spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men will have an opportunity to once against make their
pitches at the first Republican debate on Friday in New Hampshire.
Bush has opted not to participate.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster, warned that it would be
foolish for Bush's rivals to get too excited. ``People are slowly,
some more slowly than others, coming to the conclusion that this
nomination is over,'' he said. ``It's not being confronted just
with the money. It's the fact that 60 percent of Republican primary
voters support Bush. It's a tough wall to get over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
