<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-INTERNEES-MEMORIAL-AR     10-20 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNEES-MEMORIAL-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONUMENT TO JAPANESE-AMERICAN INTERNEES WILL RISE IN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT19, NYT35 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of families were crowded together in
despair in the desert heat of an Arizona internment camp in 1942
when Eleanor Roosevelt suddenly appeared one day pleading with them
not to lose faith in American democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine?'' asked Cherry Tsutsumida, exulting anew at
the apparition-like visit 57 years ago. She was then a disheartened
6-year-old in the camp of uprooted Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that's a great woman,'' Ms. Tsutsumida said, remembering
details of the first lady's silk blouse and gabardine skirt and,
above all, of the comfort that she brought to the traumatized
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the great domestic tragedies of World War II, 120,000
Japanese-Americans had been denied due process and trucked off by
federal agents after Japan attacked Pearl Harbor, solely because of
their Japanese ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This great lady, coming out to tell us not to lose faith,''
said the American-born Ms. Tsutsumida, explaining in a rush of
recollections just why she could never lose faith.
</P>
<P>
   Such memories of the harsh world of the interned
Japanese-Americans of World War II will soon have a focus near the
Capitol in a sculptured pair of graceful flying cranes _ one
pinioned by the barbed wire of internment, the other soaring like
Ms. Tsutsumida's faith in America.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze sculpture will be the centerpiece of a street-corner
memorial park three blocks north of the Senate chamber.
Construction is to begin Friday amid a celebration by some durable
Americans who well recall their internment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monument will tell the story forever,'' 80-year-old Joe
Ichiuji said, looking back to when federal agents ominously
descended along the Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tsutsumida's nation turned upside down, she recalled. In
that frenzied time, FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover argued against the
need for internment, proving more liberal than California Attorney
General Earl Warren, who led the internment drive yet was later
chief justice during an historically liberal era of the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To neutralize local leadership and forestall any protest, agents
first arrested the elders _ fathers of thousands of
Japanese-American families. Most were too stunned to disobey the
government, said Ichiuji, who went from being a 22-year-old
citizen, proud to have been drafted into the United States Army,
before Pearl Harbor, to an official pariah discharged as an ``enemy
alien'' and bound for internment.
</P>
<P>
   Families soon followed the fathers into exile solely on the
strength of an executive writ from President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   In the camps, fathers were often separated from their families,
and the barracks style of living _ lining up for meals and showers
and losing privacy in common rooms _ presented a woeful threat to
family integrity, Ms. Tsutsumida recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I later studied political science,'' said Ms. Tsutsumida, who
is director of the National Japanese American Memorial Foundation,
which financed the $10.6 million memorial. ``And I remember one of
my professors, Hannah Arendt, teaching that the internment was
significant because it was the first time a democratic nation took
a group of people who had citizenship and acted on them without due
process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Far from bitter, Ichiuji yearned like many friends in the camps
to show his loyalty and demanded military service. When the
government formed an Army unit of Japanese-Americans to fight in
Europe, he volunteered. That unit, the 442nd Regimental Combat
Team, was one of the most decorated front-line units of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Ichiuji's most harrowing war memory is of being in the vanguard
that liberated the Dachau concentration camp. He winced in
recalling a scene of starved inmates staggering into the street to
claw sustenance from the carcass of a dead animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sight I will never forget,'' said Ichiuji, a
shoemaker's son who used the GI Bill of Rights after the war to go
to college and achieve a 37-year career in the Agency for
International Development. ``It is indeed ironic that I, who had
come from an American internment camp, would come upon the Nazi
death camp and its Jewish victims. There were vast differences, of
course, but the basis for incarceration was the same: racial
prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the camps, some young men became known as the No-No Boys,
refusing as conscientious objectors to fight for a nation that took
away their families' rights. ``These days, our young generation
resonates to the No-No Boys,'' said Ms. Tsutsumida who celebrates
patriot and objector as one. ``The diversity, that's what so
important. Japanese-Americans were not stereotypical.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Tsutsumida and Ichiuji offered their recollections in
separate conversations, they shared an admission of pride as
Americans in having seen their government steadily, if slowly,
reverse the injustices of internment. Laws barring foreign-born
Asians from owning land or obtaining citizenship were repealed.
Apologies were offered by Congress, and reparations paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This memorial celebrates the fact that our great democracy did
finally admit it did a great wrong,'' Ms. Tsutsumida said. ``This
is not a war memorial. This is a civil rights memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Ichiuji agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Truman pinned a citation to our unit's colors,'' he
said, ``And he told us, `You fought not only the enemy, but you
fought prejudice, and you won.'''
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will occupy three-quarters of an acre and offer the
quiet of a rock garden and pool set amid cherry trees and a
28-foot-tall ceremonial bell suggestive of a Japanese shrine. The
government donated the land and will maintain the park, while
Japanese-Americans financed the construction.
</P>
<P>
   When Ichiuji came back from the war, he found that his family's
old home, unlike that of many other internment victims, had been
kept empty and protected by friendly fellow citizens in Pacific
Grove, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``My folks were lucky,'' he said. ``I am proud of my heritage
and my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tsutsumida recalled internment as ``a very quick lesson in
civics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the potential of the United States,'' she said,
anticipating the memorial as a redemption of the long-ago plea she
heard from Mrs. Roosevelt.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
