<HEADER>
A3259 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CORWIN-RADIO-2TAKES-$     10-20 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORWIN-RADIO-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG THOUGHTS, STILL UNCENSORED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Ohio, Calf.)   (af)  
 By CHARLES STRUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RADIO ANNOUNCER: The following is a dramatization.
</P>
<P>
   (Music up _ something portentous, by Liszt, perhaps _ fading to
the sound of Big Ben chiming midnight.)
</P>
<P>
   RADIO EXECUTIVE: Holy smoke, it's October! The millennium is
almost here. Get Corwin on the line.
</P>
<P>
   SECRETARY: Yes, sir.
</P>
<P>
   (Sound of dial tone, then of phone buttons being punched. Three
rings.)
</P>
<P>
   CORWIN: Hello?
</P>
<P>
   RADIO EXECUTIVE: Norman? Norman! Where the heck are you? The
millennium is coming. Do something!
</P>
<P>
   CORWIN: O.K. Give me 30 minutes of air time, Walter Cronkite and
Elmer Bernstein and call me in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of a stretch, this little scene. For more than 60
years, Norman Corwin's radio dramas about the human condition and
the state of the planet _ America, in particular _ have helped
shape the public perception of who we are and what we're doing
here. Through war and peace, Corwin opened his microphone to big
thoughts and the common man: freedom, loyalty, courage, fear,
despair, triumph. For nine years at CBS _ 1938 to 1947 _ he
presided over national catharsis at the radio console.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with the last 1,000 years to look back on, Corwin has
come up with ``Memos to a New Millennium,'' a half-hour script he
calls a meditation for radio. Underwritten by the Corporation for
Public Broadcasting, it will be distributed nationally at year's
end by Public Radio International.
</P>
<P>
   But its premiere will be Tuesday evening at the Museum of
Television and Radio, in Manhattan, followed by a discussion
featuring Corwin, who is flying in from his home in Los Angeles,
and Cronkite, who narrates the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Corwin's ``Memos'' are not prescriptions from the perspective of
his long life, 89 years so far, or his illustrious career as
dramatist or propagandist for the good guys and the right stuff.
He's too smart to make predictions for the next thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back on predictions, you and I know for a certainty,''
Corwin said in an interview last week, ``that nothing's going to
change overnight. But the logic finally asserts itself.'' His
memos, then, are offered as hopes for the coming 365,000 or so
days: keeping the peace, cleaning the environment and giving
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   With a ghostly trumpet fanfare scored by Elmer Bernstein,
Cronkite, in the familiar voice that is itself a kind of studio
sound effect, starts his narration slowly: ``The new millennium.
Say it slowly. It will be with us for the next 1,000 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the birth of Jesus and the calendar that brings us
to the year 20 centuries into the present, he continues: ``It was
one of very few global covenants ever made without having to fight
over it. Not everybody was satisfied with the arrangement, but
right now, this being the last day, you have only to put a simple
question to every knowing civilization in the atlas. Ask them what
date they will print in their newspapers tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   An actress' voice says, ``Jan. 1, 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite follows up, ``Even though the new millennium will have
arrived on schedule and to nobody's surprise, it will be the
biggest of all late-breaking news.''
</P>
<P>
   News, especially breaking news, was where Norman Corwin began
his career but not always where his mind and heart wandered. A
Bostonian by birth, Corwin finished high school and went to work
almost immediately for a small Massachusetts paper, The Greenfield
Daily Recorder. He joined The Springfield Daily Republican two
years later, in 1929, where besides covering courts and the police,
he became radio editor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A stint on a local station in Massachusetts and in Cincinnati
adapting, writing and reciting poetry in 15-minute broadcasts
eventually got him to CBS in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At CBS, Corwin was often given free rein to write, cast and
direct radio dramas as well as several landmark patriotic programs
that continue to be studied and marveled at in radio-journalism
classrooms today.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were ``We Hold These Truths,'' an all-star program
that featured Orson Welles, James Stewart (then an Army Air Corps
corporal), Edward G. Robinson, Lionel Barrymore and Walter Huston
in a coast-to-coast, four-network extravaganza to commemorate the
150th anniversary of the Bill of Rights. But eight days before the
broadcast, the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor, so the show served
at least two purposes: a group hug to a frightened America and a
call to arms for the sake of liberty and security.
</P>
<P>
   Corwin orchestrated similar programs with nationalistic themes
for V-E Day and V-J Day. His dramas derided fascism and cheered on
Allied soldiers, sailors, marines and airmen. Other productions,
like ``The Plot to Overthrow Christmas'' (Will Geer as the Devil in
an unsuccessful attempt to assassinate Santa Claus) and ``The
Undecided Molecule,'' about a molecule ``that couldn't make up its
mind what phylum it wanted to be assigned'' (Groucho Marx portrayed
the judge at the molecule's trial) were bright and inventive in
ways uniquely Corwin.
</P>
<P>
   He adapted works by Carl Sandburg and Edgar Lee Masters and made
the language of the Bible, Shakespeare and Whitman the common
currency of his research and writing.
</P>
<P>
   At CBS, Corwin was largely free to write, direct and produce in
the artistic or public service vein that shielded him from the
pressures of advertising agencies, sponsors and broadcasting
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Corwin considers himself blessed to have landed at CBS, because
``at that time, and at no time since, or in any other radio entity,
it was possible for a writer like myself to have complete autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the prime examples of that is when CBS asked me to do a
program commemorating the end of the war in Europe, `On a Note of
Triumph.' They said, `We are going to requisition an hour of
commercial time for you to do the program. They never asked me for
a first draft; they never asked what my approach would be; they
didn't ask me to send them the first 20 pages; they didn't ask who
I was going to use in the cast. The first time any of the hierarchy
heard it was when it was on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Corwin, who has taught telecommunications and journalism at the
University of Southern California since 1970, said that within five
years of that broadcast ``radio became more guarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has published 17 books, written plays and stories
and lectured for decades, the radio is home. ``Memos to a New
Millennium,'' is, in fact, the sixth in a series called ``More by
Corwin,'' an undertaking for public radio commissioned by his
collaborator and producer Mary Beth Kirchner.
</P>
<P>
   With easygoing chauvinism, he added: ``In radio, there was never
a term equivalent to boob tube or couch potato. The eye is so
literal, whereas the ear makes a participant of the listener. The
listener becomes the set designer, the wardrobe mistress, the
casting director. You can listen to `Carmen' on radio. Carmen in
person may weigh 350 pounds, but to the listener she's a beautiful,
steamy lady with a rose in her teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   So Corwin is a romantic? ``Yes, but not religiously so.'' And an
optimist? ``I would say not an optimist as much as an
affirmationist. I believe in affirming what is valuable. I believe
America should remind itself of who it is and how it began.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
