u f BC-NASDAQ-RISE-BOS &LR;      10-20 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-RISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREASE BELIES VULNERABILITY OF TECH STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq stock index rose 3.72 percent
Wednesday, its fourth-biggest percentage gain this year.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the Nasdaq alone, technology stocks are still on a
roll. Amid concerns about inflation, an overpriced stock market,
and the new millennium, the index reached an all-time high of
2915.95 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's rise of 99.95 points erased part of the loss in the
index since then. The index closed at 2788.13. But the Nasdaq, on
closer inspection, is increasingly being pulled up by a few heavy
hitters, such as Microsoft Corp. and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the broad index, a raft of technology companies _ and not
just Internet companies _ have shed 20 percent to almost 60 percent
of their value since reaching highs earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the board right now, tech stocks are under pressure,''
said Mark Minervini, chief investment strategist for Quantech
Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Several major computer firms have suffered steep falls from
their levels early this year. They are among the workhorses that
money managers a year ago were hailing as unstoppable leaders of a
rising market.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Wednesday's closing prices, Dell Computer Corp. has
dropped 26 percent from its 1999 high; Intel Corp., 22 percent;
Unisys Corp., 51 percent; Compaq Computer Corp., 59 percent; and
Lucent Technologies Inc., 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these stocks staged short rallies in late summer but
have fallen further since.
</P>
<P>
   If the once high-flying tech sector is in the midst of a huge
pullback, as pessimists think, its impact would go far beyond the
Nasdaq. The sector has grown to more than 22 percent of the value
of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index, up from 8 percent just
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 gained 28.11 points Wednesday, or 2.2 percent, to
1289.43. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 187.43 points, or
1.8 percent, to close at 10,392.36. IBM Corp. and Hewlett-Packard
Co. are the only pure technology stocks among the Dow30.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, the largest company by market value, contributed most
to gains Wednesday in both the Nasdaq and S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Kirk disagrees with the pessimists. A managing director
in the Boston office of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, Kirk sees the high-tech
sector heading in one direction in the long term: up. ``We're
surrounded by technology in our everyday lives,'' she said. ``I
think we're in a great secular growth trend for tech long-term.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why is the stock price for Compaq Computer Corp. about 59
percent below its all-time high, reached on Jan. 26, of 49 1/4?
Compaq closed Wednesday at 20 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, one of the world's largest makers of personal computers,
has struggled for months. But a warning by the Houston company last
week that the recent earthquake in Taiwan may make it more
difficult for the company to fill orders for personal computers
caused its stock to drop again.
</P>
<P>
   L. Emerson Tuttle, portfolio manager for State Street Global
Advisors, traces the tech shares' woes back to last April when many
investors moved into lower-priced cyclical stocks. ``This has been
a market in which investors have been very unforgiving of any
company that provides even a whiff of bad news,'' Tuttle said.
</P>
<P>
   Small firms can be more vulnerable to bad news, creating a
market in which companies either hit home runs and their stock
soars or are eclipsed by competitors, causing their shares to drop.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nasdaq has charged higher each month, individual tech
stocks that are small to midsize have declined steadily. Since
highs reached during 1998, Avid Technology Inc., which is in the
digital entertainment business, and Cambridge Technology Partners,
a computer consultant, are among those whose stocks have sunk,
respectively, 31 percent and 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, other small firms, particularly in the software
industry, have been hit. Since reaching an all-time high in
September, Houston-based BMC Software Inc.'s stock has fallen
nearly 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointing profits are to blame for declines in some stocks.
Drops in Intel's and Dell's shares followed recent predictions that
third-quarter profits would be disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   For the tech sector overall, however, earnings are very strong.
</P>
<P>
   The 32 tech companies in the S&AMP;P 500 that have announced
third-quarter earnings posted profits that are a total of 34
percent higher than they were last year, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial Corp. Revenues are 11 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft used the word ``awesome'' to describe sales of
personal computers in the third quarter, which pushed up its
revenues and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies ``are having a good quarter,'' said Ken
Perkins, analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Ghriskey, a senior portfolio manager for Dreyfus Corp.,
said investors these days flee technology stocks if their earnings
are anything less than awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shoot-now-ask-questions-later mentality,'' he said.
``If there's any bad news, even if it's explainable, the market
doesn't want to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the vulnerability of tech stocks, Ghriskey said, are
the extremely high valuations of many stocks _ ranging from 37
times forecast earnings in 2000 for Dell to 128 times 2000 earnings
for America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the S&AMP;P 500 is priced at 23 times its year 2000
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Walsh, an associate portfolio manager who invests in
small technology firms for State Street Research &AMP; Management Co.,
said increasingly he is hunting for companies with unique products
that are immune to the competition coming from newly capitalized
companies that come into the market to take on the market leaders.
</P>
<P>
   There are gems to be found, he said. But the high valuations of
many stocks make more difficult his decision about when or whether
to invest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
