<SLUG> BC-SCFLAG-FLAP21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP may focus on BMW, Michelin in boycott against S.C. flag
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NAACP is ready to shift gears in its economic
boycott of South Carolina, a plan designed to force the Confederate
battle flag from the top of the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   As early as this afternoon, when the South Carolina Conference
of the NAACP convenes its annual meeting in North Carolina,
delegates may drive a new symbol into the fray: BMW's Z3 roadster
and the company's new X5 sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Since July, the South Carolina NAACP has relied on a tourism
boycott focused on beaches from Charleston to Myrtle Beach. Last
week, the national NAACP formally endorsed a boycott of the state
beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
   The BMW vehicles are manufactured near Greenville, S.C., the
``business capital'' of the state, said Nina Brook, press secretary
for the state's governor, Jim Hodges. NAACP officials also hinted
that Michelin North America Inc., which makes Uniroyal and
BFGoodrich tires throughout South Carolina, is a potential target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about BMW and Michelin in all of this,'' said
James Gallman, president of the NAACP's South Carolina conference.
``Whatever is at the top, we'll take a look at. I'm not discounting
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   However, as boycotts broaden, the less effective they become,
said Donald Ratajczak, director of the Economic Forecasting Center
at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure BMW is quaking at its potential sales loss,''
Ratajczak said.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hitt, a spokesman for BMW Manufacturing Corp. in Greer,
S.C., said the company will steer clear of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of building cars,'' Hitt said Wednesday.
``We don't get involved in political positions. We didn't get
involved in video poker. We didn't get involved in abortion. We've
only been here six years. The debate has been going on for more
than 20 years and has roots more than a century old. It doesn't
seem appropriate for us to get involved in the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Michelin has worked toward a compromise that
would display the Confederate flag in a memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelin is very interested in finding a way to resolve this
issue so all parties concerned are satisfied,'' said Jim Morton, a
company spokesman. ``People do not forget a boycott.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina resolution adopted Saturday by the NAACP
national board calls for economic sanctions Jan. 1. But several
groups, most of them with predominantly black memberships, already
have canceled meetings in the state. South Carolina tourism
officials still are trying to figure the exact dollar impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to bring tourism in the state to its knees,''
said Lou Fontana, a South Carolina tourism spokesman. ``But they
don't mind kicking us in the shins. It hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature hoisted the Confederate flag over the State
House in 1962 to commemorate the centennial of the Civil War, which
saw its first shots fired in South Carolina. The red flag with its
blue X and white stars has flown there ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is different than in Georgia,'' where the Confederate
emblem is incorporated into the design of the state flag, said
Democrat Tom Turnipseed, who ran unsuccessfully for state attorney
general last year. ``We have the Confederate flag over the State
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewed as a political fulcrum, BMW and Michelin sit in the back
yard of state House Speaker David Wilkins. But the top Republican
at the State House says there's no political will to move the flag
from atop the capitol, especially under threat by the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two-edged sword,'' said Wilkins, reached Wednesday at a
conference of state House speakers in San Antonio. ``While (the
boycott) is of great concern to all of us, people are not going to
do anything while there's a boycott. People resent being pushed
into a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins always has voted to keep the Confederate symbol flying.
He voted against a proposal that would have moved it to a memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represented part of our heritage, and I felt no reason to
make any changes,'' Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   When Republican David Beasley, voted out of the governor's
mansion last year, proposed moving the flag to a memorial site,
conservatives ended their allegiance to him.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's spokeswoman criticized Wilkins for not working
toward a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor doesn't feel there's enough support in the House
for removal of the Confederate flag to be viable this year,'' said
Brook. ``The business community says the flag should move, but it's
just not worked its way through, especially to the majority party
in the House ... Legislative reservation is a major road block.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
