<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3266 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DOLE-WITHDRAWS-ART-2N     10-20 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-WITHDRAWS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: things up.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole spoke fervently of the historic nature of her campaign
and the excitement she generated among many women, who often
brought their daughters to meet her. But she rejected the
suggestion that she was running as a woman and her message was
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster based in Atlanta, said that
being female was a plus for Mrs. Dole. ``There was some grumbling
that people were more reluctant to give to a woman, but it gave her
a certain cachet among Republican primary voters and got her more
attention than she might otherwise have gotten,'' he said. ``She
excited moderate and conservative women, and it's a shame she
couldn't have leveraged that cachet into serious contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Another drawback was that she had never been elected to public
office. Only Dwight D. Eisenhower and Herbert Hoover have been
elected president without running for office before.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mrs. Dole's pollster, Linda DiVall, said that in a
hypothetical match-up with the Democratic frontrunner, Vice
President Al Gore, Mrs. Dole was leading, 44 percent to 37 percent.
Bush leads Gore by even wider margins in most polls, but Ms.
DiVall's point was that only in a primary so skewed by Bush's
outsized bankroll and sweep of endorsements does Mrs. Dole look
wanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will clearly go down in history for running a serious and
substantive campaign,'' Ms. DiVall said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until now, women had run for president as little more than
tokens of protest. The Equal Rights Party began running female
candidates in 1872, to little notice. It was not until 1964 that a
woman, Sen. Margaret Chase Smith of Maine, was nominated at a major
party convention. She received 27 votes at the Republican
convention, then withdrew after the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Shirley Chisholm of New York became the first woman and the
first black woman actually to campaign for the nomination of a
major party. In 1972 she earned 151 delegates through the
Democratic primaries and caucuses. This was only a fraction of the
total, but unlike Elizabeth Dole, Ms. Chisholm at least had her
name on the ballot in several states.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mrs. Dole, a former Cabinet secretary and Harvard-trained
lawyer, was the first woman to be perceived as a serious
presidential prospect. As she said on Wednesday, ``What we've done
is paved the way for the person who will be the first woman
president.'' And there is much speculation now whether she would
consider the vice presidential nomination or at least a position in
a Republican Cabinet. She demurred on Wednesday, but did not rule
out accepting the number-two spot.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres said that Mrs. Dole was a serious prospect for vice
president but added: ``She is a higher-risk choice now because you
won't know how she would react in the heat of a campaign as a
candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
