<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3270 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CRAVEN-FILMS-ART-2TAK     10-20 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAVEN-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFTING FROM BLOOD AND GUTS TO HEART AND BRAINS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Jamie Malanowski's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the movie ``Dick.''  
 By JAMIE MALANOWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not hard to believe that any director, even a veteran
director, would feel butterflies at his first meeting with Meryl
Streep, especially if that gold-standard actress was considering
taking the lead in his new film.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness could be granted if he felt obliged to mention his
credits, refer to his grosses, point to the performances he had
wrung over the years from Johnny Depp, Sharon Stone and Eddie
Murphy, among others.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the director had something else on his mind. ``The
first thing I did,'' admits Wes Craven, ``was try to make her feel
like she'd be working with someone who had a brain in his head and
normalcy to his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Displaying ``a brain'' and ``normalcy'' is usually an achievable
goal for a vertebrate, even for ones who work in Hollywood, but
Craven of course has for a quarter century been famously producing
work less known for brains and normalcy than for viscera and
extremes.
</P>
<P>
   From his cringingly inexpert yet profitable debut with ``The
Last House on the Left'' (1972), the story of a Manson-like family
of killers and the vengeance that is wreaked upon them, through the
imaginatively sinister and profitable ``A Nightmare on Elm Street''
(1984), which established the teen-age horror movie genre, and on
to the witty and profitable ``Scream'' (1996) and ``Scream 2''
(1997), the second amusingly deconstructing the first, Craven could
always be counted on to spill an audience-pleasing ocean of blood.
But his success had the effect of placing him in a sanguine
straightjacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, I had never really intended to do
horror,'' says Craven, who is the kind of person _ tall, lean,
soft-spoken, modest, 50ish, neatly bearded, professorial,
Midwestern _ that you might believe is repressing a kink or two but
not a ravenous appetite for the macabre. ``All of a sudden, after
`Last House on the Left,' I was a maker of scary movies. It
immediately cut off any perception that I was capable of something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a source of no small amount of frustration for him over
the years, as producers and studios ruled him out of consideration
for projects merely because of the images his name conjured up. But
fortunately for him, the success that so long pigeonholed him
eventually sprang him.
</P>
<P>
   Craven's new movie, ``Music of the Heart,'' which opens Friday,
stars Ms. Streep as a music teacher in East Harlem. It is based on
a true story, is chock-full of feet-on-the-ground characters and
has heart and grit and genuine warmth. And while there's a lot of
sawing in the movie, it's done not with Freddie Krueger's
fingernails but with horsehair bows.
</P>
<P>
   Craven's moment of liberation came during dinner at Harry
Cipriani's, a Manhattan restaurant, after ``Scream'' came out.
Craven, his longtime producer Maryanne Maddelena and others who'd
worked on the Miramax production, were celebrating the success of
the movie, when, quite unexpectedly, in came the maharajahs of
Miramax, Bob and Harvey Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps,'' says Craven, ``because I had been speaking a lot in
the press about hoping to make whatever picture I was working be
the last one in the horror genre, and they wanted more out of me,
they made a very canny offer.'' Hoping no doubt to keep their
lucrative ``Elm Street''-like franchise from evaporating, the
Weinsteins, with characteristic bravura, spread their development
schedule across the table. ``They offered me a deal for three
pictures,'' recalls Craven, ``one of which could be a nongenre
film, and that film could be anything on their schedule.'' Dinner
did not proceed much farther before Craven was focusing on a
project called ``Fifty Violins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those flukes,'' says Craven. ``Some years
earlier I had had some time, so I signed up to be on the Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Sciences prescreening committee in the
documentary category.'' There he first saw ``Small Wonders,'' which
would become a 1996 Oscar-nominated documentary.
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of Roberta Guaspari, a high school violin
teacher, and of how her music program was saved from the budget ax
by a benefit concert at Carnegie Hall that featured not only Ms.
Guaspari's current and former students but eight prominent
admirers, including Isaac Stern, Itzhak Perlman and Arnold
Steinhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Craven _ former teacher, classical music devotee, Guaspari
enthusiast, artist in search of an antipodal project _ saw his
destiny. ``The guys ran down the list of properties, and I said,
`That's the one!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Music of the Heart'' _ the title ``Fifty Violins'' was
scrapped after research showed potential audience members were
reluctant to see a Meryl Streep movie that had violins in the
title, fearing it would be, as Craven puts it, ``either something
very sad or incredibly erudite'' _ will inevitably be compared to
``Mr. Holland's Opus,'' Disney's successful 1995 foray into
``Goodbye, Mr. Chips'' territory.
</P>
<P>
   But though both are about high school music teachers, they're
different in tone and approach. ``Mr. Holland's Opus'' is a warm
story that follows a teacher over the years as he develops his
inner mensch-hood. ``Music of the Heart'' is far more realistic and
far less contrived.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Ms. Guaspari is a gifted teacher with a sometimes
prickly and imperious personality, one who shows no reluctance to
toss the lackadaisical and ditsy out of her class. She also has a
healthy ration of problems that she just has to deal with _ men,
children, mother, co-workers, building renovation, parking tickets
_ all of which are pretty much based on fact.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Gray, the screenwriter who also wrote ``A Walk On The
Moon,'' ``virtually moved in with Roberta for a month,'' says
Craven, ``and she just let her hair down about the most intimate
details of her life, many of them revealing and not very glamorous,
like her unsuccessful attempts with men and the pain of her
divorce.'' What comes across very clearly is a very realistic and
likable person who has found in music a way she and others can deal
with the challenges life presents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first conversation I had with her,'' Craven
said. ``I said, `You must be so proud to have kids playing in the
Denver Philharmonic and elsewhere,' and she said: `It's O.K., but
it's not the most important thing. I'm teaching them how to play
their lives.' She said the violin is a terribly difficult
instrument, but life is a much more difficult instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said: `Everything I teach _ discipline, how to stand, how
to stand strong, how to learn the rudiments before you try anything
more, to be responsible for the tone you make _ is teaching them to
play their lives better. I teach them that you have to learn the
process, and that it's difficult, but you also get that knowledge
that people have been there before you, and that they've figured
out certain things you can do that are better than other things,
and if you put in the time and you put in the discipline, you give
yourself a leg up on life.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
