<SLUG> BC-IAPA-PRESIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING EDITOR OF TEXAS PAPER TO LEAD FREE PRESS ORGANIZATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional trim and optional ending included) 
 
By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Managing Editor Tony Pederson of the Houston Chronicle
took over as president of the Inter American Press Association on
Wednesday night, pledging to continue an ``unflinching, unrelenting
and uncompromising'' fight for media freedom in the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson, 48, closed the 55th assembly of the association by
recognizing journalists who have died while doing their jobs,
including Philip True, the San Antonio Express News reporter killed
last year in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson noted that many of the journalists at the Houston
meeting had been victims of violence or forced from their home
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are real heroes among those here who have been a part of
the historic fight for a free press in the Americas,'' Pederson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe those heroes past and present nothing less,'' than to
fight against threats against journalists, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson also promised to continue pressuring Cuban President
Fidel Castro to increase press liberty on the island.
</P>
<P>
   His speech came after an awards ceremony in which True's wife,
Martha, received an IAPA grand prize for his work. Philip's infant
son, Philip Jr., who was born after Philip was murdered last
December while hiking in central Mexico, was also present at the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha True thanked the organization for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I receive it in his name, in the name of his son and in the
name of all those who have lost their lives working as
journalists,'' she said in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The press association also gave its Freedom of the Press award
to four Cuban dissidents who were imprisoned for producing a
political flyer calling for increased freedom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
One of the four sent a letter of thanks from his jail cell in
Ariza, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we can be there next year to thank you personally for
this award,'' wrote Vladimiro Roca.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The IAPA, which represents 1,300 news agencies from throughout
the Americas, also produced a final set of resolutions Wednesday,
condemning continued problems for journalists throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution noted that seven journalists have died in the 12
months since its last annual assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in democratic nations, politicians uneasy with a free and
independent press are using every means at their disposal to
silence or pressure their critics and limit the watchdog role of
the media,'' the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
   The IAPA also noted that Venezuela represents a ``disturbingly
new'' threat to press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   A leftist Army leader, Hugo Chavez, was elected president of
Venezuela last year. His allies are now rewriting the country's
constitution, and press freedom appears at risk.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Pederson said the IAPA will likely send a
mission to Venezuela next month to lobby for journalists there. He
also said he would like to send a mission to Cuba, though he
doubted Fidel Castro would allow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am particularly concerned about Cuba,'' Pederson said.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Waco, Texas, Pederson graduated from Baylor before
receiving a masters degree in journalism from Ohio State
University. He was sports editor at the Chronicle before being
named managing editor in 1983. He is now vice president and
managing editor of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fluent in Spanish, Pederson attended his first IAPA meeting a
decade ago, but was skeptical at first, based on what he had heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rap against the IAPA at the time was that it was a group
of rich and conservative Latin American newspaper owners who were
more interested in promoting their own business than in preserving
freedom of the press,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But after getting to know the organization, Pederson discovered
that many of its members were serious journalists who had risked
their lives to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I started to appreciate were the stories,'' he said.
``People losing their family, going to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes his one-year term as president will do at least
some help bringing new freedom throughout the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalism is part of the greatest freedom people are given,''
he said, ``the freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
