<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PEREZ-BOS &LR;      10-20 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PEREZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BACKUP' IS ON A ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His work title is backup catcher. Despite his extra
duties of late, and his exceptional job in carrying out those
duties, Atlanta upstart Eddie Perez has no illusions. He said when
starter Javy Lopez returns to the team when his knee is healthy, he
will return to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he is the reigning Most Valuable Player of the National
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was 10 for 20 in six games with two home runs and five
RBIs. His last hit of the series, a one-out single, came in the
eighth inning Tuesday. Otis Nixon pinch-ran, stole second, went to
third on a throwing error, and scored the tying run on Brian
Hunter's single.
</P>
<P>
   Three innings later, Kenny Rogers walked in the winning run and
the Braves were headed back to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest thing that happened to me,'' Perez said.
``Now I've gotten the chance to play and win the National League
Championship. And hopefully, this will be my biggest moment, the
next step.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lopez can't return next spring, the Braves know they won't
have to go shopping for a quality catcher. They will only need to
change Perez's job description.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year old catcher from Cuidad Ojeda, Venezuela, who was
used primarily as Greg Maddux's catcher (catching all 33 of
Maddux's starts this season), is making the most in Lopez's
absence. Perez started a career-high 86 games this season and set
career-highs in games (104), at-bats (309), runs (30), and hits
(77). He threw out 21 of 72 base stealers.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the postseason where Perez has shone. He homered in
the first two games of the National League Championship Series,
when he went 7 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Perez belted a sixth-inning homer off Pat Mahomes for
the decisive run in the Braves' 4-2 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, Perez hit a home run off Kenny Rogers in the sixth
after Brian Jordan's two-run home run tied the game. Perez's shot
put the Braves up 4-2 in a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still the backup catcher,'' said Perez, who has been the
starter since his friend Lopez suffered a partial anterior cruciate
ligament tear in his right knee in July. Perez hit .249 during the
season with seven home runs and 30 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just doing the job because Javy is not here. That's why
I'm backup catching. But I think my knee is worse than Javy's
knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who was on the disabled list from Aug. 30 to Sept. 14,
1996, with a torn right quad muscle, said he will have offseason
surgery because of tendinitis in both knees.
</P>
<P>
   But until then he hopes to help the Braves in their march toward
another title. ``This year I don't think I'm doing the job I want
to do at hitting, but I'm concentrating more, and catching, because
we've got a good pitching staff,'' said Perez. ``That's what I'm
trying to do. When it's time to hit, I hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this season, Perez was best known for the grand slam in
the eighth inning off then-Cub closer Rod Beck to give the Braves a
6-0 lead in the clinching Game 3 of the NL Division Series last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was in the first round, this is in the second
round,'' said Perez, when asked to compare the home run off Rogers
to the one off Beck. ``This is a lot better, and especially against
a pitcher who was throwing _ I was, like, 0 for 100 against that
guy _ and I finally got a hit. It was very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez might draw comparisons to former Braves star Francisco
Cabrera, a reserve known for a ninth-inning, two-out, two-run,
pinch-hit RBI single in the deciding game of the 1992 NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   But like Cabrera, Perez has had other quality moments as a
reserve. Last year, in his third full season, he batted a
career-high .336 and posted career-highs in RBIs (32), doubles (12)
and hits (50). He also recorded his first stolen base after 208
career games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I put up good numbers,'' said Perez, who was signed
by the Braves as a free agent on Sept. 27, 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
