<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3274 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CRAVEN-FILMS-ART-2NDT     10-20 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAVEN-FILMS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: on life.'''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Guaspari, by the way, also remembers her first meeting with
Craven warmly, though she allows: ``I was pretty leery. I hadn't
seen any of his pictures, but my sons explained who he was. It
seemed so absurd, so weird! But I had coffee with him, and he was
so gentle, and kind and sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Madonna was originally set to play Ms. Guaspari, but her
relationship with Craven was marked by creative differences of an
actually creative and not a National Enquirer sort.
</P>
<P>
   According to the director, Madonna wanted the story to focus
more on Ms. Guaspari's relationships with adults, particularly
boyfriends. ``We were not far from shooting, and she was calling
for more and more really quite drastic script changes,'' Craven
said. ``I felt if I went along with it I would be giving up control
of the picture I wanted to make, to make one Madonna would see but
that I wouldn't. And I thought, what was the point? I wasn't going
to come all this way and get my chance to make a nongenre film,
just to make somebody else's movie.''
</P>
<P>
   This placed the Weinsteins, who were trying to entice Madonna
into starring in a film version of ``Chicago,'' in a predicament,
but Miramax backed Craven, and Madonna departed. (Her withdrawal
from the project was an ``amicable decision,'' a spokeswoman for
Madonna said.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two months, Craven and Ms. Maddelena searched
furiously for a Roberta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan Sarandon was one of the people I thought would be good,
but she wasn't available. For about a week Julia Roberts was
interested in doing it, but she had a conflict with `Runaway
Bride.' We had always hoped Meryl would do it, but early on she had
said she was too tired.'' Meanwhile, the project was in free fall.
``We went from 70 staff members to two. We lost all the locations
and had to sell off our coffee makers. We were sharing our office
with another production, and we were two days from having to
vacate.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven approached Ms. Streep again in the form of a letter. ``I
poured out my heart to her,'' he said. ``I said I thought the story
of Roberta deserved to be told, and all these kids had worked so
hard and they were primed to go, and I desperately wanted to do
this, and I thought she was perfect for it, and would she please
reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   He allows that at one point he even offered to mow her lawn for
her. With mere days to go before the project was to be shelved, Ms.
Streep reconsidered; she credits the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time Meryl met Roberta at my office,'' Craven
recalls, ``Meryl said to her, `Let's go into wardrobe.' After 10
minutes you could hear them laughing. And then they closed the
door. They were in there for three hours, and you could hear all
this laughing and loud voices, and while they were in there, they
completely told each other their lives. It was Meryl's way of
drawing everything out about this woman that was germane to this
role, and when she came out, she had Roberta cold. It was like she
had downloaded her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Streep also undertook a crash course in the violin, her
success at which was demonstrated at the culmination of the shoot,
when the concert at Carnegie Hall scenes were filmed. ``Meryl took
her position for the first run-through, and as she did, she looked
over and saw Itzhak Perlman and Isaac Stern staring at her. It was
one of the few times I'd seen her shake. Of course, she did it
perfectly, and their jaws just dropped open. They said, `We can't
believe her, she's perfect, her form is perfect, how did you do
it?' Of course, it was all her.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Craven is tossing around compliments _ to Ms. Streep, to
Ms. Guaspari, to Miramax _ one might get the impression that he was
merely a very fortunate bystander. But in fact he ramrodded the
production, which included numerous scenes with a lot of tightly
scheduled amateur child actors and tightly scheduled professionals,
on time and under budget, while managing to help mold some
marvelous performances from his pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wes was generally very open to hearing how we wanted to do
things, which I like,'' said Aiden Quinn, who plays Roberta's love
interest in the film, ``but he was also sometimes very specific
about line readings, which I generally don't like, and which I
usually regard as a sign of an insecure director. But it was just
the opposite here. Every time he wanted that specificity, it was
because the rhythm of the scene was off and wasn't working. And
every time, what he wanted us to do brought the scene together.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from keeping his fingers crossed for ``Music of the
Heart,'' Craven has been putting ``Scream 3'' through
post-production, as well as monitoring the release of his first
novel, ``The Fountain Society.'' The novel isn't quite a horror
story, but it does have clones, brain transplants, murder-mad
scientists and high-level government conspiracies.
</P>
<P>
   Film rights to the book have already been purchased by
Dreamworks SKG, and Craven will direct. Beyond that, is he
contemplating a return to scary subjects? Could be. ``I'd like to
explore something more personal,'' he says, ``perhaps divorce from
the father's side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
