<HEADER>
A3277 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-GANGES21-COX     10-20 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANGES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waters of Ganges River unrivaled for many Hindus
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Along the lanes of Calcutta's congested Kumartuli
neighborhood, artisans craft colossal idols of the goddess Durga
for one of India's biggest religious festivals. The mud they use to
mold their gaudy images comes from the Ganges River, which flows a
few hundred yards behind them.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this week, public worship of the goddess of
strength will be over. The idols will be immersed in the river from
where they came to dissolve in the waters believed holy by Hindus _
symbolic of how, for many Indians, life begins and ends with the
Ganges.
</P>
<P>
   In the towns and cities that have grown up along its banks,
ancient rhythms go on, reflected in the daily ebb and flow of life
along the river.
</P>
<P>
   The Ganges supports more than 400 million Indians, in the most
populous river basin in the world. It provides irrigation for
agriculture, food from fisheries, transportation and trade.
</P>
<P>
   In Calcutta, when the river is not swollen with monsoon rains,
life bustles on its crowded, muddy banks. Under the shade of an old
railroad overpass, 33-year-old Ballav Sen lies on his back on a
slatted wooden mat just a few yards from water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Sen, an orthodox Hindu, frequents the river to fetch water for
his home. To the Hindus, the Ganges, or Ganga as it is locally
known, is the holiest of rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect Ganga jal (water),'' says Sen, as a professional
masseur works his body over. ``All the gods we worship depend on
Ganga jal. So I come here to take water home. When I have the time,
I get a massage.''
</P>
<P>
   Between Sen and the stone-paved accesses to the water, garbage
is strewn in the silt. Gentle waves lap piles of rotting marigold
garlands, cracked earthen urns and straw-filled skeletons of
immersed mud idols.
</P>
<P>
   None of the thousands gathered on the bank or ghat are bothered
by the debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not waste products,'' says Sen. ``What you see are
all natural products. After worshiping, we Hindus immerse figures
of the Gods into the Ganga. The straw, the bamboo, the flowers, the
urns, they are all left over from our pujas (ceremonial worship).''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sen's claims, the waters of the Ganges in Calcutta are a
far cry from their pristine beginnings high up in the Himalayas.
Chemicals and human and animal waste make India's largest river
increasingly polluted in its 1,560-mile trip from the mountains
through the vast fertile plains to the Bay of Bengal just south of
here. Along its southward route, the Ganges picks up a
mind-boggling 343 million gallons of sewage and 687,000 gallons of
industrial waste per day from about 30 cities, 70 towns and
thousands of villages. In addition, the river accumulates thousands
of animal carcasses and the remains of dead Hindus, whose cremated
ashes are put into the river for spiritual salvation.
</P>
<P>
   But this does not matter to Sen and other Hindus. They believe
in the magical self-cleansing properties of the river they call
Mother Ganga.
</P>
<P>
   `it's a problem, I suppose. It is a fact the waters are
polluted and even dangerously polluted, but what can we do? It is
the Ganga, after all,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A stone's throw away from the makeshift massage parlour, Khokon
Shai and his three brothers perform last rites for their father.
The Shai brothers have their heads shaved, make their offerings to
the departed soul and take a dip in the holy water. Their father's
ashes are scattered in the same water.
</P>
<P>
   No other water will do, says Khokon Shai.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have gathered here for a simple bath are oblivious to
the ritual around them. An old woman shuttles back and forth from
the river, wringing the water from the sari she has just washed.
Another woman shampoos her hair. Others clean their cooking
utensils.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, elevated ramps lead from ticket booths to the commuter
ferry docks. A million Calcuttans each day walk over the creaky
wooden paths at various ghats to board the ferries.
</P>
<P>
   Hari Chetri, a dock worker, uses the ferry to go back and forth
from work in the morning, at lunch and in the evening. The trip
from Babughat south to Shibpur takes him 13 minutes. By land, it
would take an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Jibon Shardar prefers the 4 cent boat ride to a bus because of
Calcutta's pollution and horrific traffic, which averages just 5
miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so much more comfortable this way, isn't it? Especially
in the heat,'' he says aboard the Shibpur ferry.
</P>
<P>
   The boat is now midway in its crossing of the river. The water
glistens under the afternoon sun like a sheet of metal. To the
right, two barges carry bundles of straw down river. To the left,
the greenery along the once majestic Strand Road adds a bit of
welcome color to the dreary backdrop of Calcutta's skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen watch their nets that haul in the giant carp and other
fish that fill city markets every morning and evening.
</P>
<P>
   And at Babughat, a new set of bathers has descended to the muddy
shore, just as keen as the last group to take a dip in Ganga jal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
