<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE'S FRUSTRATIONS RUN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Patriots fans expect Bledsoe to win every week,
just as Red Sox fans expect Pedro Martinez to win every game he
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The realists know this is not always going to happen. During the
course of making 35 starts, Martinez is not going to be on his
``A'' game in a half-dozen or so games. He might miss with a
breaking pitch on a full count, and instead of a strikeout, there's
a walk, and that leads to the other team ultimately scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Bledsoe hasn't been completely on his game. He's missing
deep. This is the strength of the Patriots' offense, the basic
element of it, really. The Patriots have speedsters in Terry Glenn,
Shawn Jefferson, and Tony Simmons who can blow away the opposition.
Two Sundays ago in a 16-14 loss in Kansas City, Bledsoe missed
Jefferson downfield twice, all alone for potential touchdowns. Last
Sunday, in a 31-30 loss to Miami, he missed Jefferson twice and
Glenn once, though he nailed Simmons on a 29-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City game was more understandable because he was
pressured, hit, and hurried beyond belief. Last week, the Patriots
had more protection, sometimes using seven players to block, and
were able to pick up the Dolphin blitzes. Bledsoe just missed his
targets, especially on third down when he converted only 2 of 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went in with a different emphasis in that we kept more guys
in to block,'' Bledsoe said. ``The pass protection was excellent.
But when we win battles down the field, it's my job to make the
throws and I didn't do that. This week (against) Denver), we have
to find a balance between keeping seven guys in or sending
everybody out. When my guys are open downfield, I have to hit
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have won the four games in which the ratio of
passes to runs was close, and have lost the games in which they had
to pass much more than they ran. It seems a simple prescription for
victory. Run it, even if you're only grinding out 2-3 yards at a
time. But you'll have to pardon offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese
and Bledsoe if they're tempted too much down the field. When
Jefferson is waving his arms because he's so loose and free, the
temptation is there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we do best,'' said Jefferson. ``Sure we need a
running game, every team does, but I think I've done the best I can
do as far as getting downfield and getting open. We've missed some
of those opportunities, but we'll have others we're not going to
miss. We just have to be consistent with it and things will happen
in our favor most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe is correct when he says the Patriots could have iced
Miami with just ``one or two'' more third-down conversions. And one
huge reason why they couldn't do it was the absence of wide
receiver Troy Brown, who missed the game with an ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think particularly in this last game with the type of
coverage the Dolphins played against us, Troy would have made a big
impact in that game,'' Bledsoe said. ``He would have been good for
a couple of third-down conversions which is all we would have
needed to win the game. (Vincent) Brisby came in and did a great
job. Briz is a guy who would start for a lot of teams, but Troy's
ability as an inside receiver is unparalleled.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried moving Glenn inside a few times, but the
Dolphins anticipated the move by doubling Glenn with a linebacker
and a cornerback. Bledsoe admitted that when Glenn was outside, he
often drew single coverage and ``we should have exploited that more
than we did.'' Glenn did not make a catch against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Every week brings a new set of problems. The revived Broncos are
probably going to copy much of what Miami did to Glenn, though
Brown has a chance of getting back on the field. If he does, he
should take care of the third-down issue. But if he doesn't, Glenn
and Brisby go back into Brown's role and they must be more
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a different way and a different style, Brisby is very
effective,'' said Bledsoe. ``He's stronger and he can get
separation because of his strength. Briz will do a very good job
for us when he fills in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Bledsoe and the Patriots must rediscover the middle
of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Ben Coates.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt now a coach or two must have gotten the ear of
the officials and told them to watch Coates. The Patriots tight end
has made his living catching the ball as he's being pushed and
shoved _ while also using his strength to get free. Now in search
of that freedom, he's being tagged by the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a frustrating thing because Ben gets mugged all over the
field,'' said Bledsoe. ``On one play early in the (Miami) game,
(linebacker Zach Thomas) just grabbed him and prevented him from
making a play, and that doesn't get called. And then Ben gets
called for one that looked less severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes what happens is when Ben is getting held, he'll talk
to the refs about it and then they'll start watching. And all of
sudden they'll see him do something and it works against him. Ben,
all (of) his career, has been good at getting free and he has to
continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe is calling Sunday's game ``critical'' for both teams.
The Patriots (4-2) have an 11-game losing streak against the
Broncos dating back to Sept. 29, 1980, when the Patriots beat the
visiting Broncos, 23-14, when the stadium was called Schaefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our work cut out for us,'' said Bledsoe. ``When we got
through the first four weeks, we hoped Denver would continue to
lose and it looked like they were a terrible team. That's not the
case now. Over the past two weeks they've looked like a very good
football team. I don't think anyone expected it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Broncos (2-4) making changes at quarterback (Brian
Griese instead of John Elway), running back (Olandis Gary instead
of the injured Terrell Davis), and tight end (Dwyane Carswell and
Byron Chamberlain for the injured Shannon Sharpe), Bledsoe thinks
Denver looks the same on defense. Broncos defensive coordinator
Greg Robinson and Patriots coach Pete Carroll are friends and share
the same defensive philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand what they're trying to do against us,'' said
Bledsoe. ``We can do some things scheme-wise. It's important to
establish the running game, balance in the offense. We're playing a
team that, if they had continued to lose, they'd be 0-6 right now
and pretty much out of it. But if they win three or four in a row,
they're right back in the race. We've lost two straight, so this
becomes a pivotal game for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   He has tried to forget the Miami loss, but in retrospect, ``It
was very frustrating for me because our defense shouldn't have been
put in that position,'' he said. ``But you have to have the ability
to put it behind you. Nobody wins during the week. If you're going
to be ultimately successful, you have to move on and make it right.
Football is unique in that you have to wait a week to make things
right.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not unique in that those who throw the ball for a living
can be off from time to time. This week, Bledsoe is out to show
he's back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
