<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-SIDE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole's hometown has a tip for Bush
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALISBURY, N.C. _ Retired textile worker Colene Williams likes
the sound of ``Vice President Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If she could not make it as president, I think she would make
a great vice president,'' Williams said of Elizabeth Dole, a
Salisbury native who had hoped to be the first woman elected to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's announcement Wednesday that she is dropping her
Republican campaign got people talking _ in a city where Dole and
the soft drink Cheerwine are local favorites _ about the political
future of the 63-year-old former Cabinet secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The news spread rapidly across the city of 26,792, several hours
before a screaming headline in the local afternoon paper, the
Salisbury Post, proclaimed ``Dole dropping out.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in Washington, Dole declined to comment on
speculation that she would like to be the GOP vice presidential
candidate. But in her hometown, at one of Dole's favorite breakfast
places, the Big Pig, people were hoping that GOP front-runner
George W. Bush would tap her as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush says he wants the women's vote,'' said waitress Mable
Hatfield, carrying out plates of chopped pork and reddish cole
slaw. ``He'd be stupid if he does not ask her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She would be a credit to him ...'' said Mary Penley, 72,
interrupted by friend June Curran, 76, who finished her sentence.
``... if he would listen to her,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A mile away, inside the stately English Tudor home where Dole
grew up, her brother, John Hanford, said she might wind up on the
ticket as part of the GOP's strategy late in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the 76-year-old retired businessman said, ``She will not go
out seeking the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanford learned of his sister's decision Tuesday, after Dole had
concluded that Bush, the Texas governor, and millionaire publisher
Steve Forbes had ``insurmountable'' leads in fund-raising. Dole was
particularly concerned that she couldn't compete with her rivals'
upcoming TV ads in New Hampshire and Iowa. ``That is when this
discrepancy (in funds) begins to make a huge difference in the
effectiveness of campaigning,'' Hanford said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's 98-year-old mother, Mary Hanford, eating lunch in the
kitchen, declined to comment. Her son said she was comfortable with
her daughter's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Several diners at the Big Pig said they were disappointed, but
not surprised that Dole dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she would have made a pretty good showing,'' said
retired trucker Turner Williams, drinking coffee with his wife,
Colene, in the Big Pig.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield, the waitress, said she would have supported Bush, even
if Dole had stayed in the race. ``I don't think a woman is going to
be president,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody believes she would have gone all the way, but people
thought she'd make a better showing than she did,'' said Walter
Koontz, 57, the Big Pig's owner.
</P>
<P>
   Penley was relieved to hear that Dole was dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want her to go up there and get hurt in all that
political mess,'' she said. ``She is too good a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
