<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3282 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ELDERLY-GAYS-360(2TAK     10-20 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-GAYS-360(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPERS PLAN RETIREMENT COMMUNITIES FOR GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ David Krongelb, a Fort Lauderdale businessman, came out
of the closet in his 20s and believed that the door would never
close on him again. He is 50 now, and wonders if he will need that
secret place again when he grows old.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're old,'' he said, ``the last thing that you want to
do is to have to hide.'' .
</P>
<P>
   Many gay Americans who, like Krongelb, have lived openly as
homosexuals well into middle age are now worried that they will
have to retreat into secrecy if they enter retirement communities
or nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these Americans, in particular the baby boomers who
endured years of discrimination, worry that they will be isolated
and discriminated against by elderly neighbors and health care
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the first openly gay generation grows grayer and
contemplates retirement, developers around the country are planning
gay-only retirement communities and assisted-care complexes that
would allow aging gays to grow old surrounded by other gays, where
they do not have to live, and ultimately die, amid lingering
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Lauderdale, Boston, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Atlanta
and other cities, these developers _ many of them gays themselves
who have their own fears of old age _ are promising a haven for
those who will become old and infirm, many of them without the
support of children or other family members.
</P>
<P>
   For gay men in particular, the ones who have lived into middle
age under the stigma of AIDS and amid fear and talk of shortened
lives, the idea of living too long once seemed novel. But gays
around the country say that retirement has been dinner-table
conversation for the past few years, talk that is growing more
urgent as they grow older.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always ask, `What are we going to do?'' said Jeffrey
Dillon, 37, who, along with John DeLeo, 54, is arranging financing
for a 270-unit assisted-care high rise in downtown Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   DeLeo and Dillon envison a community in which gay couples can
live together without persecution, but also one in which the
community would stave off loneliness and insulate people from the
meanness outside.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scott Schieman, an assistant professor of sociology at the
University of Miami who specializes in aging, said the planned
developments could become more than just places to grow old among
people with similar pasts and similar stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``What defines later life for gays?'' he said. ``Many of them
have not formed any kind of nest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay men in particular,'' he said, ``saw a truncated life,''
because of AIDS, and spoke more of dying young than growing old.
``They deal with a lot of loss, loss of partners, and loss of
friends.'' The survivors often find themselves with an isolation
that is complete, or almost so, when they finally enter retirement
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you have a new form of self-segregation,'' he said of
the gays-only retirement developments. But it is one that many gays
say they would find much more preferable to fighting old battles _
or hiding _ amid a colony of elderly strangers.
</P>
<P>
   They have seen it happen to people like 76-year-old like Evelyn
Kinser, who lives in a Los Angeles retirement home.
</P>
<P>
   To her, it is like being a girl again, made to feel ashamed
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sad world to live in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For her generation, the solution had always been secrecy. ``They
go back into the closet,'' said Krongelb, ``and play bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kinser came out when she was 12, a pioneer of sorts. Like
Krongelb, she thought she was out for good. But now, living in a
senior citizens home in Los Angeles operated by the Salvation Army,
she hides her sexual orientation out of fear she will be ridiculed
or isolated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hard way to live, having to be someone you're not,''
she said. ``I don't talk to my neighbors about much of anything.
Except sports. That's a safe topic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kinser has never told her neighbors at the home that she is
gay. But she knows that they know she is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen that look in their eye,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even friends who give her that look are better than no friends.
So, she remains quiet. But she is tired of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm closeted again,'' she said. ``I hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of special housing for elderly gays cite a number of
incidents as evidence of a need for it. In 1996, a lesbian couple
who had shared a home for years were forbidden to stay together in
an assisted-living center in Northern California, said Doni
Gewirtzman of the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, the gay
rights group.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, in Virginia, an elderly woman was refused
personal care in a nursing home because the staff claimed that she
had engaged in ``inappropriate sexual behavior.'' The staff there
claimed that she made sexual advances towards them, Gewirtzman
said.
</P>
<P>
   And some years back, a nursing home employee refused to give a
resident a bath after learning she was a lesbian, according to the
New York chapter of Senior Action in a Gay Environment. ``It's very
daunting, especially for those people who have been out a long
time,'' said Sandy Warshaw, director of policy education and
community outreach for that organization.
</P>
<P>
   Max Weatherly, 78, lives in public housing in Delray Beach,
Fla., amid neighbors who are not unkind to him, but with whom he
has little in common. To him, a self-contained, gays-only
retirement home would be a utopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like my grandfather told me I would turn out to be no
good,'' he said. ``I would play the piano and read books, but they
thought I was a sissy because I couldn't get on a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He would like to spend his last years among people who would nod
their heads in understanding when they hear that story.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for a gay person to walk the corridors in a
nursing home or an assisted-living center and find themselves, even
among so many people, completely alone, said Veronica St. Claire,
chief executive of the Gay and Lesbian Association of Retiring
Persons, in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   She knows one man, a retired teacher who developed Parkinson's
disease, who went to live in an assisted-care home and found that
he was the only gay man there. ``He can't have his books out, or
his magazines. He felt his care would be compromised if they
knew,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But while gays his age see it almost as a dream, gays of a
younger generation _ the baby boomers _ will demand that kind of
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the first to come forward,'' as a generation with an
openly gay life style, said Stephen Golant, a gerontologist at the
University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   And those who helped create thriving gay communities in American
cities will insist on living that way, if at a somewhat slower
pace, in retirement, said developers in Boston, Fort Lauderdale and
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a healthy phenomenon,'' said Golant, who sees plans for
the developments as proof that a generation of gays have the social
and economic power to carry it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're willing to define themselves as old and gay. These are
big self-identity issues. They're saying, `We're not afraid of who
we are. I'm proud of who I am, and I'm going to stand by it,''' to
the grave.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of creating communities specifically for gay people is
really not new, said Dillon. It is just the first time the concept
has been applied with older gays in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we don't have big families, we tend to think of our
friends as family, and our neighbors become our friends,'' said
Dillon. ``So they become like our family. This way, we're
surrounded by family.''
</P>
<P>
   Developers have said would not undertake such projects if they
did not think they could sell them.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, a project called the Stonewall Communities _ named
after a gay bar in New York's Greenwich Village where a 1969 clash
with police is credited with beginning the modern gay rights
movement _ is planning a retirement community in or near that
city's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Gay and Lesbian Association of Retiring Persons
in Los Angeles is in the process of financing and designing a
retirement community on 19 acres near Palm Springs that, like the
high-rise in Fort Lauderdale, will offer both assisted living and
nursing care. Another feature: vistas of the Santa Rosa Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   She believes there will be more such communities, as gays and
lesbians insist on the same freedom in old age they won over time.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, the project is past the planning stage, and awaiting
financing. If the financing continues on schedule _ DeLeo said he
does not expect any problem _ then construction on that project,
estimated to cost between $40 million and $60 million, would begin
within the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Living there would not be cheap. Residents would pay $235,000 or
more for one- and two-bedroom apartments, and a monthly fee of
$2,000 to $4,000, depending, DeLeo and Dillon said, on how much
care the resident needs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a nursing staff and in-house health care, the high-rise
would have its own theater, where independent films could debut,
its own art gallery, a market with specialty foods and restaurants.
The developers say it would be the first of many, and plan other
high-rises in Atlanta, San Francisco, Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The developers picked Fort Lauderdale, they said, because it has
a history as a gay-friendly city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will support it, some people will oppose it,''
said Mayor Jim Knaugle. ``I think it could be a successful
project.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Latona, a Fort Lauderdale city commissioner, said he doubts
if the construction of the facility would become an issue. ``We
have a substantial gay community that is well received,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But would not the construction of such a place be a form of
unlawful exclusion? The developers say not, that _ while it is
designed with gays in mind _ it would be open to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that any straight people who want to live in a
place intended mostly for gay people would not be the kind of
people who would be hurtful. They would just be neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be homophobes out there,'' said Krongelb.
``But we've come too far to suffer like that again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
