<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORRIS IS GIVEN LITTLE CHANCE   IN BOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The father's nickname is ``Shot.'' Most people think
his son should be called ``No Shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what the majority of fight fans and Las Vegas wise guys
think of Orlin Norris Jr.'s chances of surviving a business meeting
with Mike Tyson Saturday night at the MGM Grand Garden Arena. Shot?
No shot.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a reflection on Tyson, who did not look good in his
January knockout of Frans Botha. Tyson lost every round up until he
landed a bomb on Botha's face that rendered the need for additional
rounds unnecessary. Botha folded up like a beach umbrella late in
the fifth, his mind suddenly put on hold for about 30 seconds while
his body quivered on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tyson has knocked down sparring partners each of the
last two days at the Golden Gloves Gym and looks fit and trim at an
estimated 220 pounds, the prevailing opinion is that, at 33, he is
on the dark side of the fistic mountain. Although he retains his
legendary punching power, much of Tyson's speed and reflexes have
deserted him because of age and inactivity, leaving him appearing
more like just another small heavyweight rather than the small
nuclear bomb he once was.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few see that as helpful to poor Norris, who is no spring
chicken himself at 34, and stubbier than even Tyson. Although
Norris will weigh in Thursday at around 212 pounds, he is a
cruiserweight by breeding and class, having once held the WBA
version of the junior heavyweight title (1993-1995).
</P>
<P>
   After losing the championship to a losing battle of the bulge
and a losing battle with someone named Nate ``Mr.'' Miller, Norris
returned from whence he'd first come and decided to campaign as a
full-fledged heavyweight. He has won seven times in eight fights
since. His only loss a 12-round decision to 6-foot-7-inch Henry
Akinwande on a night when it looked like Akinwande had chosen his
opponent from the jockey room at Aqueduct. The 5-9 1/2 Norris
struggled to get close enough to reach him with a local call.
</P>
<P>
   Norris (50-5, 27 KO) failed at that but pressed on, fighting
occasionally until Tyson's people called this summer looking for
just what he appeared to be: an aging, short heavyweight with
minimal punching power, but the boxing ability to give Tyson some
much needed rounds without posing a threat.
</P>
<P>
   With that call came a check for $800,000, money Norris sorely
needed to help pay his father's mounting medical bills. After
watching Shot fight leukemia to a standoff after looking like he
might not make it through the summer, No Shot now looks at Tyson as
far less formidable than most of the observers who won't be in the
ring with him Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   If his father could win his fight, why can't he win his?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had anything easy come to me,'' Norris said. ``This
will be no exception. But I plan to be there. I know he's going to
hit me and I'm going to hit him. My job is to not get hit with that
big shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds of Shot getting to see No Shot avoid being hit by a big
shot long enough to win Saturday night are 12-1 on the Strip.
</P>
<P>
   That's not good if you're a gambling man, and worse if you're a
fighter. But that's the way it is for Norris this morning, and
he'll take it because Wednesday his father was at his side against
longer odds, walking a bit slower than when he used to work his
son's corner, but still walking tall. Walking the same walk his son
will walk Saturday night. A long walk against long odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very relaxed,'' the son said as the father looked on.
``That's my personality. At this point of my career, I still have
speed and the ability to think in the ring. People expect me to box
him and take him into the later rounds, and that is what I'll do.
That's the way I fight. The longer the fight goes, the larger the
advantage for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been an underdog so this is nothing new. I like
being an underdog. I like doing something no one expects to have
happen. The media all say I'm the first rung on Tyson's ladder to
the top. If I am, it won't be an easy step. I'm one tough old
chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson can vouch for that because when they were both spring
chickens, he lost an amateur fight to Norris on a decision down in
Texas. That was 18 years ago and neither can remember much about
the fight beyond its outcome. Neither thinks it will make a
difference Saturday night except it tells Norris something. It
tells him that long odds aren't the same as no shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlin did it once so he knows he can do it again,'' said Abel
Sanchez, his lead trainer. ``It was the same kind of fight. Power
puncher against a boxer and the boxer won. Mike Tyson gets
frustrated when you box him. Orlin knows that. He knows he can beat
this man again.''
</P>
<P>
   If he can, he knows something else, too. He knows what he'll
become if he does. He'll become a big shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize what a fight like this can do for my career,''
Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   If it does more than just pay his father's medical bills, it'll
be a miracle. But Orlin Norris has already seen one of those this
summer, so he understands what the world does not. He understands
all things are possible for a guy called Shot. And maybe even for
one called No Shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
