<HEADLINE>
SNIPING OVER BUDGET RESUMES IN CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a conciliatory meeting at the White House on
Tuesday night, Republicans and Democrats in Congress reverted to
form Wednesday, sniping at each other over the budget and attending
more to political positioning than to bridging their differences.
</P>
<P>
   First thing Wednesday morning, the House Republican leaders
brought up a bill to finance programs of the Departments of
Commerce, Justice and State and pushed it through on a near
party-line vote in the full knowledge that President Clinton would
veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the majority whip, called a news
conference with several other Republicans and accused the president
of wanting to raise taxes and spend money reserved for Social
Security on other programs, like foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress said Republicans were negotiating in bad
faith. Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the minority leader, accused
Republicans of ``duplicity when it comes to the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep.Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader, said in an
interview that the Republicans had agreed at the White House
meeting on Tuesday to consider all the spending bills at once but
were already reneging and taking them up one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bad disagreement on process,'' Gephardt said. ``The
result is that we're going to be here till the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans acknowledged that the president requested
consideration of all the controversies together, but they said they
had never agreed to that procedure.
</P>
<P>
   In other budget battles over the years, Clinton has found it
advantageous to deal with one omnibus bill rather than many
separate ones, a point on which the Republicans do not need to be
reminded.
</P>
<P>
   After the White House meeting, both sides promised to work
together over the next week or so to resolve their budget
differences.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, Jack Lew, the president's budget director, went
to the Capitol on Wednesday afternoon and met for about an hour
with the senior members of the Congressional Appropriations
Committees. No specifics were discussed, the participants said, and
no disagreements were settled.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David R. Obey of Wisconsin, the top Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee, said after the meeting that progress was
impossible without House Republican leaders participating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem lies above our pay grade,'' Obey said. ``We are
light colonels, not four-star generals.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Appropriations Committee chairman, Rep. C.W. Bill Young,
R-Fla., said that the meeting with Lew had ``opened a lot of
doors'' and that another meeting to deal with specific budget
issues might be held on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill for the Commerce, Justice and State
Departments was approved, 215-213, after Republican leaders twisted
arms at the last minute to assure a majority. Only 13 Democrats
voted for the measure; 17 Republicans and one Independent voted
against it.
</P>
<P>
   The president opposes the bill because it allocates only $325
million of the $1.3 billion he requested for his program to put
more police officers on the streets. He also objects to provisions
that freeze financing for the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission and make it unlikely that money will be available for
the United States to pay its debt to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The president Wednesday did sign a $99 billion bill for
veterans, housing and space programs. He called this bill a product
of bipartisan cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted Wednesday that they would be able to clear
all the spending bills without dipping into Social Security
reserves. DeLay said that when all the spending bills had been
completed, the Congressional Budget Office would be asked to
certify that no Social Security money had been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't, then we'll go back and cut spending until they
do,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans actually drafting the spending bills said DeLay
and the other leaders had still not decided where they would trim
to meet their spending goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
