<HEADER>
A3290 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-AUTHOR-FALUDI-SPI &LR;      10-20 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-FALUDI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSAN FALUDI ON MEN'S ANGER AND CRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why American men are so angry was the question that originally
confounded feminist Susan Faludi.
</P>
<P>
   So this is where the Pulitzer Prize-winning writer went for
answers: to Promise Keepers and the Spur Posse, to aerospace and
shipyard workers laid off during downsizing, to a group of men
convicted of domestic violence, to Vietnam vets and the original
astronauts, to the ``Dawg Pound'' bleacher fans of the Cleveland
Browns, to L.A. gang bangers and military cadets at the Citadel and
also to Sylvester Stallone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested in men who are facing crisis today,'' Faludi
said in an interview, ``men who are angry and have been lashing
out, often at false enemies. I was not interested in doing a Gallup
Poll on men today. I wanted to understand the dynamics of men with
real anger and frustration. And I believe that is a significant
number of American men, who demanded an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Faludi's investigation, almost seven years in duration, has now
yielded ``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the American Man'' (William
Morrow, 608 pages, $27.50). This is a tour de force of personal
reportage, brilliantly written, immensely compelling, filled with
fascinating stories and insights worthy of thorough study, but also
a book that is way too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel an obligation to write longer when you have been
generously supported,'' related Faludi, who received a reported
$1.5 million advance for the book and last week received a
``mid-six-figure'' sum from Home Box Office, which plans a
television adaptation. ``I wish `Stiffed' was shorter; no doubt,
there would be more readers. But I also felt a responsibility to
the men I interviewed to tell their stories in a longer form.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stiffed'' is, without question, one of this fall's most
important books. But it is also a big book that is having
considerable trouble finding an early audience, despite massive
coverage in the media (the cover of Newsweek, covers of most major
book reviews, a 17-city cross-country tour by the author).
</P>
<P>
   Male readers seem in no hurry to weigh into a massive book about
their plight written by one of the country's leading feminists.
Female readers, who buy far more books than men, seem put off by
the notion of a feminist spending 600 pages to detail just how
rough men have it today. ``Stiffed'' has yet to crack the major
best-seller lists, and is languishing well below the ``Hot 100''
books at Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a tired and frustrated Faludi who flew into Seattle
for another dizzying round of media interviews and a packed reading
at The Elliott Bay Book Co.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the 40-year-old writer's dismay comes from the number of
interviewers asking her questions based on a press kit instead of
her book. Part of it comes from suggestions that ``Stiffed'' is not
selling as well as might be expected (``I didn't write this book to
compete with `Titanic,''' she countered. ``It's only been out three
weeks, but everything these days has to be an overnight
sensation!''). But nothing unsettles Faludi quite like hearing that
some female readers, especially fellow feminists, have no interest
whatsoever in reading about the travails of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that shocking,'' Faludi said. ``It just shows that
women can be as heartless as men. It is really depressing to me to
hear women boo-hooing about what more do they need to know about
men and their problems, as if they're competing to be on some
higher level of oppression. ... I would think people would want to
read this book to better figure out the world. And women, for all
the energy they spend berating men, talking about men, obsessing
about men, could spend five minutes looking at things from the
man's point of view. It wouldn't kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stiffed'' looks at things from the male point-of-view in
exhaustive detail, mostly through in-depth and empathetic profiles
of the men whom Faludi interviewed. This technique of chronicling
social history through individual stories is quite similar to that
used, to great effect, by fellow journalist David Halberstam.
</P>
<P>
   Faludi, a summa cum laude graduate of Harvard, is a far more
adroit writer than Halberstam, turning memorable phrases on many
pages (``the astronaut was a dependent strapped to a couch in a
fetal position, wrapped in swaddling clothes''). But Faludi is also
a master interviewer, a thin rail of a person who obviously uses
her shy, unadorned manner to best advantage, the sort of intently
interested questioner who hangs around a subject and then hangs
around more and more and more until finally the subject is
thoroughly disarmed and willing to tell her anything and
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very frank with you,'' a displaced McDonnell Douglas
worker tells Faludi in a slow manner which she describes as
``placing every word down as if each were an increasingly heavy
weight.'' Then he concludes: ``I. Feel. I've. Been. Castrated.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a recurrent complaint of the men in crisis. So, too, is
a sense of being cast adrift in a consumer-driven,
celebrity-obsessed culture where the old ``male'' virtues (doing
productive work, loyalty, sacrifice, fellowship) no longer matter.
So, too, is the sense, especially among baby boomer men, of being
abandoned by their fathers or at least being left clueless by
silent fathers about ``how to be a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An aching sadness remained,'' Faludi writes. ``Men spoke to me
of waiting, year after year, for a sign, a late-night confidence, a
death-bed confession, even _ desperately _ a letter delivered
posthumously, for any moment that would decode the mystery of their
mute fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   This complaint about absent or silent fathers fueled much of the
``men's movement'' and its literature in the last decade. But it
seems to acquire more gravity somehow when it is recounted
sympathetically not by Robert Bly or Sam Keen but by a feminist
icon, the celebrated author of ``Backlash: The Undeclared War
Against Women,'' a well-timed, well-argued polemic that was a best
seller in 1992 and has gone on to become an important work in the
feminist canon.
</P>
<P>
   Faludi's criticism of the generation of men who won World War II
and then somehow let their sons down is among the most pointed in
the book (although she tends to let that complaint stand
unchallenged either by historical research or by a response from
men in the criticized generation). But, in person, Faludi is far
less critical of the World War II fathers, contending that both the
fathers and their sons fell victim to sweeping cultural forces that
overwhelmed them, especially the rapid onrush of the consumerist
mentality (Faludi's prime villain).
</P>
<P>
   These cultural forces are the main reason why many men feel
emasculated and angry, Faludi discovered. Men are not lashing out,
as she initially suspected, because of ``masculinity on the
rampage'' or even because they feel threatened by the gains made by
women, although feminists themselves are a frequent target of male
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Faludi concludes ``Stiffed'' with a brief note of optimism that
``men and women are at a historically opportune moment when they
hold the keys to each other's liberation.'' But that closing
optimism, which does not seem all that justified by what has been
detailed in the 600 pages that have preceded it, does depend on
both men and women recognizing that their real enemy is not one
another but rather the culture that enslaves them both.
</P>
<P>
   Faludi, in person, has some hope of that happening, but not
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there comes a point when people can't bear the
soullessness, the deadened quality of being in a culture that does
not nurture human creativity,'' she stressed. ``One hopes that
enough people will have had it with the dehumanizing aspects of
this culture to rebel against it. But we're in new territory here,
when the seductive consumer culture seems both benign and
consoling. It is not a situation where it's like we're sending
children to work in the mines and everyone knows that is wrong. So
what it will take to overcome this culture, I just don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
