<SLUG> BC-DOLE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTERS SADDENED BY DOLE'S WITHDRAWAL
</HEADLINE>
   (See also DOLE-WITHDRAWS, DOLE-ASSESS) 
(sw) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wherever she spoke, Elizabeth Dole unfailingly
brought up the trailblazing nature of her candidacy. She often
managed to get introduced by a woman in authority, and would quip,
``Hmm. A female president . . . Sounds good to me.'' Banners, signs
and even the chocolate mousse cake at a recent luncheon for her
urged, ``Let's Make History.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Mrs. Dole gave up on making history. She
blamed not her gender, but the quirk of political fate that pitted
her against George W. Bush, who had amassed a war chest of some $60
million, and Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher with a
seemingly bottomless personal fortune to finance his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's exit from the race saddened many, including those
who disagreed with her position on specific issues but who were
pleased to see a woman slug it out for the nation's top job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My disappointment is acute that she is not in there,'' said
Geraldine Ferraro, the first woman to run for vice president, in
1984. ``I would have liked to have seen her participate in the
primaries. She would have added to the dialogue in that party.''
</P>
<P>
   But in fact Mrs. Dole did not alter her message to appeal
strictly to women. Mrs. Dole, a conservative Republican, traced a
fine line on her road to the presidency: If she tried to build on
the unique nature of her campaign by embracing traditional
``women's causes,'' she risked feeding into stereotypes and
alienating men who might otherwise vote for her.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mrs. Dole took on many of the same issues her rivals
raised, like education and defense, calling for greater local
control of schools and a nuclear arms buildup. She called for
pouring more money into drug interdiction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, her longtime opposition to abortion except in dire
circumstances lost her the support of liberal-minded women, who
might have been considered her natural constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of her gender she didn't have a cause behind her,''
said Tanya Melich, a political consultant and author of the 1996
book, ``The Republican War Against Women (Bantam).'' ``She was a
traditionalist running a non-traditionalist campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after her announcement, Mrs. Dole said she
did not think her decision to drop out would discourage other women
from entering politics. ``What we've done is paved the way for the
person who will be the first woman president,'' she said, adding
that she was ``delighted,'' because ``we've really made a great
contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Mrs. Dole's candidacy did break new ground was in its
success attracting women and young people who had never before
taken part in the electoral process. More than 50 percent of Mrs.
Dole's big supporters were women, more than twice the number who
usually contribute more than $200 to political campaigns. Through
the Internet and personal and professional connections, she had
signed on thousands of volunteers, many of them young people and
women.
</P>
<P>
   Polls, however, did not show Mrs. Dole's support running
stronger among women than men. Kate Michelman, president of the
National Association for Reproductive Rights League, said, ``Many
women were understandably excited about a woman running for
president, but I think her candidacy failed to excite most people,
women as well, because she didn't connect on the issues of greatest
concern to women.'' Mrs. Michelman's group opposed all Republican
candidates because of their stand against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   A good number of the political greenhorns Mrs. Dole attracted to
politics were drawn by her charm and character, rather than her
position on issues. It is unclear whether these supporters will
translate into a political force with her campaign now over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with people who don't have an intrinsic
interest in the process, said Norman Orenstein, of the American
Enterprise Institute, ``and whose attention span can be turned to
something else quite quickly.'' .
</P>
<P>
   Mary Mason, a 61-year-old bookkeeper who helped organize a
reception for Mrs. Dole in Richmond, Va., said she volunteered
because a friend in the campaign had asked her to. Now, she said,
she did not plan to throw her energy behind another candidate.
``I'm disappointed,'' Ms. Mason said in a telephone interview on
Wednesday. ``I think it's sad that we can't even get to the year
2000, when the campaign really gets started.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanya White, the campaign's finance chairwoman in South
Carolina, said Dole supporters had signed up 4,000 volunteers in
her state. ``That's what she brought, people who were disenchanted
or saw a way to become involved in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   She contended that Mrs. Dole did bring a woman's perspective to
her bid, focusing on what was practical and attainable, whether the
issue was handguns or drug interdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White herself was not a newcomer to politics, but had no
plans to throw her expertise behind anyone else for the moment. ``I
was trying to get uninvolved in campaigns, but I wanted to help
because I thought it was a worthy cause,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's staff and supporters contended that her favorable
ratings in opinion polls, which showed her beating Al Gore and Bill
Bradley in two-way races, proved that Americans were ready to elect
a woman president.
</P>
<P>
   Her national finance chairman, Bonnie McElveen-Hunter, said it
was timing, not sexism, that blocked the Dole campaign from winning
more money or endorsements from Republican leaders. ``This process
began three years ago,'' she said. ``I think there were commitments
that were made.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mrs. Ferraro said she had no doubt Americans were ``ready''
for a female chief of state. ``Were they ready for a wrestler in
Minnesota? Are they ready for a billionaire?'' she asked. ``This is
a country where everybody has a chance, especially women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
