<SLUG> BC-MA-DOT-COM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE IS DUBBED `DOT-COMMONWEALTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Portraying the Bay State as a world center of computing
technology, Gov. Paul Cellucci and dozens of the state's top
high-tech business leaders Wednesday awarded Massachusetts another
nickname _ the ``.commonwealth.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a dot there before the word ``commonwealth,'' as in an
e-mail address, and pronounced the same way _ dot-commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   State officials and business leaders said they intend to exploit
the new nickname to promote Massachusetts for further high-tech
business investment and employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `dot-commonwealth' campaign will help us educate
businesses and employees about the strength of the Massachusetts
economy and what sets us apart from other high-tech states,''
Cellucci said at a news conference at the Museum of Science.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, said Joyce Plotkin, executive director of the
Massachusetts Software Council, the new name is cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not believe the positive feedback we have gotten
about that name,'' Plotkin said. ``It makes Silicon Valley sound
old.''
</P>
<P>
   A little East Coast hipness might make it easier to attract new
technology businesses and trained workers to the state. With a
nationwide shortage of high-tech workers, industry leaders say
Massachusetts needs a program that will attract competent employees
from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need constant acess to intellectual property to help our
company grow,'' said Jon Radoff, chairman and chief technology
officer of Eprise Corp., a Framingham-based maker of Web server
software. ``The only way to do that is to get people to come to the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   So the ``.commonwealth'' initiative will feature national
advertising, such as an insert in the Nov. 22 issue of Business
Week magazine. The group has established a Web site
(http://www.the.commonwealthmass.com) to tout the advantages of
setting up technology businesses in Massachusetts. And local tech
firms will begin adding the new ``.commonwealth'' logo to their ads
and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Economic Development will provide some
funding to the initiative through an existing $50,000 fund used to
bring new businesses to Massachusetts. But most of the money will
come from 100 local technology companies and several of the state's
top technology trade associations. Plotkin would not disclose the
exact amount budgeted for the campaign, but said it was in the
six-figure range.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the member companies in the ``.commonwealth'' campaign
are relatively small startup firms, the sort that dominate today's
Massachusetts tech economy. But Cellucci doesn't think this puts
the state at much of a disadvantage in the struggle for high-tech
hearts and minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the global headquarters like we used to have.
But in a global economy, that's not so important,'' Cellucci said.
``But I'll tell you what _ Harvard isn't going to go away; MIT is
not going to go away; Boston College is not going to go away.''
Cellucci said the state's reputation for academic excellence would
be one of the chief selling points in the ``.commonwealth''
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci asserted that one nickname that no longer applies to
the state is ``Taxachusetts,'' and touted his administration's
policy of cutting taxes on Massachusetts businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He also called for a permanent, worldwide ban on all taxation of
economic activity on the Internet. With more than 60,000 taxing
authorities worldwide, he said, it is utterly impractical to levy
sales taxes on Internet transactions. ``It seems to me it's crazy
to try to sort that out,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
