<HEADER>
A3296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DOLE-QUITS21-COX     10-20 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-QUITS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole quits for lack of cash
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth Dole ended her run for the White House,
short of the cash she said she needed to become the nation's first
woman president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line remains funding,'' Dole said at a news
conference Wednesday with her husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, at her
side.
</P>
<P>
   She is the fifth candidate to exit the Republican field this
year. A sixth, Pat Buchanan, is expected to switch to the Reform
Party next week.
</P>
<P>
   Dole brushed off questions about her interest in the vice
presidency. But she did say, ``I'm a long way from the twilight.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she reached the decision to leave the race on a flight
Sunday from Seattle to Washington, D.C., after reflecting on the
massive spending by two of her Republican rivals: Texas Gov. George
W. Bush and magazine publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two people have spent $19 million already'' before costly
television advertising campaigns have even begun, Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was a distant second to Bush in most polls, although Sen.
John McCain (R-Ariz.) passed her recently in New Hampshire. She
said although she was used to facing long odds in the
male-dominated worlds of law and government, she could not ask her
supporters to persist while she was being outspent 75 or 80 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole's tepid fund-raising _ she raised $1 million to Bush's
$20 million in the past three months, for example _ was symptomatic
of other problems in the campaign, said Larry Sabato, a University
of Virginia political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she said was true, but as with all politicians, it was
only a part of the story,'' Sabato said. ``She ran a terrible
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on her brief campaign, Dole said she might have
been better off leaving the presidency of the American Red Cross
earlier than January to begin countering Bush's quiet attempts to
line up financial commitments from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Dole seemed to be in an enviable position to raise money as the
former Red Cross chief executive, a former Cabinet secretary and
the wife of a former Republican nominee for president and vice
president who maintains a formidable network of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   She and Bush were neck and neck in polls early this year, before
either really started campaigning. No woman had ever had such
standing in a national presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's inability to capitalize on her advantages puzzled
political analysts and frustrated her staff. An example: She
finished a surprisingly strong third in the Iowa straw poll in
August, then took a 10-day vacation instead of building on her
showing. Her two main spokesmen left the campaign shortly
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   There was an undeniable excitement in the large crowds that
turned out for Dole events. Among those she attracted were people
who hadn't voted before or who hadn't considered voting for a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Her speeches sometimes rambled, but she roused audiences by
talking about the prospect of her becoming the first woman
president.
</P>
<P>
   Dole altered her pitch somewhat Wednesday. ``I think what we've
done is pave the way for the person who will be the first woman
president,'' she said, as supporters cheered in a crowded room in a
Washington, D.C., hotel. Many in the room, including her husband,
struggled to fight back tears.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's national finance team, in a morning conference call,
tried to dissuade her from quitting, said Margaret Kluttz, a
longtime friend and former mayor of Salisbury, N.C., Dole's
hometown. ``But she had reached her decision,'' Kluttz said.
</P>
<P>
   Her pollster, Linda DiVall, said Dole should be seriously
considered as a vice presidential candidate because she would help
keep women from deserting the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Praise flowed Wednesday from Bush and McCain, the two candidates
who might benefit from her withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called her a ``trailblazer.'' McCain, stressing campaign
finance reform in his own campaign, lamented that money had forced
Dole from the race.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia GOP Chairman Charles ``Chuck'' Clay said he expects Bush
to pick up the bulk of Dole's support in the state, mainly because
McCain has made little effort in Georgia. Already, Atlanta lawyer
Oscar Persons, a leader of the Dole campaign in Georgia, said he
has offered his services to Bush. Of the three leading Republicans
in the race, Forbes probably will attract relatively few Dole
supporters, if for no other reason than his barrage of television
ads against Bob Dole in the 1996 Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans had 12 candidates for president at one point
this year. If Buchanan joins the Reform Party as expected, the GOP
field will consist of: Gary Bauer, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, Alan
Keyes, Bush, Forbes and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have dropped out are: Lamar Alexander, Dan Quayle, New
Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, Ohio Rep. John Kasich and Dole. Smith is
now an independent, mulling whether to continue his campaign for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
