<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-BO     10-20 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSLIM CLERIC PICKED AS PRESIDENT, INCITING PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A respected but sickly Muslim cleric
snatched Indonesia's presidency Wednesday from the people's
favorite, the daughter of the country's founder, setting off a wave
of deadly protests by her frustrated followers.
</P>
<P>
   Abdurrahman Wahid, 59, the moderate leader of the largest Muslim
organization in the world's largest Muslim country, was not even a
candidate until a coalition of Islamic parties this month urged him
to abandon his longstanding support for presidential frontrunner
Megawati Sukarnoputri. He cited her party's alleged use of ``money
politics'' when he jumped in, but critics saw it as an ego trip and
few took his candidacy seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of a cleric over Megawati, a populist, secular
nationalist, highlighted the rising power of Islam in this
historically secular nation. The violence sparked by Wahid's
surprise victory also raised the spectre of an eruption of
fraticidal conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Two people were reported killed and at least two dozen injured
here in the capital Wednesday as three bombs exploded in the
streets and melees broke out among protesters. Mobs set fire to the
Jakarta Convention Center and a highway toll booth, churning black
funnels of smoke into the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's bid was bolstered when incumbent President B.J. Habibie
withdrew from the race at the last minute Wednesday after the
national assembly dramatically rejected his accounting of his 17
months in office. After a flurry of attempts to nominate
alternatives, many ruling party members and more radical Muslim
groups apparently threw their votes behind Wahid rather than cede
them to longtime opposition figure and secularist Megawati.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, who within hours was sworn in as the first president ever
elected in a contested race in Indonesia, will shape the future of
Asia's newest, and still fragile, democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid will face a host of challenges, including Indonesia's
worst economic crisis in three decades and a persistent wave of
religious and separatist violence that has claimed thousands of
lives this year across a diverse chain of islands that are home to
210 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers immediately questioned whether the frail and
legally blind leader, who had to be physically aided to cast his
vote, read his inaugural address and sign his oath of office
Wednesday, is up the far more difficult tasks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati, once a close friend of Wahid's who considered him her
``teacher,'' walked to his seat in parliament and stood behind him,
holding his hand high in the sign of victory after his win was
announced. But as he and others sang the national anthem, she held
back tears, bit her lip and remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   In a bow to her father Sukarno's legacy and Megawati's own
contribution to the transition from the autocratic rule of former
President Suharto, Wahid praised ``our second independence since
founding president Sukarno planted the flag upon our soil. I have
great respect for Madam Megawati. She must be respected for her
role in all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Megawati conceded victory to ``my dear friend'' and urged
loyalists to accept the result ``for the unity of our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Megawati's bid failed in part because conservative Muslims
didn't want a woman president. She also became arrogant after her
June parliamentary win, critics say, refusing to lobby the assembly
and make deals with other parties _ one reason for her fallout with
one-time coalition partner Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's election was cheered by many observant Muslims who have
felt sidelined in a country where they are the overwhelming
majority. They see Wahid's ascension as gaining unprecedented
influence for Islam in a diverse nation where ethnic Chinese and
Christians have held disproportionate power in economic, military
and political spheres.
</P>
<P>
   But others _ especially rank-and-file supporters of the woman
whose party won the largest number of popular votes in
parliamentary elections four months ago _ felt cheated. They called
the final result a mockery of the will of voters who favored a
pluralist nationalist leader.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati's party won 34 percent of the popular vote for
parliament in June, finishing first. Wahid's party finished third
with 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Street protests that followed Wahid's 373-to-313 victory _ which
surprised even many in parliament, where Megawati led in the early
vote count _ drew well over 10,000 people outside parliament alone.
</P>
<P>
   At the city's main traffic circle where Megawati loyalists had
camped out for days preparing to celebrate, her supporters seemed
stunned as a live television broadcast announced Wahid's name. A
few cried, others staggered around in a daze, and some _ in
apparent confusion _ jumped into the fountain where they had
planned to celebrate when victory seemed so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Megawati supporters then walked to a major
intersection where she and Wahid had promised to address the
people, but when the leaders were unable to arrive, angry youths
began occupying office buildings, setting fires and viciously
beating a few bystanders. Outside parliament, an apparent car bomb
exploded around 4 p.m., killing at least two people and sending
protesters and journalists scurrying at first, but failed to
disperse the crowd. In the morning, an explosive hidden in a flower
pot at the main traffic circle injured four Megawati supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, thousands of Megawati supporters trudged home
disconsolately, but several hundred continued to hurl stones,
sticks and firebombs at riot police and soldiers, who responded
with tear gas and, finally, shots. It was not clear if the bullets
were live or rubber.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you care about Megawati, go home!'' a party organizer
vainly implored the protesters over a megaphone. ``The party does
not condone violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very disappointed, because we paid such a high price for
these elections,'' said Rosita Sitohang, 36, a business owner,
holding back tears. ``This winner is not from the people, but from
the factions in parliament. . . . He just came out of the blue to
be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Wahid's ill health, Thursday's selection of a vice
president takes on greater significance. Wahid on Monday named the
ruling Golkar party's chairman, Akbar Tandjung, as his preferred
vice president. The ruling party Wednesday named the armed forces
chief, General Wiranto, as its No. 2 choice. But Wahid might have
to offer the slot to Megawati to appease the masses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
