<HEADER>
A3302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-20 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISRAEL: NETANYAHU GIFTS SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   In a search at the former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
home and office, police officers found and seized what they said
were dozens of expensive gifts, including gold and silver objects,
that he should not have kept after leaving office. Netanyahu's
attorneys said that the items came from boxes that had not yet been
unpacked or sorted.
</P>
<P>
   WEST BANK: SETTLERS DIG IN
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of religious settlers showed up to dedicate a makeshift
synagogue at one of the illegal outposts destined to be torn down.
Havat Maon is the one outpost that contains a militant population
and authorities are most concerned about a confrontation with its
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: 4 FACE DEATH
</P>
<P>
   The threat of death sentences loomed over four students and a
professor who went on trial in Tehran accused of insulting one of
Shiite Islam's holiest figures in a campus magazine satirical
dialogue that was denounced as insulting to the 12th Imam, whose
return is awaited by pious Shiites. Judge Saeed Mortezavi noted
that the death penalty has been applied in similar cases.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: TANKS FOR TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Looking to clinch a possible $8 billion order for 1,000 Leopard
II tanks, a German federal agency agreed to deliver one of the
tanks to Turkey. The decision, approved by Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder, angered the Greens, his junior coalition partners. The
party is concerned that the tanks will be used against Turkey's
Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TALKS ADJOURN
</P>
<P>
   Intensive talks in London on the stalled peace settlement
adjourned, with final sessions in a seven-week-old rescue mission
conducted by former Sen. George Mitchell expected to continue this
weekend in Belfast. There has been no breakthrough reported in
ending the stalemate over paramilitary disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PADDINGTON UP AND RUNNING
</P>
<P>
   Trains were scheduled to resume running in and out of Paddington
Station in West London today more than three weeks after an
intercity express collided with a commuter train, killing 30
people. John Prescott, the deputy prime minister, said he would
await final studies before deciding whether to take authority over
safety away from Railtrack, a company that owns tracks, signals and
stations, which has been accused of placing profits before
standards.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: FAYED AWAITS FATE
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian-born owner of Harrods, Mohamed Fayed, 66, will
learn from the High Court on Thursday whether his four-year-old
fight for British citizenship has been successful. His lawyers
argued that Home Secretary Jack Straw had acted in a
``disproportionate, irrational and unfair'' manner in refusing him
a passport. Straw ruled him ``not of good character'' for having
made payments to members of Parliament for favors.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: HOPE FOR PINOCHET
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Abel Matutes said the Spanish government would
not appeal if Home Secretary Jack Straw of Britain decided to free
Gen. Augusto Pinochet from house arrest on humanitarian grounds. A
London court ruled that the former Chilean dictator can be
extradited to Spain on charges of human rights abuses, but
Pinochet, 83, has tried to build support for his return to Chile on
grounds of ill health.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: NEW POLICE CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   A civilian has been named to lead the understaffed, often
overmatched national police service in its battle against crime,
which has become one of the country's most serious threats to
stability and growth. Jackie Selebi, who has been the senior civil
servant in the Foreign Ministry, will become the first black to
head the force when he takes over in January for George Fivaz, who
is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: DEATH THREATS OVER VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   Reuters suspended its television operations in Cape Town this
week after its staff received death threats from anonymous callers.
The threats started this summer after it became known that the
station had videotapes of vigilantes killing a suspected drug
dealer. The vigilantes, known as People Against Gangsterism and
Drugs, have denied making the threats.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MAYORS FIRED
</P>
<P>
   Residents of two towns in Puebla state have fired their mayors
for failing to organize relief efforts after recent flooding, said
Teodoro Lozano, chairman of the Puebla legislature's human rights
committee. Warehouses in some damaged towns were full of
foodstuffs, but mayors from President Ernesto Zedillo's governing
party were refusing to distribute the supplies to any but party
members, Lozano said.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: EARLY ELECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   President Chandrika Kumaratunga called for early presidential
elections and said she would press forward with efforts to find a
constitutional solution to the deadly ethnic strife that has
plagued the country since 1983. The elections, which were scheduled
for November 2000, will take place in the next two to three months.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: U.N. AIDE QUITS
</P>
<P>
   The representative in Afghanistan of the U.N. Secretary-General,
Kofi Annan, is pulling out of an active role in peacemaking, saying
the Islamic Taliban movement and neighboring countries supplying it
or its enemies with weapons and other support are not cooperating
with United Nations efforts to find a political solution. The
envoy, Lakhdar Brahimi, said he would return only when progress had
been made.
</P>
</TEXT>
