<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE     10-20 1622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I haven't seen William F. Buckley's TV show in quite some
time. What has happened to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Buckley's PBS program ``Firing Line'' hasn't been broadcast
in some markets in recent years, which perhaps is why you haven't
seen him except when he turns up on other shows. But as of
December, ``Firing Line'' will end for good in all markets,
according to a spokesman for the program in New York. ``Firing
Line,'' which started in 1966 and has been seen on PBS since 1971,
is said to be the longest-running public affairs program on
television.
</P>
<P>
   But the show's demise doesn't mean that the
editor-author-commentator with the affected speech and dry
political wit is disappearing from the public eye. He will continue
to write and edit and make speeches, keeping his relentlessly
erudite and conservative views out front for everyone, including
many liberals who count themselves as fans.
</P>
<P>
   While he's best known for his political commentary, the
73-year-old Buckley of late has expanded to a new subject:
religion. Just last year, Doubleday published his 314-page ``Nearer
My God: An Autobiography of Faith.'' Buckley admitted that he is no
theologian, but he does have some expertise in Catholicism. He was
born into a wealthy and devout Catholic family, the sixth of 10
children.
</P>
<P>
   Q: New York Mets fans roasted Atlanta Braves fans because some
of the post-season games at Turner Field weren't sold out. How did
the teams compare in attendance at regular-season home games?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Braves were a clear winner: Braves 3,284,897; Mets,
2,725,920. A mitigating factor for Atlanta's Turner Field not being
filled for some of the games probably was because of the early
afternoon starting time mandated by TV, combined with the short
notice given to fans about the game time and the difficulty of
getting off work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are there so many fire ant hills this year? I've been
visiting my father's grave for 69 years and have never seen so many
mounds before. How do I get rid of them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fire ant mounds may go undetected in hot, dry weather, so you
just didn't notice them before, said entomologist Beverly Sparks of
the University of Georgia. But as temperatures cooled and the soil
became saturated by fall rains, the mounds became conspicuous. An
observer may not even realize that an area is infested until the
upper portions of the mounds become more developed.
</P>
<P>
   To manage fire ant populations efficiently and economically over
large areas, you need to broadcast fire ant baits over the infested
area twice a year (spring and fall). Research shows that applying
fire ant baits will reduce ant populations by more than 85 percent
within four to 12 weeks, Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a recipe in the newspaper for a cheese mold with fruit
in the middle, but I lost it. Rosalynn Carter was making it for
ex-President Carter's birthday. Can you print it again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's how to make the appetizer: Combine 16 ounces of
cheddar cheese, one cup of mayonnaise, one cup of chopped pecans,
one small grated onion, black pepper to taste, and a dash of
cayenne pepper. If you mold the mixture into a circle, spoon a jar
of strawberry preserves into the center of the ring. Chill before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that Delta and Atlantic Southeast
Airlines put Andrew Young, his wife and nephew on a flight from
Atlanta to Roanoke, Va., which then made an unscheduled stop in
Asheville, N.C., so Young could make a speaking engagement on time.
Will the passengers who were inconvenienced and delayed by that
decision be compensated?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. On Oct. 1, Young and his party were scheduled to fly
from Washington to Atlanta on a Delta flight, then from Atlanta to
Asheville on ASA. Because the Delta flight from Washington was
delayed, they missed their connecting flight. So they were put
aboard ASA Flight 4715 to Roanoke, which made an unscheduled stop
in Asheville to let Young and the others off.
</P>
<P>
   ASA spokesman Sam Watts told Q&AMP;A that the Roanoke-bound
passengers arrived at their destination only 58 minutes later than
scheduled. ``We have done two things for the passengers on 4715,''
Watts said. ``Through media reports, we have apologized publicly
for any inconvenience. In addition, we have sent letters of apology
and provided a goodwill gesture of transportation credits to those
passengers affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: We read a lot about the Mount Washington Observatory weather
station in New Hampshire, but I've never seen anything explaining
what it does. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a non-profit scientific and educational institution
created to observe and record the mountain's extreme weather
conditions, conduct research, and promote the science, history and
natural history of the White Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The first regular meteorological observations there were
conducted by the U.S. Signal Service, a precursor of the Weather
Bureau, from 1870 to 1892. Although its relationship with the
Weather Service always has been close, the observatory isn't part
of any government agency.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the facility unique is its location, on the summit of
Mount Washington at an elevation of 6,288 feet. The weather
extremes are said to be the greatest found outside the deep polar
regions, with cloud or fog at least 300 days out of the year,
annual temperatures ranging from 47 degrees below zero to 72 above,
as much as 556 inches of snow in a season, and a record wind
velocity of 231 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Online information is available at the observatory's Web site _
www.mountwashington.org/index.html _ and includes up-to-the minute
weather conditions at the station.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain the term ``Bible Belt'' as it's often used in
reference to the South?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bible Belt can be defined as an area, chiefly in the South
and Midwest, noted for its religious fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 Southern Focus poll conducted by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and the University of North Carolina confirmed
that the roots of fundamental Christianity are deep, and the
influence of Bible-based beliefs pervades the region. The poll, for
example, showed that 9 out of 10 lifelong Southerners express a
firm belief in God.
</P>
<P>
   An article about the poll quoted Dan Carter, an Emory University
professor who has studied Southern culture for years, as being
impressed by the powerful relationship between the region and
religion. He cited this statement on a bumper sticker as expressing
it concisely: ``Jesus is coming. Y'all try to look busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I find out when future shuttle launches are scheduled
from the Kennedy Space Center, say over the next six months? Is
that information published by NASA?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's as near as your telephone, but if you're planning a
Florida vacation around a launch, keep in mind that schedules are
subject to change because of weather, mechanical problems and many
other factors. The number to call for recorded information is
407-867-4636.
</P>
<P>
   These are launches currently scheduled: Discovery, Dec. 2, a
10-day mission; Endeavour, Jan. 13, 11 days; Atlantis, Feb. 10, 11
days; Discovery, liftoff ``no earlier than Feb. 24,'' 10 days;
Endeavour, March 23, 9 days; Atlantis, ``no earlier than April
20,'' 10 days; and Discovery, June 29, nine days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For your readers who want to keep clothing sparkling clean,
can you share Major League Baseball's secret for maintaining such
white uniforms? Or are they discarded after every game and new ones
worn the next game?
</P>
<P>
   A: The uniforms are kept clean and reused. The Atlanta Braves
say they use a combination of Amway products and some
pretreatments, such as Shout or Spray and Wash. After pretreatment,
stains are scrubbed and the uniforms are soaked. Then, as quickly
after a game as possible, the uniforms are washed in as hot water
as tolerable. Bleach is not used, and the uniforms are hung up to
dry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a recent item about the Bataan Death March in World War
II, Q&AMP;A mentioned a Camp O'Donnell. For whom was it named?
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. Army Center of Military History has no definitive
explanation, nor does retired Army Maj. Richard Gordon, who
represents a group of Bataan Death March survivors. But both offer
some possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   There are two schools of thought, Gordon says. One is that it
came from an American officer of that name killed in the Philippine
Insurrection. The other, said to be a Filipino story, is that the
town's original name was Odonnel, traced to a Spanish officer.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Center for Military History quotes indecisive
information from the book ``O'Donnell,'' subtitled ``Andersonville
of the Pacific.'' The author, retired Army Col. John E. Olson,
traces the earliest written record to an account of the capture of
a remote town in the Philippines named O'Donnell. There's no
explanation for the Irish name.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's book also cites a ``prevalent rumor'' in the 1960s that
the camp was named for ``an Army Air Corps hero.'' Although a Maj.
Emmett O'Donnell Jr. did command a B-17 squadron at Clark Air Base
after September 1941, the camp name was published as early as 1900,
so that connection is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is known for certain. Camp O'Donnell was the terminus
of the Bataan Death March. And as such, it had this chilling
nickname: ``Camp O'Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
