<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE     10-20 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS21-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I paid into Social Security, but I lack about 24 quarters.
I'm 68 years old and retired, so it's unlikely that I will work the
remaining quarters I need to receive benefits. Can I be refunded
the money I paid in?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. People cannot withdraw their Social Security taxes, even
when no benefits are payable, according to Social Security
Administration rules. Under normal circumstances, 40 calendar
quarters are needed to qualify for retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security taxes paid on a worker's earnings aren't
placed in an individual worker's account, but are pooled in special
trust funds from which benefits are paid to eligible workers and
families. Social Security's rationale is that it's a system of
social insurance under which covered workers and their employers
pay taxes to provide insurance protection for the workers and their
families. Such people are protected against the loss of income from
work because of the retirement, disability or death of the worker,
as well as hospital care costs in old age and in severe and
extended disability.
</P>
<P>
   So, to put it plainly: The program isn't intended to guarantee
the return of a person's Social Security taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do I call to find out the winning numbers in the
Florida Lottery? I tried the number printed on the ticket, but it
doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's 1-900-737-7777, with a charge to the caller of 77 cents
a minute. There's no toll-free number. A Florida Lottery spokesman
said calls won't go through if your phone has a block on 900 calls,
which involve a fee.
</P>
<P>
   An option for Internet users is the Florida Lottery's Web site _
www.flalottery.com/ _ which posts winning numbers. No charge for
viewing, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A newspaper item on the subject of flying a flag on the
Martin Luther King Jr. holiday referred to 10 federal holidays. I
can only think of seven. Can you list them all?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are indeed 10 annual legal federal holidays as declared
by Congress: New Year's Day (Jan. 1); Martin Luther King Jr.'s
Birthday (Jan. 15, but observed on the third Monday in January);
Washington's Birthday (Feb. 22, but observed on the third Monday in
February); Memorial Day (the last Monday in May); Independence Day
(July 4); Labor Day (the first Monday in September); Columbus Day
(the second Monday in October); Veterans Day (Nov. 11);
Thanksgiving Day (the fourth Thursday in November); and Christmas
Day (Dec. 25).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some televised football games have a yellow line that appears
across the field designating where the first-down marker is. How is
this done?
</P>
<P>
   A: Talk about smoke and mirrors! New Jersey-based Princeton
Video Image calls the ``virtual first-down line'' one of several
innovations _ which include ``the virtual strike zone, real-time
box scores and more'' _ designed to enhance the viewer experience
of broadcasts. A person actually attending the games sees no such
thing, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The L-VIS (Live Video Insertion System) is described by the
company as a system of proprietary hardware and software designed
to insert electronic images into live televised broadcasts. The
inserted images may be two- or three-dimensional, static or
animated, opaque or semitransparent, and may be placed so they
appear to exist on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Before the broadcast, images to be inserted into the broadcast _
such as the first-down line or an advertisement that appears to
viewers to be on the stadium wall _ are prepared and the operator
identifies the location in the broadcast scene where they will be
inserted. The L-VIS system recognizes the scene in ``real time''
during the broadcast and inserts the image as instructed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who assigns names to hurricanes, and why do they always have
America-style names? I am not a native of this country and find
this confusing.
</P>
<P>
   A: Names are selected from library sources and are agreed upon
by nations involved in international meetings of the World
Meteorological Organization. The names are chosen because they're
short and distinctive and easier to understand than the older,
cumbersone longitude-latitude identification methods when exchanged
between hundreds of widely scattered stations, airports, coastal
bases and ships at sea. At attempt is made to give some of the
storms names with what the WMO calls an ``international flavor''
because hurricanes affect, and are tracked by, nations other than
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic storms have a rotating six-year list of names. Some
samples of those that can be considered ``international'': (1999)
Jose, Philippe; (2000) Alberto, Ernesto, Rafael; (2001) Humberto,
Lorenzo, Pablo; (2002) Cristobal, Marco, Omar, Paloma; (2003)
Henri, Isabel; (2004) Tomas.
</P>
<P>
   Samples of Eastern Pacific storms with ``international'' names:
(1999); Beatriz, Fernanda, Pilar, Ramon; (2000) Aletta, Carlotta,
Emilia, Fabio, Hector, Sergio, Vicente; (2001) Kiko, Lorena,
Manuel, Narda, Octave, Tico; (2002) Fausto, Hernan, Iselle, Julio;
(2003) Andres, Blanca, Guillermo, Ignacio, Jimena; (2004) Blas,
Javier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our grandchildren have started collecting the Mint's 50 state
coins. Does anyone make a folder to put them into? I've tried
national bookstores with no luck.
</P>
<P>
   A: If you can't find something at a coin shop, the U.S. Mint may
have just what you're looking for. It's a map of the United States
_ The Official United States Mint 50 State Quarters Collector's Map
_ that folds out to about 3 feet in length, with pockets to hold
each state's coins as they are produced. The map has information
about each state, and the year each will be featured on a U.S.
quarter. The map costs $24.95 and can be ordered by calling
1-800-872-6468, or online at www.usmint.gov/catalog/help.cfm
</P>
<P>
   Another option is a folder available for $4.95 from Littleton
Coin Co. Call 1-800-645-3122 or, for online information and
ordering, check the company's Web site: www.littletoncoin.com
</P>
<P>
   Q : What has become of a striptease artist in the 1950s who
performed under the name Candy Barr? As I recall, she was convicted
of some crime and went to prison. I haven't seen anything about her
in years.
</P>
<P>
   A: At last report she was living near Brownwood, Texas, as
Juanita Phillips. Her birth name was Juanita Dale Slusher; Phillips
was the last name of one of her four ex-husbands.
</P>
<P>
   She was born around 1935 in Edna, Texas, and ran away at 12. As
a Dallas newspaper reported in a 1985 interview, she was a
prostitute in Dallas as a teenager, a stripper at 19 _ when she
took the name Candy Barr _ and, later, a nightclub performer in
Dallas and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1957, Dallas narcotics officers arrested her at her
apartment on a charge of illegal possession of marijuana. After
being convicted and sentenced to 15 years, she entered prison in
December 1959, and was paroled after serving three years and 91
days. In 1967, Texas Gov. John Connally granted her a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   She tried dancing again, but her comeback failed. In the years
since she has published a book of poetry and posed for pictures in
Oui magazine, but other than that she seems to have dropped out of
public view.
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
