<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO SEE BARAK AND ARAFAT IN EFFORT TO SPEED PEACE MOVES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will use a visit to Norway early
next month to give ``added momentum'' to the Middle East peace
effort and will meet there together with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, administration
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Israel Policy Forum on Wednesday, Sandy
Berger, the national security adviser, said Clinton would reinject
himself into the negotiations between the two leaders because ``we
are at a pivotal strategic moment'' in carrying through on the Wye
River Accord, signed a year ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   All three leaders will be attending a commemoration for Yitzhak
Rabin, the Israeli prime minister who was assassinated four years
ago. Oslo was also the site of the 1993 peace accord in which
Israel first agreed to withdrawals from the West Bank and both
sides agreed to negotiate a final peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But progress since then has been episodic, and Clinton is
clearly concerned that the peace effort could simply drag on
without concrete results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of his legacy issues,'' one of Clinton's top
foreign policy advisers said recently. ``Along with Ireland, and
getting China relations back on course, the Middle East is what he
wants to be remembered for.''
</P>
<P>
   Establishing just what role America will play, however, has been
a sensitive issue, as Berger acknowledged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has made it clear that he hopes the United States will
lower its profile, and Berger suggested Wednesday that Washington
has taken on a more restrained role with the accord signed at Sharm
el Sheik, along the Red Sea in Egypt, in early September, two
months after Barak took office and formed a new government.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially a revision of the Wye Accord, the latest agreement
was negotiated without a visible American role, though Clinton and
Berger spent much of August on the phone to both leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement envisions the end of conflict between the
Palestinians and Israelis a year from now, with the emotional
issues of boundaries and the status of Jerusalem solved by that
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have witnessed since then is powerful evidence that
having the two parties work together directly, while maintaining a
robust American role, is the most effective way to advance peace,''
Berger said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While suggesting that Barak and Arafat are now able to deal
directly with each other, Berger was clearly making the case that
Washington remained an indispensable player in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Palestinian track, the parties at long last have agreed
to address the core issues that have defined their conflict for the
past 50 years and that will define the peace for generations to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must not be said that when the parties were prepared to do
what we all along have pressed them to do, America opted for the
sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His comments came as Clinton is still fighting the
Republican-controlled Congress over Washington's financial
contributions to the peace effort. Clinton sought $800 million to
finance the Wye accord this year and $500 million for next year.
But both were deleted from the Foreign Operations budget bill that
Clinton vetoed earlier this week. Berger said that ``the president
will not sign a foreign operations bill that does not contain this
funding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
