<HEADER>
A3318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT &LR;      10-20 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS SEEK 25TH TITLE TO ROUND OUT CENTURY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wednesday was a casual day at Yankee Stadium. Only
about a dozen players worked out indoors on a voluntary basis,
David Cone bypassed throwing baseballs to pack two boxes and Joe
Torre wore blue jeans during a relaxing session with the smallest
assemblage of reporters he has seen in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A day and a half before this calm setting, the Yankees had
stymied the Red Sox to snatch the American League Championship and
rumble into the World Series. About twelve hours earlier, the
Yankees yawned and stretched while learning that the Atlanta
Braves, not the Mets, would be their opponents in Game 1 on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Yankees admitted that they watched the Mets lose to
the Braves in a thrilling game that did not end until Wednesday
morning, which is why many of them looked so sleepy. While some
Yankees were disappointed that there would not be a Subway Series
that surely would have turned this city into wall-to-wall baseball,
others sounded relieved. The Yankees should be.
</P>
<P>
   As much pressure as is already inherent in trying to defend a
World Series title, especially for a historic team like the Yankees
and especially against a pitching-rich team like Atlanta, the
attention would have intensified even more drastically if the
series was New York, New York.
</P>
<P>
   The hype about the Yankees-Braves being a skirmish for who is
crowned the team of the decade will be persistent, but pursuing
that fabricated distinction is not as burdensome as trying to win
while being scrutinized by a city of eight million fans, all
experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we had played the Mets, it would be a much more
difficult situation,'' said Joe Girardi. ``Not from the standpoint
of who we played, but how you're remembered. If it was the Mets,
neither the Mets or Yankees would want to be remembered as the team
that lost. That would have been a hard thing because that's how the
players who played in that would have been marked and that's not
really fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of being brandished would have been especially
dangerous to the Yankees, who would have been the solid favorites.
Other than obviously winning their third title in four years, the
Yankees would have had little to gain in conquering the Mets
because George Steinbrenner would have expected it and they would
have had much more to lose, including some jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of our minds, everybody would have liked to play
the Mets to see what the city would be like, but, in a way, it is
kind of a relief,'' said Jeff Nelson. ``It would be a mad house
around here. Maybe it is a little relief that we don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul O'Neill, who was chagrined that reporters were even
allowed in the clubhouse after the optional workout and then
lectured them about what is and what is not a legitimate story, did
not feel the Yankees will receive any benefit from the Mets going
home. To O'Neill, any World Series foe is scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is to win the World Series, whether you play the
Mets, you play the Diamondbacks or you play the Braves,'' said
O'Neill. ``You're going to have to beat a quality team. Being with
the Yankees and having done what we've done, we've kind of set
ourselves up to where you got to win. That's all there is to it.
You win the World Series. You don't just get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Soaked with Champagne at Fenway Park on Monday night,
Steinbrenner vowed, ``We're not going there to lose, I'll tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Brian Cashman, who has watched Steinbrenner
explode after losses to the Mets during spring training, admitted
that playing the Mets would have created distractions that might
have proved detrimental. Although Cashman stressed that the Yankees
have deep respect for the Braves, a team that stifled them twice in
three games this season, and will approach them in the same way as
they would have the Mets, there is a big difference between
opposing Atlanta and the team from Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be a lot more at stake than just the World
Championship if we were playing the Mets,'' Cashman said. ``It
would be the city and bragging rights. That's a story within the
story, whereas now we're playing for the world title, which really
should be everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Since half of the Yankees took the day off, Torre declined to
discuss any rotation or roster decisions. But Orlando Hernandez is
on schedule to pitch the opener on Saturday and David Cone hinted
that he would start Game 2. There is a chance that Torre would
flip-flop Roger Clemens and Andy Pettitte, meaning that Pettitte
would pitch Game 3 at Yankee Stadium and a possible Game 7 on the
road and Clemens would only start Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Torre explained how he is not as worried about O'Neill's
fractured rib as he was last week so the Yankees could replace
reserve outfielder Shane Spencer with Jim Leyritz. When Leyritz was
left off the ALCS roster, Torre told him he would probably be
reinstated if the Yankees advanced to the World Series. It helps
Leyritz that he belted one of the most important homers in recent
Yankees history off Atlanta's Mark Wohlers in Game 4 of the 1996
World Series, which the Yankees won in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a little success against them,'' said Leyritz,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The team of the '90s debate will certainly follow this World
Series like a full-time scalper. Chili Davis called the matchup
``perfect'' and Alan Watson said it was ``neat,'' but some players
denounced the debate and most Yankees were quiet when asked to
select the team of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention is to win the World Series,'' said Torre, ``but
not just so we're the team of the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman was even more direct and said, ``I don't know what it
means to be the team of '90s. We're just trying to win this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Cashman paused and asked reporters, ``Are we the team of
the century?'' There was silence and then knowing laughter because
the Yankees have a record 24 World Series Championships and the
answer is obviously a resounding yes. Still, the Yankees know the
25th would end the century symmetrically and stylishly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
