<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-SUIT-ART-2T     10-20 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-SUIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF MAYOR SUCCEEDS IN EVICTING MUSEUM, FATE OF ARTWORK UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J., Britain)  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT29, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The target of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's public fire in
his battle against the Brooklyn Museum of Art has been the museum's
trustees, whom the mayor says he wants to oust as irresponsible and
insensitive for staging an exhibition he considers offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But City Hall's lawsuit against the museum has a different and
specific goal: to evict the museum from the city-owned building on
Eastern Parkway in Brooklyn. If that strategy succeeds, it could
have a remarkable result. The museum, not the city, owns the
artwork. So if the museum were evicted, it could theoretically pack
up all 1.5 million artworks, the second largest collection in the
country, after the Metropolitan Museum of Art in Manhattan, and
take them somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota acknowledged this possibility when he
was questioned recently by lawyers for the museum. After agreeing
that the museum owns the art, Lhota was asked to consider what
would happen if the city succeeded in terminating the museum's
lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you aware that if that corporation is ejected from the
building, it can remove its property and go elsewhere?'' Susan
Buckley, a lawyer for the museum, asked Lhota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am aware of that,'' he answered. ``I would like to say that
`it can,' I think, should be changed to `it will' have to take its
artwork and move elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buckley continued: ``And it could move it to Los Angeles,
couldn't it?'' Lhota replied, ``My answer to your question is
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the museum trustees who expect the worst from the mayor say
they find it impossible to believe that he would go through with an
eviction. It has taken the museum a century to assemble its
collection through acquisitions, private donations and expeditions
to the far regions of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees have donated millions of dollars for building
improvements. To them, the notion of moving vans pulling up to cart
off Egyptian mummies and African fertility statues and bucolic
Winslow Homer paintings seems too preposterous to consider, except
that this is precisely what Giuliani is demanding. It is right
there in his lawsuit, which asks a judge to order that the museum
``deliver possession of the premises and the building thereon to
the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe he means it,'' said Frieda Rosenthal, a
vice chairwoman of the Board of Trustees. ``I don't really believe
they could do this. It would be so harmful to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``What would the city do with the building? It's all
been redone. It's suitable just for us, with special climate
control and remodeled galleries.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the trustees, there is speculation that Giuliani
miscalculated and assumed the board would back down rather than
fight it out in court. Some suspect that Giuliani knows he cannot
win in court, and so he is simply trying to make as much noise as
possible to increase his support among conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's always been threatening gestures,'' said Barbara
K. Debs, a trustee and chairwoman of the museum's strategic
planning committee. ``I'm quite sure that he felt we might actually
back down, but it's very hard for me to figure out the real motives
of any of this. It just strikes me as bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. Hess, the corporation counsel, said Wednesday that
the mayor has no desire to see the collection ``scattered about''
to other cities. The mayor's intent, he said, is to gain leverage
over the museum's board. Lacking any clear authority to remove the
trustees himself, the mayor hopes that the trustees will, if
evicted, voluntarily agree to cede ownership of the art to the city
rather than see it leave Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling,'' Hess said, ``is that if we win the eviction, the
practical result is that the art will not be scattered all over the
place. Human beings of good faith will find a way to work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hess acknowledged the risks implicit in the city's strategy.
What happens should the trustees decide they cannot stomach giving
Giuliani control of more than $1 billion worth of art?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what they own they would have to take with them and
either set up a collection elsewhere or merge it with other
collections,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Debs barely paused when asked if the museum would ever
agree to surrender the art for the sake of keeping it in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see it happening,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other trustees laughed at the idea, in part because they were so
confident of victory in court. As with another of the mayor's
recent forays into First Amendment territory _ his failed attempt
this summer to ban a youth rally in Harlem _ city lawyers have been
unable to cite a legal precedent that squarely supports his
position.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the most analogous case, a federal judge ruled in
1991 that the city of Miami violated the First Amendment when it
tried to evict the Cuban Museum of Arts and Culture from a city
building for displaying art that angered Cubans in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, Judge Nina Gershon of the U.S. District Court is
expected to rule soon on whether Giuliani's decision to cut off
public financing and seek eviction has likewise violated the First
Amendment. In a brief hearing Wednesday, Gershon gave City Hall
until noon Thursday to submit final papers in the case.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, city officials sought to sidestep the First
Amendment issues by raising as reasons for eviction the museum's
initial plan to restrict children from viewing the ``Sensation''
exhibition and its decision to charge adults $9.75 for admission.
They had said that the city's lease required the mayor to approve
such conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But in arguments before Gershon, the city's lawyers abruptly
dropped those issues as grounds for terminating the lease. They
also abandoned the argument that the museum violated its lease by
staging an exhibition to advance the commercial interests of
Charles Saatchi, the wealthy British advertising entrepreneur who
owns all 90 of the works. Despite Giuliani's threats, his lawyers
have yet to assert in court that he has the authority to remove
trustees from the museum board.
</P>
<P>
   The only official empowered under state law to act against
trustees of charitable institutions is the attorney general,
lawyers in the case said.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves Giuliani with but one remaining rationale for
eviction. By staging an exhibition of ``sick stuff,'' the mayor and
his lawyers contend, the museum violated a provision in its lease
from 1893 requiring it to ``enlighten, educate and provide
enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Lehman, the museum's director, and Robert S. Rubin, its
chairman, declined to comment on what would happen to the art if
the museum were evicted. According to a recent sworn statement
submitted to Gershon by Lehman, the mere threat of eviction has
already inflicted ``extraordinary damage'' on the museum. Donors,
he said, have called to express ``very serious concerns'' about the
museum. Lenders of art have called to ask whether their pieces
``will be returned safely.'' The museum, he said, ``cannot
responsibly make plans for future exhibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Giuliani this month, District Council 37, the
municipal union that represents 5,800 employees in 20 of the city's
cultural institutions, warned that the mayor's actions have
imperiled the jobs of its members at the Brooklyn Museum. ``This
union can't stand idly by and allow the jobs of our dedicated
workers to be threatened,'' union leaders wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Floyd Abrams, the museum's First Amendment lawyer, is
squeezing the eviction issue for all it is worth in the battle for
public opinion. Almost gleefully, he raises the prospect of moving
vans spiriting art off to, say, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum would own the art, so the board would have to
consider where to set up a new museum,'' he said with a smile. ``I
assume there would be a serious amount of bidding by other museums
in the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
