<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE DEFICIT NARROWED IN AUGUST AS EXPORTS GREW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reflecting some long-awaited gains from economic recovery
abroad, the huge American trade deficit narrowed in August for the
first time in four months as exports rose faster than imports.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets reacted calmly to Wednesday's government
report, a sharp contrast to the previous month, when currency and
bond markets fell after the Commerce Department reported a large
increase in the trade gap at a time when Japanese authorities were
doing little to reverse a worrisome rise in the yen. Indeed,
indications that the trade gap may no longer be widening appear to
have contributed to a powerful rally in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The latest tally showed a gap between exports and imports of
$24.1 billion, down from $24.9 billion in July.
</P>
<P>
   With economies in Asia, Latin America and Europe on the mend,
demand for American exports of goods and services is finally
improving. But some experts worry that such gains will only further
stoke a U.S. economy that is already operating at a pace that
leaves the Federal Reserve nervous about revived inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This confirms that economic growth overseas is taking hold,''
said Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. in
Minneapolis. Noting a near-doubling of American exports of
aircraft, he added, ``Asian airlines are buying again because their
traffic has built tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the U.S. deficit with China soared to
$6.9 billion, the largest ever with any country, from $6.3 billion
in July. This prompted a fresh expression of unhappiness in
Washington, where support for China's efforts to join the World
Trade Organization seem to be fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S.-China trade remains a troubling story,'' William Daley,
the commerce secretary, said. American imports from China exceeded
exports by an additional $6 billion so far this year compared with
the similar period in 1998. He said that at talks set in Seattle
next month he would keep pressing the Chinese to remove obstacles
to American companies seeking to do business there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere you look, you see stuff made in China,'' said James
Glassman, senior U.S. economist at Chase Securities, adding that
the primary ``culprit'' causing the widening of the nation's trade
imbalance in previous months was recession in Asia rather than any
lack of competitiveness on the part of American business, as was
the case in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The government's statistics on trade between individual
countries, which are not adjusted for normal seasonal variation,
also showed that the deficit with Japan shrank in August to $6.4
billion, from $6.8 billion in July.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the report showed, exports climbed $2.9 billion in
August, to $82 billion, while imports rose $2.1 billion, to $106.1
billion. That reduced the trade gap $800 million, with July's gap,
upon revision, moderately lower than first reported.
</P>
<P>
   This was the eighth consecutive monthly rise in imports,
reflecting the continued domestic boom and by far the largest of
three consecutive gains in exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to see evidence of global healing,'' said
Richard Berner, chief U.S. economist at Morgan Stanley, Dean
Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while encouraged by rising exports, Berner said the trade
deficit could easily expand again in coming months since exports
must grow 30 percent faster than imports at current levels merely
to keep it steady.
</P>
<P>
   James Annable, chief economist at Wingspanbank.com, also
expressed concern about the impact of American consumers' strong
demand for foreign goods. If this doesn't subside, he said, the
deficit could swell enough that the dollar would weaken, tending to
bring inflation, higher interest rates or both.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the deficit is raising far fewer alarms than it
did a decade ago; it is less than 3 percent of gross domestic
product, about half a percentage point less than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   That is largely because American industry is making immense
investments in new equipment that should raise productivity.
Moreover, consumers are likely to slow spending since rising
interest rates have nearly ended home refinancings which, along
with the stock market, had helped fuel the current binge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the worst of all worlds yet,'' Annable said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' trade deficit with Canada, muddied by
border-area production for tax reasons and other issues, climbed to
$3.5 billion from $3.1 billion for the month while the deficit with
Mexico was essentially unchanged at $2.2 billion. The American
deficit with Western Europe narrowed to $4.4 billion, from $6.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the industrialized countries of the Far East _ Hong Kong,
South Korea, Singapore and Taiwan _ the gap shrank to $1.7 billion,
from $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest rise in imports in August was for industrial
supplies and materials _ mainly crude petroleum that has risen
sharply in price this year. Petroleum imports rose to $5 billion,
from $4.44 billion in July, as the price for a barrel jumped to
$17.40, the highest level since March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The next biggest increase was for automotive vehicles, parts and
engines.
</P>
</TEXT>
