<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BOWDENS21-COX     10-20 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWDENS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowdens getting ready for family feud
 &HT;    By Tom DeAngelo
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The college student was in no mood for
pranks _ especially ones aimed at his father.
</P>
<P>
   So West Virginia tight end Tommy Bowden told his dad to stop the
car one Sunday morning as the family was headed for church. Right
there, along the main street on the Morgantown campus, was a
crude-looking dummy hanging from a tree by its neck with a sign
that read ``Coach Bowden.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy hopped out of the car armed with scissors. A security
guard appeared and said, ``You can't cut that down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my father,'' Tommy replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still can't cut it down,'' the guard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to cut it down,'' Tommy said, ``I want to add to
it. He's not fat enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Bowden, of course, freed the likeness of his father from
the noose that day 25 years ago. But Saturday, he has the chance to
tighten the grip around the old man's national championship hopes
in a game featuring more intrigue than perhaps any other in the
history of college football.
</P>
<P>
   When Bobby Bowden's Florida State Seminoles play Tommy Bowden's
Clemson Tigers, the game not only will mark the first time in NCAA
football history a father and son have faced each other as head
coaches, but it could result in Bobby's 300th victory. If Clemson,
a 16 1/2-point underdog, pulls off the upset, Tommy will be toasted
in South Carolina as if it were his 300th victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a national championship at stake,'' Tommy said. ``All
the pressure is on him. It's an opportunity for me to enjoy the
game. They'll be tightened up over there _ one slip and they're
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bowden Bowl is more than father vs. son, it's a family
affair. Also on the sidelines will be Bobby and Ann Bowden's
youngest son Jeff, Florida State's receivers coach, matching wits
against brother-in-law Jack Hines, Clemson's secondary coach. Hines
is married to the Bowden's oldest child, Robyn.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Terry Bowden, the former Auburn coach who was
supposed to play his Dad this season before resigning last season,
will be in the ABC studio to analyze the game.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Ann, Bobby's wife of 50 years, and the rest of the
children _ Steve Bowden and Ginger Bowden Madden _ to watch from
the stands, along with many of Bobby and Ann's 21 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I get there and see Tommy on one side and Bobby on the
other, I think I am going to retreat up to the end zone and let my
emotions hang out,'' Ann said.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy, 45, is the Bowden's second-oldest son, behind Steve, the
only son not in coaching. Tommy, according to the family, is most
like his father in his personality, his beliefs and his religious
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a scaredy cat,'' Bobby said. ``I was always afraid to
try things. If we were going in a swimming pool, Terry would run
and jump in before he'd see if there was water in it. Tommy was
like I was. I would go up to the water put my toe in and pull it
out. Then I'd stick my ankle in and pull it out. Then I might
finally go in if it was just right.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tommy was not scared the night he tracked down a fraternity
president and demanded he send a retraction to the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The frat boy, a West Virginia student, wrote a letter to the
editor criticizing Bobby and saying the players did not have
confidence in their coach. Tommy saved it in his wallet for six
months, the time it took to track down the author.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy took six teammates, including FSU's current strength and
conditioning coach Dave Van Halanger, and visited the fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was upstairs and someone said a couple of people want to
see you,'' the 6-foot-6 Van Halanger said. ``He came downstairs and
his face turned white. We said, `We don't want to have trouble but
we could start trouble. We just want you to write a retraction.' He
said, `Yes sir.'''
</P>
<P>
   Watching how his dad handled adversity was an important lesson
for Tommy, who decided at an earlier age than Terry or Jeff that he
wanted to coach. Ann still keeps a paper Tommy wrote in sixth grade
about how he wanted to be a football coach. And unlike Steve, who
has his Ph.D. in philosophy, and Terry, an Oxford graduate who has
a law degree, and Jeff, who graduated from Florida State, Tommy
majored in physical education at West Virginia with the sole
purpose of becoming a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy didn't prepare himself for any other profession but
coaching,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy took a much different path than Terry. Although two years
younger than Tommy, Terry's first full-time job was as a head
coach, at Salem College in 1983. Tommy had seven stops before his
first head coaching job, at Tulane in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry wants the brass ring right away,'' said Ginger, 38, the
youngest of the Bowden children. ``Tommy is more willing to take
the longer route to get to the same place. ... take a lot less
risk. Dad is not a big risk taker. ... except with his offense.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Bowdens felt pressure to follow Dad into coaching,
and none was being compared to Bobby. Terry believes Steve's
decision not to pursue the profession was the best thing for him,
Tommy and Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve, being the oldest son, he may have felt the most
pressure to be Bobby Bowden's son,'' Terry said. ``When he didn't
become a coach, that took the pressure off of us. The oldest son is
supposed to take over the legacy. It kind of freed us up to do what
we wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   The three coaching sons have worked for their father. Tommy's
career started in 1978 at Florida State. After switching jobs five
times, he was hired by Pat Dye at Auburn, where he was eventually
reunited with Terry after Terry replaced Dye in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he could coach,'' Dye said. ``What I didn't know is
what a class guy he is and the character he had. Tommy Bowden is
real. A lot of people project what Tommy Bowden is. I can tell you
now Tommy Bowden is genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he was at Auburn, Tommy spent three years coaching
receivers at Alabama for coordinator Homer Smith. Tommy's offensive
philosophy was rooted in Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Bobby visited Tommy at Auburn to talk about the shotgun
formation. Bobby had never used the offense and figured he had the
perfect quarterback for it in Charlie Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby took it back to Tallahassee, redesigned his two-minute
offense using the shotgun and by the end of the season he was
running it on almost every down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry copied it as soon as I did,'' said Bobby. Terry was in
his final season at Samford.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy was feeling pretty good about teaching his dad something
about the game when he had his most humbling experience as a coach
the next year. That was when Terry was hired at Auburn and Tommy
was forced to work for his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been working hard in the SEC to get a job like that and
all of a sudden your younger brother gets that job in your home
state,'' Tommy said. ``I didn't work 15 years to work for my
younger brother.''
</P>
<P>
   When Terry was hired, he was told he had to fire the entire
staff, including his brother. Terry told Auburn officials he would
not take the job if he had to fire Tommy. ``I felt that was not the
way to start my career in Division I,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry won the struggle and named Tommy receivers coach, although
he was technically the offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was blaming Tommy for not being able to run the
offense (under Dye),'' Terry said. ``I didn't name him coordinator
because I thought we wouldn't be any good and I wanted to take all
the blame. But he was the coordinator. I just had the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry's prediction was way off. The Tigers went 11-0, but
because of NCAA sanctions were not eligible for a bowl. Otherwise,
the first father-son match-up could have occurred Jan. 1, 1994, in
the national championship game. Instead, the door was open for
Bobby to win his first and only title, which he did with a victory
over Nebraska in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Tommy joined Terry as the only Bowdens to finish a
season undefeated as a head coach, leading Tulane to an 11-0
record. Bobby still is looking for his first perfect season after
34 years. But like Terry, Tommy did not coach the bowl game,
leaving for Clemson before the Green Wave's final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a little bit of needling, but Dad's response is
neither of you coached in the bowl game at the end of the
(undefeated) season,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the way of Bobby's undefeated season this week is
his son, but that will not stop Tommy from trying to break his
father's heart. The Bowdens are a competitive family and will use
any tactic to win, whether it's a trick play on the football field,
or tricks on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   If Saturday is anything like the Bowdens' annual Father and Sons
Skins game at the Tyndall Air Force Base in Panama City each
summer, Tommy isn't about to give his old man a break.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, sides are picked for the outing. According to
Steve, Bobby was on the winning side in the inaugural match 13
years ago after some creative scorekeeping and even more creative
shots. From that point on, the tournament was dubbed the Tyndall
Swindle and the losing team receives a trophy of a slack-shouldered
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't nothing but cheatin' going on, full-blooded
cheatin','' Bobby said. ``There ain't a lie you can't improve.
There's a lot of trash talking going on. Talking on somebody's back
swing, disrupting them.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a good ol' family feud, just like the one that
will take place at Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
