<HEADER>
A3342 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ATMS21-COX     10-20 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATMS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First Union sells stamps, phone time via ATMs
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ First Union is selling long-distance
phone time and postage stamps through its ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's sixth-largest bank is among the first to turn
automated teller machines into vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend that could catch on, bankers say. ATMs soon could
sell traveler's checks and tickets to movies, concerts and
ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, N.C.-based First Union sells MCI long-distance
service at its 2,900 ATMs on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The ATMs don't dispense calling cards. Instead, they print
receipts that list an 800 number and a long-distance code.
Customers can buy 30 minutes for $8.40 or an hour for $16.80.
</P>
<P>
   First Union also sells stamps in packages of 18 for $6.60.
That's 66 cents more than at the post office, a trade-off for
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 First Union ATMs in Palm Beach County and the
Treasure Coast hawk stamps, because they take space otherwise
occupied by cash, said Gary Bargeron, the bank's vice president of
ATM operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some banks plan to use ATMs as vending machines; others are
waiting to see how the strategy works.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Levan, president of BankAtlantic in Fort Lauderdale, said
his ATMs will sell stamps and phone cards in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank says it won't sell through ATMs because customers
don't want to wait while someone else shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always joke that I don't want to wait in line behind the
person who's buying opera tickets,'' said Ann DeFabio, spokeswoman
at NationsBank parent Bank of America, also based in Charlotte.
``We're still looking at the convenience factor.''
</P>
<P>
   First Union's Bargeron says it's a balancing act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ATM can become an electronic vending machine,'' Bargeron
said. ``All that has to be couched in the mantra of fast,
convenient transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   First Union (NYSE: FTU, $37.38) wouldn't say how much it expects
to make from ATM sales.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo of San Francisco and BB&AMP;T of Winston-Salem, N.C.,
also use ATMs as vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   Bank critics say the trend of squeezing more profits from ATMs
weakens the industry argument that customers should pay fees to use
ATMs owned by banks where they don't have accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it a whole lot harder to argue that they need those
surcharges,'' said Gail Hillebrand of Consumers Union in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
