<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL IS BUYING DOLLARS, PUTTING NEW PRESSURE ON ITS CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By SIMON ROMERO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Facing market pressure to meet obligations
to foreign creditors, including an outflow of capital, Brazil found
its currency under stress for a seventh consecutive session
Wednesday, with the currency fluttering around a psychological
threshold of 2 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian real weakened to a rate of 2.007 to the dollar,
its lowest level in more than seven months, before recovering a
little to settle in New York at 1.9890 after new unemployment data
suggested a modest improvement in economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, currency traders remained jittery as concern grew over
recent government actions that have caused the currency to weaken.
</P>
<P>
   In moves that surprised many people, the Brazilian Treasury has
purchased hundreds of millions of dollars from banks in the last
three weeks to pay off installments and interest on foreign debt.
By doing so, it departed from a strategy of dipping into the
central bank's foreign-currency reserves to honor obligations
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The logic behind such a move has to do with Brazil's agreement
with the International Monetary Fund, which put together a $41.5
billion bailout package for the economy early this year. The
agreement requires Brazil to maintain $22 billion in
foreign-currency reserves, aside from money from the IMF and other
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, this means that the government has to buy the
dollars it needs elsewhere to prevent a depletion of reserves. Yet
while the central bank president, Arminio Fraga, expressed calm
over the effect this has had on the Brazilian real's value, saying
his concern is focused on inflation, a declining real has generated
some alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some elements are sensing weakness on the part of the
authorities and are wondering how far the real can be pushed,''
said Alexandre Fialho, head of the foreign-exchange desk at
Finambras Corretora, one of the country's largest currency-trading
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the concern stems from an easing by the central bank of
the sale of dollar-linked bonds, which it used until recently to
curb the real's decline. The bonds themselves, which now account
for a quarter of the domestic debt, may have generated wider
anxiety over the debt service burden, since financing costs rise
with the weakening of the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Still, such concern may be overdone as recent data show an
improvement in the fundamentals of Brazil's economy. The data
released today said that unemployment fell in September to its
lowest level this year, 8 percent, down from 8.3 percent in August.
And the deficit in the current account, a wide measure of foreign
transactions, shrank to 4.69 percent of the gross domestic product
in the 12 months ending in September, down from 5.14 percent in the
previous 12-month period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Logic is not the currency market's forte,'' said Roberto
Macedo, an independent consultant and economics professor at the
University of Sao Paulo. ``The pressure from external commitments
is passing and should be absorbed with time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
