<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES CONTINUE TO REPORT WEAK QUARTERLY PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's airlines continued to report weakened third-quarter
earnings Wednesday as rising fuel prices, the growing number of
airplane seats and bad weather helped to reduce profits from last
year's record highs.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, Trans World Airlines, and the UAL Corp., the parent
of United Airlines, all disappointed Wall Street, while the AMR
Corp., the owner of American Airlines, was the lone bright spot.
</P>
<P>
   After four consecutive years of record profits, many airline
executives contended they had finally learned how to increase
profits consistently in the notoriously cyclical industry. But even
as the domestic economy remains strong, carriers are having
difficulty maintaining past earnings levels. Third-quarter profits
were also down at some other major carriers. Part of the problem is
that the number of new seats is growing faster than the number of
new passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating in a reasonably good operating environment,
year over year, that we haven't been able to keep our shareholder
returns up,'' Gerard J. Arpey, AMR's chief financial officer, told
reporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   UAL said its net income fell to $456 million, or $3.75 a share,
from $516 million, or $4.02 a share, in the corresponding period
last year. Revenue rose 1.3 percent, to $4.85 billion from $4.78
billion. UAL, which is the nation's largest employee-owned company,
reports results as if all employee shares have been distributed.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings just missed the $3.76 a share average estimate of
analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Rono Dutta, UAL's president, said the performance of United,
which is the world's largest airline, was strong in July and
August. But last month, Hurricane Floyd forced the airline to
cancel 750 flights, costing it $15 million. Revenue per seat
declined 3 percent domestically during the quarter, while it rose
12 percent overseas. The airline's costs were up 3 percent, mainly
because of higher wages and salaries, Dutta said.
</P>
<P>
   AMR said Hurricane Floyd cost it $17 million after it canceled
700 flights. But a hurricane also upset American's operations last
year, neutralizing the effect of Floyd on this year's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Profits declined 36 percent during the quarter to $279 million,
or $1.76 a share, from $433 million, or $2.49 a share in the third
quarter last year. Revenue rose 2.1 percent, to $5.1 billion from
$5.05 billion last year. The average estimate of analysts surveyed
by First Call/Thomson Financial was $1.69 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Arpey of AMR said the average cost of jet fuel had risen 3
cents, to 56 cents a gallon, in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Arpey said an offer made on Monday by Air Canada to
buy the rival Canadian Airlines with the financial backing of UAL
and Deutsche Lufthansa A.G. was not credible. The Air Canada bid
counters an offer, backed by AMR, from the Onex Corp., a Canadian
buyout specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in it for any of the Canadian
constituencies,'' Arpey said of the Air Canada proposal, ``and
there is certainly nothing in it for AMR shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, which is the nation's sixth-largest airline and has
struggled all year, continued to disappoint Wall Street. It lost
$85 million, or $1.19 a share, during the quarter in contrast to a
profit of $142 million, or $1.51 a share, in the period last year.
Revenue fell to $2.1 billion from $2.2 billion last year. Analysts
had predicted a 33-cent loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results are clearly unacceptable,'' said Rakesh Gangwal,
the president and chief executive of US Airways. ``Our operational
difficulties during this quarter have taken a significant toll on
our financial performance.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hurricane Floyd, which forced the airline to
cancel 1,500 flights, US Airways suffered from shortages of pilots
and airplanes because of slowdowns in its training and maintenance
operations. As a result, the capacity, or number of seats, fell 6.6
percent. Its costs, which were already the highest in the industry,
soared to 13.51 cents per seat-mile flown from 12.26 cents in the
third quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   TWA said it had suffered from rising fuel costs and the threat
of a strike by its flight attendants and machinists. Its loss
widened to $36.2 million, or 61 cents a share, from $923,000, or 11
cents a share, in the period last year. Revenue rose 1.5 percent,
to $876 million from $863 million in 1998. Analysts polled by First
Call had expected TWA to lose 52 cents during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
