<SLUG> BC-FOODLION-ABC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC NOT REQUIRED TO PAY DAMAGES TO FOOD LION SUPERMARKET, APPEALS
COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: 2nd take will move by 10:15 p.m. ET.) 
(js) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A divided federal appeals court Wednesday threw out all but $2
of the remaining $315,000 in damages that a jury had ordered ABC
News to pay to the Food Lion supermarket chain after it reported
that the grocery chain sold beef and other food that was tainted.
</P>
<P>
   In the majority opinion, a panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, in Richmond, wrote that Food Lion's attempt to win a
multimillion-dollar fraud verdict because two ABC employees had
lied their way into jobs in Food Lion stores was ``an end-run
around First Amendment strictures foreclosed'' by existing legal
precedents.
</P>
<P>
   The case had been closely followed by major news organizations
that feared that, unless constitutional barriers were explicitly
provided in lawsuits focused on newsgathering techniques,
plaintiffs could win cripplingly high damage awards without having
to prove that the news reports in question were false or malicious.
Specialists in media law said the ruling Wednesday set high
constitutional hurdles for plaintiffs whose lawsuits focus on
journalists' newsgathering techniques and could blunt that line of
legal attack.
</P>
<P>
   The case was initially filed in a North Carolina court after the
ABC program ``Primetime Live'' broadcast a report that Food Lion
workers mixed out-of-date beef along with new beef. The report also
included videotapes secretly made of the chain's employees.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier federal district court ruling in the Food Lion case
struck down most of the $5.5 million in damages awarded by the jury
in the fraud suit, but did so on narrow grounds that avoided First
Amendment issues. The $315,000 punitive damage award which the
district court had left standing was struck down by the appeals
court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the appeals court's ruling only $2 of the original damage
award remains untouched. The jury awarded Food Lion $1 because the
journalists had trespassed on the supermarket chain's property and
$1 because they had breached their legal duty to be loyal to their
employer.
</P>
<P>
   David Westin, the president of ABC News who was the network's
general counsel when the lawsuit was filed, applauded the ruling,
which, he said, ``should help blunt'' an ``important and dangerous
shift.'' Instead of plaintiffs ``challenging what we said, through
libel and defamation, they are trying to get around through the
back door, attacking the process we used to get'' the information
used in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Westin and several specialists in media law said that the high
hurdles faced by libel plaintiffs have led plaintiffs to attack not
the substance of news reports, but the sometimes questionable way
journalists gathered their information _ in this case, ABC
reporters' deception on their job applications.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the court wrote in its majority opinion Wednesday, ``We
are convinced that the media can do its important job effectively
without resorting to the commission of run-of-the-mill'' breaches
of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, a partner at the law firm of Cahill Gordon &AMP;
Reindel who is a well-known First Amendment specialist, said of the
case Wednesday that: ``What people have tried to do is an end run
around the First Amendment protections that exist in libel law.
This case is a quintessential example. Food Lion didn't care at all
that two employees had false information on their applications for
employment. What they cared about was what ABC said about them.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
