<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves to Chandler: Stay in
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves reminded quarterback Chris
Chandler in a talk this week that part of his job description
includes setting an example.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Reeves wants Chandler to start and finish a game.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's season has been an exercise in frustration. He missed
three of six regular-season games with a right hamstring injury. He
also left two regular-season games when he aggravated the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during Sunday's game against the Rams, Chandler left in
the third quarter of a 41-13 loss with flulike symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said that Reeves pulled him; he did not ask to be taken
out. And after taking intravenous fluids, he wanted to return. But
if he had taken an IV before the game, Chandler might have felt
well enough to start and finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to make sure we're on the same page,'' Reeves
said. ``(The conversation) was mostly things that are private. We
tried to get him to take an IV; he didn't want it. We can't force
anything on (players).''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, a 12-year veteran, has never had a season without
missing games because of injuries or illness. Since joining the
team in 1997, he has missed seven of 38 regular-season games and
left 10 others.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons signed Chandler to a five-year, $27 million
contract before last season, Reeves said the team was taking a risk
on a player with a history of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sticking our necks out,'' Reeves said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Chandler still had a cough, but he said he felt
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few people who should and do care about how I
feel,'' he said. ``(We) didn't talk about IVs. (Reeves) said some
things, I said some things, and that was about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Bob Whitfield, who has played in 108 consecutive
games and started 102 in a row, said players like himself and wide
receiver Terance Mathis, who has started 62 games in a row, aim for
durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do is set examples,'' he said. ``You see
Terance practicing every day and playing, and he doesn't get hurt.
You see me practicing every day and playing, and I don't get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman has missed 15 games in the 1990s,
and San Francisco's Steve Young is about to miss his 14th in five
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   However, Green Bay passer Brett Favre has started 114 games in a
row, Tampa Bay's Trent Dilfer 69, Miami's Dan Marino 46, and
Pittsburgh's Kordell Stewart 38.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said his team desperately needs Chandler to get in a
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris... hasn't played enough (this season) to see things,''
Reeves said. ``You don't just go out there and start playing and
all of a sudden get your timing back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
