<HEADER>
A3352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS21-COX     10-20 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for jackpot in the slot
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Thrashers undeniably have a relative shortage of
speed and skill. But with a little attitude _ and perhaps a
willingness to trade body parts for goals _ from the players, coach
Curt Fraser is convinced that goals don't have to be a rare
occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebounds, tips, all those things come from a willingness to go
to the net,'' Fraser said. ``You're going to get whacked. You're
going to get a stick in the mouth. But that's what's going to give
you an opportunity to score. After awhile, your skin gets thick,
and the rewards start coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar to the key in basketball, the slot area between the two
faceoff spots is where a majority of the damage is done in hockey.
As a player, Fraser, who did not have a lot of natural ability,
would park himself in the slot, when he wasn't in the corners. From
the slot, he created traffic, followed shots and scored 193 goals
in 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked playing there, but that's where I had to play to be
successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his players have to follow that example. The Thrashers have
scored 14 goals in six games, and nine of those came in ties with
Buffalo (5-5) and Tampa (4-4). They scored two goals in one game
but one each in the other three.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-1 loss to the New York Rangers on Sunday exemplified the
problems, Fraser said. By his count, the team had 64 offensive
opportunities, including official shots, blocked shots and shots
that went wide of the net. Second attempts, however, could be
counted on one hand. Seldom did the Thrashers have a player in
front of goalie Mike Richter to set a screen or get a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to pay the price if you're going to score goals,''
forward Kelly Buchberger said. ``(Edmonton's) Ryan Smyth isn't a
great skater or shooter or passer, but he pays the price, and he's
hungry and he goes to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A basketball player has to put his time in the paint to get
rebounds, and it's the same in hockey,'' Andrew Brunette said.
``You're going to take some abuse in there, but that's how you
score goals, especially with how we're going to play. We're not
going to go around three guys and beat the goalie and score. We
have to find other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not always going to get rewarded, that's for sure,''
Brunette said. ``Maybe one every 20 times, you'll get a goal, if
that. You usually get a whack or a cross-check or a punch in the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Emerson said, ``We're all trained to get in there. But
the other team is trained to keep you out of there. I know I've
seen a lot of pucks on the ice. I've just got to be quicker getting
there.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that skilled players aren't needed to score goals,
Fraser cites career minor-leaguer Craig Fisher. In 1995-96, Fisher
scored an IHL- leading 74 goals for the Orlando Solar Bears. ``He
was a soft guy, not tough at all,'' Fraser said. ``But there was
nothing getting between him and the net. I've seen him get smoked
and his helmet go 20 feet in the air. But he kept at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can work on it, teach it and insist upon it. But a player
has to be willing to get into that position.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   A doctor confirmed Wednesday that defenseman Maxim Galanov needs
surgery on his broken left hand. It's expected that he will be
placed on injured reserve and be sidelined for about four weeks,
but he probably will seek a second opinion. Galanov started
experiencing pain after the first exhibition game, but doctors said
the injury might have occurred last season when he played for the
Pittsburgh Penguins.... Left winger Matt Johnson (groin) and
defensemen Petr Buzek (hip) and Yannick Tremblay (hip flexor)
missed practice Wednesday. Tremblay is questionable for Saturday's
game against Colorado, but Buzek and Johnson should be ready.
Because of the defensive shortage, Steve Staios skated on the blue
line.... The Thrashers are not going to change the scheduled
faceoff times for Saturday's game against Colorado or Oct. 31
against Ottawa, despite conflicts with the World Series. The
Halloween game could not be switched to the afternoon because
Ottawa plays in Florida the night before.... As projected, Vladimir
Vujtek, who is expected to be activated in time for Saturday's
game, skated on a line with Patrik Stefan and Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
