<SLUG> BC-IRS-CHARITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES GROCERY CHAIN CANNOT USE A TAX SHELTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tax court judge has ruled that Winn-Dixie Stores cannot deduct
interest paid on loans it took out on life insurance policies
covering 36,000 of its employees in 1993, throwing into doubt
several billion dollars of income tax deductions taken by hundreds
of major corporations since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Winn-Dixie's corporate-owned life insurance program is ``a sham
for tax purposes,'' Judge Robert P. Ruwe wrote in a strongly worded
81-page opinion reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of big corporations have taken out life insurance
policies on all their workers and then borrowed back the premiums,
creating an income tax deduction for the interest expense. The
companies said the deduction helped pay for life insurance benefits
for their workers. In 1996, Congress outlawed the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Winn-Dixie said it ``followed the letter of the law'' in
designing its program and would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case, the latest in a string of victories by the Internal
Revenue Service against corporate tax shelters, is significant
because many similar programs are more aggressive than
Winn-Dixie's.
</P>
<P>
   Winn-Dixie, which operates nearly 1,200 grocery stores in 14
states, took out life insurance policies on 36,000 of its 109,000
workers and then borrowed the cash value of the policies at more
than 11 percent interest, taking a $3.7 million tax deduction for
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Henke, a lawyer with Vinson &AMP; Elkins in Washington
who represented Winn-Dixie, said that ``if the judge finds that
this is a sham, then all of these things are shams,'' because ``we
spent a lot of time at trial attempting to show the judge that the
Winn-Dixie program was very middle of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an aggressive policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Henke said his client ``threaded the statutory needle'' in
designing its plan and that it served a legitimate business purpose
of helping pay for employee benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision,'' Henke said, ``runs roughshod over a long
history of congressional actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruwe relied heavily on internal company documents in finding
that the program was a sham meant solely to generate tax
deductions. He reproduced a chart that showed money flowing from
the IRS to Winn-Dixie and then flowing in a circle between
Winn-Dixie and the American Heritage Life Insurance Co., a unit of
the American Heritage Life Investment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also quoted at length from internal memos that said so
few employees died before quitting or retiring that ``the cost of
providing the benefit is insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disappointing opinion that the judge painted with a
broad brush'' that will affect many other companies, said Lawrence
M. Hill, a tax specialist at White &AMP; Case in Manhattan, who has a
similar case in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas P. Ochsenschlager, a tax partner with the Grant Thornton
accounting firm in Washington, said that ``this was a very popular
shelter, but a lot of us wondered why it wasn't challenged before
this.'' He added, ``The IRS already has the tools it needs to deal
with all the crazy schemes out there, and they never seem to use
those tools, but maybe that is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months the IRS has won cases against Compaq Computer,
United Parcel Service and other companies. Ochsenschlager said this
suggested there was no need for Congress to pass broad new
authority for the IRS to challenge corporate tax shelters, as the
Clinton administration has requested.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
