<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barcelona first to reach Champions quarterfinals
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The legendary _ and notoriously crabby _ Johan Cruyff
says he isn't watching the first group round of the European
Champions League because it is ``decaffeinated.''
</P>
<P>
   The new, but not necessarily improved Champions League, which
has gone from 24 to 32 teams this season, has drawn complaints from
players, coaches and international soccer officials, as the global
calendar grows increasingly unwieldy.
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth match day of Champions League play concluded
Wednesday, only Barcelona, the defending Spanish champions, had
clinched a spot in the quarterfinal round that begins next month.
</P>
<P>
   Barca's deep, flexible lineup has remained injury-free, unlike
some of the other leading European powers, and has been disciplined
in avoiding cards and suspensions. In tough Group B, Barca routed
Arsenal 4-2 in London on Tuesday, getting goals from Rivaldo on a
penalty kick and Luis Enrique a minute apart in the first half to
set the tone. Next week's showdown between Arsenal and Fiorentina,
a 3-0 winner over AIK Stockholm, should determine the other
qualifier from that group.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Manchester United, which has struggled in the
past month, had its 19-match Champions League unbeaten streak
snapped Tuesday in a 1-0 loss to Olympique Marseille in Group D.
Next week's United match at Croatia Zagreb is crucial for its
advancement hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid thrashed Porto three weeks ago, but the Portuguese
champions, playing at home, held on for a 2-1 win on two goals from
Mario Jardel to take the lead in Group E. AC Milan dropped a 1-0
decision on Hertha Berlin, which now leads Group H. Right behind is
enigmatic Chelsea, which throttled Galatasaray 5-0 in Istanbul on
Wednesday as Tore Andre Flo had two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is on the verge of advancing from Group A after soundly
defeating Slovenian side Maribor 2-0. In Group F, Rangers grabbed
the lead with a 4-1 win over PSV Eindhoven as Dutchman Michael Mols
had two goals. Valencia and Bayern Munich played to a 1-1 draw in
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND: SUNDERLAND GOES THIRD
</P>
<P>
   A goal in the 80th minute by Premier League scoring leader Kevin
Phillips lifted Sunderland to a 2-1 win over Aston Villa on Monday
and into third place, a point behind Manchester United and two
behind Arsenal. ITALY: INTER SUFFERS FIRST LOSS
</P>
<P>
   A goal by Venezia's Filippo Moriero was enough to hand Inter
Milan its first loss of the season in a 1-0 surprise on Sunday.
Lazio took a slim Serie A lead with a 3-0 win over Udinese....
Zinedine Zidane's first goal in 10 months, on a free kick, lifted
Juventus to a 1-0 win over AS Roma, which lost for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: BAYERN THRASHES HERTHA
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich chased away some demons in destroying Hertha
Berlin 3-1 in its best Bundesliga outing of the season. Paulo
Sergio had two goals and Giovanne Elber, who signed a long-term
contract extension, had the other. The club also has dropped
troubled Mario Basler and Sven Scheuer from the active roster after
they got into a fight at a Munich restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BARCA DRAWS TWICE
</P>
<P>
   Newly promoted Numancia got its best result of the Primera
Division season when Pachete scored the tying goal in the final
moments of injury time in a 3-3 draw with Barcelona. The defending
champions also missed out on three points last week when Real
Madrid's Raul scored a late equalizer to salvage an electrifying
2-2 draw at the Nou Camp.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TOLUCA WIDENS LEAD
</P>
<P>
   While three of the four group races in the Torneo Invierno
appear to be up for grabs through the end of the season, Toluca
took a big step last week toward wrapping up a playoff spot. The
defending Verano season champions routed hapless Leon 5-2 on Sunday
as Carlos Maria Morales had two goals. Toluca, which has 25 points
in Group 1, has a comfortable 11-point lead. Second-place UAG was
routed 4-0 by Club America as Cuauhtemoc Blanco, Pavel Pardo and
Fabian Estay had goals.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AMERICA: RIVER DUMPS BOCA
</P>
<P>
   Two goals by Pablo Aimar fueled River Plate to a 2-0 win over
Buenos Aires rival Boca Juniors on Sunday in the ``El Classico''
grudge match as the victors took over first place in the Apertura
season.... Penarol defeated Montevideo rival Nacional 2-1 on Sunday
to win the Uruguayan Clausura season and set up a two-leg matchup
between the two clubs to determine the overall champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
