<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3357 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-NLCS-DRAMA21-COX     10-20 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-DRAMA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A series for the ages
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They shall be known, simply and forevermore, as the
Fall Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, when you're awfully low, when the world is cold, you
will feel a glow just thinking of them. Games 5 and 6 of the 1999
National League Championship Series. The Fall Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Years from now, you'll gather the grandkids at your knee and
begin: ``Back in '99, just before the turn of the millennium, in
quaint old ballparks without retractable roofs, the Braves and Mets
played the most remarkable series of games you ever saw. And those
last two games? Well, folks just called 'em the Fall Classics.''
</P>
<P>
   Two games in two cities. Two games spread over three days that
spilled into the wee hours of a fourth. Two games that lasted
nearly three games, two extra-inning games totaling 26 innings and
untold tension and drama, heartache and gallantry, improbable
heroism and rain, lots of rain. Two games that each concluded in
the most implausible manner, one leaving the Mets high, if not dry;
the second prompting Dixie delirium and this Internet headline:
``Subway Series? No thanks, we'll walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Saturday night awaits a Braves-Yankees '96 redux and the
first World Series game at Turner Field, take a moment and look
back in wonder: The Fall Classics, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   GAME 5
</P>
<P>
   It took the Mets three batters to score twice off Greg Maddux.
It would be another 14 innings before they'd score again. By then,
Mets coach Mookie Wilson was recalling his playing days. This day:
Oct. 15, 1986, when the Mets and Houston went 16 innings in the
Astrodome in Game 6 of that NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   In '86, the Mets scored three runs in the ninth to force extra
innings; once in the 14th, only to see Billy Hatcher homer in the
bottom half; and finally three more times in the 16th, only to see
Houston score two before Jesse Orosco saved the longest day and the
NL pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday in Shea, though, proved even longer, if an inning
shorter. The longest postseason game in major-league baseball
history lasted 5 hours, 46 minutes. What began in late-afternoon
sunshine ended in a dark-of-the-night downpour, courtesy of a
baseball rarity: A grand-slam single.
</P>
<P>
   When Robin Ventura, just 1-for-18 in the NLCS after starting out
0-for-16, launched Kevin McGlinchy's pitch over the right-center
field wall, the Mets had staved off elimination for a second
consecutive game. This was far more dramatic than Game 4; Atlanta,
somnolent all that day, had taken a 2-1 eighth-inning lead Saturday
on back-to-back homers by Brian Jordan and Ryan Klesko, only to see
John Olerud's two-out, two-run single in the bottom half glance off
the diving Ozzie Guillen's glove for a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that paled beside Ventura's Sunday best. Never mind that
after Ventura rounded first base, Todd Pratt touched second, then
raced back to embrace Ventura and turned his grand slam into an RBI
single. Shea was electrified. The Braves, mortified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were down coming back on the plane,'' said Braves
hitting coach Don Baylor. Atlanta _ chasing bad pitches all game
long _ left 19 runners on base, hitting 4-for-29 with men on base,
3-for-20 with men in scoring position. There was Maddux's failed
suicide squeeze-turned-double play in the sixth inning. In the
13th, Keith Lockhart was easily thrown out at the plate on Chipper
Jones' double. Even after Lockhart tripled home Walt Weiss in the
top of the 15th, the Mets rallied against the rookie McGlinchy, the
last guy left in Atlanta's bullpen on a day-night the teams used a
total of 45 players.
</P>
<P>
   After loading the bases and walking in the tying run, McGlinchy
gave up Ventura's blast. That gave the Mets the chance to become
the first team in big-league history to overcome an 0-3 deficit. It
also set the stage for perhaps the most riveting back-to-back games
in major-league postseason history. Or as Brian Hunter, who would
become one of Atlanta's many Game 6 heroes, said, ``The last two
games are probably the best two games in a long time.'' Perhaps
since Games 6 and 7 of the 1991 World Series, when Minnesota's
Kirby Puckett homered off Charlie Leibrandt in the 11th to force a
Game 7. Then John Smoltz matched zeroes with Jack Morris before
Gene Larkin's pinch single in the 10th gave the Twins a 1-0 win and
the title.
</P>
<P>
   GAME 6
</P>
<P>
   This looked easy. Al Leiter hit two of the first three men he
faced, got no one out and the Braves scored five times in the first
inning for a 5-0 lead. Easy, right? Look again. The Mets got three
runs off Kevin Millwood in the sixth before the Braves' first
unlikely hero surfaced in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Hernandez, who lost his starting shortstop job after Game 3
of the Division Series, stroked a two-out, two-run pinch single in
the bottom half. But when Mike Piazza completed a four-run uprising
in the seventh with a two-run homer off Smoltz, it was tied 7-7.
When Melvin Mora's pinch single put New York up 8-7 in the eighth,
more Atlanta heroes emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez, voted the MVP of the NCLS after hitting .500
(10-for-20) with two homers and five RBIs, singled off John Franco.
Enter Otis Nixon, the pinch runner who is 40 years old, looks 60
facially but ran like 20 in stealing second and taking third on
Piazza's throwing error. Nixon scored on Hunter's single, his first
hit of the entire postseason.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets took a 9-8 lead in the 10th, Andruw Jones led off
with a single and advanced on pinch hitter Ryan Klesko's one-out
walk. Enter Guillen, who at 35 has lost a step but not his ability
to hit a fastball. Even the blazing fastball of Mets closer Armando
Benitez, who'd allowed just one Atlanta baserunner all year in 10
2/3 innings of relief. Guillen drilled a single to right to tie it.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th? Heavenly after Williams _ 1 for his previous 21 _ made
an adjustment, waiting long enough to pull an 0-2 off-speed pitch
from Kenny Rogers for a double. As Bret Boone's sacrifice moved
Williams to third and Chipper Jones came to the plate, Baylor was
already thinking three batters ahead and talking in Andruw Jones'
ear.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor knew the Mets would intentionally walk Chipper Jones,
``and I knew they wouldn't pitch to Brian Jordan.'' That left
Andruw Jones. ``Uh-oh,'' Baylor thought, ``my impatient young
hitter, they're going to give him a chance to win the ballgame for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did, walking Jordan to load the bases with one out. By
then, Baylor had already told Andruw Jones what he'd been preaching
in the batting cage all year and earlier that night: ``Just relax,
take a deep breath, be selective and get a good ball to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jones, the most impatient Atlanta hitter, found himself
ahead 2-0 in the count, then 3-1, and showed some restraint. Then
the count ran full and Rogers made his 3-2 delivery. ``Usually,''
Baylor recalled later, ``Andruw swings at that pitch _ five feet
outside!'' And Baylor grinned, chuckling. When Jones took ball
four, Williams safely touched home plate (``I just wanted to make
sure I didn't take wings,'' he later said), Jones reached first and
52,335, the largest crowd in Turner Field history, went berserk one
last time. ``Well,'' Braves president Stan Kasten said later in the
clubhouse afterglow, ``baseball got what it wanted.'' Perhaps. If
not an all-New York Subway Series, then a Braves-Yankees World
Series for validation as the Team of the '90s. But whatever that
outcome, we've already got something to treasure forever: The Fall
Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
