<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MINORITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES TRADE ACCUSATIONS OVER RACE AND NOMINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., S.D., N.C., Mo., Texas)  (mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two political parties traded angry accusations
over race and nominations Wednesday after the Democratic leader of
the Senate accused Republicans of demonstrating an ``array of
anti-minority sentiment'' in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leader, Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, said
the Republicans had shown a ``pattern'' of insensitivity to
minorities, and called on Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the chairman of
the Foreign Relations Committee, to show a ``change of heart'' over
President Clinton's nomination of Carol Moseley-Braun as ambassador
to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., who had been the first black woman
elected to the Senate, lost her re-election bid last November.
Helms, who has had run-ins with her in the Senate, made clear this
week that she would not have an easy confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The array of anti-minority sentiment expressed almost each
week now by Republicans is historic,'' Daschle said at his weekly
Capitol news conference. ``I have never seen a party become this
defiant when it comes to protecting minority rights in my time in
public life.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader,
shot back by recalling the Senate confirmation hearings, when the
Democrats were in the majority, in which Anita Hill accused
Clarence Thomas of sexual harassment. The spokesman, John
Czwartacki, echoing a phrase Thomas had used, said he found
Daschle's remarks ``ironic'' coming from a member of a political
party that he said ``attempted a high-tech lynching of the Supreme
Court's only African-American justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitter exchanges escalated the political warfare over
Clinton's nomination earlier this month of Moseley-Braun. Helms,
who as head of the powerful Senate Foreign Relations Committee has
stopped the appointments of other high-profile diplomatic nominees,
said this week, ``This nomination comes o the Senate with an
ethical cloud hanging over Ms. Moseley-Braun.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges also came at a time when both parties recognize
minorities as a crucial voting bloc. Black voters turned out in
record numbers in some areas last November, helping Democrats win
some House seats as well as the governorship of South Carolina.
Hispanic voters helped Democrats in California and were considered
crucial to the coalition that propelled Gov. George W. Bush, now
the Republican Party's front-running presidential contender, to
re-election in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Helms this week attributed his reservations about Moseley-Braun
to ethical questions. In a statement criticizing her actions as a
senator, he went on to wonder ``if the president and his associates
even examined her record before submitting it to the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   During her failed re-election bid last year, Moseley-Braun was
heavily criticized for her 1996 meetings with the former Nigerian
dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha, and dogged by accusations _ never
proved _ that she used 1993 campaign money to pay for personal
luxuries. She was defeated by Peter Fitzgerald, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But Helms also suggested to a reporter for Roll Call, a
newspaper that covers Congress, that Moseley-Braun should apologize
for a battle with him in 1993 in which she defeated Helms' proposal
to grant the United Daughters of the Confederacy a renewed patent
on an emblem featuring the Confederate battle flag. She called the
flag an emblem of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Daschle sought to put the nomination battle in a
larger context. He cited the Senate's recent party-line vote
rejecting Ronnie White, a black judge on Missouri's state Supreme
Court, for a federal judgeship, and its three-year stall on taking
up Clinton's nomination of Richard Paez, who is Hispanic, to the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   He also mentioned the dispute between Sen. Phil Gramm, R- Texas,
and Clinton over the Community Reinvestment Act, a 1977 law
intended to eradicate discrimination in lending. The dispute has
been stalling legislation to overhaul the nation's financial
system. Gramm has urged changes in the act, calling it burdensome
on small financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter whether he was saying that Senate
Republicans are racist, Daschle said, ``I'm not calling them
racist.'' But he went on to say ``it raises some ve2y serious
questions about the perception, the attitude of some on the other
side when it comes to minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made similar comments after the Senate's rejection of
the nomination of White, saying the action was ``strong evidence
for those who believe that the Senate treats minority and women
appointees unequally.'' Republicans said White, the first black
judge on Missouri's state Supreme Court, was insufficiently
supportive of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Czwartacki indicated Wednesday that Lott would not interfere
with Helms. And he noted that the Senate had recently approved
three judges. He asked: ``Are we being asked to go back and catalog
and identify everyone's race, religion or ethnic background? I
mean, there's a term for that. It's called racial profiling. I
thought we were all trying to get away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms on Wednesday referred reporters back to his earlier
statement raising questions about Moseley-Braun's ethics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
