<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL EXCEEDS EXPECTATIONS; AGREES TO INVEST IN A PC MAKER
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expanding its growing domain into the PC market, America Online
punctuated a stronger than expected earnings report Wednesday by
announcing it would invest $800 million in Gateway Inc., taking a 5
percent stake in the maker of consumer computers.
</P>
<P>
   The investment will be made over two years and will be paid for
in part with $180 million in America Online stock. In return,
Gateway will offer America Online membership to new PC customers.
</P>
<P>
   Many computer makers already bundle America Online with all
their new machines. But the marriage goes far deeper than those
agreements. As part of the deal, Gateway will move the 600,000
subscribers of its own Internet access service, Gateway.net, to the
America Online network, in effect putting two competing services
onto the same network infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, AOL, already the world's largest Internet service
provider, or ISP, will handle all network operations, billing and
customer service functions, Gateway officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway said it would commit $85 million to market its products
on AOL and would market AOL's products and services in nearly 200
Gateway retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   News of the deal was released as the online service reported net
income of $184 million, or 15 cents a share on a diluted basis. The
results exceeded analysts projections of 13 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced its earnings after the close of the
regular trading day which ended with the shares at $118, a rise of
$2.75, on the New York Stock Exchange. In after-hours trading, the
shares fell slightly.
</P>
<P>
   In separate conference calls with reporters, American Online and
Gateway asserted that their deal represented an inevitable
convergence of hardware makers and Internet providers. For example,
they said they planned to use the partnership to pursue development
of and deploy high-speed Internet technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Weitzen, president and Chief Operating Office of Gateway,
said the deal with the world's largest Internet access provider did
not amount to an admission of failure for Gateway.net. He said the
service had added 200,000 subscribers this quarter, equal to the
growth it had last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He sought to differentiate Gateway's Internet offering, which is
more of a direct pipeline to the Internet, from America Online,
which offers more proprietary content, including chat rooms, news
services and shopping channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL is more of a mass-market pre-packaged service,'' he said.
``Gateway.net is a more personalized service.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts said the deal had the markings of
throwing in the towel on Gateway.net, despite its seemingly healthy
growth in recent quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about it,'' said Bran C. Oakes, senor Internet
analyst with Lehman Brothers, ``it sounds like Gateway is saying,
`We gave it a good run. Let's do a good deal and get out of the ISP
business,'''
</P>
<P>
   This is the largest investment by AOL in a PC maker, but it is
hardly a unique strategy, and the company has made substantial
investments in other hardware companies. For instance, it invested
$1.5 billion in Hughes Electronics, the General Motors unit that
makes satellite receivers and direct television.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Robert Pittman, the president of American
Online, said the latest deal showed the clear convergence of PC
makers and the Internet industry. ``The big reason people are
buying computers is so they can go online,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   American Online's earnings report underscored the fact that it
knows something about consumers' rush to get online. Continuing its
unmatched growth, the company reported that it added 1.1 million
subscribers worldwide in its first fiscal quarter, which ended
Sept. 30, for a total of more than 18 million. Its subsdiary
Compuserve, has 2.2 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   America Online attributed the growth in revenues and profits to
strong performance in several of its brands, _ including the online
service itself, the ICQ chat service and its subsidiary Compuserve
_ and in particular to a continued growth in revenue from
advertising and electronic commerce transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The company said revenue from advertising, e-commerce and other
non-subscription based revenue rose to $350 million, compared with
$175 million in the same quarter a year ago. Its quarterly
subscription revenues rose to $995 million, compared with $723
million for the first fiscal quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   The growth came amid a period in which there were increasing
competitive pressures on AOL. Growth in low-cost services,
including free ISPs and broadband access, notably cable modem
services.
</P>
<P>
   And there was some concern that AOL would face competition from
itself, in the form of its subsidiary, Compuserve, which it has
marketed aggressively in the last several months.
</P>
<P>
   And there was some concern that AOL would face competition from
itself, in the form of its subsidiary, Compuserve, which it has
marketed aggressively in the last several months.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said AOL could cannibalize its namesake service by
making Compuserve too attractive. But company officials argued
Wednesday that the growth in both Compuserve and America Online
showed that those fears had not been borne out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're cannibalizing anything, it's Earthlink and
Mindspring,'' said Oakes, the Lehman Brothers Analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Case, Chairman of AOL, said the earnings augur a bright
future for America Online, which was launched 10 years ago this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of progress in the decade,'' he said. ``But
most people still aren't connected, so the big opportunity during
the next decade is to make the transition to a connected society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
