<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES21-COX     10-20 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Start spreading the news
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just when the Braves' 1999 postseason story shouldn't
get any better, they get the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting off the New York Mets, one of the most stubborn
teams in baseball history, the Braves are headed to their first
World Series since 1996. And waiting for them are the Yankees, the
team responsible for the Braves' most brutal postseason experience,
in a decade loaded with them. In the '96 Series, the Yanks came
back from a 2-0 deficit to win the next four.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have had a hard time shaking those memories.
</P>
<P>
   During the Braves' wild 10-9 win in Game 6 of the National
League Championship Series on Tuesday night, Chipper Jones watched
in agony while the Mets laughed in the face of 5-0 and 7-3 Braves
leads. The Mets did to the Braves what nobody does: They made their
pitching look helpless. And Jones thought of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 4 of the World Series back in 1996,'' Jones said,
referring to the pivotal game, when Jim Leyritz homered off Mark
Wohlers. ``Give our guys a lot of credit. We didn't hang our
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves found new life against the Mets on game-tying RBI
hits by Brian Hunter and Ozzie Guillen. And by the time they scored
in the bottom of the 11th, they might have reminded any Yankees
watching of their own resilience.
</P>
<P>
   Former Yankee Gerald Williams doubled off another former Yankee
Kenny Rogers to lead off the 11th and was bunted to third by Bret
Boone. Intentional walks to Chipper Jones and Brian Jordan, nearly
a Yankee, brought up the one Brave no Yankee could ever forget _
Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones still is baby-faced, but he's a grown man compared with
the 19-year-old rookie who homered twice in his first two World
Series at-bats in 1996. Those hits made him just the second player
to accomplish that feat and also made him the youngest to hit a
home run in a World Series game.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, Jones has struggled with a tendency to swing
at breaking balls off the plate. But on Tuesday night, he showed
the utmost in discipline in drawing a bases-loaded walk to win the
game _ and bring the Braves and Yankees together again.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams are different now. The Yankees aren't the
formidable force that won a major-league record 125 games last year
and swept the Padres in a four-game World Series laugher. The
Braves are not the invincible pitching bastion with a loaded
power-hitting lineup. Both are scrappers, which should make this
World Series as intriguing as any.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the miracles all the other teams were having,
but we just hung in there,'' Yankees owner George Steinbrenner
said.
</P>
<P>
   This World Series will be the first in which the teams played
during the regular season. The Braves won two out of three
interleague games at Yankee Stadium right after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves did some unusual things to the Yankees in that
series. In their second consecutive win, 10-7 on July 16, the
Braves homered three times off the Yankees' Orlando ``El Duque''
Hernandez. Then, on a night when Greg Maddux was ineffective, the
Braves beat Yankees closer Mariano Rivera on a two-out, three-run
home run by Andruw Jones. Rivera, who allowed four runs that day,
has allowed only one run in the three months since. Jones' homer
was one of only two he allowed this year. The game also was the
last of his four blown saves and the third of his three losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've almost got the same starting rotation that we saw in
the series, and almost the same one as in '96 when we faced them in
the World Series,'' NLCS MVP Eddie Perez said. ``I don't know if
they're pitching different. I think we have to play better than we
did the last four games, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves avoided blowing a 3-0 lead in the NLCS and withstood
the Mets to earn this shot at the Yankees. But the way it happened
might give them reason to feel good about their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Chipper Jones said, ``we've got destiny on our
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
