<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3366 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-MEDIA_SFCHRON &LR;      10-20 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MEDIA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST  &HT;     Red Hat Plans Net Publication to Cover the Open Source 
 Phenomenon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
As the open source software Linux gives Microsoft's Windows
operating system its first real challenge, dozens of Web sites have
proliferated that are devoted to the movement.
<P>
   Now Red Hat, the North Carolina company that sells and supports
Linux operating systems, plans to start an online journalistic
venture devoted to authoritative coverage of the open source
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat has hired U.S. News and World Report's technology
correspondent Russ Mitchell, a veteran scribe who has served as a
Business Week bureau chief and managing editor of Wired magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is editor in chief of the company's Web site at
www.redhat.com and now is starting up a San Francisco Web
publication called Wide Open that will cover the open source
movement, which advocates giving away for free the computer code
for software like Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell and Red Hat say the site _ to debut early next month at
www.wideopen.com _ will be an independent look at all things open
source. If that means writing something flattering about a Red Hat
competitor, or negative about Red Hat, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, 45, admits that when Red Hat approached him, he found
the notion hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was skeptical at first of the idea that a company could or
would journalistically cover an industry that it's a part of,''
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   But when he went to North Carolina to meet with Red Hat chief
executive Bob Young and President Matthew Szulik, he was convinced
that their commitment to open source extended to journalistic
objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat's Web site is run out of an office on Folsom Street, and
Mitchell is one of four employees working on Wide Open. That number
could double as the site gets off the ground and starts updating
stories throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Although the site will be meant mostly for the information
technology managers who use programs like Linux, Mitchell also
hopes to draw in journalists, venture capitalists, lawyers and
economists. Mitchell plans a mix of features and analysis about
such topics as the legal and economic ramifications of open source.
</P>
<P>
   As with other journalists who have left their old media careers
for a new life on the Web, Mitchell said he wanted to be part of
the phenomenon, as well as to cover it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that the future of news is on the Web,''
Mitchell said. ``I've had other opportunities to get involved in
Web operations, but they didn't make sense because I couldn't
continue to do journalism. And this will allow me to maybe buy a
house in the Bay Area someday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MR. SPACEMAN: Former CNN ``Moneyline'' anchor Lou Dobbs, who left
one of the prime perches of financial journalism to become an
Internet entrepreneur, spoke to several hundred people this week in
San Francisco as part of the Internet Commerce Expo. In his talk on
economics and politics, Dobbs confessed to being a poor
prognosticator who forecast George Bush's resounding re-election as
president and who initially dismissed Ted Turner as a ``millionaire
drunken playboy.''
</P>
<P>
   He then offered his own predictions: The current economic
prosperity ``will continue unabated,'' and George W. Bush will win
election to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   More entertaining, however, were his tales of Turner, the
flamboyant founder of CNN and Dobbs' boss and friend for 19 years.
This year, even though Dobbs left the cable network to seek his
fortune running Space.com, a Web site devoted to space-related news
and entertainment, he still went to Turner's Montana ranch for an
annual fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted said, `This is kind of funny. You don't work for me any
more,''' Dobbs said. ``I said, `Yes, and I outrank you. I'm
chairman and CEO of Space.com. You're a lousy vice chairman of one
division.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the head of Time-Warner's CNN division, Turner is
still worth several billion dollars. But he played along. ``He
said, `I'm chairman _ of the Turner Foundation,''' Dobbs said. ``I
said, `Yeah, but that's a nonprofit.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `So's Space.com.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BIG GAMES: Computec Media will launch two splashy computer game
magazines next week, part of a $20 million effort by the German
company to invade a U.S. market dominated by Ziff-Davis, Imagine
Media and IDG.
</P>
<P>
   Incite Video Games and Incite PC Games, both published in San
Francisco, aim to break the mold of traditional gamer mags by
selling for low prices and by appealing to the casual gamer.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, said Computec CEO Torsten Oppermann, magazines in
this space aim for the hard-core gamers and sell for $5 or more.
Incite Video Games will sell for a mere 99 cents at first, going up
only to $1.99, while the PC pub, which comes with a CD-ROM, starts
at $1.99 and will be hiked to $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   Incite's covers will feature celebrities for a dose of ``real
humans, not computer graphics,'' Oppermann said.
</P>
<P>
   Oppermann hopes to produce magazines that people would be proud
to leave out on their coffee tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read any old gaming magazine, you are characterized as
a nerd,'' Oppermann said. ``You don't need to be embarrassed if you
play games and read our magazine in public.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazines will start with more than 80 pages of advertising
each and will guarantee advertisers a reach of more than 400,000
readers. But with Oppermann claiming that 75,000 retail outlets
already have agreed to carry the magazines, he plans a circulation
that will top 1.3 million copies on each.
</P>
<P>
   Computec, a 10-year-old firm that went public last year in
Frankfurt, has a five-year lease at Eighth and Townsend streets in
San Francisco, where it now employs 75 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the magazine business, you have to be in it for the long
term,'' Oppermann said. ``We are here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com, call (415) 777-6004 or
fax (415) 543-2482.
</P>
