<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC RESTRICTS WEB DEALINGS WITH YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With advertisers eyeing the growing multibillion
dollar children's market, the government Wednesday issued new rules
that companies must follow to solicit personal information from
Internet users under 13 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, expected to change the way hundreds of Web sites
operate, were prompted by reports in recent years that companies
were asking children to reveal personal details before allowing
them to participate in on-line contests or games.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the Federal Trade Commission complained that a
Boston money management firm sought information about family
finances from children and said the data would be retained
anonymously. In fact, the FTC said, the company kept the names and
addresses of the children along with their responses.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses can use personal information to fashion
advertisements that appeal to specific audiences and then, through
the unique medium of the Internet, present the ads to those groups
by e-mail or on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   While many companies changed some of their most aggressive
practices after regulators intervened, Congress last year issued
new rules for soliciting information from children and asked the
Federal Trade Commission to set specific requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In the rules issued Wednesday, which take effect in April, the
FTC said that companies must ask for parental permission in many
cases before seeking information from children.
</P>
<P>
   When companies plan to make the information public through chat
rooms or other Internet activities, they must seek parental
permission by mail, fax, toll-free phone line or by electronic mail
message in which the parent attaches a digital signature or
password. Companies must also use these methods if they plan to
disclose the personal information to business partners. These
methods are considered more secure than merely asking a parent to
send approval by e-mail, which could be forged by a child.
</P>
<P>
   When companies seek personal information for internal use to
market products and services to children via e-mail, they may ask a
parent to send an e-mail giving consent. The company must send its
own e-mail to the parent, however, to confirm that consent was
given.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are not required to seek parental consent when
collecting limited information for certain Web activities, such as
one-time homework help. And companies may enter a child in a
contest or send an e-mail newsletter as long as the parent receives
notice and can prevent further use of the child's information.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer and business groups were generally enthusiastic about
the rules, though they were cautious about some provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, we are pleased,'' said Kathryn Montgomery, president
of the Center for Media Education, which had complained to the FTC
about some company practices. She said the government had acted
wisely to post rules early, while on-line marketing is still
developing as a business.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups had lobbied hard against the requirement that
they seek parental consent by phone, fax or mail, which they said
would be costly for Internet start-ups. But most said they were
generally happy with the FTC rules.
</P>
<P>
   The phone or mail requirement ``is going to be a sticking point
for some, but I think that marketers are going to be able to live
with it _ not without some effort,'' said Hal Shoup of the American
Association of Advertising Agencies. ``But nonetheless, given the
complexity of the issues, what has been worked out here is on
balance quite good.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups said they had concerns about a provision that
allows schools to act on behalf of parents in giving consent for
companies to seek personal information from children.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that rules were released on the same day as the
initial public stock offering of ZapMe!, a company that provides
free computers and an online service to schools in return for the
right to post Web ads. Some consumer advocates cautioned that
schools were essentially allowing companies to set up shopping
malls in the classroom through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The computer can become ``a surveillance device that collects
information and exposes (students) to extremely targeted and
intrusive advertising,'' said Jason Catlett, president of
Junkbusters Corp., which offers products to filter unwanted postal
mail, e-mail and telemarketing calls.
</P>
<P>
   Catlett said that schools that are eager to receive free
computers might not properly guard students' privacy. ``Parents
shouldn't assume that schools are looking out for the privacy
concerns of their children . . . . We don't think the school is
necessarily on the side of your kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ZapMe!, based near San Francisco, has been called a computer
equivalent of the Channel One Network, which gives free television
equipment to schools that agree to show a daily 12-minute broadcast
that includes advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokeswoman said ZapMe! was in a ``quiet period''
because of the stock offering and could not comment on the FTC
rules.
</P>
<P>
   According to information provided by the company, the content it
offers through its on-line service is targeted at students aged
13-19, while the new FTC rules cover Web sites that market to
children under age 13. However, the company also says its free
computers are available for kindergarten through grade 12.
</P>
<P>
   Students can sign up for e-mail accounts and are asked only for
their gender, age and zip code, according to information provided
by the company. But the company's web site does not say whether it
monitors how students use the computers and which Web sites they
favor, and whether it will share that information with other
companies. Computers have been installed in about 230 schools, and
6,000 others have asked to participate.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said it would review its parental consent rules in 18
months and might make changes to account for new technology.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the parental consent provisions, the FTC said
that Web sites aimed at children must post a ``clear and
prominent'' link to the company's privacy policy on its home page
and at each area where personal information is collected.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are already barred from soliciting more information
than necessary for a child to join an online contest or game. That
provision was included in a 1998 law, called the Children's Online
Privacy Protection Act, which also required the FTC to flesh out
the privacy rules.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston privacy case, the FTC last May settled a complaint
against Liberty Financial Companies Inc., an asset management
company and operator of the Young Investor site. The company
admitted no wrongdoing and said it did not use or resell any of the
information it collected. It agreed to post a clear privacy policy
and to seek parental consent before soliciting information from
children.
</P>
<P>
   Companies appear to be disclosing more about their privacy
policies. Nearly 66 percent of companies online tell customers how
they use personal information, according to Georgetown University
study. That compares to 14 percent in an FTC study a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-IBOOK-IBOOK_SFCHRON &LR;      10-20 1733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBOOK-IBOOK </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Checking Out Apple's New iBook  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The iBook, Apple's curvy and colorful new notebook computer, has
been compared to everything from a Creamsicle to a toilet seat and
lid. It's also been called a ``people magnet'' and ``almost a
sensuous object of desire.''
<P>
   Most of the buzz has been about the $1,599 machine's design,
which is every bit as distinctive among laptops as the iMac was on
the desktop _ and even more controversial because some complain
that it looks like a ``girly computer.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the theory that you can't judge an iBook by its cover,
I'll steer clear of such debates. Instead, I'll focus on what the
iBook is and isn't good for, based on my experience using it daily
for the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In general, with one important qualification and a few
additional cautions, I think it's a terrific computer for the
purposes for which it mainly was designed. Just make sure your
needs match its talents and pay attention to the caveats, or you'll
be sorry.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the components that differentiate great laptops from
also-rans _ the screen, the keyboard and the battery _ the iBook is
a clear winner:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; The screen.  &LR; It measures 12.1 inches diagonally, which is
relatively modest compared with many competitors. But it displays
an ample 800 by 600 pixels, and it's as bright and crisp as they
come; to my eye, it's better than most desktop monitors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; _The keyboard.  &LR; It's made of white plastic and is pleasant to work
at. The main keys are full-size, and the wrist rests are generous
and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; _The battery &LR; . According to Apple, it can keep the device working
for ``up to six hours.'' That's more than twice the industry norm.
In real life, your mileage will vary depending on how you use the
machine, but in my testing, I frequently got more than five hours
per charge.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason the battery lasts so long is that the machine
goes into power-saving mode whenever it's been idling for ``a
substantial period of time (a half second or so),'' as the
technical documentation for the machine puts it.
</P>
<P>
   It also automatically goes into a deep and silent sleep whenever
you close its clamshell case. In that state, it draws fewer than 7
watts of power, compared with 5 watts when it's completely shut
down but still plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're worried about that 2-watt differential, that means
you never have to shut down at all. The big advantage: When you
lift the lid again, you're right back where you left off in about
15 seconds, without having to wait for the minute or two it takes
to boot up from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   As exceptional as the iBook is with these sensitive components,
it's anything but outstanding with respect to some more mundane
ones.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the hard disk has a capacity of only 3.2
gigabytes. Today's software eats gigabytes for breakfast, and 3.2
of them won't last long _ especially if you get into collecting MP3
digital-audio cuts or QuickTime movies.
</P>
<P>
   A worse problem is that the iBook comes with only 32 megabytes
of RAM. That may sound like a lot, but Apple's operating system
grabs most of it _ about 28 megabytes _ before you even have a
chance to launch a program. With so little memory free, the iBook
has to depend on ``virtual memory'' _ a technique that fools the
system into using some hard disk space as if it were RAM. Apple
configures it to give the machine an effective memory of 64
megabytes, but you pay a severe performance penalty because drives,
even fast ones, are always much slower than real RAM. When I first
hooked the iBook up to the Internet, I was struck immediately by
how sluggish it felt downloading even routine pages.
</P>
<P>
   To check my impression, I fired up my Windows 95 laptop, a
2-year-old Fujitsu model with a lowly 150-megahertz Pentium chip
but 48 megabytes of memory. Stopwatch in hand, I timed how long it
took Internet Explorer on each machine to connect to 15
representative Web sites, including Apple's own home page, online
store and QuickTime site.
</P>
<P>
   Results: The Fujitsu took a total of 81.1 seconds, or an average
of 5.4 seconds per site, while the iBook needed 190.6 seconds in
all, or 12.7 on average.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even though Apple calls the iBook ``the
second-fastest notebook in the world'' (after the PowerBook G3,
naturally) and says it was designed specifically for Internet
access, my ancient PC laptop ran rings around it on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   After totaling up those results, I appealed to Apple to lend me
some extra memory for testing. They sent up another 32 megabytes,
which I installed myself with only a minimum of grief. Then I redid
my tests, without in any other way reconfiguring the system. This
time, the iBook needed only 75.1 seconds in all to download the
same 15 pages, or an average of just 5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of the story is clear: With only 32 megabytes of RAM _
the only configuration Apple offers _ the iBook is a crippled
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the company should make 64 megabytes standard, as it
did in its revamped iMac models. Because the company chose not to
do so _ ``We had a price point to hit,'' a senior executive
explained _ you'll have to do it yourself, or get your dealer to do
it or keep living with the World Wide Wait.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the ever-volatile price of RAM has risen sharply
of late. An extra 32 megabytes today likely will cost you between
$130 and $200 extra; an extra 64 megabytes, which I'd recommend,
will set you back $200 to $300.
</P>
<P>
   Before you plunk down the cash, though, consider some of the
iBook's other limitations:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; _Size and weight.  &LR; The iBook is pretty big and pretty heavy to
carry around. Not that it's much different from most comparably
priced Windows notebooks marketed to consumers _ IBM's latest
consumer ThinkPads are a shade smaller but weigh even more (7.7 to
7.8 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   Still, as I can attest from carrying the iBook back and forth
between home and The Chronicle for the past few weeks _ by foot and
by BART _ 6.6 pounds, on top of my usual load, is a lot to haul
around.
</P>
<P>
   As for air travel, even if I were willing to cart it through the
airport, I don't think one could even open it on an airline tray,
at least not in coach class. Apple's marketing materials say the
machine ``was born to travel,'' but they must mean by car.
</P>
<P>
   Another note about the size issue: Apple made the machine's
footprint on the desktop even larger than necessary by putting all
of its ports and the power connector on the sides rather than in
back, apparently to leave the rear clear for the handle.
Personally, I'd much rather have the cables out of sight behind the
screen, rather than dangling from both sides like an unruly mane.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; _Limited expandability.  &LR; In the name of simplifying and modernizing
the Mac architecture, Apple has eliminated the serial,
keyboard-and-mouse and SCSI ports that were standard on its old
models.
</P>
<P>
   They even omitted a microphone jack, spoiling my plan to try out
video-conferencing with my iMac-equipped daughter in college, and a
video-out port for connecting to a larger display or projection
system _ a significant deficiency, I should think, in one of its
target markets, K-12 classrooms. And unlike almost every other
notebook today, the iBook lacks a slot for plugging in the
credit-card-size add-ons known as PC Cards.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, it's true, as Apple argues, that most PC Card slots
are used for modems or network adapters, and the iBook has both a
56K modem and a fast Ethernet connector built in. But those who
might like to add something else are out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, you can find the features you'd like to add in
the form of an external device you can connect to the iBook's
Universal Serial Bus port. Recent months have brought a rising tide
of USB products, including printers, scanners, video-capture
devices, Zip drives, CD-ROM burners, pocket-size MP3 music players
and lots more. Many of these products work on Macs as well as PCs.
</P>
<P>
   USB was designed to handle up to 127 devices simultaneously, but
you need ports to plug them into. Unfortunately, Apple cut another
corner by giving the iBook only one port. If you use it for your
printer (or for an adapter connected to an older printer) and then
you decide to add, say, a Zip or floppy drive, which Apple doesn't
offer even as an optional extra, you'll have to purchase a USB hub
with extra ports.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that these hubs aren't expensive _ they start
at $35 or so _ and they couldn't be easier to set up. But
considering that Apple, by removing all other expansion connectors,
put so much weight on USB, it could at least have provided a pair
of these ports.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ledger, the iBook has one other
important feature I haven't mentioned yet: support for wireless
networking. Sometime during the next few weeks, Apple will begin
selling its $99 AirPort card. Plug it into a special slot inside
the machine and you should be able to communicate at 11 megabits
per second _ faster, if only slightly, than the typical office
network _ over a distance of up to 150 feet without a wire
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'll need a similarly equipped device to
communicate with. Apple will sell an AirPort ``base station'' _ a
flying-saucer-shaped device equipped with its own modem and network
connector so that it can serve as a link to the Internet for up to
10 client machines with AirPort cards _ for $299.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also is building AirPort slots into all its
latest models, and any Mac that has both an AirPort card and a
modem or network connection, even another iBook, can function as a
base station for just the cost of the $99 card.
</P>
<P>
   The AirPort products aren't available yet, so I wasn't able to
test them. But if they perform as advertised, they'll give the
iBook a significant advantage over any other current laptop.
</P>
<P>
   With or without AirPort, the iBook is a great choice for many
settings _ for use in a dorm room or small apartment or in a
classroom, or for anyone who just enjoys surfing the Web in an easy
chair or catching up on work out on the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Just be sure its weight and its limited expandability won't
interfere with your plans for it.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to budget for that extra memory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
