<HEADLINE>
BOEING IN A DEAL TO DEVELOP MISSILES FOR EUROPEAN WARPLANES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Boeing Co. said Wednesday that it would join French
and British manufacturers to develop a sophisticated air-to-air
missile, opening a head-on competition with the Raytheon Co. to
supply at least $1.65 billion worth of missiles for a new
generation of European warplanes
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with the separate introduction Wednesday of a joint
missile company grouping the top military contractors in Britain,
France and Italy, the Boeing deal with British Aerospace PLC and
Aerospatiale Matra SA showed the dizzying pace of efforts to
streamline the military business as the arms market shrinks after
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The two deals were a further illustration of the crosscurrents
within the trans-Atlantic military industry as European companies
slowly coalesce.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Aerospatiale Matra announced a merger with
DaimlerChrysler AG of Germany that would make it the world's
third-largest aerospace and military company after Boeing and
Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In the missile businesses announced Wednesday, Aerospatiale
ended up as a partner of both Boeing and British Aerospace in the
development of the Meteor air-to-air missile for the Eurofighter _
a long-running venture between Britain, Germany, Italy and Spain to
build the Continent's own warplane. The British government has
ordered 232 of the 620 Eurofighters to be supplied to the countries
making the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, currently the world's third-largest military and
aerospace company and the dominant global missile maker, won U.S.
government endorsement last month for a bid to sell its own Amraam
missiles to Britain for its Eurofighters. While the contract for
missiles supplied to Britain is valued at $1.65 billion, the figure
could be much higher if other European air forces follow Britain's
lead in choosing air-to-air missiles. Alan Garwood, deputy chief
executive of Matra BAE Dynamics _ a joint missile venture owned by
Aerospatiale Matra and British Aerospace _ said the total value of
sales could reach $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever gets this, you are talking about lots and lots of
missiles,'' said Andrew Brooks, a military analyst with the
International Institute for Strategic Studies in London. ``It's big
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   European countries are desperately seeking to build their own
military identity to offset what they see as an embarrassing
dependence on far more advanced American military technology _
illustrated most recently in the high-technology air war over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's involvement in Europe's Meteor project thus ``muddies
the waters,'' Brooks said, `'and for that reason, Meteor will be
presented as a European solution.'' Garwood said the Meteor project
``is an opportunity to take Raytheon on its own back yard and score
a win for Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schlueter, a spokesman for Boeing's military operations,
said the company would provide expertise in low-cost manufacturing
and in integrating the systems linking the Meteor missile to the
Eurofighter. But it is not expected to take an equity stake in the
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, British Aerospace and Aerospatiale Matra announced a
link-up Wednesday with Finmeccanica of Italy intended to pool their
missile businesses, creating the world's second-largest missile
operation after Raytheon. ``This move is a natural development in
the consolidation of the European aerospace and defense industry,''
the three companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement added a further strand to the web of deals
linking European military and aerospace. Just this week,
Aerospatiale Matra and Marconi Electronics said that they planned
to form Europe's biggest space venture with DaimlerChrysler's
aerospace unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
