<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ADD GUARD DEPTH, SIGN SHAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brian Shaw's offseason has been dizzying to say
the least. And to make matters dizzier, now he has to learn the
triangle offense. He welcomes the vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw became the latest beneficiary of Kobe Bryant's hand injury
when the Los Angeles Lakers signed him to a one-year, partially
guaranteed deal Wednesday. If he makes the team, Shaw is eligible
to earn $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't figure to get this opportunity. The Lakers had scouted
Shaw in pickup games at UCLA last month but eventually signed Ron
Harper to add veteran depth to the backcourt. The door reopened for
Shaw when Bryant broke his right hand last week. Harper had to move
to Bryant's off-guard slot, leaving a gap behind Derek Fisher at
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big guard (6-foot-6) that has experience in this
league,'' coach Phil Jackson said of Shaw, 33. ``We think maybe he
can add something.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear if Shaw is just a temporary acquisition or a
longer-term role player. His signing increases the roster to 18
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how anybody's going to fit in until they come in
and play in this game,'' Jackson said. ``This is an opportunity for
us to get a player that has what we consider a valuable asset to
us, which is that he can play a big guard, he can originate an
offense, he reads defenses pretty well and he's got some speed.''
</P>
<P>
   If Shaw picks up the offense quickly, he could stick even after
Bryant returns. That would be a welcome bit of stability for the
10-year veteran. After playing for Portland last season, Shaw was
dealt to Houston as part of the package for Scottie Pippen. The
Rockets, stocked with guards, waived him the next day. That was
fine with Shaw, who wants to be closer to his 5-month-old son in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go too far away. This is a perfect
situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw played just one game for the Blazers last season. His
career averages are 8.2 points, 3.7 rebounds and 5.0 assists.
</P>
<P>
   __ Game on: The Lakers' light exhibition-game schedule just got
heavy. They will play the Miami Heat on Sunday at 1 p.m. in
Bakersfield, replacing the canceled Oct. 12 game in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   That makes five games in six days, a pace reminiscent of last
season's post-lockout schedule. After playing tonight and Friday in
the Lakers Shootout at the Forum, the Lakers will have Saturday
off, then play three in a row _ at Bakersfield, Albuquerque and Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad about the game,'' Jackson said. ``Three in a row,
we're not so glad about.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hot seat: Jackson didn't name names, but he was clearly
disappointed with the play of his second unit in Tuesday's victory
over Golden State. The reserves lost an early lead and generally
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some guys out there in the second unit that just
aren't giving us anything out there on the floor,'' Jackson said.
``They're veterans, they're just not playing well and it's just
unfortunate. They're teamed up with some kids that are looking for
some leadership; we're just not getting leadership in our second
unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks seemed to be aimed at reserve forwards Rick Fox and
Robert Horry. Fox finished with three points and three turnovers in
17 minutes. Horry had two points, five rebounds and a pair of
turnovers in 18 minutes, going 1 for 5 from the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
