A3374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MILLS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-20 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: DEVELOPER PROMOTES ITS MALLS AS DESTINATIONS FOR FUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Va., Texas, N.C., Fla.)   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The commercial depicts a suburban dad greasing a pig, then
setting him free in the living room for a fun, family chase.
</P>
<P>
   An ad for hog farming, perhaps? A spot for a new game?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the commercial, which is being broadcast this week in
the Houston area, advertises the grand opening of Mills Corp.'s
Katy Mills, a new kind of mall that mixes off-price retailing with
a heavy dose of interactive entertainment. The message is that Katy
Mills offers an exciting outing _ without the extreme of
pig-chasing.
</P>
<P>
   Call it ``shopper-tainment.'' But in a retail environment filled
with growing competition for shoppers from mail-order houses, home
shopping and e-commerce, real estate companies have been adding
entertainment-type businesses as featured attractions in the
nation's 1,800 enclosed malls.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, a real estate investment trust based in Arlington, Va.,
is credited with expanding the entertainment concept at malls,
creating something more like tourist destinations by blending
off-price shopping with high-technology amusements from arcades,
theme restaurants, interactive retailers and vast 24-to-30-screen
multiplex theatres.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the company is trying to explain the concept in two
30-second television spots from its agency, the Southfield, Mich.,
office of Doner that barely mentions shopping at all. Instead, it
promotes its newest malls as simply places to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign theme is also intended to give the 10 Mills malls
around the country a single, national brand image. All 10 Mills
malls will use the same ``total experience'' theme, though the
individual executions will differ. Combined, Mills' total budget
for the campaigned is about $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mills began adding many entertainment features to its malls in
1996, but this is the first time its campaign focuses strictly on
the Mills ``experience.'' Because the campaign is such a departure
from typical mall advertising, Mills tested the ads before the
introduction in Houston, and also ran tests in Charlotte, N.C.,
where they ran in September to open the Concord Mills mall there.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Lipscomb, group marketing vice president for Mills, said
the research found consumers by and large understood the message
that the malls offered a different shopping experience _ aside from
a few exceptions where viewers were left scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The wacky spots were even preferred over the old Mills campaign
that was humorous but with a more traditional shopping message, Ms.
Lipscomb said. ``Where consumers' heads are, I think, is that
people feel rushed, and they just want to have fun, to go and do
and not take life too seriously,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's second TV spot features friends wrapping
bubble-wrap around a Diane Keaton look-alike and then rolling her
down a hill through a sprinkler. Shopping isn't even mentioned
until the tagline, which is ``shop together, play together, eat
together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very deliberate,'' said John Parlota, executive vice
president at Doner. ``The idea is to give a sense of intrigue that
this is a new type of experience. This does not look like other
mall advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides evoking an experience, the ads are also intended to
``brand'' Mills properties. Other mall companies also branding
their properties with image campaigns include the Simon Property
Group _ the nation's largest owner-operator of malls _ and
Westfield Shopping Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Branding builds an image not only for consumers, but also for
Wall Street as many mall owners and developers have become public
companies, said Malachy Kavanagh, spokesman for the International
Council of Shopping Centers in New York. ``Malls that use branding
are attempting to build an identity,'' he said. ``It's no different
than, say, what the Gap does or other retail brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Establishing a unified national image may also help attract
marketing partners that are not traditional mall advertisers, like
big national name brands, Malachy said. Over the years, malls have
marketed themselves by selling brand signage, merchandising and
sponsorship opportunities. Simon Brand Ventures, for instance,
offers mall marketing programs and includes clients like Visa, AT&AMP;T
and Pepsi-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Besides 200-plus stores and an average of 1.5 million
square-feet of space, Mills shopping malls typically feature theme
restaurants like Rain Forest Cafe, which features food in a faux
jungle with mechanical butterflies; ``interactive'' retailers like
Bass Pro Shops Outdoor World where the shopper can try out all
manner of sports equipment before buying; and virtual-reality game
centers/restaurants like Dave &AMP; Busters that offer huge arcades and
games like simulated skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a large mall today that isn't incorporating some
elements of entertainment,'' Malachy said, ``but Mills has perhaps
taken it to a higher level _ everything in their center is geared
to entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   With entertainment such a large part of its experience, Ms.
Lipscomb said that the company's campaign relates more to tourism
than to traditional mall advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Mills centers draw from a broader geographical reach than the
typical mall, and often get tourists, she said. Some 40 percent of
the visitors to its Sawgrass Mills mall in Florida are tourists,
many of them from outside the United States. Indeed, Mills compares
its total number of visitors not to that of other malls, but to
other entertainment outlets like Disney amusement parks and Major
League Baseball attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a brand,'' Ms. Lipscomb said. ``The reason why people
shop regional malls? We're not those reasons. Their product
attributes are different from ours _ and for us, fun is way up
there on our product-attribute list.''
</P>
</TEXT>
