<SLUG> BC-NY-KLAN-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON IS UNLIKELY ALLY OF KLAN IN SUIT AGAINST CITY ON RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Amsterdam News, the largest black newspaper in
New York City, and the Rev. Al Sharpton said Wednesday that they
had each filed legal papers supporting the right of a Ku Klux Klan
group to demonstrate Saturday in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's publisher and Sharpton said they despised the
Klan's message, but also believed that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was
wrong to block the group from holding the rally, which is expected
to draw several dozen Klan members and hundreds of Klan opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The court filings come on the eve of a hearing set for Thursday
in U.S. District Court in Manhattan where two judges will consider
claims by the Klan and a group of opponents who will contend that
the Giuliani administration violated the Klan's First Amendment
rights by denying permission for the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, a lawyer for the city, Daniel Connolly, said of
the new filings in support of the Klan's First Amendment position:
``This is a case about balancing individuals' First Amendment
rights with the city's ability to maintain public order and protect
the rights of every citizen to freely and safely express
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Elinor Tatum, publisher and editor in chief of the Amsterdam
News, said her paper ``has stood up for the First Amendment rights
of several organizations,'' adding that ``if we did not stand up
for the Klan's right, we had no right to stand up for anybody
else's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's brief was filed in the name of the National Action
Network, a nonprofit group of which he is president. ``I feel
strongly that the Klan is a terrorist group,'' Sharpton said
Wednesday. ``But I feel just as strongly that the mayor should not
be allowed to use this group to suspend the constitutional rights
of others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
