<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-TEAM-OF-DECADE-HN     10-20 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TEAM-OF-DECADE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ This is the way baseball should end the 1900s _ with its
franchise of the ages battling its franchise of the decade for the
World Series championship.
<TEXT>
<P>
   To some, that would suggest the New York Yankees and the Atlanta
Braves will meet in the Fall Classic; to others, it means the
Yankees are battling themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves hold the distinction of being the Team of the '90s
based on their eight consecutive playoff appearances, five National
League pennants and 1995 World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   While those are certainly strong credentials, some might argue
the Yankees have a greater stake to the claim because they have won
the World Series twice this decade, a feat matched only by the
Toronto Blue Jays _ the last team to win back-to-back World Series
titles.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how the Blue Jays have struggled since their
early-'90s success, the Braves and Yankees clearly are at the top
of the heap. But which is the team of the decade?
</P>
<P>
   That's a matter to be settled over the next several days,
beginning Saturday when the Braves host the Yankees in Game 1 of
the World Series. Game 2 also is in Atlanta, and the next three
games are scheduled for Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team has revealed its pitching rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees reached the World Series by disposing of the Boston
Red Sox in five games in the American League Championship Series.
The Braves needed six games to rid themselves of the pesky Mets in
the NLCS, setting up a rematch of the 1996 World Series, which the
Yankees won in six games.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, determining the Team of the '90s depends on the
criteria. The Braves' .595 winning percentage is tops in the majors
during the decade, while the Yankees check in at .548, good for
second place.
</P>
<P>
   How much would that really matter if the Yankees beat the Braves
in the World Series again, claiming a third title in the '90s?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we win another World Series,'' said Braves general
manager John Schuerholz, who doesn't believe the issue should be
open to debate. ``At least that would put an end to that question.
We don't need to do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won more games (in the '90s) than any team; we've won
100 games three years in a row; we've won eight straight division
titles. If you choose any criteria except for one narrow criterion
_ World Series championships _ we lead it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good argument _ but one the Yankees aren't buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about pitching and how the Braves are this and
that, but if we win the whole thing, we are the Team of the '90s,
no doubt about it,'' Yankees reliever Jeff Nelson said. ``They've
been in the playoffs every year since 1991 but won it all only
once. We would have three in four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, would be impossible to simply discard in this
team-of-the-decade debate, no matter what Schuerholz says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think we have a pretty good shot,'' Yankees pitcher
Andy Pettitte said. ``We have a pretty good thing going right now.
We've been in the playoffs five straight years. But we have to win
it first.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees should be favored to beat the Braves in the World
Series. But if they don't, Atlanta likely would be recognized as
the Team of the '90s, having matched the Yankees in World Series
championships with more pennants and a superior won-lost record in
regular-season play.
</P>
<P>
   Those who claim interleague play removes some of the intrigue
from the World Series will no doubt note this is the first matchup
of World Series teams that played during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves took two of three games at Yankee Stadium, but that
hardly avenged their 1996 World Series defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the World Series would do the trick, while no doubt
ending the debate regarding the team of the decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
