<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3377 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     10-20 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-1STDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES AND AN OLD FRIEND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Eds: subs to correct reference to Turner Field in 6th graf to
Fulton County Stadium) SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEES PREPARE TO FACE By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They rode buses together for long, hot summers in the minor
leagues, and rose to the majors to spend more than a few nights
chilling out on the bench. They would engage in the chatter of
chances, wondering when their respective turns might come.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz was brash, eager to inflate his worth, the
occasional irritant to established players. Gerald Williams was
reflective, easygoing, best friend to a born star, Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy had five tools,'' Leyritz said, giving Williams the
ultimate baseball scout's honor. ``I would've had to have been the
first to tell you it would've been Gerald who got a chance, with
the talent he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Williams, an outfielder with speed and a quick
bat, he didn't have the ability to retire a left-handed hitter late
in a game. In August 1996, the Yankees had one crying need as they
coasted toward their first post-season under their new manager, Joe
Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had built this $60 million house with a hole in the
roof,'' said Brian Cashman, the general manager who, at the time,
was assistant to Bob Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams, after nine patient years in the Yankee
organization, was deemed expendable. He went to Milwaukee as part
of what would become a very good deal for the lanky southpaw Graeme
Lloyd. Hole repaired, the Yankees went to the World Series.
Eventually, Leyritz went to the plate in Game 4 against the Atlanta
closer Mark Wohlers, who was in to protect a 6-3 Braves lead in the
eighth inning, two men on, at Fulton County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, with heat often too nasty to hit, threw Leyritz a
slider without enough snap. Leyritz sent it over the left-field
fence and turned around a World Series that the Braves had appeared
certain to win.
</P>
<P>
   Fate and fortune are funny that way. While Williams and his
tools were gone from the Yankees, the headstrong Leyritz had struck
a blow that made him, as he said Wednesday while contemplating
another World Series against the Braves, ``a Yankee forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all good Yankees and half the city, Leyritz was up past
midnight Tuesday, into Wednesday morning. Starring in their roles
of dead men slugging, the Mets were making a gallant last stand,
the brave against the Braves. But in the bottom half of the 11th
inning, here came Gerald Williams to lead off against Kenny Rogers,
star-crossed man on his nightmare mound.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rogers, remember, who had started for the Yankees,
pitched them into a hole, on the night Leyritz rode to the rescue.
Now Bobby Valentine had handed him the ball, and every Met fan and
maybe most Yankee fans saw sudden death for the Subway Series.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz said he had been rooting for the Mets, but a return to
the scene of personal glory was all right with him. The truth was,
he also couldn't help but pull for Gerald Williams, the unlucky
soul who had been hauled off baseball's equivalent of the space
shuttle a month before launch, and ordered aground to a team with
no wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to root for guys you came up with,'' Leyritz
said. ``Especially a guy like him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leyritz was in San Diego last season, the Padres had one of
those bench-clearing tangos with Atlanta, where Williams had
happily gone in an off-season trade. The two former Yankees found
each other, held on, not quite like Jeter and Alex Rodriguez, just
two journeymen who had done their bench and bus time together.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, this season, Williams stepped into a floodlight of
opportunity. He had 422 at-bats. He played left field, often led
off, hit 17 home runs, drove in 68 runs and became another example
of the Atlanta organization's stubborn resourcefulness in a season
supposedly lost to crippling injury and illness. In the Braves'
neediest hour, the 11th inning of Game 6, Williams lined a double
off Rogers into the left-field corner. He soon crossed the plate as
the series-winning run. He stepped into a celebration that would
carry him, finally, to a Braves-Yankees World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make sure I didn't take wings,'' he said, when
someone asked what he was thinking as he came down the third-base
line following ball four to Andruw Jones. By this he meant that, if
anything, experience had taught him to stay grounded _ the advice
he shares with nephews and nieces.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Williams told Leyritz he would do long after he was
traded by the Yankees, after he missed out on those ultimate games.
He told Leyritz he would stay calm, and things would work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to play against old friends,'' Williams said after
they had.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz _ to date off the Yankees' post-season roster after his
midsummer return to New York _ can only assume that Torre wants his
bat for late-inning at-bats against the tough lefties in the
Braves' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when opportunity was with him, Leyritz became a
World Series hero. Maybe you believe in fate. Maybe you don't. Some
good advice for Mariano Rivera, though: stay grounded, and watch
those sliders when Gerald Williams comes up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
