<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN OPPORTUNITY KNOCKED, MANY MISSED IT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, master of all managerial minds, had one ploy
left in his duffel bag of tricks. It was the 11th inning of Game 6
of the playoff series with Atlanta and the Braves had runners at
first and third with one out. As Brian Jordan took his bat to the
plate, the Mets' manager went to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby came out,'' related Todd Pratt, who was catching, ``and
said we're going to walk him, but let's try to bait him into a
squeeze or maybe Chipper would run to second and I'd throw him out.
Pretty good idea, but it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, the Atlanta manager, did not take the bait. Playing
the situation conservatively, confident there was a run lurking in
that inning, he called for neither squeeze nor steal. Kenny Rogers
pitched out on his first two pitches to Jordan, and no one moved.
The next two pitches were balls intentionally and loaded the bases.
The four balls Rogers subsequently threw to Andruw Jones were not
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, a veteran at pitching poorly in post-season games, thus
joined Kevin McGlinchy, a Braves rookie, in incurring the onus of
being the losing pitcher in one of the last two games of one of the
most scintillating post-season series ever played. If their
teammates had done their jobs, though, Rogers and McGlinchy would
never have been put in position to fail. And failure comes often to
pitchers who work in extra innings. Someone has to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that other players on both teams failed to do their
jobs highlighted the missed opportunities that abounded in the
series. McGlinchy was the losing pitcher in Game 5, but before he
even got into the game, his teammates had left 17 runners on base.
Rogers will be remembered as the man who walked in the run that
decided the 1999 National League Championship Series, but what
about the opportunities John Franco and Armando Benitez had to shut
down the Braves and protect one-run leads?
</P>
<P>
   Franco, pitching in the first post-season of his 16-year career,
gave up the game-tying run in the eighth inning. Benitez, who had
supplanted Franco as the closer, surrendered the game-tying run in
the 10th, setting the stage for Rogers to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Mets had run out of comebacks in what had been a
remarkable three-week sprint, Darryl Hamilton said, ``I just think
we ran out of gas. We had a lot of guys playing hurt. Armando
Benitez's knee has been bothering him the last month and a half. He
still went out there and gave us everything he had. He didn't have
much the last week, but he didn't care. He went out there and
pitched. The same with Kenny Rogers. The guy's been tired, very
tired. He's been getting up every other inning, it seems, and he
went out there and gave us everything he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter, starting on three days' rest for the first time when
it meant something, did likewise, but he discovered too late he had
nothing to give in Game 6. ``The break on his ball was so big,''
Don Baylor said, ``that he had to sacrifice stuff to try to get it
over. That comes from three days' rest.'' The Braves hitting coach
explained that the plan was for the hitters to take as many pitches
as possible, wearing Leiter down. But Leiter self-destructed in six
batters and 25 pitches, washing away all of the brilliant
performances he had provided in previous weeks.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the series, most of the pitchers were exhausted.
Valentine used 17 pitchers in the last two games, Cox 12. ``The
series was so intense pitchers were used over and over and over,''
Baylor said. ``That's what it came down to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' starting pitchers, however, once again shined. In
lasting only five and one-third innings and giving up three runs in
Game 6, Kevin Millwood was the only starter who didn't pitch at
least seven innings and gave up more than two earned runs. ``It
ended up being our pitchers vs. their good-hitting lineup,'' Baylor
said. ``They have a bunch of good hitters on that club.''
</P>
<P>
   But the good hitters didn't hit enough. Robin Ventura had three
hits, including his memorable grand-slam single, in 25 at-bats;
Mike Piazza, four in 24. Edgardo Alfonzo started the series well
with four hits in eight at-bats in the first two games, which the
Mets lost in spite of his hitting. But then Valentine flip-flopped
Alfonzo and John Olerud in the batting order in an attempt to
generate better hitting, and Alfonzo stopped hitting. He did not
get a hit and struck out seven times in his next 10 at-bats, and he
had only two hits in his last 19 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' leading hitter in the series was their least known
player, Melvin Mora. The 27-year-old rookie batted .429, his six
hits including a second-game home run and a sixth-game single that
gave the Mets an 8-7 lead. Mora also was the impetus for and part
of the double steal that led to the victory in Game 4, the one that
nearly turned the series around.
</P>
<P>
   But even more impressive was Mora's right arm. The Venezuelan
had offered a glimpse of what he could do when, playing left field,
he threw out Jay Bell at the plate in the eighth inning of what
turned out to be the last game of the division series against
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Playing center field in Game 3 against Atlanta, he threw out
Bret Boone at home in the first inning. In Game 5, as a right
fielder, he initiated the relay that caught Keith Lockhart at the
plate in the 13th before he could score what could have been the
winning run. In Game 6, he executed a dandy play in the 10th
inning, realizing he couldn't get Andruw Jones at home on Ozzie
Guillen's single to right and throwing instead to third, where he
nailed Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Mets fans can't wait to see more of Mora.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
