<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCFLOOD21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flooding tests historic N.C. town's hearts, history
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCEVILLE, N.C. _ The Tar River rose again, cresting Wednesday
for the fourth time in two months in this abandoned, flood-socked
town founded by former slaves. But Murray Morning plans to come
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my home,'' the 49-year-old man said, sitting on the
brick steps that had led to his double-wide mobile home, destroyed
by Hurricane Floyd's historic flood waters a month ago. ``I plan to
rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   But across town, past the leaning houses with blown-out windows
and past the stinking piles of shoes, mattresses and spoiled food,
Isaiah Dickens, 55, is leaving Princeville for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to come back,'' he said, loading his black pickup
truck with a big-screen TV and other household items he hopes will
dry out and, somehow, work again.
</P>
<P>
   Princeville is among dozens of eastern North Carolina
communities deluged by three hurricanes _ Dennis, Floyd and Irene _
the past two months. The state's most costly natural disaster,
Floyd flooded an estimated 60,000 buildings. Among those, 6,500
were destroyed and another 9,000 were so badly damaged they're
considered unlivable.
</P>
<P>
   As home to descendents of ex-slaves who settled here after the
Civil War, Princeville drew national attention during the flooding.
Now, as it tries to recover, the town is grappling with preserving
its history while providing a safe environment for residents who
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a balancing act,'' said Gavin Smith, an assistant
director for the North Carolina Emergency Management Division.
</P>
<P>
   It could be months, even years, before Princeville's future
becomes clear. Now, as town officials conduct business in nearby
Tarboro and federal inspectors assess damage to water-soaked houses
standing in buggy pools, prospects for the town seem as murky as
the brown film left by receding waters.
</P>
<P>
   This week's culprit is torrential rain from Hurricane Irene,
which is swelling the Tar River above flood stage. Flood waters
were not expected to breach the crescent-shaped earth levy along
the river. For more than 30 years, until Floyd, the man-made wall
had protected Princeville whenever the river rose above its banks.
</P>
<P>
   As the Tar's black waters rose silently, Morning strode across
the levy. He stopped at the sandy spot where Floyd's flooding first
spilled over, before it covered all but Princeville's highest
rooftops and church steeples with foul, swirling water.
</P>
<P>
   He gazed toward the abandoned town, where officials have vowed
to rebuild in a flood plain originally named Freedom Hill by freed
blacks who settled there in 1865. Others, however, are talking
about relocating all but Princeville's most historic buildings and
rebuilding on higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see it come back,'' said Mayor Pro Tem Milton
Johnson, 58, who, like the town's other 2,100 residents, evacuated
during Floyd. He lost almost everything he owned. With most
buildings declared ``unfit for human habitation,'' many of the
people haven't returned. ``It takes people to make a town,'' said
Johnson, a 30-year resident. ``But I don't know what is on people's
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents will get the chance to speak up Monday when the Town
Council meets at Edgecombe Community College in Tarboro with
representatives of federal and state relief agencies. ``We are not
going to tell Princeville what to do,'' North Carolina Gov. Jim
Hunt said. ``I think they will want to take steps to see that this
doesn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``How it is going to be done, I don't know,'' Hunt said. ``You
can say move to a high area, or raise the levy, or put everything
on stilts. There are a lot of ways you can do this, and Princeville
is going to determine its own future.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaks in the levy have been repaired temporarily. Officials are
determining whether Floyd's flooding at Princeville was greater
than what is considered a 100-year level. If that is the case,
federal laws would allow Princeville to rebuild where it is,
officials said. Few property owners in Princeville had flood
insurance. Few imagined the Tar River would rise higher than the
levy, which is 48 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Good gracious, I reckon, where did all that water
come from?''' Morning recalled. ``Wherever it came from, it wiped
us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Recovery has a long way to go. The stoplights in Princeville
don't work. When residents venture back into their homes, they wear
rubber gloves. At the police station, officers drape soaked
uniforms over squad cars to dry.
</P>
<P>
   At Mutual and Greenwood boulevards, eight feet above the ground,
a tan lounge chair hangs over a dogwood limb. Beside it, a white
wooden bench is stuck on a utility pole hook. Trucks continue to
haul away debris discarded by the roadside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to construct the whole town like it was,'' said
Rodney Cogdell, 31, Princeville's acting police chief. ``In fact,
it is going to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought we were going to bulldoze the whole town,''
he said, ``but we are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Town Manager Sandra White said pledges of money and labor for
rebuilding Princeville are coming in. Outside of Raleigh,
fast-growing, prosperous Cary has adopted the town. ``We are still
in the infancy,'' White said. ``You cannot put a timetable on this
type of devastation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
