<SLUG> BC-MENINGITIS-COLLEGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES COLLEGE STUDENTS TO CONSIDER MENINGITIS IMMUNIZATION  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (mk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal health advisory panel on Wednesday urged
first-year college students to consider being immunized against
bacterial meningitis, an extremely rare but potentially fatal
infection.
</P>
<P>
   The Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices urged
universities and health professionals to tell college freshmen
about the availability of a vaccine that has proved to be effective
against most strains of meningitis that circulate in the United
States. Health officials have found that college students living in
dormitories are more susceptible to the disease because they live
in close proximity to many other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals who provide care to freshmen, particularly those
who live in or plan to live in dormitories or residence halls,
should provide information about meningococcal disease and the
benefits of vaccination to those students and their parents,'' the
advisory panel said in a statement that was unanimously adopted
Wednesday at its meeting in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Even among college students, the disease is extremely rare,
striking only 3.8 of every 100,000 freshman dorm residents,
according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
Meningococcal invasive infection, or bacterial meningitis, causes
an inflammation of the membranes that cover the brain and spinal
cord. It causes flulike symptoms like headache, high fever, stiff
neck, nausea, vomiting and drowsiness.
</P>
<P>
   Meningitis is an especially virulent disease, and it is fatal in
10 to 15 percent of the cases, studies show. It can get worse very
quickly, sometimes in a matter of hours, if it is not promptly
treated by antibiotics, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, health professionals have become increasingly
concerned about the risks of bacterial meningitis to college
students who live in dormitories. In May, the CDC reported that
college freshmen living in dormitories were six times more likely
to contract meningococcal meningitis than college students living
off campus. Another study, conducted by medical investigators at
the Johns Hopkins School of Public Health in Baltimore, reached
similar conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The federal advisory committee released its recommendation after
hearing testimony from a Georgia woman whose 20-year-old son died
in April 1998, 26 days after contracting meningitis at Georgia
Southwestern University. Several former students from other
colleges around the country who had contracted meningitis also
testified that they had never been told about the availability of a
vaccine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2241EDT &QL; 
