<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIANS GO TO MARKET, AND FIND THE DEMAND RESTRAINED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ With Asia's stock markets shaking off two years of
near-paralysis, it is no surprise that Asian companies are rushing
to raise billions of dollars. The surprise is how hard they are
finding the job.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the third-largest Chinese petroleum company, China
National Offshore Oil, postponed a $1 billion share offering _ a
day after it had cut the size of the sale by more than half. And
that came after a leading Thai bank shelved its plan to raise $800
million in a stock sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rally in Asia made companies desperate to raise capital,''
said Marc Faber, the head of his own investment firm in Hong Kong.
``Unfortunately, the markets peaked in July and have been weakening
ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest reversals have unnerved Asian government officials,
corporate executives and investment bankers, none more than in
China and Hong Kong. A flood of new Chinese and Hong Kong shares is
scheduled to reach the Hong Kong stock market over the next six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some bankers express fear that they may have missed the
window to cash in on Asia's improving health. Others worry that the
raft of offerings _ $30 billion or more in Hong Kong alone _ could
overwhelm demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very large pipeline, which has contributed to the
mart's fragility,'' said Richard Margolis, a regional strategist at
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing is leading the auction. Besides reviving an attempt to
sell stock in China National Offshore Oil, it plans to offer shares
in several flagship state-owned companies, including the China
Petrochemical Corp., China National Petroleum and China Unicom, the
second-ranking telecommunications provider.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the largest phone company, China Telecom, began
marketing a new offering of at least $2.6 billion in stock and
debt. In 1997, China Telecom, the country's dominant mobile phone
operator, set the standard for China stock issues with a wildly
successful initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's government plans to begin disposing of the $27
billion in shares it acquired in August 1998 in a buying campaign
intended to thwart currency traders whose speculation was
disrupting the market. The shares are being packaged in a mutual
fund that tracks the benchmark Hang Seng index. They will be
offered to investors in chunks, the first of which could raise as
much as $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The government will begin marketing the fund, to be called the
Tracker Fund of Hong Kong, next Monday and hopes to list it here on
Nov. 12. The government notes that the fund contains the bluest of
blue chips, including the global banking giant HSBC Holdings, which
now has its headquarters in London. Critics said the fund is
overweighted toward property companies.
</P>
<P>
   Optimists note that in 1997, before the regional economic crisis
took hold, Asia's markets produced $42 billion in equity offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything falls into place, there's no reason why Asian
markets couldn't generate $70 billion in equity financings a
year,'' said John S. Wadsworth Jr., the chairman of Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter Asia. ``But I don't want to give the impression it's a
shoo-in. It all has to come together correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the requisites, he said, is the continued strength of
United States stock markets. Asian markets are heavily influenced
by the performance of the Dow Jones industrial average, and Hong
Kong especially follows Wall Street because its currency's value is
linked to the United States dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, investors have to be persuaded that Asia is entering
a genuine recovery, not just a temporary rebound. Economists are
confident that Asian countries will return to moderate growth. But
initial euphoria fueled by resurgent stock markets has given way to
a more cautious outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think, after the devastation that Asia suffered, that
you get a V-shaped recovery,'' Faber said, using economics
shorthand for a steep turnaround. ``I think you get a strong
rebound, followed by a period of volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   China National Offshore Oil fell victim to one of these
unpredictable swings. But bankers said that the underwriter,
Salomon Smith Barney, a unit of Citigroup, also priced the offering
too high. When it realized its error, they said, it could not get
approval from Chinese officials to lower the price in time.
</P>
<P>
   Such missteps are common with Chinese companies. Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter had hoped to hold an initial public offering for China
Unicom next month. But it was forced to postpone it until next year
to allow China Unicom to unravel a series of joint ventures with
foreign telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth said the latest wave of Chinese stock offerings is
different from most previous ones in a key respect: the Beijing
government is offering stakes in potential blue-chip companies. In
the past, most Chinese offerings have been been in hastily
assembled conglomerates, many of which were poorly managed or
involved in dubious businesses. The question this time around is
whether quantity will drown out quality.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
