<SLUG> BC-CHASE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Dallas, Tampa)  
 CHASE POSTS BETTER-THAN-EXPECTED EARNINGS IN 3rd QUARTER  
 (bl)  
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chase Manhattan Corp., the nation's third-largest
bank, said Wednesday that its third-quarter earnings were 67
percent higher than last year _ a report that was better than
expected and came less than two weeks after the company said it was
moving thousands of jobs out of Manhattan to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The company's third-quarter net income was $1.19 billion, or
$1.37 a share, beating analysts' average estimates by 5 cents. In
comparison, a year ago, net income for the third quarter was $738
million or 82 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares surged, closing Wednesday, at $75.8125, up
$4.6875.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were very good numbers,'' said Timothy Ghriskey, senior
portfolio manager at Dreyfus Corp., which manages $100 billion in
assets, including shares of Chase. ``We are slightly increasing our
estimates for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan has bolstered its earnings recently by
diversifying its traditional banking business and trying to build a
strong investment banking practice. Investment banking fees were
$486 million in the third quarter, compared with $322 million in
the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has also greatly increased the revenue it earns from
trading. For the quarter, trading revenue was $679 million,
compared with $76 million in the third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chase's earnings are much more tied to the stock market now,''
said Ghriskey. ``If we have a market correction, Chase will feel
it,'' he said, just like many other banks, which have also
diversified.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 7, Chase Manhattan, the largest corporate employer in
New York City, announced that it would soon move 3,500 of its jobs
there to offices in Florida, Texas and Massachusetts. By moving its
jobs, the bank plans to cut costs significantly. Salaries, real
estate costs, taxes and utility expenses are all lower in Tampa,
Fla., and Dallas, where most of the jobs are to be relocated.
</P>
<P>
   William B. Harrison, Jr., who became the company's president and
chief executive June 1, said Wednesday that the company would
continue to make investments aimed at growing revenues. One of
those investments came in September, when Chase announced it was
buying Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, an investment bank based in San
Francisco, for $1.35 billion. By buying the investment bank, Chase
can increase the number of technology companies and Internet
start-ups it underwrites.
</P>
<P>
   Although it leads its competitiors in the traditional lending
business, Chase has been slow to seize opportunities to expand into
stock underwriting. Competitors like Citigroup, Bank of America and
BankBoston have been quicker to snap up stock underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   In a statment, Harrison said Wednesday: ``This is another strong
quarter, with each of our major business lines _ global banking,
global services and national consumer services _ producing income
growth of 25 percent or more, and return on equity in excess of 20
percent. These earnings continue to demonstrate Chase's disciplined
approach to managing capital and making investments that propel
future growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
