<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A NEW INFLEXIBILITY IN OVERHAULING U.S. FINANCIAL LAWS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After more than 20 years of battles, truces and
unholy alliances over broad legislation to reshape the nation's
financial system, the measure's fate rests on what has turned into
a bitter and largely symbolic political fight between President
Clinton and Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   More than seven hours of negotiations Wednesday involving Gramm,
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers and Gene Sperling, the president's top economic
adviser, inched closer to a resolution but failed to yield a deal
over the legislation's effect on a 1977 law aimed at eradicating
discrimination in lending.
</P>
<P>
   The main sticking point appeared to be whether to require
community groups to divulge the details of deals they strike with
banks to make loans to minorities and the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   The talks may continue this week, or Gramm, and his counterpart
in the House, Rep. James Leach, may try to force the issue by a
vote of the House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the administration and Gramm moved slightly closer
to agreement, the positions on both sides of the Community
Reinvestment Act of 1977 have begun to harden. As the talks, which
began late Monday night, begin to stretch out, the prospects of
overhauling the banking system begin to fade.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have begun to recognize political benefits from
standing firm as the new election cycle begins, even as the most
powerful financial interests in America clamor for a new law. Gramm
and other Republicans would undoubtedly blame the White House for
failing to approve a bill long sought by Wall Street and corporate
America. Equally, Clinton and Vice President Al Gore would
undoubtedly be able to accuse the Republicans of retarding decades
of progress in civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When symbolic politics begins to get elevated, it gets harder
to make a deal,'' said one Democratic senator who wants to see the
legislation signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists who champion the legislation agreed. ``If there is not
a bill, it will be because the White House and the Treasury
Department feel very strongly about the Community Reinvestment Act,
and Senator Gramm feels equally strongly, and both sides think they
will win the White House next term and can get a better bill,''
said Paul A. Equale, a lobbyist for the Independent Insurance
Agents of America.
</P>
<P>
   Already Wednesday there was talk on both sides that foreshadowed
what may be to come, including angry accusations over race as it
related to several issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The array of anti-minority sentiment expressed almost each
week now by Republicans is historic,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., the minority leader, citing Gramm's view on the Community
Reinvestment Act, among other things. ``I have never seen a party
become this defiant when it comes to protecting minority rights in
my time in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that ``in the end the administration has to decide if
they want a bill or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that we have to wait 15 months for a new
administration to approve this bill,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   For years, efforts to overhaul the nation's financial system
failed in Congress because three of Washington's most powerful
lobbying interests _ banks, insurers and securities firms _ were at
war, each lobbying to defeat the interests of the other. Their
efforts led to many stalemates, but ultimately, the three interests
became allies, as the distinctions between the financial products
offered by the three industries began to blur.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prospects of the legislation remained dim because of
a turf war between the Treasury and the Federal Reserve over which
agency should oversee the new financial conglomerates of the 21st
Century.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Fed and the Treasury reached an agreement to
share that authority, and the mood brightened considerably among
advocates for wholesale changes to the 66 years worth of laws that
have made it difficult for banks to expand into securities and
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Now one obstacle remains in the way of a new law: a partisan
fight between Democrats and Republicans over the meaning of
community lending and the philosophy behind the Community
Reinvestment Act, a 22-year-old law that was intended to eradicate
red-lining and other forms of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   While the provisions under debate affect relatively obscure
elements of the act, they are powerfully symbolic, affecting core
constituencies of both parties. Gramm has repeatedly criticized the
way regulators have interpreted the act, saying the federal
government should not be in the business of ``reallocating
capital'' and that the law imposes unnecessary and burdensome
requirements on small banks and savings associations.
</P>
<P>
   His critics say that the Financial Services Act of 1999, as his
bill is called, would roll-back the Community Reinvestment Act.
Those critics include the Congressional Black Caucus, a group that
helped rescue Clinton from removal during the impeachment
proceedings this year.
</P>
<P>
   There were fresh signs Wednesday that Democrats and Republicans
were hardening their views. Nine Republicans sent a letter to Gramm
urging him to hold the line and not make any significant
concessions on the issue. At the same time, the Rev. Jesse Jackson
said in an interview that he was urging the White House to hold
firm and that a compromise on the Community Reinvestment Act would
undermine the president's commitment to raising capital in poor
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats criticized the White House on Wednesday, saying
that it had caved in to industry pressure by abandoning their fight
to put provisions in the legislation that would have made it more
difficult for financial conglomerates to share confidential
customer information with other businesses and telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They inexplicably pulled the rug out from underneath us,''
said Sen. Richard H. Bryan, D-Nev., who had been leading an effort
in the Senate for provisions that would have strengthened the
privacy protection elements of the legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
