<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHASTEWART-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A FLUSTERED HOUR OF TRADING ON THE BIG BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Martha Stewart Omnimedia initial public offering
was the hottest one to hit the New York Stock Exchange in many
years. The shares, which were offered at $18 each, more than
doubled when they began trading Tuesday morning. Then they went
much higher.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Big Board may be happy to have had one of the most
notable initial offerings of the year, it should not be happy with
the way the stock traded in the first hectic hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks very peculiar,'' said a senior official of the
Securities and Exchange Commission on Wednesday. He declined to be
identified, or to say what action, if any, might be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all hot initial offerings in recent years have been
listed on the Nasdaq market, where the existence of multiple market
makers can produce chaos when a stock opens for trading. But the
Big Board, with an auction market centered on a single specialist
firm, contends that it is able to provide something better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our desire to bring supply and demand into balance is what
makes us different,'' said New York Stock Exchange president
William Johnston in a telephone interview Wednesday. ``The whole
point of the auction market is to try and get sellers and buyers
together and trade at reasonable prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston argued that the Big Board accomplished just that. It
was true that the trades that were reported by the exchange seemed
to reflect an effort to have a balance of buyers and sellers. But
that was not true in the so-called third market, comprising
brokerage firms that trade exchange-listed stocks off the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exchange doesn't like to halt the stock,'' said one trader
involved in Tuesday's action. ``In lieu of halting the stock, they
spread the quote, which effectively stops trading in the stock and
allows natural buyers and sellers to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   But while trading was more or less halted on the Big Board, the
third market was up and running. From 10:09 a.m. through 10:21
a.m., the posted bid stayed at $37.44 a share. But the ask price
rose as high as $52. Small investors who had submitted market
orders, and whose orders were sent by their brokerage firms to
third-market brokers rather than to the exchange floor, were taken
to the cleaners. Those who were selling stock were paid the $37.44
price. Those who were buying were charged up to $52 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying at $37 and selling at $52 is extremely profitable,''
Johnston said dryly.
</P>
<P>
   All the trades at $52 were later canceled, perhaps out of
embarrassment. But some of the $50 orders stood, as did many others
above $47.50 a share, the highest the stock traded on the exchange
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Martha Stewart offering was hot in large part because the
founder of the company is so well known. Only 8.28 million shares
were available for trading, including the offering of 7.2 million
shares and the shares the underwriter had an option to sell if
demand was high.
</P>
<P>
   The opening trade in the stock, at 10:08 a.m., was for 3.6
million shares. The price was $37.25, more than double the price
that investors had paid in the offering.
</P>
<P>
   But then, said John Lyden, a senior managing director of Lyden,
Dolan, Nick &AMP; Co., the specialist firm that handled the stock,
``the Dot machine just lit up.'' That is the machine that relays
orders from small investors. As the buy orders poured in,
specialists _ including Lyden's son, Barry, also a senior managing
director _ conferred with representatives of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, the lead underwriter, about prices at which more shares
would be available from customers who had bought in the offering.
To draw in those shares, the posted ask price began to rise, first
to $45 at 10:10, then to $50 at 10:11 and finally to $52 at 10:20.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board executed large trades, sweeping in all the orders
it had, at $45 at 10:14, at $46 at 10:17 and at $47 at 10:19. In
the meantime, many trades were reported by third-market firms. The
Big Board high trade, of $47.50, was reported at 10:22, and by
10:23 the spread was down to reasonable levels.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, a clerk for Lyden, Dolan made a serious error,
and then repeated it a few minutes later. About 150,000 of the
324,200 shares bought in the $45 trade were bought by customers
whose orders had arrived over the Dot machine. But because the
clerk did not push the right button, the Dot machine still showed
those orders waiting to be executed. He made the same mistake on
the $46 trade. So some orders were executed again at $47.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that mistake was discovered hours later, the price
of the stock had fallen to the high $30s. Because the real buyers
were not going to buy the shares three times, the specialist became
the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost substantial money,'' said John Lyden, refusing to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, because the error had made demand appear to be higher
than it was, it drove up the price. ``There is no way it sells at
$47.50'' without the error, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, the price had fallen to $35.56, a price
that may have been driven down as the specialist sold some of the
shares that it had been forced to buy because of the mistake.
Wednesday it rose $4.1875, to $39.75. Total volume for the two days
was 14.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   And what will happen to the clerk who made the mistake? ``I'm
not going to fire him,'' Lyden said.
</P>
<P>
   With benefit of hindsight, it appears that the Big Board would
have served the public much better if it had simply halted trading
to deal with the huge volume of orders. The clerk's mistake might
not have been made, and third-market brokers would not have been
given a huge spread to work with.
</P>
<P>
   If trading had been halted, that would have seemed embarrassing
to exchange officials, who are tired of taunts from Nasdaq about
such halts. But what actually happened should be far more
embarrassing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
