<SLUG> BC-IBM-EARNINGS-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM EXPECTS LOWER PROFITS DUE TO REDUCED DEMAND FOR MAINFRAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM warned investors Wednesday that its profits would be as much
as 15 percent below expectations in the current quarter and in the
first quarter of next year, because corporations' efforts to deal
with the Year 2000 computer problem were dampening demand for its
big mainframe systems.
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter, ending Sept. 30, International Business
Machines Corp. met Wall Street's profit expectations, despite a
sharp drop in mainframe sales. The company said Wednesday it earned
$1.8 billion, or 93 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   But that news was overshadowed by its announcement that for the
next two quarters, earnings would be 15 to 20 cents below the
corresponding quarter a year earlier. That would represent a profit
shortfall of as much as $540 million below what analysts had been
expecting for each of the two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, investors, anticipating a solid earnings
report, sent IBM's shares up $7.75 to $112.75. But after the 4 p.m.
announcement, they fell sharply, ending the trading day at $107,
and falling to as low as $99 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's announcement was the latest in a series of surprising _
and contradictory _ results posted by technology companies, a mixed
bag that has sent technology stocks careening.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, shares in Unisys fell by one-third when it said its
revenue growth rate had slowed. On Monday, Dell Computer said its
profits would suffer because the Taiwan earthquake was causing
memory prices to rise. Its shares fell by 8.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Microsoft reported that its profits were well above
expectations because of ``awesome'' demand for personal computers.
As a result, Microsoft's shares rose by $5 15/16 Wednesday, and the
entire Nasdaq market rose by 104 points to 2466.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between Y2K and Taiwan, the tech stock market is on pins and
needles,'' said Steven Milunovich, an analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Milunovich said that IBM's woes shouldn't affect most
other technology firms, as the slowdown is related to the sort of
very large computers for which IBM has few competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like most of the Y2K effect has landed on IBM's
doorstep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, IBM said that its largest customers, like banks
and insurance companies, had bought extra mainframes earlier in the
year in order to test their software to make sure it would operate
properly with dates after the turn of the millennium. Now that this
testing is largely completed, the companies have the extra machines
available to put to work in their main systems, reducing their need
to make new purchases.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said that it had not expected the slowdown because it had
thought that the surge in mainframe purchases in recent quarters
was due to a rise in new applications related to the Internet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts expressed frustration that IBM hadn't warned them of
the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They provided a level of comfort that didn't exist,'' said
Laura Conigliaro, an analyst with Goldman Sachs.``You can never
believe companies when they give you a prediction for the end of
the year at the beginning of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with investors, IBM chief financial officer
Douglas Maine said the company's earlier surveys of customers
indicated that demand for mainframes would hold up through the end
of the year and that it didn't notice the shortfall until the end
of the third quarter. He said that after the first quarter of 2000,
the company expected its sales to rebound to the levels that
analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Unisys reported that its sales of mainframes had
increased in the third quarter, but would fall by a corresponding
amount in the fourth quarter, because its customers didn't want to
install new machines right before new years.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, IBM said its revenue increased by 5 percent to $21.1
billion in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It earned 93 cents per share, but of that, 3 cents or $63
million, represented one-time items. Thus its 90 cent per share
operating profit matched expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Year 2000 problem, IBM said its results were
also hurt by a shortage of display screens for its popular line of
ThinkPad portable computers and by sharp price cutting in hard disk
drives.
</P>
<P>
   Making up for these shortfalls, IBM said it experienced
continued growth in computer services, software and semiconductors.
Moreover, it was able to cut $100 million in expenses compared with
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of mainframes and other big computers known as servers
fell by 30 percent to $2.0 billion. The pre-tax profit from the
servers fell by 60 percent to $295 million.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the company's money-losing personal computer
business continued to show improvement. Sales increased by 11
percent to $3.7 billion. The company lost $69 million from PCs, but
that was a 43 percent improvement over last year, mainly because
the company is shifting sales to higher margin products like
portables. On Tuesday, IBM said that it would no longer sell
desktop computers to consumers through retail stores and that it
would shift the business to the Internet, where costs are lower.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's global services unit posted sales of $7.9 billion, up 12
percent. The increase would have been 15 percent, the company said,
had it not sold its network unit to AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said that it did not expect the earthquake in Taiwan to have
a significant effect on its business. It is paying more for memory
and other components, but the cost is partially offset because
IBM's semiconductor business benefits from the higher market
prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
