<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MORE SUBDUED TYSON GETTING READY TO RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ The promoter Dan Goossen introduced Mike Tyson
Wednesday afternoon at a news conference for his heavyweight bout
Saturday against Orlin Norris at the MGM Grand, and everyone waited
and waited and waited some more.
</P>
<P>
   After about two minutes, Tyson emerged from behind a curtain
onto the stage. It was not a grand entrance, such as when he
entered wearing a crown and flowing royal robe before his bout
against Tony Tucker to unify the heavyweight title in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his latest attempt to be more mature, Tyson was
subdued. No ranting. No raving. No cursing. About as heated as it
got was near the end when Tyson was asked how he saw the fight
going and what he planned to do. ``I'm bringing some pain, baby,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson (46-3) has not fought since he met Francois Botha on Jan.
16. Botha toyed with Tyson over four rounds until Botha walked into
Tyson's loaded right hand in the fifth round and was knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't fought in two and a half years,'' said Tyson, who is
33. ``That wasn't a good experience, but a sensational ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of the major fights this year were unsatisfying duds:
Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis fought a controversial draw in
March, and Oscar De La Hoya ran a marathon and lost his title to
Felix Trinidad last month without the exchange of a telling blow.
So Tyson has the opportunity to bring some excitement back into the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   If he can keep his head about him, maintain his current level of
maturity, stay out of trouble and fight on a regular basis, Tyson
can regain viability in the sport. Talks are already under way for
him to fight at Madison Square Garden in December. Plans are also
being made for a bout in February of next year.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time since he first lost to Holyfield in 1997,
Tyson is talking about being heavyweight champion again. ``If
nothing happens to me, like Monday following Sunday, I'll be
champion again,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, who has a four-fight deal with Tyson, is eager to see
how Tyson looks against Norris, a former cruiserweight with a 55-5
record. That will determine Tyson's credibility as a heavyweight
contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, he's got his stuff together,'' Goossen said. ``He's
talking about being the world champion again. I didn't hear that in
the Botha fight. He says he's in the best shape he's been in in the
last 10 years. I believe him, because I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson had to overcome several hurdles to set up the Botha fight.
He had to undergo a battery of psychological tests at Massachusetts
General Hospital in Boston to satisfy the Nevada Athletic
Commission that he was psychologically fit to return to the ring.
The commission had revoked Tyson's license after he bit Holyfield's
ears during a bout on June 29, 1997. Tyson was also facing assault
charges in Maryland, involving a minor fender-bender after which he
punched one man and kicked another.
</P>
<P>
   After the Botha fight, Tyson was sentenced to one year in jail
on the charges. He spent three and a half months in jail. It may
have been humiliating, but Tyson has not blamed anyone else for his
troubles: he has said he wants to take responsibility for his
actions. He said he was trying to salvage his marriage, which had
been strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that I've been through has been slightly stressful,
but I overcame it,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   He came out of jail in June weighing 280 pounds. Through
conditioning and training he has trimmed down to 220 pounds. He has
rehired Jay Bright as one of his trainers. Bright, a disciple of
Cus D'Amato, is working with Tommy Brooks, whom Tyson hired before
the Botha fight to try to get Tyson back to the form he had 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   During a public sparring session here on Tuesday afternoon,
Tyson displayed the kind of explosiveness and hand speed that made
him dangerous when he raced through the heavyweight division in the
late 1980's. His sharp left hook knocked down a sparring partner,
Everett Martin, in the first round of a three-round session.
Wednesday Tyson used a double left hook to knock down another
sparring partner, Stan Allen. The session was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   It is always hard to know with Tyson whether he has really
changed. Even Shelly Finkel, Tyson's adviser, said as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Finkel said about Tyson's new mature approach.
``All I know if for the last four or five weeks he's really been
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
