<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ISLAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOLERANT AND INCLUSIVE MUSLIM TRADITION THRIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The election of Indonesia's most important Muslim
religious leader as its first democratically chosen president was
welcomed Wednesday by Western governments and human rights
advocates who describe the new Indonesian leader as a champion of
human rights and religious tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Islam as practiced by the new president _ Abdurrahman Wahid,
leader of what amounts to the largest Muslim political party in
Indonesia _ is a faith in which religious and cultural differences
between neighbors are carefully respected, and in which free speech
is a right.
</P>
<P>
   His rise to power put human rights groups in an unusual _ and,
they said, welcome _ position: greeting the ascension of a foreign
religious leader to the reins of power.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates often cringe when religious leaders take
control of a government, fearing the intolerance of Muslim-governed
nations like Iran or Afghanistan, or recalling the first months
after Hindu nationalists took power in India last year and were
accused of orchestrating violence against Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be very important in terms of showing the
rest of the world such a tolerant Muslim leader,'' said Sidney
Jones, Asia director of Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is critical of some of Wahid's political alliances,
Ms. Jones said that he ``has personally been a staunch defender of
human rights'' and that his election begins ``an experiment to see
whether an overwhelmingly Muslim country can be a true democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People despair of that ever happening,'' she said. ``Maybe
Indonesia will be the first.''
</P>
<P>
   With approximately 220 million people, 90 percent of whom
describe themselves as Muslim, Indonesia is home to more followers
of Islam than the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The faith found its way to Indonesia beginning in the 13th
centurie aboard the trading ships from the Indian subcontinent.
Islam was not forced on the population, and it did not replace
traditional Indonesian spirit-worship and mysticisim. Rather it
became layered upon Hindu and Buddhist practices.
</P>
<P>
   For most Indonesians, the fact that they are Muslims is only one
element of their identity, and not necessarily the first to come to
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Islam in Indonesia has never been an extreme orthodoxy,'' said
James Clad, a professor of Southeast Asian politics at Georgetown
University who recently returned from Indonesia. ``It's a religion
there that has been in tune with traditions that are open to
tolerance and a willingness to disagree. Broadly speaking, this is
a place where Islamic fundamentalism finds the soil pretty thin.''
</P>
<P>
   When Muslim political parties were first formed in Indonesia
early this century, few called for an Islamic state. Instead,
historians say, they reflected a desire to defend their basic
political and economic rights from encroachments by the Dutch
colonialists.
</P>
<P>
   When Indonesia won its independence in 1949, its constitution
guaranteed freedom of religion, and Hinduism, Buddhism and
Christianity are widely and openly practiced.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, no one has been a more important champion of
religious and cultural tolerance than Wahid, the leader of the
Council of Islamic Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s and early 1990s, Wahid was outspoken in his
condemnation of human rights abuses by the Indonesian Army in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The richness of Indonesia _ it's diversity _ is also its
weakness,'' he said in an interview in 1993. ``Look at what has
happened in Yugoslavia and the Soviet Union. That's what I'm afraid
of in Indonesia _ disintegration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UPS-IPO-NYT &LR;      10-20 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPS' INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERING COULD BE BIGGEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Parcel Service said Wednesday that it could raise as much
as $4.6 billion when it sells its shares to investors for the first
time in its 92-year history later this year, making its initial
public offering perhaps the biggest ever.
</P>
<P>
   UPS, which is the world's largest package &UR; - &LR; delivery company and
is currently owned by its employees, announced in July that it was
finally succumbing to the siren song of Wall Street and would sell
its shares to the public. But until Wednesday it did not say how
many shares it would sell or at what price.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, UPS
revealed that it planned to sell 109.4 million shares, or a 9
percent stake, at an estimated price between $36 and $42. At the
high end of the spectrum, UPS would raise $4.6 billion, larger than
the record $4.4 billion raised by Conoco last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is it is going to be very well subscribed,'' Edward
Wolfe, transportation analyst at Bears Stearns, said of the UPS
offering. ``I am getting more questions on a daily basis about this
than about any other company I am following. There is tremendous
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS hopes to sell the stock in November after employees vote to
approve the offering later this month. Oddly enough, the company,
which had $25 billion in sales last year and has more than $3
billion in cash on its balance sheet, does not need the money. It
has said it would use the cash it raised to buy shares back from
its employees.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it was going public because it needed to have
stock to use for acquisitions at a time when the package &UR; - &LR; delivery
industry is consolidating around a few global players, including
UPS &UR; ; &LR;  FDX Corp., which is the parent of Federal Express &UR; ; &LR;  DHL,
and several European postal services.
</P>
<P>
   To preserve its employee-managed culture, UPS has structured the
stock offering so that 99 percent of the voting rights will remain
with its employee-managers.
</P>
<P>
   Though Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the offering's lead
underwriter, suggested the estimated price range between $36 and
$42, the UPS sale could ultimately yield more.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Barsky, co-manager of MRG Nucleus Fund, which invests in
new public companies, said that in general there had been two kinds
of initial public offerings recently: established large, name-brand
companies, like Conoco and Delphi Automotive, with long histories
and strong earnings, and Internet startups with short track records
and no earnings.
</P>
<P>
   While the prices of Internet offerings have often soared, few of
the established companies have priced above their suggested ranges.
But UPS is an interesting case because in addition to being a
long-established business with multibillion-dollar earnings, it
also has a strong Internet connection since its signature brown
trucks deliver many of the products now being ordered via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said they felt UPS could be priced like an
Internet offering. ``Why not? It helped Martha Stewart and WWF,
both of which were positioned as Internet plays,'' Barsky said,
referring to two recent successful offerings _ Martha Stewart
Living Omnimedia and World Wrestling Federation Entertainment.
``And UPS is arguably much more related to the Internet economy
than they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
