<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-METS-HONEYMOONERS-     10-20 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-METS-HONEYMOONERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEYMOON IS OVER FOR A CALIFORNIA COUPLE AND METS RETAILERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Felix and Brenda Manglinong, newlyweds from
Sacramento, Calif., spread a Mets jersey between them Wednesday as
if examining a religious frock. Married on Saturday, they had flown
to New York this week with hopes of spending their honeymoon in a
frenzy of giddy borough-hopping. A Subway Series, they said, that's
how they wanted to spend the first days of their marriage, watching
the Mets face the Yankees in a battle for New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have needed a hotel room, because we just would
have gone from stadium to stadium night by night,'' said
Manglinong, musing over their team's extra-inning elimination at
the hands of the Atlanta Braves on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Manglinongs, Californians with an almost inexplicable
fascination with the Mets, were still feeling a bit world-weary
Wednesday after suffering fandom's one-two punch.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had finished the season for their favorite team (this
is a couple, after all, that has an oil painting of Darryl
Strawberry, in a Mets uniform, hanging in their bedroom). Their
ideal of a Subway Series-honeymoon had ended even as they prepared
to get in line and wait for tickets overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought a rain suit, an umbrella, heavy boots and a
thermos,'' Manglinong said. ``I would have stood outside Shea
Stadium as long as it took.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many a New York baseball fan, the Manglinongs found
themselves seeking commiseration, and so they lingered at the Mets
Club House Shop in Manhattan, where memorabilia and misery mixed in
equal measure as the rain drizzled outside. ``You can look at that
weather right now, and that pretty much describes how the Mets fan
feels,'' said Joey Torres, a cashier, as he tended to the wounded
wandering around the store.
</P>
<P>
   Big things had been lost, the fans in the shop said, big things
like a citywide celebration and a chance to get to the bottom of
whose baseball town this really is. ``Straight up, this would have
been the ultimate challenge,'' said Rafael Torres, 23, a Grand
Central Partnership security guard who ducked in with his partner
during his lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   Torres is a Yankees fan, an irretrievably partisan Yankees fan,
and he said he had dropped by the shop to buy a jersey for his
girlfriend, a Mets fan, who had refused to speak to him since
Atlanta won. His intentions started out good. But he had gravitated
toward a display of Yankees caps and he had begun to gloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a Subway Series,'' he said, ``they all would have
found out that the world we live in is __.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Yankee world,'' said Shekemia Napoleon, 25, his partner, who
also roots for you-know-who.
</P>
<P>
   The dispiriting realization that 1999 would not include the
ultimate Mets-Yankees showdown traveled far beyond this little
corner of the Mets' universe. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a similarly
partisan Yankees fan, but one who can at least root for the Mets
when he has to, expressed disappointment at the Braves victory at a
dedication of a library in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were virtually this close to it,'' the mayor said, holding
his thumb and index finger about an inch apart. ``Maybe we'll get
there next year. One of my unredeemed campaign promises is that we
would have a Subway Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Giuliani announced that a pep rally for the Yankees would
be held at 4:30 p.m. Thursday near the fountain in City Hall Park.
Back at the Mets Club House Shop, the security guards left without
a jersey, passing by Robert A. Katz, who stops in almost every day.
Katz, who described himself as ``acting like I'm 20 but I'm really
34'' was complaining bitterly that Yankees caps were for sale in
his sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that George Steinbrenner would let this
happen, would let Mets hats in the Yankees Club House,'' he said,
sharply, to Joseph McGrath, the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath seemed not to mind. ``It's like the Hatfields and
McCoys,'' he said, after Katz wandered off.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, for his part, managed to find some solace in the loss: no
more late nights watching baseball, at least until next year.
``I'll get to bed at 10:30 and I'll get to see my wife and kids a
little more often,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
