<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DOLENYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MRS. DOLE DEPARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Oct. 21:
</P>
<P>
   In the end, not even her brave stand on gun control, her swarm
of sorority sisters or her winning ways with large crowds could
save Elizabeth Dole's campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination. In the end, there simply was not enough money. As she
explained Wednesday in her graceful departure from the race, the
big bucks were elsewhere. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has his $60
million campaign bankroll, and the publishing millionaire Steve
Forbes has the family fortune. At the present rate, their cash
advantage going into the primary season next year would be 80 to 1,
Mrs. Dole figured. ``I can handle 2 to 1 or even 10 to 1, but not
80 to 1,'' she told friends, supporters and the largest collection
of television cameras she had seen since she launched her campaign
nine months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   When candidates quit for lack of money, there are usually other
problems as well. In this case her helpmate, Bob Dole, gave
interviews hinting, most unhelpfully, that his wife could not win.
Still, Mrs. Dole departs sounding an important alarm about how
money shoves real debate under an expensive carpet of television
ads. As she put it, ``In the real America, it's more important to
raise issues than to raise funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, the fifth Republican to drop out of the presidential
race, had one of the more impressive resumes in the field, having
served in two cabinet posts and a successful term as president of
the American Red Cross. Despite her lack of experience campaigning
for herself, as opposed to her husband, she did well with women.
That means the Republican nominee might consider her for the second
position on the ticket or other important jobs. Her statement hints
that she is not retiring from the fray to become one of the poor
spirits described by Theodore Roosevelt who ``live in the gray
twilight that knows not victory nor defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   More concretely for next year's early primaries, Mrs. Dole's
departure leaves an all-male contest that tightens the pressure on
its front-runner, Bush. Forbes will aim to his right, and Gary
Bauer to his far right. Meanwhile, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who
has been gaining strength in early-primary states including his
own, could be an even more durable competitor. McCain offers an
interesting contrast in style and substance, with his deeper
knowledge of global issues and his strong views on campaign finance
reform. Like Mrs. Dole, voters can hope that the next rounds of the
campaign will include not merely the most expensive campaign ads
that fund-raising can buy but open debates on issues as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
