<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3546 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-RICE-TCU-HNS &LR;      10-20 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RICE-TCU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEAL FARMER  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
They're brothers who will be playing on the same field for the last
time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   TCU senior punter/receiver Royce Huffman and Rice redshirt
freshman linebacker Scott Huffman _ both from Elkins _ could
literally run into each other Saturday when the Horned Frogs and
Owls meet at Rice Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who our parents will be for,'' said Royce. ``They
might be fair-weather fans, rooting for whoever does well. I think
the main thing is that they want to see us both do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Scott: ``We are just going to go out there and compete with
each other and see which team comes out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huffmans aside, Saturday's game is more than a sibling
rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Rice and TCU have long been like brethren, sharing the same
conference affiliation for decades. Rice was an original member of
the Southwest Conference in 1915, and TCU joined in 1923. Both went
to the Western Athletic Conference four years ago after the breakup
of the SWC.
</P>
<P>
   Now, TCU is leaving the WAC for Conference USA. Some interpret
that to mean TCU thinks it is better than Rice and the rest of the
WAC.
</P>
<P>
   TCU is scheduled to join C-USA after the 2000-2001 academic
year, but WAC officials say privately they want to force the Frogs
out earlier. Whether the conference can do that is unclear, but
regardless, Saturday's game will be the last between the schools in
Houston in the foreseeable future. Neither school has immediate
plans to schedule the other once TCU bolts.
</P>
<P>
   With both teams in the thick of the WAC championship hunt _ Rice
is 3-0 and TCU 2-1 in league play _ Saturday's game is probably the
most important between them since the 1950s. But there will be much
to prove on other levels as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has a three-game win streak in the series, and its
fourth-year seniors have a chance to go out perfect against the
Horned Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go 4-0,'' said senior quarterback Chad Richardson,
``and this is going to be the hardest year to do it. They were down
the first two years we played them. Last year was hard because they
were good, and this year will be tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU, obviously, wants to reverse the trend. As a fifth-year
senior, Royce Huffman was with the Frogs the last time they beat
Rice (33-28 in 1995). ``There are only four, maybe five, of us on
the team who have beaten Rice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because they have won the last three meetings in the series, the
Owls still are burning over the fact most preseason forecasts had
TCU as the better team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got an opinion,'' Rice coach Ken Hatfield said.
``I don't worry about what you think. I worry about how well we
play against them on Saturday. That is my main concern.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the preseason thinking took into account TCU's win over
Southern California in last year's Sun Bowl. Rice officials chide
TCU by noting its fans can't seem to go 50 words into a
conversation without the words Sun and Bowl coming up.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Horned Frogs could counter that Rice is just
jealous, since ``Bluebonnet Bowl'' has lost some of its luster
since the Owls made their last postseason appearance in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Rice feels it was lied to by TCU. When Rice officials called to
ask if the Horned Frogs were pursuing C-USA membership instead of
emphasizing their five-year commitment to the WAC, TCU officials
said no. As it turned out, the answer was yes. ``That's not the way
we do business,'' said Rice president Malcolm Gillis.
</P>
<P>
   The teams pit similar strengths against each other. Both have
superior running games and quality defenses. They rank 1-2 in the
WAC in rushing offense, scoring defense, total defense and rushing
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls bring the momentum of a four-game win streak and are
playing at home, where they have won 12 of their 13 WAC games. A
fifth straight win would put them in the catbird seat for the Las
Vegas Bowl bid extended to the WAC champion. Hawaii, Fresno State
and Texas-El Paso, which like TCU have one conference loss, will be
watching with interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone in the league will be for us,'' Royce Huffman
said. ``Rice is undefeated in league play. If we win, then we level
the playing field for the other teams. However, it's still early to
say this makes the season, because all games are important.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, Rice has been in the league chase
through November. Had the Owls defeated Air Force in Colorado
Springs last year, they would have advanced to the WAC championship
game as Mountain Division champions. Instead, the Owls lost a 22-16
heartbreaker.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Rice would have won the Mountain title if not for a
31-14 loss at Utah. And in 1996, a 49-0 loss at Brigham Young took
the Owls off the title track.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hatfield and TCU coach Dennis Franchione don't want to
put too much emphasis on this week's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if we win this game, we talk about winning the league
more,'' Franchione said. ``But as of yet, we have not played
ourselves into position to talk about the league chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice admits the grudge factor against TCU is not as strong as it
was against Baylor and Texas Tech, who surprised the Owls by
bolting from the Southwest Conference to the Big 12 along with
Texas and Texas A&AMP;M, two schools the Owls knew were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are there the same ugly feelings Rice officials held toward
Colorado State, whose president, Al Yates, organized the departure
from the WAC of the eight teams that formed the Mountain West
Conference. There was dancing in the streets of West U. last year
when Rice played its best game in years to slap the Rams 35-23 at
Rice Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But as Saturday inches closer, Rice's players, coaches and
administrators might at least find some of their dislike for the
Horned Frogs seething a little.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Royce Huffman, who left his minor-league baseball team
early last summer to once again be a part of TCU's football team,
said it best when he talked about playing his brother in what he
knew would be their last meeting. He wants to be able to say he
bested him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game had a little bit more meaning for me to come back to
TCU and play because I wanted to play against my brother,'' Royce
said. ``We can talk about it for the rest of our lives. Whoever
wins this ballgame will have bragging rights for the rest of his
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
