<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EDUCATION-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DANGEROUS EDUCATION BILL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Oct. 21:
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party is being pulled in contradictory directions
on the question of how to close the school performance gap between
affluent white children and poor minority children. Progressive
Republican reformers have seen that school districts tend to ignore
the poorest, least prepared students unless pressured from above.
But the Republican leadership in Congress views federal pressure as
evil, even when it is applied on behalf of the nation's most
vulnerable children.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Texas, led by Gov. George W. Bush, have seen
their state make impressive progress in closing the achievement gap
between the affluent and the poor, mainly by targeting its effort
on poor students and penalizing schools that fail to meet
improvement goals for  &UR; all  &LR; of their students. Even so, Republicans
in Congress have consistently backed legislation that would
eliminate the targeting mechanisms under Title I, the federal
funding stream that was developed in order to supplement
instruction for the nation's poorest students.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``straight A's'' bill, for example, would harm
America's poor, despite its bright and shiny name. The GOP
leadership argues that the bill would give the states
``flexibility'' in how they spend federal money. But the bill would
allow legislatures to rewrite the distribution formula, shifting
the money around at will _ even taking it away from poor schools.
The possibility that federal education dollars targeted at the poor
would become subject to political horse-trading at the state level
has caused even the National Governors' Association to oppose this
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The duplicitously named bill is an attempt to undermine HR-2,
the sensible bipartisan measure that would require states that
accept Title I money to improve instruction for the poorest
students and commit to narrowing the achievement gap. That is the
goal to support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0491 </DOCNO>
