A3553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-RUSSIA-DEFENSE-NYT &LR;      10-20 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SELLING RUSSIA ON MISSILE DEFENSE 
 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Oct. 21: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Russia has made it clear that it does not like American
proposals to renegotiate the 27-year-old Antiballistic Missile
Treaty in order to permit America to build defenses against nuclear
attacks from unpredictable nations like North Korea. Moscow has
even rebuffed Washington's offer to help Russia create its own
missile defense by financing a new radar system in Siberia. But
Russia's current resistance may be a bargaining ploy. America
should keep trying to negotiate mutually agreeable modifications to
the treaty. What Washington must not do is abandon the treaty in
frustration if such revisions prove beyond immediate reach.
</P>
<P>
   The ABM treaty has been an essential component of arms control
understandings between Washington and Moscow since the Nixon
administration. It has effectively precluded most defensive missile
systems on the grounds that they would encourage the development of
increasingly powerful offensive weapons to penetrate them. But the
Clinton administration believes that it is necessary to update the
treaty to guard against the North Koreas of this world, and that
this can be done without setting off a destructive and costly new
arms race. The Russians have agreed to listen to the
administration's proposals, but have made it clear that they do not
like what they have heard so far and have warned that American
abandonment of the treaty could put all other arms control
agreements at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Under most circumstances, fiddling with the ABM treaty would not
be a good idea. The biggest potential threat to America comes from
established nuclear powers like Russia and China, not smaller ones
like North Korea. Existing arms control agreements, like the 1972
treaty, have a good record of managing these threats. But the
administration makes a plausible case, and its proposal ought to be
the basis for further discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's concept of a limited missile defense would not
require Russia or China to build more missiles to penetrate the new
American shield. Ambitious missile defense systems that could
provide effective coverage against Russia's thousands of missiles
are well beyond the reach of existing technology. But a limited
system would also serve Moscow's interest, since Russian territory
is even more exposed than America to attack from rogue states.
Still, Washington should not go ahead with a defensive system until
the technology is more certain and the negotiations with Moscow
have reached a satisfactory conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The interest both sides share in countering the threat from
rogue states suggests that with good-faith negotiation, agreement
on carefully drawn changes in the ABM treaty may eventually come to
pass. With a new Russian government possible after next year's
elections, Washington should continue negotiating with Moscow in an
effort to find mutually acceptable revisions, and defer any thought
of renouncing the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
