<DOCNO> NYT19991020.0492 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-20 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ENGINE-THEATER-REVIEW     10-20 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGINE-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WATER ENGINE': AT THE 1934 WORLD'S FAIR, SPEAKING THE WRONG
LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles Lang, the clear-speaking inventor hero of
David Mamet's pithy fable of a play, ``The Water Engine,'' which
has been given a befittingly lucid revival by the Atlantic Theater
Company, is a man uncontaminated by the pollutions of contemporary
English.
</P>
<P>
   He talks in simple, declarative sentences that are heavy on
monosyllables. As he carefully places one word before the other,
avoiding slang, hyperbole and indirection, he suggests the verbal
equivalent of a mountaineer walking a straight line on a high,
narrow ledge.
</P>
<P>
   In most fictive worlds, people who talk like Charles are usually
the victims of lobotomy, brainwashing or hypnosis. In Mamet's
world, they are more likely to represent an elemental purity, which
can translate into either idealism or brutal primitivism. In either
case, they're children in a land of conniving grown-ups. And poor
Charles, living in the sea of fancy, self-congratulatory elocution
that surrounds the Chicago World's Fair in 1934, is clearly a
doomed soul.
</P>
<P>
   Language is fate in the dramas of David Mamet, a key not just to
character but to chances of survival, something especially evident
in his short, elliptical morality plays of urban life. Having done
brilliantly by one of those plays, ``Edmond,'' several years ago,
the Atlantic Theater Company (of which Mamet is a founder) has now
taken on ``The Water Engine'' as the opening production of a season
devoted to the playwright.
</P>
<P>
   It's a smart choice, in many ways. ``The Water Engine'' was
first conceived as a radio play, and most of its subsequent
stagings (which included a run on Broadway in 1978) have retained
the central conceit of a work intended as much to be heard as seen,
blurring the lines between genres. This puts the emphasis on
listening as an active, rather than passive, process, which is
always essential in approaching this dramatist. And the
diagrammatic quality of ``The Water Engine'' serves as something of
a primer for Mamet's murkier plays.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is possible to be too clear and careful in the
theater, and this incarnation of ``The Water Engine,'' directed by
Karen Kohlhaas, is suffused with an air of caution that keeps the
evening from ever rising above room temperature. As designed by
Walt Spangler (sets), Rick Gradone (costumes) and Robert Perry
(lighting), it is an exceptionally handsome production. Yet it only
rarely creates that electric friction, the sense of words' rubbing
fiercely against each other, that sets off such memorable sparks in
the best of Mamet productions.
</P>
<P>
   There is a feeling that the talented actors (many of them Mamet
veterans) are reciting their lines as though they were reading
sheet music on which pauses and inflections are carefully noted.
Now this may conform to Mamet's own published theories about
acting, which are basically of the ``just-say-the-words'' sort, but
it makes the pleasures of this production more academic than
emotional. It also makes the none-too-subtle thematic ironies of
``The Water Engine'' fall more heavily than need be.
</P>
<P>
   The engine of the title is the invention of Charles (Steven
Goldstein), a contraption that runs on basic water. How appropriate
that Charles should have made his discovery in the year of the
World's Fair, a celebration of science and progress.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Charles begins to deal with a pair of slick-tongued
lawyers (Peter Jacobson and Jordan Lage) who claim to represent his
best interests, it becomes obvious that the organic water engine is
actually a threat to the status quo of official Science and
Progress, and their corporate embodiments. Charles and his equally
idealistic sister, Rita (Mary McCann), become innocents in
jeopardy, and the play soon acquires the tone of a radio suspense
thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this production never picks up those rhythms of
suspense, a surprise given Ms. Kohlhaas' wonderfully energetic
staging of Harold Pinter's ``Hothouse'' last season. The show
smoothly orchestrates disparate voices into a symphony of
counterpoints, from the grandiloquence of a guide in the fair's
Hall of Science (Jacobson) to the contrastingly superstitious
admonitions of a chain letter (spoken by Kelly Maurer).
</P>
<P>
   But it keeps you at an unengaged distance, despite winningly
unctuous performances from Lage and Jacobson, and an affecting (and
expertly lighted) moment from Goldstein, in which Charles visits
his own Gethsemane of doubts.
</P>
<P>
   While the themes of corruption and Darwinian struggle so
abundant in Mamet's work are sharply sounded here, so is a more
poignant and empathetic note, one that the playwright explored most
deeply in the autobiographical ``The Old Neighborhood.'' This is
the idea, which the very notion of the radio play picks up on, of
the fumbling ways in which people grasp for connection, form and
explanations in life.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the subject of ``Mr. Happiness,'' the evening's
brief curtain raiser, in which a radio problem solver (Bob Balaban)
reads letters from assorted distressed listeners and offers advice.
Balaban wisely avoids the temptations of canned glibness,
presenting Mr. Happiness as a simple, pious man who has come to
accept the culture's prevailing platitudes as gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Balaban occasionally falls prey to mechanical
self-consciousness, like someone following an orchestra conductor's
baton, that is the evening's dominant danger. Presumably, both he
and the ensemble of ``The Water Engine'' will melt a bit more into
their roles as the run continues.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there is absolutely nothing to fault in the
technical execution of the production. Andrew Keister has done
wonders in making standard radio sound effects seem like part of a
natural reality. And Spangler and Perry make marvelous use of the
play of repeated shadows, of both words on signs and technological
images, against the gleaming chrome of the set. In fact, as it
stands, ``The Water Engine'' is more of a thrill for the eye than
the ear, which is surely a first in a Mamet production.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WATER ENGINE' and `MR. HAPPINESS'
</P>
<P>
   By David Mamet; directed by Karen Kohlhaas; sets by Walt
Spangler; costumes by Rick Gradone; lighting by Robert Perry; sound
by Andrew Keister; production stage manager, Alex Lyu Volckhausen;
production manager, Richard Burgess; general manager, Bardo
Ramirez. Presented by the Atlantic Theater Company, Neil Pepe,
artistic director; Hilary Hinckle, managing director. At 336 W.
20th St..
</P>
<P>
   `THE WATER ENGINE':
</P>
<P>
   With: Steven Goldstein (Charles Lang), Mary McCann (Rita), Peter
Jacobson (Morton Gross/Ensemble), Jordan Lage (Lawrence
Oberman/Ensemble), Maryann Urbano (Gross' Secretary/Mrs.
Varec/Ensemble), Peter Maloney (Mr. Wallace/Ensemble), Carl
Matusovich (Bernie/Ensemble), Josh Stamberg (Dave Murray/Ensemble),
Kelly Maurer (Chainletter/Ensemble), Maggie Kiley (Murray's
Secretary/Ensemble) and Jody Lambert (Ensemble/Sound Effects).
</P>
<P>
   `MR. HAPPINESS':
</P>
<P>
   With: Bob Balaban (Mr. Happiness).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
