<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY CENTER HONORS JONATHAN WINTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jonathan Winters was awarded the Mark Twain Prize
for humor by the Kennedy Center Center for the Performing Arts on
Wednesday night, getting praise from contemporaries like Steve
Allen and Sid Caesar, who starred with him in television situation
comedies, as well as from younger proteges, including Bonnie Hunt
and Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of show in which a star was honored and all of
those singing praise performed their own routines. Caesar, for
example, spoke in the fractured foreign-language gibberish that he
perfected when he was a star in the early days of television.
</P>
<P>
   With Allen as his straight man, Caesar spoke in an unknown
French dialect in which some of the few discernable words were
Voltaire, Victor Hugo and Louis Pasteur. Similar injustice was
visited upon German (some words were Richard Wagner and Lily
Marlene), Italian (Leonardo da Vinci and Enrico Fermi) and ersatz
Japanese (Datsun and Toyota).
</P>
<P>
   Another comic, Robert Wuhl, put Winters on his all-star baseball
team of comedians, in which, he said, batting cleanup were ``the
Three Stooges _ Buchanan, Trump and Beatty.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams picked up the political theme, saying Winters should
seek the White House because with his gift of impersonation, ``Not
only will he be president, he'll be the whole Cabinet.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Winters prepared for the event on Wednesday afternoon
with a discussion in which it was difficult to separate the serious
from his improvisational wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a true story,'' he began, an introduction that made
the listener wonder if it really was, and he went on to tell about
a recent trip around the world that found him one day at the Temple
of Athena in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman asked what I thought of it,'' he related, ``and I said
that I was terribly disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it goes back five centuries before Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been fixed by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters, who will be 74 next month, made most of his movies
before actors were able to demand multimillion-dollar fees.
Williams gets $20 million for a movie, Winters said. So he said he
told a studio executive, ``If Robin says I'm his idol, shouldn't
you give me $1 million more than that?''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work, and Winters said that for his movie work, which
includes ``It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World,'' his biggest pay was
$130,000.
</P>
<P>
   Winters is the second winner of the Kennedy Center Prize for
comedy; Richard Pryor won the first award last year. Wednesday
night's tribute to Winters was taped for broadcast on Jan. 12,
2000, on the Comedy Central cable network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
