<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHALETE STAYS IN LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ After Ife Ohalete committed a costly
personal-foul penalty against Notre Dame, USC flirted with the idea
of benching the strong safety this weekend and replacing him with
cornerback Kris Richard.
</P>
<P>
   The change would have also forced freshman Kevin Arbet to start
at cornerback in place of Richard against Pacific-10 Conference
leader Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Ohalete was told he had his starting job back and
the defense remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an alarm,'' Ohalete said of his temporary demotion.
``It's just to get my emotions under control. I can't be having
these stupid problems. The last couple of days I've grown up a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohalete's personal foul against Notre Dame's Bobby Brown on a
third-down play allowed the Irish to keep a drive alive and score a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to keep the defensive lineup the same was a relief
to Richard, who wasn't keen on moving to safety six games into the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm staying in my own spot, but I was up for it,''
Richard said. ``I'm glad Ife's still in there. I wouldn't say it's
too late to make a change, but this is a big game. This is a
must-win game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Steele sits: Linebacker Markus Steele will not start but will
play Saturday, after sitting out Tuesday's and Wednesday's
practices with torn tissue in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The injury will require surgery after the season but should not
force Steele to miss any games.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said sophomore Henry Wallace would probably start at
weakside linebacker, or possibly freshman Troy Polamalu.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Windrell Hayes re-aggravated his ankle injury but
is expected to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   __ Freshman mark: USC wide receiver Kareem Kelly's 26 catches is
already a USC freshman record, according to a spokesperson. Kelly
also needs five more yards to surpass R. Jay Soward's
freshman-record yardage total of 507 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   __ Where's the D? Stanford is ranked 110th in the country in
total defense, 104th in pass-efficiency defense and 98th in scoring
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinal is vastly improved in run defense, where it was
ranked among the worst in the nation last season. It is currently
37th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
