<HEADLINE>
STATUS QUO WINS ON TOBACCO, CAMPAIGN SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - On a visit to Lexington, Ky., last weekend, where I
lived for a decade and learned that betting on horses was not a
reliable investment strategy, the earthy aroma of burley tobacco
being trucked from the farms to the auction warehouses wafted
through town.
</P>
<P>
   I like the smell of freshly cured burley. Even though cigarette
smoke bothers me, the leaves have a rich, satisfying scent.
</P>
<P>
   For people who raise it, the crop also smells like money. Almost
half of Kentucky's agricultural income comes from the state's
45,000 tobacco farms. Thanks to a federal price-support program,
tobacco has long been America's most profitable crop. Legal crop,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Something I read in the Lexington paper, however, didn't smell
so good. Tucked into the record $8.7 billion farm-relief bill
signed into law last week is $328 million for tobacco farmers. Why
such generosity? Because Congress bought the twisted argument that
the government ought to compensate them for falling cigarette
sales.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading advocates for this gift was Kentucky's senior
senator, Republican Mitch McConnell. He contends that it's only
fair for tobacco farmers to get more federal money since their
incomes will be down as the result of a 29 percent quota cut
imposed this year because of declining demand.
</P>
<P>
   Quotas are set by the federal government to maintain a
supply-demand balance and keep the price of tobacco up. So the
tobacco farmers will get high prices from the quota cut and will
receive an extra $328 million to offset the lower quotas.
</P>
<P>
   This would be farfetched for any product, but it's nuts in the
case of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has no business enriching tobacco farmers
at a time when it's waging a war against smoking and suing tobacco
companies. And it shouldn't be tossing around millions to offset
free market forces. With demand for tobacco dropping sharply, many
farmers should start planting other crops. When the federal
government acts to prop up their incomes artificially, where's the
incentive?
</P>
<P>
   Rather than face up to the reality of changing times for
tobacco, politicians like McConnell work to preserve the status
quo, even when it takes your and my tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But McConnell's strongest efforts to keep the system unchanged
have been made as an opponent of campaign finance reform. He scored
another big victory Tuesday when his attacks on the McCain-Feingold
bill helped bury it in the Senate for the fourth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell cloaks his approval of the escalating millions poured
into political campaigns in the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spending is speech,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to impose limits on campaign contributions are
``trying to take away your right to speak. They want the speech
police,'' McConnell insists.
</P>
<P>
   That's a fat distortion, and he knows it. Reform proponents
don't want to curtail speech. To the contrary, they want a more
level playing field that allows opposing candidates a decent chance
to get their message out, rather than a system that lets big money
determine what voters hear.
</P>
<P>
   Under current finance laws, big contributions come with the
expectation that the favor will be repaid. Special interests thus
gain priority over the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians like McConnell resist reform for the plain reason
that the current system serves them well and makes unseating
incumbents extremely hard.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky senator sought to put John McCain on the spot last
week in the Senate for daring to say that big money has a
corrupting influence. Show us where the corruption is, McConnell
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   McCain resisted the temptation to point straight at McConnell.
Instead, he responded with an honest admission:
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are tainted by the system, myself included.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell's embrace of the First Amendment to give wealthy
special interests enormous influence over government is no less
offensive than Larry Flynt wrapping himself in it to defend his
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference is that Flynt doesn't have the power to
write the nation's laws. McConnell and the deep pockets making
six-figure campaign contributions do. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at (602) 444-8775, or at
steve.wilson(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
