A3574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HOLBROOKE-LOBBY-1STLD     10-20 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-LOBBY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE LOBBIES CONGRESS ON PAYMENTS TO U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add a 2nd take.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Since his confirmation as chief delegate to the
United Nations, Richard Holbrooke has turned himself from
high-flying diplomat to part-time lobbyist, walking the halls of
Congress and buttonholing members on the elevator, on the Capitol
subway, at their doors _ anywhere he can find them.
</P>
<P>
   He was campaigning again Wednesday, and by midafternoon, with a
bevy of aides in tow, the tally was six formal appointments, 14
chance encounters and still more meetings to go, all in the cause
of rescuing the United States' standing at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, whose appointment was confirmed by the Senate in
August, has come to Washington every week, sometimes twice a week,
to try to persuade Congress to pay nearly a billion dollars that
the United States owes the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequences are catastrophic if we don't get this,''
Holbrooke said to Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Calif., after
running into the congresswoman in the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   He then dashed into the office of Rep. James Greenwood, R-Pa.,
who is one of the high hopes in Holbrooke's nitty-gritty campaign
to persuade Republicans who are against abortion to untie that
issue from legislation authorizing payment of the U.N. money.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, President Clinton vetoed a bill containing payments
for the United Nations because it included an amendment restricting
U.S. funding for family planning organizations abroad. Holbrooke,
whose success as the American representative depends in part on
whether Washington pays the arrears, is seeking to avoid a similar
outcome this year.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his crusading, Holbrooke knows that as the budget
battle with the Republicans unfolds, the heavy lifting on the U.N.
payments must come from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He said Wednesday that he was heartened to be informed by Sandy
Berger, the national security adviser, that Clinton had put foreign
policy _ including the U.N. arrears and financial assistance to the
Middle East _ ``on top of the agenda'' during a budget negotiations
session with Republican leaders Tuesday night at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has made it a priority issue,'' Holbrooke said,
just as he bumped into an old friend, Rep. Patsy Mink, D-Hawaii,
who served at the State Department with Holbrooke and who did not
need any cajoling on the U.N. issue as they rode the subway
together.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans were not sounding so positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House has to come up with some ideas on how to solve
this issue,'' said a senior aide to the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The aide said the White House was trying to figure out how to
solve the matter through deft legislative and political handiwork.
``They have to think out of the box,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As Holbrooke made his rounds Wednesday, the House passed the
Commerce, Justice, State appropriations bill that contains the
money for the United Nations. But there was little room for
Holbrooke to celebrate. For the money to be actually paid, the
Republicans have insisted that an authorization bill be passed as
well. In the past, the amendment restricting financing of
family-planning groups that support abortion has been attached to
the authorization legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke concedes that he leaves the intricacies of legislation
to experts from the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   For him, there is only one issue: national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the United States and our national security,
about funding peacemaking efforts in East Timor and local police in
Kosovo,'' he said. In both those places, the United States has
argued for strong U.N. involvement rather than sending the American
military.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, like any savvy lobbyist, has his script rehearsed. He
reminds members of a deal between Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, which calls for the payment
of $926 million in arrears in exchange for Washington's insistence
on various U.N. reforms. Those include zero growth in the U.N.
budget and a reduction in the United States' share of the
administrative budget, to 22 percent from 25 percent. The deal also
mandates that the United States get back its seat on the budget
committee, which Holbrooke tells members has been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   The $926 million is actually less than the United Nations says
the United States owes, but it is enough to continue the ``United
States in the business of the United Nations,'' Holbrooke said. The
total tab is $1.7 billion, according to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   One of Holbrooke's last calls Wednesday was to Rep. David
Dreier, R-Calif., the chairman of the subcommittee on rules and
organization. When it gets down to the wire, Dreier can decide how
the vital authorization legislation is played out.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke emerged from the half-hour meeting satisfied.
``Congressman Dreier is clearly in the category of
national-security-conscious members of the congressional
majority,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
